<HEADLINE>
HERSHISER HAS FOND MEMORIES IN MONTREAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ It's easy to bag on Olympic Stadium as being a
smoke-filled dungeon in which one feels trapped rather than
comfortable watching a baseball game.
</P>
<P>
   But Orel Hershiser actually has nice memories of the Concrete
Fortress, and he'll script another chapter today. The Dodgers
right-hander made his major-league debut here, won his 200th career
game here last year with the Mets, and now makes his first
appearance in his who-woulda-thought-it return to the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ballpark has significance with me even though people
don't like the ballpark around the industry,'' said Hershiser, who
faces the Expos. ``My last start was against Colorado right before
the strike, and I joked about it how it might be my last start as a
Dodger. Everybody joked, `No way. No way.'''
</P>
<P>
   But there it was, Aug. 7, 1994, the last time Hershiser pitched
for the Dodgers. He threw six innings against Colorado, allowed one
run and won.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Hershiser said if not for the work stoppage, he may
be in his 18th season with the Dodgers, rather than having spent
the last five years in Cleveland, San Francisco and New York. But
because of the work stoppage, the Dodgers couldn't watch Hershiser
throw during the winter. Therefore, the Dodgers' brass had no
understanding that his health shouldn't be a concern once the labor
strife was settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of that season, I looked like a 35-year-old pitcher
with a reconstructed shoulder that would have a pretty solid year
but probably was on the tail end of his career,'' said Hershiser,
41, who's 69-43 in the past five years. ``The philosophy that had
been passed down from Branch Rickey to Al Campanis to Fred Claire
was, `It's better to get rid of a guy one year too early than one
year too late.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing that philosophy and being brought up through this
organization ... so when all of a sudden the equation has you in
the center of it, why should I all of a sudden be surprised that
they're not going to change the rules. And they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   MILLS, HUNDLEY INJURED: Catcher Todd Hundley and relief pitcher
Alan Mills both were unavailable for Tuesday's game because of
injuries. While Hundley could return today from a slightly strained
medial collateral ligament in his right knee, Mills' ailment
appears to be much more serious.
</P>
<P>
   Mills sprained his right ankle when he stepped on a ball while
jogging in the outfield Monday and could miss as much as two weeks.
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said the club could decide today
whether to put Mills on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trainer said it may be a week before he can get on the
mound,'' Johnson said. ``I'll look at both those injuries (today)
really close.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers elect to put Mills on the DL, they'll be forced
to decide whether to remain with 12 pitchers or purchase the
contract of outfielder Geronimo Berroa and add him to the roster.
Berroa is in extended spring training as a non-roster player, so
the Dodgers have until Sunday to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley tweaked his knee during an at-bat in Monday's game, and
he said it bothered him when he awoke Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked if he'd be ready to face Bobby Valentine and New
York on Friday, ex-Met Hundley smiled and said: ``Oh, yeah. Believe
me, I already thought about that.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hundley's place, Chad Kreuter made his Dodgers debut and went
2 for 3 Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
