<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-WIZARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NETS ARE FEELING MARBURY'S SHARP PAIN
</HEADLINE>
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With fragile playoff hopes and a limping point
guard, the New Jersey Nets came into the MCI Center on Tuesday
night on a survival mission.
</P>
<P>
   When the night was over, their playoff hopes were severely
crippled by the Wizards' 102-93 victory and their marquee player,
Stephon Marbury, was sidelined for two days and possibly the season
with a painful left knee. Marbury will travel with the team to
Indianapolis where they take on the Pacers Wednesday night and he
will have a magnetic resonance imaging test on his
tendinitis-plagued left knee on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's hurting, he will not play back-to-back,'' Nets Coach
Don Casey said. ``If anywhere close to damaged, he will not play. I
will not put him in the game. He's been too good and worked too
hard for this franchise and his teammates to come up lame.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey said Marbury had a sharp pain in the patella tendon area
and had been getting progressively worse. He said that was why the
decision was made to rest Marbury and to proceed with an MRI.
</P>
<P>
   With Orlando's 107-97 victory over San Antonio Tuesday night,
the Nets are now seven games back with eight games to play.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Marbury sat at his locker with his head down and
was barely audible when he spoke to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   During the morning shoot-around, Marbury said that his knee had
made it harder for him to do the things that he is accustomed to
doing.
</P>
<P>
   He made a couple of explosive moves to the basket in the first
half, but Casey said that it wasn't the same Marbury that the team
was used to having. He said Marbury could not play defense well
because of his knee.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets (31-43) have lost all three games since Marbury's knee
flared up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're struggling,'' said Nets forward Keith Van Horn, who had
24 points. ``We've become dependent on Stephon for certain things.
We're used to going to him for a big part of our game and when
we're not able to do that it's hard for us to adjust.''
</P>
<P>
   Marbury had 13 points on 5-of-14 shooting from the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets were also hurting at the other guard spot when Kerry
Kittles banged his knee against another player during the first
half and played just 18 minutes. Kittles was 1 of 6 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Kittles had his head wrapped in his jersey. When
he emerged he said his knee was a little sore, but it was nothing
that would keep him from playing against the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   On the hot shooting of Van Horn, who had 17 first-half points,
and Marbury, the Nets were able to take a 10-point lead at the end
of the first quarter. The Wizards (27-47), who had six players in
double figures, managed to cut the lead in half by halftime and
trailed by 54-49 going into the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   With Marbury's knee wearing down, the Nets lost some of their
zip in the second half. The Wizards, on the strength of guard Chris
Whitney's 7-of-11 night shooting from the field and some great help
from the reserves Aaron Williams (15 points) and Richard Hamilton
(13 points), took over the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets suffered a major power drain in the fourth quarter,
hitting only 4 of 18 shots from the field.
</P>
<P>
   If it wasn't for center Gheorge Muresan, they would have gone 10
minutes without a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Muresan made two field goals and then the Nets went 6 minutes 16
minutes before the starting center Evan Eschmeyer hit an
uncontested layup with 1:53 to play. That gave the Wizards a 95-87
lead, making the game out of the Nets' reach.
</P>
<P>
   Muresan, who has missed 20 games this season with injuries and
has been on the injured list three times, was looking to play 10
minutes in each half. Casey allowed him to play eight minutes for
the game, and Muresan gave Casey 8 points. It wasn't nearly enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he played OK,'' Casey said. ``It was fun to see when
Elliot Perry got that steal at the end, Gheorge running down to
finish off. He looked a bit awkward at times, but I thought he did
well.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the few bright spots of what turned out to be a
very dim night for the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager John Nash said that in the last few games of the
season, it will be important for Muresan to get some minutes so the
Nets can assess where he is. The Nets feel that Muresan is better,
physically, than he was when he played in Washington four years
ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
