<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COMMUTER-TAX-355&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK HIGH COURT UPHOLDS REPEAL OF COMMUTER TAX 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The state's highest court Tuesday upheld the
repeal of New York City's commuter tax for state residents and
ruled that the tax must also be eliminated for out-of-state
commuters _ a double blow to the Giuliani administration that will
cost the city $360 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous decision by the state Court of Appeals concludes
more than a year of legal and political struggle that had begun
with both major parties' attempts to influence a legislative
election northwest of the city and that had put Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani in an awkward position in his race for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 800,000 people who work in the city but live
elsewhere, the ruling means that they will no longer have to pay
0.45 percent of their income to New York City, a tax in place, in
varying forms, since 1966. The state, which collected the tax for
the city, stopped taking it from the paychecks of New York state
residents when the law went into effect last July 1 but continued
to deduct it from out-of-state commuters' pay. The state's
Department of Taxation and Finance says it must now refund $115
million to 340,000 people, most of them New Jersey residents.
</P>
<P>
   Repeal of the commuter tax had long been a political rallying
cry for suburbanites, but for years their demands went unanswered.
But last year as a special election approached in a state Senate
district in Rockland and Orange counties, Republicans and Democrats
raced to outdo each other in their appeals to suburban voters, and
with dizzying speed, the tax was repealed last May. In that race,
the Republican, Thomas P. Morahan, narrowly won.
</P>
<P>
   The bill that was passed by the Legislature and signed by Gov.
George E. Pataki repealed the tax for in-state commuters but left
it in place for out-of-staters. But the bill also provided that if
that distinction was ruled unconstitutional, as it was Tuesday, the
tax would be repealed entirely. Many lawmakers said at the time
that they knew they were discriminating illegally against
out-of-state commuters but wanted the courts to shoulder the blame
for taking that money from the city.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   About 480,000 New York state residents paid $210 million a year
under the commuter tax. Out-of-staters paid $150 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani complained loudly about the state's actions last
spring, saying that the state had illegally and unfairly deprived
the city of an important source of revenue and that commuters had a
duty to help pay for the services they used while in the city,
everything from police protection to street paving. He said the
repeal was a product of politics ``out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   That view is at odds with many suburban voters, who are
Giuliani's strongest base of support, and his comments last year
could be used against him during his Senate campaign. In fact, the
mayor has had less to say about the commuter tax as the campaign
has heated up, and his response to Tuesday's ruling was muted.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he was not surprised by the court's ruling, and,
defending the tax as ``modest,'' said he hoped state lawmakers
would restore it someday. ``This is one of those political
things,'' he said. ``Albany can sometimes be as convoluted as
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey called the decision ``a
clear-cut victory for the 240,000 New Jerseyans who cross into New
York City to work each day,'' and urged Pataki to speed the
refunding of withheld taxes.
</P>
<P>
   There were no surprises in the court's 7-0 decision, written by
Judge Richard C. Wesley.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration had sued to challenge the repeal,
saying the state could not alter the city's tax policy without a
request from the city, known as a ``home rule message.'' While that
is generally true, Wesley wrote, a large exception is made where
there is a ``substantial state concern.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, a tax paid only by New York State residents who live
outside New York City is a matter of substantial state concern,''
he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The city contended that state officials were motivated by
politics _ the state Senate race _ and not by a genuine concern
over the underlying policy, voiding the state's claim to a
substantial interest in the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But ``speculation on the political motivation of the
Legislature,'' Wesley wrote, ``would be a slippery and dangerous
slope.''
</P>
<P>
   The states of Connecticut and New Jersey, and residents of both
states, also sued to challenge the repeal law, on the ground that
it discriminated against out-of-state commuters and was
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The court said the law violated two of the original sections of
the Constitution: the ``privileges and immunities clause,'' which
says, in essence, that states must treat residents of other states
in the same way they treat their own residents; and the ``commerce
clause,'' which says that only Congress may regulate activities
involved in interstate commerce.
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
