<SLUG> BC-SKAKEL-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESS ASKS JUDGE TO MAKE SKAKEL FILE PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ A lawyer representing six news organizations
asked a juvenile court judge here Tuesday to unseal all of the
court documents related to the case against Michael C. Skakel, who
is charged with killing his next-door neighbor, Martha Moxley, in
Greenwich in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel, 39, is charged as a juvenile in the case because he was
15 when Moxley, also 15, was killed. Criminal proceedings against
juvenile defendants and all related court records, even the
outcomes of cases, are usually kept confidential.
</P>
<P>
   But in March, acting on a motion by the news organizations,
Judge Maureen Dennis agreed to open the court proceedings against
Skakel to the press and the public. She ruled that he no longer
needed the protection of confidentiality and noted that Skakel and
his lawyer supported opening the case.
</P>
<P>
   In a follow-up request Tuesday, David Fein, a lawyer
representing The New York Times, Newsday, The Hartford Courant, The
Advocate of Stamford, The Greenwich Time and The Associated Press
asked Judge Dennis to unseal the case file, including an affidavit
that prosecutors filed to obtain a warrant for Skakel's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The newspapers are particularly interested in the arrest warrant
affidavit because it outlines the evidence on which the prosecutors
from the state's attorney's office are basing their case, including
allegations that Skakel confessed to killing Moxley to classmates
at a school in Maine for troubled teen-agers. Skakel has denied
that he killed Moxley and has said he never confessed to doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis said she would consider the news organizations' request,
but did not say when she would issue a decision.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's hearing at the state Superior Court complex, the
prosecutor, Jonathan C. Brennan, said he would not object if Dennis
opened the court record to the public, saying that Skakel had
already waived his right to confidentiality as a juvenile
defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel's lawyer, Michael Sherman, also told Dennis that he did
not object to the release of the file, but then said he had grave
concerns about the effect that releasing some of the documents
might have on a future trial.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman said he was most concerned that many of the allegations
outlined in the warrant were attributed to unnamed sources. He
asked Dennis to require the state's attorneys to reveal the names
of those potential witnesses if she decides to make the documents
public. Sherman acknowledged that any statements made by Skakel's
former classmates at the Elan School in Poland Springs, Maine, ,
were of crucial importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statements from Elan are the case,'' he said bluntly.
``There is no question about that.''
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
