<HEADER>
A7412 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-HATE-ARSON-SFCHRON &LR;      04-05 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-ARSON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROTHERS ENTER NOT GUILTY PLEAS IN FIERY SACRAMENTO HATE SPREE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Two white supremacist brothers pleaded not guilty
Tuesday to charges of setting last summer's fires at three
Sacramento synagogues and firebombing an area abortion clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Matthew Williams, 32, and James Tyler Williams, 29,
appeared in U.S District Court in Sacramento and were charged with
arson, conspiracy to commit arson, destruction of religious
property and use of fire to commit a felony.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Williams, who has told reporters that he alone is
responsible for the attacks, appeared with his head shaved, a
scraggly beard and narrow mustache. As the charges were read, he
looked around at the crowded courtroom and winked broadly at one
side.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he had had a chance to consult with his attorney,
Benjamin Williams said sharply, ``Yes, a very brief opportunity.''
He emphatically said ``Yes, I do,'' when asked if he understood the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the younger brother, wearing glasses and neatly
combed hair, looked straight ahead and answered only ``yes'' to the
questions. Both men appeared in dark blue jail uniforms, with their
hands and legs shackled.
</P>
<P>
   They are already being held in a Shasta County jail on charges
of killing a gay couple, Winfield Mowder and Gary Matson. The
prosecutor in that case has said he will seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Holley, Benjamin Williams' appointed defense attorney,
said he believes the federal case will proceed before the state
case. He also suggested he may ask for a change of venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fairly logical that Sacramento would probably be
the worst place to try a case where the issue is the burning of
Sacramento buildings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holley said he would have preferred if his client had not talked
to the media.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Williams admitted in a November jailhouse interview
with the Sacramento Bee that he shot the men because he believed
their homosexuality violated God's law. He later admitted
responsibility for the arson attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more any criminal defendant says about anything _ that
makes it harder for us to work with him,'' Holley said. ``But
what's been said has been said.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers will meet Friday with U.S. District Judge Garland
Burrell, who presided over the Unabomber trial.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Steven Lapham, the government's lawyer,
refused to comment beyond saying that ``the game is starting.''
</P>
<P>
   The synagogues sustained $1 million in damage during the early
morning attacks on June 18. Only minor damage occurred at the
Sacramento medical clinic, which was hit early July 2. No one was
injured in the incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Matt Friedman of Congregation Beth Shalom, one of the
synagogues attacked, said seeing and hearing the brothers in person
was ``rattling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially the one brother who spoke with arrogance and
contempt in his voice,'' he said. ``That he is unwavering, at least
in his outward demeanor, is disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman said he wants the trial to be over so the focus can be
moved away from the two men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see the emphasis shifted away from them and their
platform, and rather shifted to what goes on at these synagogues
currently,'' he said. ``We continue to serve the Jewish community
and are there as a resource for spiritual well being.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in the courtroom Tuesday was Brian Matson, brother of Gary
Matson, one of the two Redding men the Williams brothers are
accused of shooting to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to remind people that the brothers accused in
the synagogue fires also murdered my brother and one of my best
friends,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the Assembly Public Safety Committee passed 5 to 1
a bill by Assemblywoman Pat Bates, R-Laguna Niguel, that would
impose a sentence enhancement of up to five years for anyone
causing the burning and destruction of a church, synagogue or other
religious facility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
