<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7415 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     04-05 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CAUTION: MAY CAUSE ACUTE HILARITY  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Honesty in television advertising is good, but
it sure can be scary.
</P>
<P>
   Many new prescription drugs are now advertised on TV, and
federal law requires that the announcers announce the drug's side
effects, which the announcer does, sometimes in such a soothing or
peppy voice that the side effects sound kind of attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``So ask your doctor about Gorpomax and kiss toenail fungus
goodbye! Side effects occur in fewer than 90 percent of users and
include severe headaches, menstrual pain, minstrel pain, gangrene,
swelling of the eyeballs, ringing in the nose, gas, bloating,
levitation, inability to recall the words to Wilbur Harrison's
``Kansas City,'' uncontrollable urge to operate heavy machinery,
hallucinations, halitosis, mitosis, tennis elbow, paranoia, Donald
Duck speech, blackouts, comas, amnesia, where was I? sagging
kneecaps, road rage, itchy trigger finger, itch in that spot on
your back you can only reach with a garden tool, ambivalence to the
first track on the new Santana CD, runny ears and spontaneous
combustion.''
</P>
<P>
   MY STOCKBROKER, Dot Commuppance, reminds me that the difference
between NASCAR and NASDAQ is that the former has brakes.
</P>
<P>
   And she says to remember that the polite British term for wacko
or absurd is ``dotty.''
</P>
<P>
   HELL NO, because of Mo we won't bestow on Joe no plaque at SFO.
</P>
<P>
   That's the unanimous sentiment, that San Francisco should not
cave in to Joe DiMaggio's Florida attorney Morris Engelberg and
rename SFO or the Bay Bridge after Joltin' Joe.
</P>
<P>
   Joltin' Mo is creating a DiMag backlash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than play baseball for a San Francisco minor league
team,'' says Matt White, ``what did Joe DiMaggio do for San
Francisco? Did he spend time with `disadvantaged' youth? Did he
establish a scholarship for high school athletes? Did he
participate in any civic activities?''
</P>
<P>
   One thing DiMaggio did do was hire a lawyer to educate us as to
how ungrateful we are.
</P>
<P>
   George Markell named a bookshelf in his North Beach apartment,
upon which he keeps his baseball books and his dad's ``Home Run
Champ'' trophy from the 1948 B'nai B'rith softball league in
Cleveland, ``the Joe DiMaggio Memorial Bookshelf'' and says,
``Screw Mo Engelberg.''
</P>
<P>
   SO JOLTIN' MO Engelberg is demanding that the city properly
honor the name of a man who for years allowed himself to be known
throughout the world as Mr. Coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Denno says, ``How about naming one of those view-blocking
pillars at Pac Bell Park the Morris Engelberg Memorial
Obstruction?''
</P>
<P>
   Nah, too subtle.
</P>
<P>
   HONESTY can be useful. Dale Zaret's answering-machine message
is, ``Hi, this is Dale, I can come to the phone right now but I'm
not going to. So please leave your name and number and I'll get
back to you ... eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   And Cuffs Corbett, man about town, notes that the worst thing
you can hear when you place a phone call is, ``Your call is very
important to us ...''
</P>
<P>
   WHOEVER SAID there isn't a dog seat in the house at the Giants'
new ballpark was incorrect, reports Darryl Forman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the Yankee game on Saturday and I was in row K, seat
9.''
</P>
<P>
   Man, it's bad karma to sit in that seat and eat a dog.
</P>
<P>
   THE FINAL FOUR, basketball, was great, but maybe at the next big
sports event we can do without the remote TV shots of bars where
patrons feel compelled to hold aloft their beer, never an iced tea
or a BLT, and say, ``Look, I am drinking a beer! Can you believe
how cool I am? And this is not my first frosty one tonight, no way,
Jose! Eat your heart out, girlfriend who dumped me in high school!
Whoo!''
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENT CLINTON, arguing for normalization of trade relations
with China, used the phrase ``Nothing, zip, zilch, nada, zero.''
</P>
<P>
   This shows two things. One, Clinton is hip, using a hipster
phrase that is only about a decade out of date. You never heard FDR
say that.
</P>
<P>
   Two, it shows how badly we need to expand that list. Those can't
be the only five words for ``nothing.`
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of cliches, how's this for Clinton's official legacy:
``Been there, done that.''
</P>
<P>
   THE HEARSE was parked in front of St. Mary Magdalen Church in
Berkeley, with the funeral's guest of honor in the back.
</P>
<P>
   A meter maid motored up and informed the hearse driver he was
parked in a ``disabled parking'' space. The coffin was taken inside
the church and during the ceremony, the meter maid returned and
issued a $75 parking citation.
</P>
<P>
   Which caused one bystander to wonder, ``How disabled do you have
to be?''
</P>
<P>
   IN THE POST OFFICE at Geary and Parker streets in San Francisco,
Stephen Carlson is mailing a large envelope.
</P>
<P>
   The clerk looks at the address and asks Carlson, ``What does
`OR' mean?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oregon,'' he explains diplomatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Oregon in the United States?'' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   Because if Oregon is outside the local galaxy, there's an
additional space-time continuum delivery charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
