<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, April 5.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-U.N. (Daru, Sierra Leone) _ This town, attacked 59
times during a nine-year civil war, had been left for dead,
deserted by its residents. Now, a few weeks after U.N. peacekeepers
arrived, life has begun to stir again. The peacekeeping operation
in Sierra Leone will be watched closely, especially as the U.N.
Security Council considers sending troops to Congo, a much larger
country whose conflict has drawn in half a dozen nations. By
Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ENVIRON (Iguala, Mexico) _ Humble Mexicans who stand in
the way of profiteering from the country's natural resources have
often faced brutal treatment, but one such man, Rudolfo Montiel,
has discovered in recent days that he has international friends to
help him fight his cause. Montiel organized peasants to block roads
after loggers began felling virgin forests around his village in
the mountains north of Acapulco. Last Friday, Amnesty International
declared Montiel, who is now in prison, a prisoner of conscience,
provoking a flood of protest letters to the Mexican authorities.
And on Wednesday, a San Francisco foundation is to announce that it
has awarded him a $125,000 environmental prize. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CORRUPTION (Kaliningrad, Russia) _ If President-elect
Vladimir Putin is going to fight corruption and lawlessness in
Russia, as he has vowed to do in the wake of last month's
elections, he might start here on the southern shore of the Baltic
Sea. By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-POLITICS (Lima, Peru) _ Alejandro Toledo grew up shining
shoes in the grimy port of Chimbote, one of 16 brothers and sisters
whose father was a bricklayer and whose mother sold fish in a
street market. Now, he is giving President Alberto K. Fujimori the
fight of his life in the April 9 presidential election. By Clifford
Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT22) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-SMUGGLING (Washington) _ Border guards in the former
Soviet republic of Uzbekistan seized a radioactive cargo on an
Iranian truck bound for Pakistan last week, State Department
officials said on Tuesday. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HORMONE-REPLACEMENT (Undated) _ Researchers have informed
about 25,000 women taking part in a federal study of hormone
replacement therapy that, far from protecting the heart as many
researchers had assumed, the therapy may have put the women at
slightly higher risk of heart attacks and strokes. The study, known
as the Hormone Replacement Therapy trial of the Women's Health
Initiative, is the first large-scale, controlled clinical trial
asking whether hormone replacement therapy prevents heart disease
in healthy post-menopausal women. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   ORE-ADOPTION-RECORDS (Albany, Ore.) _ The continuing legal
controversy over a law passed by Oregon voters in 1998 giving any
adult adoptee access to their birth records, which had been sealed,
so that they may try to track down their birth parents and/or
half-siblings. The legal issue pits their ``right to know'' versus
the confidentiality the state at one time promised to women who
decided to give children up for adoption. The law, the first such
measure approved by voters in any state, has been stayed ever since
by a legal challenge from six anonymous birth mothers. Now it's
coming to a head before the Oregon supreme court. By Sam Howe
Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT23) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
