   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-RIDGE (Harrisburg, Pa.) _ A look at George W. Bush's
relationship to Gov. Tom Ridge, a potential running mate. By Frank
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS _ Seven months before Election Day, the struggle
over expanding Medicare to cover prescription drugs for the elderly
is escalating, with both parties maneuvering furiously on an issue
that matters, deeply, to a critical group of voters. As the debate
over the Republican budget resolution began in the Senate, for
example, Democrats were pushing for an amendment that would require
the creation of a Medicare drug benefit before any tax cut could
take effect. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-SPENDING _ Hundreds of millions of dollars in
Medicaid money designated for disabled poor children has been
siphoned off by consulting firms and state governments, federal
investigators said Tuesday. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ There was sound. There was fury.
But what stock market investors wanted to know after Tuesday's
bizarre bungee jump in share prices was, what does it signify?
Midway through one of the weirdest and wildest days in stock market
history, the Nasdaq composite index had plunged 634.31 points,
shearing 13.6 percent off its value. Had it closed there, it would
have been the worst one-day decline in Nasdaq history. But a flood
of buying rescued the index, propelling it up almost 500 points.
Even though the markets recovered by the end of the day, traders
and investors were shellshocked by the extraordinary moves. By
Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SUITS (Undated) _ In the wake of a federal judge's
harsh antitrust ruling, Microsoft Corp. now faces the threat of a
rising wave of consumer class-action and other private lawsuits.
But while the ruling in the government case makes things easier for
private antitrust plaintiffs, it by no means insures that they will
win in court. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL-MONITORS (Undated) _ Andrew Quinn, a systems manager for a
toy company near Montreal, is starting to learn more about his
fellow employees than he ever wanted to know. He has found that one
co-worker has a penchant for herbal remedies, another likes jokes
about women drivers and another checks the lottery numbers each
morning. He knows these things because he has installed a new piece
of software on the computer network that enables him to monitor not
only every Web site that his employees browse, but every e-mail
message that they send or receive. His company is one of hundreds
that are looking at workers' correspondence. And the number of
companies is soaring. By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   IPO-FINANCE (Undated) _ With stock prices sinking fast, cracks
are starting to appear in the market for new issues of shares,
sending companies scrambling for other ways to raise capital.
Several young, technology-based companies have postponed plans for
initial public offerings and others are finding that demand is weak
for their second or third stock offerings. Some investment bankers
on Wall Street fear that the market has entered a period of
sustained softness, while others think the weakness may be
temporary. By Patrick McGeehan and Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   REORG-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Two well-known agencies based in
New York are reorganizing in ways that are indicative of the
substantive shifts taking place along Madison Avenue to try
matching the pace of change in cyberspace and at client companies.
By Stuart Elliot.
</P>
<P>
   DAVE-THOMAS (Undated) _ Dave Thomas, founder and chairman of
Wendy's International.
</P>
<P>
   COMMUNICATIONS-DEAL (Undated) _ Hoping to create a national
giant in wireless communications, BellSouth and SBC Communications
are near a deal to merge their North American wireless operations,
executives close to the negotiations said Tuesday. By Seth
Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-1900 (Paris) _ The art world has not escaped the tyranny
of round numbers this year. Exhibitions in Amsterdam, London and
Paris are currently celebrating the art of 1900. The aim of this
year's shows, though, is not to present great art as such but to
convey something of the mood of the times. And there was indeed
much going on in 1900, nowhere more than in Paris. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   ANGLER-ARTIST (New York) _ Sidney A. Neff, who calls himself a
piscatorial bibliophile, has taken his personal library of rare
books on fishing and, using the book binder's art he took up 20
years ago, transformed them into desktop fishing expeditions. By
picking up one of Neff's works, the ``reader'' literally opens a
series of doors to explore an elegantly tooled world of trout,
insects, and iris-lined river banks, all wrought in dyed African
leathers, Japanese paper, and gold. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-CLOONEY-DRAMA (Hollywood) _ The actor George Clooney is
producing and starring in a highly unusual live drama,
``Fail-Safe,'' based in the 1962 best-selling novel by Harvey
Wheeler and Eugene Burdick. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   HUMAN-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Human Resources'' slowly and
deliberately spirals its ingenuous hero down a treacherous rabbit
hole of duplicity and corporate politics at a French factory, and
eventually threatens to put him and his father on opposite sides of
a war between management and labor. This film, directed by Laurent
Cantet, explores class differences, corporate behavior, labor
relations and father-son strife with an unusual depth and subtlety.
By Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Black and White'': James Toback,
director; with Robert Downey Jr., Ben Stiller. Reviewed by Elvis
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   SIX-NUMBERS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Just Six Numbers: The Deep
Forces That Shape The Universe,'' by Martin Rees (Basic Books).
