<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7419 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-EXPOS-LAD     04-05 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-EXPOS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SCORE A PERFECT 10 IN WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Remember, it's the Montreal Expos, it's only two
games and the Dodgers started last season 5-1 before all you know
what broke loose.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there's a reason everyone in the Dodgers clubhouse is
smiling brightly. They are pounding pitchers and have overwhelmed
an excited and supposedly much-improved Montreal club in getting
out to a quick start.
</P>
<P>
   The revamped Dodgers offense scored double-digit runs for the
second straight night and beat the Expos 10-4 Tuesday at Olympic
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In two games, the Dodgers scored 20 runs and have 26 hits, and
the only thing that seems to be missing is Shawn Green's bat.
Despite the outpouring of offense, Green has one hit in eight
at-bats. But with the way the club has started, Green also has no
worries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty much doing it all myself,'' Green said jokingly.
``When you see guys coming up there hitting the ball hard and not
getting cheap hits, that's a good sign early on. It's huge,
especially early the year. It lets (the pitchers) relax and get
some confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you give pitchers run support early in the year, maybe
they go out there and give up a couple of runs and don't worry
about it as much because they're used to seeing runs on the
board.''
</P>
<P>
   A matchup that drew more international media than regular media
was decidedly in favor of the Dodgers' Chan Ho Park. He withstood
early control problems to pitch six innings and ease to a win after
the offense provided seven runs in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in that inning the Dodgers had seven consecutive hits
before an out was recorded, including a two-run homer by Gary
Sheffield, and knocked out Montreal starter Hideki Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' 17 hits matched their highest total of the dark and
dreary '99 season. And last year's club never scored at least 10
runs in back-to-back games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the lineup has some protection for some guys, and guys
are comfortable,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``We've got
some guys where we can rest other guys and have them fill in, and
I'm going to do that (today). (Chad) Kreuter did a good job filling
in for (Todd) Hundley. It takes 25 guys. That's the fit, and right
now this team is kind of coming together.''
</P>
<P>
   In the opener, it was the middle of the lineup that did the
damage in driving in eight of the 10 runs. While Sheffield did his
part with the homer and a single, the rest of the lineup beat up a
quintet of Montreal pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Devon White led off the game with a homer and scored twice. Mark
Grudzielanek, Kreuter and Adrian Beltre each had three hits, and
Kevin Elster had two hits. Those five scored seven times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very important from both our offense and the
pitching standpoint to start the season this way,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   The big lead certainly relaxed Park, who sometimes loses his
focus and composure on the mound. That time nearly came in an
erratic second inning when a pair of outs on the basepaths helped
Park escape huge problems, but throughout the night Kreuter made a
few visits to the mound to help Park calm down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to be as positive as possible and pump him up and get
him in the right frame of mind where he's not trying to nibble at
the hitters,'' Kreuter said. ``Make quality pitches and make them
hit the ball and let them make the outs, because his stuff is that
good.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
