<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVISCUP-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS CUP GOING `HOLLYWOOD'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Alex O'Brien is no slouch when it comes to
professional tennis. He just doesn't carry the same name
recognition as Andre Agassi, Pete Sampras or John McEnroe.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien is part of the world's fifth-ranked doubles team (with
Jared Palmer), but that's not as glamorous as Agassi and Sampras,
who are first and third in the world singles rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Yet O'Brien is excited because he's playing Davis Cup with
Agassi and Sampras, and McEnroe is the captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a great atmosphere _ the whole Hollywood
scene,'' O'Brien said. ``We have the No.1 and No.2 singles players
and the top two doubles players. It's pretty amazing. I look at
this team and say, `Wow, I'm part of it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although it won't be official until Thursday's draw, all
indications are Agassi and Sampras will compete in this
quarterfinal tie against the Czech Republic. Competition begins
Friday at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi arrived Monday and briefly practiced before practicing
harder on Tuesday. He showed no affects of a sprained ankle he
suffered in last week's Ericsson Open in Key Biscayne, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt great,'' Agassi said. ``Everything that I wanted to
do, I did, so it will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who took Monday off after winning the Ericsson,
practiced lightly Tuesday to get used to the hardcourt surface and
the different balls than he used last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be indoors and not have to deal with the humidity
like in Florida,'' Sampras said. ``I wanted to break a sweat. I'll
hit again Wednesday and Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   WHY NOT DAVIS CUP? Other sports' international competitions
attract large followings. Soccer's World Cup is the largest, but
golf's Ryder Cup also gets plenty of attention.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis Cup lags behind.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret why: the schedule. Teams play four rounds spread
over a calendar year. In 2000, for example, the 16 competing
nations began in February _ the week after the Australian Open. The
quarterfinal round is this weekend and the semifinals will be two
weekends in July _ two weeks after Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's a long wait to the final in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't really work well,'' said Todd Martin, who is
practicing with the U.S. team but likely won't play. ``If we get it
to two points a year rather than four points a year, I think it
would help.''
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe said he thinks 99 out of 100 people wouldn't know when
the next Davis Cup weekend is or why it's played over a year.
</P>
<P>
   That includes the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not acceptable,'' McEnroe said. ``It still has to
change.''
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe would like to see the tournament held over one week, or
weekend. Or hold it every other year. Or not hold it in an Olympic
year. Anything but the current format.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras thinks a Davis Cup boycott by the world's top players
would cause the International Tennis Federation to examine the
schedule. But he doesn't see that happening.
</P>
<P>
   TICKET UPDATE: A record 20,000 tickets have been sold for the
weekend, including about 11,000 for Friday. The 20,000 is the most
sold in a day since the 1990 Davis Cup final in St. Petersburg,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets remain available through the Forum box office or
Ticketmaster. U.S. Tennis Association officials said the Forum is
configured to hold 13,000, but they can raise barrier curtains and
seat 17,000. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
