<HEADLINE>
OBITUARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Casey, 81, Tax Lawyer and Lobbyist &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Casey, 81, a prominent tax lawyer in New York and
Washington, died March 31, at a nursing home in Washington. He was
81.
</P>
<P>
   Casey was a partner in several law firms: Finley, Kumble,
Underberg, Wagner &AMP; Casey in New York; Shea, Gould, Climenko &AMP;
Casey in New York, now known as Shea &AMP; Gould; and the Russell Long
Law Firm in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He was also a lobbyist, lecturer and writer with a specialty in
taxes and natural resources and railroads. Among his longtime
clients were Occidental Petroleum and Union Pacific Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   From 1987 to 1993, Casey was chairman of Marymount University in
Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Robert John Casey was born in Syracuse, N.Y., and graduated from
Syracuse University and Catholic University Law School.
</P>
<P>
   His first wife, Patricia, died in 1975. He is survived by his
wife, Barbara; two sons, Robert G. Casey of Springfield, Mass., and
Daniel Casey of Duxbury, Mass.; two stepsons, Raymond Luckey of
Washington and Michael Luckey of Atlanta; three daughters, Ellen
Deschamps of Ipswich, Mass., Martha Shugrue of New Canaan, Conn.,
and Karen O`Neill of Winter Park, Fla.; and eight grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Goldman, 78, Theatrical Producer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Byron Goldman, a garment industry executive who was better known
as a theatrical producer, died March 28 at his home in Manhattan.
He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, said a friend, Sidney Kraines.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently Goldman was a co-producer of the Broadway
production of ``Copenhagen,'' which opens April 11.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s Goldman, who was an executive with GGG
Clothes in Manhattan, a family business, was one of Broadway's most
successful angels, as investors in theater productions are known.
</P>
<P>
   He began his show-backing career in 1946 with an investment of
$1,000 in ``The Bench Warmer,'' which flopped. He made more
successful investments in shows including ``Butterflies Are Free''
and ``Hello, Dolly!''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman was born in Manhattan and earned a bachelor's degree
from New York University. No immediate survivors were known.
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
