r a BC-WTO-POLICE-SPI &LR;      04-05 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-POLICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE POLICE ADMIT THEY WEREN'T READY FOR WTO PROTESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KERY MURAKAMI  
 and KIMBERLY A.C. WILSON  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seattle police officials have formally acknowledged
that they took too much for granted and were generally overwhelmed
and outmaneuvered by protesters during last fall's World Trade
Organization conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department's initial planning and staffing were inadequate
for handing the situation that confronted the city,'' concluded a
critical 63-page self-evaluation released by the police department
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made mistakes,'' said Assistant Police Chief Clark Kimerer,
who wrote the report.
</P>
<P>
   The report was given to Interim Chief Herb Johnson, whose
predecessor, Norm Stamper, resigned over the handling of the
protests.
</P>
<P>
   Even though press reports, the city's fire department, the King
County Sheriff's office and information from the FBI warned of
massive protests, police officials placed too much stock in the
belief that the protests that occurred wouldn't happen here.
</P>
<P>
   What plans they had for major protests _ including a ``flying
squad'' of police officers to arrest instigators right off the bat_
were quickly overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   Outnumbered, police officers were forced to work long hours
without food or rest. Some, including city Ethics and Elections
Commission chairman Tim Burgess, a former Seattle Police sergeant
who serves on one of three Seattle City Council citizens' panel
reviewing the city's handling of the WTO, believe that led to
isolated incidents of over-reaction against protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Calling it a ``tough self-analysis'' by the police, Mayor Paul
Schell said he hoped the report would begin moving the city past
the controversy surrounding the conference.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged, however, that the report was only a first of
several inquiries into how a conference that was supposed to
showcase Seattle ended up filling downtown with tear gas and
leaving business owners with about $3 million in property damage
and lost sales.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd and riot control consultant hired by Schell is expected
to finish its own review of the police department and the mayor's
office in about three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council is reviewing a number of questions _ including
how the city ended up with a $9 million bill for hosting the event.
That report is not expected until July, and will by no means quell
criticism from some quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The report released Tuesday made pains to praise front-line
police officers and supervisors, saying, ``They quite literally
saved the day.''
</P>
<P>
   The report noted that ``the professionalism and restraint
displayed by police officers, supervisors and commanders on the
`front line' ... was nothing short of outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Schell added, ``They have my profound admiration and
gratitude.''
</P>
<P>
   That may improve relations with police officers who were angered
by the lack of breaks, food and equipment during the WTO
conference. But police officials Tuesday barred officers from
speaking publicly about the report.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said the use of tear gas, pepper spray and
rubber pellets against protesters represented a moderate use of
force, and were considered preferable to the alternative _ night
sticks.
</P>
<P>
   John Sellars, director of the Berkeley, Calif.,-based Ruckus
Society, one of the groups involved in the protests, said, ``I
guess we should be counting ourselves as lucky they didn't actually
kill anybody out there, that they didn't resort to using their
firearms.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer said he believed police acted responsibility in the
Capitol Hill neighborhood, where residents were caught up in the
tear gas and police violence.
</P>
<P>
   The report contends that police did not chase protesters from
downtown to Capitol Hill, as some in the neighborhood reported, but
were sent to ``shadow and monitor'' protesters and avoid contact
with them.
</P>
<P>
   Police used tear gas and pepper spray not only against
protesters but neighborhood residents. Kimerer said police were
responding to ``serious threats to public order.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, protesters vandalized buildings, and
rocked and blocked a police car.
</P>
<P>
   The report and questions from a press conference focused on the
police preparations for the event.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Assistant Police Chief Ed Joiner, who supervised the
police handling of the conference, said he put too much stock in
Seattle's history of peaceful protest.
</P>
<P>
   The report noted: ``While we needed to think about a new
paradigm of disruptive protest, we relied on our knowledge of past
demonstrations, concluding that the `worst case' would not occur
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Joiner said, ``it wasn't pretty,'' but he pointed out
the WTO was able to meet and no one was seriously injured during
the protests.
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer said police received ``skeletal, fragmented''
intelligence about the possibility of civil disorder.
</P>
<P>
   A July 7 FBI report warned there was ``a strong indication'' of
major protests at the conference, but concluded there was ``no
credible information'' to suggest there would be ``violence or
significant property damage.''
</P>
<P>
   A subsequent FBI report in mid-November found the ``threat of
violent protest activity directed at the WTO ministerial is low to
medium.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officials noted that protesters publicly trained to
``shut down'' the conference. But the report noted it's difficult
to tell rhetoric from reality. Kimerer said even the best
intelligence doesn't provide a ``crystal ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The police department did double the number of officers assigned
to deal with demonstrators, to 400. ``However,'' the report said,
``our general theory did not change: Seattle has enjoyed a history
of peaceful protest; Seattleites do not deface the places where
they live and work; and SPD can handle potential disruptions with
existing resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Police were also hampered by a lack of money.
</P>
<P>
   Internal documents obtained by the Seattle Post-Intelligencer
indicate the city knew as it was preparing for the protests that
the Seattle Host Organization _ a group of corporate leaders
sponsoring the conference _ was having trouble raising $1.5 million
it promised for security costs.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it were raised, the money was likely going to be eaten
by reimbursing businesses at the Washington State Trade and
Convention Center for closing during the conference. The report
noted that Seattle police were reluctant to ask other law
enforcement agencies for help without knowing how they would be
repaid for their time.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, planners thought they had more officers available
than they did.
</P>
<P>
   Their information did not consider officers who had approved
vacations during the week. As a result, police planners reduced the
number of officers assigned to the conference, and officers who
were to relieve line officers were eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that police had little inkling of the tactics
protesters would use. Well-equipped with walkie talkies and police
scanners, protesters were able to maneuver in response to police
actions. For instance, Joiner said, police did not expect
protesters to bar delegates from leaving their hotels.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that forced police to reassign the ``flying
squad'' of 30 officers to the convention center. Kimerer said
arresting leaders of the protest may have changed the tone of the
day's events.
</P>
<P>
   The report contended that police were hampered by a city law
barring them from gathering intelligence on Seattle citizens.
Joiner said that prevented police from infiltrating protest groups
to learn their tactics and their plans.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lessons learned, the report noted, was that the
planning and tactics used by protesters may have ushered in a new
era of such actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``From this day forward, we will use WTO as the model for future
planning,'' Kimerer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0020 </DOCNO>
