<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLAUS CONCERNED WITH WINS, NOT NUMBERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ In 1999, Troy Glaus hit 29 homers and drove in
79 runs in his first full season in the big leagues at age 22. He
has the baseball world at his feet, but Glaus didn't spend the
offseason patting himself on the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked back and said I struggled the entire season,'' he
said. ``We finished in last place. So I look at it as a
disappointing season.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus is regarded as one of the top up-and-coming third basemen
in all of baseball, so why the sour taste? He insists his numbers
only mean something if the team wins. ``If we win, it means I did
enough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus would like to improve on last season's .240 batting
average. But don't bother asking him if 30 or 40 homers is a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about it,'' he said. ``When (Mark) McGwire hit
70, do you think the next year he thought about hitting 80? When
the year ends, I'll end up with what I end up with. To me, the only
numbers that are important are wins.''
</P>
<P>
   TEST PASSED: Ken Hill passed the first test of the season,
holding the Yankees to two runs and four hits in 5 innings on
Monday night. But for Hill, who went 4-11 last season and was
bothered by arthritis in his right elbow, each start will be a new
test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy right now,'' Hill said. ``I was able to throw the
way I've thrown throughout my career. I can pitch with anybody if
I'm healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's a big ``if'' and manager Mike Scioscia realizes it.
He will hold Hill to a strict pitch limit and demand Hill be honest
with him if his elbow is hurting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny's straight up with me,'' Scioscia said. ``The only words
I want to hear after he pitches is `I'm cool,' which means he's all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   BELCHER THROWS: Pitcher Tim Belcher threw 38 pitches over two
innings in a simulated game Tuesday and said he didn't hold back.
Belcher, who is recovering from offseason surgery on his right
elbow, said he expects to make a rehab start late next week.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher went 6-8 with a 6.73 ERA last season before a muscle
tear in the elbow ended his season. Having signed a two-year, $10.2
million contract, Belcher admitted feeling bad about letting the
team down.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, I have an obligation to myself to perform
to the best of my capabilities,'' he said. ``I feel I owe a debt of
gratitude to (former GM) Billy (Bavasi), TC (former manager Terry
Collins) and everyone involved with bringing me in to this
organization. I got a nice contract and didn't do very well. Those
two guys lost their jobs because of it. I certainly feel
responsible for my 1/25th of that debacle.''
</P>
<P>
   SHORT HOPS: The average cost of a ticket to a major-league
baseball game went up 11.8 percent to $16.67 in 2000, but the
Angels' average ticket remained the same at $13.19. ... During
Belcher's simulated game, coach Orlando Mercado, who was catching
Belcher, got hit underneath his right eye by a bat on Orlando
Palmeiro's follow-through. Part of Mercado's helmet cut into the
skin, causing a gash that resulted in four stitches. ... Pitchers
Ramon Ortiz (small tear in shoulder) and Jarrod Washburn (pulled
muscle in side) will start back-to-back nights at Single-A Lake
Elsinore on rehab assignments. Ortiz, who will pitch Thursday, will
make his season debut five days later on April 11 at Edison Field.
Washburn, who will pitch Friday, is a couple of weeks away from
returning. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
