<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-3RDLD-     04-05 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 RULING PARTY PICKS No. 2 OFFICIAL TO TAKE OVER AS JAPAN PREMIER  
(EDS: Recasts top and adds fresh quotes from Mori.) 
(See also JAPAN-OBUCHI-REACT) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japan's ruling party acted quickly Wednesday morning to
pick a successor to Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, who fell into a
coma on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Party lawmakers selected Yoshiro Mori, who was second to Obuchi
in the party's heirarchy. He has also been its secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
   The parliament is to vote later Wednesday to elect him prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting his party's choice, Mori bowed to the assembly and
said, ``I am praying together with all our party members for the
quick recovery of Mr. Obuchi.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also looked ahead, saying, ``I have no intention of
delaying structural reforms.'' He is expected to continue Obuchi's
policies including giving priority to economic growth even if it
means increases in government debt.
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for the party decision, the nation's cabinet
resigned on Tuesday evening at a brief meeting. Mori is expected to
reappoint the cabinet ministers and then to turn to the onset of
government business, including economic doldrums and scheduled
diplomatic meetings.
</P>
<P>
   He will also have to act soon to set a date for new national
elections, perhaps by summer.
</P>
<P>
   Mori, 62, won support by demonstrating a strong loyalty to
Obuchi. Even more useful to him were his close ties to the party's
major coalition partner, the Buddhist-backed New Komeito. Mori's
ratification by the parliament, or Diet, is already considered a
foregone conclusion, since the coalition, led by the Liberal
Democratic Party, has a large majority.
</P>
<P>
   Mori is a lifelong party operative who, as with Obuchi before
him, gradually rose through the ranks. He was elected to parliament
in 1969 and at various times was education minister, head of the
party policy council, trade and industry minister and construction
minister. He has twice been secretary general of the Liberal
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But the portfolios that typically define the true party
heavyweights, finance minister and foreign minister, have eluded
him. Those gaps in his resume and his reputation for timidity on
policy issues have led many commentators to say they would expect
little innovation under his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Many commentators said Tuesday, however, that by choosing Mori _
a burly, raspy voiced politician not especially known for his
personal popularity or campaigning skills _ the party was taking a
huge risk in national elections that are widely expected before
summer.
</P>
<P>
   With tears streaking down his cheeks, the caretaker prime
minister, Mikio Aoki, said Tuesday afternoon that the dissolution
of the government was made ``based on the judgment of the doctors
and from the viewpoint that we should not allow even one moment's
political vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   The news came after persistent reports throughout the day that
Obuchi's condition was steadily worsening and that the prime
minister was brain dead. Aoki denied that, calling himself ``very
upset'' at news organizations for passing on rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians close to the transition process and several Japanese
political analysts said Tuesday that the governing party had used
the extraordinary 22-hour news blackout surrounding Obuchi's
hospitalization early Sunday, and the carefully stage-managed
process since, to engineer the selection of Mori as its unopposed
candidate for the succession.
</P>
<P>
   The party has a long history of running things; it has governed
the country alone or in coalitions for all but two and a half years
since 1955.
</P>
<P>
   The secretive handling of the news of Obuchi's hospitalization
and the back-room machinations drew renewed criticisms Tuesday from
several quarters, with the view that the episode revealed a side of
Japan that was neither altogether modern nor Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Mori speaks volumes, political experts say, about
unusual imperatives in Japanese politics _ loyalty to partners and
allies in a crunch _ rather than to the party's immediate political
needs and even, potentially, to its survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not that the LDP lacks people who could enjoy
popularity,'' said Masumi Ishikawa, a professor of politics at
Niigata University of International and Information Studies.
``There is Mr. Kono and Mr. Kato, both of whom would probably be
more popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Yohei Kono, the foreign minister, and Koichi Kato, a former
chief Cabinet secretary, were both believed to aspire to the prime
minister's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The LDP is basing its decision on who has a good relationship
with Komeito,'' Ishikawa, a former senior political correspondent
of the daily Asahi Shimbun, said. ``They are not thinking of the
reaction of the people of Japan, and this behavior is very
strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts were describing the Liberal Democratic Party's
choice of Mori on the basis of the New Komeito Party's comfort as a
recipe for electoral difficulties, because the coalition between
the two parties has been deeply unpopular since it was formed last
October. Opinion polls have consistently shown that Japanese voters
disapprove of having a party with religious affiliations in the
government.
</P>
<P>
   The new government will have to dissipate growing criticism of
the secretive, seemingly antiquated mechanics of a succession in
which Aoki was allowed to become caretaker merely on the basis of
what he described as a private conversation with Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
   Further contributing to the image of a process of party barons
meeting in smoke-filled rooms to keep the public in the dark was
the way in which Mori was selected.
</P>
<P>
   Some insiders spoke with almost reverential approval of the
offstage consultations that produced Mr. Mori as Mr. Obuchi's
successor, describing it as a confirmation of the efficiency of the
political system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Aoki's reaction to Obuchi's collapse was very tactful,''
said Kozo Watanabe, the deputy speaker of parliament's lower house.
``If he had waited a week or 10 days after Mr. Obuchi collapsed,
somebody else could have raised their hand as a candidate, and
there could be some chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``But by the time Mr. Aoki announced the condition of Mr.
Obuchi, it was already virtually decided who would take over.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, for independent politicians and commentators,
and indeed much of the public, the process provided a field day of
introspection about how, 55 years after World War II, Japan has
remained a democracy largely in name, rather than in spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process of choosing a successor has revealed itself as not
very democratic, and is indeed very closed,'' said Shusei Tanaka, a
political scientist at Fukuyama University in Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling is that even if the prime minister changes, the
policies won't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (js-nk)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
