<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JANITOR-STRIKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIKING JANITORS BLOCK TRAFFIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Staff Writers Donna Huffaker and Sylvia Oliande contributed to
this story) 
By TROY ANDERSON AND JASON KANDEL 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Escalating their demand for a $1-an-hour raise,
thousands of janitors walked off the job Tuesday in the San
Fernando Valley and downtown, blocking traffic and confronting
replacement workers.
</P>
<P>
   Arm-in-arm, striking janitors tried to block replacement workers
from entering Nestles offices in Glendale, north of downtown, and
DreamWorks SKG studios in Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   Strikers were expected to march about 10 p.m. in the San
Fernando Valley community of Woodland Hills outside Warner Center.
</P>
<P>
   About 8:25 a.m., about 2,500 red-shirted janitors tied up
morning commuters by blocking the northbound Harbor Freeway exit at
Sixth Street near Figueroa Street. They left peacefully when asked
to by police wearing riot gear.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police said no arrests were made, but plans were
made to call in officers from around the city to handle problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They cooperated with us to the fullest,'' said Los Angeles
police Sgt. Dave Nunez of the Central Division. ``At times, we had
to deploy our units to move them along in the intersections.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations came a day after the Service Employees
International Union Local 1877 called a strike of its 8,500
janitors Monday to demand a $1-an-hour wage hike for each of the
next three years. The janitors, who clean office buildings
citywide, now make between $6.80 and $7.80 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Contractors who hire the janitors are offering them raises of 50
cents an hour for the first year and 40 cents an hour more for the
second and third years.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 700 janitors work in the Valley, according to the
union. Contractors put the number at about 1,500, working in a
cluster mostly in Warner Center and along Ventura Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   The strike is expected to continue Wednesday as janitors march
downtown and throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The janitors are the first large group to strike in many
years,'' said union spokeswoman Blanca Gallegos. ``I think it's a
sign of the new labor movement. They are willing to go out on the
streets and take bold steps.''
</P>
<P>
   The Teamsters have sanctioned the strike, according to Paul
Mihalow of the Teamsters Joint Council 42. That means Teamsters,
including United Parcel Service delivery drivers, will not cross
picket lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we sanction it, we believe in it,'' said Mihalow,
assistant to joint council President Jim Santangelo.
</P>
<P>
   Contractors who assign janitors said they have hired
replacements and do not expect disruptions in service.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are on their merry way, demonstrating and we are on our
merry way, cleaning,'' said Dick Davis, a bargaining coordinator
representing the janitorial firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, I like all these people,'' Tim Tuttle, owner
of Peerless Building Management, said as his replacement workers
tried to enter the Nestles building in Glendale. ``But we are here
to make sure the buildings get cleaned or we'll lose contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   Jlus Serrato, 32, who works across the street for American
Building Management, said the worker action is worthwhile if it
helps with more pay and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``These shoes I have, I bought in a secondhand store,'' said
Serrato, a father of two whose wife, Carmen, works for Peerless.
``These pants, $1.75 in a secondhand store. I don't have any money
for anything. We can't go out for dinner or nothing. There's no
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the workers also won symbolic support from the Los
Angeles County Board of Supervisors, which voted 3-2 to support the
goals of the janitors, many of whom attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The supervisors called on city building owners and janitorial
contractors to ``accept their responsibility to address the gap
between the rich and the working poor'' by giving them raises.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city and this county are experiencing an unprecedented
economic boom, and there is no reason in the world why people who
sweep our buildings and clean our toilets can't be offered and
given a decent livable wage that lifts them out of poverty,'' said
Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky, who introduced the motion.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Yvonne Brathwaite Burke said she supported the motion
because her father was a janitor for 28 years. She said she sits on
the board ``only as a result of the kind of actions by the unions
who made sure there were adequate wages for people who were working
in menial jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Supervisors Don Knabe and Michael D. Antonovich voted against
the motion.
</P>
<P>
   Knabe said he thought it was inappropriate to enter into
``somebody else's fight'' when the county is preparing to negotiate
contracts with its own employees.
</P>
<P>
   Antonovich said the vote panders to the unions and interferes
with the collective bargaining process between employers and
employees.
</P>
<P>
   To help those striking, the union has established a $1 million
strike fund, and the county Federation of Labor has set up food
banks for families with breadwinners out of work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
