<HEADER>
A7448 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-SOCAL-MARKET-REACT-LA     04-05 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCAL-MARKET-REACT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCAL INVESTORS, COMPANIES RIDE OUT THE STORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Staff Writer Jason Cohn contributed to this story) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY AND JASON TAKENOUCHI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The mood among local investors and publicly traded
companies was calm Tuesday, quite a contrast from Wall Street which
suffered through its most volatile trading day in history.
</P>
<P>
   Elliot Carmen, for example, was at the Charles Schwab office in
Encino on Tuesday to open an account for his son, not to liquidate
his holdings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I invest for the long term,'' said the school bus driver.
``I'm not in (the market) to buy today and sell today.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tuesday was a day that no one had seen before. While the
Nasdaq composite index ended the day down ``only'' 74.79 points,
earlier in the day it had slid as much as 574.57 points, or 13
percent, to 3,649.11. The 634-point swing from its high in positive
territory to its low was the biggest ever for the Nasdaq and
followed Monday's 349.15-point drop.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which early in the day was
nearly 200 points in the black, closed down 57.09 points after
falling as much as 504.15 _ or 4.5 percent _ to 10,717.78 earlier.
The day's 700.46-point swing was also a record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was panic out there for a while,'' said Ross Gerber,
manager of the Woodland Hills office of Sun America Securities.
``The reality was as soon as prices dropped to levels people were
comfortable with they came in and bought.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Shaw of Sylmar agreed, and said he's still hoping shares
of Microsoft come down to a more comfortable level. Monday's court
ruling against Microsoft is blamed by many analysts as the catalyst
for this week's sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll come in on Microsoft when it hits $60 later this month,''
said Shaw, who stopped by the Schwab office to check his account
before heading to work at the Great Earth Vitamins store at
Panorama City Mall.
</P>
<P>
   While investors were riding out the market's wild swings
Tuesday, it was business as usual for MiniMed Inc., a Los
Angeles-based medical device maker.
</P>
<P>
   MiniMed officials said the company does not discuss the market
or the company's stock price with its employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take a very conservative approach,'' said Deanne Roth,
manager of corporate services. ``It's our policy not to comment on
stock prices and the volatility.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Valley companies have taken a slightly different tack.
</P>
<P>
   At a regular monthly address Monday to his company's employees,
Homestore.com Inc. Chief Financial Officer John Geiske centered on
market volatility and what it means, and does not mean, for the
company based in Thousand Oaks in neighboring Ventura County.
</P>
<P>
   Geiske said his address _ transmitted via an internal network to
Homestore.com offices across the country _ tried to alleviate any
concerns employees may have had about market volatility. He said he
emphasized the fact that Homestore.com is in a volatile industry
and that price swings did not mean the company had fundamental
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to make sure people aren't overly sensitive,'' he said.
``It was a very timely discussion, particularly in light of what
happened today.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock closed down $5.93 at $40.12 on volume of 1.4
million shares on the Nasdaq exchange.
</P>
<P>
   At Internet World at the Los Angeles Convention Center,
tech-heads from across the nation were more interested in the
latest online wizardry than the action on Wall Street. After all,
the millions of dollars they lost and then gained back during
Tuesday's wild swing was all on paper anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volatility is to be expected,'' said Roger Sawhney, director
of zgraffiti.com. ``There is going to be a shakeout. You are
already seeing that in the (business-to-consumer) space.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The market leaders are going to do very well,'' Sawhney added.
</P>
<P>
   Murali Prahalad, director of business development at the
Bethesda, Md.,-based company said, ``Profitability will matter. The
online world is going to look a lot like the off-line world.''
</P>
<P>
   As for today, local brokers expect investors to snap up the
bargains.
</P>
<P>
   After the last couple of days, it becomes ``an opportunity to
get into an issue that you've been waiting to get into,'' said
Gerber.
</P>
<P>
   Richard L. Paler, branch manager of Charles Schwab's Encino
office, said, ``The only thing I expect is it's going to be another
very busy day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
