<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7453 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HN     04-05 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
PITTSBURGH _ The frigid conditions at Three Rivers Stadium on
Tuesday made it feel more like Christmas Day than opening day.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And to that end, we now know what was waiting under the tree for
Richard Hidalgo, whose mighty bat all but gift-wrapped the Astros'
first victory of the millennium, a 5-2 walk over the Pittsburgh
Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   Santa brought Hidalgo a familiar gift _ Pirates righthander
Jason Schmidt, who is perhaps Hidalgo's favorite toy among
major-league pitchers. Hidalgo drove in all five of the Astros'
runs with a double and a grand slam that broke the game open in the
sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God he came,'' Astros second baseman Craig Biggio said
of Hidalgo. ``If Richard didn't play in this game, we would have
been in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was the Pirates who had their opening day ruined for
the second night in a row. Mother Nature wiped out Monday's
scheduled opener, and Hidalgo and Co. put a damper on things
Tuesday. Hidalgo's blast over the left-field wall was the first
opening-day grand slam in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds also made a little Astros history, tying J.R.
Richard and Mike Scott with his fifth opening-day pitching
assignment. Reynolds, who is 3-1 with a no-decision in opening-day
starts, worked seven strong innings and allowed six hits, including
John Vander Wal's pinch-hit two-run homer in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of pre-game introductions, a ceremonial first pitch by
Bill Mazeroski and a soulful rendition of the national anthem by
Pittsburgh native Christina Aguilera, the too-little, too-late
homer was all the hometown crowd had to cheer in the final
opening-day game at Three Rivers Stadium, which will be made
obsolete next season by PNC Park.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if Hidalgo starts a petition to halt plans
for demolishing the 30-year-old multipurpose stadium. Hidalgo has a
.476 lifetime batting average at the Pirates' digs, and he has more
home runs (five) and RBIs (11) at Three Rivers than in any other
opposing yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked hitting in this ballpark,'' Hidalgo said.
``I see the ball well here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo, who missed the final two months of the 1999 season
because of knee surgery, was 3-for-4 with five RBIs and came within
a triple of hitting for the cycle. His eyes must light up like the
morning sun at the sight of Schmidt, against whom the 24-year-old
outfielder has a career .636 batting average, with three home runs
in just 11 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schmidt throws mostly hard stuff, and Richard likes to hit the
fastball,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt's biggest nemesis _ other than Hidalgo _ was his
control, which was a bit out of the ordinary for the 27-year-old
righthander, who averaged 3.5 walks per nine innings last season.
He had six walks in six innings Tuesday, and four of the free
passes led directly to runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schmidt is not a wild pitcher,'' Dierker said. ``But on a
(cold) night like this, any pitcher can get wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker was fortunate not to have that problem with the three
pitchers he sent to the mound. Reynolds and relievers Doug Henry
and Billy Wagner combined for just three walks despite a wind-chill
factor that dipped to 10 by game's end, making the ball slick and
difficult to manipulate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely cold, but everyone had to fight it,'' said
Wagner, who worked a scoreless ninth inning to earn the save.
``It's not often that you're warming up in the eighth inning and it
starts snowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Hidalgo, Schmidt's stormy weather started much
earlier. Schmidt retired the Astros in order in the first inning
but led off the second by walking third baseman Ken Caminiti, who
showed just how good his 36-year-old legs have been feeling by
scoring from first base on Hidalgo's double down the left-field
line.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates attempted a two-out rally in the bottom of the
second, but their hopes of tying the game on Mike Benjamin's single
to left were gunned down when Bill Spiers threw out Chad Hermansen
at home plate for the final out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Spiers was a late addition to the lineup because of soreness in
center fielder Roger Cedeno's right elbow. Hidalgo moved from left
to center, and Spiers started in left. The move was something of a
gamble by Dierker considering Spiers didn't play a single inning in
the outfield during spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised when they asked me about it, but I told them
that I could handle it,'' Spiers said. ``Making that throw actually
relaxed me, just to get that out of the way. I played out there
enough last year to where it didn't feel strange to be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio, Jeff Bagwell and Caminiti worked Schmidt for walks in
the sixth inning before Hidalgo delivered the punishment. One has
to wonder if Schmidt's concentration was affected by a 12-minute
delay to repair some padding behind the home-plate area. Two of the
walks, not to mention the homer, came after the delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might have bothered me,'' Schmidt said, ``but who knows?
The main thing is I didn't throw strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, who retired 19 of the 28 batters he faced, lost his
shutout bid with two out in the seventh inning on the 14th
pinch-hit homer of Vander Wal's career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane was great,'' Dierker said. ``To start on the road and in
this kind of weather, we could have seen the same thing (the
Pirates saw with Schmidt). But he pitched a strong game. If he
would have still had the shutout going, I would have kept him out
there, but I thought that maybe he was getting a little tired.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
