<HEADER>
A7454 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-05 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INDIANAPOLIS _ It was a vertical leap of faith.
</P>
<P>
   The Flintstones, fresh off a bare-knuckles, ground-assault
affair with Wisconsin in the national semifinals, transformed
themselves into the Jetsons right before the nation's collective
eyes Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Gators wanted to run and jump? A missile-to-missile
war? The Gators wanted to press the pace and raise the rpms?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, we can do that, the Michigan State Spartans emphatically
said with their play in Monday night's NCAA championship game.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators want to launch a few 3s? The Gators want to lean on
their guards? Sure, we'll play that game, too. And the Spartans
went on to an amazing 11-of-22 night from 3-point range while
holding Florida's starting guards scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was only one championship-caliber team on the floor
tonight,'' Florida guard Teddy Dupay said. ``And it wasn't us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Spartans. And in the aftermath of Michigan State's
thorough 89-76 win over Florida, we are reminded that champions can
be measured several ways, but no gauge is more important than
versatility and the ability to adapt.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State showed us. In a pair of equally impressive _ if
drastically different _ victories in Indianapolis, Tom Izzo's
Spartans gave us a capsule look at their entire year.
</P>
<P>
   One night, the Spartans played the Neanderthal game, the
Flintstones game. They chugged through the Badgers' ridiculous
scratching, clawing and crawling pace but won easily.
</P>
<P>
   Two nights later, they beat the alleged best running and
pressing team in the land. They outran and outdefended the Gators
at every turn and won easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they ran through our press the way they did,'' Gators
forward Mike Miller said, ``I knew it could be trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Transition scoring in the Spartans' win Monday night was a
stunning 27-4 in MSU's favor. Their 89 points were the most given
up by the Gators all year.
</P>
<P>
   One night, MSU guard Mateen Cleaves played the calm, patient
game. He walked the ball upcourt, surveyed overmatched Wisconsin
and pummeled the opponent toe-to-toe like his name was George
Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   Two nights later, Cleaves turned into George Jetson. He pulled
all sorts of gadgets out of his game, blasting past overmatched
Florida guards and leaving the Gators' press all shriveled up and
gasping.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans didn't commit a turnover in Monday night's title
game until they already had built a double-digit lead. They shot
nearly 56 percent. The MSU bench stepped up for 16 points against a
team said to be much deeper. Easy baskets led to wide-open jumpers
and vice versa. The pace was wild, but the Spartans always seemed
to be in control.
</P>
<P>
   ``People forget,'' Izzo said, ``we like to run, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Or not. Whatever it takes.
</P>
<P>
   If the Gators were going to win this championship, there was
only one way they were going to do it _ running, pressing and
hitting 3s.
</P>
<P>
   But the Spartans stormed to the title because they had the
ability to march to the beat of any drum, whether it was the slow
death-march kind of cadence of a Wisconsin or the rolling
double-time beat of a Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made us make mistakes we usually don't make,'' Gators
center Udonis Haslem said. ``They got the best of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans got the best of every team they faced, no matter
the style. That's the true measure of a champion.
</P>
<P>
   That's also the biggest reason you have to believe these
Spartans would have been doing the same dance and holding the same
Sears Trophy even if Cincinnati could have had Kenyon Martin in the
NCAA Tournament or Duke could have escaped the Gators in the East
Regional final.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it would have been fun watching MSU try to exact revenge
in the Final Four against Duke, which ousted the Spartans in the
semifinals last year. And if Florida's Haslem could score 27 points
inside against the Spartans, imagine what Martin might have done.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter, you have to believe this MSU team would have
adapted and conquered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of took it upon ourselves to show that we can run the
same-style game that Florida likes,'' MSU forward Morris Peterson
said. ``Nobody has been able to press us all year, so when they
pressed, we looked at it as something we could take advantage of.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it takes. It's what the Spartans did all year, and it's
the true measure of a champion.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
