<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7455 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-MASTERS-NORMAN-HN     04-05 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NORMAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDDIE SEFKO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Usually, a golfer becomes identified with a
tournament because of unbridled success at the event.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Furyk is everybody's annual pick at the Las Vegas
Invitational because of the way he thrives in the desert. Davis
Love III has made the MCI Classic his personal playground. Tiger
Woods is the honorary mayor when he shows up at oh, any tournament
he wants to show up at.
</P>
<P>
   But it's less common that a player becomes well-linked to a
tournament because he hasn't won it.
</P>
<P>
   Such is Greg Norman's notoriety at the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   While Norman prefers to remember good times, it is a crowd of
ghosts that jam the memories of fans and even other players as they
prepare for the 2000 edition of the tournament at golf's most
hallowed shrine. This will be Norman's 20th appearance at Augusta
National. It isn't accurate to say that all of the previous 19 have
been disappointing. But with three second-place finishes and three
thirds, there have been more than a few letdowns, collapses, upsets
or all three.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's just a shame that he hasn't won it, because
he's such a great player,'' Woods said Tuesday. ``To win as many
tournaments as he has around the world _ and to be as great a
champion as he's been for a number of years _ all the heartbreaks
he's had in this tournament are a shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's his own doing or other players pulling off shots,
he's been there so many times with a chance to win. It's tough for
me to imagine somebody going through all that and coming back again
and again and putting himself in position to win again without
having won.
</P>
<P>
   ``That, to me, is a credit to the kind of person he is, what
kind of inside he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman has never given up the quest for a green jacket. And he
still has that yearning fire inside of him. That in itself is
amazing to some, considering his history at Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think of Greg, and you realize he's put himself there _ in
position to win _ so many times, probably 10 or 12 times,'' said
David Duval. ``It's not routine. But it's almost like it's routine.
He's been there a lot. And not to win it ''
</P>
<P>
   Duval shook his head and didn't have to finish the thought. It's
a painful sight. Whether looking back at 1996 when his final-round
78 was one of the most famous meltdowns of all time and let Nick
Faldo slip away with the win, or Larry Mize's 140-foot chip-in in
'87, or last year when Norman simply wasn't quite good enough to
catch Jose Maria Olazabal, no matter what he does, Norman can't
seem to win the prize.
</P>
<P>
   But 2000 is no different than the past 19 years. Norman is back
at the Masters. And he's ready to fire all his bullets again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want this tournament,'' he said. ``If I thought about
all that (bad times), I'd go crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman is facing up to the fact that his chances to win a
Masters are running out. At age 45, he figures he has eight more
major championships _ two years' worth _ before he'll likely be
playing out the string on the regular PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings Norman to one of his favorite subjects, a prodigy
of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   While he is well into the autumn of his career, he is becoming
close friends with 19-year-old fellow Australian Aaron Baddeley.
Norman stops short of calling himself a mentor. He doesn't work
with Baddeley with the physical aspects of the game. But he's there
to answer any question about the mental part of golf and life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was his age, I was still on a surfboard,'' Norman said.
``I really like his demeanor, his determination and his willingness
to learn and improve. When you want something bad enough, you're
going to do everything in your power to get it. And he's very
willing to ask questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was at my house for that period (during the Florida
swing on tour), anything he wanted to talk about _ from life in
general to management to golf to caddies to girlfriends to getting
married _ we talked about. I was like that when I was a kid. I
would never have any fear of going to ask Jack Nicklaus or Lee
Trevino or Ray Floyd or the CEO of a company for advice. And when I
saw that in Aaron, I knew this kid was going to go a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't hurt that Baddeley already has won the Australian
Open as an amateur at age 18, three months ago. Now he's at
Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I've dreamed of doing ever since I started
playing when I was 12 or 13,'' Baddeley said. ``I wanted to play at
Augusta, play in the British Open, play in the PGA and have a
chance to win these events.''
</P>
<P>
   Baddeley proved greatness wasn't far away when he won the
Australian Open _ beating Norman and other notable Australian
players, not to mention a handful of American pros _ to win the
national championship in his home country.
</P>
<P>
   And this week, Baddeley wants to win, despite his
wet-behind-the-ears status. But if he doesn't win, he's rooting for
Norman.
</P>
<P>
   ``My expectations for the week are that if I can focus on one
shot, one hole, one round at a time and then be in contention on
Sunday, I want to win the golf tournament,'' Baddeley said. ``I
remember Tiger said the same thing. He said he was here to win. And
I'm exactly the same way. I don't see the point of entering a golf
tournament if you don't think you can win.''
</P>
<P>
   But if he doesn't, Baddeley is in Norman's corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg's come so close so many times here. I want to see him win
the golf tournament,'' Baddeley said. ``He deserves it in a way. It
would be a fitting end to his career for him to win the green
jacket.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured both the young and the old of Australia will come
out with guns blazing.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
