</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A TALL TEXAN MUST LEAD THIS DRIVE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Subs for updating, rewriting throughout) By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ As an imported New York Yankee, Roger Clemens
has worked hard to fit into their championship cast, to be himself,
the down-home Texan and hard-throwing Rocket. Now if only Cy Young
will revisit his right arm, and make him whole.
</P>
<P>
   He looked more like himself here on Tuesday night but bad
fielding by the Yankees' B team defense cost him a sixth shutout
inning against the Angels and left him with a no-decision in a
Yankees' 5-3 victory on Bernie Williams' two-run homer in the ninth
inning at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   These things happen, and Clemens wasn't about to complain about
Clay Bellinger's throwing error that set up two unearned runs, and
Ricky Ledee's senseless throw home that put a third run into
scoring position. Not after the way the Yankees pulled him along
through the gates of World Series heaven last October, when a year
of pitching dangerously had quite the climactic ending, even if it
came without the rest of the storybook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to the ring ceremonies when we get back
home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens redeemed himself against Atlanta for his modest
performance last season (14-10, 4.60 earned run average), or at
least that was the spin on the postseason pitch. He was forgiven
for his excellent impersonation of an aging power pitcher. He
earned the ring. Now comes what could be a trickier process,
deserving a raise.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't talk about next year, and neither do the Yankees, but
it is out there, the belief that George Steinbrenner made an
agreement with Clemens' agents, Randy and Alan Hendricks, to extend
his contract upon acquiring him last spring. Steinbrenner is not
likely to treat two leveraged agents from the powerhouse SFX the
way he would the politicians who are trying to get his commitment
to remain in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Boss has been known to use other methods of
dealing with star players (see Winfield, Dave) who have him backed
into a financial corner but don't meet his level of performance
expectation.
</P>
<P>
   Like any sure-fire Hall of Famer, Clemens has flattering goals
for himself, another 20 victories that would accelerate his pace to
300, from his current 247. But he's also tasted Champagne now, got
high on Yankee success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've won 20 numerous times and five Cy Youngs,'' he said. ``If
it means 15-15 and having the opportunity to pitch in the World
Series, that overrides any individual achievements.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't awful last season, just not the pitcher selected to
baseball's All Century team. The Yankees sure made their share of
excuses for Clemens. He was trying too hard and he was struggling
with location and pitching to a new set of catchers.
</P>
<P>
   The truth was, as David Cone said, ``We didn't see his good
splitter and slider last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for him, there was never an urgency for the Clemens of
old. Even in the three postseason series, by the time he pitched,
the Yankees had their claws around the opposition's throat. In the
end, that was Cy Young Clemens out there against the Braves, and
his mother, Bess, who suffers from emphysema, traveled to see him
pitch, and back home in Houston, his winter days were filled with
more ``way-to-gos'' than ever.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't watched the tape of Game 4, because the off-season, he
said, is about family and fatherhood. ``I'm not the Rocket to
them,'' he said of his four children. Then again, they are named
Koby, Kory, Kacy and Kody, so down-home dad very likely has more
invested in Rocket-hood than he lets on.
</P>
<P>
   Cone called him ``the greatest pitcher of our generation,'' and
remarked how strange it was to hear him booed in Boston, in Texas,
and when he struggled in New York. ``It was like he didn't have a
home,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston last week, Clemens had the whole team out to his
house. Cone has sensed greater comfort and a larger leadership role
for Clemens this spring, and still sees remarkable arm strength for
a 37-year-old pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens struck out seven on Tuesday night. He reached 96 on the
radar gun. It was a good start, but it could get hot and sticky if
he doesn't pitch with a vintage flourish. For one thing, the
Yankees might actually find themselves in a pennant race. For
another, Cone, also 37, and a virtual reservoir of good Yankee
will, could have as good a year, or better, and not get an
invitation to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing unusual, not that much different than last year,''
Clemens described the spring on the eve of his 2000 debut.
</P>
<P>
   It is different, though. Clemens rode a bandwagon last season,
and took a big bow at the finish. This time around, he has to help
steer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (sw) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
