<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ROBLEDO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ WOULD BE NICE FIT FOR L.A. GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There have been indications in the past week that
Mexican striker Luis Hernandez will be the next foreign allocation
to the Galaxy, but Ivan Gazidis, Major League Soccer's executive
vice president in charge of player acquisitions, remains mum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have no comment on negotiations with Mexican players,''
Gazidis said Tuesday. ``I want to make sure that the deals we have
as possibilities are not prejudiced, so that that we can bring the
best product to our fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Gazidis said bringing a Mexican player to Los
Angeles is a high priority. He also said that if it happened, a
player wouldn't be available until May, when the Mexican season
ends.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez's name was brought up weeks ago, but he was believed
to be too expensive and courting a career in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Yet three Galaxy officials confirmed last week that Hernandez is
a serious option. Hernandez remains under contract with his Mexican
team, Tigres, for another year, but Tigres apparently could use the
type of transfer fee money Hernandez would command.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who said months ago he would rather play in Europe
than the MLS, reportedly is starting to rethink his options since
he is not getting the offers in Europe he had hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez could also use the MLS as a way to get to Europe. The
MLS has served as a good feeder program for European teams. New
England's Joe-Max Moore, San Jose's Eddie Lewis and Tampa Bay's
Frankie Hejduk used the MLS to get overseas. Fourteen current and
former U.S. players are now playing in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, despite its recent success in past World Cups and
international play, doesn't have a reputation for sending players
to Europe. Rafael Marquez, who plays for Monaco in France, is the
lone Mexican overseas.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Hernandez is a player the Galaxy desperately wants,
and for all the right reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Known for his long flowing blond hair, Hernandez is as instantly
recognizable as former Galaxy (and Mexican) goalie Jorge Campos.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez is so popular in Mexico that he would draw 5,000 to
10,000 more people to the Rose Bowl per game. He's a bigger
attraction than either Campos or Carlos Hermosillo were.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, adored because of his work habits and finishing
skills, would bring instant credibility to the team in the mind of
the knowledgeable fan. He's 32 and in his prime, not one of the
many aging foreign allocations MLS has signed in the past.
</P>
<P>
   And imagine a Galaxy front line of Cobi Jones, Clint Mathis and
Hernandez. There would be some magical nights for those three
speedy forwards.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez gets those kind of goals you don't expect, mostly from
sheer hustle. And he always seems to be in the right place at the
right time because of his deep understanding of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy will receive some good news sometime in the next two
months. Mauricio Cienfuegos is close to earning his green card,
which will strip him of his foreign status with the Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   In the event the Galaxy does acquire Hernandez or another
foreign player through an MLS acquisition, the Galaxy will be free
to seek another foreigner as a discovery player because of
Cienfuegos' new status.
</P>
<P>
   Last season Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid showed his eye for talent
by signing New Zealander Simon Elliott as a foreign discovery
player. Schmid's next foreign discovery player will likely be a
young midfielder or striker. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fred J. Robledo covers soccer for the San Gabriel Valley Tribune.
His column appears every Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
