<HEADER>
A7460 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT &LR;      04-05 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES TOP ANGELS, 5-3 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Serving in a role he hates, Bernie Williams
found himself pacing during Monday's season opener, when a sore
triceps muscle forced him to be the designated hitter. Williams
tried to keep occupied between at-bats, going back and forth to the
clubhouse, but nothing worked and he went hitless in four at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams somehow found a way to relax on Tuesday night,
hitting two doubles before breaking a tie with a two-run homer in
the ninth inning, as the Yankees edged Anaheim, 5-3, to salvage a
decent performance by Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander walked five in seven innings but struck out
seven. All of the three runs he allowed were unearned.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Percival, the Anaheim closer, came on in the ninth inning
and retired the first two batters. Paul O'Neill then pulled a
single through the right side of the infield, bringing Williams to
the plate. Williams had doubled and scored in the fourth and
doubled home a run in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   This time he reached over the plate and slammed a long drive
that curled toward the left-field foul pole. It stayed just inside,
prompting the Yankees' dugout to erupt, with most of the players
raising their arms before spilling out to greet Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Rivera pitched a perfect ninth inning for his second
save in two nights, preserving a victory for Ramiro Mendoza. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius was scratched from the starting lineup after
straining a rib cage muscle during batting practice, and Clay
Bellinger replaced him, making a couple of nice plays in the early
innings to help Clemens through some trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' first pitch was a fastball high and outside _ something
he did constantly last season, when he seemed to be overthrowing
and losing command in the first two innings. Darin Erstad,
Anaheim's leadoff batter, singled and Adam Kennedy followed with a
single. And as Mo Vaughn struck out, Kennedy stole second. Clemens
walked Tim Salmon, the bases were loaded and it was an instant
replay of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But Clemens discovered his split-fingered fastball, a weapon he
rarely had at his disposal last season. He struck out Garret
Anderson and Troy Glaus, shouting and raising a fist as he ran off
the field. Clemens continued to get in and out of trouble in the
middle innings, filling the bases with runners, whom the Angels
left stranded. Bellinger fielded a grounder to start a double play
in the second, Vaughn bounced into another double play in the third
and Salmon grounded out with two runners on in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens had seven strikeouts, four walks and a 2-0 lead through
five and two-thirds innings. He walked Scott Spiezio, however,
before Bengie Molina topped a bouncer along the third-base line.
Bellinger rushed in, gloved the ball and threw it away. With
runners on second and third, Gary DiSarcina, who had a career
average of .186 against Clemens, singled through the middle to
drive in both runs and tie the score. He took second when Ricky
Ledee missed the cutoff man while throwing home. Erstad singled to
center and the Angels led, 3-2, all the runs unearned.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees tied the score immediately. Derek Jeter singled and
swiped second. O'Neill walked and Williams laced his second double
of the game into the left field, scoring Jeter. The Yankees had
second and third and one out.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Scioscia, the Anaheim manager, elected to intentionally
walk Tino Martinez and then call for Mark Petkovsek _ a
sinkerballer who prompts opposing batters to hit ground balls _ to
face Ledee. Just as Scioscia had hoped, Ledee grounded into a
double play.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels loaded the bases on two broken-bat hits and a two-out
walk in the bottom of the seventh, and the catcher Bengie Molina
grounded slowly toward third; the go-ahead run was coming home. But
Bellinger darted in, barehanded the ball and threw to first to end
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Williams mentioned how much he hates being the designated hitter
as he rests the sore triceps in his right arm. Unable to work off
his nervous energy while playing his position, he rode an exercise
bike and hit off a tee .
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of the Yankees' hitters seemed to be anxious. Facing
Ken Hill on Monday and then Kent Bottenfield on Tuesday night, the
Yankees would patiently wait through pitches and get ahead in the
count, before swinging at some offerings out of the strike zone and
dribbling weak groundouts or lifting popups.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, Jeter, Shane Spencer and others were guilty of
this in the first two games, a trend that manifested itself in the
Yankees' production: They accumulated nine hits in the first 14
innings of this series, winning Monday only because O'Neill and
Spencer smacked home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield shut out the Yankees for three innings, before
Williams finally charged the offense with one out in the fourth,
reaching out and poking a line drive toward the right-field corner
and sliding into second with a double. Martinez drew a walk, and it
seemed that Bottenfield might escape the jam when Ledee fouled out.
</P>
<P>
   But Bottenfield, who had been challenging the catcher Jorge
Posada with high fastballs in his first at-bat, left one over the
middle of the plate. Posada singled through the middle, allowing
Williams to score with a sweeping slide.
</P>
<P>
   As Hill had done on Monday, Bottenfield drove his pitch count
over 80 by sixth inning, the Yankees forcing the David Wells
lookalike to labor. O'Neill singled sharply off Vaughn's glove
leading off the sixth, and after a fielder's choice left Williams
at first with one out, Martinez smashed a breaking ball toward the
right-field wall. Salmon approached the fence apprehensively and
the ball fell in and ricocheting back toward the infield. Williams
scored easily and Martinez pulled into third with a triple.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees failed to add more runs in the inning, however,
after Ledee and Bellinger both struck out. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
