<HEADER>
A7462 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LAPD-RAMPART-2TAKES-L     04-05 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAPD-RAMPART-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D.A. LEFT OUT AS FEDS, LAPD PROBE RAMPART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG GITTRICH AND BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ LAPD and federal officials have agreed to set up a
joint task force for possible Rampart Division scandal prosecutions
without the participation of the District Attorney's Office, the
Daily News has learned.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, the strongest indication yet that federal civil
rights prosecutions are likely, is in line with Police Chief
Bernard C. Parks' effort last month to use the U.S. Attorney's
Office as a clearinghouse to make sure statements made by officers
against their will cannot be used against them or other officers.
</P>
<P>
   It was that proposal that prompted District Attorney Gil
Garcetti to accuse Parks of refusing to cooperate with his office _
a charge the chief has denied _ and left relations between police
and local prosecutors fragile.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks since the controversy erupted, sources close to the
investigation said the District Attorney's Office has taken little
interest in setting up a task force for joint investigation of
possible crimes by Los Angeles Police Department officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The LAPD is involved. The U.S. attorney is involved. The FBI
is involved. The D.A. is not involved. It's the U.S. attorney's
protocol, and the D.A. can get involved at any time,'' said a
senior source close to the new task force.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD Cmdr. David Kalish acknowledged that the task force was
being formed with FBI agents, LAPD detectives and federal
prosecutors with no previous connection to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the team will not have access to statements that
officers made without being given the right to remain silent.
Because officers cannot invoke Fifth Amendment protection in
administrative proceedings, their statements in these matters
cannot become the basis of criminal prosecutions. Neither can
evidence derived as a result of the compelled statements.
</P>
<P>
   One official close to the probe said the role of the District
Attorney's Office has not been determined. ``It hasn't been sorted
out,'' the official remarked.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney's Office spokeswoman Sandi Gibbons said she
was unaware of a formal invitation by the U.S. attorney to
participate in the federal ``clean team,'' adding that Garcetti
already has a similar operation in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working very closely with the U.S. attorney, the
attorney general and the LAPD,'' Gibbons said. ``Everyone is
talking and on board.''
</P>
<P>
   However, she said there has been no cross-deputization of
prosecutors, which would be required for members of the district
attorney's staff to work directly on the federal government's clean
team.
</P>
<P>
   She said the district attorney and his deputies remain the
prosecutors of state crimes while the U.S. Attorney's Office deals
with federal crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons said creation of a federal team does not mean the U.S.
attorney is taking over the Rampart corruption investigation, but
only that the federal government is positioning itself for possible
prosecutions under federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Kalish said the LAPD has named seven people so far to
participate with federal officials on the clean team and hopes the
new task force will be up and running within a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The LAPD is totally committed to working with the
representatives of the various agencies in this endeavor,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti's claim that Parks refused to cooperate with his office
prompted a Police Commission investigation that still is pending.
Parks insisted he was merely trying to set up a clean team with the
U.S. attorney and intended to supply whatever information
Garcetti's staff wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons said U.S. Attorney Alejandro N. Mayorkas and Garcetti
talk frequently, but that the issue of a joint task force has not
been broached. She described a joint meeting scheduled for Thursday
by federal and state prosecutors as routine.
</P>
<P>
   Mayorkas spokesman Thom Mrozek declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   If district attorney's representatives do not join the task
force, the LAPD will continue to provide them with all the
information they request, Kalish said.
</P>
<P>
   One source, however, said it would be more difficult to run
parallel investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is more efficient if you have one team,'' the source added.
</P>
<P>
   Creation of the new federal task force represents the clearest
sign the federal government is taking a greater interest and role
in the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This indicates this is a serious investigation and that they
are handling it professionally,'' said Loyola Law School professor
Laurie Levenson, a former federal prosecutor. ``They're conducting
the investigation in a way that shows they're anticipating there
could be criminal charges down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Essentially the U.S. attorney's protocol calls for a ``clean
team'' and a ``dirty team.''
</P>
<P>
   The dirty team works downtown and is supervised on the LAPD side
by Cmdr. Dan Schatz. All of the evidence of police corruption
starts on the ``dirty'' side, where it is reviewed separately by
teams of LAPD detectives, FBI agents and assistant U.S. attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Before passing along information to the clean team, assistant
U.S. attorneys on the dirty team remove any evidence that cannot be
legally used to win indictments and convictions. Most notably,
compelled statements made by LAPD officers at administrative
hearings or when being administratively interviewed by their
superiors must be removed or ``cleaned'' from the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The clean team gets only evidence considered legally usable in
prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Weisselberg, a law professor at the University of
California at Berkeley, said courts have overturned convictions
because evidence was tainted by compelled testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The best-known reversal for that reason came when the conviction
of Lt. Col. Oliver North, the central figure in the Iran-Contra
scandal of the late 1980s, was struck down.
</P>
<P>
   ``His conviction was overturned because it was determined by the
court that members of the Independent Counsel's Office had not
shown that evidence they introduced against him at trial was free
of statements he made during his immunized congressional
testimony,'' Weisselberg said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
