<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEETING WITH MARTINEZ RESULTS IN COOL RECEPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Without hesitation, Alex Rodriguez had the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit, beginning of the '96 season,'' he said. ``Had to have
been 25 degrees.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners shortstop fouled back a Detroit pitch that sent a
vibration through the bat handle to his hands that delivered
fleeting thoughts of relief through amputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt so bad,'' he said of his coldest moment in a baseball
uniform, ``that I pretended that I had cracked my bat, so I could
walk back to the dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was stalling until the ache went away. He brushed off
the batboy's offerings, went all the way to the bat rack and stuck
in his bat, then pulled it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long walk to the dugout, too,'' he said. ``I needed
every second.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Tennyson alleged that spring is when a young man's
fancy lightly turns to thoughts of love, he never had to turn on an
0-2 forkball with a frozen tree branch.
</P>
<P>
   That is what awaits the new generation of Mariners players in
Seattle, where the game has gone cold.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite his Detroit experience and his Miami roots,
Rodriguez is cool about baseball frigidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I don't mind it,'' he said. ``I take it as a personal
challenge. I take a lot of pride in playing well when conditions
are bad. The weather can affect some guys. They don't want to play
as much. Maybe I can take advantage if they aren't as prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   A stalwart sentiment, but one that really didn't get tested
Tuesday night. Owing to the facts that it was the season opener as
well as a matchup of the two most successful pitchers in the
American League over the last half-decade, everyone at the Guilty
Pleasure was on high alert.
</P>
<P>
   Adrenaline is a wonderful source of warmth.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Mariners, neither body fluids nor muscles
were worth anything against Pedro Martinez, who shut down the party
Tuesday night faster than a SWAT team. His two-hit, 2-0 stuffing of
the Mariners was, as form charts go, dead-on.
</P>
<P>
   Neither he nor Jamie Moyer, the Mariners' almost equally
effective starter, were bothered by the chill. As Mariners pitching
coach Bryan Price put it afterward, ``I never worry about that for
starters. The pitcher and catcher are the only two people in the
park who are warm.''
</P>
<P>
   For an April evening alongside Puget Sound, it probably doesn't
get any better. Tuesday night was beach weather _ 50 degrees at
game time, with a breeze from the north and a mix of sun and
clouds.
</P>
<P>
   OK, beach weather for an orca. Still, it could have been worse.
And it will be _ start time was two hours earlier than normal,
thanks to national TV. Team management was so twitchy about a
momentary pregame sprinkle spoiling the evening that the roof was
closed despite the absence of a real weather threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the roof closed, there's a noticeable temperature change,
maybe 10 or 12 degrees,'' said Rodriguez, who failed to cite even
Harry Wappler as a meteorological source for his observation. But
after one magazine called him the most powerful man in baseball,
who's to argue?
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, you can start to work up a sweat after the roof
closes,'' he said. ``But I don't know that they would do that for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The deployment of the roof this spring will be a nightly debate.
Other than the no-brainer of steady rain, the iffy weather creates
an esthetics vs. comfort argument.
</P>
<P>
   The massive gray carport has no appeal, but if Rodriguez's inner
Doppler is right, fans might jump on the side of the players,
especially if the joint keeps running out of coffee, as was the
prevailing contention along the concourses. (A Seattle business
that runs out of coffee is a Seattle business flirting with being
run out of town.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, in no case will Seattle encounter what Lou Piniella
recalled as his worst cold-weather episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blizzard of '82,'' he said, when the season's first four
games in Yankee Stadium _ two against Texas and two against the
Chicago White Sox _ were postponed because relentless snow could
not be cleared from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is Seattle's spring close to what Mariners second baseman
David Bell remembers from his youthful days in his hometown of
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some spring days there were colder than in the winter,'' he
said. ``Freezing rain, some snow ... it was tough. But it didn't
matter, because we played in it. The worst part was if you weren't
in the game. Sitting on the bench was terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   So comparatively, Tuesday night wasn't so bad. Since Rodriguez
and the rest of his teammates had almost no chance to get wood on
the ball, no hand injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   The big chill came not from the sky, but from 60 feet, 6 inches
away.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
