<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS LOSE OPENER TO RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Pedro Martinez, quite obviously primed to defend his
American League Cy Young Award, threw ghostly pitches past the
Mariners for most of Tuesday night in leading Boston to a 2-0
opening night victory.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, 23-4 a year ago, showed no evidence that the cool
Seattle air or the passage of another birthday has affected him in
the slightest. The 28-year-old right-hander fed the Mariners
streaks of fastballs and wisps of changeups for the better part of
108 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in front of a Safeco Field record crowd of 45,552 in the
first Safeco season-opener, Seattle got all of two hits off
Martinez and got just two runners past first base. Until baseball
rules permit holding over excess runs from spring training, that's
a sure way to lose the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   With the stuff Martinez had, he didn't need much support. Which
was good for Boston, because the Red Sox didn't get much off
Mariners starter Jamie Moyer. The lefty shut out Boston for the
first five innings, then suffered one-run paper cuts in the sixth
and seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Those rallies didn't draw much blood, but they were enough to
pronounce the Mariners down for the count in the first of 162
rounds of American League baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when Pedro's pitching when one run feels like
five runs,'' Mariners shortstop Alex Rodriguez said. ``Still, we
had a lot of optimism when it was 1-0. There are a lot of ways to
score a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he kept making good pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, did former Mariner Derek Lowe, who pitched the final
two innings, retiring all six batters he faced in sending the
Mariners to their third consecutive season-opening loss. The record
book will show that Moyer took the loss, but it won't show how
close he came to getting out of both the sixth and the seventh
unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   A two-out, bases-loaded roller off the bat of Troy O'Leary
produced the sixth-inning run when second baseman David Bell's
throw couldn't beat O'Leary to first base. An inning later, with
one out and a man on second, Jose Offerman's flare to left field
made it 2-0. Game time.
</P>
<P>
   ``O'Leary hit a chopper in the middle of nowhere for one run,''
M's pitching coach Bryan Price said. ``The other came from a hit
off the end of the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said he knew the play was going to be close, so he
didn't spare himself fleeing toward the sanctuary of first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to instigate the call just in case it was
close,'' he said. ``I'm not the fastest man out there, but I got
down the line pretty good tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said runs were so hard to come by, ``we were probably
pushing him down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   That push would prove to be all the Red Sox would need, although
Offerman would add some insurance on a 50-degree night with his
double an inning later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martinez is a true professional,'' Moyer said. ``He's got good
stuff, he's got great ability and he's got great competitiveness.
When you face him, you know it's going to be a test. It was fun.
I'm not saying I was sitting on the bench laughing, but you enjoy
the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as the Mariners praised the 23-game winner, Martinez
said he wasn't quite right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I got better command after the fifth inning,'' he said.
``I know I was spotting the fastball and throwing it hard, but the
breaking ball wasn't quite there. And the changeup wasn't pretty
despite throwing it frequently.''
</P>
<P>
   Is he primed for another 23-4-ish season? Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are special seasons,'' Martinez said. ``Those don't come
every day. You can't think about trying to do the same thing. It's
too hard. You'd go crazy before you pitched the first game.''
</P>
<P>
   The only ones who went crazy Tuesday night were the Mariners,
trying to figure out a way to solve the best pitcher in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
