<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7466 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     04-05 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT-IF FILES: TORRE COULD EASILY BE MANAGING ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Perhaps the best manager ever employed by the
Anaheim Angels did all of his work in the press box.
</P>
<P>
   For more than five years (1985-1990), Joe Torre was the analyst
on Angels KTLA telecasts before being pulled away from his
microphone to manage the St. Louis Cardinals. He was a good
analyst, too, explaining strategy to viewers while adding honest
commentary in an understated way.
</P>
<P>
   But he's a better manager, as anyone in New York would tell you.
The Yankees, this week's opening series guests at Anaheim Stadium,
have won three world titles in four years under Torre's guidance,
all coming after the most fractious period in the Yankees'
considerable history.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1982 and 1995, the Yankees didn't play a single
post-season game. The closest they came was a 70-43 mark in 1994
before everyone adjourned for a strike. They employed 10 different
managers in that span Long Beach favorite son Bob Lemon, Gene
Michael, Clyde King, Billy Martin, Yogi Berra, Lou Piniella, Dallas
Green, Bucky Dent, Stump Merrill and Buck Showalter and made a
dozen managerial changes.
</P>
<P>
   The only franchise that comes closest to matching that kind of
instability would be the Angels. Mike Scioscia is the 16th Angels
manager since 1969, and the club has made a change during the
season a dozen times. The longest anyone has lasted with the Angels
since Bill Rigney managed the first eight-plus seasons was Gene
Mauch (1985-87) during his second tour.
</P>
<P>
   All this makes one wonder how different things might have been
for the Yankees, Angels and Torre if the late Gene Autry had
thought to consider hiring Torre as manager when he was in the
broadcast booth. There were windows of opportunity, in 1985, 1988
and 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gene and I would talk about managing, but we never talked
about my managing the team,'' Torre said Monday. ``I watched a few
good managers from the booth ... Mauch, Cookie Rojas, Doug Rader.''
</P>
<P>
   He also watched the 1986 Angels team, which won 92 games and was
a strike away from their first World Series appearance when
disaster struck in Game 5 of the ALCS against Boston. It was a sad
moment that left a mark on everyone involved. Mauch retired after
the 1987 season, still heartbroken from 1986. Pitcher Donnie Moore
would commit suicide a few years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching that game in Chicago, and I don't think I ever
pulled for a team more than I pulled for that one, for both
Genes,'' Torre said. ``Donnie was one of my guys, too. That was a
very sad time.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no way to know how Torre would have done as Angels
manager. But he would have been working for an owner who at the
time was willing to spend money as much as George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Torre's success in New York undoubtedly comes from his
ability to communicate with veteran, well-paid players. The Yankee
clubhouse is peaceful especially in contrast to the day-care
centers that were the Dodger and Angel clubhouses a year ago and
the team plays with envious discipline and confidence.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours before Monday's game, one could walk into the
Yankee clubhouse and account for all 25 players. A dozen or more
players, from Derek Jeter to Clay Bellinger, sat side-by-side on a
couch watching other games.
</P>
<P>
   Across the field, the Angels clubhouse was typically chilly. The
few players in it most hide in the outfield or the players-only
lounge to avoid contact with the media were moving around quietly.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre doesn't delude himself, either. He has the advantage
of Steinbrenner's money on his side and all of the favor curried in
winning a title in his first season (1996).
</P>
<P>
   He also walked the plank in his first three managing jobs. His
first run as a manager with the Mets produced zero winning seasons
in five years, and he was fired. He had winning seasons in two of
three years in Atlanta, but was fired anyway. He had three straight
winning seasons in St. Louis, but was fired after the labor chaos
of 1994-1995.
</P>
<P>
   He learned from those experiences, and understands that managing
in the 21st Century comes with little job security and a new set of
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, stability doesn't happen in baseball unless you
win,'' he said. ``The track record (in New York) wasn't all that
great, either, and not so long ago. We won the first year (1996),
which cuts you some slack, then made the postseason the next. That
puts you in better shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's no such thing as long term today. Everybody is
trying to win. Expansion clubs are trying to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are trying to win, too, appearances aside. When asked
what chance Scioscia has, Torre talked about how the job
description has changed. In the '80s, managers could pull rank.
These days, most managers are outranked. When push came to shove
last season in Anaheim, it was Terry Collins tumbling out the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, if you didn't like someone, you could dispatch that
person,'' he said. ``Now, you can't. You can't threaten players
with losing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, there are similarities with the way parents treat their
children. Parents can't threaten their kids. With kids, you have to
make sense and explain what you're doing and why you're doing it so
that maybe they will gain an understanding of it, as opposed to
doing so just because you said to.''
</P>
<P>
   The comparison shouldn't be taken literally. Torre isn't saying
ballplayers act like children. Just the opposite. They have to be
treated like men, with all the responsibilities that go with it.
</P>
<P>
   That was a core issue in the Angels' clubhouse escapades last
season, and no amount of lip service cures it overnight. Scioscia's
first season will be a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   If there's anything Scioscia can learn from Torre, it may be
that it took Torre four shots to find the right job. The rest of us
may wonder how things might have changed if one of those shots had
been in Anaheim. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 0213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
