<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7468 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     04-05 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEASON OPENER NO TIME TO BE LOOKING BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ How was opening day?
</P>
<P>
   How about fickle?
</P>
<P>
   The weather was fickle, drizzly early in the day and later
sunny.
</P>
<P>
   Fickle also tells the story of the Safeco Field roof operators,
who were itchy on the trigger finger. Perhaps the point was:
</P>
<P>
   If you have a retractable roof, you might as well show the darn
thing off.
</P>
<P>
   During batting practice, the roof was closed. Then, as your 2000
Mariners came streaking down a swath of red carpet to a celebratory
introduction, the roof was peeled back. Then, just before game
time, the pricey canopy was wheeled closed again.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there was more back and forth on the roof Tuesday night
than meaningful, long-term negotiations between Alex Rodriguez's
agent and the Mariners, but that's a story for another day.
</P>
<P>
   However, while we're on the subject of Mariners superstars, it
was impossible to look out into the splendid, frigid, monstrous
theater of Safeco Field and not notice what was missing.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about a little of that old electricity, the kind
generated by Ken Griffey Jr., who hit seven opening day homers
during his Seattle reign.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, after opting to go home to Cincinnati, Griffey is
the man Mariners fans can't afford to miss.
</P>
<P>
   Not now, anyway. Not on opening day. Not in April or May or
June. Not until the new Mariners like John Olerud and Mark McLemore
and Mike Cameron and Aaron Sele get their chance to show off.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there have been snide asides about how Griffey's house,
the Kingdome, is now just a heap of dust and rubble, as if it's a
proper metaphor.
</P>
<P>
   If there is quiet optimism in Seattle over the Mariners'
prospects in 2000, it is because there is a wing and a prayer that
the Ken Griffey Jr.-less Mariners are somehow better than Ken
Griffey Jr.'s Mariners, or better off, or something like that.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, the new king of the M's (even though Lord A-Rod is
only renting his Safeco palace for the season), said he can't tell
us if the 2000 M's _ his M's _ are better without Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the season will tell that,'' Rodriguez said. ``You have
to play it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of optimism all over baseball right now, and
we've had an optimistic spring, too. This team is a bunch of
gamers. We miss Ken as a teammate and as a friend, and right now
we're working on our camaraderie.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, even Griffey would have been hard-pressed to
muster a Safeco homer off Boston's Pedro Martinez, who was the star
of the show with a 2-0 victory and the sort of superlative snapping
off of strikeouts that should have won him the American League MVP
last season.
</P>
<P>
   But the M's don't face Martinez every night, thank goodness. And
Joe Morgan, the Hall of Fame second baseman from Cincinnati's Big
Red Machine days, said the Mariners are NOT better off without
Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't be better. They can be a different team,'' Morgan
said. ``But I don't care what team you are, you can't take a
superstar's bat out of the lineup and become better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm speaking from experience. When they took Tony Perez out of
the lineup, we still had Johnny Bench, Pete Rose, (myself) and
George Foster, but we were not the same. The Mariners can be a
different team. They can be good. But they will not be better. You
can't be better with 50 home runs and 140 RBIs gone. How can you be
better?''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan was talking in the Mariners dugout Tuesday night, fresh
off a plane from Cincinnati where his ESPN duties let him watch the
Reds' opener Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said Griffey was great, although nervous, and Reds fans
were terrific, cheering for Griffey's official debut before rain
ended the game in the sixth, with Griffey 0-for-2 after rushing two
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mariners can't be better without Griffey, how much better
are the Reds? Morgan says much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to jump-start the Reds. I think they're going to
get off to a great start, and I think the Reds are the team to beat
in the Central Division because of that,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to explain that on the air (Monday). When you walk
down that tunnel every day with a superstar, a guy who can carry
you and win games by themself or carry you for weeks at a time, it
makes everyone around him better. It makes everyone else relax to
know he's the guy. He's going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Optimists in Marinerville will say Griffey didn't do enough of
that in his last days here. Marinerville optimists will say A-Rod
will lead the way now, for awhile at least.
</P>
<P>
   But Morgan, a self-admitted Mariners fan, isn't sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody's underestimating. I think you always
underestimate (the loss of a player like Griffey) until it
happens,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's necessarily bad. If you're on the
Mariners, if you're in the city, you should underestimate his loss
because you want to go out and play the best you can without any
strings attached.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to go out there and say `Hey, we can be better.' You
want to go out there with the attitude, `Hey, now the rest of us
will have a chance to shine.' You don't want to out there as a
Mariner feeling the loss of him yet. They will feel it, but you
don't want to go out there with that attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is praiseworthy to be fickle about the loss of
Griffey, as Morgan suggests. The first season without him is under
way now. We can look back later, if this early optimism gives way
to another reality.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
