<HEADLINE>
SONICS TOP NUGGETS, REGAIN SWAGGER IN KEYARENA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When the Sonics run an offensive play designed for
Horace Grant to score, one of four things are taking place.
</P>
<P>
   Either: a) his four teammates completely misread a signal from
the bench, b) Grant and the Sonics are both so potent with the ball
that anything goes in a rout, c) Grant mistakenly wore Vin Baker's
jersey or d) the normally mild-mannered Grant wielded a remote
control in a threatening manner to get his way.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the type of question worth a million dollars for the
correct response. But the final answer is ``b,'' which provided the
most astute assessment of the Sonics' 106-93 victory over the
Denver Nuggets Tuesday night in KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   Grant put together his best offensive performance of the season.
He led five Sonics scorers in double figures with 26 points. The
13-year veteran is usually revered for his defense and rebounding.
However, this time Grant transformed into a scoring machine.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-10 center sank his first 10 shots. At one point,
Grant's shooting line hit 13-for-14. That is when Sonics coach Paul
Westphal, with game in hand, decided Grant was eligible for a ``Who
Wants to Be The Man?'' segment of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had a play run for me in 10 years,'' said Grant, who
made 13 of 17 shots for the game and picked up 12 rebounds along
the way, ``and coach wanted to give me a post-up play. The easiest
shot I was supposed to make and I missed a layup. But, you know, we
were just having some fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were also just taking care of business in dispatching
the 30-44 Nuggets. Since losing five consecutive games at home, the
Sonics have won two in a row in KeyArena by an average margin of 14
points.
</P>
<P>
   It was an timely victory considering Sacramento lost at Dallas.
It pulled the eighth-seeded Sonics within a half-game of the Kings
for the seventh spot in the Western Conference playoff standings.
</P>
<P>
   Grant's outburst was also suitable in that forward Baker had an
off night, going 0-for-7 for seven points. Gary Payton had 21
points and 13 assists but shot a paltry 7-for-20 from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always scored,'' Westphal said of Grant, who scored all
his points without a single free throw. ``He's a good,
double-figure scorer, and we need him to score for us. If he can
get 10, 12, or 15 points every night, it makes it that much easier
for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant normally gets his points when teams double-team Payton and
Baker _ a strategy that was both effective and painful for Denver.
Grant made the Nuggets pay by making mid-range jumpers that had
been failing him lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve (Gordon, a shooting coach with the team) has been
working with me on game days,'' Grant said. ``We shoot for about 45
minutes in the mornings, and he told me to stay focused on my shot
and bend my knees _ you know, the fundamental stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver tried to offset Grant with George McCloud's 28 points off
the bench and forward Antonio McDyess' 17 points and 15 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   However, each time the Nuggets threatened, the Sonics answered
with easy fast-break baskets . The Sonics 18-point third-quarter
lead got sliced to 87-81 early in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Sonics backup forward Jelani McCoy and guard Brent Barry
responded with a back-to-back dunks. Denver never got within eight
points after that sequence.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy, who scored 12 points, mimicked Grant to some degree by
making all six shots he took.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to come in and bring energy, play defense and play
hard,'' McCoy said. `` ... I just tried to go out there and make
something happen, and some shots happened to go down.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant and McCoy made it a long night for the Nuggets' young
front line _ particularly rookie Keon Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to get back on (Grant),'' Denver coach Dan
Issel said, ``but we were slow on recovery, and that certainly
didn't help.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did the Sonics' defense (which held the Nuggets' to 41
percent shooting), rebounding (the Sonics held a 48-41 edge) and
free throw shooting. The Sonics are the second-worst foul shooting
team in the league, but made 18 of 21 free throws against Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' transition offense put distance between themselves
and the Nuggets in the first half. Leading 35-28, Greg Foster sank
an 18-footer. McCoy then rammed back-to-back dunks after beating
the Nuggets up court on fast breaks. The Sonics eventually took a
60-51 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Westphal was very aware of the Sacramento loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the team that the playoffs start now,'' said Westphal,
whose team improved to 24-7 against teams with losing records.
``It's time for a charge. We're in a position where we expect to
have one, and we've got to go out and take care of games like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   With eight games left, there is no other way to play.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
