<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 02:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7470 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-SAHADI-CORRECTION     04-05 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SAHADI-CORRECTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINER SAHADI USES GENTLE TOUCH
</HEADLINE>
 
Eds: Fixes first name ``Jenine'' sted Janine (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ The Deputy, a big three-year-old colt with
tons of promise, walked onto the track at Santa Anita and stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he was just enjoying the warm sun on his back or the
stiff wind in his face. Whatever. He was stopped and not in much of
a hurry to go anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   His trainer Jenine Sahadi, surrounded by a busy television crew,
walked over and smiled. In a fleeting, but candid moment, before
the crew had their equipment set, Sahadi gave her charge a nice pat
on the head and sent him off to do a workout as if there was no one
else within miles.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that his mood changed and The Deputy galloped off to
begin his workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very, very good horse,'' she said. ``I think we're
finding out now just how good he is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy is one of six horses scheduled to run in this
Saturday's $1 million Santa Anita Derby. Depending on his
performance it's likely he'll take a shot at the Triple Crown
beginning with a run in the Kentucky Derby on May 6.
</P>
<P>
   If The Deputy runs in both derbies, Sahadi, a 34-year-old
resident of Pasadena, would be the first woman to train a horse in
both events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's upbeat,'' she said. ``It's been fun with him ...
training for the Santa Anita Derby and Kentucky Derby, so it's
exciting in that respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame Jockey Chris McCarron, himself the winner of two
Kentucky Derbies and a pair of Santa Anita Derbies will be aboard
The Deputy on Saturday. As a guy who's ridden for some of history's
top trainers, McCarron holds nothing but praise for Sahadi.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very understanding to ride for,'' McCarron said.
``Jenine is very frank _ she speaks her mind. She tells you exactly
what's she's thinking, which I like in a person.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a tremendous amount of success together so it's been
a good relationship,'' he continued. ``She's been really great with
(The Deputy), she's asked me for input, she's allowed to
participate in some of the preparation and everything, she's asked
me my opinion and it's been an enjoyable experience.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time, Sahadi has been in the spotlight for
breaking down walls separating the sexes in the horse racing
community. In 1996, she became the first woman to win a Breeder's
Cup race _ and a $1 million race _ when Lit de Justice won the
Breeder's Cup Sprint at Woodbine.
</P>
<P>
   She followed that up with a win in the same race in 1997 at
Hollywood Park with Elmhurst. The list of Sahadi's training
accomplishments goes even further.
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi's won stakes at Santa Anita, Oak Tree, Del Mar, Hollywood
Park and Turf Paradise. In 1996, her earnings of more than $3.4
million ranked her 12th nationally and is the national record for
money won by a female trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Although she didn't begin training until 1993, Sahadi isn't new
to the game. Her parents, Fred and Helen Sahadi owned Cardiff Stud
Farm and Sahadi's been around thoroughbreds all her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``My high school graduation present was a race horse,'' Sahadi
said. ``Cutting Line. He broke his maiden and probably raced a few
times after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi graduated from USC with a degree in journalism and after
that went to work at Hollywood Park in both the publicity and
marketing departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time the trackwas owned by Marge Everett. I got a
great background working for her and she and I got along real
well,'' Sahadi said. ``Under other circumstances things might not
have been so good. But she was pro-woman. I couldn't have asked for
a better opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   After seven years at Hollywood park, Sahadi went to work as an
assistant trainer to Julio Canani between 1991 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In her work on the backside, Sahadi gained a reputation for
caring about the horses she took care of. It's a reputation she
maintains to this day. While some in the gritty racing business may
look upon that as a weakness, plenty of others admire that quality
in Sahadi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say this about the women that I've ridden for,'' said
McCarron. ``They tend to be more conscientious. More like an animal
lover than the average male trainer. They really love their horses
and treat them like family.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a jockey's standpoint, when it comes to Jenine,''
McCarron said, ``I think that's a great quality.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Sahadi, who can be found at the track most mornings before
dawn, clad in her trademark sweatshirt and John Lennon sunglasses,
is proud of her pro-horse stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The horses need to be the priority,'' she said. ``They are not
here to be just exploited. Fortunately, the people I train for
understand how I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   That kinder, gentler treatment of the animals is a large part of
Sahadi's training philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need to be a rocket scientist to do this,'' she
said. ``I treat my horses like pets. After that it's all a little
bit of luck and a little bit of common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you feed him right and train him right, you are going to be
fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, despite her success on the track and her attitude
toward the hores in the stable, Sahadi has a difficult time
maintaining a full barn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would venture to say that if a man was in the same position
as me he would have a lot of clients,'' Sahadi said. ``But, I
haven't been inundated with clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps all that is about to change, but for now Sahadi's got to
get The Deputy ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always something to do,'' she says, walking away. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
