<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONDOR-FREE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDOR RETURNS TO WILD ON WING AND A PRAYER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``a'' national news file.) 
By STEVE CARNEY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FILLMORE, Calif. _ She hopped to the edge of the cliff Tuesday
morning, paused and took off _ soaring above the Sespe Condor
Sanctuary in Ventura County.
</P>
<P>
   AC-8 was home.
</P>
<P>
   After 14 years in captivity, where she was bred to help revive
the population of the nearly-extinct California condor, Adult
Condor 8 became the first of its species to be returned to its
former home.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife officials hope the bird, estimated to be between 24 and
40 years old, will act as a mentor to the two 10-month old condors
released with her _ showing them how to forage, where to nest and
how to avoid the dangers of human contact.
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't done so on her own since 1986 when she was captured,
as one of the last 27 of her kind alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the last of the free-flying condors,'' said Marc
Weitzel, project leader for the U.S. Fish &AMP; Wildlife Service.
``She's come around full-circle.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the species has 157 birds, with 60 of those born in
captivity and released into the wild since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The methodical, 30-year process of reviving the species has cost
an estimated $25 million in funding from federal, state and local
agencies, and private sources including the Zoological Society of
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity for man to bring a species back from
the brink,'' Weitzel said. ``A lot of people consider the
California condor to be the flagship of endangered species. We feel
they have as much right to exist on the Earth as man does.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunting, poisoning and loss of habitat drove the species to the
edge of oblivion. In 1986 wildlife biologists made a critical
decision: Remove the remaining 27 condors from the wild and try to
breed them in captivity, in hopes of one day re-introducing them to
the skies through which they once soared.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was believed if these birds were left in the wild, they
would have gone extinct,'' Weitzel said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan seems to have worked. Of the 157 total birds, 19 live
in the wild in Southern California, 15 in Central California and 26
in Arizona. All the birds released before AC-8 on Tuesday were born
in captivity.
</P>
<P>
   AC-8 hatched nine chicks during her time at the San Diego Wild
Animal Park, but the last was in 1995 and keepers believe she may
be past breeding age. So they felt she would be most useful as a
mentor in the wild, as some of the chicks bred in captivity and
released eventually flew into power lines, drank antifreeze and
died, or otherwise strayed dangerously close to humans.
</P>
<P>
   Better still, she may find a mate and start hatching again.
</P>
<P>
   ``In either case she's an important bird for the program. It's a
win-win for us,'' said Michael Mace, curator of birds at the Wild
Animal Park.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists' goal is to have at least 150 condors in the
wild in California, 150 in Arizona and 150 in captivity.
</P>
<P>
   At about 10:05 a.m. Tuesday, when wildlife officers released
AC-8 and the two younger birds, she ``spread her wings and kind of
posed for the camera, and then launched off the cliff,'' Weitzel
said.
</P>
<P>
   The next step in the program may come next year, when the first
hatchlings released in 1992 will be old enough to reproduce,
Weitzel said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he said, the wild California condors the rarest and
largest birds in North America, with 10-foot wingspans and ``a face
only a mother could love'' may become proud parents themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 0219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7474 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-4THLD-     04-05 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-4THLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Eds.: Subs to update and rewrite top of story)  
 RULING PARTY PICKS NO. 2 OFFICIAL TO TAKE OVER AS JAPAN
PREMIER  (Also see JAPAN-OBUCHI-REACT) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Just hours after the Cabinet resigned to make way for a
smooth transfer of power, Japan's governing party on Wednesday
nominated its secretary general, Yoshiro Mori, to replace the
ailing prime minister, Keizo Obuchi, who was felled over the
weekend by a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Later both houses of the Parliament voted for Mori as the new
prime minister. He and his new Cabinet were expected to be sworn in
by Emperor Akihito later on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination of Mori, who was second to Obuchi in the party
hierarchy, reflected the fulfillment of a carefully choreographed
script by the governing Liberal Democratic Party to ensure a smooth
and quick succession to Obuchi, who still lies in a coma.
</P>
<P>
   Once Mori is sworn in, the new prime minister, a longtime party
stalwart, is widely expected to organize new elections quickly,
most likely before Japan plays host to a summit meeting of the
leading economic powers, known as the Group of Eight, in Okinawa in
July.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of Mori's selection by the Liberal Democrats
and his ratification by Parliament represents the culmination of an
extraordinary transition in Japanese politics, in which news of
Obuchi's hospitalization early on Sunday was kept from the nation
for 22 hours while party leaders consulted among themselves over
what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment the announcement of Obuchi's stroke was made,
late Sunday evening, the succession of events here has been almost
blindingly fast for a country more used to political changes
measured at a snail's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanics of the succession, however, from the temporary
passing of power to a caretaker prime minister, Mikio Aoki, to the
selection of Mori in backroom consultations among the party's
factions has left many Japanese complaining that their political
system is both antiquated and relatively undemocratic.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi was Japan's first prime minister to suffer a
catastrophically incapacitating illness before any transition
arrangements could be made, revealing a system badly unprepared for
such an eventuality. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mori, in a brief statement on Wednesday morning, praised
Obuchi's record and promised to follow in his footsteps. ``My
mission is to make sure that we stay on the path of economic
growth,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to continue Obuchi's policies, including giving
priority to economic growth, even if that means increases in
government debt. In preparation for the party decision, the Cabinet
resigned on Tuesday evening. Mori is expected to reappoint the
ministers and then turn to regular business, including economic
doldrums and scheduled diplomatic meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Mori, 62, won support by demonstrating a strong loyalty to
Obuchi. Even more useful to him were his close ties to the party's
major coalition partner, the Buddhist-backed New Komeito. Mori's
ratification by the parliament, or Diet, is already considered a
foregone conclusion, since the coalition, led by the Liberal
Democratic Party, has a large majority.
</P>
<P>
   Mori is a lifelong party operative who, as with Obuchi before
him, gradually rose through the ranks. He was elected to parliament
in 1969 and at various times was education minister, head of the
party policy council, trade and industry minister and construction
minister. He has twice been secretary general of the Liberal
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But the portfolios that typically define the true party
heavyweights, finance minister and foreign minister, have eluded
him. Those gaps in his resume and his reputation for timidity on
policy issues have led many commentators to say they would expect
little innovation under his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
