<HEADLINE>
KOBE-LESS LAKERS SLIP BY SUNS, 84-83
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Officially, the NBA's one-game suspension applied only
to Kobe Bryant. But it looked as if the Lakers had their entire
offense put into suspended animation Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Everything, of course, except for Shaquille O'Neal. And
fortunately for the Lakers, that _ plus a bit of defense, a little
clutch shooting from Robert Horry and an extra helping of luck _
was all the Lakers needed for a nail-biting 84-83 victory over the
Phoenix Suns at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers extended their winning streak to 10 and cut their
magic number for clinching the NBA's best record to one. But it
didn't come easily with Bryant sitting home in L.A. serving his
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   They survived a clutch 3-pointer from the Suns' Clifford
Robinson, escaped despite two missed free throws by Ron Harper with
22.7 seconds left, then held off the Suns' last charge, an errant
25-footer from Robinson with the final seconds ticking away.
</P>
<P>
   They manufactured a win even while shooting 40.2 percent and
committing 18 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, what an ugly game we played tonight,'' said coach Phil
Jackson, ``and won it. I don't know how.''
</P>
<P>
   They did it mostly on the strength of O'Neal's 32 points, plus
several key plays from Horry and Rick Fox in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was his game,'' Jackson said of O'Neal, ``and it showed
the reason why he's the MVP.''
</P>
<P>
   After Harper's missed free throws, the Suns had a chance to win
it. Trailing 84-83, they tried in vain to work the ball inside, but
Robinson was forced to shoot from behind the arc. The attempt
struck the back of the rim and the Lakers batted away the long
rebound as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   Good defense or good luck, it worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept them outside, we didn't give them a chance to get down
the line,'' Harper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky. Very lucky,'' said Horry, who finished with 11
points and 11 rebounds, his first double-double of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Harper could have made the last play irrelevant by
making his free throws. But both bounced off the iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harp is a reluctant free-throw shooter and there have been
many games that either I've had him take the ball out of bounds or
he's the decoy, because he is reluctant in that regard,'' Jackson
said. ``But tonight he was the guy that kept standing up for us
most of the time, so it was appropriate that he had to come back
and get the ball and was the guy that had to go to that line.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper laughed off the ``reluctant'' tag _ ``That's some Phil
talk,'' he said _ but was relieved the misses didn't lead to a
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually I will hit them, but today was one of those days,'' he
said. ``The bear ate me. I didn't eat the bear. So I'll take the
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave the Lakers a season sweep of the Suns, a
potential second-round playoff opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Hardaway led the Suns with 23 points and 10 assists, and
Robinson scored 20 points. Kevin Johnson, who recently unretired to
fill the void left by the injured Jason Kidd, played his first game
back at America West and scored 14 points against the Lakers'
undermanned backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   With 29 wins in their last 30 games, the Lakers (63-12) also
have their third double-digit winning streak of the season _ a feat
achieved only twice before in NBA history. This streak, however,
nearly was history.
</P>
<P>
   The offense often sputtered without Bryant's playmaking and the
Lakers struggled to find other sources of offense. Derek Fisher,
starting in Bryant's place, went 2 for 11. Brian Shaw was 2 for 7.
A.C. Green went 0 for 4. And Glen Rice, expected to pick up the
slack, scored just 10 points on 4-of-13 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we're disappointed,'' Jackson said, ``and yet we did the
job and won the game and we have to look at it as a team win. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good fortune, basically, that won us the game,'' he
said. ``We led most of the way during this game and it was really
our game to lose. And we almost accomplished it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
