r s BC-BBA-YANKEES-ANGELS-LA     04-05 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERNIE'S BASH BEATS ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Angels played about as well as they could play the
last two nights, and all they have to show for it is a 0-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   Loss No.2 came Tuesday after Bernie Williams' two-out, two-run
home run off Angels closer Troy Percival (0-1) in the ninth inning
gave the New York Yankees a 5-3 victory in front of 25,818 at
Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Williams went the other way, slicing a fastball on the outside
corner from Percival just inside the left-field foul pole and into
the seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it would get out, but it did,'' said Percival,
who made his first appearance of the season following offseason
shoulder surgery. ``I've had my day with him, and today, he got
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival blamed his approach and not the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally I wasn't real sharp,'' he said. ``I didn't move
anybody off the plate. I was trying to locate the ball and that's
not my game. ... I'm not a pitcher, I'm an aggressive thrower. I
got myself in a pitching mode and that's my fault.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had rallied against Yankees starter Roger Clemens to
take a 3-2 lead in the sixth, but Williams came up with a
game-tying RBI double in the seventh inning. The Angels outhit the
Yankees for the second night in a row, 10-9, but the Yankees made
their hits count.
</P>
<P>
   With two out and nobody on in the ninth, Paul O'Neill grounded a
single up the middle to set up Williams for the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more upset about the pitch to O'Neill,'' Percival said.
``I hung a splitter. I had more options and threw an 84-mph
splitter over the middle of the plate. That was my only mistake of
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Kennedy (Cal State Northridge) tied a career-high with four
hits in the game for the Angels, but he never got past second base.
Leadoff hitter Darin Erstad followed Monday's three-hit performance
with two more Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing a good job of setting the table, now if we can get
some of the guys to clean it up, we'll be fine,'' Angels manager
Mike Scioscia said. ``No way Mo (Vaughn), Timmy (Salmon) and Garret
(Anderson) are going to leave guys on base the whole year like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, Salmon and Anderson _ the Nos.3, 4 and 5 hitters _ are a
combined 4 for 26 with two RBI in the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   Once Williams gave the Yankees the lead in the ninth, Mariano
Rivera closed it out for his second save in as many nights. Ramiro
Mendoza (1-0) pitched one scoreless innings to get the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Making his Angels debut, starter Kent Bottenfield gave up two
runs and five hits in 5 innings, the second solid performance by an
Angels starter after Ken Hill's opening-night performance (5
innings, 2 runs, 4 hits in a 3-2 loss). Bottenfield gave up an RBI
single to Jorge Posada in the fourth inning, and an RBI triple to
Tino Martinez in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to set a good impression for my teammates,''
Bottenfield said. ``I have to earn respect from them. But you can't
do it in one night. It's something you have to see over time in my
approach and my performance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was everything we expected,'' Scioscia said of
Bottenfield. ``He had great command and moved the ball in and out.
He kept a good left-handed hitting lineup off balance all night.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 0300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
