<HEADER>
A7508 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-JAZZ-CLIPPERS-LAD     04-05 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-CLIPPERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS RALLY FALLS SHORT AGAINST JAZZ, 103-93
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Most students of Clipperology 2000 eventually
become disillusioned by the lack of variety in game-night failure.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the hackneyed routine: a competent first quarter,
followed by three quarters of remarkably gruesome basketball.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday's 103-93 loss to the Utah Jazz risked the
application of an atypically entertaining format. After four days
since their last date, the Clippers opened the game in alarming
disarray. They spotted the Jazz 11 points, and rope-a-doped Utah
into leading by 15 points. The Jazz (50-23) led 29-20 at the end of
the first act.
</P>
<P>
   Then, backed by the semi-stunned howls from 13,819 Staples
Center fans, the home team rallied, pressing and outscoring Utah
30-22 in the second quarter to trail by one (51-50) at
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were definitely leery after that slow start,'' said interim
Clippers coach Jim Todd. ``But we played hard for 48 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't enough to deal with Utah's Karl Malone, who worked for
37 minutes and produced 34 points, despite hoisting four of the 11
shots blocked by the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   If the Clips _ as it has been alleged _ were conniving to lose
for the purpose of securing the first pick in the Y2K NBA Draft,
somebody missed rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a nice job of hanging in there,'' Jazz point guard
John Stockton (12 points, 8 assists) noticed. ``They shot well,
played good defense, executed.''
</P>
<P>
   This unexpected eruption of snappy play just may have coincided
with another unusual event _ the resurrection of Maurice Taylor and
Lamar Odom.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor returned from a five-game, ankle-related absence to score
16 points and locate 9 rebounds. He even twisted the bad wheel in
the third quarter, but insisted on remaining in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming out of the game really hadn't crossed my mind,'' said
Taylor, who had been suspected by media watchdogs of babying the
ankle to avoid hacking his value in this summer's free-agent
supermarket. ``I know the chances of us winning are better with me
out on the court. I feel like it's my obligation to compete until
the end of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom, down five of the last seven games with alternate-calf
strains, contributed 11 points and enough savvy to make the entire
team play well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can play,'' Odom said, ``once we get it through our heads
to do what we're supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Clippers (14-60) _ who received a team-high 20 points and
19 shots from Derek Anderson _ did lose for the 10th game in row.
But they actually refused to roll over at halftime, hustling out of
the dressing room to control the third quarter, too.
</P>
<P>
   Center Michael Olowokandi (16 points, 4 blocks) worked Utah's
Olden Polynice for 10 points in that period, which ended with the
Clippers leading 82-76.
</P>
<P>
   But Malone, who muscled up for 9 points in the fourth quarter,
scored from point-blank range to give Utah the lead for good at
87-86 with 7:10 to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Utah didn't get to this level by not being able to execute
down the stretch,'' said Todd, whose team has been blindfolded in
the fourth quarter before. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
