<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 09:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7602 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-PVR-ANALYSIS-KANSAS-K     04-05 1394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PVR-ANALYSIS-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALLER, SIMPLER VIDEO RECORDER LETS YOU SAVE TV SHOWS WITHOUT
ADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON BARNHART  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Get ready to welcome a new abbreviation into the consumer
lexicon: PVR, as in personal video recorder.
</P>
<P>
   This tapeless TV technology may well challenge DVDs and
satellite dishes as the hottest video item in stores this year.
</P>
<P>
   PVRs _ minimalist-looking black boxes that save TV shows on a
hard drive instead of on videotape _ rolled onto the market in
mid-1999. Priced at $400 to $800, they immediately became the rage
among the nation's ``time-shifters,'' Americans determined to watch
their favorite TV shows when they want _ not when the networks
dictate they be in front of the tube.
</P>
<P>
   The PVR greatly simplifies the act of selecting a show to
record. It also does something no VCR can: It will actually pause
and ``rewind'' live television, as you watch it.
</P>
<P>
   ReplayTV and TiVo are the companies that sell personal video
recorder technology in the United States. Prices for PVRs have been
falling steadily; TiVo's models range from $399 to $699, while
ReplayTV's top model dropped from $599 to $499 in March. Look for
prices to drop below the magic $300 threshold soon. That's the same
divide DVDs crossed when their sales took off.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a comparison of the ReplayTV 2020, supplied to me by
ReplayTV Inc., and TiVo (with help from some of my TiVo-using
readers), I concluded that whether you choose ReplayTV or TiVo
depends more on the features you want than on either product's
recording quality or ease of use.
</P>
<P>
   There are three parts to any PVR: a sophisticated on-screen
guide, powerful microprocessor chips that turn the TV signal into
data, and a huge hard drive where the digital pictures are saved.
</P>
<P>
   To watch live TV, you can do the usual channel-surf, or use the
on-screen guide to browse the on-screen listings, then choose a
program. The listings are customized to your local cable, satellite
or over-the-air setup when you use your PVR for the first time.
Then, every night, the built-in modem dials out to a local number
and updates the listings. (TiVo charges $9.95 a month for the
listings service or $199 for a ``lifetime'' subscription. The more
expensive ReplayTV doesn't charge for listings.)
</P>
<P>
   As you watch a program, any program, the recorder automatically
saves everything you see onto the hard drive. Which means you can
pause the picture if something or somebody interrupts, or you can
review what you've just watched.
</P>
<P>
   What I found addictive was the ``instant replay'' feature that
lets you jump back (7 seconds on ReplayTV, 8 seconds on TiVo) at
the touch of a button.
</P>
<P>
   To anyone who has missed a line of dialogue on a program, or
waited in vain for a sportscast to show the last play over again,
the instant-replay button is strangely empowering. At first you'll
thrill to even the most seemingly trivial use, like when TiVo user
Jeff Reynolds was watching the Golden Globes and called his wife in
from the other room. He hit the instant-replay button and showed
her ``just how goofy-looking'' Peter Fonda's glasses were.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that alone is worth a couple of hundred dollars,''
Reynolds said in an e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly as revolutionary as the live-TV features is the way the
PVR makes recording shows a relative breeze. For instance, here's
what I'd have to do to catch the nightly broadcast of ``Late Show
With David Letterman'' on my VCR:
</P>
<P>
   1. Put a blank tape in the machine.
</P>
<P>
   2. Hit the PROG button on my VCR's remote control.
</P>
<P>
   3. Enter the start time (10:35 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   4. Enter the end time (11:38 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   5. Enter the channel (3, for KCTV).
</P>
<P>
   6. Hit PROG two more times to OK the recording.
</P>
<P>
   7. Shut off my VCR. If I have other tapes I want to watch, I'll
have to find another machine or remember to pop the blank back into
the VCR before airtime.
</P>
<P>
   Now here's how I record Letterman using ReplayTV:
</P>
<P>
   1. Press the Channel Guide button for the on-screen TV listings
supplied by ReplayTV.
</P>
<P>
   2. Scroll over to tonight's listing for ``Late Show With David
Letterman.''
</P>
<P>
   3. Press the REC button twice.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. Three steps and I have Dave for life _ not just
tonight's broadcast but every broadcast till kingdom come. No
tapes, no times, no 8-digit VCR Plus codes and, best of all, no
screwups.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does a personal video recorder require fewer steps to
record, the steps are more intuitive. Though I was using ReplayTV,
the recording process is much the same for products licensed by
TiVo.
</P>
<P>
   ReplayTV and TiVo also let you search for shows by name and set
up ``theme channels'' to automatically record any show with a
certain keyword in its description (e.g., Bogart or millionaire).
</P>
<P>
   The on-screen guides are comparable to those found on
satellite-TV systems from DirecTV and DISH Network, or the new
digital-cable service of Time Warner Cable. They have full capsule
descriptions of all shows looking out a week in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the basic route taken above, you can tell your PVR to
save a certain number of back episodes of each show; if you like to
record a lot of programs, you may want to keep your backlog to one
episode apiece, lest you run out of disk space. Both PVRs also have
a feature for transferring favorite episodes to your VCR.
</P>
<P>
   Until now ReplayTV has been available only from ReplayTV Inc.,
either direct at www.replaytv.com or through online retailers such
as amazon.com. Panasonic is introducing ShowStopper, the first
retail version of ReplayTV, in stores this month. Philips already
manufactures retail TiVo boxes, and Sony also has licensed TiVo's
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the drawbacks, and they are complaints made by ReplayTV
and TiVo owners alike:
</P>
<P>
   - As with every video device, there's an inevitable tradeoff
between recording time and video quality. The ReplayTV 2020, for
instance, brags about its ``20 hours of storage,'' but that's only
if you accept the standard recording speed. Many viewers won't.
Standard speed results in a rough-quality image that pixillates
heavily when there's a lot of action (a movie or a football game,
for instance).
</P>
<P>
   ReplayTV offers three levels of recording quality, TiVo four.
But the higher in quality you go, the less total storage you'll
have _ far less than the 20 hours ReplayTV claims (30 hours for
TiVo's top model).
</P>
<P>
   If you're less concerned about quality than about not missing
your must-see TV, or if you tend to record programs that don't move
around a lot, such as talk shows, you'll happily accept this
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   - Not everybody has a phone line in the room where they watch
TV, which is a problem since the PVR needs one to dial out for the
nightly updates. In my case I had to string a cord out of the
kitchen; to keep from tripping over it, I applied several long
strips of duct tape to the floor and countertop. Duct tape, as all
home decorators know, adds a special boiler-room touch to any
living space.
</P>
<P>
   - These first-generation PVRs have trouble with the vagaries of
network schedules. For instance, NBC's and CBS' late-night shows
actually end at 11:38 local time _ but ReplayTV and TiVo both shut
off at 11:35, the ``published'' ending time.
</P>
<P>
   Both PVR makers say they are planning to add a feature that will
let viewers add an extra few minutes to the recording time. Since
this is a software fix, older models will likely also get it by way
of the nightly schedule update.
</P>
<P>
   - You're going to be watching more TV. Some users say they watch
less TV thanks to their PVRs, but most couch potatoes I heard from
said the opposite was true. It seems that being able to watch
programs more selectively actually increases your appetite for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I'm watching more TV now,'' said Kevin Hamburger,
producer of TV's ``Politically Incorrect'' and an ardent TiVo user.
</P>
<P>
   - It's one more set-top box to set on top of all your other
set-top boxes. But at least there's no LED panel blinking 12:00 for
all eternity.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Like all microcomputers, the personal video
recorder is going to get cheaper, faster and better the longer you
wait to buy one. But if the idea of never again missing a favorite
show or a compelling video moment is irresistible to you, the time
to buy one of these beauties is now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 0945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
