<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pay $35,000 to move a tree? Leaf me out
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Activists are trying to save a large live oak
tree near Auditorium Shores even though it may be 40 years old _
instead of 300 years old as was originally suspected.
</P>
<P>
   A 40-year-old-tree. I'm supposed to be impressed? We've got
hippies around here older than that, and nobody's trying to save
them. And have you ever wondered why they call them live oaks? Of
course they're live. If they weren't live, they'd be firewood.
</P>
<P>
   At first, it was thought a big live oak next to an Austin Parks
and Recreation building west of Palmer Auditorium was ancient,
historical _ a Treaty Oak sort of a tree.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Kaye Trybus of the South Central Coalition of
Neighborhoods told the Austin Chronicle, anyway. ``You can always
plant another tree,'' she told the Chronicle. ``But you can't plant
a 300-year-old tree.''
</P>
<P>
   Save the tree, she said. This is an old tree. This is a tree
with roots. This is a tree that has been around longer than Gus
Garcia, Carl Hickerson, even Willie Kocurek. Trybus says landscape
architects working on Town Lake Park guesstimated the tree to be
300 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Trybus was concerned because the old tree would be taken down as
part of the redo of the Greater Palmer Auditorium area into a park,
community events center, and performing arts center, or, if you
will, a toe-dancing joint. She wants the tree dug up and moved to
another spot.
</P>
<P>
   So now comes KEYE-TV reporter and meteorologist Dan Robertson.
He reads in the Chronicle about the 300-year-old tree that needs
saving and decides to do his own story. So he visits the Austin
History Center and looks for a photo of the alleged AARP Oak. He
looks at photos of Palmer Auditorium under construction in the
1950s. This tree does not appear in these photos. Finally,
Robertson finds a tree in the right location in a photo from 1967.
The tree is a sapling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about trees really,'' Robertson said.
``But it did kind of spoil the story.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's still a swell tree. So Trybus and friends still want to
save it from the bulldozer. She says $35,000, or close to it, is
needed by the end of May to pay Environmental Design, a tree moving
company in Tomball, to move it. They're looking for a donor.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that a lot of bread to save a grackle launchpad of
questionable heritage? Maybe I'm a little fed up with trees,
though, because I just backed into one the other day in the
Jovita's parking lot, and it's going to set me back several hundred
bucks at Southwest Body &AMP; Paint.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the reason some people thought the tree was 300 years
old is that it's big for 40. The tree, says David Marks, president
of Environmental Design, is 45 inches in diameter, which he says is
larger than normal. So what would make it grow so fast?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the speed rolling downhill from Armadillo World
Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   There are more cost-effective ways to save this tree. With all
of these Californians moving to town, somebody ought to move into
it. Isn't that what Californians do when they want to save a big
tree? Get a sleeping bag, climb up in there and refuse to come
down? With rents being what they are around here, think of the
savings. You could probably rent the lower limb to a family of four
for $800 a month.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso's humor column appears in the Austin
American-Statesman. He can be reached at jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
