<HEADER>
A7645 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN06-COX     04-05 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maybe Microsoft went too far, but it did more for buyers than
ruling did
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The government stomped a mud hole in Microsoft.
Why don't I feel good about it?
</P>
<P>
   After all, government attorneys keep saying that they spent $15
million in tax dollars to protect consumers.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a consumer. I should be celebrating _ popping champagne
corks. Hurrah, valiant government knights on charging steeds slew
the dragon and saved me and all my fellow consumers huddled in our
global cybervillage.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement Monday by U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson that the Bill Gates dragon had violated antitrust laws
caused Gates to drop a cool $12 billion in the value of his
personal stock holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I don't really care if Gates loses a few billion
dollars. He's got more billions to tide him over.
</P>
<P>
   As crass as it must sound, I was thinking about me, not the
world's richest man, when I heard that Microsoft had been found
guilty of unfair competition. Microsoft stock went into free-fall
and took other technical stocks down with it.
</P>
<P>
   As a longtime computer devotee, I still have a Victor computer
that runs CPM, a computer operating software that predates Gates'
DOS software.
</P>
<P>
   CPM may have been superior to Gate's software, but the brilliant
man who invented it didn't have Gate's vision of the future, his
marketing savvy or his ruthlessness.
</P>
<P>
   I also have an old database management program that boots up
from 5.25-inch floppy disks to show a single dot on the screen.
From that single point, you have to build your database program. It
takes the patience of Job and the brains of Einstein to get
anything useful out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing about this program or anything else associated with the
early days of computers could be described as user-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates may have broken a few eggs while making his omelette,
but it was a meal that the consumers got to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the computer fare we had been fed before Gates began
to consolidate all the dead-end digital dissonance, Microsoft food
tasted pretty good. And the price was right, too.
</P>
<P>
   Gates' marketing and business tactics overwhelmed or absorbed
any number of products that appeared superior to Microsoft's
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Apple computers come to mind. I have always felt that Apple had
a better, more bullet-proof platform and operating system than PCs
and DOS/Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The Tucker car introduced after World War II was superior to
anything Ford or General Motors offered. It still failed.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of thing happens all the time. Marketing and agility
often overcome quality, which doesn't count for much if it doesn't
get into the hands of consumers at an affordable price.
</P>
<P>
   I can't argue that Microsoft did not violate antitrust laws, but
I do think that the company brought light into the darkness of
computer geekdom. For that, consumers should be thankful.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad pioneers were considered saviors when they were
bringing trade and prosperity to an expanding frontier. Later,
after the country was settled, they were considered robber barons.
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for ``The Telephone Company'' that
brought the United States the best telephone service in the world
right up until it was broken up into Baby Bells.
</P>
<P>
   Now the government is on the verge of breaking up Microsoft into
Baby Bills.
</P>
<P>
   If Gates broke the law while he was getting rich bringing order
out of chaos, then he should be punished.
</P>
<P>
   Gates vows to fight on. But there's blood in the water, and the
lawyers are circling.
</P>
<P>
   The government said it won this victory for me and other
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   That's nice. I'll celebrate later.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: Nethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
