r d BC-COOKING-WITHWINE06-CO     04-05 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKING-WITHWINE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A splash of wine uncorks a world of flavor
 &HT;    By Ann Heller and Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ There's a secret ingredient lurking in your
basement_ or perhaps in your refrigerator door.
</P>
<P>
   You might not have used it lately to cook with, preferring to
consume it in its raw form. But wine has earned a place on your
kitchen countertop as well as the dining room table.
</P>
<P>
   The same flavors that make wine appealing to sip also make it a
tasteful addition to sauces, meats and desserts. It's a crucial
ingredient in classic stews such as Beef Bourgignon, Coq au Vin and
Osso Buco. But don't let the fancy names intimidate. Cooking with
wine can be amazingly simple, its impact profound.
</P>
<P>
   Pan-frying (oops, we mean sauteing) a fish filet, steak, chicken
breast or pork chop? Remove the meat, keep the burner on and pour
in equal parts wine and low-sodium chicken broth _ about 1/4 cup
each. Scrape the pan to free the tasty little browned bits. Cook
for a couple of minutes to reduce the liquid by about half, then
whisk in a tablespoon of butter. Pour over the main course.
</P>
<P>
   Want to pump it up a notch? Saute a teaspoon or two of chopped
shallots (or mild onion) with the wine and stock, perhaps with a
pinch of freshly minced garlic to add some new flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Your simple pan-fried entree just got much more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Some other recipes demand a bit more time, but the results make
the effort worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   We could go on. Wine is essential in everyday marinades. A
splash of wine adds flavor to the mussels in the pot. A shot of
sherry added to the turtle soup is traditional. Poaching pears in
wine is as basic as Desserts 101.
</P>
<P>
   Cookbook author and chef John Ash makes the the case for cooking
with wine in a line or two poached from the book ``History of
Food'' by Maguelonne Toussaint-Samat:
</P>
<P>
   ``Wine puts all its nutritional virtues at the service of the
cooking and digestion of food. Wine contains glycerine, so it helps
to bind sauces and less fat can be used. Wine is well flavored and
allows the cook to go easy on salt or omit it altogether. Wine
contains tannin, particularly when it has been cooked, and
stimulates digestion. Wine contains alcohol, but very little once
it has evaporated in being cooked. It stimulates the tastebuds and
thus the appetite. It brings out the flavor of food and helps the
system to digest fat. And it is very good for morale.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
