<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7652 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS06-COX-     04-05 1614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS06-COX-FILE1 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   FILE 1 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happened to popular Atlanta Braves shortstop Jeff
Blauser? Did he retire?
</P>
<P>
   A: Blauser, who played for the Braves from 1987 to 1997, is not
hooked up with any team this season. Braves spokesman Glen Serra
said Blauser, 34, became a free agent after the 1997 season and
then signed with the Chicago Cubs. He was released by them in 1999
after two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the exact wording of the oath of office that every
member of Congress must take?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Constitution requires that senators and representatives
take this oath: ``I do solemnly swear that I will support and
defend the Constitution of the United State against all enemies,
foreign and domestic; that I will bear true faith and allegiance
and to the same; that I will take this obligation freely, without
any mental reservation or purpose of evasion and that I will well
and faithfully discharge the duties of the office on which I am
about to enter. So help me God.''
</P>
<P>
   The specific language is set by statue enacted by Congress (5
U.S.C. 3331). U.S. law requires that members must be sworn in
before they can take their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why are the Peabody Awards conferred in New York and not at
the University of Georgia where they originated?
</P>
<P>
   A: The only time the Peabody Awards ceremony has been held in
Georgia was 10 years ago in Atlanta to mark the 50th year of the
competition. Tom Hoover, activities director for the Peabody
Awards, said the annual ceremonies are held in New York where cable
and network headquarters are situated.
</P>
<P>
   UGA's College of Journalism started the competition that
recognizes distinquished achievement and public service in the
broadcast media. The organization is still based in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Named for philanthropist and banker George Foster Peabody, the
first awards were given to the best broadcasters in radio in 1940.
It has grown to an international competition that has had more than
40,000 entries. A national advisory board meets at the university
the end of March each year to judge the best in radio and
television. This year, 36 awards will be given at ceremonies at the
Waldorf Astoria May 22. The awards were announced March 30.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do all states observe Daylight Saving Time?
</P>
<P>
   A: Daylight Saving Time is not observed in Arizona, Hawaii or
the Eastern time zone portion of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The idea originated with Benjamin Franklin, who wrote a humorous
essay in 1784 about saving time. The concept of adding an hour to
each day wasn't advocated strongly, though, until 1907 when an
English builder wrote a pamphlet, ``The Waste of Time.''
</P>
<P>
   Saving fuel became important during World War I, when many
European countries and the United States mandated Daylight Saving
Time. But it proved to be unpopular in this country, and was
repealed in 1919.
</P>
<P>
   It resumed in the United States during World War II when
year-round Daylight Saving Time was observed from February 1942
through September 1945. It was not used consistently again in this
country until President Johnson signed the Uniform Time Act of
1966. Additional federal legislation in 1986 set Daylight Saving
Time to begin at 2 a.m. the first Sunday of April and end 2 a.m.
the last Sunday of October.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who is the lady who sings the title song in the
``Goldfinger'' movie?
</P>
<P>
   A: Welsh-Nigerian diva Shirley Bassey hit the charts in 1964
with the title song from the James Bond movie ``Goldfinger.'' The
61-year-old singer had her first hit in 1957 with a calypso-style
``Banana Boat Song'' Recognized for her throaty sound, she
continues to record and perform in concerts around the world. She
will be presented to Queen Elizabeth II this spring as Dame Shirley
Bassey.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It has been reported that QPM, or Quality Protein Maize, was
being introduced in countries around the world. An article about
the Carter Presidential Center said this strain had several
benefits over regular corn. Why isn't QPM used in this country?
</P>
<P>
   A: Compared to people in developing countries, Americans don't
need QPM _ which is a genetically engineered corn with amino acids
added _ because we get enough protein in our normal diet, said
Carrie Harmon of the Carter Presidential Center. QPM has the same
dietary advantages of meat and milk together, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Also, for those people in this country who don't get enough
protein in their diet, soybean and other supplements are readily
available and inexpensive, which isn't the case in developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last September, former President Jimmy Carter
said corn is the primary food for poor people, even though it is
``food-deficient.'' QPM, on the other hand, is ``a complete food,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   It has been introduced in Ghana, South Africa, Brazil and
nothern China, with plans also announced for North Korea to get it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I receive my mail at a post office box and didn't get a
census form. When I inquired at the post office, I was told that
people who get mail at a box there won't receive a census form. Is
this so?
</P>
<P>
   A: Bea Piddock of the Census Bureau confirmed that census forms
are delivered to ``housing units,'' and not to post office boxes.
She suggests that you not call the bureau to request that a form be
hand-delivered to your residence, but wait for someone to visit
personally to conduct the enumeration.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How are prisoners being counted in the census?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Census Bureau counts them at the prison. Inmates are
listed as residents of the location of the prison, not the location
where they lived before incarceration.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've noticed many times that microwave ovens in public-use
areas are dirty, with food splattered inside from previous users.
Are there any health risks involved? Can harmful bacteria grow in
this mess?
</P>
<P>
   A: Like any dirty counter top or kitchen surface, a dirty
microwave could provide an opportunity for bacterial growth and
pest infestation, said Connie Crawley of the University of Georgia
Extension Service. But she said she has never seen any studies
indicating potential dangers of dirty microwave ovens.
</P>
<P>
   If the oven is used frequently, the repeated heating likely
would destroy some bacteria, she said; but if it's used less
frequently, bacteria could start to grow.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that manufacturers always recommend regular cleanup of
any spills to maintain oven efficiency and hygiene, including the
top of the oven, where food may splatter, but isn't as visible.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I frequently hear news commentators, when talking about
politicians, use the term ``litmus test.'' What does that mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: Anyone who has taken a high school chemistry class will
recall dipping a piece of litmus _ from the Scandinavian word for
lichen _ paper into a solution. In such a test, the paper turns red
in acid, blue in alkaline.
</P>
<P>
   In politics, a litmus test is a position or vote so closely
associated with a political philosophy that it immediately
classifies a politician or movement. The phrase became common in
this context in the 1970s. At the time, the most frequently
discussed litmus test was a Republican's position on the Panama
Canal treaties of 1977, which supporters of Ronald Reagan said
would determine whether any candidate would get the 1980
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples: A Democrat's litmus test was the
Humphrey-Hawkins bill to reduce unemployment; a Republican's was
the Equal Rights Amendment for women.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the phrase most often was applied to the selection
of Supreme Court justices. That litmus test was their attitude
toward abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it possible to get a videotape copy of the 2000 Grammy
awards program?
</P>
<P>
   A: No such video is available, but Adam Sandler of the National
Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences says a DVD release about the
42nd annual Grammy Awards show is in the planning stages.
</P>
<P>
   It likely would highlight certain artist performances, have some
key artist interviews, and provide a view of behind-the-scenes
action, among other features, he added.
</P>
<P>
   No release date has been set, but if you like to cruise online,
you can monitor the situation at www.Grammy.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has become of the Enterprise, America's first space
shuttle? I'm going to Washington this summer and would like to see
it if it's on display anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   A: While OV-101, as Enterprise is known in NASA lingo, never
went into space, it's considered a cornerstone of U.S. space
shuttle development.
</P>
<P>
   After it was used in various stages of testing, Enterprise made
a series of appearances at air shows in the United States, Europe
and Canada before being turned over to the Smithsonian
Institution's National Air and Space Museum in Washington. NASA
says it's currently in storage at Dulles International Airport near
Washington, so you won't be able to see it this summer. When
construction is completed on a museum annex, however, it will go on
view, along with other large and historic aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Many other early spacecraft, used in programs such as Mercury,
Gemini and Apollo, can be viewed at NASA institutions and science
museums around the nation. The Apollo 11 command module, for
example, is a popular exhibit at the Air and Space Museum, so you
can see that during your Washington visit.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
