<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   FILE 2 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are professional hockey players required to wear protective
headgear, or is it optional? I know goalies wear face masks.
</P>
<P>
   A: All NHL and minor league players must wear a helmet. Goalies,
by the way, wear more than face masks. Their protection includes
leg pads, a padded catching glove and a blocker (blocking glove),
which is used to hold the stick.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where does Georgia, the Peach State, rank among other states
in peach production?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's safe to say that Georgia consistently ranks among the
top five states. Beyond that, several factors figure into peach
crop production, making the rankings subject to change from year to
year. The main variable is the weather.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Georgia had a ``near normal'' year, resulting in a No.
2 ranking behind California, said Faith Peppers of the University
of Georgia Extension Service. In 1998, crops suffered damage from
hail and freezing weather, making the crop that year the
second-lowest in the past seven years. Georgia tumbled into a tie
with Pennsylvania for No. 4. California remained first, followed by
South Carolina and New Jersey. In 1999, Georgia was No. 2 again.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Attorney General Janet Reno, appearing on CNN in connection
with the Elian Gonzalez case, seemed to be shaking constantly.
What's wrong with her?
</P>
<P>
   A: The attorney general announced in November 1995 that she has
Parkinson's disease, a degenerative neurological disease that can
cause trembling, muscular stiffness, stooped posture, poor balance
and slow movement. The disease, for which there is no cure, starts
relatively mildly _ in Reno's case, with occasional shaking in the
left hand _ and continues in a relentless deterioration.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has experienced several well-publicized fainting
spells, her doctors have said repeatedly that Reno is in good
health, except for the Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The National Rifle Association created a controversy when it
published some statistics about crime in Australia. What was the
reaction of the Australians?
</P>
<P>
   A: Here's what happened after the NRA posted a video on its Web
site about gun crimes in Australia. Presented as a television news
story, the video claimed that Australia's gun reform laws
backfired, and said gun-related crime rates rose after the country
banned semiautomatic rifles, semiautomatic shotguns and pump-action
shotguns.
</P>
<P>
   Australian officials accused the NRA of misrepresentation, and
demanded that the video be pulled and any reference to Australia
dropped. In a letter to NRA president Charlton Heston, Australia's
federal attorney general, Daryl Williams, wrote: ``I find it quite
offensive that the NRA is using the very successful gun reform laws
introduced in 1996 as the basis for promoting ownership of firearms
in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Australia adopted the gun laws after an April 1996 rampage by
Martin Bryant, who opened fire with military-style rifles in
Melbourne, killing 35 people.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA didn't return Q&AMP;A's call asking for its response, but
the video appears to have been pulled from its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Parade magazine recently had a brief mention about the old
Stanley Steamer automobile. By definition it must have been
steam-powered, but how did it work?
</P>
<P>
   A: The vehicle had a boiler under its hood that provided
pressure to drive a two-cylinder engine beneath the floor. Because
of its abundant torque, the Stanley Steamer _ named after its
inventors, twin brothers Francis and Freelan Stanley _ didn't have
a transmission. Just one gear engaged the center of its crankshaft
and directly turned the rear wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Steamers had several disadvantages, including being slow to warm
up. Driving also was difficult, requiring patience and knowledge to
manipulate the valves controlling the flow of fuel, water and
steam.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley company began producing steam automobiles in 1897.
With the appearance of Cadillac's self-starter, steam cars
gradually disappeared. In 1924, the Stanley brothers' company went
bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I enjoyed the book ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and
Evil'' about Savannah. Is The Lady Chablis still performing there?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. The Web site www.theladychablis.com/events.htm lists
these dates for personal appearances at Savannah's Club 1Jefferson
(named after its location at 1 Jefferson St.): April 22; May 27;
June 17; July 8; Aug. 12; and Sept. 2. Information: 912-232-0200.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We're planning a trip to Alaska in May and are considering
driving west on the Trans-Canada Highway. How do gasoline prices in
Canada compare to those here?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Canadian Automobile Association says the national average
cost of gasoline is 71 cents (Canadian) a liter, which is how it's
sold. That is the equivalent of about $1.85 U.S. per U.S. gallon,
said Lauren DeWolf of the Canadian Consulate in Atlanta. She
pointed out that one U.S. gallon equals 3.875 liters; and $1 U.S.
equals 1.453 Canadian dollars, subject to fluctuation.
</P>
<P>
   Information about driving in Canada can be obtained by calling
the Canadian Automobile Association in Ottawa, Ontario, at
613-247-0117.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When are this year's space shuttle launches scheduled from
Cape Canaveral? Also, several years ago Q&AMP;A printed information
about obtaining a parking pass for better viewing. How is that
done?
</P>
<P>
   A: The schedule is being revised, so you'd be wise to check
frequently before making a trip. Information is available online at
www.ksc.nasa.gov, or you can call 321-867-4636 to listen to a
recording.
</P>
<P>
   As of March 28, information was available for only two launches,
both by Atlantis. The first is tentatively set for 6:37 p.m. April
18, with landing anticipated about 1:30 p.m. April 28. (The
recording, by the way, says launch will be ``no earlier than April
17 at 7:03 p.m.'').
</P>
<P>
   The second is tentatively planned at 4:57 p.m. Aug. 19, with
landing at 11:51 a.m. Aug. 30. Several other launches are planned,
but dates and times are listed as ``to be determined.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the shuttle launch car passes for this year
already have been allocated, according to the space center, and
requests for car passes beyond this year aren't being accepted.
However, a limited number of bus tickets to view the launches may
be available through Delaware North Park Services of Spaceport.
Information: 321-449-4444. No car passes or bus tickets are
available for viewing shuttle landings. Cloud cover frequently
makes landings more difficult to see than launches, and there's no
viewing area large enough to accommodate the public.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Much has been written about gun locks, but I've never seen
how they work. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are a number of variations, but one type that's
beginning to see widespread use in lock giveaways from Augusta to
Minneapolis resembles a bicycle cable lock. It has a metal cable,
coated in plastic, that hooks into a small key-operated padlock.
The device is pulled through gun handles or barrels. When the lock
is in place, the gun cannot be fired or loaded. This is different
from trigger locks, which keep the trigger from being pulled.
</P>
<P>
   Other types include digital locks, touch-sensitive combination
magazine and grip locks for semiautomatics and revolvers, and an
electronic trigger locking system encased in a tamper-resistant
polymer that covers the trigger and guard of most firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Before the California primary, the media had a lot to say
about the importance of the popular vote there. I never saw a
report with the exact number of votes for all the various
candidates. Do you have that information?
</P>
<P>
   A: These were the numbers in California's March 7 presidential
primaries, with vote totals followed by approximate percentages.
</P>
<P>
   Republican: George W. Bush,1,542,110 (61); John McCain, 885,255
(35); Alan Keyes, 100,173 (4); Steve Forbes, 7,505 (.2); Gary
Bauer, 6,039 (.2); Orrin Hatch, 5,421 (.2).
</P>
<P>
   Democratic: Al Gore,1,965,516 (81); Bill Bradley, 437,897 (18);
Lyndon LaRouche, 14,642 (1).
</P>
<P>
   Green: Ralph Nader, 20,727 (91.8); Joel Kovel, 1,873 (8.2).
</P>
<P>
   American Independent: Howard Phillips, 2,814 (100).
</P>
<P>
   Libertarian: Harry Browne, 7,961 (71.3); L. Neil Smith, 992
(8.9); Larry Hines, 842 (7.6); Dave Lynn Hollist, 721 (6.4); Kip
Lee, 656 (5.8).
</P>
<P>
   Natural Law: John Hagelin, 954 (100).
</P>
<P>
   Reform: Donald Trump, 659 (37.1); John Anderson, 424 (23.9);
Robert Bowman, 276 (15.5); Charles Collins, 219 (12.3); George
Weber, 201 (11.2).
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
