<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-WHAT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What to pour (into the pan)
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher and Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ So what kind of wine do you use in cooking?
</P>
<P>
   First off, never ever pour anything labeled ``cooking wine.''
Take one sip of that and you'll spit it out.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom is to use the same wine or the same varietal
you'll be serving with dinner. But what if you're not having a
glass with dinner?
</P>
<P>
   There are still options. A quarter-cup of dry vermouth often
will do when a splash of white wine is called for. So will Marsala
_ either dry or sweet _ or nutty Madeira. Because of their higher
alcohol content, all three can be kept on the shelf once opened.
</P>
<P>
   Another good tip: At the end of a meal when there's some wine
left in the bottle, pour it into an ice-cube tray and freeze it,
just the way you should do with excess chicken broth. Keep the
frozen cubes in well-sealed freezer bags and you've always got a
little wine when the recipe calls for just 1/4 or 1/2 a cup. Be
aware that because of the alcohol, the wine doesn't freeze as rock
hard as water.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't want to thaw and drink the wine, but it's OK for
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
