</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7661 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-WINE-RECIPES06-COX     04-05 1429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-RECIPES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recipes using wine are well worth a try
 &HT;    By Ann Heller and Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Wine figures in many a seafood recipe, whether
poaching salmon or making a fish soup. Inevitably, a simple
appetizer of mussels relies on some wine in the pot.
</P>
<P>
   This recipe comes from Preston Vineyards, where owner Lou
Preston suggests using their Dry Creek Valley Semillon. The simple
instructions suggest heating virgin olive oil in a small pan,
tossing in some garlic and parsley and cooking until it sizzles. A
couple of handfuls of mussels are added, and when they open, a bit
of Semillon is dashed over them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toss everything about like a chef gone wild,'' the recipe
reads.
</P>
<P>
   Here are more precise instructions. For a mildly sinful sauce,
add a couple of tablespoons of cream with the wine.
</P>
<P>
   MUSSELS WITH WHITE WINE AND GARLIC
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 appetizer servings
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   40 mussels, about 2 pounds
</P>
<P>
   mussels, scrubbed and beard removed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Semillon or other dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup whipping cream, optional
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Additional minced parsley for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a medium skillet or pot that has a lid. Add the
garlic and parsley and cook about 30 seconds. Don't let the garlic
brown. Add the mussels and cover. Cook, shaking the pan repeatedly,
for 4 to 5 minutes, until the mussels open. Add the wine and cook,
shaking the pan, for about 1 minute. Remove mussels with slotted
spoon to individual soup plates, removing any mussels that haven't
opened. If using cream, add it to the pan and boil over high heat
for a minute. Add a couple of pinches of salt and pour the liquid
over the mussels. Sprinkle with parsley. Serve with chilled white
wine and crusty bread for dipping.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving without cream: 253
calories, 8.6 g fat, 64 mg cholesterol, 659 mg sodium; with cream,
289 calories, 12.3 g fat, 77 mg cholesterol, 665 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   This recipe for Bolognese sauce sets the standard for Italian
meat sauce. It's adapted from ``Essentials of Classic Italian
Cooking,'' by Marcella Hazan, (Alfred A. Knopf).
</P>
<P>
   PASTA WITH BOLOGNESE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 6 first-course servings or 2 to 3 entrees
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter plus 1 tablespoon butter for tossing with
pasta
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup chopped carrot
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound ground chuck
</P>
<P>
   Salt, black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup whole milk
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups canned Italian-style plum tomatoes chopped, with
their juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound pasta, cooked according to package directions
</P>
<P>
   Freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Heat butter and vegetable oil in large skillet over medium heat.
Add onion and cook until onions become translucent. Add celery and
carrot, and cook 2 minutes. Add meat, along with a large pinch of
salt and two grindings of pepper. Crumble meat with a fork, stir
well and cook until meat loses its red color. Add milk, let simmer
until milk evaporates. Add nutmeg and stir. Add wine and cook until
wine is evaporated. Add tomatoes, stir well. When the mixture
begins to bubble, turn heat down to simmer and cook for 3 hours,
checking and stirring occasionally. Add 1/2 cup water if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of cooking time, no water should be left in the pan.
Taste, add salt to taste. Add 1 tablespoon butter to cooked,
drained pasta and toss with sauce. Top with a sprinkle of grated
Parmesan.
</P>
<P>
   Note: The sauce portion of this recipe can be doubled or
tripled; leftover sauce freezes and reheats well.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per appetizer serving: 443
calories, 21.8 g fat, 63 mg cholesterol, 463 mg sodium (not
including sodium in Parmesan cheese added to taste).
</P>
<P>
   Red wine, specifically a Zinfandel, is used in both the marinade
and sauce for grilled lamb. Already-boned lamb, wrapped in a string
net, is available in most Kroger stores. Be sure to buy one that
has not already been seasoned. Then cut off the netting and unroll
the lamb. It will be uneven, but that's perfect for grilling
because some parts will become well done while others remain medium
rare. You can please everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to this early spring, mint is already 8 inches high in
any garden where it grows. It is also available in the herb section
of the produce section, as is fresh oregano. The sauce, while
flavored with mint, is a more sophisticated companion than
old-fashioned green mint jelly.
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED LAMB WITH ROASTED GARLIC-MINT SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   MARINADE:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup reduced-salt soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Zinfandel
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sliced yellow onions
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons chopped fresh oregano (or 1 teaspoon dried)
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   MEAT:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 leg of lamb, boned, butterflied and trimmed of most fat
(about 2 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   1 large whole head of garlic, unpeeled
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups Zinfandel
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups fat-free chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoons chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped roasted garlic
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Mix all the marinade ingredients. Unwrap the lamb if it was
purchased in a string net. Place in a large, sealable plastic bag
and add marinade. Marinate, refrigerated, for at least 2 to 3
hours, turning the bag occasionally. Remove lamb from marinade and
pat dry.
</P>
<P>
   While the meat marinates, preheat oven to 350 degrees. Cut off
just the top of the garlic head, so that the individual cloves are
just exposed. Drizzle with the olive oil and sprinkle lightly with
salt and pepper. Wrap in aluminum foil, leaving a small area open
at the top. Roast for 45 to 60 minutes. Remove from oven and cool.
Squeeze the roasted garlic cloves out of the head, discarding the
skin. (Refrigerate unused roasted garlic, covered, for up to one
week.)
</P>
<P>
   To make the sauce, heat olive oil in a medium pan. Add shallots
and cook for 2 to 3 minutes. Add the wine, bring to a simmer and
boil until reduced by half. Add the stock, mint, roasted garlic and
mustard until the sauce is reduced by half. Season to taste with
salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare a hot charcoal fire and grill lamb for 8 to 9 minutes
per side, until cooked medium rare, about 130 degrees. Let the lamb
rest for about 10 minutes before carving.
</P>
<P>
   Slice and spoon sauce over the lamb.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving (for 6): 367
calories, 14 g fat, 122 mg cholesterol, 652 mg sodium, not
including salt to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe adapted from the ``Wine Lover's Cookbook'' by Sid
Goldstein (Chronicle, $22.95 paper).
</P>
<P>
   Because of their sweetness, desserts and wines are a hard match.
But sometimes wine is incorporated in the final course. This
dessert recipe for jellied champagne and fruit served in wine
glasses was a fad during the holidays. Now you can use the
California strawberries that are in season.
</P>
<P>
   STRAWBERRIES
</P>
<P>
   IN CHAMPAGNE JELLY
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   4 1/4 teaspoons unflavored gelatin
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup plus 3 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 bottle (3 1/2 cups) dry champagne
</P>
<P>
   1 pint strawberries, rinsed, hulled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle the gelatin over the water in a medium saucepan and let
soften for about 5 minutes. Put the pan over low heat and stir with
a wooden spoon just until the gelatin has dissolved. Stir in all
but 1 tablespoon of the sugar and remove from the heat. Stir until
the sugar has thoroughly dissolved, then stir in the champagne.
Pour the mixture into a shallow bowl; cover and refrigerate until
set, at least 6 hours.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to serve, combine the strawberries with the remaining
1 tablespoon sugar. Scramble the gelatin with a fork. Spoon 3
tablespoons of the jellied champagne into individual wine glasses
and top with a layer of berries. Repeat two more times. Drizzle a
little juice from the berries over the top. Serve cold.
</P>
<P>
   (Note: if you make this a day ahead and refrigerate overnight
you can use only 3 1/4 teaspoons gelatin).
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 228 calories, no
fat or cholesterol, 10 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
