<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VILLAGE EXISTS ON ECONOMY OF SCALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KASENYI, Uganda _ The auction starts right on the boat. Men bump
and shout, waving fans of worn bills. Some teeter on the gunwales.
Others stand waist-deep in the water or haggle from the shoulders
of others. A tax man hovers, collecting his cut at the conclusion
of each transaction.
</P>
<P>
   In a country whose shape is determined by the northwestern
shoreline of Lake Victoria, a body of fresh water that could almost
swallow Maine, nothing edible sets Uganda in motion more than fish.
And in this fishing village, the largest and most productive near
the capital of Kampala, buying and selling follow two simple rules:
Freshness lies in the color of the gills and price is a function of
proximity to water.
</P>
<P>
   Ugandans pull, on average, 135,000 tons of fish from Lake
Victoria annually, according to government statistics. Most of that
haul is brought in by small commercial fishermen who often spend
their nights on the water in ``kabalegas,'' long narrow boats,
guarding their nets from pirates. Their catches spawn vibrant _ and
often pungent _ lakeside marketplaces.
</P>
<P>
   If bees could catch fish, their hives might resemble this
fishing village, where the daily harvest and the crushing human
need for work result in a highly specialized division of labor. The
arrival of each boat sets in motion a frenetic bustle of
auctioneers, buyers, mongers, waders, tax collectors, fish
cleaners, ice packers, boat tenders, tallymen, money changers, and
net menders.
</P>
<P>
   All that just to beach the catch. The journey from fish to
fillet slips through many hands.
</P>
<P>
   Kasenyi wakens slowly. In the calm of early morning, Africa's
largest lake pats the shore like a cat licking its paw. The
fishmongers' tables lie empty, the merchants' kiosks shut tight.
Smoke curls up from the jumbled wooden dwellings that huddle
tightly a hundred yards up the beach. Young boys fill yellow cans
with water. The first returning fishermen, back from a night on the
water, untangle their catch, mend their nets, share tips on where
the fish might be.
</P>
<P>
   The beachcombers come first, sweeping the sand of the previous
day's flotsam and refuse. Then the merchants come, lifting the
shutters from their clapboard hovels: Kagozi's general store,
Okello's cafe, Kasenyi Village Pharmaceutical. Soon, the beach will
be a swarm. Women from inland villages hawking onions and bright
orange peppers; women from Kasenyi grilling chicken livers, five
cents a skewer; women selling beautiful sarongs with matching
headdresses.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the beach, in the grassy dunes, Kiyonga Leonard and his
laborers build kabalegas from rough-milled planks of blond mukebo
wood. The boats are 35 feet long and three times deeper than
canoes, sealed tight with inner tubes, twine, oil paint, and sheet
metal.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard shrugs more than he talks. ``I make about a hundred
boats a year,'' he said, lifting his Chicago Bulls cap to wipe his
brow. ``They last about five years.''
</P>
<P>
   By midday, the fish tables at the water's edge sag and sway
under the weight of the day's catch. Mounds of tilapia as plump as
couch cushions, some still twitching, lie under a tablecloth of
banana leaves. Nile perch gape in the humid heat, their huge fleshy
tongues jutting outward. The only shade is under the tables, where
fishmongers fend off the day in the company of their women.
</P>
<P>
   Haggling starts as soon as the boats cut their motors. Here, a
platter-sized tilapia might cost 30 cents, and if you don't want to
get wet, you can hire a wader and ride out to the kabalega on his
shoulders. Five feet up the beach, after the same tilapia has
already been bought and sold twice, the cost rises to a dollar. In
downtown Kampala the price is about $6.
</P>
<P>
   No matter the niche, the days are long, the money little.
Fishermen work 12-hour days and barely cover their costs. Young
boys clean fish for nothing but tips.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Kagwa, a wader, buys fish off the boat, carries it to
shore, and sells it to the fishmongers at the tables. ``I load and
offload, 8 a.m. to 7 p.m.,'' he said. ``Maybe I get a few dollars a
day. Anyway, I survive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
