<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7663 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SKI-KOZNICK-BOS &LR;      04-05 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-KOZNICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRISTINA KOZNICK'S FANTASTIC FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After two back-to-back slalom wins to put a blazing finale on
her World Cup season for the US Ski Team last month, Kristina
Koznick had all but forgotten what a short leap it had been from
the lowest point in her career.
</P>
<P>
   Life as she knew it pretty much ended for Koz on a warm wet day
in Nagano, Japan, Feb. 26, 1998, when she got her weight thrown
back in a slalom gate and in a split second spun off the race
course into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of skiers did and always do DNF in slalom. But these were
the Winter Olympic Games, and with very few bright spots on the US
team, Koz, the 21-year old from Burnsville, Minn., was just about
the last hope for a podium spot on the Alpine technical side.
</P>
<P>
   Picabo Street would take gold in the Super-G that year, but
Koznick had the US medal hopes riding high into the last race day
of the games. And she was to learn that day how the very word
Olympic transforms ``just one more ski race'' into a live-or-die
pressure cooker.
</P>
<P>
   To counteract the emotional supercharge of Nagano, Koz remembers
approaching the race casually. ``I kept telling myself it wasn't a
big deal, I'd be fine, not to make a big deal out of it,'' says
Koznick, a muscular 5-foot-7-inch, 157-pounder from the middle of
the nation's frozen plains country, ``and that's pretty much how I
skied that race. Like it was no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, the rest of the skiers in the world were making
it a very big deal, and by comparison to the elite class she skis
with, Koz was plain flat-out slow in the first run.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the second run I didn't have a choice. I had to go pretty
much all-or-nothing, and I went out (skied off course for a DNF). I
thought, `Oh no, my life is over.' It was a pretty tragic moment
for me. I couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   And so at the tender age of 22, after romping through her
formative years with eight junior titles in all four events, and
joining World Cup at age 15, the most promising American Woman
skier of a decade had hit a definite bump in the road.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she ended that season in second place in the final World
Cup standings, with her first World Cup finish in Are, Sweden,
among her four trips to the podium, and her fourth straight US
slalom title. Still, the Olympic non-performance was the story of
Koznick's long-awaited debutante year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always say, `Oh you didn't win the Olympics. That was a
bad seson for you.' But,'' says Koz, ``I say, `No, it was a great
season for me.' Sure, I would have loved to do well in the
Olympics, but look at the rest of my season. The first race in Park
City was the only surprise for me all season. I knew I was capable
of being top three and I was fourth. But that was still a great
season for me, and I'll still get another shot at the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   But following her disappointing Olympics in 1998, Koznick's
career would tailspin deeper before she would hit bottom and start
on a comeback that found her soaring at the end of this season to
back-to-back wins.
</P>
<P>
   Koznick smiles easily and makes no excuses for herself. Like the
mythical Minnesotans in Garrison Keillor stories, she is
plain-talking and painfully honest at times, particularly when
assessing her own worst races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always look back at my bad races and learn an incredible
amount from them. And when I see what I did, that gives me real
growth and confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   She grew up skiing in the Erich Sailer's Buck Hill racing
program, one which taught skiers technical, quick, and aggressive
turns. She ended up ``skiing up,'' racing against skiers older than
herself. From the age of 12 through her teens, Koz won eight junior
championships, including, in 1991, the title in GS and Super-G. A
week later, she was asked to become the youngest member of the US
Alpine Ski Team.
</P>
<P>
   But Koznick says she will always consider Sailer her ``real''
coach. ``I say Erich Sailer was my first coach, but he really is
still my coach today and will be forever, even though we went our
separate ways when I made the national team. There's no one who
knows me better. We have that special connection that led me to my
optimum potential.''
</P>
<P>
   After the '98 season, in which she combined a nice consistency
over the winter with her disappointment at Nagano, the next year
was her worst on the circuit. Injuries and equipment problems
robbed her of the consistency she had the year before.
</P>
<P>
   In February at the Alpine Worlds in Vail, Koz fell one more
notch. Again, skiing as the United States' only medal hope at the
event, she filled the stands at the finish in Vail Village with
thousands of ski fans revelling in the Colorado sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   They grew expectant as her run became imminent and as she
started a huge roar went up. But as if a balloon popped, Koznick
again skied off course very early in the first run and the festival
atmosphere sagged. Koznick was not only inconsistent, but getting a
reputation for blowing the big races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look back at both those races,'' she says, ``and I hear
people saying I can't ski in important events, but it's just based
on two events, and I learned so much from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``After last season I really started out this one in the hole,''
she says. ``I mean I almost wasn't qualifying. So I had to pull
myself together and be patient with my skis. I just learned so much
about confidence _ just who I am and what's going on with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The first part of this season was not the turnaround that
Koznick had hoped it would be, though her persistent back problem
seemed to be solved and she was in the greatest shape of her life
thanks to her efforts with a personal trainer.
</P>
<P>
   But now equipment problems were holding her back. She was skiing
on long straight edged skis at a time many racers were adopting a
shorter, slightly shaped ski.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started doubting myself, and before one race I grabbed a
pair of short skis and went down the course with perfect form. But
I was slow. Up to the middle of January, I switched skis before
every race, which is really not great for your consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   But then Koz switched ski companies to Voekl, began racing on a
slightly carved shaped 170cm model, and finally was ``with a ski
company that seemed excited to have me.''
</P>
<P>
   And, by the next month, the results started to come. In
February, Koz started to hit the top five with a fourth and a
second. Than came Sestriere, Italy, and in front of a friendly
crowd, she got her first win of the season, the third World Cup of
her career.
</P>
<P>
   Her second victory came a week later, and she became convinced
that her training had overcome her old injuries, and that her skis
were dialed the way she needed them to win races.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a day,'' she said about her second conseutive win. ``It
was a beautiful sunny day, and the skiing couldn't have been much
better. And just to end the season with two wins gives me such
confidence going into next season. That's going to be the test.
Next year I have to be consistent and get some good results looking
ahead to Salt Lake City. We're psyched to have the games in our own
country and want to be ready for them.''
</P>
<P>
   If the timing is right, says Koz, the next Olympics could be
good for the home team, at least on the women's side. Youngsters
like Sara Schleper and Caoline Lalive are following Koz toward the
leader list, and Picabo Street will be returning from a major knee
blowout, perhaps to do some gate racing rather than downhill.
</P>
<P>
   After shoulder surger this summer, Koz says, ``It may take a
month or more to recover, and then I just want to get on my skis
and start training. This was definitely the way to finish my
season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
