<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPENCER TRACY: THE ACTOR'S ACTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's actors, however skilled or even Oscar-honored, usually
let the audience know they are acting. They did not have James
Stewart's good luck in 1935 during his first film, ``Murder Man.''
The star, Spencer Tracy, advised him to forget about the camera.
The rest is Hollywood history.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Milwaukee on April 5, 1900, Spencer Bonaventure Tracy
was the actor's actor. He worked hard to make it look easy. ``You
don't see the mechanism working, the wheels turning,'' Humphrey
Bogart once said of him. ``He makes you believe what he is
playing.'' Did he just play himself with minor variations or did he
inhabit each role with unsurpassed skill? That is Tracy's secret,
which he took to his grave in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   His believability made biographical films succeed: ``Edison the
Man'' and ``Stanley and Livingstone.'' From romantic comedy in
``Libeled Lady'' and ``Woman of the Year'' to sturdy political
melodrama in ``State of the Union'' and ``The Last Hurrah,'' he was
also the complete actor.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his nine Oscar nominations came from playing priests,
Father Mullin in ``San Francisco,'' and Father Flanagan in ``Boys
Town.'' Only Bing Crosby got more mileage out of a Roman collar.
Tracy once astonished his pal, Frank McHugh, by telling him that
Irish Catholic guilt helped him play priests. He was the fiercest
drunk this side of W. C. Fields and would vanish, as he confessed,
``to take two-week lunches.''
</P>
<P>
   After toiling for 20th Century Fox and MGM, the film factories
of the 1930s, Tracy's two Oscars came back-to-back. In ``Boys
Town'' in 1938, he boxed Mickey Rooney's ears. In 1937, portraying
Manuel, a Portuguese fisherman, in ``Captains Courageous,'' he
looked, said Joan Crawford at the time, ``like Harpo Marx.'' Worse,
he sounded like Chico Marx. He rarely appeared in great movies,
which intensified the admiration of his fellow actors.
</P>
<P>
   A later movie shows a truer Tracy. In 1955, he starred in ``Bad
Day at Black Rock,'' which John O'Hara called ``one of the finest
motion pictures ever made.'' Tracy's character subdues notable
heavies Robert Ryan, Ernest Borgnine, and Lee Marvin.
</P>
<P>
   Who, after Spencer Tracy's century, can replace him? Joe
Morgenstern of The Wall Street Journal says today's crop is ``more
mannered, much more facile, always actorly, while Tracy, Gary
Cooper, and those guys looked like they were plunked down on the
set.'' Morgenstern mentions John Cusack, ``who has that elusive
quality in an actor, what the Italians call `the art of concealing
art.' '' I tentatively nominate Sean Penn, once he shakes off early
mannerisms.
</P>
<P>
   David Thomson, a film historian who writes for London's
Independent, sees one older actor as ``the person who I would say
is Tracyesque. That is Gene Hackman, who is absolutely reliable.
There's the same privacy there that Tracy had. Neither man is
desperate that you should know him or like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy ``was a leading man and yet he was not pretty,'' Thomson
says. ``He later benefited from his biggest fan, Katharine Hepburn.
Supposing they had not met each other? Their relationship started
when they were past the blush of youth.'' Indeed, Hepburn was
``Keeper of the Flame,'' the title of one of nine movies in which
they co-starred, from 1942 to 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Kramer directed Tracy's final films. In Thomson's
``Biographical Dictionary of Film,'' the kindest adjective for
Kramer is ``pretentious.'' That is true of ``Judgment at
Nuremberg'' and the actor's last film, ``Guess Who's Coming to
Dinner?'' Shedding the advice of his mentor, George M. Cohan,
``Spencer, you have to act less,'' Tracy became preachy and
actorly.
</P>
<P>
   But in his prime, he had no peer. Nightclub comics once
impersonated stars like Bogey, Gable, and Cooper. ``I'm easy to
imitate,'' James Cagney said of his old pal, ``but you never saw
anyone imitate Spencer Tracy. You can't mimic reserve and control
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
