<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7666 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-05 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO THE BAD GUYS IN THE ELIAN AFFAIR: LET THE KID GO HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Send the kid home. Now.
</P>
<P>
   To his father. To Cuba. To The Big Beard. To the place where he
belongs. Maybe not the right place by everyone's lights. But four
months of legal mumbo-jumbo, political pandering, and mouthy
protestations of altruistic intervention in this poor tyke's
confused life do not mask the greasy reality: Elian Gonzalez has
been hijacked and is our political prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we all know Elian's deceased mother fled Cuba for Florida;
she wanted out for herself and the boy. But some things are bigger
than politics. And parenthood is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   The father is the father. He deserves custody, by any reasonable
standard of family court practice in the modern world. The Cuban
community in Florida, exiles bitter at Castro and expert at
manipulating conservative anti-Castro sentiment, have turned the
kid into a political football, with predictable negative
consequences for the lad.
</P>
<P>
   When the mayor of Dade County goes on TV with 20 other mayors to
boast that that he'll never let his police be used to enforce
federal immigration law in this case, he betrays the sort of
loutish rule-or-ruin mindset that belongs in a totalitarian state,
not here. What is it about the Cuban-American propaganda
puppeteers? What part of our legal system is it that they don't
get?
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore's apparent capitulation to the political
lobby in Florida is disappointing. Gore wants Congress to pass a
special law granting permanent resident status to the boy, his
father, and five other relatives. That's Florida Democratic Senator
Bob Graham's political solution; that, and give the state's family
court system jurisdiction over Elian's ultimate custody, not the
federal Immigration and Naturalization Service. Gore defenders
shrug and say that's what Al thinks is right, too. And George W.
Bush makes three.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Al, don't let those recent polling numbers in Florida
confuse you. Yeah, you're up by a handful over Bush in the land of
Mickey, mangroves, and Metamucil. But that ain't gonna last. Forget
about those 25 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   If you are to win Florida, you'll be winning about 43 other
states to boot. By November, the Florida governor, also named Bush,
will have shaved that lead of yours. Al, I know I was with John
McCain during the primaries. But I'll be with you in November, I'm
almost positive. George W. is not my cup of tea.
</P>
<P>
   But, Al, don't make it any harder than it has to be, for all
those of us who were looking elsewhere over the winter. Check out
what happened to Bush, after he ditched ``compassionate
conservatism'' for Bob Jones and McCain-bashing. Bush's once-comfy
lead among independents and women has gone poof!
</P>
<P>
   As Al From, the Democratic strategist of moderate _ and
therefore winning inclinations put it _ ``the way you win
Independents is with independence.'' Americans elsewhere have not
been stampeded by the Cuban contortions in Miami. The latest Gallup
Poll survey on CNN says 64 percent want Elian restored to his
father. That 2-1 verdict in the court of public opinion has been
virtually immovable over nearly half a year of political
tug-of-war.
</P>
<P>
   In an unsolicited discussion with a lower-ranking Clinton
administration political type, I was told that the Gore camp made
an apparent miscalculation about the views of Hispanic voters on
this sensational case. They are not monolithic; while Miami Cubans
want to hold on to the kid, the Mexican-Americans of the Southwest
and the Latin-Americans of the Northeast coalesce around the notion
that family is family and that fatherhood is too important to
overturn hundreds of centuries of hewing to that fact.
</P>
<P>
   It's fact-facing time: Two-thirds of Americans want the boy to
go back. His father wants him back. Bill Clinton wants him to go
back. Hillary, too. But the same gang of right-wingers who gave us
impeachment, the government shutdown, no action on gun control a
year after Columbine, and the wrangling over abortion has seized
this little kid for the crassest of political reasons. By their
motives shall we judge them.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Republican Party sent out fund-raising letters
predictably accusing the Clinton administration of ``cowardice''
and appeasing Castro. That was too much for Governor Jeb Bush, who
disowned the embarrassing letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor believes it was and is inappropriate to use Elian
Gonzalez for political purposes,'' said Jeb Bush's spokesman. Oh?
Yeah. Right.
</P>
<P>
   We are on the cusp of the nastiest political year since 1968.
Back then the rough stuff was in the streets. This year the dirty
game is in the suites. The Bush campaign has gone the sleaze route
from Day One against Clinton-Gore. The Gore campaign is equally
adept in areas that would cause the Marquess of Queensberry to
swoon. This is not a year for the faint-hearted voter. On the
matter of pandering to the 12 percent of Florida voters of
Cuban-American descent, both Bushes and now Gore have shown
profiles in discouragement.
</P>
<P>
   And don't tell me McCain would be any better on this issue. My
friend John had his chance and tanked too. Could it be something in
the water pumped in from the Okefenokee Swamp?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
