<HEADLINE>
SEX PREY; STAR DIGS; THE DOUBTING DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a creepola story in the April GQ called ``My Mentor, My
Rapist,'' and it's by a magazine writer who chooses to call himself
Anonymous. The piece charts his dawning awareness that his trusted
friend, a slightly older ``rising star at a big-city magazine''
whom he calls ``the tall man,'' was drugging him and then raping
him. Twice, the two men agreed to take the tall man's
hallucinogenic mushrooms, but the effect both times found
Anonymous, who is straight, waking up in the tall man's bed after
huge blacked-out gaps of time. Not very psychedelic. Anonymous's
next epic blackout came after a drink and a joint, and the final
episode was induced by a bowl of soup.
</P>
<P>
   Why did the increasingly suspicious Anonymous continue to spend
time with his friend? Haunted by his father's suicide, he wondered
if ``this blacking out, or this loss of memory, or this sexual
schizophrenia might be its shadow.'' Also, amid his friend's
denials, he had his urine tested for Rohypnol, aka Roofies, the
tasteless, colorless drug that has been in the news because of its
use by sexual predators. The results came back negative.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, however, after breaking off with the tall man
and trying unsuccessfully to shake feelings of violation, Anonymous
has the same urine retested and, alas, the results reveal
concentrations of a hypnotic sedative called Restoril. Lost in
violent fantasies about retribution, he instead decides to call the
police, who quickly assure him that the tall man was a rapist and
that he exhibited familiar patterns of behavior. But, in a twist of
the knife that Anonymous doesn't elaborate on, the detectives don't
encourage him to press charges; Anonymous' recreational drug use
would ``trouble the D.A.'' And so the tall man, now the head of a
``new cyberventure,'' remains free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I won't even pretend I read Architectural Digest for the
articles. And this month's issue is a particularly fat and gorgeous
invasion of privacy called ``Hollywood at Home.'' The photo spreads
jump between now (Claire Danes, Samuel L. Jackson, William H. Macy)
and then (Clark Gable, Natalie Wood, Bing Crosby), and it's
interesting to note just how much simpler home glamour was back in
the black-and-white days. Does Mickey Rourke actually take off his
shoes and kick back in his gaudy, gilted, fringed, draped, and
monotonously maroon-colored pied-a-terre in New York?
</P>
<P>
   In The New Yorker for April 10, Jerome Groopman looks into what
the French call ``the doubting disease,'' and what we call
Obsessive Compulsive Disorder. He notes that many prominent
scientists exhibit traits of the disorder, and goes on to discuss
the matter with a series of experts. The piece is particularly
interesting in light of our eagerness to diagnose children with the
likes of Attention Deficit Disorder and give them drugs, and it
addresses what one psychologist calls the ``pathologizing of
people's behaviors.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of obsessive behavior . . .
</P>
<P>
   When you don't even pause for a moment to scan an infinitely
long ``Boys on the Bus''-esque Rolling Stone meta-article about a
week with John McCain written by the 
so-brilliant-he-knows-he's-not-brilliant-which-is-what-makes-him-so-
brilliant author David Foster Wallace, an article whose subtext is
nothing less than American politics, Young Voter apathy, and, of
course, the media, and when you ignore David Fricke's beautifully
photographed Crosby, Stills, Nash &AMP; Young piece, which you later
discover is impressively honest and thorough and worthwhile for any
fan, semi-fan, or former fan, all just so that you can skip
directly to the junky celebrity profile of Julia Roberts, a
surprisingly late-in-the-game article that arrives a veritable
Hollywood eternity after the 32-year-old actress has already
appeared in almost every major glossy and newspaper promoting her
new movie, ``Erin Brockovich,'' quipping about the everpresent
cleavage and the everpresent tongue-wagging about the everpresent
cleavage, chatting oh-so-confidentially about her love affair with
Benjamin Bratt, and miraculously maintaining her wholesome-girl
image while peppering her comments with truck-driver expletives,
then you have to admit that you can understand how a mildly
talented actress with a horsey, 1000-watt smile can not only carry
a movie but inspire millions of fans to read about her over and
over again, in stories that all sound the same, in magazines that
all look the same, and that you instinctively understand the
meaning of star quality, circa 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
