<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7669 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-RAP-STABBINGS-BOS &LR;      04-05 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAP-STABBINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMOTERS SAY MAYHEM MIGHT HURT FUTURE TOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was supposed to be a monumental collaboration _ one
that raised rap shows to a new level in terms of dollars spent and
money made, and for its emphasis on unity. The violence that
erupted in a backstage corridor at the Ruff Ryders/Cash Money show
Monday night at the FleetCenter was in tragically ironic
juxtaposition to the values of brotherhood and camaraderie espoused
by the two families that respectively run the Ruff Ryders and Cash
Money record labels.
</P>
<P>
   Five people were stabbed just inside the only entrance to a
backstage VIP area halfway through the show, and another victim was
injured by a thrown marble bench just after a large group crashed
the security checkpoint, according to Phil Casey, executive vice
president and head of urban music for International Creative
Management, which booked the tour. ``I understand that people
bum-rushed the backstage area,'' Casey said. ``They rushed right
through and then the confrontation happened.'' In a genre already
saddled with a reputation for deadly rivalries, and in the midst of
a tour that's trying to dispel some of those negative images, the
FleetCenter fracas is likely to have a far-reaching impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major setback,'' said Glen Miller, vice president of
media relations at New York-based Double XXposure and publicist for
the Ruff Ryders/Cash Money tour. ``It's very sad that this singular
incident will probably overshadow the whole tour.''
</P>
<P>
   There had been no unusual problems on the tour, according to a
check of police reports filed in Rochester, N.Y.; Long Island;
Philadelphia; Houston; Cleveland; Baltimore; and Washington, D.C. A
return engagement at the First Union Spectrum theater in
Philadelphia scheduled for Tuesday night has been postponed
indefinitely _ a decision made by the tour producers, not the
venue, said First Union spokesman Ike Richman. The remaining nine
shows on the tour, which began on Feb. 23, will continue as
planned, according to Casey.
</P>
<P>
   Although police aren't releasing details in the ongoing
investigation, many sources say that Boston rap group Made Men _
who only recently joined the tour _ and their entourage were
involved in the altercation and may have been among the stabbing
victims. ``I think this was an aberration. Boston hasn't been
identified as a problem market,'' said Casey, whose company beefs
up the standard metal-detector and bag check with uniformed police
details and two or three checkpoints in high-risk markets like LA
and New York. ``We are strongly considering additional security
backstage and cutting out backstage guests for the rest of this
tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Aberration or not, the mayhem at the FleetCenter will further
entrench hip-hop's reputation for violence. ``What we'll be dealing
with is venues not wanting shows to come in, and parents not
wanting their kids to come to the shows,'' says Casey. ``But
there's never a problem like this on the floor. The trouble takes
place when people who believe they should be backstage try to get
in backstage, or when they try to go to the hotel afterwards
looking for a party. We know where these problems are. But parents
hear there's a problem, and they aren't gonna let their kids go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ruff Ryders/Cash Money tour is expected to be the biggest
hip-hop road show in the genre's history. So far it's been
averaging $500,000 a city, compared with $275,000 for last year's
Hard Knock Life tour, according to the concert trade publication
Pollstar. As a collaboration between two dominant labels, the tour
was also intended to undo some of the PR damage inflicted by
historic inter-label and bicoastal rivalries, which are generally
believed to be behind the murders of rappers Biggie Smalls and
Tupac Shakur.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Casey spoke to Ronald and Brian Williams, co-founders of
New Orleans-based Cash Money, at 3 a.m. Tuesday, approximately five
hours after the stabbings occurred. ``They are freaked out by
this,'' said Casey. ``They've been getting this racially mixed,
gender-mixed audience. We've all felt that we had a pretty secure
thing. There haven't been problems of this sort. The brothers are
insisting that we put it on lockdown and police detail from now
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Full refunds will be given to fans with April 3 ticket stubs at
the point of purchase; those who bought tickets over the Internet
or via phone charge will automatically have accounts credited. The
question is: Will those kids buy tickets to the next hip-hop show
that rolls through town? Or perhaps more to the point, will there
be a next hip-hop show?
</P>
<P>
   According to Casey, this won't deter the fans. ``You know why?
Because there were 5,000 people at the FleetCenter who didn't know
that anything was going on. It didn't affect the audience.'' The
future of the rap tours themselves, though, is another story. ``The
building managers have been looking for any excuse not to put these
shows into their buildings. For them, it's just another nail to
hang the hat on.'' Local promoter Don Law, who books the majority
of local music shows for national promoter SFX, would not comment.
Al Haymon, who promoted the tour nationally for SFX, did not return
calls for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
