<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIP-HOP DOESN'T DESERVE THE RAP FOR VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someone somewhere is shaking their head saying, ``I told you
so.''
</P>
<P>
   With this week's headlines that at least six people were
stabbed, one critically, during a backstage fracas at the Ruff
Ryders/Cash Money tour stop at Boston's FleetCenter Monday night,
will come the inevitable bray of naysayers strenuously voicing that
no one should be surprised violence marred a hip-hop concert.
</P>
<P>
   They will point to the still-unsolved murders of Tupac and
Biggie, the mayhem-laced lyrics of many rap artists, and the
ongoing legal problems of Jay-Z and Puff Daddy _ on assault and
weapons charges, respectively _ as evidence that this is an unruly
music marinated in brutality, and that the culture it spawned has
yet again shown its true, savage self. Already Tuesday's
Philadelphia show, featuring such hot hip-hop stars as Eve, DMX and
Juvenile, was canceled, and the rest of the tour remains up in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   I, for one, hope the tour continues because anything less would
dishonor hip-hop and its legions of fans who deserve better.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: no one should ever attend a concert, rap or
otherwise, either as a fan or performer, and leave in an ambulance
because of violence. But as unsettling as it is, it's shortsighted,
and just plain wrong to blame rap music in general, and hip-hop
culture in particular, for the troubles at Monday's FleetCenter
concert.
</P>
<P>
   Because of problems at some shows in the 1980s, rap had all but
died as a concert attraction. After several scuffles during
Run-DMC's ``Raisin' Hell'' tour in 1986, it was nearly impossible
to find venues and promoters willing to mount shows some began to
believe were inherently rife with difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Such attitudes began to thaw in 1997, when Puff Daddy, then at
the height of his powers, launched the ``No Way Out Tour,'' with,
among others, Jay-Z, Usher, Mase and Lil' Kim. Even Puff understood
that the tour wasn't just about the Benjamins. It was also a vote
on the viability of the rap concert, and an opportunity to prove
that such shows could be violence-free.
</P>
<P>
   The tour went off without a hitch and Puffy couldn't help but
trumpet what its success meant, not only to him personally, but to
the hip-hop community at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody hugging, touching, everybody just up against each
other, and everybody was cool with it,'' Puffy told MTV News during
a Detroit stop. ``They came to enjoy the music and that's what they
did, that's what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first tour to go over good,'' said DMX, ``and to
give a rap tour the credibility it needs to continue to exist.''
</P>
<P>
   With rap proving it could throw a peaceful party, 1999 saw the
even-more ambitious ``Hard Knock Life'' tour. Even though Puff &AMP;
Co.'s shows were as problem-free, this tour was again heavily
scrutinized since this was the first featuring all hardcore rap
acts with Jay-Z, DMX, Method Man and Redman.
</P>
<P>
   (It's as if every rap tour has to pass a test. Yet, I don't
recall other bands, say, the Rolling Stones, undergoing a rigorous
examination after their disastrous concert at Altamont Speedway in
1969, where a fan was stabbed to death by the Stones' hired
``security,'' the Hell's Angels.)
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, two months, 54 shows (including a stop at the
FleetCenter), and $18 million later, ``Hard Knock Life,'' left the
road as the most successful hip-hop tour ever. More important,
there was no violence.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, there were no problems on the Ruff Ryders/Cash Money
tour, which began in February, until Monday's FleetCenter show. But
hip-hop's critics, who've been forecasting its demise for 20 years,
will conveniently overlook that fact. They will also ignore the
fact that many concerts, regardless of the artists or type of
music, have been scarred by boorish behavior or violence _ from the
Who's ill-fated Cincinnati concert in 1979, where 11 fans were
crushed to death to last year's Woodstock, which degenerated into a
Bacchanalian free-for-all, although the majority of fans behaved
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a sporting event or a concert, there always
potential for danger and disorder when large groups of people
congregate. But you could no more blame baseball for a fight in the
Fenway stands _ or an on-field dust-up among teams _ than hip-hop
should be blamed for Monday night's events.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, other rap tours scheduled this year, including the
hotly-awaited ``Chronic 2000,'' with Dr. Dre, Eminem, Snoop Dogg,
Warren G, and Xzibit, will not be unfairly branded. What occurred
at the FleetCenter should not be taken as a referendum future rap
tours _ nor should hip-hop and its fans be condemned for the
stupid, selfish actions of a few.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham comments on the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7672 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-FARAH-ART-BOS &LR;      04-05 1572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-FARAH-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 A NOVELIST'S VIVID VOICE OF SOMALIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With deliberate moves, Nuruddin Farah took three of his
novels from a canvas bag and placed them on a podium. Then, after
donning glasses, he paused to peer at the 30 people who recently
gathered at the Barnes &AMP; Noble to hear him read.
</P>
<P>
   The quiet, respectful group was a small testament to the growing
popularity of the Somali novelist. Critics call Farah, 54, a
writer's writer, and his most ardent fans are certainly a literary
who's who: Nadine Gordimer, Chinua Achebe, Salman Rushdie. Recent
glowing reviews in The Wall Street Journal, the New York Times Book
Review, and Washington Post Book World (not to mention the
prestigious Neustadt International Prize for Literature, which he
won in 1998) are helping to spread the Farah gospel.
</P>
<P>
   His eight novels combine unique turns of phrase, political
criticism, and vividly crafted characters to deftly bring to life
the country Farah calls his obsession: Somalia. He creates a
three-dimensional world far more complex than the media's depiction
of bellicose Somalis chewing buzz-inducing khat leaves during the
US military relief mission in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Farah's candid critiques of the country's dictatorship resulted
in three attempts on his life while former president Mohamed Siad
Barre was in power. Ultimately, his tangles with Barre forced him
to live in exile, for 21 years now, in various African countries.
South Africa is his current home.
</P>
<P>
   He ``approaches subjects that most people are scared to write
about nowadays, subjects of a sexual nature and a political
nature,'' says acclaimed author Ishmael Reed, who notes that among
the literati, Farah is rumored to be the next African writer in
line for a Nobel Prize in Literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a leading African writer of great talent and
originality,'' Gordimer recently said of Farah in a written press
statement.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of the bookstore event, Farah began by reading
from his sixth book, ``Maps.'' The novel, which tells the story of
a Somali orphan raised by an Ethiopian woman, explores territorial
issues. (Ethiopia and Somalia have been hostile neighbors for more
than a century because of border disputes.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You sit,'' Farah begins in a Somali accent tinged with British
inflections, ``in contemplative posture, your features agonized and
your expressions pained; you sit for hours and hours and hours,
sleepless, looking into darkness, hearing a small snore coming from
the room next to yours. And you conjure a past: a past in which you
see a horse drop its rider; a past in which you discern a bird
breaking out of its shell so it will fly into the heavens of
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours earlier, in the bookstore's conference room, Farah talked
about the forces that brought him to this point in his career. Like
a human ocean wave, he leans in when a subject he's excited about
is broached, then relaxes back into his chair, stretching out his
ropelike arms and legs.
</P>
<P>
   A salt-and-pepper mustache and half-moon eyes add character to
Farah's face, which is the color of rich mahogany. He speaks five
languages, including Amharic (the official language of Ethiopia),
Italian, Arabic, and Somali, and chooses his words carefully, often
pausing thoughtfully before finishing sentences rife with dry wit.
</P>
<P>
   Farah started his literary career in the late 1960s, at a time
when Somalia didn't have a written language. Then fate _ in the
form of an English typewriter _ interceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very practical person,'' he says wryly. ``I found an
excellent typewriter so I said, `Why not? Why not write in that
language?' ''
</P>
<P>
   It was our gain, says Richard Seaver, the publisher of Arcade
Publishing in New York, who edited Farah's last three novels.
``Nuruddin's English enriches our language because he brings to it
both an African sensibility and a gift for language that just flows
in a way I have never read in anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet writing in English has limited Farah's Somali audience.
Gamal Gulaid, a Somali now residing in Malden who came to hear
Farah read at Barnes &AMP; Noble, noted that Farah's audience is
usually composed of educated Somalis, Westerners, and college
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are about 5,000 Somalis in this city, and at this
reading there were less than 10 that showed up,'' Gulaid said after
the event. ``On one hand, he carries the banner for Somalia. On the
other hand, the majority of Somalis don't know about him or they
know about him but don't read him.''
</P>
<P>
   Farah often tells proverbs to illustrate a point. Ask him about
his family's reaction to his political outspokenness and he
recounts a Somali folk tale about a woman whose child refused to
speak. The mother would pray every day: ``God, God, make my son
speak.'' Finally when the child was 9, he did, saying, ``Mummy,
let's make love.'' The mother then recommenced her prayers,
``Please make him quiet!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Somalis were rather hopeful,'' Farah explains, ``that it would
be one of their sons who would become a writer, would do good,
would bring a good name to the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Farah's literary output had his family begging him to be
silent for his own safety. He first crossed the government when he
wrote a play in which the only Somali character got drunk onstage.
He ran into more trouble when his first book, ``From a Crooked
Rib,'' criticized the treatment of women in his homeland, which
also isolated him from his male friends.
</P>
<P>
   He continues to take a feminist stance in his books that's
unique for male African writers. He fills his novels with strong
female characters inspired by his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``She struck me as being a great deal wiser than my father,''
says Farah. ``And yet, although people came to her privately, she
could never have opinions on matters of great importance. There was
no public function for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember thinking to myself, `You know, it's necessary for
the privately held view of my mother to be made public. The wisdom
of women should become the property of all.' ''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Farah released his third novel, ``Sweet and Sour
Milk,'' part of a trilogy bluntly called ``Variations on the Theme
of an African Dictatorship,'' he had been sentenced to a life
outside his home country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shock at first,'' remembers Farah of his inability to
return to Somalia under Barre's rule, which ended in 1991. Five
years later, Farah paid a visit to Somalia, which has not had a
central government since Barre was ousted.
</P>
<P>
   Farah casually mentions that during the trip, he was taken
hostage by a warlord for five days (he tends to discuss the more
dramatic aspects of his life in a blase, another-day-at-the-office
tone). The author then traveled to Mogadishu, where he absorbed the
experience of modern-day Somalia by listening to locals tell their
tales.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in a sense,'' Farah continues, ``it was also a relief. . .
. We have another Somali proverb: A hunchback must learn to live
with the discomfort of his body. You see, you can't continue
saying, `I'm a hunchback, and I don't know how to sleep.' You have
to find a way of sleeping comfortably.''
</P>
<P>
   Farah found his solution by remaining in Africa. He's lived in
Nigeria, Ethiopia, Uganda, Sudan, and Gambia. Most recently, he
settled in Cape Town, South Africa, where his wife is director of
the University of Cape Town's Gender Studies Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The creativity of my neuroses depends on my presence in
Africa,'' explains Farah. ``Lots of people who don't live in Africa
see Africa as a crisis point. . . . Whereas when you live in it on
a day-to-day basis, it becomes one of the narratives that are
unfolding. It doesn't shock you anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   But it does allow Farah to produce loving portraits of Somalia
in a publishing environment that, Ishmael Reed believes, expects a
less magnanimous approach when it comes to this subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult for a writer like Nuruddin to not just
write about the pathologies of African culture, which is how you
get over here,'' says Reed, who met him when Farah was speaking at
the University of California at Berkeley in 1980. ``There are a
couple of major African writers who are like a road show. They go
around universities bad-mouthing Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in his first work of nonfiction, ``Yesterday, Tomorrow:
Voices From the Somali Diaspora,'' Farah's goal is to clarify and
educate. The book, released in March, recounts the experiences of
Somali refugees in Africa and Europe culled from 250 interviews
Farah conducted over a seven-year period.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Farah doesn't summon up an African proverb to explain
why he embarked on this project. He uses blunt, straightforward
English.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't read anything good about the civil war in Somalia,''
says Farah, whose next work of fiction will focus on his homeland
during the period of 1990 to 1994. ``I thought I should start the
debate. . . . Even if people don't agree with my interpretation, at
least there is an interpretation made from the perspective of
knowledge. Because the majority of people who have written about
Somalia _ Americans and other foreigners _ have really no idea of
Somalia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
