<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7675 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-BLACK-BOS &LR;      04-05 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BLACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELODRAMA MARS EDGY LOOK AT RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
BLACK AND WHITE 
Written and directed by: James Toback 
Starring: Scott Caan, Robert Downey, Jr., Stacy Edwards, Gaby
Hoffman, Allen Houston, Jared Leto, Marla Maples, Method Man, Joe
Pantoliano, Bijou Phillips, Power, Raekwon, Claudia Schiffer,
William Lee Scott, Brooke Sihelds, Ben Stiller, Eddie Kaye Thomas,
Mike Tyson, Elijah Wood 
Running time: 100 minutes 
Rated: R (strong sexuality, graphic language, some violence and
drug use) 
Rating: !! 1/2 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1935, DuBose Heyward, author of ``Porgy'' and the screenplay
of Eugene O'Neill's ``The Emperor Jones,'' wrote of a deadened
white culture vampirically sucking vitality from marginalized
blacks. Long before that, minstrel shows served blacks up as clowns
for the consumption of white audiences, while white performers
slipped into blackface to indulge in behavior deemed out of bounds
to whites. In 1958, Norman Mailer updated the situation in ``The
White Negro.'' He described would-be white hipsters latching onto
black cool, continuing the grotesque, mutually exploitative dance
of the races in America. Whites want rejuvenation and validation
from blacks. Blacks want power denied them by whites.
</P>
<P>
   If there's one American subject that comes fully loaded, it's
this still unresolved one. Today it's being danced to rap and
hip-hop. James Toback's ``Black and White,'' about upper
middle-class white kids trying to be black at precisely the moment
when their black gangsta heroes are trying to mainstream themselves
out of the ghetto, latches onto this uneasy symbiosis with an
invigorating edge before losing itself in cumbersome melodrama.
It's at its best in its semi-improvisatory confrontational dialogue
of cultural collision _ white kids exasperating their parents by
talking trash at their pricey Upper East Side dining room tables,
black guys allowing the same kids to hang around their cribs, where
the kids fantasize about belonging.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing Toback does in his best film _ flaws and all _ is
to convey the idea that nobody feels that he or she belongs.
``Black and White'' is above all a comedy of universal dislocation.
Nobody is as cool or as confident as he or she pretends to be.
Toback juggles irony and compassion deftly even when he dances on
the edge of caricature, as with Brooke Shields's dreadlocked
documentarian, following the white kids around with her camcorder,
consuming them as they consume hip-hop culture. Her flamingly gay
husband, played by Robert Downey Jr., has a brilliant scene when he
hits on Mike Tyson at a party with the predictable result.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that Mike Tyson. He's surprisingly disarming and even sweet
in his feature debut. Tyson does a great Tyson. ``Black and White''
gives a meaty role to another pro athlete, Knicks mainstay Allen
Houston, who's both charming and affecting as a college basketball
star tempted to throw a game. You expect droll performances from
Downey and the revved-up younger actors. What you don't expect are
a handful of entertaining performances by people you don't think of
as actors _ Claudia Schiffer's treacherous girlfriend, Marla
Maples's beleaguered mom, even Toback's smarmy studio owner.
Obviously, this was an energized shoot. Still, the dominant
performance is that of Wu Tang Clan's Oli ``Power'' Grant as the
brooding producer who doesn't want to mess up his chance at real
showbiz clout.
</P>
<P>
   It can at least be said of his character that he knows what he
wants and is something more than the sum of his insecurities and
identity crises. Otherwise, the film is a mix of danger and poses.
Unfortunately, it veers away from the freshness and urgency of its
across-the-board culture clashes and into a series of increasingly
contrived melodramatic dead ends that play like outtakes from a TV
cop show. In the end, it just may be too honky-centric to cover the
ground it wants to cover. Marginalized Irish and Italians
reinvented themselves in empowering ways in America's first wave of
gangster movies in the '30s. There's no reason African-Americans
can't do the same in gangsta movies. Certainly there's a great
film, a ``Godfatha,'' to be made about gangsta culture, but I'm not
sure Toback is the one to make it. Still, ``Black and White'' is an
often dynamic film and a stretch for Toback, even if it's a case of
nice try but no exploding cigar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1140EDT &QL; 
