<HEADER>
A7731 &Cx1f; tab-z
u d BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV17-     04-05 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV17-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV17 
 (FOR RELEASE WED., APRIL 17, 2000, AND THEREAFTER) 
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: ASPARAGUS _ ROASTED, IN SALAD AND IN
RISOTTO 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by 20-MINUTE-MENUS clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Asparagus are native to the eastern Mediterranean. They were
cultivated by the ancient Greeks despite warnings from a 4th
century B.C. writer who said they caused blindness.
</P>
<P>
   You can understand why the warnings were ignored. Asparagus are
so delicious, so filled with the flavors of spring. Everyone says
that wild asparagus are far superior to the cultivated variety.
Since most of us aren't likely to find them it's hardly a hardship
to have to eat those that we find in the store.
</P>
<P>
   But you will find the best flavor if you wait until asparagus
are in season, and the closer they are to where you live the better
they are likely to taste. Asparagus start to lose both flavor and
texture the moment they are picked. One way you can improve on them
is to break off the tough part of the stalk and sit the rest of the
asparagus in sugared water for 30 minutes. Prime season is March to
May.
</P>
<P>
   If you are serving asparagus with a dressing that contains lemon
or vinegar do not sauce them until just before serving because the
acid will turn the asparagus a yellowish to grayish green.
</P>
<P>
   ASPARAGUS AND CHEESE SALAD
</P>
<P>
   The only way this recipe works is if the spears are sliced
paper-thin. If you are very good with a knife you can do this.
Otherwise, use a mandoline if you have one. You can also cut them
on the thinnest slicing blade of a food processor.
</P>
<P>
   12 asparagus spears
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   A few shakes salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 ounces Parmigiano Reggiano (heaping 7 tablespoons)
</P>
<P>
   1. Snap the tough end of the asparagus from the tender at the
point where it breaks naturally. Wash the asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cut the asparagus tips from the stalk and cut lengthwise in
halves. Slice the stalks on the diagonal as thin as possible.
</P>
<P>
   3. Arrange the asparagus on a serving plate; season with salt
and pepper and drizzle with oil.
</P>
<P>
   4. Using a vegetable peeler scrape the cheese right over the
asparagus to cover.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   12 asparagus spears
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 ounces Parmigiano Reggiano
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED ASPARAGUS
</P>
<P>
   Roasting changes the flavor of asparagus from green and
springlike to rich, earthy and concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   1 pound asparagus
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Few shakes salt, optional
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon, optional
</P>
<P>
   1. Place the oven rack in the top third of the oven and preheat
the oven to 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   2. Break the tough ends from the asparagus at the point where
they meet the tender part and break easily. Wash asparagus, place
on jelly roll pan and drizzle with oil. Season with salt, if
desired. Roll the asparagus to coat them with the oil.
</P>
<P>
   3. Roast for about 5 minutes; shake the pan to prevent sticking.
Continue roasting, another 2 to 5 minutes. When the asparagus
soften and begin to brown here and there _ 7 to 10 minutes _ they
are done.
</P>
<P>
   4. Serve with lemon wedges if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: I think they have their truest flavor without the salt and
with just a squeeze of lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   You can also steam the asparagus and follow the directions in
the recipe above. Heat the oven to 475; roll asparagus in oil,
eliminate the salt and sprinkle with 2 tablespoons of grated
Parmigiano Reggiano. Roast for 5 minutes without turning or shaking
the pan.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Lemon
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   1 pound asparagus
</P>
<P>
   RISOTTO WITH ASPARAGUS AND PROSCIUTTO
</P>
<P>
   4 cups no-salt-added vegetable or chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   2 large shallots
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 pound asparagus
</P>
<P>
   1 cup arborio rice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces Parmigiano Reggiano (1/2 cup plus 2 tablespoons
coarsely grated)
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces prosciutto
</P>
<P>
   1. In a saucepan, heat the stock to a simmer.
</P>
<P>
   2. Chop the shallots. Heat the oil in a deep, heavy-bottomed
pot; add the shallots and saute until they take on a little color.
</P>
<P>
   3. Wash the asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   5. Add the rice to the shallots; stir well to coat.
</P>
<P>
   6. Add the wine to the rice, stir, and let the wine cook away,
about 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   7. Snap the tough stem ends of the asparagus, breaking them at
the point where the woody part meets the tender part. Cut the
spears just below the tips and cut the rest of the stems into 1/2
inch pieces.
</P>
<P>
   8. Add about a cup of simmering stock to the rice and cook over
medium high heat, stirring frequently until the liquid has been
absorbed. Repeat this procedure, adding more stock as it is
absorbed into the rice while stirring often.
</P>
<P>
   9. Grate the cheese and cut the prosciutto into small pieces.
</P>
<P>
   10. Five minutes before the rice is cooked, stir the asparagus
into the rice. When the rice is tender but before all the stock has
been absorbed _ the mixture should be slightly runny _ remove from
the heat. Season with pepper and stir in the cheese and the
prosciutto.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   4 cups no-salt-added vegetable or chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   2 large shallots
</P>
<P>
   1 pound asparagus
</P>
<P>
   Package arborio rice
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces Parmigiano Reggiano
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces prosciutto
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING
</P>
<P>
   Asparagus and Cheese Salad
</P>
<P>
   60 calories, 5 grams fat, 5 milligrams cholesterol, 70
milligrams sodium, 3 grams protein, 1 gram carbohydrate
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Asparagus
</P>
<P>
   75 calories, 5 grams fat, 0 cholesterol, 5 milligrams sodium, 5
grams protein, 5 grams carbohydrate
</P>
<P>
   Risotto with Asparagus and Prosciutto
</P>
<P>
   710 calories, 18 grams fat, 30 milligrams cholesterol, 490
milligrams sodium, 25 grams protein, 100 grams carbohydrate
</P>
