<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7742 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-BLACKANDW     04-05 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-BLACKANDWHITE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHAT'S `BLACK AND WHITE' AND DULL ALL OVER? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tag line for ``Black and White,'' James Toback's
improvisatory investigation of hip-hop culture and the white kids
who've embraced it, asks: ``What happens when you mix it up?''
</P>
<P>
   You should answer, ``Ideological disaster!'' Then wave your
hands in the air, wave 'em like you just don't care. It's that kind
of experiment.
</P>
<P>
   As hip-hop has become what rock critic Tour defensively dubbed
``its own nation,'' the problems of such a self-governing body _
foreigners working without visas, urban sprawl, pollution, a budget
surplus _ only beget more problems.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-age poseurs from the Upper West Side of New York aren't
thorns in hip-hop's side, they're its insane clown posse. And for
its first 15 minutes, ``Black and White'' gets off on telling that
joke: rich white kids (none more thrilling in her obnoxiousness
than Bijou Phillips' Charlie) eliding their wealthy backgrounds as
a means of rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Toback seems to grasp the race-trading going on among a pack of
kids literally horny for hip-hop: Philips' performance begins as a
whiny grotesque _ she's a toddler with gold caps and bamboo
earrings who calls the place you go to borrow books a ``lybaree.''
She's late for dinner because she and a girlfriend were out
trysting in the woods with thug-turning-rap producer Rich (Wu-Tang
Clan's Oli ``Power'' Grant) and rapper Cigar (Wu's Corey
``Raekwon'' Woods). We know where she's been, and her B-girl
ecstasy manifests itself as hip-hop potty mouth that sends welfare
chills down her mother Muffy's (Marla Maples) spine. It's a funny,
if utterly rote subversion of upper-echelon staidness that's like
beating a long-empty piata.
</P>
<P>
   It also telegraphs the pseudosensationalism to follow. Toback is
on a serious Altman bender here. In a matter of minutes, the
``Black and White'' ensemble swells from one girl and her friends
(seemingly cuckoo for Cocoa Puff Daddies) into an abominably
distilled opera cum traffic jam about racial and pop essentialism
that in its shortcomings feels desperately snoopy.
</P>
<P>
   Brooke Shields materializes in dreadlocks as Sam Donager, a
documentary filmmaker who wants to make a video documentary about
Charlie and her friends _ the rest of whom are played by Gaby
Hoffman, Eddie Kaye Thomas and Elijah Wood, three actors who are
trying to stretch their caricatures into a realm of three
dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   The kids explain their lifestyle to Sam and her gay husband
(played by Robert Downey Jr., doing a swishier, creepier remix of
his ``Wonder Boys'' slattern). If ``Black and White'' seems facile
and inconclusive wading in this end of the pool, it's downright
retarded as it skates on the patina of black male virility and
racism. There's a story line involving Dean, a college hoops star
(New York Knicks point guard Allan Houston) who's duped into
accepting money from a fallen cop (Ben Stiller) looking for
redemption. He uses Dean to get to Rich. And somewhere in all this
is Claudia Schiffer as Dean's manipulative grad-student girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   As he demonstrated with the similarly improv-derived ``Two Girls
and Guy,'' Toback is an actor's director only insofar as he carves
out spaces for improvisation. But Downey, who's been blazingly
self-aware in two previous outings with Toback, is the one actor
who knows what to do within them.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what Toback appears to be doing involves laying out
texts like Albert Murray's ``The Omni-Americans,'' Norman Mailer's
``The White Negro,'' and Robert Downey Sr.'s film, ``Putney
Swope,'' enacting and bottling aspects of them, but to no avail.
He's building a dialectic between two worlds in which synthesis is
the result of access, not the exchange of actual feeling or ideas.
But the director seems more interested in ironic juxtapositions:
Maples in a hip-hop club, Schiffer making out with a founding
father of the Wu-Tang Clan, inter alia.
</P>
<P>
   The film's exclusive focus on white kids imbued with the souls
of black folk leaves you wondering about the more intriguing
preponderance of Asian and Hispanic kids under the same influence.
(FYI: Black women, here, are relegated to being naked bodies in a
player scenario.)
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the best caricature is Mike Tyson. The boxer plays
himself and is written and performed as some sort of Shakespearean
survivor. He gives sage, if lilting, advice. He seems deep,
complicated, preoccupied, but with what? His own loneliness? The
Shakespearean dimensions of his own life?
</P>
<P>
   There's not a single thing about this movie as hypnotic or
profound as he. And in his willed solitude he's independent and
questioning in a movie that moans like a trust-fund baby.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
