<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYT-WORLD-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
(js) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors for publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service for
 &UR; THURSDAY, April 6  &LR; of particular interest:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' news category)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-POLITICS (Tokyo) _ Closing out a period of unusually
intense, if scrupulously shrouded political jockeying, Japan's
parliament Tuesday elected a new prime minister to replace Keizo
Obuchi, who was left in a coma by a stroke over the weekend. Mori
said he will continue Obuchi's policies to try to revive the
economy. An election is expected in early June.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   (This story will move by 1 p.m. EST)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-MORI-PROFILE (Tokyo) _ A profile of the new prime minister
of Japan, Yoshiro Mori. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S.-SPY (Moscow) _ Russia's security services detained a
U.S. citizen in Moscow Wednesday on spying charges, officials said.
The American is the director of a private firm but was earlier
employed by a U.S. intelligence agency, said a spokesman with the
Federal Security Service.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Jerusalem) _ Israel released on Wednesday a
Lebanese who was kidnapped more than a decade ago and held without
charges ever since. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-DRUG (Paris) _ The World Health Organization and UNAids
have recommended the use of a common and affordable antibiotic for
the 23 million people infected with the AIDS virus in Africa. If
preliminary tests are borne out and the drug _ which can cost as
little as $8 a year _ can be distributed widely, many of the
Africans infected with HIV may have years added to their lives and
longer gaps between debilitating secondary infections. By Donald G.
McNeil Jr. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-POLITICS (Istanbul) _ Turkey's parliament is to vote
Wednesday on whether to allow President Suleyman Demirel to seek
re-election, a political battle that is threatening to derail the
government. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-CIA-FILES (Berlin) _ The U.S. Central Intelligence
Agency has returned some of the East German secret police files
Germany has been demanding. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-DIAMONDS (Undated) _ A special report: The value of
diamonds, coupled with the anonymity and portability of the stones,
have made them one of the most potent and dangerous currencies of
modern Africa. By Blaine Harden.
