<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVESTMENT-ADVICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ADVISERS SAY TOPSY-TURVY MARKET WARRANTS LONT-TERM APPROACH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VICTORIA COLLIVER and ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The advice from financial advisers in the midst
of market volatility is like a mantra: Stick to a long-term,
diversified investment plan, and don't do anything rash.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't have all your money in dot-com, small-cap tech
stocks,'' said Scott Lummer, chief investment officer for mPower,
an on-line investment advising firm in San Francisco. ``If there a
lesson to be learned from the last three months it's
diversification.''
</P>
<P>
   While investment advisers and brokers say that topsy-turvy days
like Tuesday, when the leading indexes experienced a frenetic
trading range, few seem to be panicking.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Deely, vice president and branch manager for Fidelity
Investment's San Francisco center, said most customers who went
into the office Tuesday were making contributions to their
retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know that it's the long-term, not the short-term. The
majority were not concerned with what's happening today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lummer said that while this is not a good time to sell, it could
be a great time to get into the market. People who are feeling
nervous, he said, are likely too heavily invested in the tech
sector.
</P>
<P>
   While the Web will continue to be a big part of the economy, he
said ``old economy'' stocks that seem fuddy-duddy compared to
technology stocks remain the driving forces of the current economy
_ companies such as the automotive makers and utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Such companies don't have the same cachet as trendy Internet
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of showboat investing,'' Lummer said. ``You
don't showboat by buying Chase Manhattan Bank. That's so 20th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris Fricker, president and chief executive of Whatifi.com, a
financial investment site that will soon be launched in San
Francisco, suggests such matters be left to the professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big secret to financial investing is there is no secret,''
he said. ``The best bet is to buy the entire market, and I don't
mean just stocks. I'm talking index funds that give you broad
exposure to stocks, bonds and cash. Hold it long, don't sell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let someone else worry about the next hot stock,'' Fricker
said. ``You already have a job. You don't need another one,
worrying about your stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale W. Schultz, principal at Schultz Collins Lawson Chambers
Inc. in San Francisco, suspects the growing number of individual
traders are responsible for some of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``This market volatility begs a few questions: To what extent
are individuals responsible for the daily volatility?'' he said.
``Five years ago, the number of individuals participating directly
in the market on a daily basis was only a fraction of what it is
today.''
</P>
<P>
   He repeated the mantra: ``Stay with your long-term investment
policy. Avoid acting on short-term market exigencies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
