<HEADER>
A7765 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-POLICE-TRAINING-BOS &LR;      04-05 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-TRAINING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URGING POLICE TO REACH FOR TACTICS, NOT GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gary Moskowitz is disturbed by one thing, above all
else, in the spate of police shootings that have gripped this city.
In nearly every case, the officers have approached the victim-to-be
with their guns out of the holsters, ready to fire.
</P>
<P>
   All too often, he knows, the police rely on their guns because
they have not been trained to rely on much else.
</P>
<P>
   Moskowitz, 43, a former New York police officer, is trying to
change this situation. He runs a private company in Queens called
American Law Enforcement Restraint Tactics (ALERT), which trains
people in martial arts.
</P>
<P>
   His students have included security guards, ordinary citizens,
and about 200 members of the New York Police Deptartment, who have
come to him in their free time and paid him out of their own
pockets, to learn how to handle tense situations without drawing
their guns.
</P>
<P>
   David Goldenberg, 39, a New York police officer who patrols the
Bronx, has been taking classes with Moskowitz for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've used Gary's techniques in confronting emotionally
disturbed people, in making street arrests where there's
resistance, with violent kids,'' he said. ``It's saved my life
several times.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Police Department gives an all-day training course
in nonlethal defensive tactics for patrol officers, but it is not
mandatory and it lasts just one day. At the end, the trainer
advises officers to take a private martial arts course if they want
to learn more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should cops have to go take private lessons?'' Moskowitz
exclaimed. ``Let the NYPD pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moskowitz, who worked in the NYPD from 1982 to 1991 as an
undercover narcotics officer and a mediator for youth gangs, has a
personal stake here. He would like the NYPD to hire his company to
teach an official course. He has offered his services in the past,
but to no avail. He is lobbying state legislators to pass a law
requiring officers to be trained in these methods.
</P>
<P>
   But, he maintains, there is more than self-interest in his plea.
``Cops have to qualify with their handguns,'' he said. ``Why
shouldn't they have to qualify with their hands?''
</P>
<P>
   The danger, otherwise, is not only that officers sometimes shoot
people they don't need or mean to shoot. It's also that a lot of
officers wind up injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they have their gun out and they realize they can't use
it,'' Moskowitz said, ``it becomes like a heavy paperweight in
their hand. They can't protect themselves and their weapon at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing these techniques would also improve community
relations,'' he said. ``A lot of cops hurt people when they do use
their hands. They don't mean to. It's not their fault. They don't
have the training. If people know the cop's been through training,
that he's tried these techniques before having to beat up a bad guy
or shoot him, they might be more willing to give the police the
benefit of the doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   One night last week, Moskowitz gave a demonstration of his
techniques. He played a police officer, while Goldenberg played an
assailant.
</P>
<P>
   Goldenberg is a tall, trim man who works out with weights. He
came at his teacher with fists, chokeholds, a knife, and a (fake)
gun. But Moskowitz, though considerably shorter, subdued him easily
with each attack.
</P>
<P>
   In one exercise, Goldenberg grabbed for the teacher's gun. ``You
don't need to grapple and struggle for it, that's a lot of
nonsense,'' Moskowitz said. Then with a quick move and a twist of
the wrist _ the whole struggle lasted two seconds _ he forced the
gun out of Goldenberg's grip.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing is,'' Moskowitz said, ``you don't have to be
in great physical shape to learn these things. It's all technique.
You don't need to learn many skills, but you have to apply your
skills to many situations. You have to work it into your instincts.
That takes time and practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Moskowitz held up a long baton made of hard foam. ``Every
patrol car should have one of these,'' he said. ``You have a guy
coming at you with a knife, you can take him down, upset his
balance, no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled the incident last year when officers in Brooklyn
shot a mentally disturbed Hasidic Jew named Gideon Busch after he
came at them with a hammer. ``If they'd had this, that shooting
wouldn't have had to happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moskowitz does not argue that police should never take out their
guns. ``Cops have to take out their gun quite often,
legitimately,'' he said. ``There are times when shooting is the
only thing you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, five young men in Brooklyn held up two undercover
officers at gunpoint, not knowing they were police. The officers
took out their own guns and fired, killing two. They later
discoverd that the men were holding toy guns.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the initial reports of what happened are true,
Moskowitz defended this shooting. ``A cop has to defend himself and
there are times when there's no other way,'' he said. ``The kind of
`restraint tactics' I teach are for situations when the other guy
is unarmed.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been virtually no community outrage over Friday's
shooting. People seem to draw a distinction between this incident
and the others that have called police tactics and training into
question.
</P>
<P>
   The four undercover officers who shot Amadou Diallo last year
all had their guns drawn when they approached him on his porch in
the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, an officer shot Malcolm Ferguson, a Bronx drug
dealer, while chasing him in his stairwell. The officer had drawn
his gun as he chased him. Ferguson was shot during a struggle for
the gun.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Patrick Dorismond was killed while scuffling with
an undercover detective who had asked him for drugs, when a gun
carried by a back-up officer went off.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, an officer chased a drug dealer through a school
playground in Brooklyn _ filled with children _ with his gun drawn.
The officer was put on desk duty for inappropriate behavior.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
