u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      04-05 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REACHING $1 MILLION MEANS A BIG UPTICK IN SAVINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. My husband contributes 7 percent of his salary to his
401(k), which comes to $485 a month with the company match. We are
very risk tolerant and would like our investments to be worth $1
million in 10 years. How should we streamline our portfolio to
maximize growth? Should I take the money out of my mother's IRA
over five years, or take it all now and accept the tax bite?
</P>
<P>
   R.W., Long Beach, Calif. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm afraid I'm going to have to be a bit of a wet blanket:
Unless you dramatically increase your savings rate, you are
unlikely to reach $1 million in this portfolio after 10 years. To
do so would require a 20.69 percent average annual return from your
investments, and recent market years notwithstanding, that seems to
me very unlikely. A more comfortable projection of market returns
over a decade is 10 percent, and that growth level would take you
to only $381,269. You would have to contribute $3,506 a month to
get to $1 million in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   I think your expectations are unrealistic. This is particularly
true given the fact that we are probably very near the end of a
bull market of unprecedented proportions, and when it comes to an
end, the market will probably require a prolonged period in the
doldrums before it moves to a new growth phase.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say I'd advise you against the market, just lower
your expectations. The first move I'd make would be to transfer the
balances in your bond, CD, and money market accounts to stocks. In
the case of the two bond holdings, I'd consolidate the IRA account
in AARP GNMA and US Treasury into Vanguard Index 500, and move the
small accumulation in Fidelity Investment Grade Bond in your
husband's 401(k) into Fidelity Spartan US Equity Index.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest you transfer both the inherited money market and CD
accounts to Vanguard Index 500 _ or to Vanguard Index Growth if you
really want to take a bullish position and believe I'm wrong about
the near-term prospects for the stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   You'll have to examine your own tax situation to determine the
best way to take your withdrawals from the IRA, but it appears most
likely you'd be best off by taking more or less equal distributions
within the five-year period that's allowed you.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on another tax matter, I would question whether you are
really getting the desired bang for the buck in the Vanguard
tax-exempt fund. Sure, you're paying no state or federal taxes, but
the returns are accordingly meager. If you really want to aim for
maximum growth, I suggest you transfer this money to USAA
Aggressive Growth and face the tax bills as they come due.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How should I best invest the money in my 401(k) account? I
will be retiring in 18 months because of heart problems. Social
Security will be my main income. I was wondering if I could take
anything out of the 401(k) without touching the principal?
</P>
<P>
   W.P., Dracut, Mass. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, neither of your two 401(k) holdings is producing much
in the way of yield. Courier Corp.'s dividends represent just 1.8
percent of its share price as this is written, and the yield on
Vanguard's Index 500 is an appalling 1.11 percent, indicating, at
least to me, how far ahead of the fundamentals the market has run.
</P>
<P>
   If you simply took the yield from these two holdings to provide
a supplemental income stream, it would bring in only $3,730 a year.
Looking at the 14 investment options available in your 401(k) plan,
it seems to me that the Strong Government Securities fund is the
best candidate for producing an income stream. The fund, which
invests in intermediate-term government-backed bonds, has a current
yield of 5.72 percent. If all of your money were in this fund, you
could expect an annual income stream of $14,682, quite a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   However, I don't suggest you move everything there. It would be
nice if you could leave some of your money in Vanguard Index 500,
which would provide the prospect for some long-term growth that
might protect you against the ravages of inflation on your income
stream later on.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion: Begin by working out a retirement budget,
carefully and realistically calculating how much you would need to
live. For example, if you decided you could get by on $24,000 a
year, that would mean a requirement of $9,600 a year to supplement
Social Security. Thus you might put $170,000 of your 401(k) savings
into the Strong fund, leaving $86,683 in Vanguard Index 500.
</P>
<P>
   Bond funds are not without risk _ note the 1.1 percent loss for
the Strong fund last year _ but over the long haul the bad seasons
for bond funds, which are caused by rising interest rates, are
offset by subsequent gains, which are the result of falling rates.
With good fixed-income funds such as this, you can expect the
principal value to change very little in the long haul, which the
income keeps rolling in. Study the fund's past performance before
you make any move.
</P>
<P>
   I would suggest you focus more on the long-term results than
recent history. For example, its 10-year total return has been 8.08
percent, which wins it a four-star, or above-average, grade from
Morningstar Mutual Funds. And despite the risk level inherent in
the bond fund, a 401(k) portfolio divided between Strong Government
Securities and Vanguard Index 500 would be considerably safer than
your current holdings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. A good possibility exists that I will be getting married
soon. A concern from my point of view is that my fiancee expects
her investments and some future inheritance to be enough for her
retirement. She has a tough time understanding that this is not
enough. I explained about inflation, but she counters that we will
be debt free and we don't want a lavish lifestyle. We fall into the
middle-income bracket, with blue-collar jobs. She is divorced with
two children. I just need to see some basic figures of where we
will be in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   K.S., Bethlehem, Pa. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Despite your fiancee's disinclination to talk about it, I
suggest you have the discussion _ or fight, if it comes to that _
now rather than later. It could be as instructive about your
character and prospects together as a long session with a lawyer
working out a prenuptial agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Since the amount of the anticipated inheritance isn't certain,
I'll just focus on that $50,000 now in retirement savings. If you
waited 20 years to retire, and if her nest egg grew by an average
10 percent annually, she would have $366,410 in the account. But if
inflation averaged 3.5 percent during the same period, it would
have the buying power of about $184,000 in today's money.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, you might expect that savings pool to produce
an annual income stream that is the equivalent of $5,460 in today's
money. Worse, since she would _ or should _ want to keep part of
her retirement funds invested for growth so as to protect her
against the likely effects of inflation later in her retirement
years, she probably shouldn't count on an income stream equivalent
to about $4,000 in today's money.
</P>
<P>
   I hope figures such as those will get her attention. If not, you
might put it to her another way. Every $1 saved today would have a
dollar value of $7.33 if it is invested for 20 years and returns 10
percent. But if inflation runs at 3.5 percent, that dollar would
have the buying power of $3.685 in today's money. After 20 years
you could expect a dollar saved today to produce an income stream
equivalent to about 2.4 cents in today's money. So it's important
for her not only to keep saving, but also to do it sooner rather
than later.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
