<HEADER>
A7767 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     04-05 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 MARTINEZ DOES HIS USUAL JOB ON THE MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Red Sox Cy Young honorees have not always followed
their award-winning seasons with fast starts. Jim Lonborg, who won
the award in 1967, hurt himself skiing and limped into the 1968
season. After winning the trophy in 1986, Roger Clemens walked out
of 1987 spring training over a contract dispute and endured a
sluggish April.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez, on the other hand, has picked up where he left
off in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching the first game of the second century of Red Sox
baseball Tuesday night, Pedro struck out 11 Seattle Mariners and
gave up only two hits in seven innings of a 2-0 victory. This comes
on the heels of his 23-4, 2.07, 313-strikeout season.
</P>
<P>
   Where does it end? Pedro is only 28 years old. Does he just keep
throwing zeroes throughout the month, season, decade? Are hitters
ever going to catch up to the Dominican righty who is no bigger
than your typical high school junior?
</P>
<P>
   Asked to assess the efforts of the Mariners, Pedro stated,
``They swung. Did they find the ball? No. But they tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they tried. Two of them struck out in the first. Two more
in the second. Two in the third. Three in the fourth. Two in the
fifth. Pedro settled down after that. He let the Mariners get
themselves out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were starting to swing more, getting desperate, getting
easier outs,'' he said of his last two innings.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that worked perfectly, according to the February
blueprint, Pedro handed the ball to Derek Lowe in the eighth and
the goofy righty retired all six batters he faced for the save.
</P>
<P>
   The pregame festivities were somewhat hideous. Fans applauded
when the retractable roof was rolled back, and none of the Pacific
Northwesterners seemed to mind the chilly conditions (50 degrees).
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to Boston during the playoffs, this was Dominican
weather,'' said Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   After the Sox were introduced, the public address system played
the ``Mr. Mojo Risin' '' part from the Doors' ``LA Woman,'' then
the Mariners appeared, one by one, through a smoke-filled gate in
the right-field fence. The players ran down a red carpet to the
first base line. No Junior Griffey. The biggest hand went to Alex
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   The roof was put back in place for the start of the game, but
the chill remained. Safeco Field is an open-air stadium. When the
roof covers the field, it's like being in a convertible with the
top on and the windows open. The ball doesn't carry. Small wonder
Griff left. No one's going to hit 756 homers playing here.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig threw out the first ball and was soundly
booed. In Seattle, Selig is best-known as the man who stole the
Pilots and made them the Milwaukee Brewers after the 1969 season.
None too affected, the commissioner wore a Safeco Field name tag
that read, ``Bud Selig.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro Martinez is a great pitcher and great for baseball,''
said the commissioner as he watched Martinez shred the Seattle
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro took the mound at 5:20. He blew hot air on his hand during
warmups. On this night he did not have the luxury of pitching to
Seattle right fielder Jay Buhner, who is 0 for 8 lifetime against
Pedro, all strikeouts. Manager Lou Piniella decided it was best to
give the slugger a night off even if it was the opener on national
television. Such is the impact of Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   His first pitch of 2000 was a called strike to center fielder
Mike Cameron. Cameron struck out, swinging, on five pitches.
Welcome to the new millennium. Mark McLemore was next and he fanned
on a 3-and-2 pitch. Alex Rodriguez walked on four pitches. So much
for the perfect game. Pedro went to 2-and-0 on John Olerud (six
balls in a row), before getting the new Mariner cleanup man on a
hard fly to left.
</P>
<P>
   He got the side in order in the second, then fanned Dan Wilson
to open the third. But No. 9 batter Carlos Guillen fought off a
2-and-2 pitch and dumped a single to center. So much for the
no-hitter. But the shutout would be preserved.
</P>
<P>
   In a battle of Dominican-born All-Stars, Pedro fanned Rodriguez
on a 96-mile-per-hour fastball to start the fourth. After Olerud
scorched a single past Nomar Garciaparra (and took second on a
passed ball), Pedro caught Edgar Martinez looking at a 3-and-2
strike, then blazed a 93-m.p.h. heater past John Mabry to end the
inning. On the upper-deck facade in left center, A group of Boston
fans showed nine K-Cards after four.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does his most serious work when there's men in scoring
position,'' said Sox general manager Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   The Ace of Diamonds struck out two more Mariners in the fifth,
then got the rest of his outs on harmless grounders and fly balls.
He threw 108 pitches, 60 for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had better command after the fifth,'' he said. ``I felt
pretty confident, but I wouldn't say I knew I was gonna have a good
game. I just had a good day. I was throwing the ball well.''
</P>
<P>
   As he has all spring, he rejected the notion that fans should
expect a repeat of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't look for it,'' said Pedro. ``A year like that
happens. Gibson. Koufax. You can put that season right in there.
Those are special seasons and they don't come every day. You can't
think about it. You'd go crazy. I'm not gonna stop and think about
it. That's behind. That's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro improved to 3-0 with 31 strikeouts in three Sox openers.
Wednesday night, the cowhide torch is passed to brother Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
