<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANY FRIEND OF MR. FUSSY'S IS PROBABLY . . . LONELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mr. Fussy is very, very fussy about people.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of people does Mr. Fussy like? To start with, he likes
people who like him, because they show good taste. Here is a
passage from Fay Weldon's novel, ``Big Girls Don't Cry,'' that
summarizes Mr. F's position nicely. The well-heeled Layla is
explaining to her less fortunate boarder, Stephanie, why she is
being evicted:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to share my home with someone who keeps telling
me the truth,'' said Layla. ``I want to fill it with people who
admire me and worship me, and that's not you.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be an exaggeration to say that Mr. Fussy's house is
filled with admirers and worshippers. Familiarity breeds grudging
acknowledgement is the watchword there. The people Mr. Fussy likes
best are the people he doesn't know. There's still hope for them.
In theory, at least.
</P>
<P>
   Certain kinds of people are annoying: overachievers, for
instance. She's a world-renowned oncologist; he invented a Web site
that sells gasoline over the Internet; their children attend the
private school of the moment, and are beta testers for Microsoft _
how can you not feel small? You exchange a few words on the
sidewalk and, inevitably, her cell phone chirrups forth. Her
presence is required at a World Health Organization conference in
Geneva. What can you possibly say, other than: Can I drive you to
the airport?
</P>
<P>
   Appearances can be very helpful in sorting out people. ``Teeth
are important,'' observed Burt Bacharach, one of People magazine's
``50 Most Beautiful People Ever,'' and he was right. Teeth are
important. But skin is very important, too. Mr. Fussy only wishes
that fathers taught their young sons more about moisturizers and
less about hitting a curve ball (impossible, anyway). Look at
Robert Redford _ a lifetime wasted in the sun! But Mr. F digresses.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know how ``socially responsible'' investors pick stocks?
They set up ``screens'' to weed out evil corporations, the ones
that sell tobacco, exploit Third World labor, or print unposed
celebrity photos. So Mr. Fussy has devised his own screens through
which strangers must pass in order to enter his peculiar orbit.
</P>
<P>
   1) They must live either very nearby, or very far away,
preferably, in a castle in Ireland. With halfway people one can
never make up one's mind. Mr. Fussy sees his friends in Seattle
much more often than he sees his friends in Stockbridge, for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   2) Not too tall. Tall people are too imposing, too superior. But
not too short, either. Too many hang-ups.
</P>
<P>
   3) Too rich is OK.
</P>
<P>
   4) NNPNA: No Night People Need Apply. Mr. Fussy is a Day Person.
He works very hard from early morning until about lunch time, then
he just throws in the towel. At the newspaper where Mr. Fussy
works, he occasionally meets the movie reviewers or the rock music
critics, stumbling into work just as Mr. F. is leaving. As far as
he is concerned, they are nice people who may as well be working in
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   5)Movies can be useful screening tools. Did you like ``Pulp
Fiction?'' Mr. and Mrs. Fussy walked out. Anything by Robert Altman
is acceptable, even the critically savaged ``Gingerbread Man.'' And
if you enjoyed the Brazilian cannibal classic ``Macunaima,'' well,
soup's on! You're a candidate for friend for life.
</P>
<P>
   6) Phone etiquette is very important to Mr. Fussy. Rule No. 1:
Don't Call. Rule No. 2: If you must call, don't call at night. Rule
No. 3: If you must leave a message, make it very brief, e.g.
``Hello, Mr. Fussy. It's me. Goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is the typical, unacceptably long phone message: ``Hi, Mr.
Fussy, it's _ Oh, this cord is getting all tangled _ hi, it's Mary,
remember, I said I would call you today, Thursday, because you
probably remember that we had discussed doing that thing with
Robert, and I'm really not sure. . .'' Mary is a leading candidate
for Call Blocking, the handy new sociopathic feature available on
many telephones.
</P>
<P>
   7) No golf, no golf, no golf. If Mr. Fussy never hears the
g-word again in this lifetime, it will be too soon.
</P>
<P>
   So _ can we be friends?
</P>
<P>
   (With gratitude and apologies to the late Roger Hargreaves,
creator of the wonderful children's book character Mr. Fussy.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
