<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7771 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-NASDAQ-MANIA-ART-BOS &LR;      04-05 1430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-MANIA-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 HIGH-FLYING NASDAQ IS VERY MUCH IN STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Morning, noon, and night, their hopes soar or plunge with the
gyrations of the Nasdaq exchange, which advertises itself as the
``stock market for the digital world.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq maniacs withstand the precipitous declines in their stock
index, such as the one last week, with the devotion of sports fans.
If the index continues its Friday rebound this week, they know the
feeling will be sublime.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq watchers are everywhere today _ lurking in suburban
homes, office cubicles, RVs, airports.
</P>
<P>
   William Sheskey ambles down to the sunny kitchen in his Hingham
home each morning, and, in a ritual of retirement, eats a breakfast
prepared by his wife while tuning in to CNBC Network to see how the
Nasdaq is doing.
</P>
<P>
   What he sees all day long is Tom Costello, the Nasdaq
correspondent for CNBC, broadcasting market updates from Nasdaq's
new storefront in Times Square. Tourists peer into the picture
window for a glimpse of Costello, a glance at the index. Is it up
or down? Did MicroStrategy's stock price explode or fizzle?
</P>
<P>
   When James Paragamian returns home from his job as a stock
broker in downtown Washington, D.C., each evening, 9-year-old Matt
asks, ``How'd the Nasdaq do today, dad?'' Paragamian says. ``He
doesn't ask how the Dow did. He asks how the Nasdaq did.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq, home to the four horsemen of high-tech _ Cisco Systems,
Microsoft, Intel, and Oracle _ has eclipsed the Dow Jones
industrial average as the index to watch for this nation of
investors, online traders, and tech junkies.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq ``has come as close to the new national obsession as
anything we have,'' said Antonio Cecin, director of stock trading
for US Bancorp Piper Jaffray, a Minneapolis investment firm that
creates markets in Nasdaq-listed stocks.
</P>
<P>
   As the public and corporate America stampede into tech stocks,
Nasdaq _ which, like the Internet itself, is no more than a vast
network of interlinked computers, a virtual place _ has become the
world's biggest stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq, established in 1971 and once home to dubious,
small-company stocks, has a new reputation as the place to be for a
long line of young companies. Its trading volume now far
outdistances the quintessential establishment trading floor, the
New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The storefront in Times Square is, in fact, sheer advertising.
No trading, and little exchange business, goes on there. Its
purpose is a garish display, adding to the bright lights and
scrolling news zippers blanketing Broadway and grabbing the
attention of tourists likely to walk away with a Nasdaq key chain
or coffee mug.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely entertainment,'' says Robert Shiller, a Yale
University economics professor, repeating a theme from his book,
``Irrational Exuberance.'' ``That is one thing that drives this
boom _ people have found a new diversion.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, people aren't just watching. They are investing. Like
never before, the public _ housewives, police officers, waiters,
retirees _ is putting an enormous amount of money into
Nasdaq-listed technology stocks, placing high-risk bets on the new
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Investors pushed the Nasdaq index through the 5,000 barrier
briefly, on March 9. Share volume on the exchange smashes record
after record: Eight of the 10 largest-volume days all occurred in
March _ the other two were in February. That's due to a torrent of
orders from discount brokers, and from mutual fund giants such as
Fidelity Investments, whose specialty technology fund quadrupled in
size, to $80 billion, in five years.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? Those who went with Nasdaq, shunning the dowdy Dow,
have made boatloads of money. What could be more fun? Neither a
correction in the index last week, nor warnings by investment
professionals, have deterred nascent speculators. ``The new
economy,'' said Kenneth Heebner, a veteran Boston money manager,
``is an illusion. It's a word that allows people to feel
comfortable with paying ridiculous prices for stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If stocks start going down, the obsession (with
Nasdaq) would disappear real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Nasdaq's relentless rise only lures more people into
its sticky web; wild price swings are rationalized as a bump on the
road to more winnings for an index that gained an extraordinary 86
percent last year and is now at five times its 1995 level. Despite
last week's plunge, the index is up 12 percent so far this year _
more than most stocks, and stock market indexes, gain in an entire
year.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Mattox has an acute case of Nasdaq obsession.
</P>
<P>
   Up at dawn, he logs on to the laptop in his Mt. Vernon, Va.,
home to see how Nasdaq futures contracts are faring before US stock
markets open. In his photography studio, where portraits of
presidents Johnson through Clinton and comedian Lucille Ball hang,
Mattox monitors six computer screens. He's tracking the Nasdaq's
swings. He's watching his Nasdaq-listed stocks. He's checking for
stock tips on stockwinners.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather watch my Bloomberg (terminal) than go to the
movies,'' said Mattox, a 30-year investor.
</P>
<P>
   He said he made so much money last year _ ``six figures'' _ he
was able to buy his wife a topaz-colored Jaguar XK8 convertible
2000 with a navigation system. ``You have to be disciplined and
focused,'' he said. ``It's like driving a race car. You take your
eye off of it, and you crash.''
</P>
<P>
   You have to be obsessed.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals swept up in Nasdaq stocks ``see all these people
around who don't have any special insight or talent,'' said Cornell
University economist Richard Frank, ``and they're getting rich _
just by letting their investments sit in the Nasdaq. I think that
drives ordinary people nuts.'' But Frank admitted, ``I get a kick
out of my numbers every day because they're going up every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies are equally smitten. Aeroflex Inc., an electronics
company based in Plainview, N.Y., last month abandoned the Big
Board to list its shares on the Nasdaq _ and be associated with its
chic. ``There's the old economy and the new economy _ we're new
economy,'' said Aeroflex's president, Michael Gorin. ``It's just
that we wanted to align ourselves with our peer group.''
</P>
<P>
   As Nasdaq's popularity grows, it has established an identity
even among casual investors, such as retiree Sheskey. Investment
professionals, reviewing the day's events on Wall Street, no long
confine analysis to the Dow. Increasingly, they talk of the money
sloshing from Nasdaq to the Dow and back _ causing one market to
fall and the other to fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't pay nearly as much attention to the Dow as I do the
Nasdaq, because I'm in the new-economy stocks,'' explained Sheskey,
a former shoe industry executive.
</P>
<P>
   Such an attitude, shared by a growing public, is welcomed by
Nasdaq officials who, only a decade ago, succeeded in a
public-relations campaign to persuade nightly news programs to
broadcast Nasdaq's daily moves _ right after the Dow's.
</P>
<P>
   Today, an entire network devotes much of its broadcast time to
Nasdaq: CNBC. True, CNBC deploys Maria Bartiromo on the floor of
the New York Stock Exchange for the popular morning stock show. But
the star is Nasdaq. Host Joe Kernan trots out screen after screen
of stock charts resembling the Alps before investors' eyes.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC, which had only 19,000 households tuning in daily in 1996,
claims 375,000 households do so now. CNBC's investment daily
business programming is so popular, the television show is a new
kind of wallpaper for retail establishments, from a barber shop
near the Astor Place subway stop in Manhattan that airs the
program, to a Waltham health club where cyclists gaze at a TV set
during lunch-hour workouts.
</P>
<P>
   As with any fad, Nasdaq's rise occurred with lightning speed.
Alternative computerized trading forums are in ascendance and may
just as quickly usurp it.
</P>
<P>
   Already, trading by investment professionals and casual
investors has begun a shift: Day-traders at home buy and sell
stocks with market makers on Wall Street. Retirees buy stocks via
online trading firms, never lifting a telephone to call a broker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really at the dawn of a new marketplace,'' said Antonio
Cecin, the Minneapolis market maker. Things are happening so fast,
he added, ``none of us knows what it all means.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
