<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Neither would look very good in a push-up bra. And
they would never, ever be caught in spike heels at the office.
</P>
<P>
   But like Erin Brockovich, who in the person of Julia Roberts
looked darn good in both, Brian J.X. Murphy and Edward Notargiacomo
spent endless hours at their law firm helping win a giant
class-action suit against Big Business. When the jihad ended the
real-life, Brockovich walked away with real money, $2 million in
cash. Murphy and Notargiacomo got a few weeks' severance pay and
were shown the door.
</P>
<P>
   Brown Rudnick Freed &AMP; Gesmer just can't understand how it has
come to be typecast as a firm of greedy lawyers after winning the
biggest settlement in the history of the Commonwealth _ $8.3
billion _ against Big Tobacco. Hint: Greed, exploitation and
arrogance are no more attractive in a law firm than a tobacco
company.
</P>
<P>
   In February, I told you about the donnybrook that had erupted
inside Brown Rudnick over the $178 million the firm had been
awarded over the next 25 years for its role in the litigation.
Thomas Sobol, the firm's lead attorney on the case, announced he
was leaving. Brown Rudnick said OK, but you're not getting your
share of the settlement, by far the largest in the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the case of Brian Murphy and Ed Notargiacomo.
</P>
<P>
   The two were part of a team of young attorneys Brown Rudnick
used to reduce the costs of the high-risk litigation. Of roughly 11
attorneys who worked primarily on the tobacco litigation team, half
were so-called contract lawyers who, like Murphy and Notargiacomo,
were paid as little as $18 an hour and got no benefits. They worked
up to 80 hours a week, shared offices, computers and telephones and
had no secretarial help.
</P>
<P>
   But by Brown Rudnick's own telling this pool of cut-rate talent
played an important role in the litigation. Several, including
Murphy and Notargiacomo, were sworn in as special assistant
attorneys general. ``No attorney in the case defended more public
health-related depositions,'' George K. Weber, the head of the
attorney general's tobacco team, said of Murphy in a letter of
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Reiner, who was Sobol's chief deputy at Brown Rudnick,
said Murphy was ``quickly singled out'' for his ability to think
``big picture'' and look ``outside the box.'' Wrote Reiner: ``Brian
was able to predict issues no one else had thought of.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Brown Rudnick attorney, James McGuire, praised
Notargiacomo's ``extraordinary contributions'' to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Both worked about 20 months on the case. When it was settled,
Murphy, 29, was dumped with six weeks of severance pay;
Notargiacomo, 32, with four weeks. The other contract attorneys
were also let go.
</P>
<P>
   The two say ``promises were made,'' and asked Brown Rudnick to
make good. Although the four other law firms in the Massachusetts
case awarded Brown Rudnick $23 million for the extra work the firm
put in, the requests of Murphy and Notargiacomo amount to peanuts:
$120,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Brown Rudnick to the two lawyers: drop dead. ``When your
services were no longer necessary, the Firm made a gift to you of
six weeks weeks additional compensation, a gift the Firm was under
no obligation to make,'' Brown Rudnick wrote to Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Jasse, Brown Rudnick's chairman, said all regular
employees got a one-time bonus earlier this year from the tobacco
money that totalled $1.5 million. ``I believe we have treated all
our staff, including contract lawyers, fairly,'' he said in a
statement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Not long from now, Brown Rudnick will sue the state for the
balance of the fee it says it is owed under the original agreement.
That money, which could top $300 million, would come out of the
state's part of the settlement, not from the tobacco firms.
</P>
<P>
   And then Jasse and the other senior partners at One Financial
Center can adjourn to the club, and whine about how unfair it is to
be called a bunch of greedy lawyers. ``Waiter, another martini,
please. . .''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can reach me at bailey(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
