<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7774 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     04-05 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO BURST BUBBLE FOR TECH MARKET, BUT A DEFINITE HISS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Feeling irrationally exuberant now?
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who sweated Tuesday's technology stock market through
each wrenching turn to its eventual, ho-hum close is more likely to
feel like a wet dish towel.
</P>
<P>
   By lunch time we would have sworn the bubble of wild expectation
and crazy valuation had finally burst, as many predicted. Later, it
felt more like a balloon hissing lost confidence from a bad leak.
</P>
<P>
   Stock bubbles are burst or deflated by unpredictable things,
often coming out of left field. For all of his jawboning about tech
stocks and the wealth effect, Federal Reserve chairman Alan
Greenspan would only have to look across Washington to a federal
judge for the spark to this week's activity.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft Corp. antitrust case and Monday's decision by US
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson had little to do with the
direct fortunes of most technology companies. But that was enough
to trigger selling that began to feed on itself in a Nasdaq market
that had lost nearly 9 percent
</P>
<P>
   the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   To Barry Evans, Tuesday felt a lot like Oct. 15, 1989, when the
Dow Jones industrial average plunged by 6.9 percent (a mere 190.58
points at that time). The catalyst then: the closely watched
leveraged buyout planned for United Airlines parent UAL Corp. was
collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually there's some sort of tag-along news like that,'' said
Evans, a senior vice president at John Hancock Funds. ``That one
told you the LBO game was over. What the Microsoft news might be
suggesting is a lot of the tech momentum is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you call Tuesday, it was immensely volatile and moved
at warp speed, with a record 2.7 billion Nasdaq shares changing
hands. Don't be surprised by more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to see a lot more volatility and high
volume,'' said Edward G. Riley, chief investment strategist at
State Street Global Advisors in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   As the day wore on, much of the afternoon recovery was pinned on
a flight to quality, or at least size. Money seemed to gravitate to
larger companies and a few, like Applied Materials Inc., a
semiconductor company, actually posted strong gains.
</P>
<P>
   This may be the way of the immediate future. Some mutual fund
managers and market analysts suggest technology stocks may fall
into one of several clusters in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   By their thinking, the giants with established business and
earnings will decline but suffer through the least volatility by
attracting and holding on to institutional investors. Another group
of companies, with solid futures but wildly inflated stock, will
keep a market following despite big price drops.
</P>
<P>
   But a category of smaller technology stocks that have counted on
Wall Street to keep funding their growing businesses will face
serious problems. Many of those stocks have been knocked down and
are least likely to get back up. Their challenge: find a way to
make money or start thinking about mergers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be the first iteration of that process,'' said
Bernice Behar, portfolio manager of the John Hancock Small Cap
Growth fund. ``I think this gets played out in a fairly complicated
fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   That would only be a bit of history repeating itself. Most
recently, the same pattern was on display when technology stocks
got clobbered in the summer of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a flight to safety and size, then a tier of
highfliers that were struggling to regain their impressive
valuation, and then an entire group of smaller caps which were
forgotten as more illiquid than the other two categories,''
recalled Michael Halloran, the Boston-based global head of the
technology group at Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for many tech stocks may pose a problem in the weeks
ahead. And then there's the supply question.
</P>
<P>
   Investment bankers limit or virtually shut down the fat pipeline
of initial public offerings in times like these. But they can't do
anything about existing stock that will soon become available for
sale in public markets for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai Technologies Inc. of Cambridge, Mass. went public with a
bang in October, hitting the market at $26 per share and reaching a
peak of $345.50 in January. It has since retreated to $115.46875.
</P>
<P>
   But only a small portion of Akamai's shares outstanding were
actually sold to the public. The IPO of 9 million shares accounted
for less than 10 percent of its 93 million shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   The balance is owned by insiders, venture capitalists, and
others prohibited from selling any of their stock or exercising
options for six months. For Akamai, that's the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   The booming IPO market of 1999 is creating the same type of
phenomena on a massive scale across the market. Soon, more than 2
billion shares will be unlocked and may be sold, by some counts.
</P>
<P>
   Just because insiders can sell doesn't mean they will. But their
expired lockups are a weight that may hang over the tech stock
market any time it tries to rally. How can prices move higher when
there are so many potential sellers waiting in the wings?
</P>
<P>
   Halloran thinks expiring stock lockups are a minor issue. But
several money managers said they believed the issue could hold back
many stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it goes straight to the heart of supply and demand,''
said Behar. ``No matter what the level of the market, the very
nature of those lockups very definitely are an issue we need to get
past.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
