<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7775 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HIGHTECH-MINORITIES-A     04-05 1827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHTECH-MINORITIES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 HIGH TECH FIRMS STEP UP EFFORTS TO RECRUIT MINORITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was almost dusk when 75 African-American, Asian, and
Latino seniors from colleges around the country filed into a
banquet room at the Boston Seaport Hotel last month for dinner and
a chance to meet Al Zollar, president and chief executive of
Cambridge-based Lotus Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   At 45, Zollar is among a small but growing number of
African-Americans nationwide who hold influential positions in
technology. ``I really want young people to understand that there
are opportunities in technology right now,'' he said. ``But they
must be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, opportunities abound. Faced with a shortfall of more
than 100,000 information technology professionals in the industry
each year and a dearth of engineering graduates, both companies and
colleges are vying for talented students.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Lord, a 17-year-old honors student at Phillips Exeter
Academy, was able to pick and choose: She was accepted to both
Stanford University and Washington University at St. Louis, and was
guaranteed admission and a $40,000 scholarship to Florida
Agricultural &AMP; Mechanical University, even though she hadn't
applied there. She ultimately chose Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   This shortage of high-tech professionals is necessitating the
diversification of a traditionally white-male industry. Women have
fought hard to break into the field and have made progress toward
the executive ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet at a time when there is so much to gain, few
African-Americans fill professional jobs in the exploding high-tech
market. In the Boston area, black professionals hold only 3.4
percent of the high-tech jobs. One reason, say experts: lower
college enrollments.
</P>
<P>
   Though they represent 12 percent of the overall US population,
African-Americans were awarded just 8.3 percent of the 1.2 million
bachelor's degrees conferred in 1997 _ a 66 percent increase since
1987 but still not big enough to close the technology gap, reports
the American Council on Education.
</P>
<P>
   In both Silicon Valley and Massachusetts, critics say companies
would rather hire from abroad than nurture US talent. Many
high-tech start-ups are not recruiting from the US colleges that
have higher black and Latino enrollments.
</P>
<P>
   As competition for technical professionals and savvy consumers
intensifies, however, some noteworthy alliances are being forged
among companies, minority institutions, community groups, and
public schools in a push to recruit minorities and tap what many
see as a potentially lucrative consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprising, most of these new coalitions involve the
country's more established firms. Absent from the table: Many of
the dot-coms and Internet firms credited with fueling the surging
economy.
</P>
<P>
   In Cambridge, for example, Lotus Development Corp. has matched
students from a local public school and their families with free
computers, assigning digital buddies, or mentors, who will serve as
the families' personal Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   Zollar, who heads Lotus, an IBM software subsidiary that will
likely gross well over $1 billion this year, credits his public
school teachers with sparking his interest in math.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not come from a privileged background,'' he said. ``I
was good at math, but I also had a couple of teachers who inspired
me. I really had no idea what I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Zollar, who holds a bachelor's of arts degree from the
University of California at San Diego and a master's degree in
applied mathematics, credits a strong diversity program at IBM with
helping him advance.
</P>
<P>
   In all, about 600 minority college seniors, the majority of them
participants in the company's nationwide Project View recruiting
program, are hired yearly by IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Other alliances involving minority advancement in technology
include:
</P>
<P>
   --A $130 million partnership of the United Negro College Fund,
Microsoft Corp., IBM Corp., and AT&AMP;T Corp. to improve computer
access to students and faculty at black colleges.
</P>
<P>
   --The Bill Gates Millennium Scholars Program, which will award
full scholarships to 20,000 economically disadvantaged minority
students under a multimillion dollar program of the Gates
Foundation, the United Negro College Fund, the Hispanic College
Fund, the American Indian College Fund, Microsoft, and IBM.
</P>
<P>
   --America Online and Darien Dash, the 28-year-old founder and
chief executive of DME Interactive Holdings Inc., a New York
multimedia firm, are expected this month to announce details of a
multifirm partnership that will bring discounted computers,
Internet access, and low-cost urban programming to millions of
newly wired minority households.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal,'' said Dash, ``is to develop an urban branded
Internet service provider and offer access to people who have just
recently begun to take advantage of the technology.'' Programming
is expected to include distance learning, job placement, technical
certification, music, and multimedia.
</P>
<P>
   Altruism is not the sole motivation. As AOL's new urban brand,
DME's Places of Color is expected to reach millions of minority
households when it is launched this spring, a potential goldmine
for the company and its mega partner, AOL.
</P>
<P>
   --Bell Atlantic's community technology centers at local Urban
Leagues, where students can study and learn to use computers; and
Cisco Systems' alliance with the Villa Victoria housing development
in Boston's South End and a nonprofit that serves the Latino
community.
</P>
<P>
   --A coalition of business groups that is donating thousands of
dollars to fund scholarships and internships for talented youths
enrolled at historically black colleges.
</P>
<P>
   One example: Florida Agricultural &AMP; Mechanical University,
widely known as FAMU. Fifteen years after Frederick S. Humphries
became president, the college is competing with Harvard University
for top minority high school seniors. Backed by 135 major
companies, FAMU created the $40,000 four-year award, the Life Gets
Better Thurgood Marshall Scholarship, as a lure.
</P>
<P>
   These alliances offer one solution, but they're hardly enough.
``Right now, the biggest predictor of whether someone goes on to
college is the academic preparation they receive in their
elemenatary and seconday school years,'' said Jacqueline King, a
spokeswoman for the American Council on Education in Washington,
D.C. ``Marked variations in the quality of elementary and secondary
education students receive as well as social class, institutional
racism, and the notion among many American youth that it is uncool
to be a `nerd' or computer `geek,' have all played a role in
impeding advancement.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those African-Americans who, like Zollar, have climbed the
upper rungs of executive management in technology, many first
entered the industry through the doors of big technical firms such
as IBM, Digital Equipment Corp., or the nation's reigning
telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   The companies, many of them federal contractors, are required by
law to diversity their ranks. But some value the synergy created
when different perspectives are shared.
</P>
<P>
   Robert E. Dowling Jr., chairman, president, and chief executive
of California-based COVAD Communications, which offers broadband
access services to the Internet, was an executive vice president at
U.S. West before assuming the top post at COVAD.
</P>
<P>
   Wharton B. (Zie) Rivers, the newly appointed president of Cable
&AMP; Wireless North America, had served as president of Ameritech's $4
billion network services division before he was named to his new
post last October.
</P>
<P>
   A bachelor's or master's degree in mathematics or computer
science is not a necessary prerequisite to advancement. Kingsley
Idehincq, president of OpenLink Software in Burlington, which sells
e-business infrastructure technology to brick-and-mortars seeking
an Internet presence, was an accountant before becoming an
entrepreneur in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Idehin, like many minority entrepreneurs, received no outside
support from local bankers or venture capitalists and relied,
instead, on $50,000 in savings to launch his company. This year, he
expects to gross $5 million in sales. These days, he counts such
firms as Lucent Technologies, the Federal Energy Reserve
Commission, AT&AMP;T, and the US Army among his 5,000 clients.
</P>
<P>
   DME Interactive's Dash, who grew up in the Bronx, graduated from
the University of Southern California in 1983 with a bachelor's in
political science. The same year he started working for Digital
Music Express, which distributed music through a cable company.
``In 1994, I saw there was a great opportunity in technology and,
especially, in the urban market,'' recalled Dash.
</P>
<P>
   He started the firm with a computer and $500, and then financed
it himself for four years before attracting financial support. Last
year, DME went public. The company reported more than $1 million in
sales in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   For African-American students who do pursue bachelor's or
advanced degrees in computer science, engineering, or mathematics,
the future seems particularly bright.
</P>
<P>
   Take Peter Onyisi, a 17-year-old physics major at the University
of Chicago. Last year while still in high school, he was ranked
among the top 100 math students in the country. After scoring 800
on the quantitative portion of the Scholastic Aptitude Test and 780
on the verbal portion, Onyisi was accepted to Harvard, Princeton
University, MIT, and the California Institute of Technology. He
settled on the University of Chicago, which awarded him a full
four-year scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   IBM IT specialist and developer Diana Meadows of Allentown, Pa.,
who is finishing a doctorate in computer science, was inundated
with job offers while studying at Indiana University last year.
</P>
<P>
   A former high school dropout and hair dresser who had grown
bored with her job, Meadows returned to earn a high school
equivalency diploma, intending to pursue a career in the US Air
Force. When the Air Force rejected her because she did not have
enough course credits, Meadows enrolled at Brooklyn College.
``Essentially, I went to college for 15 credits and never left,''
she said. ``I loved it. I took Algebra, Calculus I, II, and III.,
and wound up minoring in math.''
</P>
<P>
   Meadows graduated Phi Beta Kappa and Sigma Psi, and then entered
graduate school at Indiana University. Now in her 30s, she says she
was working on her doctorate last year when a bunch of companies
came knocking. She received several offers, settling on IBM, she
said, because it sent a representative to the university to meet
her. Today, Meadows makes almost twice the amount she would have
earned if she had stuck to her plan of becoming a college
professor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
