</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEIR SPARTAN EXISTENCE YIELDS A JUST REWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a very good thing for Michigan State that the young Mateen
Cleaves was not your basic front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   He came of athletic age at a time when Wolverine Chic was taking
over the state of Michigan, not to mention countless other urban
areas. Anywhere you looked in the early and mid '90s, kids were
wearing snappy Michigan garb. The colors, after all, are classic:
blue and gold, or, as they quaintly insist in Ann Arnor, maize and
blue. And the Fab Five defined the sport for the hip-hop set. So
Michigan was very much the school of choice.
</P>
<P>
   But up there in Flint, little Mateen was thinking along
different lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came up,'' he says, ``my father was always a Michigan
State guy. You know, I always went for the underdog, so I really
fell in love with Michigan State. I've always been a guy that roots
for the underdog. And the guards they had coming through _ Magic
Johnson, Scott Skiles, Steve Smith, Eric Snow _ I can go on and on
about the guards that played there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in Flint, Michigan was the big thing. Michigan State was
always second to Michigan. But if there was a question of Michigan
vs. Michigan State in my house, my father wouldn't allow you to
watch Michigan. You had to watch Michigan State.''
</P>
<P>
   That pretty much sums up the state of affairs in college
basketball at the conclusion of the 1999-2000 season, doesn't it?
If you want to see college basketball played at its absolute
highest, most athletic, most cohesive, and most intelligent level,
why, you simply had to watch Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing we can ask for from any athletic campaign is
justice. We don't like messy or ambiguous endings. Oh, we get them,
all right, but when we do, we simply deal with them. We don't
embrace them. But the college basketball season that concluded at
the RCA Dome Monday night supplied us with the kind of warm glow we
seek. The best team won, and they did so by bringing their Tiger
Woods ``A game'' when it was most desirable.
</P>
<P>
   That was Michigan State basketball we saw Monday night. No,
let's back it up a bit. That was Michigan State basketball we saw
both Saturday evening and Monday evening. Rarely has an aspirant to
college basketball's throne been asked to put on such radically
different faces after having arrived at the Final Four. What
Michigan State did in dispatching Wisconsin in Saturday's peach
basket 53-41 game required one sort of discipline. What Michigan
State did in slicing through the feared Florida press and then
dissecting the Gators with a well-designed half-court offense
required quite another.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can beat you, 50-45 or 90-80,'' says coach Tom Izzo.
</P>
<P>
   That's not hyperbole; that's the God's honest truth, and it's
why there shouldn't be any question as to the identity of the best
team. Sure, there are teams that could beat Michigan State in a
one-shot deal. They did lose three games even with Cleaves in the
lineup. But not even a fully healthy Cincinnati (i.e. with Kenyon
Martin) has the full range of skill Michigan State has. The
Spartans would win a seven-game series with anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there always seems to be two kinds of kids taking in
everything that's going on. The first are the impressionable ones,
who see something gaudy and want to partake. Cleaves, smooth
forward Morris Peterson and Charlie Bell, a junior who will inherit
Cleaves's playmaking spot next year, all come from Flint, a
hardscrabble town immortalized by documentary filmmaker Michael
Moore in ``Roger and Me.'' They could have plugged into the
Michigan thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michigan was always on TV,'' Cleaves says. ``They had the
All-Americans. They had the flashy players and that type of
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But they chose Michigan State. They wanted to make their own
mark. Along with senior A.J. Granger and junior Andre Hutson, they
have given Michigan State a less-heralded Fab Five of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys were incredible, the three seniors,'' says Izzo.
``I don't know how I can make everybody believe how special they
are to me. They've done an incredible job of helping build this
program, and hopefully they'll be great alums and come back and
teach the guys what they did so gallantly tonight, and that was
play with as big a heart and as good an effort as I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   A coach can only dream of his team coming up as big as Izzo's
did in a game as big as this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk before a game,'' Izzo says, ``and one of the things
we said was that everybody's got to play tonight.
(itals)Everybody.(unitals) I said, `Each of you, look at each other
and give the other 40 minutes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Against a great pressing team, Mkchigan State did not turn the
ball over _ even in the halfcourt _ during the first 11 minutes and
55 seconds. The Spartans shot 53 percent in the first half and 60
percent in the second half. They got strategic bench contributions
from freshman Jason Richardson and Duke transfer Mike Chappell, who
may have scored the game's single biggest basket when he nailed a
3-pointer coming out of a timeout emanating from Cleaves's ankle
injury. That basket made it 53-44 and demonstrated to the Gators
just how tough-minded a team this was.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State won 15 of its last 16, the only loss coming in
overtime at Indiana on a put-back of an air ball at the buzzer. The
Spartans outscored Syracuse, 17-0, to finish off one tournament
game and outscored Iowa State, 20-3, to finish off another. They
knew how to play slow against Wisconsin and how to play fast
against Florida. And they saved their best for last.
</P>
<P>
   That's called having the answer to every question. That's called
being a champion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
