<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7779 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-COL-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      04-05 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-COL-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLD-FASHIONED CHAMPION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The memories should linger for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Mateen Cleaves limping back on the court, his injured right
ankle heavily taped but his spirit so overwhelming that the entire
RCA Dome could feel it.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves and his coach, Tom Izzo, crying tears of joy as they
stood on the court and watched joyous teammates go through the
ceremonial process of cutting down the nets.
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson sitting in the stands watching something unfold
that hadn't happened in 21 years _ a national championship for
Michigan State _ and no doubt flashing back to when he was a
sophomore in college, doing much the same thing that Cleaves and
his teammates were doing.
</P>
<P>
   In the litany of NCAA championship moments, Michigan State's
89-76 win over Florida Monday night should be put near the top. Not
so much for the competitive aspect of the game, which was basically
a blowout in the final 10 minutes, but because of all the drama
surrounding Cleaves and his two senior starting brethren, A.J.
Granger and Morris Peterson, each of whom did more than their share
in securing the title.
</P>
<P>
   The moment was special just for that reason: Michigan State won
a title with three senior starters. And that is something we might
not see again soon.
</P>
<P>
   We live in an era of instant gratification. Of taking the money
and running, sooner rather than later. College basketball has been
affected deeply by that attitude, to the point where it is now an
even-money guess as to whether the best high school seniors even
make it to college.
</P>
<P>
   It is a disturbing trend. Not since 1995, when UCLA beat
Arkansas in a title game that featured three senior starters on
each team, have we seen such a collection of veterans in a title
matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the talent drain has been steady. In 1996,
Kentucky's national championship team lost underclassman Antoine
Walker; after the 1997 game, Kentucky lost Ron Mercer and Arizona
lost Mike Bibby; last year, Connecticut won the national
championship and lost forward Richard Hamilton, while runner-up
Duke lost three underclassmen: Elton Brand, William Avery, and
Corey Maggette.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, Michigan State's veteran team has become the exception
rather than the rule. You could see the progression of the Spartans
over the past four years, from an NIT team, to a Sweet 16 team, to
a Final Four team, to a national champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great for the game,'' said a bleary-eyed Izzo at
a press conference. ``I'm not for guys leaving early. But I
understand there are Chris Webbers, Magic Johnsons, and Glenn
Robinsons. Certain players are ready and I would never be against
that if they really are. It's just that so many players leave for
the wrong reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves flirted with the idea of leaving after his junior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mateen could have left,'' said Izzo. ``But I think he needed
to stay. And he knew that.''
</P>
<P>
   Purdue coach Gene Keady said the difference in Monday night's
game was as much experience as talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what you expect to happen with older guys,'' said
Keady. ``If Glenn would have had the same `I want to win a national
championship' attitude, we might have experienced that.''
</P>
<P>
   Keady, like most coaches knows, the reality of the times as they
affect today's players.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have a family that has an education background, it
will probably be a factor,'' he said. ``But I don't think that's
going to change anything. I hope it will. But I don't think so. I
don't think so. I hope five years from now, I can say I was
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens in the next several weeks, when current
underclassmen determine whether they want to return to college, may
determine what team cuts down the nets a year from now when the
Final Four is held in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Already, there is talk that Florida could lose its best player,
sophomore forward Mike Miller. Ohio State could be a strong
contender if guard Michael Redd, its best scorer, decides to
return. Wisconsin, which played the role of underdog in this Final
Four, could do a repeat of Michigan State next season. The Badgers
figure to have four senior starters returning.
</P>
<P>
   But such things would go against the norm, which is why Monday
night's title game was so special.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just Michigan State vs. Florida. It was youth vs.
experience, and experience won.
</P>
<P>
   And so did college basketball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
