<HEADER>
A7783 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-MASTERS-SUTTON-BO     04-05 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-SUTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE HIS SHOT, SUTTON'S AUGUSTA CHANCES ARE LOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ He has an urge to spit it out, as if he had just
taken a bite of a lemon. The taste is bitter, so bitter that words
begin to shape an unthinkable thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be that little wire around the fringe there
where the ball couldn't come down back in the water, but they shave
everything down,'' Hal Sutton said in reference to the par-3 16th
hole at Augusta National. ``They want you to take the risk and
punish you for it. That is what they really want.''
</P>
<P>
   (itals)A player suggesting he doesn't like Augusta National?
Sacrilegious.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Sutton caught himself. Augusta National, where the Masters
begins Thursday, is a shrine; playing in the tournament is a
privilege. Criticism will get him nowhere, so he shifts focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to have a good tournament there,'' he said. ``I have
never played well there.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not an admission of guilt; it is a peace offering to a
golf course that has punished him unmercifully. Thirteen times
Sutton has teed it up in the Masters, and the results are
forgettable: 11 missed cuts, a tie for 27th, and a tie for 31st. He
hasn't played a weekend round at the Masters since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone in his misery. Augusta National has taken its
toll on countless professionals over the years, and the reasons
vary. The course, it has been argued, favors those who can hit a
long, high draw off the tee, then shift to a high fade into the
greens. But, others will say, it all comes to how well you chip and
putt.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton, a low-ball hitter whose short game has always been
marginal, does not fit into either style. That reality does not
send him down Magnolia Road with visions of green jackets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think everyone is on an equal playing field here,''
said Sutton. ``You don't have to hit a straight ball. It opens the
doors to swing hard and hit it anywhere. They are trying to shut
the door by adding the rough, but that doesn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many a player has felt defeated before putting the first peg in
the ground. Sutton is perhaps today's most glaring example, but Lee
Trevino remains Augusta National's most notorious critic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it, and it doesn't like me,'' is the gist of
Trevino's feelings. His low, cut iron approaches were not well
received by the firm, hard greens, and personal dislike for the
social setting led him to come here with apprehension.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Trevino's record, unlike Sutton's, is not one of failure.
He made the cut 17 of 20 times and had two Top 10s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lee pretty much was the exception,'' said Jay Haas, who will
be playing in his 19th Masters. ``A guy who had pretty much done
everything in golf. But for some reason he just got it in his head
that he could not play there comfortably. I disagree with that, and
I think as he looked back on it, he's kicking himself that he
didn't (give it a chance).''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton does not want to look back with regret. He is a few weeks
shy of his 42d birthday, and after some turmoil in his personal
life and a period of self-doubt with his golf game, his career has
been rejuvenated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am appreciative of the opportunity to get back my golf
game,'' said Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   The Masters, he said, is the ultimate test for him. More of a
challenge, perhaps, than beating Tiger Woods head-to-head two weeks
ago in The Players Championship. More of a challenge, certainly,
than the PGA Championship victory in 1983. Because now, the mind is
the opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Appleby can relate to Sutton's woes at Augusta. And to
Jeff Maggert's. And to Paul Azinger's. And to Bob Tway's. And to
Lee Janzen's. And to those of so many others who concede that they
have let the course get to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, there is a mental hump here,'' said Appleby, who
has missed the cut twice in three Masters starts. ``It's not that
the holes are shaped differently, but there's a mental barrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get over the Augusta aura and just play the
course. Players try to read the greens too much, try to win the
golf tournament, and when your nerves shut down, everything else
shuts down.''
</P>
<P>
   All of them, at one time or another, have hit a shot at the pin,
only to have it roll 40-50 feet away. All of them, at one time or
another, have stood over a shot with no idea how to get at a pin.
All of them, at one time or another, have felt cursed by the genius
of Alister Mackenzie.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Burke Jr.'s advice to all of them: ``If you've got some
sort of animosity, don't go. If you want to go, change your shoes
in the parking lot and go to the first tee. Leave all the other
stuff alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1956 Masters champion said too many players go to Augusta
with 14 clubs and twice as many excuses as to why they can't play
the course.
</P>
<P>
   Azinger, for instance, heard so many times that his low
trajectory did not fit in at Augusta, he started to believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I found out a couple of years ago that wasn't the case,''
said Azinger. ``I only lost by three shots and didn't even putt
particularly well. I could easily have found three shots out there
on the greens.''
</P>
<P>
   After 10 indifferent appearances, Azinger said, a different
frame of mind gripped him: ``My expectations probably are just a
little higher than they might have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Not in the atmosphere of Sutton's, however. The TPC victory _
during a week in which he constantly said he would not back down
from Woods _ has filled his tank with confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player, you are going to like the ones you play well on
and you don't like the ones you don't play well on,'' said Sutton.
``(Augusta National) hasn't been one of my favorites. But the
challenge for me to play well is still there.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sutton, we were reminded two weeks ago, puts his arms around
a challenge with a firm grip.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see is a competitive Hal Sutton,'' said his longtime
caddie, Freddie Burns. ``He wants to compete. He just doesn't want
to play at the Masters. He wants to compete at the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going there to win the golf tournament.''
</P>
</TEXT>
