<HEADLINE>
PROMISING GREECE GIVES INVESTORS HOPE FOR `EMERGING EUROPE'  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for APRIL 9 election, Greece)   (This 625-word ``separate-buy'' financial story is from the March
issue of ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her
e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been double-filed _ into the ``f''
financial news and ``i'' international news files.)  
  
 By TODD G. BUCHHOLZ  
 c.2000 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A couple thousand years after Greece supplied a name for the
continent, Europe is about to return the favor.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, when the euro likely replaces the Greek drachma, the
European Central Bank and its official interest-rate policy will
effectively rule the Greek economy, ending a history of inflation
and financial chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign lenders will sleep more soundly knowing they will be
repaid in euros, rather than drachmas. And Greek companies, which
used to pay double-digit interest rates on loans _ ten years ago,
Greece's inflation rate soared to 24 percent _ will soon be able to
borrow at lower rates than U.S. firms.
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's recently hiked Greece's credit rating two
rungs, to A-. The benefits have already shown up in the Athens
stock index, which rose fourfold between January 1997 and January
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, most Europeans opposed Greece's entry into the
European Monetary Union. If a volatile Greece joined EMU, the fear
was a Trojan Horse of economic woes might sneak inside Euroland:
exploding debt, rampant inflation, and widening deficits. Countries
such as Germany and France might get stuck bailing out Greece
during its next budget crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past year, Greece has allayed these worries by
successfully fighting fiscal and monetary excess. The budget
deficit has been reduced from 15 percent of gross domestic product
in 1990 to about 1.5 percent; inflation has fallen from 20 percent
to 2.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Greece has also jumped on the privatization bandwagon, selling
stakes in the National Bank of Greece and in the Hellenic
Telecommunications Organization, the biggest telephone firm.
</P>
<P>
   These sales raked in millions of dollars and helped push down
the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   This year looks like another good one, with GDP rising to 3.5
percent, higher than most of Europe. That's a good thing for the
ruling Panhellenic Socialist Party (PASOK), for it must hold an
election this year.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Greeks have become accustomed to a raging stock
market, PASOK is waiting for stock prices to rebound from a slump
in late 1999.
</P>
<P>
   According to Greek newspapers, the benchmark stock index must
return to the lofty 6000 level before PASOK will hold general
elections. (The index peaked at 6188 in September 1999 and sat
around 5100 in mid-January.)
</P>
<P>
   Without a guard as vigilant as the Securities and Exchange
Commission, you can't rule out some stock manipulation to get
prices up to the target. It's a dangerous game, but PASOK might
find it's more dangerous to lose the election.
</P>
<P>
   Still, whether the party pulls off a victory or not, Greece will
join the EMU, since the opposition New Democracy Party also
supports entry.
</P>
<P>
   You can almost hear the good wishes of other countries that want
to follow the Greek lead. The Czechs, Hungarians, and Poles all
imagine themselves carrying euros in the next five years. Even
Turkey sees itself joining the EMU.
</P>
<P>
   Could Greece ever abide this? Yes, because in order to
demonstrate the good behavior required for its own membership,
Greece had to act the better neighbor. So in December the
government, led by Costas Simitis, officially accepted Turkey as a
``candidate'' for the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   With EMU entry no longer a pipe dream for Turkey and the like,
speculators may begin snapping up ``emerging Europe'' equities with
as much enthusiasm as they've done with those in Greece.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the cheers going, remember that Athens will host the
2004 Olympics. That will bring plenty of tourists and foreign
currency. Even if Greece wins no relay races or wrestling matches,
she will be a big winner in the spectacle. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Contributing editor Todd G. Buchholz, president of
Victoria Capital, is the author of ``Market Shock.'') &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
