<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7816 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-05 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A MAGIC TOUCH CAN _ PRESTO _ HELP YOUR CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Which is more important: making a hard job look
easy or an easy job look hard? The answer, of course, is ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Society loves people who make a hard job look easy, with the
grace of a Magic Johnson or the dexterity of a classic chef or the
poise of an Oprah Winfrey. Nowhere on a bestseller list will you
find ``How to be a Millionaire by Scrimping and Saving and Busting
Your Hump for 40 Years.''
</P>
<P>
   But we also love magic tricks. Deep down, you know that nobody
really makes an elephant disappear, but you appreciate the
illusion. Certainly there is hard work involved, but nowhere near
as much as if you REALLY made an elephant disappear (which would
probably involve dynamite and a whole lotta Dustbusters).
</P>
<P>
   If you want to succeed, take advantage of both illusions. If you
don't have any magic, your career won't, either.
</P>
<P>
   To make hard work look easy and easy work look hard, you need a
sense of timing. Saying all the right words won't matter if your
timing is off.
</P>
<P>
   Take complaining. Unless you have an ideal job, there will be
times you could _ and should _ complain to your boss. But you
usually shouldn't do it when you're angry or upset about something
unrelated to work, or if you don't have any constructive way to
solve the problem. No matter what you say, your timing will be way
off.
</P>
<P>
   If conditions are miserable for everyone at your company and for
some reason you can't unionize or complain to the boss as a group,
griping by yourself probably won't do any good, either. Unless your
boss is a complete idiot, he already knows conditions are
miserable, and he can't or won't do anything about it. Put up with
it or leave.
</P>
<P>
   And if your high-pressure situation is temporary, that's the
absolute worst time to complain. With apologies to Rudyard Kipling,
if you can keep your head when all about you are losing theirs and
blaming it on you, your boss will love you for it. And so will your
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   When everyone is scrambling to make a deadline or panicking
about all the glitches in the new computer system, that's the time
to make the hard job look easy. Be a cross between Joe Montana and
Mary Poppins: calm, confident and compassionate. If you can, be
ahead of the pack and help the stragglers along.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a high-profile change going on, the company has
already decided that the worker strain is a small price to pay for
the long-term gain, so complaining wouldn't help you in any case.
What do you think the boss is going to say? ``Gee, Mary's feeling
stressed, so let's cancel this $100,000 project?'' ``John hates the
new phone system, so we're going back to two tin cans and a
string?''
</P>
<P>
   So when exactly is the best time to complain? When things are
going wonderfully. But instead of making it into a complaint,
consider it more like sculpting your job.
</P>
<P>
   See if there are important jobs that no one else is doing, then
offer to do them. Look at ways to streamline your current job with
things like computer shortcuts, fewer meetings and a better filing
system. Consider whether you're being too much of a perfectionist
on inconsequential things. Think about how you can do your job just
as well or better in less time. Brainstorm.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you do, don't look as if you have nothing to do. Quiet
times are like hunting season for bosses, when they look to hand
out jobs that are hardly exciting, but have to be done. Those
temporary assignments have a way of turning permanent. If you make
your easy job look hard, they won't pick you for a lot of those
dead-end assignments.
</P>
<P>
   This might sound like laziness, but it's really not. It's a
business strategy. Honest.
</P>
<P>
   Think of a company like Intel. If Intel wanted its profits to
soar temporarily, it could do it very easily; just stop spending
any money on research and development. Its revenue would stay close
to the same for a quarter or two, but expenses would drop. That
means more profit.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, though, Intel would get clobbered. Because it
didn't spend any money on R&AMP;D, it wouldn't have anything fresh to
offer.
</P>
<P>
   That is what workaholics and people who are constantly
scrambling in their jobs don't understand. They're not investing
anything in career R&AMP;D, and eventually they're going to lose. If
you're treading water in a place where the waves never stop,
someday you will drown.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there are jobs where you are expected to scramble all
the time, particularly in high-tech. But plan for some time that
you can devote to R&AMP;D, even if it's taking a sabbatical three years
from now. Many people wait until it's too late, then feel
constantly overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to your career, the greatest trick of all is
making sure it doesn't disappear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
