<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINFUL SOUPS FROM PAPPADEAUX AND COMMANDER'S PALACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A reader writes looking for the recipe for shrimp gumbo similar
to that served at Pappadeaux restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   In my search, I keyed into www.CopyKat.com, a recipe site based
in Houston. There wasn't a recipe for Pappadeaux's gumbo, but there
was one from Pappadeaux for its sinful crawfish bisque. There was
also a recipe for the seafood gumbo from New Orleans' landmark
Commander's Palace. So, here are two recipes for the price of one
stamp.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PAPPADEAUX CRAWFISH BISQUE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds crawfish
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   8 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped onion AND chopped green bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   3 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped tomato
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons brandy
</P>
<P>
   Boil crawfish in large pot of water. Drain and cool until
crawfish can be handled easily. Remove tail meat, saving shells.
Refrigerate tail meat.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in large saucepan or Dutch oven. Add crawfish shells,
paprika and cayenne. Saute 5 minutes. Add 8 cups water and bring to
boil. Reduce heat and simmer 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Strain liquid into another pan. Crush shells to remove remaining
liquid, strain and add that liquid to the strained liquid. Discard
shells.
</P>
<P>
   Return to heat and add onion, bell pepper, tomato paste, cream
and tomato. Simmer 1 hour, stirring frequently. Add brandy and
crawfish tail meat. Simmer 10 minutes. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 275 calories, 24 grams fat, 4
grams carbohydrates, 10 grams protein, 127 milligrams cholesterol,
65 milligrams sodium, 79 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   COMMANDER'S SEAFOOD GUMBO
</P>
<P>
   Yields 16 cups
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup solid shortening
</P>
<P>
   6 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup diced onion
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds peeled raw shrimp
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce can tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   12 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 pound claw crab meat
</P>
<P>
   1/4 bunch chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon thyme
</P>
<P>
   3 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce package frozen okra
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pint oysters with juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Make a roux with flour and shortening. Add garlic and cook until
golden brown. Add onion, bell pepper and celery, and cook until
transparent. Add shrimp and tomato, and simmer 10 minutes. Stir in
water and blend well. Add all other ingredients except okra and
oysters. Cook 1 hour, add okra and cook 20 minutes. Add oysters and
cook 10 minutes longer. Season with salt and pepper. Serve in soup
bowl over steamed rice.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 176 calories, 8 grams fat, 6
grams carbohydrates, 19 grams protein, 116 milligrams cholesterol,
290 milligrams sodium, 42 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Laura Gomez recently saw a recipe on WFAA/Channel 8 for baked
chicken dipped in buttermilk and rolled in cornflakes with spices.
The station hasn't been able to locate the recipe. Can anyone help?
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
