<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, April 6:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MARKETS &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Nasdaq stocks tumble at the opening but
recover. At 2:15 p.m., the Nasdaq was up 103 points, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 50 points and the S&AMP;P 500 up 6 points.
Many technology issues, including IBM, Cisco and Hewlett-Packard
were higher. But Microsoft was down 2.7 perecent and Qualcomm down
3.5 percent. Looking at what distinctions investors making among
technology stocks and among ``new economy'' and ``old economy''
stocks. Treasury prices were modestly higher. By Robert D. Hershey
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column, on the
recent market turmoil. By Floy Norris.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-TRADERS (Undated) _ Looking at market overload and the
problem of liquidity. Is there a weak link in the system? Looking
at the market makers and at technical problems. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-MARGIN (Chicago) _ Looking at margin calls and their
impact on the market. Plus get voices of small investors who have
received margin calls and how they are reacting. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-ASIA (Hong Kong) _ Stock markets from Tokyo to Singapore
swooned as investors followed the gyrating Nasdaq in the United
States by dumping shares in technology, Internet, and
telecommunications companies. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-EUROPE (London) _ European markets were sharply lower in
late afternoon trading. Frankfurt was down 3.62 percent and Paris
down 4.68 percent. In London, traders could only gnash their teeth
for most of the day: trading on the London Stock Exchange, Europe's
largest stock exchange, was suspended until mid-afternoon because
of technical problems. The exchange began trading at 10:45 a.m.
(New York time) and will stay open 2 hours longer than usual.
Shortly after the opening, the FTSE was down 1.21 percent. For
Britons, the shutdown could not have happened on a worse day. Not
only did it come on a day of worldwide turmoil on stock markets,
but Wednesday is the final day of the tax year when many private
investors buy and sell shares in a last-minute attempt to minimize
their liability for capital gains tax. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN-BANKS (Frankfurt) _ Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank
called off their $30 billion merger, after clashing over what to do
with the Kleinwort Benson securities unit. The announcement halted
what would have been one of the most far-reaching overhauls in
Germany's banking industry. By Edmund L. Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Developments: Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson, meeting with Microsoft and government lawyers,
wants to put the remedy phase of the case on a ``fast track'' and
consider encouraging the litigants to appeal the outcome directly
to the Supreme Court. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   METLIFE (New York) _ Shares of Metropolitan Life open modestly
higher on their debut on the New York Stock Exchange. Much of the
proceeds of the $2.9 billion offering will be distributed to former
policyholders as part of the demutualization. By Joseph B.
Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ECONOMY (Washington) _ Alan Greenspan, Bill Gates and others
attend a conference on the ``new ecovomy'' at the White House. By
Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   YAHOO-EARNINGS (New York) _ Yahoo will report first-quarter
earnings after the stock market closes. The forecast is 9 cents a
share; the ``whisper number'' appears to be 11 cents. By Sau
Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   MULTINATIONALS-RIGHTS (London) _ A Report by Amnesty
International on the willingness of multinational corporations to
pressure host countries over human rights abuses. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The Economic Scene column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-DIAMONDS (Undated) _ The valUe of diamonds, coupled with
the anonymity and portability of the stones _ millions of dollars
worth can be smuggled in a sock without triggering a metal detector
_ have made diamonds one of the most potent, and dangerous,
currencies of modern Africa. A Special Report by Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1, a jeweler looks at the final product in a Manhattan
store, NYT2, a diamond miner shows some of the fruits of his labor
from a mine deep in the jungle, NYT3, a diamond dealer's sign
outside a shop in Kisangani and NYT4, miners use picks and shovels
to dig to the gravel layer where diamonds are found.)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-DRUG (Paris) _ The World Health Organization and UN Aids
have recommended the use of a common and affordable antibiotic for
the 23 million people infected with the AIDS virus in Africa. If
preliminary tests are borne out and the drug _ which can cost as
little as $8 a year _ can be distributed widely, many of the
Africans infected with HIV may have years added to their lives and
longer gaps between debilitating secondary infections. By Donald G.
McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-POLITICS (Tokyo) _ Closing out a period of unusually
intense, if scrupulously shrouded political jockeying, Japan's
parliament Tuesday elected a new prime minister, Yoshiro Mori, to
replace Keizo Obuchi, who was left in a coma by a stroke over the
weekend. Mori said he will continue Obuchi's policies to try to
revive the economy. An election is expected in early June. By
Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-MORI-PROFILE (Tokyo) _ Man in the News profile of the new
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S.-SPY (Moscow) _ Russia's security services today
detained an American citizen in Moscow on spying charges, officials
said. The American works as director of a private firm in Moscow,
but was earlier employed by a U.S. intelligence agency, said a
spokesman with the Federal Security Service.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Jerusalem) _ Israel releases a Lebanese
prisoner, a ``bargaining'' chip kidnapped 14 years ago and held
without charges ever since. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-POLITICS (Istanbul) _ Turkey's parliament is to vote
today on whether to allow President Suleyman Demirel to seek
re-election, a political battle that is threatening to derail the
government. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-CIA-FILES (Berlin) _ The CIA returns some of the East
German secret police files Germany has been demanding. By Roger
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House votes on a ban on
what critics call partial birth abortion. This measure has been
vetoed twice before, and President Clinton promises to veto it
again. The Senate has sustained the veto each time. By Lizette
Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-PRICES (Washington) _ The political potency of high prices
for prescription drugs is powerfully demonstrated on two fronts
Wednesday. Slade Gorton of Washington, a mainstream Republican
senator, is complaining about the disparity between prescription
drugs in Canada and the United States. Although Democrats have been
making this point for months, the drug lobby is in a panic now that
Republicans are adding a voice to the criticism. And in the Senate,
Democrats have forced a symbolic vote on the issue as an amendment
to a budget resolution. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-VOTERS (Washington) _ EMILY's List, the nation's largest
funding resource for federal candidates, releases its second
national poll of women voters of the 2000 election, the EMILY's
List Women's Monitor, at a briefing, with pollsters Celinda Lake
and Geoff Garin. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Dateline to kum) _ The vice president's day, in
Washington, Maryland and North Carolina. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   VT-SUPREME-COURT (Concord, N.H.) _ The divorce case of a state
Supreme Court justice has taken the lid off questionable practices
in the court, leading to what some say is a constitutional crisis.
On Wednesday the state attorney general released a report detailing
his investigation into the court's practice of allowing judges who
has recused themselves from cases to comment on them. The
disclosures have prompted moves in the legislature to impeach all
five justices and the justice getting the divorce has already
resigned in a deal to avoid charges for trying to influence the
divorce case. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Dateline to kum) _ Developments in the Elian Gonzalez
case. With reporting from Neil A. Lewis in Washington and Rick
Bragg in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BISHOPS-RACISM (Undated) _ The bishops of Illinois issue
guidelines on how not to be racist. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD-SCANDAL (Los Angeles) _ Los Angeles City Council is
expected to vote to ask the Justice Department to take over the
investigation of the department's scandal-mired Rampart Division.
The move comes in response to a fight between the district
attorney's office and the police chief over the way the
investigation has been managed so far.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DRUG-ACCESS (Undated) _ Cancer patients and others with
severe pain who live in nonwhite neighborhoods may have trouble
getting treatment for their pain, because local pharmacies often
refuse to stock morphine and related drugs, doctors are reporting.
A survey of 347 pharmacies in New York City found that in nonwhite
neighborhoods, only 25 percent of pharmacies had enough
morphine-like drugs, known as opioids, to treat severe pain. But in
white neighborhoods, 72 percent of the stores had adequate
supplies. Doctors say that the problem, which they say is not
limited to New York, fits into a disturbing nationwide pattern,
revealed by recent studies showing that blacks are less likely than
whites to be referred for kidney transplants or surgery for
early-stage cancers, or to be given painkillers for broken bones or
pain follwing surgery. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BIOTECH-FOOD (Undated) _ Amid growing concerns over possible
risks posed by genetically modified crops, the National Academy of
Sciences issued a report Wednesday that calls for stronger
regulation of the novel plants and points to the potential for food
safety risks and environmental hazards. While noting the potential
for problems, the report emphasized that there was no evidence that
any biotech food currently on the market is unsafe to eat. By Carol
Kaesuk Yoon and Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HORMONE-REACT (Undated) _ Doctors officers were beseiged
with calls Wednesday from women and their husbands, wondering if
they should stop taking estrogen, following latest news that shows
it might slightly increase heart attack risk, rather than lower it.
But while many doctors pushed the concept, there has never been any
real evidence that estrogen was good for the heart. Still, the
situation has left women confused again. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OZONE-DEPLETE (Undated) _ Researchers from NASA and other
agencies said Wednesday that they have recorded one of the worst
losses of stratospheric ozone in the Arctic, coming near the end of
one of the coldest winters on record in the polar stratosphere. The
finding heightens concern that changes in the global climate may
delay recovery of the earth's partly depleted ozone layer. By
William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   William Safire's ``Essay'' and Bob Herbert's ``In America.''
</P>
