<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Fed Chairman
Alan Greenspan discuss e-commerce's contribution to the U.S.
economy at a National Economic Council business summit. One
surprise participant: Microsoft chairman Bill Gates. (Geewax, Cox
News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-GATES _ WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates
participates in the White House conference on the new economy, an
appearance some see as awkward in light of the federal antitrust
suit. (Glass, Cox News Service). 8.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Both sides in the Microsoft antitrust
case meet with U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson on
Wednesday, after which a schedule for the trial's next phase will
be issued. Jackson has said he hopes that any appeal can be
expedited directly to the Supreme Court, meaning the case might be
completed within a year. (Glass, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-AID _ WASHINGTON _ A North Carolina congressman said
Wednesday it was ``ridiculous and outrageous'' that residents of
his state might be forced to wait six months or longer for flood
relief funds. More than $300 in aid is contained in an emergency
spending bill that Senate leaders have decided not to act on.
(Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-PORK _ WASHINGTON _ In flush economic times, the
congressional largesse has hit historic levels, says a critic of
``pork barrel'' spending. In its annual accounting, the ``Pig
Book'' of Citizens Against Government Waste says that pet projects
for home states will cost $17.7 billion this year, 22 percent
higher than the previous record of $14.5 billion set three years
ago. Among the ``award winners'' this year is Rep. Jack Kingston,
R-Ga., for obtaining $100,000 for Vidalia onion research. (Malone,
Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   INFANT-HEARING _ WASHINGTON _ The National Campaign for Hearing
Health hosts a forum to discuss ''the leading birth defect in the
nation: undetected hearing loss.'' NCHH will also release its
state-by-state ``report card'' identifying which states provide
comprehensive newborn screening programs. (Turay, Cox News
Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   AL-AMIN-LAWYERS _ ATLANTA _ Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin's legal team
will not include the likes of Johnny Cochran. Instead, it will have
some of Atlanta's most highly regarded lawyers who are media-savvy
and well-suited to handle a high-profile case like Al-Amin's. Bruce
Harvey and Jack Martin, both experienced in death penalty
litigation, are expected to be named Al-Amin's lawyers. Public
defender Michael Mears has bowed out, citing personal reasons.
(Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   AL-AMIN-CAR _ ATLANTA _ Preliminary tests done on Al-Amin's
Mercedes-Benz show that the bullet holes scattered about the car,
came from the .40 caliber weapons of Fulton deputies Ricky Kinchen
and Aldranon English. The night Kinchen was killed and English was
injured in a shootout with Al-Amin in the West End, the deputies
shot at Al-Amin at least 10 times. (Longa, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   BUSWRECK-FOLO _ Updating investigation into Tennessee-Georgia
train wreck that killed three kids and injured four other people,
including the bus driver. Driver Rhonda Cloer still has not spoken
to investigators. Her daughter remains in induced coma and Rhonda
remains with her. Updating conditions of Cloer and the other child.
(Bennett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10
</P>
<P>
   LIFEBOAT _ A man's boat was torpedoed and he spent 31 days in a
lifeboat. He fought the government his whole adult life for the
right to be considered a veteran of WWII. Kalajian, Palm Beach
Post). 49. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
