<HEADER>
A7828 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     04-05 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER-SON REUNION NEEDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be a kick in the head if this feud between Elian
Gonzalez's relatives in Miami and the kid's father in Cuba turned
out to be a hoax?
</P>
<P>
   It's far-fetched, sure, but not that far-fetched. What if the
dad, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, and the Florida relatives were actually
on the same side in the dispute about the boy's residency? What if
the name-calling, the threats, the recrimination were part of a
secret plan to help Elian's father defect to the United States?
</P>
<P>
   We'll find out soon enough. According to news reports, Juan
Miguel Gonzalez could be arriving in the United States any minute
now.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no indication whatsoever that he intends to do
anything but assert his rightful custody of Elian and take him home
to Cuba as soon as possible. But once the elder Gonzalez is given
the opportunity to stand on America's ``free soil,'' as Al Gore put
it the other day, who's to say that he won't seize the moment and
request permanent residency for himself and his son?
</P>
<P>
   It's true that Gonzalez has been toeing the party _ read that
``Communist Party'' _ line in demanding the return of Elian to his
native Cuba. But what else could he do? He's hardly in a position
to say to Fidel Castro:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Fidel, life's a ball here on your island. As suffocating
dictatorships go, it's a great place to visit. But it ain't Miami,
if you know what I mean, so I think I'll just catch the next plane
to Florida, hook up with my kid and start talking about my life in
Cuba strictly in the past tense.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you suppose Castro allows political prisoners to receive mail
from their children who live in the U.S.?
</P>
<P>
   Given the impracticality of speaking his mind, perhaps Gonzalez
conjured up this plot to prove his loyalty to Castro by fostering
the illusion that he is at odds with his Miami relatives about
Elian's future _ and that he could absolutely be trusted to travel
to America and return promptly with his son.
</P>
<P>
   It's wishful thinking, I know.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it's not any kind of thinking. It's a flight of fancy. But
I'll bet it's not the most preposterous conspiracy theory you've
heard this year _ or this week, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. Until advised otherwise, we must assume that Juan
Miguel Gonzalez means exactly what he says: He wants to regain
custody of his son and take him home to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   As much as freedom-loving Americans might abhor the idea of
condemning an adorable 6-year-old to a life of relentless
oppression in Cuba, there's no getting around the reality that
Elian and his father are residents of that country _ and if that's
where the father wants his son to grow up, we have no right to
interfere.
</P>
<P>
   American politicians, especially, ought to butt out.
Presidential candidates in both parties have tried to exploit this
controversy, as have elected officials from coast to coast. It's
hardly surprising to see a Marxist thug such as Castro using an
innocent child for propaganda purposes, but we expect better from
those who call themselves leaders of the greatest nation on the
planet.
</P>
<P>
   As for those Cuban-American militants in Miami _ the ones who
threatened to form a human chain around Elian to prevent officials
from returning him to his father _ well, they say they care about
Elian, but it is perfectly obvious that what they really care about
is baiting Castro. If they had the kid's interests at heart, they
would be urging his relatives in Miami to reunite him with his
father.
</P>
<P>
   That this dispute has gone on for so long _ the boy was pulled
out of the ocean on Thanksgiving Day, for crying out loud _ is a
national disgrace. Elian should have been sent home to his father
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of people to blame, but the time for
blame-finding is past. The time has arrived to repair this mess. If
Juan Miguel Gonzalez arrives in America and says he wants to take
his son home to Cuba, he should be allowed to do so without further
delay.
</P>
<P>
   If he wants to stay, of course, then surely that can be
arranged.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
