<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, April 6:
</P>
<P>
   FAKE-GARDENS (New York) _ For the $6.2 billion artificial, dried
and preserved flowers and foliage industry, business is blooming. A
mainstay of hotels, offices, malls and atriums because they don't
require watering or spraying, don't produce pests or provoke
allergies and lawsuits, and because they ``live'' forever,
permanent botanicals are making inroads into home decor. By William
L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT6,7.
</P>
<P>
   MODERNIST-PRESERVATION (Undated) _ Subtly different and
elegantly precise, the modern house in old Charleston, S.C., could
be the proud standard for a more enlightened approach to
preservation today, beyond just stopping time in its own tracks. By
Julie V. Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
land.
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY-PRESERVATION (Philadelphia) _ If hype was an art form,
the developer Tony Goldman might have won some Pulitzers prizes by
now. And if Pritzker prizes were awarded not for boutique
architecture, but for turning seedy buildings into world class
destinations, then Mr. Goldman would surely be on the short list.
Most real estate mavens do not mess with losing propositions but
this developer loves them. So far, Goldman, a Trustee for the
National Trust for Historic Preservation, claims to have saved SoHo
in Manhattan; South Beach, Florida, and Wall Street. Now, he has
plans to recycle Philadelphia. By Barbara Flanagan.
</P>
<P>
   LIGHTNING-RODS (Undated) _ David Silvester, owner of Zeus
Lightning Rod Inc. in Hopewell, N.J., knows that proselytizing is
hopeless: not until an electrical storm gives homeowners firsthand
experience _ when it blows their chimneys apart, zaps their
computer disk drives and fries their air conditioners _ do they
consider buying a lightning rod. By Lynn Ermann.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MILKMAN (Chappaqua, N.Y.) _ There are not many milkmen these
days making the rounds of America's towns and suburbs. But
Westchester County has at least one, Hercules Bontzolakes, 48, who
is the old-fashioned, ``pay when you can, cream floats to the
top,'' real McCoy, the classic purveyor of milk, cream, cottage
cheese, eggs and juice. By Timothy Jack Ward.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT5.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
