<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7830 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-05 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `OLD ECONOMY,' REAL MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The heck with ``the old economy'' and ``the new
economy.'' I want a piece of the Willie economy.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Brown, the mayor of San Francisco, jumped with both
well-shod feet into the stock market last year and made a killing,
largely on initial offerings of high-tech stocks, doubling his
investment to almost $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to his spokeswoman, Kandace Bender, the mayor doesn't
have a new financial adviser but is ``kind of playing around on the
Internet and doing trading over the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Brown, a day trader? Why not? The man does have a short
attention span and loves quick turnarounds.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his purchases took place during last year's election. So
that's what he was doing behind the podium during debates _ buying
and selling on his laptop.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is a political genius, so why not a market genius, too?
And it's conceivable he knows how to use a computer.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor is a Democrat, despite his Republican tastes and
endorsements. He should share his wealth of knowledge with
residents. How about installing a ticker in the City Hall rotunda
to show all his purchases and their prices?
</P>
<P>
   I'd be in the rotunda with my laptop, following every move of
San Francisco's mayor and leading economic indicator. If only I
could get in on the ground floor _ or better, the second floor of
City Hall _ with those IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   The only two ``old economy'' stocks in the mayor's portfolio are
a good example of what's wrong with trying to divide the economy
into old and new sectors.
</P>
<P>
   One is UPS and the other is Mirage Resorts. The former delivers
stuff sold by e-commerce companies and the latter is in the
gambling business, like Nasdaq. The old economy and the new economy
have a way of running together into what you might call ``the
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   I ran into an old acquaintance, Howard Slater, in the lobby of
the Charles Schwab brokerage (where 15 newspeople were interviewing
three investors about market disturbances) and he explained the
difference between the old and the new economy in the most sensible
of ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old economy is the companies we grew up with, like GM and
Clorox, the companies that actually make things and show a profit
at the end of the year,'' Slater said. ``The new economy is
companies like 3Com and Palm where you're betting on future
value.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, anytime you invest in a company you're
betting on future value and hoping it makes money at the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   That's even the case with Amazon.com, which hasn't made a profit
in its six years in business, and whose founder, Jeff Bezos, says
he won't make predictions about profitability.
</P>
<P>
   After all, predicting a profit for Amazon.com could destroy
investor confidence and bring down the house of cards.
</P>
<P>
   Dividing companies into new and old economies doesn't make a lot
of sense to me. Microsoft is one of the engines of the
information-based economy, yet it ships products and makes a
profit.
</P>
<P>
   Old-line companies in which my family owns stock, like
Pittsburgh Plate Glass and Bristol-Myers, use high-tech processes
to make glass and drugs. It's not as if workers are individually
hand-blowing car windows, or mixing aspirin with ladles.
</P>
<P>
   New information systems have been integrated with steel
machinery, leading to the great productivity of the American
economy, so where do you draw the line between new and old?
</P>
<P>
   ``Old economy'' vs. ``new economy'' seems more like a cultural
distinction, a fashion distinction or a form of invective. Your
employees drink Pabst, ours drink microbrews. Your managers wear
suits and ties, ours wear bowling shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever is going on in the Dow Jones and Nasdaq, or new and old
economy, something seems to be shaking out. At least we're all
getting ready for a big shakeout.
</P>
<P>
   A Silicon Valley tech expert was quoted on the front page of the
Wall Street Journal the other day as saying that for five years
people in the valley haven't been selling products, they've been
selling stocks.
</P>
<P>
   A stockbroker was quoted on television as saying that the stocks
taking the big hits were ones for companies that had no revenues,
and would have no revenues in the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, there's the real economy and the unreal economy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I don't care if Willie Brown himself advises investing in the
following companies. These are the ones I won't touch:
</P>
<P>
   _ Anything that involves people buying pet food, CDs or
groceries over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anything in which truck drivers have to be offered stock
options so they'll deliver the pet food, CDs or groceries while
their trucks are collecting double-parking tickets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anything that involves an on-line magazine, particularly if it
promises to be cutting edge and have media critics.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anything that needs a venture capitalist.
</P>
<P>
   Call me an old economy snob, but give me an old-fashioned
capitalist anytime. Or give me WillieBrown.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
