<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7837 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-IMF-SECURITY-$ADV09-C     04-05 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-SECURITY-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLICE: SECURITY WILL BE 'TIGHT' FOR IMF, WORLD BANK MEETINGS;
NO SEATTLE REPEAT
 &HT;    (900&AMP;ADD).
 &HT;    With IMF-WORLDBANK-$ADV09.
 &HT;    With chart information attached at end of story.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., April 9 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By ALEC SCHULTZ 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The ``Spirit of Seattle'' serves as a source of
pride for the tens of thousands of protestors descending upon
Washington this week, but to police officials here it evokes images
of chaos and a breakdown of order.
</P>
<P>
   As demonstrators stream into this already crowded capital city
to protest everything from free trade with China to global poverty
at the spring meetings of the International Monetary Fund and World
Bank, Washington D.C. Police Chief Charles Ramsey is determined to
prevent a re-occurrence of the violence that derailed the World
Trade Organization summit in Seattle last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Washington, Ramsey promises, will not turn into another
``Battle in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   He promises that security will be tight throughout the city,
anchored by 1,500 police officers.
</P>
<P>
   They will be working closely with up to 500 additional officers
from the Federal Bureau of Investigation and U.S. Capitol Police,
Park Police and Secret Service, Ramsey said.
</P>
<P>
   The largest role, and thus the largest burden for containing the
upcoming demonstrations falls to Ramsey's district police. And,
having witnessed the Seattle protests _ shut down the WTO meetings,
tarnish the city's reputation and force the ``retirements'' of its
two top police officials _ district police are confident they can
control what lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, local law enforcement intends to back up such tough
talk. (Ramsey himself attended an FBI seminar on lessons learned
from the Seattle protests.) But the anti-globalization protesters
that have been salivating at the prospect of these spring meetings
_ which typically garner no more than two dozen hard-core activists
_ appear equally determined.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of their Seattle success, these protesters have
targeted the IMF and World Bank as institutions they claim serve
corporate ``big business'' interests while impoverishing ordinary
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will demonstrate that the IMF and World Bank have not
alleviated global poverty; instead they have exacerbated it,'' said
Kevin Danaher, one of the protest organizers.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters want to reduce the role of the IMF and World Bank
in countries' domestic financial affairs. Uniting under an umbrella
organization called Mobilization for Global Justice, the
protesters' stated goal is to ``shut down the spring meetings,
entirely.''
</P>
<P>
   To achieve this goal, protest leaders have vowed to follow a
policy of civil disobedience, including marches and human chains
around the IMF and World Bank buildings _ only two blocks west of
the White House. These tactics were effective in the Seattle
protests, where demonstrators were able to trap finance and trade
ministers in their hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ramsey acknowledged that the protesters have a right to
peacefully demonstrate, he emphasized that ``the ministers also
have a right to have their meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully the demonstrations will remain peaceful,'' the chief
said, hastening to add that the department has trained extensively
to deal with any outbreaks of violence. For example, officers are
learning riot-control tactics and watching videos of the Seattle
police losing control.
</P>
<P>
   The district police department has made sure its officers will
be well-equipped. If necessary, riot gear, tear gas, gas masks and
rubber bullets will be readily available for officers at the
protests.
</P>
<P>
   While the police department has kept many of its security plans
confidential, Ramsey has made it clear that his officers will not
allow violence or non-compliance with police orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not allow people to freely roam our streets and engage
in violence,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, spokespersons for the Mobilization for Global Justice
have said repeatedly that their demonstrations will remain
peaceful. They admit, however, that it is difficult to control
radical protestors. The instances of rampant violence and vandalism
during the four-day WTO summit, for example, resulted mainly from
radical fringe groups not directly associated with organized
protest demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials in Seattle drew heavy criticism for not being
prepared for the possibility of violent demonstrations. So much so,
that the city's police chief and his deputy chose to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey does not want that scenario repeated. So his department
began security preparations early, beginning with the chief's
attendance at the FBI seminar on Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he learned during the session, Ramsey replied,
``that these groups will resort to acts of violence to achieve
their goals.''
</P>
<P>
   The protestors have threatened to block Metro stations and/or
traffic on downtown Washington streets during the spring meetings.
Similar tactics succeeded in shutting down a portion of Seattle
during the WTO summit.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a proactive approach, Ramsey aims to smother any violence
early, before it has the chance to get out of control.
</P>
<P>
   For example, many of the planned demonstrations will be on
national park grounds under the jurisdiction of the Park Police,
and requiring groups to have permits.
</P>
<P>
   Park Police spokesman Robert McLain said so far, protestors have
obtained permits for official demonstrations on Sun., April 16, in
Lafayette Park and on the Ellipse _ in front of and behind the
White House, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the protests remain peaceful, McLain noted that the
Park Police will allow the demonstrations to proceed. Should
protesters assemble without a permit, however, they would first be
asked to disperse.
</P>
<P>
   If they refuse, McLain added, ``They would be subject to
arrest.''
</P>
<P>
   While Ramsey said he hopes that no arrests will be necessary,
the protestors ``are the ones responsible for their behavior and
for demonstrating peacefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he anticipated a Seattle-like shutdown of downtown
Washington, Ramsey replied emphatically, ``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   -----------------------------------------------------------
</P>
