<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A FAMILIAR GOLF COURSE FOR AN OLD PRO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SUSAN FORNOFF  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ It's not often that a member of Augusta National
holds a press conference in his green jacket, but let's cut Arnold
Palmer some slack _ he is new at this.
</P>
<P>
   Not new at the green jacket (he has won four) and not new at
press conferences (he has had umpteen zillion), just new to paying
dues. The members invited him to join last fall, and he accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now if they'd just let me play this thing from the members'
tees,'' joked Palmer, who is 70.
</P>
<P>
   Though the long ball has left him, he can still remember when,
and Tuesday he had no problem listing a host of Masters highlights
over the years.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was coming here for the first time with his wife,
Winnie, and sleeping in their camper. Someone asked if that memory
had sparked any emotion as he came to Augusta this year without
Winnie, who died of cancer last fall. Palmer couldn't answer; tears
welled up in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   There'll be more nostalgia for him Thursday and Friday, no
doubt, but he will be among friends. The committee grouped him with
Jack Nicklaus and Gary Player.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're familiar faces,'' said Palmer, who was clearly
pleased. ``I've seen 'em before.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   CH-CH-CH-CHANGES: Get ready for lots of chitchat on the CBS
telecast about the changes that have been made to this perpetually
changing golf course.
</P>
<P>
   These include new greens at 10 and 16, added trees on 14, 15 and
17 and subtracted trees on 17.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually no one would whine about such things, this being an
invitational and whining being considered rude. And Tiger Woods
even smiled about the so-called Tiger-proofing, which he seems to
think is backfiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's helping anybody who can hit the ball long and high,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   That you?
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time I checked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
