s k BC-FLAG-$ADV09-COX     04-05 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAG-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFTER 135 YEARS, IT'S TIME TO FURL THE CONFEDERATE FLAG
 &HT;    For Sunday, April 9
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On April 9, 1865, Confederate Gen. Robert E. Lee
rose from surrendering his forces at the crossroads of Appomattox
Courthouse, and found himself looking into the eyes of Ely Parker.
</P>
<P>
   Military Secretary to U.S. Gen. Ulysses S. Grant, Parker was a
Seneca Indian, readily distinguished as such by his dark features
and strong cheekbones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to see one real American here,'' Lee said, as he
shook Parker's hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all Americans,'' came Parkdr's poignant reply.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred and thirty five years after the collapse of tje
Confederacy, the symbol of the Confederate cause still has the
power to challenge the force and reason behind Parker's unrehearsed
eloquence. Much of the American South, after all, remains split
over whether to revere the Confederate battle flag and sanction it
with enduring institutional status, or to consign it, as Lee did at
Appomattox, to its rightful place in history.
</P>
<P>
   In an age when thousands of American soldiers are standing
sentry against age old regional and ethnic hatreds in Bosnia and
Kosovo, when an uncertain world looks to the United States to try
to broker peace between Arab and Jew in the fractious Middle East,
when the export of American democracy has fueled a global
revolution that has brought tyrants low and unleashed millions from
their yoke, parts of the American South remain incongruously out of
step with the nation's larger purpose, as haunted by history as any
place on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps nowhere do the ghosts of the South's rebellious past
linger with more insistence than in Richmond, Va. Growing up there
in the 1950s and 60s, I never forgot that my hometown was the
once-proud capital of the Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   Historical markers and battlefields peppered the local
landscape, and hallowed ground lay everywhere around a city that
spent most of the Civil War under siege.
</P>
<P>
   I rode my bike in the shadows of massive stone monuments to
J.E.B. Stuart, Stonewall Jackson, Jefferson Davis and Lee. I caught
catfish in the muddy waters of the James River, which guarded the
city like a grand serpentine moat from Union advances in the early
months of the war.
</P>
<P>
   I went to Douglas Southall Freeman High School, named for Lee's
celebrated biographer. Our official school name was ``The Rebels;''
our banner the Confederate battle flag. The band played ``Dixie''
at pep rallies and third and long. And we'd gird ourselves for
torturous football drills in the sweltering heat of August by
reminding each other of the necessity to show, at all times,
something we called ``Rebel Pride.''
</P>
<P>
   That's far from what comes to mind today when I watch as a
handful of southern states _ Virginia is not among them _ cling
stubbornly to the Confederate flag as some final, vainglorious
vestige of a long lost, and fatally flawed, cause.
</P>
<P>
   For what that flag symbolizes to so many Americans is national
trauma and human despair, not only at the horror of the past it
exhumes, but at the notion that the hatred and injustice that split
this nation asunder a century and a half ago refuses, for some, to
surrender or die.
</P>
<P>
   I understand, even partly embrace, the respect many Southerners
still hold for that flag and those who served it.
</P>
<P>
   For if slavery was the irredeemable evil burning at the core of
the Confederate revolt, it's also true that scores of thousands of
Southerners who never owned a slave, nor wanted to, took up arms to
defend a way of life, a culture that valued family and farm. They
resented the imposition of Washington's will and found financial
security and personal worth within a largely feudal structure
sharply at odds with the industrialist patterns that shaped the
North.
</P>
<P>
   Over those ideals, blood was shed. Good men died, a nation's
fate was cast.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, it does no service to the remembrance of those lives to
perpetuate the pain so many died to put to rest.
</P>
<P>
   When I hear my fellow Southerners defend the continuing use of
the Confederate Flag over the state houses of South Carolina,
Georgia, or Mississippi, I wonder what honor they pay to the memory
of those like General Lee who, in his final command, ordered his
men to return to those states resolved not only to rebuild them,
but to re-knit them back into the fabric of the Union he cherished
above all except his native Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   To Lee, the true heart of Dixie was Community, the idea that
Southern people shared enough common values that they could
reconcile differences deep enough to spark a war, lay down their
swords in its ruinous aftermath, and move purposefully forward,
together as one, into a future lit with renewal and hope.
</P>
<P>
   It is that very future that many Southerners turn their back on
each time they reject the diversity and opportunity of the modern
South, and instead reach into the attic for a dusty totem of an age
Lee buried at Appomattox.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, they not only keep alive the suffering behind one
of the sorriest chapters in American history, they make a mockery
of the sacrifices that brave men, the Blue and the Grey, bore to
make this nation free.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all Americans,'' Ely Parker reminded Lee on the day,
135 years ago, the Confederacy fell. The time has come to furl the
flag.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans covers the White House for Cox Newspapers. He can be
reached by e-mail at: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
