A7852 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-BOOKPASSOVER-SFCHRON &LR;      04-05 1505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKPASSOVER-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 COOKS' BOOKS: Two Jewish Cookbooks Present a Blend of
Tradition  and Innovation   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Holidays the world over, whether religious,
patriotic or personal, are intimately associated with food. The
Thanksgiving turkey, Easter ham, Passover haroset, the dates that
break the fast at Ramadan, or the double chocolate cake Cousin Joe
expects for his birthday are all part of the fabric of those
special days.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And yet, there is a fine line between celebrating tradition and
being in a rut. So a new riff on an old favorite can be welcome,
indeed. Two new books, out in time for Passover, attempt to do that
for Jewish cooking.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite of the two expresses the spirit of old-yet-new even
in its title _ ``The Gefilte Variations: A Food Lover's
Improvisation on Jewish Themes.'' Veteran culinary author Jayne
Cohen has included enough personal notes in this book to create a
warm, fuzzy feeling, yet enough innovations to add new dimensions
without diluting Jewish cooking's essential character.
</P>
<P>
   The second book, ``Mother and Daughter Jewish Cooking: Two
Generations of Jewish Women Share Traditional and Contemporary
Recipes,'' is by the British writer and television host Evelyn Rose
and her daughter, Judi, a New York food writer and television
producer. The premise is intriguing _ mother representing
tradition, daughter pushing the frontiers.
</P>
<P>
   You can certainly create fine meals from this book, though even
Mum, in the name of more healthful eating, makes changes that
traditionalists might not cotton to. ``Grandma's'' kugel, for
example, skips the  &LR; gribenes  &LR; (chicken skin cracklings) and
suggests margarine as an alternative to rendered chicken fat.
</P>
<P>
   Daughter Judi's recipes may be short on tradition but are
simplified (according to Jewish dietary laws) versions of
international favorites. So you get butterflied chicken with
Provencal herbs cooked on the grill, baby potatoes roasted in
herbed olive oil, fluffy Scottish scones and Vienna apple squares
with cinnamon-scented cream. These are delicious dishes, but their
connection to the Jewish kitchen is tenuous.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, American cooks may have a little problem with some
British approaches like corned beef brisket, considered
traditional, cured with saltpeter and served with latkes or french
fries. French fries? It's a very assimilated book.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, on the other hand, reaches back to biblical times with
some of her innovations. A brisket recipe includes pomegranate
molasses _ a historic Middle Eastern sweetener _ as well as
chestnuts, which were also staples in ancient times.
</P>
<P>
   She, too, reaches out to other countries in her recipes, as in
Italian-style fried chicken cutlets that make a delicious entree
during Passover, Romanian-style ground meat sausages, and Egyptian
fish balls. Unlike Judi Rose's international kitchen romp, these
dishes are rooted in regional Jewish cooking.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Jewish cooking may be the original fusion cuisine, as
Jews in the diaspora over centuries have adopted and adapted
ingredients indigenous to the countries they call home.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``The Gefilte Variations: A Food Lover's Improvisation on &LR; 
 &LR; Jewish Themes,'' by Jayne Cohen (Scribner, 416 pages hardcover, &LR; 
 &LR; $27.50). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``Mother and Daughter Jewish Cooking: Two Generations of &LR; 
 &LR; Jewish Women Share Traditional and Contemporary Recipes,'' by &LR; 
 &LR; Evelyn and Judi Rose (William Morrow, 294 pages hardcover, &LR; 
 &LR; $25). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; FRIED CHICKEN CUTLETS, ITALIAN-JEWISH STYLE
</P>
<P>
   Jayne Cohen writes that chicken flavored with cinnamon is a
Hanukkah specialty in Italy, but she also recommends this dish for
a nonseder Passover meal. The celery fried with the chicken (but
not eaten), adds flavor and helps make the chicken golden.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   4 large garlic cloves, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil, plus additional for frying
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds skinless, boneless chicken cutlets, trimmed of fat
and gristle
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fine matzo meal
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 celery stalks, including leaves, washed, dried, cut into
4- to 5-inch lengths
</P>
<P>
   Lemon wedges
</P>
<P>
   Fresh parsley sprigs for garnish (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl or nonreactive baking dish, whisk
together the cinnamon, garlic, lemon juice, olive oil and salt and
pepper to taste. Add the chicken and toss to coat thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Set up a work station near the stove. Spread 1 cup matzo meal on
a large sheet of wax paper or a plate and season with 1 teaspoon
salt and 1/8 teaspoon pepper or to taste. Next to it, in a wide
shallow bowl or pie pan, beat the eggs with a few drops of water
until well blended and smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Dredge the cutlets well with the matzo meal, rubbing it lightly
into the chicken. Make sure each cutlet is covered all over with
meal. If necessary, add more matzo meal, remembering to add more
seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Heat about 1/2 cup olive oil in a 10- to 12-inch heavy skillet
over medium heat until hot and fragrant but not smoking. Shake a
cutlet to remove all excess matzo meal, then coat it thoroughly
with the egg and slip it quickly into the hot oil. Being careful
not to crowd the pan, add more chicken, dipping each piece in the
egg just before placing it in the pan. Slip a few pieces of celery
in between the cutlets as they fry. Using 2 spatulas (tongs will
ruin the delicate egg coating), carefully turn the chicken when it
is light golden, 2-3 minutes. Saute the other side 2-3 minutes
longer, or until cooked through. Turn the celery pieces when you
turn the chicken. Transfer the cutlets to a platter lined with
paper towels so they can drain. Discard the cooked celery. Keep the
chicken warm in a 200 degree oven until the remaining pieces are
done.
</P>
<P>
   Continue frying the remaining chicken in batches, in the same
way, adding fresh celery to the pan with each batch. Wipe out the
skillet and replace the oil if some of the coating falls off and
burns.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the chicken right away, accompanied by the lemon wedges
and garnished, if you like, with fresh parsley. It really needs no
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 3 or 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 340 calories, &LR;   &LR; 46 g protein, 27 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 4 g fat (1 g saturated), 177 mg cholesterol, 135 mg
sodium, 1 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; HALIBUT IN A VELVET LEMON SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   This classic Passover dish from Evelyn Rose needs to be
refrigerated at least 24 hours and up to 4 days before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sea salt
</P>
<P>
   Pinch white pepper
</P>
<P>
   11/2 to 2 pounds bone-in halibut, about 6 to 8 pieces (salmon
steaks may be substituted)
</P>
<P>
   The Sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons potato starch, mixed to a cream with the minimum of
water
</P>
<P>
   The Garnish
</P>
<P>
   Curly parsley
</P>
<P>
   Sections of fresh lemon, skin left on
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   In a lidded skillet, large enough to hold all the fish in 1
layer, bring 2 cups water, the onion, sugar, salt and pepper to the
boil. (Adding the sugar at this stage greatly improves the fish
without noticeably sweetening it.) Lower the heat while you prepare
the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Wash and salt the fish and put in the skillet. Bring the
poaching liquid back to the boil, then lower the heat so it is
barely bubbling. Partly cover and simmer very gently for 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Lift out the fish with a slotted spoon or fish slice, draining
any liquid back into the skillet.
</P>
<P>
   Place the fish in an oval serving dish about 11/2 inches deep.
Remove any skin but leave in the bone, then leave to cool while you
make the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   To make the sauce, boil the remaining fish poaching liquid for 3
minutes to concentrate the flavor, then strain it and measure out 1
cupful. Beat the eggs thoroughly with a rotary whisk, then whisk in
the cup of fish liquid, the lemon juice and the potato starch
cream. Alternatively, mix all the sauce ingredients for 10 seconds
in a food processor or blender. This makes it easier to thicken the
sauce without fear of its curdling.
</P>
<P>
   Put this liquid in a thick-bottom saucepan and cook gently over
low heat until the sauce thickens to the consistency of a coating
custard _ you will need to stir it constantly. Do not let it boil
or the eggs may curdle. To make the sauce in the microwave, cook
the blended ingredients, uncovered, in a jug or bowl on 50 percent
power for 2 minutes; whisk well, then cook for a further 2 to 3
minutes, until thickened.
</P>
<P>
   Taste the sauce and add extra lemon juice, if necessary, to make
it equally sweet and sour. Pour the sauce over the fish, coating it
completely. Leave in the refrigerator overnight, covered with
aluminum foil.
</P>
<P>
   Serve at room temperature, garnished with the parsley and lemon
sections.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 290 calories, &LR;   &LR; 46 g protein, 2 g carbohydrate,
7 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 134 mg cholesterol, 166 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1504EDT &QL; 
