<SLUG> BC-GERMAN-CIA-FILES-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. RETURNS STASI FILES TO GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ After a protracted dispute that had soured German-U.S.
relations, the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency has handed over the
first of a large cache of East German files listing intelligence
agents and their code names, the German government said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The files, which will fill critical gaps in Germany's knowledge
of the activities of the old East German intelligence service known
as the Stasi, were spirited out of Berlin in 1989 and are widely
believed to have been acquired by the CIA in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Germany has long demanded the return of the files, saying they
belong in Berlin and should never have been taken to Washington.
But until an accord was reached late last year, the CIA had
insisted the files were too sensitive to be returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States handed over the first CD-ROM containing the
files on Friday,'' a spokeswoman for the German government said
Wednesday. ``The government expects to receive further files in the
near future.'' German officials, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said they expected to receive the rest of the files over
the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, the German government
took possession of about 6 million Stasi files, a product of what
was perhaps the most spied-on society in history. The former East
German communist state had 17 million citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Large quantities of these files have already been decoded, but
many contained only the codenames of spies. The set of files
essential to linking these codenames with the real identities of
agents, particularly agents who worked in West Germany, ended up at
CIA headquarters in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   This set of files _ most of which are still in the United States
_ is believed to contain over 300,000 names. That information could
shatter the cover of some former spies still living in Germany,
leading to possible arrests, German officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA has refused to say how it obtained the files.
Unconfirmed reports suggest the files were given by a high-ranking
member of the Stasi to the KGB, the Soviet Union's spy agency, in a
villa in Berlin in 1989. They were then brought to Moscow, where
the CIA later acquired them, reportedly for a large sum.
</P>
<P>
   The German government said Wednesday that the information in the
files delivered by the United States had not yet been examined, but
would be given to the Ministry of the Interior and the commission
overseeing the Stasi files.
</P>
<P>
   By comparing the new files with those it already has, the German
government expects to uncover the names of former West German
employees of the Stasi, who may have numbered as many as 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   The handover of the files may have been a gesture aimed at
patching up a somewhat frayed relationship. German-U.S. relations
have been strained in recent weeks by a fierce dispute over who
should head the International Monetary Fund. The initial German
candidate was rejected by the Clinton administration before Horst
Koehler, also a German, was appointed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A common issue also lurked behind the arguments over the files
and the IMF: a German perception of growing U.S. arrogance because
the United States is now the only superpower. Many Germans also
believe that America is finding it difficult to adjust to a Germany
that feels free of its historical complexes and ready to flex more
political muscle.
</P>
<P>
   The handover came as Germany debates whether information
gathered by the Stasi on Helmut Kohl should be used to try to
identify the donors who gave money to the former chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has insisted that records of telephone conversations with
aides that were tapped by East German spies while he was chancellor
should not be used either in the criminal investigation or
parliamentary inquiry against him. Kohl has admitted breaking the
law by accepting more than $1 million in secret campaign donations,
but has refused to say who gave him the money.
</P>
<P>
   (js)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
