<HEADER>
A7854 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-BOOKRISOTTO-SFCHRON &LR;      04-05 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKRISOTTO-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 COOK'S BOOKS: This Is Not Your Nonna's Risotto   By Noel Advincula  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  My love affair with risotto started years ago when
I first tasted it in Italy. Before then, I hadn't really paid much
attention to it. Coming from an Asian background, rice is a staple
that is either steamed or fried. But once I tasted risotto,
characterized by its wonderful blend of Italian rice (Arborio,
vialone or carnaroli) and broth, I became a convert.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Risotto is a classic, straightforward Italian dish that lets the
cook be creative with any number of additions.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of books have been written about risotto, but ``Risotto:
Over 120 Healthy and Delicious ``Little Rice'' Recipes'' is one to
have in the kitchen if you are an adventurer. The cover sets the
tone for the book, with recipes liberally illustrated with
intriguing photos.
</P>
<P>
   The authors, Jenny Stacey and Kathryn Hawkins, begin with basic
cooking techniques and serving suggestions, then launch into
variations, including new ideas for combining the rice and broth.
</P>
<P>
   Recipes like Risotto Rosso, a vibrant red risotto defined by
beets and red wine and served with sour cream and chives, is not
only eye-catching but features exciting juxtapositions of sweet and
sour flavors. It makes an excellent appetizer.
</P>
<P>
   Thai Coconut Risotto _ a fusion East-meets-West dish _ is
another winner because the Asian flavors work so well with the
risotto's texture, proving again just how flexible this ``little
rice'' can be.
</P>
<P>
   However, in stretching risotto's boundaries the authors
occasionally go too far. A dessert Tiramisu Risotto featured
unbalanced flavors _ too much chocolate and not enough sugar _ and
poor consistency. But this lapse is more than made up for by the
other imaginative recipes in the collection.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Risotto: Over 120 Healthy and Delicious ``Little Rice'' &LR; 
 &LR; Recipes,'' by Jenny Stacey and Kathryn Hawkins (Firefly Books, &LR; 
 &LR; 144 pages softcover, $19.95). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RISOTTO ROSSO
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   5 cups vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 medium-size red onions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   4 medium-size beets, peeled and shredded or coarsely grated
</P>
<P>
   2 cups coarsely grated carrot
</P>
<P>
   2 cups Arborio rice
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup red wine
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Snipped fresh chives to garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Pour the stock into a saucepan and bring to a boil. Reduce the
heat to a gentle simmer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, melt the butter with the oil in a large saucepan and
gently fry the onions, beets and carrot for 10 minutes, until just
beginning to soften. Add the rice and cook, stirring for 2 minutes
until well coated in the vegetable mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Add the red wine and cook gently, stirring until absorbed. Ladle
in the stock gradually over moderate heat until all the liquid is
absorbed and the rice is thick, creamy and tender. This will take
about 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add seasoning to taste. Serve immediately, topped with sour
cream and sprinkled with chives.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8 as a first course.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 250 calories, &LR;   &LR; 5 g protein, 44 g carbohydrate,
6 &LR;   &LR; g fat (2 g saturated), 8 mg cholesterol, 78 mg sodium, 5 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; THAI COCONUT RISOTTO
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   33/4 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces boneless skinned chicken, shredded
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped lemongrass
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon turmeric
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   2 cups Arborio rice
</P>
<P>
   2 red chiles, seeded and sliced
</P>
<P>
   11/4 cups coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Pour the stock into a saucepan and bring to a boil. Reduce the
heat to a gentle simmer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, melt the butter in a large skillet and cook the
chicken gently for 2 to 3 minutes, until sealed. Add the onion,
garlic, lemongrass, coriander, cumin, turmeric and chili powder;
cook, stirring for 2 minutes. Add the rice and cook, stirring, for
a further 2 minutes, until the rice is well coated in butter.
</P>
<P>
   Add a ladleful of stock and cook gently, stirring, until the
liquid has been absorbed. Continue adding small quantities of stock
until half of the stock is used and the rice is creamy. Stir in the
chiles.
</P>
<P>
   Mix the coconut milk into the stock and continue adding until
the risotto is thick but not sticky, about 25 minutes. Stir in the
cilantro and serve in a warm bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8 as a first course.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 335 calories, &LR;   &LR; 14 g protein, 38 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 15 g fat (10 g saturated), 36 mg cholesterol, 80 mg
sodium, 3 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1505EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
