<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7855 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-POTPOURRI-SFCHRON &LR;      04-05 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine and spirit topics. 
 
 WINE POTPOURRI: New Gin Gives Sapphire a Run for Its Money   By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Spirits sales have been in a slump for years, even
decades by some estimates. The main reason is the American lighter
diet and healthier lifestyle. An increasing number of people who
used to enjoy a Manhattan or a martini before dinner, switched to
white wine. The only vigor in spirits sales was with white goods,
like gin and vodka, presumably because of their mixability and the
assumption that white spirits were lighter than brown spirits.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most market watchers estimate that flavored vodkas, like Absolut
and Stolichnaya, saved the day for white spirits sales. Americans
love variety and plain old neutral vodka just wasn't satisfying
anymore. Gin, on the other hand, already offered the flavor of
juniper berry, citrus and coriander, although it was precisely that
distinctive perfume and flavor that turned many people off from
gin.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike vodka, gin was available in a number of different
styles, mainly London Dry, Genever and Plymouth. There also were a
few flavored gins, like Malacca from Tanqueray and the French
Citadelle, both variations on the traditional juniper-citrus flavor
profile of most popular gins.
</P>
<P>
   London Dry, the best-known type of gin, is mostly made and
bottled in Britain, although American gins, like Gilbey's and
Burnett's, are made in the London Dry juniper-flavored style.
Genever gins, from Holland, like Bols, Leyden and Van Gough, are
more flavorful than London Dry. Genever gin is made with malted
barley and sometimes aged in barrels before bottling. Plymouth gin,
historically associated with the British Navy and the port of
Plymouth, England, is softer than London Dry, with a sweet
impression in the finish.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, in a bid to satisfy the American market demand
for variety and distinctive flavor, gin distillers worldwide began
adding ultra-premium gins to their lines. Bombay drinkers soon had
Bombay Sapphire to savor. Other upscale gins like Corney&AMP;Barrow,
Boodles, Tanqueray and Daresbury's, entered the market. Now
Tanqueray has a new ultra-premium gin called No. Ten.
</P>
<P>
   Martini lovers swear that a Bombay Sapphire Martini is better by
far than one made with standard Bombay gin. A ``call'' mixed drink
is more expensive than one mixed with gin from the bar well, and
the flavor will be more assertive. Tanqueray, for instance, uses
more citrus in the recipe of No. Ten than in the regular Tanqueray.
</P>
<P>
   For No. Ten, Tanqueray prefers hand-picked whole fresh fruit and
botanicals and small copper pot stills for the distillation. Most
gin, except for some Genever, is made in large continuous stills,
providing a lighter less flavorful spirit than that produced in a
pot still.
</P>
<P>
   Tanqueray No. Ten has a fresh up-front aroma of grapefruit rind,
herbs and sweet spices. The nicely textured flavors are more citrus
with juniper berry back notes and a hint of chamomile and
coriander. Available in 750 ml ($24.99) or one-liter ($30.99)
bottles, Tanqueray No. Ten is packaged in a handsome slender
faceted green bottle with a silver cap and a distinctive red seal.
Next time you're thirsting for a stylish martini, make it with
Tanqueray No. Ten. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; A Real Millennium Bug &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 grape harvest in Australia will be leaner than
previously expected because of heavy rains and high humidity in the
eastern wine districts. According to the Australian Wine and Brandy
Corporation, floods, unseasonably hot weather, followed by
unseasonably cold weather, are likely to drop wine grape yields
below last year's 1.1 million tons. Officials say, however, that
one bad vintage probably will not affect shipments from the world's
fastest-growing wine exporter. The United States is one of
Australia's largest wine export markets.
</P>
<P>
   As if the heavy rains and flooding weren't enough grief for
Australia's winemakers, locusts hatched in the country's flooded
desert plains, then began spreading through the wine regions of
Southern Australia and parts of New South Wales.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; eBay vs. Lazy Creek &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The online auction house, eBay, has picked up a nice wine item _
Lazy Creek Vineyards in the remote reaches of Mendocino's Anderson
Valley. Lazy Creek owners, Josh and Mary Beth Chandler, told
Winetoday.com they offered 35 percent of the winery on eBay for a
minimum bid of $600,000. The 10-day auction ended March 25, but
Mary Beth Chandler said the online auction didn't produce the
results they wanted. Instead, Chandler said they attracted a
prospective partner through a story that appeared in the Santa Rosa
Press Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hard to Win for Losing &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, an item ran in Potpourri about Mendocino's
Greenwood Ridge claiming to have the first wine of 2000. Local wine
consultant Rebecca Chapa alerted me to an article in the British
wine magazine Decanter about Genesis Chardonnay 2000, made by noted
Australian viticulturist, Richard Smart, from a small vineyard in
New South Wales. Smart originally was going to call his Millennium
wine ``First Light,'' but the name already was taken by New Zealand
winemaker Phil Parker for his Firstlight Red. I should have known a
Southern Hemisphere winery would be first with the millennium
claim.
</P>
<P>
   Another message arrived by e-mail from a reader who scolded me
for a statement I made about Chardonnay lacking the inspiration to
encourage the drinker to have a second glass. The reader's
contention is ``since women are bombarded daily by magazines,
papers, radio and TV programs with the warning they should limit
their alcohol intake to no more than one drink a day, the net
effect of your remark was indeed insensitive to your female
readers.''
</P>
<P>
   My reference to having a second glass of wine is a way of saying
the wine is enjoyable, not an encouragement to overindulge. The
Wine Page encourages moderation and the enjoyment of fine wine and
spirits with food. Lighten up, folks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1506EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
