A7856 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-CLASSIC-SFCHRON &LR;      04-05 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSIC-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Bay Area Classics profiles food-related businesses
more than a half century old. 
 
 BAY AREA CLASSICS: Louis' Serves Up Eggs, Hash Browns and a View 
 on the Side   By Lynne Bennett  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Strolling on Ocean Beach in the bracing salt air
can make you hungry. In the area's heyday, in 1937, you could also
have built up an appetite ice skating at Sutro Baths. Afterwards,
you might have grabbed a hot dog, hamburger or a bowl of chili from
a tiny diner and take-out counter called Louis', just up the hill
from the Cliff House on Point Lobos Avenue.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now, that 10-stool little eatery has grown to a regular
restaurant with commanding views of Seal Rock and the ruins of
Sutro Baths, but it is still run by the same family that founded
it. Third-generation owners Tom and Bill Hontalas now have a
55-seat restaurant and employ a staff of 20.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1900s, there were several small restaurants on this
stretch of beach, and more than half of them were owned by Greek
immigrants like the Hontalas clan.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Hontalas was 11 years old when he arrived in San Francisco
in 1906 to join an older brother, who was one of those
restaurateurs. By 1937, with a growing family of his own, Louis and
his wife, Helen, started their own restaurant, opening on
Valentine's Day.
</P>
<P>
   They might have been encouraged by a boom in the area's
businesses the previous year when the freighter Ohioan ran aground
just off the point. It took more than a week to raise and salvage
the ship, a spectacle that attracted throngs of sightseers. These
``looky-loos,'' as they were called, were willing to pay nearby
restaurants 50 cents for the usual nickel cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   In the next decade, World War II also proved lucrative for beach
businesses, with servicemen comprising a large part of the
clientele. By the late '50s, when the family's second son, Jim, had
taken over, cooking alongside his mother, Helen, the main business
was on weekends and during the summers. But by the mid-'70s, after
the area around Sutro Baths had become part of the Golden Gate
National Recreation Area, year-round sightseeing buses started to
make regular stops at the ruins of the Sutro Baths, which
encouraged the Hontalases to remodel and expand.
</P>
<P>
   Louis' is now a concessionaire of the National Park Service,
just like the nearby Cliff House, owned and operated by distant
cousins of the Hontalases.
</P>
<P>
   Current Louis' operators Tom and Bill Hontalas started working
at the restaurant as youngsters in the '60s. ``We worked for 50
cents an hour washing dishes,'' Tom reminisces. The tradition is
likely to continue since the fourth generation has already started
to help out. Some older family members have been on the staff over
20 years, including Tom's wife, sister and sister-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Louis' is no longer primarily a tourist stop. Locals
provide the base of the business, with 60 percent of sales coming
from breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   While many diners have become increasingly health-conscious,
there are still those regulars who come in and order their four
scrambled eggs and toast. That's still on the menu, as well as the
other egg dishes, sandiwiches, hamburgers, fries and steaks that
have been served at Louis' for over 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Louis' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 902 Point Lobos Ave. (Great Highway), San Francisco; (415) &LR; 
 &LR; 387-6330 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Open weekdays 6:30 a.m.-4:30 p.m.; weekends 6:30 a.m.-6 p.m. &LR; 
 &LR; In the summer, open until 8 p.m. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
