 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Panel Puts the Bite on Anise Biscotti   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Biscotti _ twice-baked Italian cookies _ used to
be hard to find. Now they're mainstream enough to be on most
grocers' shelves.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted six anise-flavored biscotti, one of the
most popular flavors of the crunchy cookies. They tasted only those
available at supermarkets, not bakeries.
</P>
<P>
   The panel noticed big differences in texture and flavor. Prices
also varied widely, from $2.99 for a 12.4-ounce package to $6.99
for a 10-ounce package.
</P>
<P>
   Top honors went to  &UR; Splendido &LR;  (eight ounces, $6.29 at Whole
Foods), one of the more expensive brands. Three panelists thought
the hard texture of the cookie made it especially good for dunking.
One described the flavor as boring, but others thought it was good
overall. Three would buy it; two might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; San Anselmo's &LR;  (12.4 ounces, $2.99 at
Andronico's). It was the least costly cookie tasted. The panel
agreed that the anise flavor was too strong, but they loved the
toasty almonds and the crisp texture. Two would buy it; three might
buy it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Safeway Select &LR;  (5.5 ounces, $3.39 at Safeway) came in third.
Two panelists claimed it was good as a cookie, but not very much
like a traditional biscotti. It ``looks and tastes like a
mass-market American version of biscotti,'' one said. Two others
described the flavor as overprocessed and chemical. Two would buy
it, one might buy it, and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; La Biscotteria &LR;  (10 ounces, $6.99 at Andronico's) came in
fourth. Some panelists appreciated the tender texture, but two felt
it was bready and more like a dry biscuit than a biscotti. Two
thought the flavor was too light, but another described the
flavorings as too strong. One would buy it, one might buy it, and
three would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth place went to  &UR; Allegria &LR;  (8 ounces, $5.79 at Andronico's).
The tasters all thought this cookie was much too hard, although
some thought it would be good for dunking in coffee. Three
panelists also disliked the overly sweet flavor. Two might buy it;
three would not.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tried Pamela's but it scored too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were Flo Braker, cookbook author and Chronicle Food
columnist; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Donna Katzl,
chef-owner, Cafe For All Seasons, San Francisco; Kim Severson,
Chronicle staff writer; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San
Francisco. All products are tasted blind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1507EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
