<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here's a plan for getting quick meals on the table in
a hurry. Now &AMP; Later is a recipe cooked on the weekend in batches _
enough to serve 12 _ and functions as dinner on the night it's
prepared; freeze the rest for two future meals. The 30-Minute Main
Dish takes a half-hour or less of preparation and Fast &AMP; Fresh
gives you dinner in about 20 minutes. 
 
 THE WORKING COOK: Simple, Soothing Meals Get Spring off to a 
 Great Start   By Tara Duggan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  When Food Section intern Noel Advincula presented
us with his version of Filipino rice porridge, we were expecting
something like Chinese congee _ a milky white, mildly flavored soup
with a somewhat glutinous consistency.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Instead, the porridge, which is called  &LR; Arroz Caldo &LR;  or  &LR; Lugaw &LR; 
in the Philippines, featured whole, soft, kernels of rice suspended
in a fragrant golden-yellow broth. Like Chinese congee, the soup is
soothing and warm as it goes down, but generous amounts of ginger,
fish sauce and lemon juice fill it with exotic Southeast Asian
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Noel remembers eating it as a  &LR; merienda &LR; , or afternoon snack, in
the Philippines and says it also is popular for breakfast. He
recommends it for cool Bay Area evenings.
</P>
<P>
   Another soothing dish is this week's Now &AMP; Later recipe, Chicken
Goulash, a paprika-scented Hungarian stew. Though paprika is a
spice that Americans tend use just for color atop deviled eggs, it
has a distinctive, earthy flavor _ but only if it hasn't been
sitting on the shelf for ages. For dishes like this where the spice
features prominently, it's important to use a fresh box of imported
paprika.
</P>
<P>
   This week's Fast &AMP; Fresh recipe, Flank Steak with Grilled Spring
Onions and Arugula, is a nice way to welcome in the good weather.
If you don't want to take the barbecue out of hibernation, use a
grill pan or just put the steak under the broiler.
</P>
<P>
   The browned onions and warm steak soften the blue cheese and
lightly wilt the arugula, which is dressed in sherry vinegar and
walnut oil. Although green onions work fine, try to seek out spring
onions at a farmers' market or organic food stores. The fresh baby
onions, which look like leeks but with a white or red bulbous end,
have an incredible sweetness that comes out especially when they
are caramelized in a grill pan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FAST &AMP; FRESH: dinner in about 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   FLANK STEAK WITH GRILLED SPRING ONIONS &AMP; ARUGULA
</P>
<P>
   This recipe calls for using a grill pan. If you don't have one,
you may use a barbecue grill or your broiler instead.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1-pound flank steak, in 1 piece
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 spring onions (or 6 green onions)
</P>
<P>
   11/2 bunches arugula
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup walnut oil, or extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup crumbled blue cheese
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have a grill pan, either prepare a fire in a
barbecue grill or preheat the oven to broil.
</P>
<P>
   Mince the garlic. Rub the steak with the garlic and season
liberally on both sides with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Chop the spring onions on the bias into 1/4-inch pieces. (If
using green onions, slice into 2-inch lengths.)
</P>
<P>
   Trim the arugula and chop roughly in half. Place in a large
salad bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a seasoned grill pan over medium-high heat. Place the steak
in the middle of the pan. Grill for 5 minutes, then turn and grill
another 5 minutes for medium rare.
</P>
<P>
   (If using a broiler, place the steak and onions on an oiled
baking sheet directly under the broiler. Broil for 5 minutes. Turn
once and broil an additional 5 minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   While the steak cooks, whisk together the vinegar and mustard;
season with salt and pepper. Whisk in the walnut oil.
</P>
<P>
   When the steak is done, remove it from the heat and let rest at
least 5 minutes. Add the spring onions to the pan and let brown
undisturbed about 1 minute per side. Remove and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, toss enough of the salad dressing with the arugula to
just coat the leaves; there may be extra dressing. Slice the meat
thinly against the grain into bite-size strips. Portion the arugula
onto serving plates, and fan out the meat slices on top. Garnish
each serving with crumbled blue cheese and the grilled onions.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 500 calories, &LR;   &LR; 27 g protein, 4 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 42 g fat (10 g saturated), 67 mg cholesterol, 297 mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
30-MINUTE MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   ARROZ CALDO (FILIPINO RICE PORRIDGE)
</P>
<P>
   This recipe was created by Food Section intern Noel Advincula.
Discard the slices of ginger before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 yellow onion
</P>
<P>
   2-inch knob fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 skinless boneless chicken half-breasts
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Asian fish sauce + more to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup long-grain white rice
</P>
<P>
   5 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   Pinch saffron (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, in their shells
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch scallions
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Chop the garlic and the onion. Peel the ginger and slice it into
coins. Cut the chicken into bite-size chunks.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large heavy pot. Add the garlic, onion and
ginger and saute until the onion is soft, about 2 minutes. Add the
chicken and saute briefly, about 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   Add the fish sauce, rice, broth, pepper and optional saffron and
stir well. Bring to a boil, then add the whole eggs to the pot and
boil in their shells for 8 minutes. Stir occasionally to make sure
the rice doesn't stick to the bottom of the pot.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the eggs from the pot; set aside. Continue simmering the
porridge until the rice is fully cooked, about 12 minutes longer.
(The porridge should be quite thick, but if you like, thin it with
a little water.) Taste, and add more fish sauce, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Chop the scallions. Peel the eggs and cut them in half.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, ladle the porridge into serving bowls and top each
with chopped scallions, a hard-cooked egg half and a big squeeze of
lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 430 calories, &LR;   &LR; 25 g protein, 46 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 14 g fat (2 g saturated), 141 mg cholesterol, 892
mg sodium, 2 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NOW &AMP; LATER: dinner this week &AMP; 2 for the freezer
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN GOULASH
</P>
<P>
   This goulash calls for sweet paprika, not hot, which gives it a
mild but sweet flavor. If you'd like more of a kick, add a teaspoon
of red pepper flakes with the paprika. Serve over buttered egg
noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   24 chicken drumsticks and thighs
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   4 onions, sliced into rounds
</P>
<P>
   6 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons high quality sweet paprika
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   6 Roma tomatoes, peeled, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 red bell peppers, deribbed and chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 green bell peppers, deribbed and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch chives, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Sour cream or creme fraiche
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Season the chicken with salt and pepper. Heat enough oil in a
large heavy pot to cover the bottom of the pot. Brown the chicken
in batches, being careful not to crowd it in the pot. Add more oil
as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the chicken from the pot and drain off all but 2
tablespoons oil. Add the onions and garlic to the pot and saute
over medium-high heat until browned, about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the paprika and bay leaf. Moisten with a bit of water to
prevent burning and saute for 10 minutes, stirring frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Return the chicken to the pot, then add the tomatoes and bell
peppers and just barely enough water to cover them. (The vegetables
will release a lot of liquid.) Season with salt and pepper and stir
together. Bring to a steady simmer. Simmer, stirring occasionally,
until the chicken is tender and the sauce has reduced, about 45
minutes. Taste, and adjust seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   Ladle the goulash over buttered egg noodles and garnish with
chives. Pass a bowl of sour cream or creme fraiche at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 400 calories, &LR;   &LR; 32 g protein, 9 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 26 g fat (6 g saturated), 138 mg cholesterol, 139 mg sodium, 2 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1508EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
