<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-FISH-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Marimba's Snappy Fish: Arbol chiles and limes 
 combine to create a bold dish   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  It may be surprising to learn that some of the
best fish in the Bay Area can be found at Cafe Marimba, a casual
Mexican restaurant in the Marina.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Started by Reed Hearon and Louise Clement, the restaurant
specializes in the coastal cuisine of Mexico, with dishes like Sea
Bass with Garlic, Chile Arbol and Lime.
</P>
<P>
   The pairing of the sea bass with the smoky chiles is phenomenal.
In preparing the dish, a puree of arbol chiles _ a type of dried
chile widely available at specialty food stores and ethnic markets
_ is seared into the white-fleshed fish. The fish comes out of the
frying pan spicy hot. It's served with a wedge of lime, which helps
tame the fire.
</P>
<P>
   If you have trouble finding Chilean sea bass, Pacific red
snapper or any other tender white fish will work just as well.
</P>
<P>
   At Cafe Marimba, which is now owned solely by Clement, the food
is as bright as the decor, awash in primary colors and Mexican folk
art.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Cafe Marimba, 2317 Chestnut St. (between Scott and Divisadero &LR; 
 &LR; Streets), San Francisco; (415) 776-1506. Lunch Tuesday-Sunday, &LR; 
 &LR; dinner nightly, brunch weekends. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Searing the fish. &LR;  The spicy arbol chile puree is seared
right into the fish, giving the fish a crusty exterior.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ The lime. &LR;  Don't consider this simply a garnish; it helps to
balance and tame the heat of the chiles.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SEA BASS WITH GARLIC, CHILE ARBOL &AMP; LIME
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds Chilean sea bass, cut into 6 portions
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Arbol Chile Puree (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   6 arbol chiles for garnish
</P>
<P>
   6 cilantro sprigs for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1 lime, cut into 6 wedges
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Pour the oil onto a dinner plate with a rim and season
generously with salt and pepper. Dip each piece of fish into the
oil mixture and turn to liberally coat.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a large heavy-bottom saute pan over high heat. Working in
batches, place the fish in the pan. Top each fillet with 1 teaspoon
Arbol Chile Puree. Cook until golden brown, about 5 minutes. Turn
the fish and spread 1 teaspoon of the Arbol Chile Puree on the
cooked side. Continue to cook until the fish just loses the
translucent center, about 3 to 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the fish to plates. Garnish with dried arbol chiles,
cilantro and lime.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  Although not called for in the recipe, I've found you
can make a sauce from what's left in the pan. It's great with the
fish or drizzled over rice. After the fish has been cooked, add
about 1/2 cup water to the pan (or use reserved chile-soaking water
from the Arbol Chile Puree). Bring to a boil, scraping up all the
browned bits on the bottom of the pan. Boil until reduced by half,
then add another 1/4 cup water. Boil a minute longer. Spoon the
sauce over each serving.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 205 calories, &LR;   &LR; 26 g protein, 0 carbohydrate,
10 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 104 mg cholesterol, 180 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ARBOL CHILE PUREE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry arbol chiles (see note)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups hot water
</P>
<P>
   4 large garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Place a large saute pan over high heat. When hot, add the chiles
and toast until fragrant about 1 to 2 minutes, turning from time to
time. Transfer the chiles to a large bowl. Pour the hot water over
them and let soak until tender, about 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Drain, reserving the soaking water. Place the chiles, garlic and
1/4 cup of the chile-soaking water in a blender and puree until
smooth. Add more chile-soaking water if necessary to create a
smooth puree. Strain. Season with salt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; Arbol chiles are available at specialty food stores,
ethnic markets and in some supermarkets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1509EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
