<SLUG> BC-GRAINS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 GLORIOUS GRAINS: They're good for you, great tasting and  versatile
as the dickens   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Grains get a bad rap. Those who fear a health
conscious world balk at the idea of whole-grain anything, fearing
it will taste like those unfortunate faux meats and vegetarian
casseroles of the '70s.
 &HT;    Grains also suffer from followers of Dr. Atkins, the Sugar
Busters and other low-carb advocates who believe that carbohydrates
are taboo because they make us fat.
 &HT;    It's a shame to demonize grains because there is nothing in the
world of ingredients that's as versatile. They cross cultures as
well as courses, adding texture and flavor to a variety of dishes.
 &HT;    Because grains generally grow easily and inexpensively, most
cuisines have at least one grain that's a staple. Rice, for
example, is a staple for half the world's population. It's critical
to Asian, South American and some European cuisines.
 &HT;    Wheat is second to rice, used abundantly in American baking, but
also prevalent in the form of cracked wheat or bulgur in Middle
Eastern cooking.
 &HT;    Grains aren't limited to side dishes or meatless main courses,
either. Risotto, made with arborio rice, can be made into
sophisticated little patties for appetizers at a formal dinner
party or as part of a brunch buffet. Wheat berries can be cooked up
and served with fresh ricotta cheese and honey for brunch or
dessert. Even barley, used as animal feed in much of the world,
adds hearty texture to soups and stews.
 &HT;    Grains are as varied in flavor and texture as they are in uses.
Some, like millet or Arborio rice, are relatively bland so they
absorb other flavors in the dish. Others, like quinoa and kasha,
have strong nutty flavors and dominate the tastes of other
ingredients.
 &HT;    And truth be told, grains really are some of the most nutritious
foods around. Most offer complex carbohydrates, are low in fat and
are a good source of fiber. But if you're into a high protein,
low-carbohydrate diet, there are grains that fit that category,
too. Quinoa, for example, is considered a complete protein because
it's made up of eight amino acids. It's also lower in carbohydrates
than most other grains. Millet, a popular grain in African cooking,
is also high in protein.
 &HT;    So if you've fallen victim to the whole-grain scare, whip up
some of the recipes inside. They're sure to make you a convert.
 &HT;     
 A CONCISE GUIDE TO THE GRANARY  
 
By Robin Davis and Margarita Camacho 
c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Here's a list of some of our favorite grains and how to cook them.
<P>
   ARBORIO RICE
</P>
<P>
   This high-starch rice is shorter and fatter than any other rice.
It's used primarily in risotto because the starchiness gives the
Italian rice dish its creamy quality.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ To cook: &LR;  Gradually add liquid to the rice, stirring
constantly, and follow a recipe. One cup of rice will absorb
approximately 4 cups of liquid, and takes about 20-25 minutes to
cook. One cup raw rice yields about 3 cups cooked.
</P>
<P>
   BARLEY
</P>
<P>
   This round, ivory colored grain dates back to the Stone Age.
Today, much of it is used for animal feed or is malted to make beer
or whisky. Pearl barley has the husk and bran removed and has been
steamed and polished. Hulled or whole-grain barley has just the
outer hull removed and is more nutritious but not as easily
available.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ To cook: &LR;  Cook 1 cup of barley in 3 cups boiling water,
uncovered, until tender but still firm to the bite, about 40-50
minutes. Drain any excess liquid. One cup raw barley yields about 3
cups cooked.
</P>
<P>
   BULGUR
</P>
<P>
   Also called cracked wheat, bulgur is a staple of Middle Eastern
cooking. Bulgur is the whole kernel of wheat that has been steamed,
dried and crushed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ To cook: &LR;  Pour 2 cups boiling water over 1 cup of bulgur,
cover and let stand until the liquid is absorbed, about 30 minutes.
Uncover and fluff with a fork.
</P>
<P>
   For a slightly more tender grain, cook 1 cup of bulgur in 21/2
cups of water for 15 minutes. Cover the pan, remove it from the
heat and let it steam for 10 minutes until all the liquid is
absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   One cup of uncooked bulgur yields about 23/4 cups cooked.
</P>
<P>
   KASHA
</P>
<P>
   In this country, kasha refers to toasted buckwheat groats. In
Russia, it means any cooked grain. Don't confuse kasha with kashi,
a cereal mixture available at some health food stores.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ To cook: &LR;  The traditional method starts with dry-toasting 1
cup of kasha with 1 beaten egg in a skillet over medium heat,
stirring with a fork until the mixture is dry. This step keeps the
grains from sticking together, but it isn't necessary. Cook 1 cup
of kasha in 21/2 cups boiling liquid, covered, for about 20
minutes, until all the liquid is absorbed. Fluff with a fork. One
cup of uncooked kasha yields about 21/2-3 cups cooked.
</P>
<P>
   MILLET
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, millet is cultivated almost exclusively
for bird and animal feed, but serves as a food staple for about a
third of the world, including much of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ To cook: &LR;  Use 3 cups of liquid for every 1 cup of millet.
Cook, uncovered, in simmering water until the water is absorbed and
the grains are tender, about 25 minutes. One cup of uncooked millet
yields about 3 cups cooked.
</P>
<P>
   QUINOA
</P>
<P>
   Many people consider this a ``super grain'' because it's so high
in protein. It was a staple for the Incas in Peru, but is fairly
new to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ To cook: &LR;  Rinse the grains before cooking. Simmer 1 cup of
quinoa, uncovered, in 3 cups of liquid until the grains are tender
and the liquid is absorbed, about 30 minutes. One cup of uncooked
quinoa yields about 3 cups cooked.
</P>
<P>
   WHEAT BERRIES
</P>
<P>
   These are whole, unprocessed wheat kernels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ To cook: &LR;  Soak wheat berries in water overnight. Drain, then
cook 1 cup of wheat berries, uncovered, in 3 cups of simmering
liquid until tender, about 1 hour. Drain any excess liquid. One cup
of uncooked wheat berries yields about 3 cups cooked.
</P>
<P>
   WILD RICE
</P>
<P>
   This nutty, chewy grain isn't a rice at all but rather a marsh
grass indigenous to the Great Lakes region. Now it's cultivated in
many parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ To cook: &LR;  Cook the rice, uncovered, in plenty of boiling
water until most of the grains split, about 45 minutes. Drain
before serving. One cup of uncooked wild rice yields about 4 cups
cooked.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Most grains are available packaged at many supermarkets. &LR; 
 &LR; Whole Foods, Rainbow Grocery, Draeger's and Berkeley Bowl also &LR; 
 &LR; sell them in bulk. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ASIAN-SPICED BEEF BARLEY SOUP
</P>
<P>
   This soup is so thick and rich, it should be eaten as a main
course.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds oxtails
</P>
<P>
   2 onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 carrots, diced
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons canned tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   8 cups canned beef broth
</P>
<P>
   7 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce dried shiitake mushrooms, snipped into slices
</P>
<P>
   2 whole star anise
</P>
<P>
   2 whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   One 1-inch piece fresh ginger, cut into 4 slices
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups pearl barley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Thinly sliced green onions for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a heavy large pot over medium-high heat. Add the
oxtails and brown well on all sides. Using tongs, transfer the
oxtails to a platter.
</P>
<P>
   Saute the onions and carrots in the pan drippings over
medium-high heat until the onions are translucent, about 5 minutes.
Add the garlic and stir 2 minutes. Add the tomato paste and pepper
flakes and stir 2 minutes. Add the broth, water and shiitake
mushrooms. Return the oxtails to the pot. Tie the star anise,
cloves and ginger in a small piece of cheesecloth and add to the
pot.
</P>
<P>
   Bring to a boil. Reduce heat and simmer 1 hour. Stir in the
barley and simmer until the meat and barley are tender, about 1
hour longer. Remove from heat. Remove and discard the spice
package.
</P>
<P>
   Using tongs, transfer the oxtails to a cutting board. When cool
enough to handle, remove the meat from the bones. Discard the
bones. Stir the meat into the soup. Season to taste with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Rewarm the soup, if necessary. Ladle into bowls. Sprinkle with
green onions.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 400 calories, &LR;   &LR; 36 g protein, 41 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 10 g fat (3 g saturated), 63 mg cholesterol, 67 mg
sodium, 8 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; WHEAT BERRIES WITH RICOTTA, ALMONDS &AMP; HONEY
</P>
<P>
   This dish was inspired by a similar Sicilian recipe in Lynne
Rosetto Kasper's ``The Italian Country Table'' (Scribner, 1999).
Serve it warm or at room temperature for breakfast or brunch. It's
wonderful topped with sliced strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup wheat berries
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 whole cinnamon sticks, broken in half
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups whole-milk ricotta cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coarsely chopped toasted almonds
</P>
<P>
   Honey to taste
</P>
<P>
   Ground cinnamon to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the wheat berries in a bowl and pour in water to cover
them by 2 inches. Let soak overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the wheat berries and transfer to a heavy saucepan. Add 3
cups water, the brown sugar, cinnamon sticks and salt. Simmer until
the berries are tender, about 1 hour. Drain any excess liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the berries to a large bowl. Cool slightly, then stir
in the ricotta and almonds. Sweeten with honey; sprinkle with
cinnamon.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 345 calories, &LR;   &LR; 16 g protein, 26 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 31 g fat (9 g saturated), 47 mg cholesterol, 351 mg
sodium, 5 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; WILD RICE &AMP; HERB BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Be sure the rice is very well cooked. All of the kernels should
have split open.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup wild rice
</P>
<P>
   21/2 cups warm water (105 degrees-115 degrees)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1 envelope active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   3 cups whole-wheat flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup soy milk powder, or nonfat dry milk powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup wheat germ
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh sage, or 2 teaspoons dried ground
sage
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh rosemary, or 11/2 teaspoons dried
rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   3 cups (about) bread flour
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg beaten with 2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   Fresh sage leaves for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Cook the rice in a small pot of boiling salted water until very
tender, about 50 minutes. Drain. Cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   Stir together the warm water and honey in the large bowl of an
electric mixer fitted with a dough hook. Sprinkle the yeast over.
Let stand until foamy, about 10 minutes. Add the rice, whole-wheat
flour, dry milk, wheat germ, herbs, oil and salt. Mix until well
blended. Gradually mix in enough bread flour to form a stiff dough.
It should not be too sticky. Cover the dough with plastic wrap and
let rest for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Turn out the dough on a floured surface. Knead until the dough
is smooth and elastic, kneading in more flour if necessary, about
10 minutes. Oil a large bowl. Add the dough, turning to coat. Cover
the bowl with plastic wrap. Let rise in a warm area until doubled
in volume, about 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Line a large baking sheet with parchment paper. Punch down the
dough. Turn out onto a lightly floured surface. Knead briefly.
Divide the dough into two equal pieces. Form each piece into a
12x3-inch loaf. Transfer the loaves to the prepared baking sheet.
Cut slits diagonally just through the top of the dough for
decoration. Cover with a clean kitchen towel. Let rise in a warm
area until almost doubled in volume, about 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Brush the loaves generously with the egg mixture. Press the sage
leaves onto the loaves.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until the bread is golden brown and a tester inserted into
the center comes out clean, about 35 minutes. Transfer the loaves
to racks and cool.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 2 loaves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SLICE: &LR;   &LR; 115 calories, &LR;   &LR; 4 g protein, 20 g carbohydrate, 2
g &LR;   &LR; fat (0 saturated), 6 mg cholesterol, 191 mg sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; MILLET &AMP; KALE GRATIN
</P>
<P>
   Just about any hearty green will work in this recipe, which can
be a meatless main course or a side dish for roast chicken or fish.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt + additional for seasoning
</P>
<P>
   1 cup millet
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds kale (about 2 bunches), stemmed, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Nonstick vegetable oil spray
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups grated Fontina cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups fresh breadcrumbs
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup freshly grated Romano cheese
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the water and salt in a heavy small saucepan. Bring to a
boil. Add the millet and boil until tender, stirring frequently to
prevent sticking, about 30 minutes. Transfer to a large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a heavy large skillet over medium-high heat. Add
the shallots and saute until translucent, about 5 minutes. Add the
garlic and saute 2 minutes. Working in batches, add the kale and
saute until just wilted, about 5 minutes per batch. When each batch
is cooked, transfer to the bowl with millet. Stir the kale into the
millet. Season generously with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Spray a 11/2-quart baking dish with nonstick vegetable oil
spray. Layer half of the millet mixture into the pan. Sprinkle with
Fontina. Layer in the remaining millet mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a heavy medium skillet over medium heat. Add
the breadcrumbs and stir until just beginning to brown. Spoon the
breadcrumbs over the millet. Sprinkle with Romano cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until the topping is brown and the mixture is bubbling,
about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 as a main course; 6 as a side dish.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING (main course): &LR;   &LR; 530 calories, &LR;   &LR; 22 g protein, 47
g &LR;   &LR; carbohydrate, 30 g fat (14 g saturated), 71 mg cholesterol,
803 &LR;   &LR; mg sodium, 11 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; TUNA-TABBOULEH SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Turn the usual side dish into a main course salad for lunch or a
light supper.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup bulgur wheat
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt + additional for seasoning
</P>
<P>
   1 small red onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cucumber, peeled, seeded and cut into 1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   1 (6-ounce) can albacore tuna packed in water, drained, flaked
into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Freshly grated pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Toasted pita triangles
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the bulgur in a large bowl. Bring the water and salt to a
boil. Pour over the bulgur. Cover and let stand until the water is
completely absorbed, about 30 minutes. Fluff with a fork and let
stand until cool.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the onion, cucumber, parsley, mint, tuna, lemon juice
and oil. Season to taste with salt and pepper. Garnish with pita
triangles.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 300 calories, &LR;   &LR; 18 g protein, 39 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 8 g fat (1 g saturated), 23 mg cholesterol, 687 mg
sodium, 9 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; OVEN-BAKED QUINOA PILAF
</P>
<P>
   Almost any grain can be used for a pilaf. The oven technique
lowers the risk of burning, which can happen on the stove top.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cups canned low-salt chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 cup quinoa, rinsed
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup currants
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup toasted slivered almonds
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a heavy medium saucepan over medium-high
heat. Add the shallot and saute 5 minutes. Add the broth, thyme,
quinoa and currants. Bring to a boil. Cover the pan tightly and
transfer it to the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Cook until the liquid is absorbed and the quinoa is tender,
about 25 minutes. Remove from the oven and let stand, covered, for
5 minutes. Fluff the pilaf with a fork. Transfer to a serving bowl.
Sprinkle with almonds.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 255 calories, &LR;   &LR; 8 g protein, 32 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 12 g fat (3 g saturated), 10 mg cholesterol, 242 mg sodium, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SMOKED SALMON RISOTTO CAKES
</P>
<P>
   You have to make the risotto a day ahead, but the planning is
worth it. These cakes are marvelous for brunch, with a salad for a
light lunch or as an appetizer to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Arborio rice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces smoked salmon, cut into 1/2-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh tarragon
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   All-purpose flour for coating
</P>
<P>
   Creme fraiche or sour cream to garnish
</P>
<P>
   Chopped fresh chives to garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Bring the water to a boil in a small saucepan. Reduce the heat
to very low and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Melt 2 tablespoons of the butter in a heavy medium saucepan over
medium heat. Add the onion and saute until tender but not brown,
about 8 minutes. Add the rice and stir 2 minutes. Add the wine and
boil until the liquid evaporates, stirring constantly. Stir in 1
cup of the hot water. Continue stirring and adding water by 1/4
cupfuls until the rice is tender and the mixture is creamy, about
18 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the smoked salmon and tarragon. Season generously with
salt and lightly with pepper. Cool at room temperature for 1 hour.
Transfer to a bowl. Cover and refrigerate until well chilled, at
least 2 hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the egg in a small bowl to blend. Stir into the risotto.
Shape the risotto into cakes, using 1/4 cupful for each. Arrange on
a baking sheet. Refrigerate at least 1 and up to 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Melt 1 tablespoon of the butter in a heavy large skillet over
medium heat. Place flour in a small bowl. Working in batches, coat
the cakes in flour and add to the skillet. Cook until golden brown,
about 3 minutes per side. Transfer to paper towels to drain. Repeat
with the remaining butter and cakes.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the cakes on a platter. Top each with a dollop of creme
fraiche and sprinkle with chives. Serve warm or at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 12 cakes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CAKE: &LR;   &LR; 115 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 12 g carbohydrate, 6
g &LR;   &LR; fat (3 g saturated), 32 mg cholesterol, 84 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; KASHA &AMP; VEGETABLE CASSEROLE
</P>
<P>
   The nuttiness of kasha makes this dish work best as a meatless
main course, but you also could serve it as a side dish alongside
something hearty like steak.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt + salt for seasoning
</P>
<P>
   1 cup kasha
</P>
<P>
   1 cup small broccoli florets
</P>
<P>
   1 cup small cauliflower florets
</P>
<P>
   1 cup 1/2-inch pieces of carrot
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Nonstick vegetable oil spray
</P>
<P>
   1 cup whole-milk ricotta cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Bring the water and 1 teaspoon salt to a boil in a heavy small
saucepan. Add the kasha. Cover the pan, reduce heat and simmer
until the grains are very tender, about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Steam the broccoli, cauliflower and carrot until crisp-tender,
about 5 minutes. Heat the oil in a heavy large skillet over
medium-high heat. Add the onion and saute 5 minutes. Add the garlic
and stir 2 minutes. Stir in the vegetables and kasha. Season
generously with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Spray a 11/2-quart baking dish
with vegetable oil spray. Whisk together the ricotta, egg and thyme
in small bowl to blend. Stir into the kasha mixture. Spoon the
mixture into the prepared pan. Sprinkle with Parmesan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until the top is golden brown, about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 as a main course; 6 as a side dish.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING (main course): &LR;   &LR; 375 calories, &LR;   &LR; 19 g protein, 42
g &LR;   &LR; carbohydrate, 15 g fat (8 g saturated), 92 mg cholesterol, 820 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 9 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
