<SLUG> BC-NASA-FAILURES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NASA SCIENTIST SAYS MARS PROGRAM TOO AMBITIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. _ Embarrassed by two recent launch
failures, a ranking NASA scientist said the space agency might have
to conserve its resources by developing a less diverse array of
space missions to Mars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have another failure, the (Mars) program may be at its
end,'' researcher Daniel J. McCleese said in an unusually blunt
speech Tuesday at NASA's Ames Research Center in Mountain View.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration has launched an all-out robotic assault on Mars and
tried to develop numerous small, low-cost missions to the red
planet. To illustrate the sheer complexity of NASA's ambitions,
McCleese pointed at a slide projection listing the planned Mars
fleet.
</P>
<P>
   The full-page list includes landers that will explore the alien,
rust-red surface of the planet and rovers that will examine the
chemical composition of rocks and transmit pictures to Earth. Other
proposed craft would:
</P>
<P>
   _ Orbit Mars to monitor weather conditions and survey mineral
resources.
</P>
<P>
   _ Land, scoop up rocks and haul them back to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   _ Land at specific sites to investigate narrowly defined
phenomena.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complexity of the program has got us by the neck. ... Look
at how many vehicles we're trying to develop simultaneously,'' said
McCleese, the chief scientist of the Mars program at Jet Propulsion
Laboratory in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   Given a tight budget and limited staff, it is hard for NASA to
build so many different craft and launch them at the originally
planned schedule, McCleese said. He echoed concerns about NASA's
Mars program expressed by a recent study panel.
</P>
<P>
   One option is for the space agency to narrow its near-term goals
for Mars exploration. ``A focused program is more likely to succeed
than a broad-brush program,'' the scientist said.
</P>
<P>
   In September and December, NASA lost two highly touted probes
launched to Mars. Both disappeared while nearing the planet _ the
first mainly because of space agency teams' failure to convert
between English and metric units, the second for reasons that
remain under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The twin failures have spurred charges, both inside and outside
NASA, that the space agency is trying to do too much too fast, and
with too little money and staff. As a result, NASA administrator
Daniel Goldin is investigating ways to revamp the Mars program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1520EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
