<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITIES-ENVIRONMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BLACK AND BROWN HARD TO COME BY IN THE GREEN OUTDOORS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Note optional trims)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN WECHSLER  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESSEX, N.Y. _ When Yosef Salaam stayed at a cabin in the
Adirondack hamlet of Essex last summer to work on a play, he never
completely relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   When he walked down a country road near this Lake Champlain
vacation community, he would always step into the drainage ditch
when he heard a car behind him _ just in case.
</P>
<P>
   All because his was the only black face in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt very self-conscious,'' said Salaam, a 55-year-old
writer from New York City. ``As a black man, I always keep my
self-preservation on notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the scene around most of the 6 million acres of the
Adirondack Park. The East Coast's largest parcel of wilderness
attracts hundreds of thousands of visitors a year. But when it
comes to diversity, the region could easily be called the ``White
Mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   To an increasing number of people, it is a mystery why the
mountains of northern New York state can remain so racially
one-sided.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is not unique to the Adirondacks.
Environmentalists around the country are increasingly concerned
about the lack of minority involvement in wilderness issues.
</P>
<P>
   Their concern is more than a matter of feeling bad that, for
instance, African-Americans are missing out on Old Faithful or the
Grand Canyon. Many environmentalists think support for their causes
may slip as the populations of blacks, Hispanics and other
minorities increase and more and more minorities land prominent
positions in government and business.
</P>
<P>
   There may come a day when minorities will be in the majority.
And if that majority has no experience with visiting National Parks
and preserving wilderness, what incentive will they have for making
sure these places continue to thrive?
</P>
<P>
   It could happen sooner than you think. In California, according
to U.S. Census Bureau estimates, more than half the state will be a
race other than white by 2025.
</P>
<P>
   Census figures show that the percentage of the overall
population in New York state that is black nearly doubled between
1960 and 1990, from 8.4 percent to 15.9 percent, while the
percentage of the overall population that is white decreased over
the same period from 91.1 percent to 74.4 percent. The trend is
similar nationwide, census data show.
</P>
<P>
   But in the vast Adirondack region of upstate New York, the
minority population has stayed flat in the single digits.
</P>
<P>
   The census also estimates that between 1995 and 2025, the number
of New York state's blacks will increase from 3.2 million to 4
million, while the state's Hispanic population will rise from 2.5
million to 4.3 million. At the same time, whites are projected to
decrease from 14 million to 13.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demographics of the nation are changing,'' said Neil
Woodworth, council to the Adirondack Mountain Club, a group of
33,000 outdoor enthusiasts that is almost entirely white. ``We want
to have an organization that mirrors the demographics.''
</P>
<P>
   So outdoor groups like the Adirondack club are beginning to
question why so few minorities take part in outdoor activities and
to ask what they can do to change that.
</P>
<P>
   But it can be a mystifying process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've discussed it, but we don't know what to do,'' said Tom
McGuire, 48, of Rensselaer, an officer at the club's Albany
chapter. ``We're a group of middle-aged white people.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, some have already been taking steps. The
National Park Service, for instance, hired its first black director
three years ago. Since then, the NPS is actively recruiting
minority rangers, talking to minority groups about visiting park
lands and developing historic sites like Martin Luther King Jr.'s
house in Atlanta to appeal to minority visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The National Audubon Society has dealt with the issue by
recently recruiting the black actor James Earl Jones and a Hispanic
man onto their national board, while local Audubon groups are asked
to reach out to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not an easy issue to broach. Even the question ``Why
are there so few blacks in the Adirondacks?'' can be answered in
plenty of ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of them just don't know they can come up and do this
kind of stuff. They only know their own neighborhood,'' said Lisa
Williams, a black Atlanta woman who grew up in Delmar, N.Y., and
skied frequently in the Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason, she said, is that most African-Americans,
Hispanics and other minorities live in cities _ an urban
environment that leaves them unable to fathom why anyone would
enjoy walking in the woods, swimming in a lake or skiing on a cold,
winter day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not used to trees and quiet,'' Williams said.
``They're used to the hustle and bustle of the street.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another reason: Some minorities do not feel comfortable
in a place where everyone else is white.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Green, an Albany resident who grew up in the Adirondack
town of Witherbee, still remembers the reaction of a fellow
African-American woman who saw Green on her hometown street last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was eating an ice cream cone, and she almost ran up to me
and hugged me,'' Green recalled. ``She said, `Oh my God, I'm so
happy to see a brown face.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now 55 and director of the Center for Law and Justice in Albany,
Green says that's not a surprising reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people who go up there now who find it kind of
unfriendly, because there are no people of color,'' she said. ``If
you don't see people of color, you sort of get the impression it's
not for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who make the Adirondacks home do so for familiar reasons,
regardless of race. John Battle, a retired Navy man who is black,
moved into the hamlet of Essex with his wife two years ago. He
loves hiking and fishing, and after 25 years working around
submarines, has long become immune to being the only dark face in a
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll stay here as long as the spirit moves me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New York state has taken its own steps to bring minorities into
the mountains, with mixed results. In the past few decades,
state-funded programs like Higher Horizons and the Adirondack
Wilderness Challenge have taken urban youths on Outward Bound-type
adventures to improve their self-esteem and to keep them out of
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Despite national advertising, the state has only found one
minority employee for its program in six years, said Pat Daly of
the state Office of Children and Family Services.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Environmental Conservation has not had
much recruitment luck either. Currently, there are no black forest
rangers, either on duty or in the academy. Few even take the civil
service test, said Capt. Dan Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   But the department is working on ways to change that, said
ranger Capt. Louis Curth, who recently prepared a report on ways to
find rangers who are minorities. He suggests creating ``Urban
Rangers,'' whose job would be to work with minority communities and
try to instill an interest in the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   African-Americans have been in the Adirondacks almost as long as
white people have.
</P>
<P>
   In 1846 in North Elba _ the town where Lake Placid is now
located _ abolitionist Gerritt Smith donated 100 parcels of land to
southern black families looking to escape racism or slavery.
Thirteen years before Harpers Ferry, John Brown came to the region
to teach farming (a time period that will be commemorated this
summer at the John Brown Homestead outside Lake Placid).
</P>
<P>
   Most lasted only a few years, chased away by the rough terrain,
short growing season and brutal winters.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1890s, some black workers arrived to help build William
Seward Webb's railroad through the Adirondacks. In the 1930s, more
blacks would come to work at mining jobs in the center of the
wilderness. A few decades later, hotel service jobs would bring
black workers to the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to bring more African-Americans up to the
mountains, Green now invites black writers to stay at a cabin she
owns in Essex. For some, it can be an educational experience.
</P>
<P>
   Everett Hoagland, poet and English professor at the University
of Massachusetts in North Dartmouth, stayed there in June 1998. It
was a lesson in the joys of nature _ and the dangers of reverse
racism.
</P>
<P>
   Hoagland said he went there ready to experience what he calls
``Yankee coolness.'' Then, one day while trying to get to his
daughter's graduation, he found himself stuck at a closed gas
station with a flat tire. Within a few minutes, a local family _
whom Hoagland had dismissed as ``rednecks'' _ found someone who
plugged his flat and sent him on his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was reminded how wrong I was,'' he said. ``And how wrong it
was to make prejudgments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
