<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7899 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-BLACKANDWHITE-TE     04-05 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BLACKANDWHITE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSY `BLACK AND WHITE' IS MUDDLED ALL OVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writer-director James Toback appears to have cast ``Black and
White'' after a night of reading gossip columns and channel-hopping
between MTV and ESPN. Rappers, models, athletes and fringe
celebrities overpopulate the movie, sometimes portraying themselves
or a reasonable facsimile thereof, other times in roles they have
no business playing.
</P>
<P>
   Toback wants us to see a turn-of-the-century melting pot, but
the ingredients don't blend smoothly, and he winds up with a
cinematic mulligan stew. This is one of those movies that tries to
say so much that what it ultimately says is superficial. It's meant
to be a meditation on racial and sexual relations, but the stunt
casting and busy atmosphere turn it into a muddled curiosity piece.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's bound to attract the attention of pop-culture
obsessives, though, thanks to the bizarre parade of familiar faces
it puts on display. Brooke Shields, in dreadlocks no less, is at
the forefront of one of the movie's plot lines. She plays Sam
Donager, a filmmaker making a documentary about white teens who are
fascinated with hip-hop culture. Robert Downey Jr., virtually
repeating his ``Wonder Boys'' role, is her
closeted-with-the-door-wide-open gay husband, Terry, who comes on
to every man he meets, including Mike Tyson, in a self-deprecating
turn as himself _ if his real self is a pensive and regretful
ex-con who just wants to be left alone. This affords us the rare
opportunity to watch one celebrity ex-con, Tyson, assault another
celebrity law breaker, Downey, onscreen.
</P>
<P>
   Pop singer Bijou Phillips cops Halle Berry's (or maybe Warren
Beatty's) ``Bulworth'' attitude as a subject of Sam's documentary,
a girl who'd rather hang out with Rich, a street thug (Power of the
Wu-Tang Clan) with rap-mogul ambitions, than with her confused
boyfriend (an underused Elijah Wood). Rich's best friend is Dean, a
college basketball star played by Allan Houston of the New York
Knicks; he's also earned the attentions of a white woman, a grad
student played by model Claudia Schiffer in one of the movie's more
bizarre casting moves. Dean is at the center of the movie's other
loose plot line, as he gets in trouble when he agrees to throw a
game at the behest of a shady character played by Ben Stiller. And
if you've seen 1998's dreary ``Permanent Midnight,'' you probably
already know not to trust a movie that features an unshaven Stiller
clad all in black.
</P>
<P>
   So much is going on here _ I haven't even mentioned the Marla
Maples cameo _ that ``Black and White'' eventually sinks into its
own cross-cultural mire. The movie's examination of wannabe-black
white teens is old hat by now, and ignores more current phenomena
such as the rap-metal fusion that's fueled platinum-selling bands
such as Korn and Limp Bizkit (although we should probably be
thankful that Toback didn't cast the latter's Fred Durst). Toback's
ambitions are admirable, and they might even cause some observers
to consider the movie provocative. But it's so crowded and
gimmicky, it winds up being merely pretentious.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Black and White''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: James Toback
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Brooke Shields, Robert Downey Jr., Power, a host of
others
</P>
<P>
   Length: 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ strong sexual content, strong language, and violence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1549EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
