<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7905 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-MORALITY-GAME-NYT     04-05 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MORALITY-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOICES, CHOICES: A MODERN MORALITY PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By JANELLE BROWN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Central High, from Destiny Interactive; Windows 95 and 98;
$39.95; ages 10 to 16. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In 10 years, we might look back at the game Central High and
view it as a small token of desperation in the aftermath of the
shootings at Columbine High School. Central High, a new game from
Destiny Interactive, is a poignant attempt to help patch up a
society gone wrong: a computer game produced by adults in the hope
that it will teach teen-agers that it's a bad idea to torture their
misfit peers. The concept is doomed from the start.
</P>
<P>
   You can hardly blame Destiny Interactive _ a group of
psychologists, educators and social workers _ for wanting to do
something to prevent future violence. The reasoning seems to be
that if the pundits are correct in blaming shoot-'em-up video games
like Quake and Doom for at least some violence by teen-agers, why
not make a game that will teach adolescents how to make better
moral decisions?
</P>
<P>
   Central High takes that conceit and runs with it. The game is a
full-length, interactive feature film for your computer; you make
the decisions that will help shape the plot. Make the right
decisions and you win; make the wrong ones and you lose.
</P>
<P>
   The player takes on the role of Kevin, a teen-ager living in a
bucolic suburban town. Kevin has, for some unknown reason, been
selected to save the world from an equally vague fate at the hands
of some angry but unseen aliens. Each decision he makes in the
course of six days will help decide the future of his fellow
Earthlings.
</P>
<P>
   As Kevin, you face hundreds of questions throughout the week,
ranging from whether to eat a salad for dinner to whether to talk
back to your teacher and whether to steal Dad's car. It's a kind of
choose-your-own-adventure for moralists: make the wrong decision
and a little yellow light on the bottom of your screen comes on.
Once six lights go on, you lose; you have to start over again if
you want to save the human race. Whether the lights go on depends
on a complicated point system in which the worst decisions cost you
16 points and the best cost nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Kevin's apparently idyllic life _ a nuclear family,
including a sister nicknamed Squirt and a dog called Max _ the
teen-agers around him are a messed-up group. There are bulimic
girls, insecure bullies, suicidal adolescents and (this being a
post-Columbine game) a few trod-upon Goth kids for good measure.
For additional points, Kevin has to steer them all toward the
righteous path, demonstrating what the instructions describe as the
``11 strengths'': integrity, honesty, responsibility, respect,
self-discipline, compassion, tolerance, kindness, caring, courage
and commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the decisions players face are no-brainers _ should
Kevin participate in a playground fight or play peacekeeper? _ that
don't even require you to watch the film to get right. But others
are perplexing. What, you have to wonder, are the moral questions
inherent in the decision to watch television for a few minutes?
</P>
<P>
   The game never explains why some decisions prove to be the wrong
ones. That is where the game's pretenses to moral instruction begin
to break down. If Central High is supposed to help teen-agers learn
morals and ethics, shouldn't the game better explain why one
decision is bad and another is wise? Why, for example, is it a bad
idea for Kevin to snitch on a classmate who cheats on a test but a
good idea to snitch on a classmate who uses drugs? And why does the
light turn on when you instruct Kevin to study his math before
breakfast? There is some inscrutable agenda here, and you can't
help wondering whose ethics you are learning.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the game is downright hard to win. I lost three times
in a row before giving up in frustration _ and if it's difficult
for an adult with a presumably well-developed moral sense to muddle
through these decisions, it's hard to believe that a confused
teen-ager could ever win.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, you have to start over from scratch every time
you lose, watching the same movie footage but making different
decisions. The fourth time you listen to the cloying breakfast
chatter of Kevin's family, you'll probably want to throw the game
across the room. ``Have a nice day, dear!'' Mom says cheerily again
and again and again. ``Don't forget your backpack.'' That in itself
could drive teen-agers to violence.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, it becomes tempting to pick the clearly incorrect
answers just to see what will happen to Kevin if he buys a stolen
CD or gossips with a schoolmate. In my own malicious mind, I wanted
to find out if he would turn into a killer, or at least become a
little antisocial. The result, unfortunately, is a letdown. Nothing
happens _ the game just ends. No aliens materialize, and there are
no huge explosions. You're just supposed to sit through endless
hours of repetitive dialogue with no ultimate payoff.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it did not occur to the game makers that games
should be fun. Sure, adolescents should want to help Kevin make the
right choices and save the world from unseen aliens, but there are
some real aliens over at Quake that are looking for a good
blasting. Which would you choose?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(JT) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1600EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
