<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILKMAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLINK OF MILK BOTTLES IS HEARD IN THE LAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photo 5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By TIMOTHY JACK WARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. _ There are not many milkmen these days making
the rounds of America's towns and suburbs. But Westchester County
north of New York City has at least one, Hercules Bontzolakes, 48,
who is the old-fashioned, ``pay when you can, cream floats to the
top'' real McCoy, the classic purveyor of milk, cream, cottage
cheese, eggs and juice. His glass bottles with their crimped paper
tops hold Oak Tree Dairy milk from Long Island and Ronnybrook Farm
Dairy milk from Ancramdale in the Hudson Valley. The orders are
handwritten on paper and left in the milk box for him.
</P>
<P>
   Bontzolakes, who lives near Purchase, dons long silk underwear,
sweats and a heavy plaid flannel jacket every night at 10 to begin
work. (He needs the warm clothes even in summer, because the
temperature in his truck is 33 to 36 degrees to keep the milk
cool.) He kisses his wife, Catherine, good night, says goodbye to
his son, Alexander, almost 3, and climbs behind the wheel of his
lumbering 8-and-a-half-ton truck. He calls it his ``rolling
billboard'' with ``Milk and More: Cat's Dairy'' lettered on the
side. ``Cat'' is for Catherine. But this is not a dairy in the true
sense of the word. It's a milk delivery system.
</P>
<P>
   His stock comes primarily from Oak Tree in East Northport. At
about 11, his order of milk, eggs, cheese and juice is delivered to
him in a parking lot at an auto body shop in White Plains. His
payload is 4 to 6 tons of dairy products, which he delivers to
darkened homes in towns like South Salem, Valhalla and Greenwich,
Conn.
</P>
<P>
   His best-selling milk is Oak Tree 1 percent fat, at $2.86 for a
half gallon, about the same price as at a convenience store. He has
encountered increasing demand for organic milk and is about to add
it, for a price. His own favorite is Ronnybrook's chocolate whole
milk ($3.09 a quart). ``Straight from the thick glass bottle, it is
more simply delicious than a bowl of the best ice cream,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   All this started for Bontzolakes in 1984, when he bought the
routes in the White Plains area from Ray Marsh, who retired. In
1989, he expanded into northern Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   That means that in this bucolic area north of Manhattan, a white
milk truck still moves through the dark and lumbers to a stop.
Moments later, the hinged top of the milk box squeaks open. Empties
clink out, full ones clunk in, a routine that has almost
disappeared from this country.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Bontzolakes is a quixotic throwback or a visionary
revivalist remains to be seen. But in Chappaqua alone, his
customers have tripled in the last year. Many are transplanted
Manhattanites, not lifelong small towners.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of Americans had their milk and other dairy
products delivered in the 1950s. In the '70s, with the rise of
working mothers, the number dropped to 10 percent. These days less
than 1 percent of Americans have milk delivered to their homes. Dr.
Ed Johnston, the milk marketing specialist in the state Agriculture
Department, said that, based on an annual survey, only 0.4 percent
of packaged milk products in New York was sold by home delivery in
October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   How could this service have ever gone out of style? Besides its
comforting rhythm, milk delivery makes sense. According to the U.S.
Agriculture Department, the average American drinks about 17
gallons of milk a year. Children 5 to 9 drink nearly 28 gallons
each a year. In suburbs full of young families, like these in
Westchester, that is a lot of trips to the convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   The milkman is a low-tech, real-life service that some people
are willing to pay a premium for, just as they will consider
ordering their groceries from a Web site. It's an idea whose time
went and has come again: for pennies more than store-bought milk, a
punctual human being delivers the most basic of sustenances to a
customer's front door.
</P>
<P>
   Bontzolakes gently and courteously threads his fat rumbling
truck through the single-lane labyrinth of stone-walled alleys and
white picket fences of this town, on back streets and in hidden
pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, even with the refrigeration, Bontzolakes' truck smells
like milk and milk products. ``Don't you gotta love it?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in the South Bronx and learned about cows as a guest
each summer on a dairy farm in rural Pennsylvania, courtesy of the
Fresh Air Fund. ``It was love at first sight,'' he said. All his
life, he knew he wanted to have something to do with milk.
</P>
<P>
   One stop on the route had a broad, circular drive, with its own
fountain, one of the grander mansions in the county. Minutes after
that came a family on Whippoorwill Road, whose football player sons
require biweekly jugs of 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   From the milk truck it is possible to watch early birds slip out
the door to open their milk boxes and wave sleepily. Just before
sunrise, a few Wall Street dads whiz by, already off to work. At
each house where eggs are on order, Bontzolakes stops dead in his
tracks, opens the carton and gingerly wobbles each egg to be sure
there are no cracked shells. That's what service means, or should
mean, in a service industry.
</P>
<P>
   (JT)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
