r d BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     04-05 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOKBOOK AUTHOR HAS QUICK FIX FOR DINNER ON THE RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If anyone knows the difficulty of fixing a meal on the run, it
is cookbook author Holly Clegg.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from being the ``Louisiana Yam Lady'' for the Louisiana
Sweet Potato Commission, Clegg has also written four ``Trim &AMP;
Terrific'' cookbooks. She has appeared on many TV shows, including
``NBC Weekend,'' ``Donahue,'' and ``Crook &AMP; Chase.''She is a wife
and mother of three.
</P>
<P>
   She is busy. In her latest book, ``Meals on the Move: Rush Hour
Recipes'' she writes: ``To all the busy people who never have
enough time in the day but recognize the importance of eating
healthier. This book is for you!''
</P>
<P>
   Clegg is a familiar face in Fort Worth. She stays in touch with
her former Paschal High School classmates; her parents _ Jerry and
Ruth Berkowitz _ still live in town.
</P>
<P>
   She began studying cooking as an undergraduate at Tulane
University in New Orleans. She attended the Cordon Bleu Cooking
School in London and has taken classes at the Cordon Bleu and La
Varenne cooking schools in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Mike, live with their three children in
Baton Rouge, La.
</P>
<P>
   In a quick telephone conversation, Clegg, who is usually
reserved in appraisals of her own work, confided, ``I truly believe
`Meals on the Move' is my best cookbook, with such a powerful
message about long-term eating plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Clegg said her newest book is a common-sense approach for
today's hectic lifestyle, and she emphasizes that her recipes are
``simple, fun and nutritious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Louisiana Kitchen'' was the first book in her ``Trim &AMP;
Terrific'' series. It was self-published and sold thousands of
copies. It eventually caught the attention of a New York publisher
and was marketed nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Clegg resisted the publisher at first, wanting to keep tighter
controls on her work. She insisted on spiral binders and
easy-to-read recipes. She won out and enjoyed success on two
additional ``Trim &AMP; Terrific'' books.
</P>
<P>
   But the new one is again self-published. ``My children really
didn't want me to take off on another one of those long book
promotional tours,'' she said. ``And I didn't want to go, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Clegg has managed to get her latest work in all major
bookstores, she said, and she is doing a promotional tour for Sam's
Wholesale Club, where her book is the featured book for April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meals on the Move'' is typical of Clegg's work. She doesn't
try to dazzle anyone with culinary hyperbole. Each recipe has a few
notes on the top, a hint or two for making it even more healthful,
and a complete nutritional analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Clegg worked with the American Institute for Cancer Research on
the analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect that one of the most popular sections of my book
will be the `Mix &AMP; Match Menu Planner,' which helps provide easy
answers for those problem-dinner nights,'' Clegg writes in her book
notes. ``Also included is a `Tips &AMP; Tricks' list that helps you
stock the pantry, provides substitution items and shares some
inventive ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Clegg has her own Web site: www.hollyclegg.com.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sample recipe from the more than 200 in ``Meals on the
Move,'' $19.95:
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SHRIMP ENCHILADAS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 6-8
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   Dash cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 sliced jalapeno pepper (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup evaporated skim milk
</P>
<P>
   1 pound medium peeled shrimp, cooked
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups shredded reduced-fat Monterey Jack cheese, divided
</P>
<P>
   8 (10-inch) flour or wheat tortillas, room temperature
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a skillet coated with nonstick
cooking spray, saute onion and garlic over medium heat for several
minutes. Add flour and stir well; add oregano, basil, thyme,
cayenne, cilantro, cumin, jalapeno, salt and pepper, and gradually
add milk. Reduce heat and cook until very thick; remove from heat
and cool slightly. Fold in shrimp and 3/4 cup of cheese. Place 2
tablespoons of the filling on each tortilla and roll up. Place
rolled tortillas side by side in a 2-quart baking dish coated with
nonstick cooking spray and top with remaining 1/2 cup cheese. Bake
for 5 minutes or until cheese is melted and dish is well heated.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 389 calories, 9 grams fat, 48
grams carbohydrates, 26 grams protein, 97 milligrams cholesterol,
577 milligrams sodium, 22 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can write him at Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101; e-mail:
artc(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
