A7916 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-OLIVES-PRIMER-TEX     04-05 0312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIVES-PRIMER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OLIVE: FROM TREE TO TOOTHPICK
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies OLIVES) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The olive is a curious little creature, and we have managed to
make it curiouser.
</P>
<P>
   Bitter when picked from the tree, the olive must be treated to
become edible. Sometimes that treatment is a lye bath, sometimes a
more gentle brining technique that leaches out the bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   The American ``ripe'' olive is simply the green olive by another
name. The black olives are picked green, treated for bitterness and
then pumped with oxygen, which turns them from green to black.
Those not treated with the oxygen are sold as green olives.
However, black olives from elsewhere (Greece, Sicily, Morroco) are
truly ripe _ they were allowed to ripen on the tree.
</P>
<P>
   The ubiquitous pimento, once the only stuffing seen in an olive,
is inserted via the wonders of food processing. The pimentos are
thrown into a processor, seeds and all, and ground. The peppers are
then compressed to make a continuous strip of pimento ``ribbon.''
That ribbon is extruded from a machine in a width that perfectly
fits the hole of a pitted olive.
</P>
<P>
   For all intents and purposes, California is Olive Central in the
United States, with most olives being grown in the hottest areas.
It's natural that California would hold the crown; it was the
Spanish who brought the Old World olive to the New World missions.
</P>
<P>
   And it's California that is leading the resurgence in
``boutique'' olives with small processors, such as Capay Olives. At
Capay, owner Bruce Beauchamp hand-stuffs local olives with pickled
garlic, jalapeno peppers and sun-dried tomatoes, resulting in
olives that give the fruit a whole new attitude.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beverly Bundy
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
