<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-COUNTRY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harmony-rich family needs to mine deeper
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nashville is infatuated these days with artists who have barely
passed puberty, but the family trio the Wilkinsons is more
deserving of attention than most. Eighteen-year-old Amanda and her
16-year-old brother, Tyler, backed by their professorial-looking
dad Steve, can serve up harmonies nearly as seamless as the Everly
Brothers. Their first album showed great promise, particularly the
love-your-mama single, ``26 Cents.''
</P>
<P>
   On this followup, the trio's vocals are as rich as buttermilk.
But when it comes to material, they've struck a sour note. Most of
these tunes have little personality or backbone. The production is
often perplexing _ strings lifted off of ``Eleanor Rigby.'' Guitars
straight out of a Vegas lounge review. A bizarre novelty tune
(``Hypothetically'') that's a cross between ``Counting Flowers on
the Wall'' and something off the Monkees' ``Capricorn, Aquarius,
Pisces and Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   With a voice that resonates like strings across a cello, Amanda
has one of the most promising futures in country music. Get her
some good songs and some country instrumentation to go along with
it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Here and Now'' / The Wilkinsons / Giant / 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: More on the Wilkinsons:
</P>
<P>
   www.giantnashville.com
</P>
<P>
   The Wilkinsons fan site: www.wilkinsonsfans.com
</P>
