<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VIDEO PICK
 &HT;    Force is still with us, though dazzle is gone
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is George Lucas' movie visually amazing? Yes. Exciting?
Sometimes. Emotionally involving? Almost never. As a technological
Mount Everest (and the Mount McKinley of marketing), ``The Phantom
Menace'' is a remarkable achievement. Too bad writer-director Lucas
left out the gee-whiz enthusiasm of the original movies. He also
left out memorable characters. He left out the fun. Priced to buy:
VHS pan-and-scan, $24.98; wide-screen collectible edition, $39.98
(includes a behind-the-scenes documentary, 48 page collector's book
and 35mm strip from an original ``Menace'' theatrical print).
</P>
<P>
   `Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG / Our critic's grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   OTHER RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Messenger: The Story of Joan of Arc'' (R) _ When Joan
(Milla Jovovich) rallies her troops to victory against the British,
the movie has considerable visual oomph. But when the swordplay
slows and the characters talk, you realize it doesn't know what to
make of its heroine. It hedges its bets, presenting her as equal
parts saint and teenage fanatic. The result is, pardon the term,
half-baked. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``For Love of the Game'' (PG-13) _ No matter how hard it tries
to hit, Kevin Costner's baseball flick whiffs a lot. Costner plays
Billy Chapel, a Detroit Tigers pitching god in his waning years who
first learns that his team is being sold and he'll be traded, and
then that his girlfriend is dumping him. As he pitches what could
be a perfect game, he flashes back over his life. Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino
</P>
