<HEADER>
A7920 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS06-COX     04-05 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison, Sonia Murray, andChris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``The Man Who''
</P>
<P>
   Travis. Epic. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   With Oasis' new album in free fall from the U.S. album charts,
this Scottish quartet is the new British hope. Like touring partner
Oasis, Travis plays basic, no-frills rock. Unlike Oasis,
vocalist/songwriter Fran Healy and company do it with a lot of
heart and much less bluster. Travis' first album, ``Good Feeling,''
was a callow but enjoyable collection of riff-heavy tunes. Taking a
giant leap forward, ``The Man Who'' brims with gorgeous melodies
and spacious arrangements anchored by Healy's tough and tender
vocals. One listen and ``Driftwood,'' ``Writing to Reach You'' and
``Why Does It Always Rain on Me'' are lodged in the brain.
Memorable, gimmick-free pop-rock is a difficult thing to pull off.
Travis makes it sound easy.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: More on Travis: www.travisonline.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't Take Me Home''
</P>
<P>
   Pink. LaFace. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   In one corner of the musical battle royal between solo female
singers, we've got Christina Aguilera. In another, Britney Spears.
Both are Mickey Mouse Club graduates and role models to the
countless youthful blondes to follow. Make room for Pink, whose
personality would have that mouse shaking in his big yellow shoes.
But, hey, at least he'd be warned. First track ``Split
Personality'' features one side of the singer talking to her dark
side. But the scariest thing about the song is that it's love man
Kenneth ``Babyface'' Edmonds who creates the eerie backdrop. From
there, Pink harnesses her thin but malleable vocals to an album of
fiery declarations (``Hell Wit Ya''), slowing only occasionally
into the slinky ``Let Me Let You Know'' and ``Stop Falling.''
Altogether, this lyrically theatrical and slickly produced debut is
a ride more suitable for the screen than any amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   More on Pink: www.lafacerecords.com &QR;  BLUES
</P>
<P>
   ``Blues at Sunrise''
</P>
<P>
   Stevie Ray Vaughan &AMP; Double Trouble. Epic/Legacy. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Unlike so many six-string heroes who attack guitars, Stevie Ray
Vaughan could caress his instrument and still come up with a
monster sound. The latest posthumous release from the SRV vaults is
all caress, billed as a ``slow blues'' compilation by the label.
That, unfortunately, also suggests ``dull,'' but if there's one
thing the new CD proves, it's that Vaughan was often at his
sharpest when he could stop and smell the rosy notes coming from
his guitar. In many ways, Vaughan's ``slower'' guitarwork was his
most intense. On ``Ain't Gone 'n' Give Up on Love,'' for instance,
he's an emotional wreck. While ``Blues at Sunrise'' may leave one
wondering if the vaults are almost empty, this shouldn't undermine
its value. It's more for the SRV novices and not the diehards.
</P>
<P>
   _Chris Riemenschneider,
</P>
<P>
   Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: More on Stevie Ray Vaughan:
www.smartlink.net/(tilde)jackklos
</P>
<P>
   /srvfaq.htm
</P>
<P>
   Shane Harrison, Sonia Murray, andChris Riemenschneider writes
for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
