<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-YEEEAHBABY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big rapper's `Baby' makes for a supple swan song
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two months ago, Big Pun passed away a heavyweight in hip-hop,
and only partly because the 28-year-old was somewhere between 450
and 700 pounds when he died of natural causes. There was something
remarkable about a guy of his girth being able to rhyme with such
lilt and his playful insistence that though he was big, he was
still sexy, was nothing short of enigmatic. And convincing.
</P>
<P>
   Big Pun (born Christopher Rios) recorded only one album before
this parting effort. But the Grammy-nominated CD ``Capital
Punishment,'' released in 1998, was enough to make him the first
Latino rapper to sell a million copies. And compared to this
follow-up, it is the better of the two. Not that ``Yeeeah Baby''
doesn't find him as limber with a lyric _ particularly on the
Southern-flavored ``We Don't Care.'' His team-up with R&AMP;B singer
Donell Jones on ``It's So Hard'' approaches the catchiness of Pun's
breakthrough collaboration with R&AMP;B's Joe, ``Still Not a Player.''
And his musical salute to his Puerto Rican roots, ``100%,'' is
certainly danceable.
</P>
<P>
   But scarce is the single that has all three elements.
</P>
<P>
   'Yeeeah Baby'
</P>
<P>
   Big Pun / Loud Records
</P>
<P>
   16 tracks / Our critic's Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ON THE WEB:
</P>
<P>
   Information about Big Pun: www.rollingstone.com and
www.allmusic.com
</P>
<P>
   Information about Loud Records: www.sonymusic.com
