<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Military courts set the stage for high drama
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Rules of Engagement,'' with Samuel L. Jackson on trial after a
Marine Corps rescue goes bad (it opens Friday in metro Atlanta), is
part of a long, proud tradition of military courtroom dramas.
Consider these predecessors for your own at-home ``Please Rise''
festival. Remember these are military trials, so don't look here
for ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' or ``Inherit the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A Few Good Men'': Callow young lieutenant Tom Cruise and his
superior officer, Demi Moore, go mano a mano (so to speak) against
Jack Nicholson (left) as a hard-bitten Navy colonel in charge of a
U.S. base at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba. The case concerns a high-level
court-martial inquiry into the hazing death of a Marine private.
The director is Rob Reiner, but, perhaps more importantly, the
writer is Aaron Sorkin (the man behind television's ``The West
Wing.'') The line everyone remembers is when a bull-necked
Nicholson turns on his adversaries and snarls, ``You can't handle
the truth.'' On-set, however, Nicholson was anything but
bull-necked. His younger cast mates were astonished by his
cooperation. According to Reiner, he delivered his two-page
courtroom speech at least 50 times in one day.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Judgement at Nuremburg'':
</P>
<P>
   An impressive cast presided over by Judge Spencer Tracy tackles
the Nazi war crimes tribunal in this justly famous film directed by
Stanley Kramer. Maxmilian Schell won an Oscar, as did screenwriter
Abby Mann. The most unforgettable performances, however, come from
a triumvirate of old pros: Marlene Dietrich, Montgomery Clift and
Judy Garland. Garland's performance was especially remarkable. She,
like Clift, played an emotionally disturbed survivor of the Third
Reich's brutality. Her only problem was that, on the first day, it
took six takes for her to summon up the required tears. She
explained to Kramer, ``Damn it, Stanley. I can't do it. I'm too
happy today to cry.'' But she managed, and, tears or no tears, also
managed a best supporting actress Oscar nomination.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Sergeant Rutledge'': Directed by John Ford, it's based on an
original story called ``Buffalo Soldier,'' which was the Indian
term for the African-American soldiers in the 9th and 10th Cavalry,
most of them former slaves. The name came from their ability to
hide in the snow under buffalo skins. The highest rank a buffalo
soldier could reach was sergeant; all the higher leadership was
white. The plot concerns the court-martial of a sergeant (Woody
Strode) for alleged rape (and worst, miscegenation), flashing back
and forth between the trial and Rutledge's heroic career. The
moguls at Warner's wanted Sidney Poitier or Harry Belafonte in the
title role, but Ford insisted that they weren't ``tough enough.''
Instead he hired Strode, a former UCLA football player and sometime
professional wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Caine Mutiny'': Based on Herman Wouk's Pulitzer
Prize-winning novel, it involves naval officer Captain Queeg
(Humphrey Bogart), who's beginning to crack up. During a typhoon,
he's relieved of command by a subordinate, an action that results
in a military trial. Van Johnson is fine as the upright Navy man
doing what he thinks is his duty, and Fred MacMurray is more than
fine as the weaselly officer who goads Johnson into action. But the
movie belongs to Jose Ferrer, as the lawyer for the defense, and to
Bogart, twitching and curling his lip and playing with those darn
steel balls as if his life depended on it. Asked by a friend how he
got a certain manic, paranoid look in his eyes, Bogart replied,
``Easy. I'm nuts, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
