<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7925 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE06-COX     04-05 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roasting suits fruits, veggies as well as meats
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next few weeks may be a good time to get in some roasting
before the summer heat sets in and the oven takes a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   While other cooking methods like sauteing, baking, frying and
steaming all impart a distinct flavor and quality, many think that
the elemental alchemy that takes place when food is roasted is
unsurpassed.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to get spectacular results when roasting beef,
chicken and pork, but roasting also enriches the flavor of
vegetables and fruits that can be incorporated into lighter
springtime fare such as soups, salads and desserts.
</P>
<P>
   Tomatoes, potatoes, peppers, onions, carrots, mushrooms and corn
all take on a richness that cannot be accomplished by any other
method.
</P>
<P>
   Sliced bananas, caramel sauce and a dash of rum can be
transformed into a spectacular dessert after a few minutes in a hot
oven, then topped with chopped nuts.
</P>
<P>
   RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  While surfing for springtime roasting recipes, we came across
``The Culinary Connection,'' an easy-to-use recipe search engine
that produced great results. Go to
www.culinary.com/foodtext/direct.shtml, click ``search,'' put
``roasted'' in the search field, check off whatever categories you
are interested in and see what happens.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A consulting firm in Waterloo, Ohio, has figured out that no
matter what you are selling on the Net, adding recipes to your site
can't hurt. They have compiled an intriguing list at
www.ajlc.waterloo.on.ca/Recipes/CookingRightShow/ that includes one
for Roasted White Corn Salsa and another for Roasted Potatoes, Beet
and Onion Salad. Both sound ideal for a picnic.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An interesting Chili With Roasted Vegetables that is served at
Bear Creek Lodge in Victor, Mont., is posted at
www.virtualcities.com/ons/mt/n/
</P>
<P>
   mtn98012.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gourmet magazine does oven-roasted vegetables right at
www.foodtv.com/recipes/re-c1/0,1724,9307,00.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An imaginative roast tropical fruit salad at
www.bamco.com/kitchen/don.html combines roasted pineapple, red
grapefruit, mangoes and asparagus with lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Everyone has discovered by now that the ``flavor of the
decade'' is roasted garlic. But if you want a refresher course, see
www.culinary.com/foodtext/methodan/27.shtml.
</P>
<P>
   ROASTING SITES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  One great benefit of roasting is that it doesn't require
constant attention. But timing is important. See Better Homes &AMP;
Gardens' roasting chart at www.bhg.com/food/hroast.html or
</P>
<P>
   www.arlenes-heavenlywebs.com/personal/
</P>
<P>
   cooking/ROASTINGTIME.html for another timetable.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Roasting is one of the oldest and simplest methods of cooking.
It simply means cooking food in a high dry heat, uncovered and
without added liquid.
</P>
<P>
   People tend to favor different types of roasting. Some roast at
a high heat for a short period. Others start out at a high heat,
and then lower the heat; others maintain a steady moderate heat the
entire time. For an overview of roasting traditions and techniques,
advantages and disadvantages, see
www.honeysucklewhite.com/allaboutturkey/preparationchoices/
</P>
<P>
   roasting.html.
</P>
<P>
   The Old Farmers Almanac at www.almanac.com/cooks/roasting.html
posts some nostalgic roasting rules.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information about getting good results when roasting
vegetables can be found at
www.fatfree.com/archive/1997/apr/msg00485.html and
www.wegmans.com/kitchen/howto/tech/roasting.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  See ``How to Roast a Chicken to Perfection'' at
www.taunton.com/fc/features/techniques/chicken/1.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Roasting tips and recipes from Epicurious can be found at
www.epicurious.com/bba/b04fivebasics/roast.html.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Onion and Leek Soup With Gruyere and Parmesan Croutes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 15-20 minutes Cooking time: 1
hour, 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   A soup for all seasons, this one's savory onion flavor is
touched by sweetness of the leeks. The onions should roast only
until golden; you do not want them to singe around the edges, which
would add a burned flavor to the stock.
</P>
<P>
   For the soup:
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds onions, sliced 1/2 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds leeks, washed, white and light green parts cut into
1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   6 to 8 cups homemade or canned beef stock, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 sprig fresh thyme, or 1 teaspoon dried, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   For the Gruyere and Parmesan Croutes:
</P>
<P>
   12 slices Italian or French bread, cut 1/2 inch thick on the
diagonal
</P>
<P>
   2 large garlic cloves, halved
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup grated Gruyere cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup freshly grated Parmesan
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a large roasting pan, toss the onions and leeks with the oil
and season with salt and pepper to taste. Roast, stirring often,
for 30 minutes or until the onions are golden but not crispy.
Transfer to a large soup pot. Pour the wine into the roasting pan.
Bring to a boil over high heat on the stovetop, scraping up the
browned bits. Boil for 1 minute, then add to the onions and leeks.
</P>
<P>
   Add 6 cups of the stock, the thyme, bay leaf and salt and pepper
to taste. Bring to a boil. Reduce heat to low and simmer for 30
minutes to concentrate the flavors, adding some or all of the
remaining 2 cups stock as needed if the soup becomes too thick.
Remove and discard the thyme sprig, if used, and the bay leaf.
</P>
<P>
   For the croutes: Reduce oven heat to 400 degrees. Rub both sides
of each slice of bread with the garlic and brush with oil. Arrange
slices on a baking sheet and bake, turning once, for 7 minutes
total, or until lightly toasted. Spoon some of both cheeses over
each slice and bake for 3 to 4 minutes more or until the cheeses
are melted. Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   To serve: Ladle soup into heated bowls and top each with a hot
cheese croute. From: ``Reasons to Roast'' by Georgia Chan Downard
and Evie Righter (Houghton Mifflin, $15)
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Scallops With Leeks and Fennel
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30-35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 13-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This dinner party dish is great served with green-and-white
fettuccine. Avoid bay scallops: They are too small to withstand the
high heat of roasting and will turn into unappealing little
pellets.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup julienned well-washed leeks
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup julienned fennel bulb
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup julienned carrot
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup well-drained diced roasted red bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup diced pitted kalamata olives
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced fresh basil or parsley, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds sea scallops, rinsed and patted dry, muscle removed
if necessary and halved if large
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Lightly oil an 8-by-10-inch gratin
dish.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan, heat oil over medium-high heat until hot.
Add the leeks, fennel, carrot, garlic, salt and pepper to taste.
Cook, covered, for 5 minutes or until the vegetables soften.
Transfer the vegetables to a bowl and stir in the red peppers,
olives and 2 tablespoons of the basil or parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange half the mixture in the gratin dish; arrange the
scallops in a single layer on the vegetables, and sprinkle with
salt and pepper to taste. Top with the remaining vegetable mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Roast for 8 to 10 minutes or until the scallops are firm but
still springy to the touch.
</P>
<P>
   With a slotted spoon, divide the scallops and vegetables among
heated serving plates and sprinkle a little of the remaining
tablespoon of fresh basil or parsley over each serving.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1621EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7926 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-NORAROBERTS-BOOK-TEX     04-05 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORAROBERTS-BOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ROMANCE AUTHOR NORA ROBERTS, WRITING IS ULTIMATE PASSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took a blizzard for Nora Roberts to find her calling. Trapped
in her Maryland home by a snowstorm, Roberts, a 29-year-old
homemaker, was at the end of her rope. Her two kids, ages 2 and 5,
were climbing the walls, and their mother wasn't feeling too calm,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to do something or go crazy,'' she says. ``So I sat down
to write a book.''
</P>
<P>
   Few young mothers would choose such a daunting endeavor to keep
from going loco, but for Roberts, who had no previous writing
experience, it worked. In between feeding and cleaning up after the
kids, she wrote _ until the snow had melted and her story was
finished, both in just a matter of days. The romance novel, which
she titled ``Irish Thoroughbred,'' was good enough to arouse the
interest of an agent, and so Roberts immediately started another
book, always working with a basic plot concept but never a detailed
outline.
</P>
<P>
   The first novel sold to Silhouette, a romance paperback
publisher, as did the second, ``Blithe Images.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Roberts was a hot commodity in the publishing world.
``I figured I was on to something,'' she says. ``By the time the
kids were old enough for school, I had a writing routine going.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years and 132 books (yes, you read that right) later,
Roberts has not abandoned her original pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come up with an idea, start playing `what if,' and keep
working until it's done,'' she says. ``There's no magic involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics would simply say there's no challenge involved in
writing romance novels, but Roberts, now 49, is determined to prove
the naysayers wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carolina Moon'' (Putnam, $24.95), her current bestseller, is
her latest attempt to move beyond formula romance writing. Roberts
says she enjoys the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than any other job,'' she says. ``I get to work at
home, and I don't have to wear pantyhose. People say I do it for
the money. Let's get real. By now, money is what I've got. Does
that mean I should retire or write less?''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, she just loves to write.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get inspiration from things in my own life,'' she admits,
citing her second husband, a handsome carpenter she met when she
needed someone to build some bookshelves.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts describes writing as ``the good part'' of her work.
Publicity tours, with their dual responsibilities of meeting fans
and members of the press, are love/hate affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really means a lot to me are the personal connections I
make at book signings,'' Roberts says. ``I never get over being
pleased when somebody says, `I love your books.' Dealing with fans
is not a chore.''
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with the press, however, is.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, the person asking the questions hasn't even
read my latest book, or maybe any of my books,'' she says. ``It's
hit or miss whether you get fair treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts says her audience consists primarily of women, including
teen-agers, homemakers, working women and academics. But she hopes
to narrow the gender gap and attract more male readers, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason men can't enjoy the kind of people I write
about _ strong women, but strong men, too,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   After conquering the romance genre, Roberts decided to expand
her repertoire to reach a broader audience. Putnam, the publishing
home of Tom Clancy and Patricia Cornwell, took her on, but they
didn't want her to tone down the romantic themes of her tales. So,
sticking with the familiar, she simply began to flesh out
characters and plots more. ``Honest Illusions'' was her first
Putnam title in 1992; she still turns out several, less
research-intensive romance titles for Silhouette each year.
</P>
<P>
   ```Carolina Moon' is an example of how I still write,'' Roberts
says. ``I never write from outlines. I'm terrible at that. I can't
do it. I take a basic idea and see where it goes. This time I knew
I wanted a Southern canvas, a small town in the South. I wanted a
man in a traditional profession for one hero _ I chose a cotton
farmer. I started researching cotton farming, which I knew nothing
about, and learned about organic cotton _ so that gave a modern man
a modern approach to cotton farming.''
</P>
<P>
   Working six to eight hours a day, Roberts eventually crafted the
love story of Tory Bodeen and Cade Lavelle, childhood friends
reunited in Progress, S.C., where Tory fled after playing an
unwitting role in the death of Cade's little sister, Hope. The real
killer has been lurking in Progress ever since, and Tory's
reappearance is a signal for more murder. Though it received
lukewarm reviews, ``Carolina Moon'' debuted in February at No. 3 on
The New York Times bestseller list, and has been in the top 10 ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such success, Roberts still can't seem to slow down. She
says that Putnam is concerned that if she continues to write at
such a prolific pace, her books may cannibalize each other, with
sales of one book hurting sales of another that's in simultaneous
release.
</P>
<P>
   In response, she hasn't cut back her workload _ she's just taken
on a new name. Roberts is now publishing a series of paperback
mystery novels (''Witness in Death,'' ``Naked in Death'') under the
pen name of J.D. Robb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to keep writing,'' Roberts says. ``I never take success
for granted. So being J.D. Robb is a way to keep the publisher
happy and me happy, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts jokes that during her promotional tours, fans always
want to suggest story ideas to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them that if they have a good idea they should write
books themselves,'' Roberts says. ``Look, I did it that way, and it
worked for me.''
</P>
<P>
   And, out of 134 titles, which is her favorite?
</P>
<P>
   ``The one that's on sale right now, honey,'' Roberts says,
laughing. ``That's always going to be true.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720, or e-mail:
jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
