<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7927 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-GRAIN-RECIPE06-C     04-05 3398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-GRAIN-RECIPE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Going with the grain for good health
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The late Bert Greene must have had a grandmother like mine. In
his ``The Grains Cookbook'' (Workman, 1988) he attributes the quote
about good things ``keeping their intentions to themselves'' to his
grandmother, just as I often heard it from mine.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, his only prerequisite for recipes in the book was that
they taste good. That is the best rule of thumb to follow with
whole grains. The different grains offer so many different textures
and tastes. As I chose recipes to try, I looked for other flavors I
knew I would enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Though unfamiliar with millet, I knew I liked hot and spicy.
Waldorf salad has always been a favorite, so I decided to try the
wheatberries version _ hey, if I didn't like it, I could just eat
the apples. Of course I did like it, as well as the other dishes
below. I think they are good ones to start with. When you are ready
for more, consider finding Greene's book or consulting these
sources:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Vegetarian Cooking for Everyone,'' Deborah Madison (Broadway
Books, $35).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Laurel's Kitchen Bread Book: A Guide to Whole-Grain
Breadmaking,'' Laurel Robertson, Carol Flinders and Bronwen Godfrey
(Random House, $21).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Amazing Grains,'' Joanne Saltzman (HJ Kramer, $12.95).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.drweil.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.epicurious.com (search recipe database for individual
grains, such as barley, buckwheat, etc.).
</P>
<P>
   Starting from the outside of the kernel, grains are made up of a
protective fibrous hull called the bran, then the starchy endosperm
and at the heart the germ. In the refining process, we lose the
bran, which contains most of the minerals, fiber and much of the
riboflavin inherent in grains. The oil-rich germ, which can quickly
turn rancid, is frequently removed as well. What we end up eating
is the starchy middle. Although lost nutrients are added to refined
grains through enrichments, whole grains retain more fiber and
trace minerals, which is why they're considered nutritionally
superior.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Selecting: Buy 1-pound bags of grains you use only
occasionally and replace frequently. When buying grains and their
flours from bins, make sure they have a nice, fresh smell and have
not turned rancid.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Storing: Store in tightly covered glass jars in a cool place.
Whole and cracked grains will keep three to four months. Flours and
meals should be kept in the refrigerator or freezer and used within
two months.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Soaking: Like beans, large grains and short-grain brown rice
cook more quickly and are more easily digested if soaked before
cooking. Although this is not entirely necessary, soaking them in
cool water anywhere from one hour to overnight does help soften
them.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cooking: A 2-quart saucepan with a tight-fitting lid is ample
for cooking 1 to 2 cups of raw grains. A nonstick surface makes it
easier to clean the pans. Cooking time varies by grain. After the
grains have cooked, let them stand for 5 to 10 minutes to continue
absorbing moisture. To produce fluffy, separate grains, put a clean
towl under the lid once they've finished cooking, then let stand.
</P>
<P>
   Source: ``Vegetarian Cooking for Everyone,'' Deborah Madison,
(Broadway Books, $35.)
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   100 Percent
</P>
<P>
   Whole Wheat Bread
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 loaf (about 16 slices)
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Kneading time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rising time: 3 hours, 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45-60 minutes
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to include more whole grains in my diet, I went on
a search for a good recipe for homemade whole wheat bread. I tried
several (including a recipe for whole wheat biscuits that I sent on
to the secretary of defense.)
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that I'm not a practiced bread baker to begin with.
I've learned that whole wheat baking is tricky because the flour
doesn't have as high a gluten content as white flours. Getting the
dough to rise can be tricky.
</P>
<P>
   Through my trials, I'd say the single most important thing I
learned is to use freshly ground whole wheat flour. Luckily,
Harry's now offers hard red spring wheat you can grind and take
home.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find freshly ground whole wheat flour, find some
that specifies that it's whole wheat bread flour. Use that in this
recipe from ``The Laurel's Kitchen Bread Book'' (Random House, $21)
and you should succeed. This makes the best breakfast toast!
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons warm water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   3 cups whole wheat bread flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cold yogurt
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup hot tap water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons oil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable shortening for greasing pan
</P>
<P>
   Warm a china cup by rinsing it with hot water, then measure the
warm water into it. The water should be between 105 degrees and 115
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle yeast into the water while stirring with a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the flour and salt in a large mixing bowl and stir
lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Put the yogurt in your liquid measuring cup and add the hot tap
water to make a full cup total.
</P>
<P>
   Mix in the oil and honey.
</P>
<P>
   Make a well in the center of the dry ingredients and pour in the
wet ingredients and the yeast mixture. Begin stirring from the
center outward until mixture is well-combined. Turn the dough out
of the bowl onto a kneading surface and knead for 300 substantial
strokes, or about 10 minutes. (You may use a food processor or
mixer. Kneading time will be slightly less than 10 minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   Shape the dough into a smooth round and put it seam side down in
a large bowl. Cover it snugly with plastic wrap. Allow to rise in a
warm area (about 80 degrees) free of drafts. (I usually put my
dough in an unheated oven.) Allow to rise in a warm, dry place for
2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Poke a hole in the middle of the dough; if the side does not
collapse in, deflate the dough by gently pressing from the center
outward. Once it is deflated, tear away from sides of bowl and
shape into a small round again. Allow the dough to rise for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Deflate the dough again, round it and let sit for 10 minutes.
Prepare an 8-by-4-inch loaf pan by thoroughly greasing it with
vegetable shortening. Then shape the dough into a loaf and put in
pan. Allow to rise in a warm, dry place for 45 minutes. (Not the
oven this time, since it needs to preheat.)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Once bread has risen and the oven
is ready, bake for 45 minutes to an hour. Check at 30 minutes to
see how brown and firm the bread is. Check again at 45 minutes. Tap
the top of the loaf; when you hear a hollow sound, the bread is
done.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 100 calories, 3 grams protein, 2 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 21), 18 grams carbohydrates, 1 milligram
cholesterol, 151 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Curried Quinoa With Peas and Cashews
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Quinoa is one of the fastest-cooking grains, so it fits in with
busy lifestyles. I like to place a small poached salmon fillet atop
a bed of this crunchy, curried dish.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons canola oil or butter
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, a quarter finely diced, the remaining coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup quinoa, thoroughly rinsed
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons curry powder, divided
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon salt, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 zucchini, diced into small cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup carrot juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup peas
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup thinly sliced green onions, including a little of the
greens
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cashews, roasted and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   Heat half the oil in a small soup pot, add the finely diced
onion and cook over medium heat for about 3 minutes. Stir in the
quinoa, 1/2 teaspoon curry powder and 1/4 teaspoon salt and cook
for 2 minutes. Add 2 cups boiling water, then lower the heat. Cover
and cook for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, heat the remaining tablespoon oil in a 10-inch
skillet. Add the chopped onion, zucchini and remaining 1 1/2
teaspoons curry powder. Cook, stirring frequently, over medium heat
for five minutes. Add 1/2 cup water, the carrot juice and 1/2
teaspoon salt. Cover and simmer for 5 minutes, then add the peas
and green onions and cook for a few minutes more. Stir the
vegetables into the quinoa, then add cashews. Taste for salt and
season with pepper. Allow to cook for another 5 minutes over low
heat. Then remove from heat and serve in soup plates. Garnish with
cilantro or mint. From: ``Vegetarian Cooking for Everyone,''
Deborah Madison (Broadway Books, $35)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 397 calories, 12 grams protein, 18 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 41), 51 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 479 milligrams sodium, 7 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Wheat Berry Waldorf Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Soaking time: overnight
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1-1 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Take the familiar Waldorf and add the perhaps unfamiliar wheat
berries and you get a wonderfully nutty, crunchy, chewy, tasty
delight. This one will appeal to just about everyone. I offered it
to friends in my quilt guild and they raved.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup wheat berries
</P>
<P>
   4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 Gala or McIntosh apple
</P>
<P>
   1 Granny Smith apple
</P>
<P>
   1 celery rib, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup packed fresh mint leaves, washed well, spun dry and
chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dried sour cherries
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup golden raisins
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons walnuts, toasted and chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh orange juice
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon freshly grated orange zest
</P>
<P>
   6 boston lettuce leaves
</P>
<P>
   Put the wheat berries in a large bowl, cover with water, wrap
the bowl with plastic and let berries soak overnight.
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan, bring 4 cups water and salt to a boil and add
wheat berries. Simmer wheat berries, covered, for about 1 hour,
until tender to the tooth. Drain in a colander and cool to room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Cut apples into 1/2-inch chunks. In a large bowl, toss the
apples, wheat berries, celery, mint, cherries, raisins, scallions
and walnuts. In a small bowl, combine the rice vinegar, orange
juice and zest. Pour over the wheat berry mixture. Spoon onto
lettuce leaves to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 142 calories, 4 grams protein, 2 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 14), 30 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 109
milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Sesame Soba Noodle and Vegetable Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 8 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quick and tasty way to add a little variety to your
weeknight routine. Fancy soba noodles are made from buckwheat
(check the label; some are made with wheat). We've seen them in
regular supermarkets as well as ethnic groceries. They cook quickly
and have a mildly nutty taste. They make a great lunch!
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces dried buckwheat noodles (soba)
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Oriental sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces English hothouse cucumber, seeded, shredded
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces carrots, peeled, shredded
</P>
<P>
   6 large radishes, trimmed, sliced
</P>
<P>
   3 green onions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Toast sesame seeds in heavy small skillet over medium-low heat.
Cool. Cook noodles in pot of boiling salted water until just tender
but still firm to bite, about 8 minutes. Drain. Rinse noodles until
cold water until cool. Drain well and transfer to large bowl. Mix
the peanut oil and sesame oil, then drizzle over the noodles and
toss to coat.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, mix the vinegar with the cucumber, carrots,
radishes and onions and add to the noodles. Season with salt and
pepper and sprinkle with sesame seeds. Serve. From: Epicurious.com
(Bon Appetit, July, 1995)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 341 calories, 8 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 37), 47 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 415 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Brown Rice with Eggs, Greens and Walnuts
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time:
30-45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Vegetarian cookbook author Deborah Madison calls this dish and
other variations of eggs and rice ``wholesome fast food.'' We'd add
``delicious.'' The rice takes time to cook, but it's unattended
time. Once it's ready, this meal is done in a flash. Try other
variations, too, like pesto or grated provolone, roasted peppers or
peas. This is a new regular at my house.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups brown rice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches mustard greens, stems removed
</P>
<P>
   1 large garlic clove, minced or pressed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 or 2 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup toasted chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   Pecorino romano cheese
</P>
<P>
   for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Boil the rice in salted water until tender, 30 to 45 minutes,
depending on whether it's long- or short-grain. Meanwhile, cook the
greens in 2 quarts salted boiling water until tender, 5 to 7
minutes. Drain, then press out the liquid and coarsely chop them.
Toss the greens with the garlic and oil and season with salt and
pepper to taste. When the rice is done (drain if needed, then
return to the pot), rapidly stir in the eggs until rice is
well-coated (rice and pan should still be hot). If you work
quickly, the egg will cook evenly and be invisible except for its
shine. Add the greens and walnuts and toss again. Serve with a
light coating of grated pecorino cheese. From: ``Vegetarian Cooking
for Everyone,'' Deborah Madison (Broadway Books, $35)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 457 calories, 12 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 38), 61 grams carbohydrates, 53
milligrams cholesterol, 28 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Red-Hot Ten-Speed Millet
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Of all the grains I tried for this story, I was most unfamiliar
with millet. So I chose this spicy recipe, thinking it would be
hard to go wrong. I was right. It made an excellent side to a small
steak. To make this a main dish, mix in some cooked chopped
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup millet
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 large cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 small green bell pepper, cored, seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   1 large red bell pepper, cored, seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped roasted sweet red peppers (fresh or from a
jar)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups vegetable or chicken stock or canned broth
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon hot chili oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dark sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Chopped fresh parsley for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Place the millet in a large heavy skillet and stir over
medium-high heat until the seeds turn golden, about 5 minutes. The
millet will pop slightly as it browns. Remove from heat. Heat the
oil in a medium saucepan over medium heat. Add the onion; cook 1
minute. Add the garlic and both bell peppers; cook 2 minutes.
Sprinkle with sugar and stir in the millet, sweet peppers and
chicken stock. Heat to boiling. Reduce heat, cover and cook over
medium-low heat until the millet is tender and all liquid has been
absorbed, 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the chili oil, vinegar and sesame oil. (If you are
serving with chopped chicken, spoon it over the millet.) Remove the
pan from the heat and let it stand, covered, 10 minutes. Then fluff
the millet with a fork, season with salt, sprinkle with parsley and
serve. From: ``The Grains Cookbook,'' Bert Greene (Workman
Publishing, 1998)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 167 calories, 3 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 56), 16 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 5 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Armenian Style Chicken With Bulgur
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour and 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This Turkish-inspired dish is hearty and exotic, with whiffs of
peppers and honey. Walnuts add crunch to the sweet bulgur. This
would be delicious with just chicken thighs and legs, if you don't
want to do a whole chicken.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 chicken (about 3 pounds), cut into serving pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon chopped fresh thyme (or 1/4 teaspoon dried)
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 small hot red pepper, seeded, deveined and minced
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken stock or canned broth
</P>
<P>
   1 cup bulgur
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup broken walnut pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon honey
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil with the butter in a large cast-iron skillet over
medium heat. Sprinkle the chicken pieces with the salt, pepper and
thyme and saute a few pieces at a time until golden brown, about 10
minutes. Transfer the pieces to a plate as they are done.
</P>
<P>
   Remove all but 1 tablespoon fat from skillet. Add the onion and
cook over medium-low heat, scraping the sides and bottom of the pan
for 2 minutes. Add the garlic and hot pepper; cook 4 minutes
longer. Return the chicken pieces to the skillet, stir in the stock
and heat to boiling. Reduce the heat and simmer, covered, for 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Using tongs, remove the chicken pieces to a plate. Stir the
bulgur into the cooking juices and add the walnuts and honey. Mix
well and return the chicken pieces. Continue to cook, covered,
until the chicken and bulgur are tender and all liquid has been
absorbed, about 20 minutes longer. Turn off the heat and let the
skillet stand, covered, for 10 minutes. Before serving, fluff the
bulgur with a fork and sprinkle with the mint and basil. From:
``The Grains Cookbook,'' Bert Greene (Workman Publishing, 1998)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 676 calories, 45 grams protein, 37 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 49), 44 grams carbohydrates, 111
milligrams cholesterol, 432 milligrams sodium, 9 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Mushroom-Barley Risotto
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Soaking time: 20-30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Barley makes a wonderful alternative to arborio rice for
risotto. The dish will cook up with the same creamy consistency,
but with a slightly nuttier taste. Barley is also cheaper than
arborio and requires less fuss.
</P>
<P>
   12 dried shiitake mushrooms (or other dried varieties)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups hot water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter or oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups minced onion
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh domestic mushrooms, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   2 cups pearl barley, rinsed
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry sherry, vermouth or Chinese rice wine
</P>
<P>
   about 4 cups additional water (added gradually)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Minced toasted pecans or minced fresh dill for garnish
(optional)
</P>
<P>
   Place the dried shiitake mushrooms in a medium-sized bowl and
pour in 2 cups of hot water, then let sit for 20 to 30 minutes, or
until mushrooms are very soft. Place a few layers of cheesecloth in
a strainer over a second bowl and strain the mushrooms, pressing
out and saving all their liquid. Stem and thinly slice the
shiitakes and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, melt the butter or oil and heat in a large saucepan
or Dutch oven over medium heat. Add the onion and half the garlic
and saute for about 5 minutes. Add the fresh mushrooms and salt and
stir well. Cover and cook for about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the barley and saute for a minute or two, keeping the
heat at medium. Pour in the wine; cover and turn down the heat.
Simmer until the liquid is absorbed (10 minutes). Add the sliced
shiitakes and their liquid. Stir, cover and cook over low heat
until the liquid is absorbed (another 10 to 12 minutes). Pour in 2
cups of the additional water. Stir, cover and simmer until the
water is absorbed (about 10 minutes). Then pour in the last 2 cups
of water, stirring in the remaining garlic and the vinegar at the
same time. Cover one more time and cook until all the liquid is
gone (10 minutes again). Grind in some black pepper and stir from
bottom to let steam escape. Garnish if desired and serve. From:
``Mollie Katzen's Vegetable Heaven'' (Hyperion, $27.50)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 302 calories, 9 grams protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 11), 62 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 604
milligrams sodium, 13 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
