<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7929 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-GRAIN06-COX     04-05 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-GRAIN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Climb out of your fluffy white-flour-things rut and add some
variety with healthier whole grains
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An old saying suggests things that are good for you ``should
keep the secret of their good intentions strictly to themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Or put another way: ``Whatever you do, don't call something
healthy,'' said Andrew Weil, a doctor and author of health books,
in a recent interview. ``It will be the kiss of death.''
</P>
<P>
   Because we've come to praise whole grains rather than bury them,
we'll save the health news for a little later.
</P>
<P>
   First, savor the nuttiness of brown rice mixed with some pungent
greens, an egg, minced garlic, toasted walnuts and grated pecorino
cheese _ a new comfort food standard.
</P>
<P>
   Or allow a bowl of crunchy quinoa (pronounced keen-WAH) to soak
up some curry, and then mix with cashews and peas for an exotic
side dish to fish. Then try giving the Waldorf salad new vibrancy
with some springy, yummy wheat berries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fortunate in this country to have access to grains from
all over the world,'' said Vivian Gold, a team member at Whole
Foods grocery store in Atlanta, as she stood before a row of bins
filled with barley and buckwheat, quinoa and millet. ``But we don't
take advantage of them.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because Americans are in a ``fluffy white things'' rut,
as Weil refers to products made with white flour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it is shaped into rolls, muffins or pizza crusts;
baked into pretzels or crackers; fortified with vitamins and
minerals or mixed with flours of other grains, these white-flour
products are all the same _ one of the unhealthiest creations of
food technology,'' Weil wrote in his latest book, ``Eating Well for
Optimum Health'' (Knopf, $25).
</P>
<P>
   Weil's concern with refined white flour products is that they
offer relatively little nutritionally and convert into blood sugar
quickly, provoking an insulin response. This can be a factor in
obesity and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   What concerns Kathleen Zelman, Marietta, Ga., nutritionist and
local spokeswoman for the American Dietetic Association, is that
refined white flour doesn't provide the fiber folks need, much less
the other nutrients whole grains offer.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of whole grains have been touted for years. But
just last year, the federal government approved label claims for
whole grain foods that states: ``Diets rich in whole-grain foods
and other plant foods and low in fat and cholesterol may reduce the
risk of heart disease and certain cancers.''
</P>
<P>
   Zelman said that most adults need at least 25 grams of fiber a
day; children need their age plus 5. The best way to get the
necessary fiber is to eat more whole grains and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many, the best way to start is with whole-grain cereals,''
said Zelman. Read labels for cereals that include whole wheat or
other grains, such as barley and oats. Switching from white bread
to whole wheat bread is also an easy move. But again, read labels
and make sure breads are 100 percent whole wheat.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, more and more convenience products featuring whole
grains are available in groceries. Tabbouleh mixes, with cracked
wheat, are common now. Mixes for more exotic grains like quinoa are
also on the shelves, offering quick and easy ways to try new
grains. (Seeds of Change is one brand to look for.) Whole-wheat
pastas and Japanese soba noodles (made with buckwheat) are right at
home in speedy weeknight menus.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants may be a good place to experiment. Cosi in Decatur
offers a monkfish with a barley risotto and roast lamb medallions
with bulgur enhanced with artichokes and eggplant.
</P>
<P>
   In the Shade Cafe, a vegetarian restaurant in Atlanta, offers a
variety of grain dishes, from a wheat berries and carrot terrine to
quinoa stir-fries. ``We mix cooked quinoa in near the end of the
stir-frying process, during the last minute,'' said Brad
Rubenstein. ``It really adds a lot of texture and soaks up the
flavors.''
</P>
<P>
   Once folks have tried convenience products and sampled some
restaurant fare, Zelman urges cooking up one new whole-grain recipe
a week at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average family cook has about eight to 10 recipes _ like
spaghetti, meatloaf and chicken _ that they make over and over
again,'' said Zelman. ``It's time to break out of that comfort zone
and add some variety. And adding whole grains is critical to
protecting your family's health.''
</P>
<P>
   Oops. We hope that health claim wasn't the kiss of death.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, many whole-grain dishes are as tasty as they are good
for you.
</P>
<P>
   And don't think healthy and boring. Think adventurous and
delicious.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
