<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7931 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE06-COX     04-05 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Locate hard to find items
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But because of the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It,The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com
(please include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone
number); or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for pHisoderm Antibacterial Cleanser.It's in a
white container with a bright blue, green and orange label. I used
to buy it at Wal-Mart, but I can't find it anywhere now.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pam M. Miles, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Another medicinal question: I have been unable to find
Mercurochrome, an antiseptic that would quickly relieve pain from
cuts or other superficial injuries without stinging. The main
drawback? The skin would be stained red.
</P>
<P>
   _ Barbara Brown, Alpharetta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   And another: I'm looking for merthiolate, a bright orange-red
solution that practically cured anything when I was a kid. This is
not Mercurochrome, which doesn't burn when applied to a wound.
Merthiolate, an antiseptic solution, burns a lot! But if you can
stand it (and my momma made me stand it), it'll heal almost
anything. I haven't see this miracle drug in several years. Can you
find it?
</P>
<P>
   _ Jim Henderson, Decatur, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Often bathroom-cabinet favorites come back in different
guises. Mercurochrome no longer exists but has morphed into
Mercuroclear II, a clear antiseptic that, says the manufacturer,
``helps prevent infection and relieves pain and itching of minor
cuts, burns and insect bites.'' A 1-ounce bottle is $2.99. The
first aid antiseptic merthiolate is no longer red and doesn't sting
but is still used for minor skin irritations. A 1-ounce bottle is
$2.99. Both are at Miller's Rexall Drugs, 87 Broad St.
(404-523-8481).
</P>
<P>
   Reader Miles will soon be washing her hands with pHisoderm
Antibacterial Hand Cleanser. This soap, says manufacturer Chattem,
``kills a wide range of germs hands come in contact with _ without
drying skin.'' A 6-ounce bottle is $2.83, also at Miller's Rexall
Drugs. We also found a 6-ounce bottle ($1.29) at MacFrugal's
Bargains Close-Outs, 2581 Piedmont Road N.E. (404-237-1919).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Recently I moved from New Mexico to Atlanta and have been
unable to find Milkman Instant Lowfat Dry Milk. It's perfect for
camping trips or to keep on hand for emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bren Goode, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: Touted as having the ``kiss of cream,'' Milkman Instant
Lowfat Dry Milk (four 1-quart envelopes, $2.99) is available at
Publix stores, including locations at 2900 Peachtree Road N.E.,
1544 Piedmont Road N.E., 3200 Holcomb Bridge Road, Norcross, and
3435 Ashford Dunwoody Road N.E.
</P>
<P>
   When mixed with water, Milkman contains 1/2 percent milkfat and
an added touch of cream for taste. And it's a snap to make. Simply
put the contents of one envelope into 1/2 quart of water, stirring
constantly with a spoon. Add water to make a quart, chill and
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for Hard as Nails, which I used to buy in New
York. It worked wonders on strengthening my nails. But I can't find
it here.
</P>
<P>
   _ Darlene Cherry, Buford, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: We nailed down Hard as Nails at Kmart stores and found our
.45-ounce bottle ($2.49) at the 2581 Piedmont Road N.E. location
(404-261-6900). Sally Hansen bills its product as ``the nail clinic
in a bottle!'' Nail edges ``are sealed for added protection against
chipping, cracking and splitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for a Fizz-Keeper, a small plastic pump that
screws on 1- or 2-liter bottles of soft drinks. You can pump air
into the bottle to keep it from going flat. I bought the last ones
from Wal-Mart, but my local store does not have them any more.
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Hendershott, Stone Mountain
</P>
<P>
   A: Put a little fizz back into your soft drinks with the
Fizz-Keeper Pump Cap ($2.49), available at Bed Bath &AMP; Beyond
stores. We found ours at the 1 Buckhead Loop N.E. location
(404-869-0457).
</P>
<P>
   It's also available at Lechters in Market Square for $2.99
(404-325-0358). This gizmo is simple to use. Remove the bottle cap
and screw the Fizz-Keeper on tightly. Pump until the plastic bottle
becomes firm. Unscrew and pour. Note: Do not overpump, and use on
plastic bottles only. It fits 1-, 1.5- and 2-liter bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I was a little girl in New York, my dad would go into
one of the Swedish neighborhoods and buy a can of ``fiskbullar,'' a
combination of cod and potatoes combined in oval balls. My father
has passed away, but my Uncle Jack, who still lives in New York,
tells me he would love to have ``fiskbullar'' again. If you could
locate this product, we would be most appreciative.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ruth Hayden, Smyrna, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Both you and your Uncle Jack can enjoy this Swedish treat
once again. We found a version of your fish balls at Arctic Circle,
3741 Venture Drive, Duluth (770-495-0222). A 13.2-ounce can of
Abba's Fiskbullar in dill sauce or lobster sauce is $3.25. These
fish balls, which are made from cod and haddock, traditionally are
served warm with boiled potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
