<SLUG> BC-BUBBLE-TROUBLE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOT.COM BUBBLE BURSTS, BUT IT'S NOT FATAL TO NEW ECONOMY  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 450-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By DIANE COYLE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Sometimes investors seem even more fickle in their
fashions than teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Microsoft verdict this week, the dot.coms and
other high-technology shares had been falling in price, in the
U.S., U.K. and around the globe. Their extraordinary gains last
winter have been going into reverse for more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   So, if there was a bubble in these shares, it has certainly
burst. But the harder question to answer is what real effects this
might have on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Is the New Economy past its sell-by date already, dealt a fatal
blow by the verdict of the U.S. courts on its leading company?
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the charges Microsoft would level against the
U.S. government. But it is wrong. The U.S. Justice Department is
giving the New Economy a new lease of life.
</P>
<P>
   An important reason for the vigor of the American economy in the
past century has been its tough anti-monopoly policies. Tackling
Microsoft's monopoly will stimulate more innovation, more choice
and even lower prices in the high-technology industries.
</P>
<P>
   The great thing about last year's stock market boom was that it
channelled vast amounts of cheap finance to start-up companies. It
made possible a surge of investment in new infrastructure and
markets.
</P>
<P>
   There is a clear parallel with the railway mania of the mid-19th
century, when investors funded thousands of miles of track that
remain to this day the core of the rail network.
</P>
<P>
   It may become a bit harder now for new companies to raise
finance, if share prices continue to languish and the enthusiasm
for untried businesses dims. Yet investors will continue to look
for high-tech opportunities because that is where the prospects for
future economic growth will lie.
</P>
<P>
   They will become a lot more discriminating about where they put
their money. It will no longer be enough to add a dot.com to the
name of the business to rake in the millions.
</P>
<P>
   In the short-term, drastic falls in share prices could trigger a
slowdown in the economy's growth rate. However, as the Bank of
England and its U.S. counterpart, the Federal Reserve, have been
trying to engineer slower growth, that might be no bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   And looking further into the future, there is no doubt that new
technologies have set in motion a transformation of the economy and
society that has barely begun to take shape _ just as the first
rail companies in the 1840s signalled the beginning of urbanization
and mass production.
</P>
<P>
   The dot.com share bubble has been the first hint of an economic
revolution, not its last hurrah. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 450-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
