<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7945 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-MEXICAN-ACTIVIST-HNS &LR;      04-05 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICAN-ACTIVIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STAND AGAINST LOGGING EARNS MEXICAN AN ECOLOGY PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE KAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Goldman Environmental Foundation on
Wednesday awarded a $125,000 prize to a jailed Mexican man whose
rural organization has protested logging in the Sierra Madre.
</P>
<P>
   Rodolfo Montiel Flores, 44, has been imprisoned in Iguala, in
the southern state of Guerrero, since May on drug charges. Montiel
has said he was framed by soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Montiel helped form a union of subsistence farmers and
environmentalists. Over the past several years, they halted trucks
taking old-growth logs to a sawmill once operated by the Boise
Cascade Corp., which exported the lumber.
</P>
<P>
   Montiel and his colleagues charged that the logging practices
deforested and burned the land, virtually drying up major rivers
and killing fish.
</P>
<P>
   Alvaro Umana, the former Costa Rican environment minister and a
juror on the prize committee, announced the award Wednesday in
Mexico City. Montiel has said he would use part of the money to put
in an irrigation system on the land he and others farm.
</P>
<P>
   The Goldman Environmental Foundation will present five other
prizes April 17 at its customary awards event in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual early tribute is timed to aid Montiel in his trial
scheduled for this week. The Mexican federal prosecutor has charged
him with trafficking in drugs and possessing illegal weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club and Amnesty International have named Montiel as
one of 10 environmentalists worldwide who are threatened by
government repression.
</P>
<P>
   Despite reports of torture, death threats and nearly a year of
imprisonment, Montiel continues to speak for the rural
environmental organization he helped form, said Victor Menotti, a
spokesman for the International Forum on Globalization, a San
Francisco nonprofit organization.
</P>
<P>
   Violence in Guerrero increased in June 1995, when state police
officers killed 17 people who were on their way to protest new
logging, Menotti said.
</P>
<P>
   The next month, Idaho-based Boise Cascade leased the sawmill in
Guerrero, and also gained exclusive rights to buy wood from some of
the communally operated lands, called ejidos.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the local people tried to persuade government officials
to stop the logging, saying that it stripped forests of old-growth
pine and fir. Then they disrupted the supply of logs to the
sawmill.
</P>
<P>
   Boise Cascade left Guerrero in 1998, citing difficulties in
fulfilling the timber quota. The corporation blamed lack of roads,
weather and other infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Bartels, a Boise Cascade spokesman, said Tuesday that his
company had contracts to buy logs from two dozen ejidos.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one environmental group on the lowlands that
apparently had concerns over the logging. We're not aware there was
widespread concern,'' Bartels said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican forestry service regulated the logging practices,
Bartels said, and he did not see any abuses when he was there.
</P>
<P>
   Although Boise Cascade was not logging or persecuting the
people, the multinational corporation had to take responsibility as
an instigator of the events, said Stephen Mills, director of the
Sierra Club's international campaign in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``What corporations like Boise Cascade have been involved in,''
said Mills, ``is colluding with governments in opposition to local
communities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
