<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-EDITORIAL-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERELY BREAKING UP MICROSOFT WON'T FIX THE PROBLEM  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Editorial)   (This timely 525-word ``separate-buy'' editorial is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By THE EDITORIAL BOARD OF THE INDEPENDENT  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are probably going to have to get used to Bill Gates's nasal
whine insisting that his company, Microsoft, has done ``nothing
wrong,'' and that Judge Penfield Jackson's verdict on Monday _ that
Microsoft has a monopoly position in computer software and has
abused it _ will stifle his company's ``freedom to innovate.''
</P>
<P>
   But the court evidence clearly showed that it is Gates who is
wrong, and the judge who was right.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is a company that has abused its position in the
software market to try to create a monopoly of Internet operating
systems, and seems determined to extend its hold to handheld
computers and mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is what remedies the judge should prescribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Break the company up,'' some suggest. In theory it sounds
attractive, but in practice it would be like trying to remove
unwanted software from your Windows PC _ a drawn-out process that
never quite seems finished.
</P>
<P>
   How could one define what pieces of software the different
companies should own? Microsoft has worked very hard to blur the
lines.
</P>
<P>
   When Standard Oil was broken up early in the last century, the
process was messy and simply created more powerful siblings. It
would be even more complex with a hi-tech company such as
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than teasing the company strands apart, Judge Jackson has
a simpler remedy available, which would, at a stroke, erase
Microsoft's monopoly while still leaving it ``free to innovate.''
</P>
<P>
   He should make the ``source code'' (the ``GPL'' license) of the
many variants of the Windows operating system now on sale publicly
available, for free, and stipulate that changes must also be made
public.
</P>
<P>
   Not only would that curtail Microsoft's ability to dominate the
market, but it would be a constraint in keeping with the innovative
nature of the business.
</P>
<P>
   The source code is the spell that works the magic on the
machine. See it, and you can see how the beast does its work.
</P>
<P>
   For years, software developers have struggled with the fact that
Windows is like a multi-story building with a few dusty windows,
through which they could glimpse the activity in some rooms, and
write their products according to what they saw in those rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's software developers (for Word, or Access) had
complete access to all of the building, giving them the ability to
write products that used far more facilities. And when the contents
of the rooms changed _ which they did with amazing regularity _
Microsoft always had the head start.
</P>
<P>
   Making the source code freely available would mean there was
still an industry standard that could be referred to.
</P>
<P>
   With the source code published, Microsoft would lose its revenue
stream from operating systems. It would be forced to live on its
wits _ forced to innovate, which is something it has done precious
little of in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   We will have to wait for the judge's remedies, which we feel
should also include large financial penalties to indicate the
damage that has been done to companies such as Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we can reflect on this: the U.S. Department of
Justice has shown that the courts can stop a multinational, given
able lawyers and the right laws. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 525-word editorial from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper
in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
