<HEADER>
A7959 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-THEATER-JORY-SPI &LR;      04-05 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-JORY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMANA DIRECTOR HEADING TO SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFREY ERIC JENKINS  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE _ Look out Seattle, a Louisville Slugger is on the
way. This particular heavy hitter is no candidate for the Baseball
Hall of Fame, but someone should consider making space for him in
the theatrical version.
</P>
<P>
   With the closing of the 24th Humana Festival of New American
Plays this coming weekend, director Jon Jory and his family will
begin making the transition from their home in this languid Ohio
River town to the lively environs of Seattle's U District.
</P>
<P>
   After 31 years as artistic head of Actors Theatre of Louisville
_ where he produced nearly 1,400 productions that included more
than 290 new plays _ Jory will join the University of Washington
School of Drama in the fall as a tenured professor.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, though, Jory and his talented spouse, costume
designer Marcia Dixcy Jory, have their hands full with an annual
new play festival that attracts critics, agents, producers and
theater people from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 festival includes works by 31 playwrights, a
satisfyingly symmetrical number considering the length of Jory's
tenure in Louisville. As in past years, though, only a half-dozen
of the 33 pieces on display can be considered fully realized
dramatic works. A 75-minute dramatic anthology of 19 scenes, for
instance, is little more than a contrivance to make sure that
festival visitors see performances by the company's young
apprentices.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's innovation, so-called ``phone plays,'' already
appears somewhat shopworn. The now-traditional 10-minute plays
feature Tina Howe, Naomi Wallace and David Ives writing crisp, if
familiar vignettes. But all of the brief interludes are mere
appetizers for the main course of six full-length plays.
</P>
<P>
   Many playwrights have become identified with the Humana
festival, but none more so than Kentucky playwright Jane Martin.
The pseudonymous Martin frequently tackles subjects that are edgy
and ``politically incorrect'' _ often topics of particular interest
to women. But the author tends to balance her conflicts and avoid
simplistic resolutions to issues.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one who has ever seen her will describe her, many
believe Jory himself is Martin. He is her director at Humana and
his own plays stopped appearing about the time that she arrived on
the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever Martin is, though, she is certainly a sophisticated
observer of the theater. Her current comedy, ``Anton in Show
Business,'' lacerates everyone in sight as she satirizes actors,
directors, producers, funders and critics. Seven women play 16
roles _ including several male ones _ as the author pokes fun at
Hollywood ambition, cross-dressing, multiculturalism and the grand
tradition of rehearsal romance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anton'' looks at the troubles encountered when artists with
big aspirations (and very little money) attempt a production of
Chekhov's ``The Three Sisters'' in San Antonio _ a city notorious
for its battles over arts funding in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   One critic seated nearby turned and said, ``it's the great
kiss-off.'' But Martin's own critic in the play _ who is planted in
the audience and stops the action from time to time to question or
complain _ turns the author's pen on herself when she complains
that the play satirizes ``something dead in culture'' (theater),
which is like ``beating a dead horse ... from the inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-consciously echoing the Chekhov play in its approach to the
importance of work, Martin's play is ultimately upbeat and
life-affirming. Crisply staged by Jory, ``Anton'' is both raucously
funny and painful to watch. And we never quite shake the sense that
this is a farewell to the troops.
</P>
<P>
   The other strong showing at the festival is Charles F. Mee's
``Big Love,'' a sprawling tale _ literally and figuratively _ that
pits 50 brides against 50 brothers. Based on Aeschylus' ``The
Suppliant Women,'' the play unearths every unpleasant stereotype
about the relationships between men and women. The antagonists rant
and rail at one another until words no longer suffice. Then,
passions bubble up from deep within their bodies and the actors
explode in a maelstrom of physical expression. The result is
powerfully affecting in its humor and its madness.
</P>
<P>
   In ``War of the Worlds,'' director Anne Bogart examines the life
and work of Orson Welles by mirroring the director's storytelling
style in the film ``Citizen Kane.'' But beneath the surface of the
Welles story, Bogart and her collaborator, Naomi Iizuka, also probe
the nature of truth, reality and identity. Notions of ``reality''
are commented on by shifting our gaze away from what we know or
believe to be true. Bogart and Iizuka demonstrate how reality can
be constructed by manipulating its presentation. The lingering
image of this poignant piece is that of an artist unhinged by his
personal demons.
</P>
<P>
   We expect artists to raise questions about life and our role in
the world around us. In this year's festival offerings, there seems
to be more pondering than usual. Why, these playwrights seem to
ask, must we live with so much pain?
</P>
<P>
   For the departing Jory, an exciting new life awaits in Seattle.
There is a new home, new students, new colleagues. Will the
artistic directorates of Seattle theaters open their doors to the
accomplished director? They are foolish if they do not.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, we needn't weep for Jory. Now that he is no
longer burdened with running the most important new play festival
in the United States, his work is bound to appear in theaters
around the country, off-Broadway and on.
</P>
<P>
   There's just one other question. Will Jane Martin fit into his
suitcase?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1645EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
