</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-WEBSEARCH-TEST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTER WAYS TO SEARCH THAN TYPING `NEEDLE AND HAYSTACK' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    Lisa Napoli is the Internet correspondent for MSNBC.
 By LISA NAPOLI  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The modern equivalent of searching for a needle in a haystack is
searching for just about anything on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate this, three very different people were asked to
track down three very different items in a random, completely
unscientific test _ a sort of digital treasure hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, this trio of e-commerce guinea pigs followed
similar paths. Each conducted highly focused searches, and at some
stage each used the search engine Yahoo, which could explain why
that company is valued at more than $70 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Vanderbilt, vice president and senior analyst with
Jupiter Communications, an online research firm, was then enlisted
to comment on the searchers' strategies and offer advice for doing
it better next time. Knowing where to look in the first place, how
to phrase a search term and how to weed through sites returned by
the search engine, she said, are techniques that consumers learn
over time.
</P>
<P>
   ASSIGNMENT: HAWAIIAN SHIRT. Searcher: Alesia Powell of New York.
Clicks: three.
</P>
<P>
   My friend Alesia Powell, 38, has never surfed waves in her life,
and she goes out of her way not to go to stores. So she seemed the
perfect person to assign the task of finding a Hawaiian shirt. It's
not something that she has ever done, or ever would do.
</P>
<P>
   Alesia, who works at CBS Healthwatch, a Web company, started at
Yahoo, typing in ``Hawaiian shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Why there? ``Yahoo was easier and offered a lot more specific
choices,'' she said. ``I always think of Excite afterwards, and I
can never remember the name of Larcos, or is it Lycos?''
</P>
<P>
   Her search returned 10 entries, listed under ``Business and
Economy. Companies. Apparel. Specialty. Hawaiian.'' She chose the
third one on the list: ``Big Kahuna Hawaiian Shirts''
(www.aloha-bigkahuna.com/bkframe.html).
</P>
<P>
   Why? ``The name jumped out at me,'' she said. ``I associated it
with Hawaiian shirts, although the listing above it was for a
company called Aloha, and that's very Hawaiian, I guess. Big Kahuna
just looked interesting to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The site, however, proved to be not as interesting as its name.
Being a high-end-fabric kind of person, Alesia clicked on one of
five areas offered on the site _ a page pertaining to silk shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``These don't look like the classic shirt,'' she said. ``But
then again, I hate Hawaiian shirts.''
</P>
<P>
   Interesting to note: using ``Hawaiian shirts,'' plural, turned
up a different set of shops from ``Hawaiian shirt,'' singular.
</P>
<P>
   Though it didn't happen in this case, nuances in keywords often
trip up Web surfers, Vanderbilt noted. Our search expert added,
``The more tenured online users have a better sense of how to
construct the right keyword searches.''
</P>
<P>
   Lesson learned: Watch your search terms. Try a plural if
singular does not yield what you're looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ASSIGNMENT: CHERRY RED 1965 MUSTANG. Searcher: Brian Stelter of
Damascus, Md. Clicks: seven.
</P>
<P>
   Who better to search for a classic car than a youngster who does
not have his driver's license yet? I asked my online pen pal, Brian
Stelter, 14, to shop for a cherry red '65 Mustang because he's more
into computers than cars, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Brian started on eBay. ``I thought I had gotten lucky when I
read a listing for '1965 Dark Cherry Red Mustang convertible,''' he
wrote in an e-mail report. ``But I was mistaken: it was only a toy
model.''
</P>
<P>
   He then reverted to Alesia's search engine of choice, Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt commented that Yahoo has ``done a good job of
building a brand that means 'Come here to find what you want.'''
</P>
<P>
   For this search, however, that didn't turn out to be the case:
the site led Brian to two Canadian companies selling classic
Mustang replacement parts.
</P>
<P>
   Then he tried another search site, AltaVista, which steered him
to the ``Classic Mustang Message Board''
(www.metromustang.com/classic/wwwboard.htm). Brian reports: ``I
began to hit pay dirt here. '65 Mustang needs good home,' one
message read.'' But no red.
</P>
<P>
   Another site on AltaVista contained car trivia and reprints of
Ford brochures, and another contained links to 22 chapters of the
Mustang Club of America. Still another took Brian to posters of the
elusive car.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring plain old classifieds were his best bet, he clicked on
something called ``Statewide Car Connection''
(www.carbuyer.com/moreinfo.phtml?key(EQ)113332&AMP;s(EQ)stw), which had
also appeared in his AltaVista search.
</P>
<P>
   In seconds, he turned up three Mustangs of the appropriate
vintage and color.
</P>
<P>
   Which one would Brian buy, if he had his druthers and the
appropriate papers? He may be young, but he is pragmatic: ``I would
buy the first one I found, the one with the fire painted on it.
It's cheapest and looks the nicest, plus it's sitting only an hour
away from where I live.''
</P>
<P>
   Lesson learned: Sometimes the best place to look is the most
obvious. As Vanderbilt said, ``What the unique products have going
for them is, if they're tough to find on the Internet, they are
even harder to find off-line.''
</P>
<P>
   ASSIGNMENT: HAMMOCK. Searcher: Vince Napoli of Boca Raton, Fla.
Clicks: six.
</P>
<P>
   A New Yorker who now lives in Boca Raton, Fla., my dad, Vince,
66, is not a hammock sort of person. He hardly sits still. That's
why I assigned him the task of finding the ultimate relaxation
device.
</P>
<P>
   He, too, started with Yahoo, clicking on the search engine's
shopping area. ``They found 451 products in 83 stores,'' he
reported. Some of the hammocks were not the classic backyard
variety. The search page featured a cat hammock and a ferret
hammock, as well as a hammock for fruit, alligators and fish.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four hammock merchants listed, Dad looked at all and
settled on Nicamaka from Nicaragua
(http://store.yahoo.com/buyhammocks/bluebecouphamm.html) for much
the same reason that Alesia chose the store she did: it just felt
right.
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``The site was easy to get around and has good
information and visuals for the products they sell. It lists all
kinds of hammocks for land and boats. And they have a shopping cart
for easy order and list their regular and sales prices.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Alesia and Vince both responded to sites that
simply caught their eyes ``points to an absence of really good
comparison shopping,'' Vanderbilt said.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce merchants and Web portals need to be more mindful of
the challenges faced by consumers in conducting a search, and
search engines need to provide deeper data for consumer
decision-making, she said. It takes more than a strong first
impression to drive consumers to a site.
</P>
<P>
   Though fabric hammocks turned out to be more expensive than
rope, Vince said he would opt for the former, particularly a
five-stripe model built for two, for $198.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like it wouldn't sag after use,'' he said, citing
photographs of people in rope hammocks who appear to be scraping
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson learned: Virtual shopping is often based on visceral
reactions, just as it is in the brick-and-mortar world.
</P>
<P>
   Postscript
</P>
<P>
   While all three searches were successful, Vanderbilt points out
that the e-commerce guinea pigs were engaged in a very particular
type of shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Such focused searches _ ``intended'' shopping, in industry
parlance _ are what the Web supports best, she said: ``Where
there's huge e-commerce growth opportunity is in changing shopping
behavior and increasing impulse purchases.''
</P>
<P>
   Higher bandwidth will help encourage more people to simply
browse for merchandise online, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean that coming soon to a computer near you is the
digital equivalent of the checkout-counter tchotchke?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
