<SLUG> BC-ECOM-ETAIL-PRIMER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONEY, THERE'S A DOT-COM GROWING IN THE LIVING ROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480,
fax 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333, fax
212-499-3382.)
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 By ROSEMARY BRESLIN 
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ``Good afternoon, Anthony Dunne's office _ I'll see if Mr.
Dunne's available.''
</P>
<P>
   I pressed the hold button.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony!'' I shouted toward the open bathroom. ``It's Thomas
O'Brien!''
</P>
<P>
   There was excitement in my voice about the return call from
O'Brien, the hot interior designer, but I added, ``Once in a while,
could you please close the door?''
</P>
<P>
   Our communal office bathroom was adjacent to our main working
space, our 276-square-foot living room.
</P>
<P>
   That was where we set up shop last spring when, at 45, my
husband, Tony Dunne, gave up the security of the insecure movie
business, where he was the set builder on films such as ``Die Hard
With a Vengeance'' (1995) and ``Ransom'' (1997), to pursue an
Internet idea: the first virtual interior-design center.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 15 years, Tony had informally designed interiors
for family members, friends and people in the movie business. Last
May, he was designing two apartments when he returned home from a
long day spent in the maze of furniture showrooms.
</P>
<P>
   He sat on the couch and said, ``I've been thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   In great detail, he laid out his idea for HauteDecor.com, which
would bring together about 20 top interior designers and have each
create virtual rooms, in which everything would be for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The site would offer the best of home furnishings and
accessories to designers as well as consumers. Shoppers could
choose from thousands of items selected by design professionals.
</P>
<P>
   It would be like shopping in New York or London from your office
or living room. It would be like looking at a magazine and being
inside the rooms. Rather than turn to the back of a magazine for
information, visitors could click on the item and find what they
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Though I knew little about the Internet and e-commerce, I knew I
was hearing a good idea. I also knew that it was perfect for Tony
because it would use his film background, computer skills _
computers have been used in set design for years _ business acumen
and knowledge of interior design.
</P>
<P>
   And it was a grownup idea. It would never occur to a kid playing
videos and eating Cheetos at an Internet incubator.
</P>
<P>
   As I studied Tony's diagrams for the site, I knew I could help
him execute the concept. As a writer, I had always worked under
enormous pressure with brutal deadlines. I found it all fun. We
both did.
</P>
<P>
   And so I offered my services and became Tony's first employee:
assistant and messenger.
</P>
<P>
   To both of us, the e-commerce and movie businesses seemed
similar. Both required tremendous manpower, equipment and money, as
well as highly complex tasks, all in a compressed time frame. That
was crucial to making the transition for us. We simply applied our
movie skills to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is the script _ it had better be great. The venture
capitalists who provide the money are the studio executives. The
teams who get the site running are the teams who make a movie. The
Web site is the movie. The site's debut is the release.
</P>
<P>
   Even the big egos are the same. The business people think they
are most important _ the creative people know the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Both businesses thrive on gossip and on people spewing opinions
with great authority. The accumulated knowledge does not add up to
much: Columbia Pictures passed on ``E.T. The Extra-Terrestrial''
(1982), even with Steven Spielberg involved. Bill Gates, among
others, was decidedly cool about the Internet's future but has
since changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   People talk as if they know. Nobody knows.
</P>
<P>
   Once we started to execute the idea, it turned out to be as hard
as we had thought it would be _ which means that you really had no
idea how hard it would be, and your naivete is the only thing you
have going for you.
</P>
<P>
   You actually believe it is going to get easier, and so when it
keeps getting tougher and reaches the point where it has taken over
your life, you still believe that it is going to lighten up. That
is before you find yourself stopping at Banana Republic to buy
socks and underwear on the way to a meeting, or stealing toilet
paper from a friend's hotel room because that is one item the
coffee shop doesn't deliver.
</P>
<P>
   As in a movie, you are behind before you begin. My original deal
with Tony had been six hours in the afternoons for $20 an hour, off
the books. By Week 2, I was working 14 hours a day, and the guy was
not coughing up the dough. Oh, this is the movie business, all
right _ everyone lies.
</P>
<P>
   Just wait it out. There comes a time when you are indispensable,
and then you've got them. As we refined the concept, Tony and I saw
the need for editorial content, which helps drive people to the
site and keeps them there. And so I was offered the job of
HauteDecor's editorial director. I would have been a whole lot
nicer about my deal had he paid me when I was an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Money is always the hardest part. We chose to take what in film
is called the studio route. The nature and scope of the project
required financing from a large venture-capital firm. Because we
did not know anyone at such a firm, we spoke to every single friend
we have.
</P>
<P>
   My most important recommendation: Do not be coy _ no one
appreciates it. If I thought a friend could somehow help, I started
the call with, ``I need a favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Do not ask about their kids or their work or their last
vacation. This is business. They will respect you for that, even if
they cannot help.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last eight months, Tony and I have made easily 1,000
calls and met with countless friends, acquaintances and strangers
whom we found through friends and acquaintances. A little buzz
started, and people started calling us. Most conversations went
nowhere, but a few were exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   That is how we found financing. Other people might have a more
sophisticated strategy, but this one worked for us.
</P>
<P>
   We identified two people who we believed were serious. Tony met
with the first one several times. Together, on a Sunday morning, we
met with the second at the Carlyle Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Over breakfast, Tony laid out his HauteDecor plan for
entrepreneur Kevin Kinsella and his wife, Tamara. Thirty minutes
into breakfast _ and 29 minutes after his eyes told me he was
hooked _ Kevin said he wanted in on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would provide the $1 million seed capital needed to
get the idea moving. He made a commitment to help raise, in stages,
at least $25 million to $30 million, which is what he and Tony
determined it would cost to execute the site. He laid out the
deal's terms, and the firms and people he would ask for money. We
were familiar with a number of them.
</P>
<P>
   Back at our base, Tony returned to command central: the couch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think he's for real?'' he asked, knowing the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' I said, knowing that my next words would determine
our future. Tony would not go forward without my support. ``Let's
do it,'' I said, but not in a silly, gung-ho way.
</P>
<P>
   On July 1, Kevin wired the initial $500,000 to the HauteDecor
account. A month later, we moved ourselves and four new employees
from our living room into a 2,500-square-foot space in the Flatiron
district of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie business, when every element is in place and
everyone is betting on success, the production is given a green
light. That's where we are now.
</P>
<P>
   With financing mainly from the Institutional Venture
Partners/Redpoint, we will spend the next five months continuing to
create and build the Web site, form alliances, work with
manufacturers and designers, write editorial content and perform a
long list of other tasks with the other employees, who seem to
arrive on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   By the time we begin in August, there will be 120 of us in an
18,000-square-foot space, 62 times the size of our living room,
where this venture started as a conversation between two people.
</P>
<P>
   HauteDecor.com _ coming to a computer screen near you.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Rosemary Breslin, a writer, is the editorial director of the
New York-based Haute-Decor.com.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7970 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-CHINA-NYTSF &LR;      04-05 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-CHINA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACKING THE WEB TO REMOTE WESTERN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480,
fax 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333, fax
212-499-3382.)
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 By JENNIFER 8. LEE  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The roads in Gansu, China, are sometimes barely roads. Bathrooms
are pits in the ground. Fur coats are a necessity, not fashion. In
a nod to tradition, and for self-defense, some men travel with
swords at their sides.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, thanks to modem connections and the efforts of local
entrepreneurs, the Internet is trickling into back alleys and
basements of the most remote regions of western China. A nationwide
system of local Internet service providers was completed last year,
and now the seven westernmost provinces _ half of China's land,
with 20 percent of its population _ account for 5 percent of the
country's Internet use.
</P>
<P>
   So, when in early January I set out with my backpack and no
itinerary for a seven-week trek through the mountains and deserts
of western China, e-mail was the intercontinental umbilical cord
that tethered me to my anxious mother, 12,000 miles away in New
York. From Inner Mongolia to Kashgar to Lhasa, I hunted for the
elusive wang ba, or ``Net bar,'' to send reassuring updates.
</P>
<P>
   Some things are better left out of such dispatches,
incidentally: I did not tell my mother about the time my bus almost
slipped off an icy mountain road, or about another bus that fell
off a cliff outside Lhasa, killing 12 people.
</P>
<P>
   In the one-room Net bar in Kashgar, where eight personal
computers were strung together with a tangle of wires, the
coal-burning stove, spewing black smoke, was not enough to keep my
fingers from becoming too cold to type.
</P>
<P>
   In the monastery town of Xiahe, in Gansu Province, Internet
users look out the window at the mule-drawn carts and the nomadic
herdsmen who trudge along the town's one main street, oblivious to
the information revolution.
</P>
<P>
   While the Internet may be a web of dreams, China is a country of
stark realities. Like its roads and infrastructure, China's
Internet is being sewn together piecemeal and unevenly, but it is
coming together.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on where you go and whom you ask, China is alternately
prosperous or poor, cutting-edge modern or heart-achingly backward.
</P>
<P>
   Multinational corporations salivate over magazine images of
Levi-clad adolescents eating at the McDonald's in Shanghai and
talking on their Nokia cell phones. But that slice of the
demographic pie is very slim and very urban. More than two-thirds
of China's 1.2 billion people are rural, and the overwhelming
majority of that rural population is poor.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 45 percent of China's Internet users live in Shanghai,
Beijing or in the affluent province of Guangdong, which together
account for only 8 percent of the country's total population.
Approximately 80 percent of users live in large cities.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 80 percent are men, and 85 percent are 18 to 35,
according to a government-sponsored survey by the China Internet
Network Information Center. Few rural residents can afford
computers or the fees charged by their local Internet bars, the
equivalent of $2.50 to $4 an hour. Urban Internet bars are cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet presence reflects these disparities. A wang ba can
be a sleek mirrored club, with uniformed attendants bringing tea to
customers at their computers, or a dirt-floor hovel where men
huddle under dim lighting. Beyond larger cities, wang-ba customers
are largely foreign tourists seeking quaint, traditional villages
but demanding modern communications services.
</P>
<P>
   Many wang bas use the names Hotmail and Yahoo as synonyms for
Internet access on their store signs. These services' increasing
presence is leading the way for infiltration of the Internet
throughout the underdeveloped areas of China.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, local residents who go to wang bas seem more
interested in the multiplayer video games than in the potential for
revolutionizing commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Jin, who owns Tim's Internet Cafe in Dali, in Yunnan
Province, estimates that 95 percent of his customers are
foreigners, 4 percent come from other parts of China and less than
1 percent are local residents.
</P>
<P>
   As for e-commerce, Jin says, a number of the communities
surrounding Dali still do their purchasing and bargaining at weekly
outdoor markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way we can do an e-commerce site here,'' he says, citing
the lack of infrastructure in Yunnan, the difficulty of
transportation and the low population density. ``In big cities and
through foreign mail-order companies, maybe. Locally, there's no
way.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Tibetan capital of Lhasa, which is not connected to China
by railroad, Tsering Tashi opened the Khang Li Internet Bar as soon
as Tibet established an Internet service provider last year. He
says it was the only Tibetan-owned Internet bar in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   Within 10 months, he says, he recovered his original investment
of almost $10,000. Still, nearly all of his customers are tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tibetans almost never use high technology _ they don't
understand it,'' Tashi says. ``They have heard of the Internet, but
the Internet cafe is a wholly new concept to them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the offseason, October through February, he converts most of
his Internet cafe into a clothing store.
</P>
<P>
   Sluggish connections are a problem throughout China. In
mid-February, Jin closed his cafe for two days because the Internet
was too slow, particularly the e-mail provider Hotmail, which 80
percent of his customers use.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, China is changing rapidly, and so is the Internet.
Entrepreneurs say they are optimistic that logistical obstacles can
be overcome.
</P>
<P>
   But corporate profits in China have historically been elusive.
Ask any multinational corporation that has set up shop in China in
the last decade, eager to tap into the billion-customer market.
Most companies are still waiting for the investments to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Plagued by distribution difficulties, inflated estimates of
demand and bureaucratic red tape, more businesses are leaving
China, deciding that the market can wait.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, profits in e-commerce are elusive as well, though
not only in China. E-business opportunities in China could
therefore prove to be doubly difficult.
</P>
<P>
   But low costs and tourists' cash, it turns out, can become a
very workable, albeit modest, business plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fundamental goal is to make money,'' Tashi says. ``So far,
the Internet has been very good for making money.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jennifer 8. Lee is studying international relations at Beijing
University.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
