<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By J.D.BIERSDORFER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have so many programs on my computer that I can't see the
whole list in the Windows 98 Start menu. Is there any way to
rearrange the list so I can get my most-used programs together in
one place?
</P>
<P>
   A. Windows 98 very helpfully adds most newly installed software
applications to the Programs list, but the list can get rather
lengthy if you have a large number of them. New programs are added
to the list in alphabetical order by default, with folders coming
before single items.
</P>
<P>
   You can rearrange the programs so that you can find them more
quickly on the list. In the Start menu, click on the program folder
or item that you would like to move, then drag it to where you want
it to be.
</P>
<P>
   If you use just a few applications repeatedly, the easiest place
to put them is in the center of the Programs list. You may also
want to consider making desktop shortcuts for them or loading them
into your Startup items area so they are ready to go when you boot
your computer.
</P>
<P>
   There is an alternative to rearranging the list: If you are
trying to get to a specific program, like Microsoft Word, you can
quickly jump to that area of the list by typing the first letter of
the folder or item. Clicking on Start and then typing M, for
example, will send you right into the part of the list where the
programs starting with M reside.
</P>
<P>
   If you find that your Programs menu is cluttered with
applications that you rarely use, you can remove them from the list
without removing the actual program from your hard disk. In the
Start menu, go to Settings and select Taskbar. In the box, click on
the Start Menu Programs tab and then on Remove. In the list that
appears, click on the programs you want to remove from the menu and
click on Remove again.
</P>
<P>
   If you would like to rename a program in the list (doing so will
not affect the actual program on your computer), go to the same
Start Menu Programs box and click on Advanced. In the Contents of
Start Menu area of the Windows Explorer window, find the program
you want to rename. Right-click on the program name, select Rename,
type in the new name and hit the Enter key.
</P>
<P>
   Mac users who find unwanted program alias files in the Apple
Menu can go to the Apple Menu Items folder inside the System folder
on the hard drive and drag unwanted aliases to the trash. Users can
also change the names of the Apple menu's alias files by retyping
them _ just make sure they are alias files and not the original
program icons.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm having printing problems in Windows 98 and was told that
I should make sure I have the right printer driver on my computer.
I don't see the name of my printer in the list, so how can I find
the right driver?
</P>
<P>
   A. Having the correct printer driver for your PC or Mac is vital
to trouble-free printing because the driver tells the computer
exactly what kind of printer you have and what it can do. Without
the right driver, you may be experiencing quirky output from your
printer or may not be able to print at all.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best place to find missing printer drivers is on the
floppy disks or CD-ROM that came with the printer. Check the
printer manual for instructions on where to find the driver and how
to install it. If you no longer have the disk or the manual, you
can often find a library of printer drivers available for download
on the Web site of the company that made your printer. If you don't
have Web access, call the company's technical support number and
ask about how to obtain the software.
</P>
<P>
   If you are new to the world of device drivers and have a
connection to the Web, you may want to check out the Driver Guide
at www.driverguide.com. The site asks each new user to register,
but it is free and offers a wealth of information about device
drivers, including those for printers. You can find links to major
manufacturers of printers and other hardware, as well as tutorials
on how to install and update your drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to Q&AMP;A(at)nytimes.com or mail to Questions, Circuits, The
New York Times, 229 West 43rd St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959. This
column will answer questions of general interest, but letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(JT)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
