<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7978 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV4     04-05 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV409-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOW BUSH AND GORE SHOULD CHOOSE A RUNNING MATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, April 9)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Al Gore and George W. Bush have roughly four months
to ponder the first fateful decision that a presidential nominee
must make _ the selection of a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The decision always is a gamble. The vice president, occupying
the post that John Adams described as ``the most insignificant
office that ever the invention of man contrived,'' may at any
moment succeed to one of the most significant offices ever devised
_ commander-in-chief of the world's richest and most powerful
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Some vice presidents have been nonentities, chosen simply to
provide a party's ticket with geographic, age or philosophical
balance. Others, such as Hubert Humphrey and Nelson Rockefeller,
have been men of stature who would have made excellent presidents.
</P>
<P>
   In the past century, four vice presidents _ Theodore Roosevelt,
Calvin Coolidge, Harry Truman and Lyndon Johnson _ have succeeded
to the presidency on the death of the incumbent and one _ Gerald
Ford _ on the resignation of the incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president can emerge as a highly influential force
within the president's White House team or fade into the
background. It all depends on the veep's own leadership qualities
and relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution provides only limited duty for the vice
president _ to preside over the Senate, cast the deciding tally
when there is a tie vote and take over the presidency when the
incumbent dies, resigns or is declared unable to fulfill his
duties.
</P>
<P>
   The vice presidency has played a significant role in the
political fortunes of both Gore and Bush, and how they approach and
resolve the matter of a running mate could provide an insight into
how they would conduct themselves in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who in 1988 ran an unsuccessful campaign for the
Democratic presidential nomination, was chosen as Bill Clinton's
running mate in 1992 and since then has become the president's
highly valued partner in both national and international matters.
</P>
<P>
   In designating Gore for that office, Clinton chose a moderate
Democrat from Arkansas' neighboring state of Tennessee who is two
years his junior and shares his aspirations for America. Clinton
thus abandoned the philosophical, generational and geographic
criteria that normally play a role in the nomination of a vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Gore unquestionably is the most influential vice
president in history.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, his father's elevation to vice president by Ronald
Reagan in the 1980 election followed by the senior Bush's own
presidency from 1989 to 1993 provided the name identification,
money connections and political ties that helped propel George W.
toward the nation's highest office.
</P>
<P>
   A far less successful choice was President Bush's designation in
1988 of Dan Quayle as his running mate. Quayle, a second-term
senator, was virtually unknown outside his home state of Indiana
and had little influence in the Senate. He was viewed by many
Americans as something of a sad joke.
</P>
<P>
   But the senior Bush was 64 at the time he was nominated and,
emulating Dwight Eisenhower's selection of Richard Nixon, who was
23 years Ike's junior, he chose Quayle who was 40 years old and the
grandson of Indiana's most prominent newspaper publisher, the late
Eugene Pulliam.
</P>
<P>
   Like his son 12 years later, President Bush was under strong
pressure to name an abortion foe. He started with a lengthy list of
possible vice presidents, headed by Bob Dole, his wife Elizabeth
Dole, former Rep. Jack Kemp and at least 12 others including John
McCain, a Vietnam War hero who was a U.S. senator from Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo from one GOP campaign adviser to another, Roger Ailes
wrote that Quayle ``looks like Robert Redford, only he is better
looking. He symbolizes youth in the future of the Republican
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   So George Herbert Walker Bush named Quayle, who was identified
with the GOP's right wing. If Americans remember nothing else from
the 1988 campaign, they recall the televised debate between Quayle
and the Democratic vice presidential nominee, then-Texas Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen.
</P>
<P>
   During that confrontation Quayle proudly claimed to have had as
much experience in government as John F. Kennedy did when he sought
he presidency in 1960. The words were barely out of his mouth when
Bentsen caustically declared, ``Senator, I served with Jack
Kennedy. I knew Jack Kennedy. Jack Kennedy was a friend of mine.
Senator, you are no Jack Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's feeble response was that Bentsen's remark was ``really
uncalled for.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bush is not expected to make a similar mistake this
year. When asked whether his running mate would have to pass an
anti-abortion litmus test, George W. has replied that the only
qualification he would look for in a running mate would be his or
her ability to serve as president.
</P>
<P>
   George W.'s most popular choice of a running mate would be
McCain, but the Arizona senator has vowed that he will not run for
that office.
</P>
<P>
   Three talented governors could also enhance the GOP ticket and
presumably serve well in the White House _ New Jersey's Christine
Todd Whitman, Pennsylvania's Tom Ridge and New York's George
Pataki. Ohio Rep. John Kasich, an expert in budgetary matters, and
Nebraska Senator Chuck Hagel could prove attractive and qualified
candidates. Elizabeth Dole also is available.
</P>
<P>
   Gore could choose former New Jersey Senator Bill Bradley who
opposed him in the primaries or one of several senators _
California's Dianne Feinstein, Massachusetts' John Kerry, Florida's
Bob Graham, Indiana's Evan Bayh and Nebraska's Bob Kerrey, who is
retiring from the Senate. A long shot, but a good one, would be
California Gov. Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The day that either party would choose a vice presidential
nominee who lacks strong qualifications for the presidency should
be over. We no longer can afford a vice president who is a joke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
