<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7980 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-HOSPITAL-TRANSLAT     04-05 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HOSPITAL-TRANSLATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILTERING THE DOCTOR-PATIENT RELATIONSHIP THROUGH A TRANSLATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, Dr. William Bateman looked for a way to break down
the language barriers that hampered patient care at the Manhattan
hospital where he worked as medical director. It was no easy task:
the hospital, Gouverneur, was located on the Lower East Side of
Manhattan, a neighborhood mostly made up of Hispanic and Chinese
immigrants. Half the patients could not speak English fluently.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have been using hospital volunteers or nurses when they
needed interpreters, but that practice has its shortcomings. Those
people often have no training in medical interpretation. Sometimes
the patient interacts more with the interpreter than with the
doctor. At other times, the patient is reluctant to talk honestly
to the doctor with a third person in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Then five years ago, a colleague told Bateman about medical
interpretation technology that was being developed in California.
The concept seemed simple enough: Equip doctors and patients with
wireless headsets, and hook those up to a bank of staff people
trained in simultaneous interpretation, as is done at the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, Gouverneur became one of two medical centers in the
country to introduce the technology as an alternative to on-site
interpreters. Medical staff members and patients in the adult
medicine and mental health departments now have the option of
speaking with one another by using headsets that connect with
simultaneous interpreters, five floors above them, who speak
Spanish, Cantonese and Mandarin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Effective communication is the fuel that drives medical
service,'' said Bateman, now the director of business development
at the hospital. ``Communication to us is like the Standard Oil of
the industrial age.''
</P>
<P>
   Using a system designed by a company called Simulmed, the doctor
and the patient both wear headsets connected to a small black
transmitter box that can be looped around the neck or onto a belt.
The speech is transmitted wirelessly to a nearby receiver and then
sent digitally over a fiber-optic line to a central switching
station in the interpreter room.
</P>
<P>
   There, people wearing headsets translate the speech, which is
then transmitted back to the doctor and the patient. By using a
toggle switch, the translator ensures that the doctor and the
patient hear only their own languages.
</P>
<P>
   Each interpreter speaks each word almost as soon as it is heard
through the headset.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the wireless transmission technology is the same as
that used by theater producers and football coaches. But William
Wood, founder of Simulmed, based in Foster City, Calif., said that
within the next year the technology would start using
nonproprietary Ethernet transmission, a cheaper and more flexible
method that lets new users, even at locations outside the hospital,
join the system more easily. The only difference that speakers will
notice is that they will wear headsets that communicate to cell
phones on their belts in place of the radio transmitter boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Using simultaneous interpretation in a one-on-one medical
setting was the brainchild of Dr. Count Gibson, a professor
emeritus at the Stanford University School of Medicine. As a young
lieutenant in the United States Army medical corps, Gibson spent
several hours at the Nuremberg trials after World War II. He picked
up a headset and listened as the testimonies of Nazi war criminals
were interpreted simultaneously into five languages.
</P>
<P>
   When the trials ended, the interpreters moved to New York to
work for the United Nations, and Gibson carried with him the germ
of an idea that would see fruition in the mid-1980s. That was when
he met Wood, who was running a company that provided simultaneous
interpretation at business conferences. Gibson's interest in
interpretation had been reawakened by his years at Stanford, where
he saw a large number of patients who spoke only Spanish or
Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   The first headsets that Gibson and Wood developed had wires
connecting them to remote interpreters. With a Kaiser Family
Foundation grant, they upgraded to wireless transmission and
introduced the technology in a pilot program in the Santa Clara
County Valley Medical Center, where many patients speak only
Spanish. A second study was completed in 1996, and the center is
installing the technology for use in its physical therapy
department.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Garcia, the center's language services coordinator, said
the new system saved time because the interpreters did not have to
show up in person. It also allows doctors and patients to maintain
more eye contact. ``This will also help us in the physical therapy
areas, where a lot of noise and conversations are taking place in
the gym,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bateman has added a twist to the system at Gouverneur in that
all the interpreters are visually impaired or blind. A state agency
that finds employment for people with such handicaps has paid for
training costs and monitors that magnify words on a computer
screen. The interpreters are trained and monitored by experts who
speak Spanish and Chinese dialects.
</P>
<P>
   But the remote interpretation system has its critics. What some
see as advantages _ the removal of a third person's presence, the
word-for-word interpretation _ others see as potential pitfalls.
Linda Haffner, director of interpreter services at Stanford
University Hospital and Clinics, said face-to-face interpretation
was necessary in certain situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the clues I get from the patient is when I am talking
to them in person,'' she said. ``You have to take into
interpretation the visual cues from a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Haffner said that simultaneous interpretation did not allow room
for the interpreter to stop and explain things in more depth to the
speakers.
</P>
<P>
   But several doctors who have used the system at Gouverneur said
they were pleased. Bateman said he would like to hire more
interpreters, especially a Fujianese speaker, and to distribute
headset units on more wards. But price remains a barrier: each
headset and transmitter costs $2,000, while the central switching
unit costs $10,000 and interpreter stations run $3,000 each. Wood
said the change to Ethernet technology would cut down on those
costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I wasn't sure how I would feel about
it,'' said Wendy Barron, a clinical psychologist at Gouverneur.
``But since we've been using it, I've been more and more pleased.
The interpreters have been really professional, and it's made a
huge difference for us.'' (af)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
