 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Thursday, April 6. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-DIAMONDS (Undated) _ The value of diamonds, coupled with
the anonymity and portability of the stones _ millions of dollars
worth can be smuggled in a sock without triggering a metal detector
_ have made diamonds one of the most potent, and dangerous,
currencies of modern Africa. A Special Report by Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT1-4, and map.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-DRUG (Paris) _ The 23 million Africans infected with the
AIDS virus should be given regular doses of a common and affordable
antibiotic, the World Health Organization and UNAids said
Wednesday, as a way to ward off fatal secondary infections. They
based their recommendation on encouraging preliminary studies, and
added that if the results are borne out, the impact could be
dramatic. Many people could add years to their lives and have
longer gaps between debilitating complications. But the antibiotic
is not a cure for the fatal disease. The drug, known as
trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole or as cotrimoxazole, is marketed as a
generic drug in the U.S. called Bactrim. It can cost as little as
$8 a year in Africa. Its use for prophylaxis there was endorsed for
the first time last week by AIDS experts who convened in Zimbabwe
to assess the new studies. The Clinton administration is spending
more than $100 million to fight AIDS in Africa and trying to raise
that to $325 million. It may spend millions of those dollars to
help distribute Bactrim in Africa, but has not yet calculated how
much to commit. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-POLITICS (Tokyo) _ Capping an extraordinary morning of
abruptly shifting emotions, Japan's parliament elected a new prime
minister Wednesday, replacing Keizo Obuchi, who was left in a coma
by a stroke over the weekend. Obuchi's successor, Yoshiro Mori, was
nominated, as was widely expected, by the governing Liberal
Democratic Party after a party meeting, and his candidacy was
quickly put to a vote before the two houses of the Japanese
parliament, where he was overwhelmingly approved. By Howard W.
French.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HERMAN-CLEARED (Washington) _ The independent prosecutor who has
been investigating accusations of corruption involving Alexis
Herman, the Clinton administration's secretary of labor, said
Wednesday he has concluded that Herman did not break any laws and
should not be indicted. Herman, the fifth Cabinet officer in the
Clinton administration to come under the scrutiny of an independent
counsel, was accused by a former business partner of engaging in a
plan involving kickbacks and solicitation of illegal campaign
contributions to the Democratic Party. But Ralph Lancaster, who
conducted the the 23-month-long investigation, announced in a
one-sentence statement that he would not seek an indictment of
Herman. By David Johnston and Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-CONGRESS (Washington) _ In what has become a regular
ritual complete with grisly charts and emotional rhetoric, the
House Wednesday again debated and approved a measure to ban
``partial birth abortions,'' a bill President Clinton vowed to
veto. Since 1995 the House and the Senate have repeatedly voted to
ban this specific type of abortion, which critics compare to
infanticide. Clinton has vetoed it, and has said he would continue
doing so until it allows an exemption to protect a woman's health.
(Summary from wires) By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-TRADERS (New York) _ At high noon Tuesday, after a rocky
morning of trading, U.S. stocks pitched into a 90-minute freefall.
By the time the dive ended, shares in some of the market's biggest
and most important companies, from technology leaders like Yahoo to
corporate titans like General Electric, had fallen 5, 10 or even 15
percent. There was no news bulletin to explain the decline, no mad
rumor of presidential ill health war in Asia, only a tidal wave of
selling. Then, just as quickly, the market turned, and many stocks
finished the day close to where they began or even up slightly. So
what happened? What happened, professional traders said, is that
the U.S. markets have become bigger, more volatile, and more
uncontrollable than ever before. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The trial judge and the
litigants in the Microsoft antitrust trial agreed Wednesday to
conclude the case and impose a remedy on the software giant by
roughly the end of May, and the state attorneys general who have
pushed for the harshest remedies are coalescing around the view
that they will not ask the judge to break up the company, several
officials said. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-GREENSPAN (Undated) _ A day after Wall Street endured one
of its most volatile rides, Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve
chairman, offered soothing words to investors Wednesday, saying
more explicitly than before that the central bank's interest rate
increases are not intended to drive down stock prices. But as he
has now for months, Greenspan continued to identify the wealth
being generated by rising stock prices as the primary cause of
potentially inflationary imbalances in the economy. By Richard L.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN-BANKS (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Deutsche Bank and Dresdner
Bank scrapped their $30 billion merger on Wednesday, less than a
month after they agreed to the deal, embittered over a dispute
about the future of the Dresdner Kleinwort Benson investment bank.
The merger would have created the second-biggest bank in the world
and its dissolution was an enormous embarrassment to Deutsche Bank,
which had portrayed the deal as a sign of its aggressive new
business strategy. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BIOTECH-FOOD (Undated) _ Amid growing concerns over possible
risks posed by genetically modified crops, the National Academy of
Sciences took a new tack on biotech organisms, issuing a report
Wednesday calling for stronger regulation of the novel plants and
pointing to the potential for both food and environmental hazards.
While noting the potential for problems, the report stated that so
far there is no evidence that any genetically modified foods
currently on the market are unsafe to eat. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon and
Melody Petersen.
</P>
