u l BC-MODERNIST-PRESERVATIO     04-05 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODERNIST-PRESERVATION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CHARLESTON, A MODERN HOUSE WITH GOOD MANNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: S.C., Conn., Pa.. Va.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week in Charleston, S.C., a profusion of soft-scented,
full-bloom dogwood, azalea, wisteria, Lady Banksia roses and
peppermint peach trees attested to a city populated by green
thumbs. The perfectly groomed streets of the city, pincered between
two rivers and bursting with august old piles, also bore witness to
a proud attachment to a resplendent past.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest houses date back to the early 1700s; then, the
Georgian period takes over, elegant precision with leaded glass
demilune windows and classical orders. Not to be overlooked are
those magnificent plantation-era dowagers (and tourist magnets),
the single houses with their double verandas facing south over
luscious gardens. The entire historic city is a registered National
Historic Landmark, birthplace of the preservation movement. Even
parking lots rate a mention in the guidebooks.
</P>
<P>
   Down a little alley near the district's epicenter, where even
1980s-era houses have 18th-century-style carriage doors, the most
astonishing sight is not another period gem but something more
unexpected: a modern house. Originally a 1781 brick warehouse, it
has been transformed over time into an ersatz single house.
</P>
<P>
   Today, stripped of ad hoc appendages, the building has returned
to the feeling of being a solid rectangle. The original clay-dark
red-brick walls now feature a series of disciplined steel-case
glass doors that allow an uninterrupted flow between an open
interior and a new bluestone terrace. A stucco addition in the back
is pointedly new. Its glass-and-steel awning mark the official
entrance. A black-bottomed pool reflecting a gnarled peppermint
peach tree and a tinkling rill that flows around the patio's edge
lend the place a meditative mood, offering no scars of the
ferocious battles that were waged over five years to finish the
renovation.
</P>
<P>
   Subtly different and elegantly precise, the modern house in old
Charleston could be the proud standard for a more enlightened
approach to preservation today, beyond just stopping time in its
own tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of the 3,500-square-foot house are James L. and Sarah
Coker, both ``thoroughly South Carolinian for as many generations
as we know of,'' Coker said. She grew up just a few historic alleys
away and hasn't lost a drop of her drawl despite the couple's 1991
move to Stonington, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Coker, 59, is retired, a director of the Sonoco Products Co.,
founded by his great-grandfather together with a Union soldier
while both were convalescing from wounds received, Coker said, ``in
the war.'' (The company, with sales of about $3 billion, started
with the invention of cardboard spinning cones and now produces
packaging materials, from construction columns to Pringles tubes.
Coker worked on L'eggs pantyhose holder.)
</P>
<P>
   The couple's original plan had been to spruce up the place,
vacant for a year, with a little paint to make it a pied-a-terre
for frequent visits to their hometown. They needed three bedrooms
to handle visits from their far-flung adult children.
</P>
<P>
   They hired W.G. Clark, of Clark and Menefee, a Modernist who had
trained with Robert Venturi and had come to Charleston from
Philadelphia in 1974 because, he said, ``nobody else was going
south'' and he had hoped to corner the market on modern
architecture. His compass must have been broken that day. Most
aspiring architects go west. After all, the city motto is, ``She
guards her buildings, customs and laws.'' When his first job, an
addition to a historic house, was presented to the review board,
the client's mother, a tour guide, opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was unprepared for how conservative it was,'' Clark said,
adding, ``That was my first insight into the true nature of
Charleston.''
</P>
<P>
   Well before Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis led candle-lighted vigils
to save Grand Central Station, society ladies in Charleston were
body-blocking bulldozers to halt the demolition of cherished
buildings. In 1920, the Society for the Preservation of Old
Dwellings was established and in 1931, the Board of Architectural
Review was formed to approve permits affecting historic properties.
Numerous watchdog groups monitor preservation and hold views on
change that run the gamut from seeing it as an opportunity to
enhance to a necessary evil to a sacrilege.
</P>
<P>
   But Clark was not particularly flexible himself. Brandishing
principles honed through the close study and admiration of the
works of Louis Kahn and Carlo Scarpa, Clark likes to say: ``We are
modern architects. We abhor anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   During his 15 years in Charleston, few jobs came along; no
surprise. In 1988, he moved to Charlottesville to become chairman
of the architecture department at the University of Virginia.
Clark's partnership with Charles Menefee, formed in 1985, was
dissolved amicably in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was a project in Charleston that established the
architects as inheritors of the mantle of the great Kahn with the
Middleton Inn, a compound of buildings completed in 1985. Its
picturesque siting overlooking the Ashley River and its smooth
concrete cubic forms, wooden shutter walls and window grids made
subtlety sensual and showed that the reductive nature of modernism
could still be packed with emotional power.
</P>
<P>
   Clark takes an almost spiritual approach to building. In an
essay from a forthcoming book on the firm's work, he writes that
architecture should ``seek not only the minimal ruin of the
landscape'' but should also supply ``a replacement of what was lost
with something that atones for the loss.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cokers are equally sensitive to architecture. Both are
members of the advisory council for the National Trust for Historic
Preservation and Coker is on the properties committee at Lyndhurst,
the historic house on the Hudson River. But they are also skeptics
when it comes to what Coker calls ``the whole `Gone With the Wind'
mystique that the tours are selling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cokers wanted their home to fit in without capitulating to
what they described as a local obsession with making the city more
18th century than it was in the 18th century. Not that they
necessarily shared Clark's Modernist zeal. ``James and I did an
awful lot of stretching,'' Coker said.
</P>
<P>
   The architect proposed stripping off all the various additions
to return the warehouse to its essential shoe-box shape. Gradually
laying bare the structure, Clark discovered that the ground-floor
windows had originally been tall doors and that the roof had had a
much steeper rake, which was restored. Every move was toward
clarity and reduction. The couple had to fight to keep an attached
garage.
</P>
<P>
   The ground floor of the old building became a open living and
dining room with three eight-foot doors leading to the terrace.
Materials were kept to a minimum, primarily concrete, steel and
mahogany (in tribute to the traditional furniture of Charleston).
The architect made much of the division between brick house and
concrete addition.
</P>
<P>
   On the interior, the passage from old to new is marked by a wide
mahogany staircase, flanked by a sandblasted glass scrim with a
vaguely Japanese feeling that rises through the two-story house.
The addition's commandingly modern kitchen has shiny steel
appliances, a concrete counter and mahogany cabinetry to provide
the mollifying effects of richly burnished woodwork.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors enter into the kitchen. Charleston friends find it
disconcerting. ``They get confused,'' Mrs Coker said, ``and say,
`How can a proper front door lead into a kitchen?'''
</P>
<P>
   But it is the upstairs that suggests the most radical break with
tradition. Unable to fit three bedrooms, enough closets and extra
bathrooms onto the second floor, the Cokers decided at their
architect's urging to give it all over to their bedroom. Visiting
children were relegated to a condo around the corner that the
couple bought. ``It became so clear that that was what the house
wanted,'' Coker said. ``It was a real awakening.'' Thus a 13-room
project became a 4-room house.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7988 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-MODERNIST-PRESERVATIO     04-05 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODERNIST-PRESERVATION-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: 4-room house.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The entire project took a languid five years and cost about $2
million dollars. Every decision was made in concert, not only with
Clark but also with the interior designer, Dian Boone of
Philadelphia, and the landscape architect, Warren Byrd of
Charlottesville. ``We would thrash and thrash and thrash until
everyone agreed,'' Coker said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not everyone. The neighbors, upon learning about the plans
to reinvent the house that they adored as quaint and quirky,
reacted in swift retaliation. At a meeting of the Board of
Architectural Review, a swat team of 50 people filled the gallery.
They complained about the steel and glass; they objected to a plan
to raise a wall separating the garden from the street. The new
addition, they feared, would be visible from the alley. Perhaps
worst of all, a tall plate-glass window on the north facade showed
it didn't have ``northern manners.'' (In Charleston, windows on
north facades are traditionally eliminated to give privacy to
homeowners with south-facing gardens.)
</P>
<P>
   The project was stalled for one and a half years. Some
concessions were made on both sides. The glass stayed, but the wall
was somewhat lowered. A neighboring couple moved out, dreading the
impact of a glass tower on the alley's character.
</P>
<P>
   ``It knocked the wind right out of our sails,'' Coker recalled.
</P>
<P>
   But the Board of Architectural Review took an enlightened
approach and finally granted the building permits. Charles Chase,
the city architect and preservation officer at the time, said
recently, ``We believed that it was one of the very rare moments
when design was able to find the essence of what was appropriate
and interpret it in modern materials with a quiet elegance that is
very fitting for a historic district.''
</P>
<P>
   While sensitive to the neighbors' fears, the delay matured the
Cokers' resolve, and they began to think of the project as a work
of art. ``People conjecture that modern architecture is going to be
cold,'' Coker said. ``They like to surround themselves with lots of
things and fabric and bric-a-brac in order to feel a certain
coziness and they feel threatened that that's going to be taken
away.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple experienced that themselves, at first planning to
fill the house with family heirlooms and then letting them go (but
not far, to the visitors' condo ). ``It was a major accomplishment
to realize I didn't have to live with all this stuff in order to be
comfortable,'' Coker said.
</P>
<P>
   The house was completed last fall. Even the peppermint peach
tree hobbled by Hurricane Hugo came back to life this spring,
bursting with blooms that fill the large window where the Cokers
have their morning coffee. A few neighbors are still griping that
the glass awning is tacky, but Barbara G.S. Hagerty, who lives
across the street, has grown to love the house. ``It's a Zen
space,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The most promising sign that the modern house might be accepted?
The Historic Charleston Foundation just asked if it could put it on
its house tour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7990 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-TULIPMANIA-NYT &LR;      04-05 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TULIPMANIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURSTING BUBBLES: WEB TALES OF SPECULATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For some, the bubble was the great uranium land rush of the
1950s. When it burst, most Colorado desert turned out to be
Colorado desert. For others, it was the great coin craze of the
1960s, when new Lincoln pennies were sold for dollars as great
investments. Guess what they ended up being worth? Those who
plunged into wine futures in the 1970s drowned their sorrows in
style.
</P>
<P>
   Financial bubbles, those dangerous combinations of crowd
psychology and alluring, wispy investment offers, have a long and
painful past. Today's dot-com investors may get an education from
three of history's hottest deals: tulipmania, the South Sea bubble
and the Mississippi scheme.
</P>
<P>
   All three are in an 1841 classic that is as current as today's
stock quotes: Charles Mackay's ``Extraordinary Popular Delusions
and the Madness of Crowds.'' It is online at www.bibliomania.com,
and at sailor.gutenberg.org.
</P>
<P>
   Mackay traces the tulip from Turkey to its introduction into the
Netherlands in the mid-16th century. ``In 1634, the rage among the
Dutch to possess them was so great that the ordinary industry of
the country was neglected, and the population, even to its lowest
dregs, embarked in the tulip trade.''
</P>
<P>
   One would-be buyer offered 12 acres of land for a rare bulb. A
single example of the Viceroy variety fetched four fat oxen, eight
fat swine, 12 fat sheep, a bed, a suit of clothes, a silver
drinking cup and large quantities of wheat, rye, wine, beer, butter
and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   One common thread in these accounts is that when the bubble
bursts, it bursts quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cry of distress sounded everywhere, and each man accused
his neighbor.'' Alas, Mackay wrote, the courts refused to
interfere, ruling that tulipmania debts were gambling debts, and
unenforceable.
</P>
<P>
   A shorter account that focuses more on the tulips themselves,
``A Rambling Romp Through Tulip History,'' can be found at
www.bulb.com/historymyth/romp.html.
</P>
<P>
   The South Sea Bubble, which caused the first great British stock
market crash in 1720, began in 1711 with a plan for a private group
of merchants to enrich the public treasury by trading British goods
to the Spanish colonies in America. All they needed was an
exclusive trading right and a large loan from issuing stock,
according to Mackay's account.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody had heard of the gold and silver mines of Peru and
Mexico; every one believed them to be inexhaustible and it was only
necessary to send the manufactures of England to the coast to be
repaid a hundredfold,'' Mackay wrote. Never mind that Philip V of
Spain had no intention of allowing the English free trade with
Spanish America _ the rumors were irresistible. ``Visions of ingots
danced before their eyes,'' and warnings in parliament were drowned
out.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the oddest and most instructive outgrowths of the South
Sea Bubble were the unrelated stocks that were issued just to take
advantage of the frenzy. Mackay lists four pages of them: for
insuring horses, for rebuilding parsonages, for a perpetual motion
machine, for trading in hair, and the piece de resistance: ``for
carrying on an undertaking of great advantage, but nobody to know
what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a well-illustrated account of the South Sea Bubble in
an online Harvard Magazine reprint at
www.harvard-magazine.com/issues/mj99/damnd.html.
</P>
<P>
   The Mississippi Bubble, which occurred in France about the same
time, owed its origin to a Scotsman with the magnificently
inappropriate name of John Law. A mathematical genius and bon
vivant, according to Mackay, he developed a winning gambling system
that got him kicked out of a number of countries until he
ingratiated himself with the Duke of Orleans, who became regent to
Louis XV. Law issued notes based on the profits to be made from the
gold and silver of the Mississippi and the Louisiana Territory.
(Gold? Mississippi? Hey, it sounded good in 1718.)
</P>
<P>
   Speculation in Mississippi bonds was so great that space on
Law's street in Paris was rented for a fortune to traders. ``The
story goes that a humpbacked man who stood in the street gained
considerable sums by lending his hump as a writing desk to the
eager speculators.''
</P>
<P>
   Law was not entirely to blame, Mackay wrote: ``He did not count
on the avaricious frenzy of a whole nation; he did not see that
confidence, like mistrust, could be increased almost ad infinitum
and that hope was as extravagant as fear.''
</P>
<P>
   In his epitaph for Law, Mackay compares the bubbler to the first
unsuspecting canoeist down the Niagara River: ``He was dashed to
pieces with his bark, but the waters, maddened and turned to foam
by the rough descent, only boiled and bubbled for a time, and then
flowed on again as smoothly as ever.''  &QL; 
(af) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
