<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7995 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-POMPEII-EROTICA-NYT &LR;      04-05 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POMPEII-EROTICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDALOUS CABINET FROM POMPEII OPENS, PARENTAL GUIDANCE
SUGGESTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: France, Germany, Italy)  By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, Italy _ The contents of the Secret Cabinet that were so
scandalous they were kept locked up for most of the last 200 years
will be unveiled to the public next week. Schoolchildren visiting
the National Archaeological Museum of Naples, however, will need
parental permission to see the exhibition. Curators delicately
refer to the Secret Cabinet or the ``Forbidden Collection,'' but
museum guards loudly direct visitors to ``il pornografico.''
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Cabinet is actually two rooms containing a vast
collection of ancient erotica: 250 frescoes, mosaics, statues,
talismans, amulets, oil lamps as well as votive _ and highly
explicit _ fertility symbols, most of them dug up during the
18th-century excavations at Pompeii and Herculaneum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sexuality of the ancients is not the sexuality of our
times,'' Marinella Lista, a museum archaeologist warned as she
pointed out one of the most famous works in the collection, a
second-century A.D. marble statue of the mythological figure of
Pan, copulating with a goat. Discovered in 1752 during excavations
at the Villa of the Papyrus in Herculaneum, ``Pan and the Goat''
was locked away in a chest by the Bourbon King Charles III. Even
the most noted German archaeologist of the time, Johann
Winckelmann, was forbidden to see it.
</P>
<P>
   At least compared with the rather clinical depictions of human
sexual acts surrounding it, however, this statue of two creatures
gazing raptly into each other's eyes is almost romantic. ``There is
cruelty,'' Lista said, ``but there is also tenderness.''
</P>
<P>
   The collection, which amply illustrates the sexual proclivities
of pre-Roman and Roman societies, is important to historians and
archaeologists and intriguing for ordinary tourists. It is not,
however, unique. Ancient erotic artworks can be found in major
archaeological collections around the world, including the
Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Even the famous lupanare of Pompeii, brothels richly decorated
with obscene murals, are open to all visitors. Until 15 years ago
those murals were shown only to men; women and children needed to
bribe guards for a glimpse.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Cabinet is perhaps most interesting as a reflection
of the shifting mores of recent history, a famous, rarely seen
collection that opened in rhythm with liberal political movements
that swept Europe in the 19th century and closed again when
reactionary forces regained the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
   Lista, however, seemed concerned that contemporary visitors
would draw the wrong conclusions about depravity in ancient Rome.
``Previous generations thought that the people of Pompeii were
justly punished by the volcano eruption, because they were so
lascivious,'' she said indignantly. ``Nothing could be less true.''
</P>
<P>
   The profusion of bold and bawdy Roman erotica unearthed in the
ruins led Pietro d'Onofri, a priest, to ``excommunicate'' Pompeii
in the early 1800s, saying, ``That entire city was given to the
most sordid impropriety, and so from God, it deserved, like Sodom,
the calamity of fire.'' His was a devout but somewhat empty
gesture, since Pompeii was pagan in A.D. 79, when Vesuvius erupted.
</P>
<P>
   Even broad-minded visitors like the French writer Stendhal were
taken aback that women of ancient Rome could be allowed to see such
explicit depictions of sexual acts and reproductive organs. (Lista
said, however, that Roman matrons never saw the most graphic murals
and statues, which were kept in rooms open only to men and their
concubines.)
</P>
<P>
   Obscene murals, statues and artifacts scandalized kings and
cardinals, but they also stirred 18th-century scientists. William
Hamilton, the British ambassador to the court of Naples (best known
as the cuckolded husband of Emma Hamilton, the lover of Lord
Nelson), wrote a paper in 1781 for the Royal Society of London
comparing the cult of Priapus to the contemporary Roman Catholic
cult of Sts. Cosmas and Damien in Isernia, near Naples (one of the
first anthropological comparisons of ancient and modern
examinations of sexuality). He also donated some of the phallic
votive objects he had collected to the British Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The study of Etruscan and Roman erotica was a risky business,
however. Even a well-known curator, Pierre Hugues, was expelled
from Naples in 1769 after he published a study of the secret cult
of Priapus, a compendium of lewd ancient Roman writings. (Hamilton
later rehabilitated him by hiring him as curator of his statuary
collection.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1785 King Ferdinand of Naples set aside one room in his royal
museum for obscene antiques that would be seen only with special
permission. But by 1819 the collection had been transferred to a
new museum where it was kept on open display. In 1827 an anonymous
priest wrote to Ferdinand's successor, Francis I, describing the
room as hell and begging that it be closed: ``Sire, this room is
the plague of religion. It is the corrupter of the morals of the
modest youth, the ruin of your subjects. Only in Naples do you see
such infamous things.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis complied and locked the room, opening it only to
``people of mature age and respected morals'' who had written
permission from a government minister. Predictably the Secret
Cabinet became a favorite stop for young British, European and
Russian aristocrats on the Grand Tour.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1848 revolutions that swept Europe, the collection
was re-opened for a year. After the revolutionary leader Garibaldi
defeated the Bourbons and set up his own brief dictatorship in
southern Italy in 1860, one of his first acts was to order that fig
leaves be removed from public statuary. He also demanded that the
Secret Cabinet be reopened. One of the three keys needed was
missing, so a museum craftsman broke down the door.
</P>
<P>
   After Garibaldi handed over southern Italy to King Victor
Emmanuel II in 1860, the Secret Cabinet was closed again. In 1866 a
museum curator, Francesco Fiorelli, made a catalog of the
collection, arguing that many of the objects were not obscene and
could be displayed in other parts of the museum. But his catalog
had no illustrations and used only obscure terminology
(``drillopote,'' a rarely used Italian word for vase with a figure
attached, and ``veretro,'' an amulet decorated with a phallus),
suggesting that he, too, was a bit embarrassed by his subject.
</P>
<P>
   The collection was last opened in the 1960s, but then was shut
again for restoration. It remained closed until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously in an era of proclaimed full sexual freedom and
erotic museums opened in many European capitals, it makes no sense
to speak of a forbidden collection,'' the current curator, Stefano
De Caro, wrote in his catalog, which does include illustrations. He
said one of the Secret Cabinet's attractions was its ``ambiguous
history as a museum and nonmuseum.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
