<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ASIA-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY STOCKS ARE HAMMERED IN ASIAN MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In Asia, as in the United States, the bloom is off
the rose for technology shares. But here, it has withered even more
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Stock markets from Tokyo to Singapore swooned Wednesday as
investors followed the gyrating Nasdaq in the United States by
dumping shares in technology, Internet and telecommunications
companies. The rout was most severe in Hong Kong, where the Hang
Seng index plunged 3.4 percent and popular companies like China
Telecom and Pacific Century Cyberworks led the retreat.
</P>
<P>
   The sell-off has particularly troubling implications for Pacific
Century, which is using its stock as currency to finance a takeover
of Hong Kong's dominant telephone company, Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT.
Pacific Century's shares fell 11 percent, to 14.95 Hong Kong
dollars, or $1.92, a share. The shares have declined by 32 percent
since the agreement was announced in late February.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly in the danger zone for this deal,'' said David
Webb, editor of Webb-site.com, an Internet service for investors.
``The institutional investors who own Cable and Wireless stock are
sensible people. There is a point at which they will reject the
transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Century deal is something of a bellwether because it
symbolizes the rise of Internet companies in Asia. The company,
controlled by a 32-year-old entrepreneur, Richard Li, has few
assets aside from a clutch of investments in Internet start-ups.
Yet it has become one of the most highly-valued stocks in Hong
Kong, rivaling the property empire of Li's father, Li Ka-shing.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   To win Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT, the younger Li vanquished Singapore
Telecommunications, a much larger company controlled by the
Singapore government. He was able to do so because the board of
Cable &AMP; Wireless, the London-based parent of Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT,
concluded that selling to an Internet company was more attractive
than settling for another phone company.
</P>
<P>
   But while Cable &AMP; Wireless owns 54 percent of HKT, Li still
needs the approval of other shareholders, including China Telecom
and the Hong Kong government. He is offering two options for their
shares: all stock or stock-and-cash. The value of the all-stock
offer has dropped to $25.8 billion from $38.1 billion, while the
stock-and-cash offer has dropped to $28 billion from $35.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Webb said the erosion in Pacific Century's shares all but
guaranteed that investors would opt for the stock-and-cash offer.
That would leave HKT's majority owner, Cable &AMP; Wireless, with less
cash and a larger stake in Pacific Century. Cable and Wireless has
pledged to sell a chunk of that stake soon after the deal is
completed, which will put further pressure on Pacific Century's
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts said they were baffled by the open-ended nature of
the deal. ``Cable &AMP; Wireless didn't negotiate a collar on the
stock, they didn't negotiate a walk-away price, and the break-up
fee is minimal,'' said Henry Lee, managing director of Hendale
Ventures, an asset management firm in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts pointed out that Pacific Century will not
make a formal offer to shareholders until May 18. Given the wild
swings in technology shares, Pacific Century's stock price could
well rebound by then. Despite the steady erosion in the company's
shares, there have been no public indications of concern, either
from Cable &AMP; Wireless or from other HKT shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Pacific Century declined to comment Wednesday,
noting only that the terms of the deal would not be modified.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century was far from the only technology stock punished
in Hong Kong on Wednesday. Three of the hottest local Internet
start-ups _ Tom.com, Hongkong.com, and Sunevision _ plunged 16.6
percent, 16.8 percent, and 12.2 percent respectively. After soaring
into the stratosphere, these companies are now trading below the
price at which they went public a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was the bad news limited to Hong Kong. In Tokyo, two of the
most prominent new-economy stocks also continued to languish.
Softbank, which owns a portfolio of Internet investments, fell by
the Nikkei's one-day trading limit of 5,000 yen, or $47.61, to
close at 76,500 yen, or $728.57.
</P>
<P>
   Hikari Tsushin, which sells cellular phones and has a joint
venture with Pacific Century, was halted for a fourth consecutive
session, as orders to sell shares swamped orders to buy. The
company recently warned of much larger-than-expected losses in the
six-month period that ended in February.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the angst, many analysts said this was a much-needed
correction for Asian markets that had become dangerously
overheated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tech bubble is finally bursting,'' said Marc Faber, the
head of his own investment firm here. ``In order to burst a bubble,
people have to lose money. Now, people are losing money.''
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
