u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     04-05 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAPTOPS OF LUXURY: PRICE IS AN AFTERTHOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER H. LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why is this man smiling? Here he is, stuck in the middle seat
between two large people in the third-to-last row of coach on a
bumpy, 1,500-mile, early Sunday morning flight.
</P>
<P>
   But all is well; because the Apple PowerBook G3 portable
Macintosh computer I'm testing has a gorgeous 14-inch,
high-resolution screen, a DVD drive and ample battery life to show
a full-length movie.
</P>
<P>
   High-end laptop computers, the kind that are powerful enough to
serve as desktop computer replacements, are getting fancier all the
time. For people who are willing to pay first-class prices, the
PowerBook G3 and its high-altitude Windows-based counterparts
provide the convenience of portability without sacrificing power or
features.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of power and portability does not come cheap.
High-end laptops cost $3,000 to nearly $5,000, easily double the
cost of comparable desktop computers. But for those who would
otherwise consider buying two computers, one for the desktop and
one for the road, investing in one of these double-duty laptops may
make financial sense.
</P>
<P>
   The PowerBook G3 I traveled with is more powerful than the iMac
DV SE desktop computer I bought recently ($1,499), and I was
surprised to discover that it has the same size display screen. At
the same time, at just over 6 pounds it weighs a half pound less
than Apple's top of the line portable iBook SE ($1,799), and yet is
much more powerful.
</P>
<P>
   The PowerBook G3 500 costs $3,499, or $200 more than the two
lesser computers combined. However, there is something appealing
about having just one computer and not having to worry about two
sets of data and applications. (Unless, of course, there are other
family members who compete for computer time. In that case, two
computers are always better than one.)
</P>
<P>
   The PowerBook takes up less desk space than a desktop PC, which
is important to people who live and work in cramped spaces. It is
trim enough to be locked in a desk drawer for security.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the PowerBook G3 is much too large to use on the
seat-back tray in coach, especially when the passenger in front
puts her seat all the way back and appears to be doing the
Macarena. So, to protect its screen, the G3 goes on my lap. If my
legs had not gone numb early in the flight, I might have found the
heat generated by the computer to be uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   The heat comes from the 500 MHz G3 processor with a generous 1
megabyte of performance boosting level 2 backside cache. The unit I
tested also had 12 gigabytes of storage and 128 megabytes of system
memory. A decent ATI Rage video card with 8 megabytes of video
memory keeps the display colorful and lively.
</P>
<P>
   As impressive as those specifications are, the PowerBook G3 500
is not the most powerful laptop on the market these days. There are
several 650 MHz Pentium III rivals on the Windows side, with larger
hard disks. The 14-inch screen is not the largest in its price
class, but it is plenty big enough to do justice to business
presentations or DVD movies.
</P>
<P>
   Without doubt, however, the PowerBook is the best-looking
portable around. Sleek and midnight black, it has a translucent
white Apple logo in the center of the lid that glows like a full
moon when the computer is awake, and a lightning-bug green power
light that throbs on and off while it is asleep.
</P>
<P>
   And the PowerBook has many bonus features that set it apart from
its rivals, starting with the Mac OS 9 operating system. It comes
with a pair of USB connectors for attaching external devices like a
mouse and a keyboard, and with an external monitor it becomes a
stylish desktop machine. Memory can be boosted from the standard
128 megabytes to up to 512 megabytes, and an 18GB hard drive is an
option.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Macintoshes, the PowerBook comes standard with an
Ethernet high-speed networking card, which can be used to connect
to a cable modem for an office network, as well as a built-in 56K
modem for connecting to the Internet over regular phone wires.
</P>
<P>
   Like other current Macs, it has built-in antennas for Apple's
AirPort high-speed wireless networking system (a $99 AirPort
networking card must be installed under the keyboard, which
requires some dexterity and patience). Because neither I nor the
pilot particularly cared to see if there were any sensitive
avionics devices in the cockpit that I could network with at 41,000
feet, I disabled the AirPort feature before takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   The PowerBook really excels when it comes to multimedia. It has
a pair of high-speed Firewire (IEEE 1394) ports for attaching
digital video cameras, and an S-Video Out port for sending video to
an S-Video-equipped television or video tape recorder. The DVD-ROM
drive plays audio CD's and CD-ROM discs as well as DVD movies.
</P>
<P>
   The battery life is exceptional, up to 5 hours. The DVD-ROM
drive can be popped out and replaced with a second battery,
yielding up to 10 hours of use between charges.
</P>
<P>
   At just over 6 pounds, though, the PowerBook is not an ideal
traveling companion unless one is seriously into Web design,
business presentations or video production.
</P>
<P>
   Video is certainly one of Apple's strengths, both on the desktop
and in its PowerBook line. To show off its strengths, Apple loaded
my borrowed PowerBook with Final Cut Pro, a professional-quality
video editing program that costs nearly $1,000, and sent it along
with a Canon Optura digital video camera (about $1,500). Thus
equipped, the PowerBook becomes a mobile video production lab.
</P>
<P>
   One can imagine the antitrust lawyers at the Justice Department
running around with such a system, making home movies of their
gleeful victory parties this week after Microsoft was found to have
illegally exploited its Windows monopoly to stifle competition.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Windows, the biggest news in high-end notebook
computers is the arrival of Intel's SpeedStep processor technology
(formerly code-named Geyserville), which allows the chip to vary
its speed depending on whether the computer is plugged into the
wall or running on batteries.
</P>
<P>
   If it is plugged in, the computer runs at top speed; if it is
unplugged, it ``steps down'' to a lower, power-saving speed. An
Intel rival, Advanced Micro Devices, is expected to have similar
chips this summer. Dell's new Inspiron 5000 G650VT, for example,
operates at 650 megahertz on alternating current, but ratchets down
to 500 MHz when it is unplugged, which extends the battery life for
a handful of minutes. Most people won't notice the battery savings
or the difference in processing power unless they are doing
processor-intensive applications.
</P>
<P>
   If you use your flight time to work through e-mail messages,
compose memos and make up Internet business plans, save your money
and get a cheaper portable with a one-speed chip. But if you travel
frequently, need a powerful computer and consider battery life to
be precious, the SpeedStep technology may be worth it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1724EDT &QL; 
