<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8005 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-SUPREME-TOBACCO-INJUS     04-05 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPREME-TOBACCO-INJUSTICE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SUPREME COURT TELLS JOE CAMEL: HAPPY DAYS ARE HERE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By STEPHEN L. COHEN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The smirk on Joe Camel's face has grown a bit larger of late,
thanks to his new pals William Rehnquist, Antonin Scalia, Anthony
Kennedy and Clarence Thomas. The famed outdoorsman, gambler and
raconteur has good reason to smile. After being pummeled by
anti-smoking forces for years, he just got the latest news from
Washington: Happy days are here again.
 &HT;    The Supreme Court, in fact, has just handed cigarette companies
a rare victory in one of the most pivotal battles of the tobacco
wars. Rebuffing President Clinton, the court ruled that the Food
and Drug Administration lacks the authority to regulate tobacco,
effectively bringing much of the government's anti-smoking
initiative to a dramatic halt.
 &HT;    The decision, which prevailed by just one vote, will have a
profound impact on public health because it blocks federal efforts
to protect the nation's youth from the hazards of smoking. A vital
array of FDA regulations to discourage teenage smoking -- from
advertising restrictions to rules governing sales to minors -- must
be rescinded in the wake of the court's decision.
 &HT;    In the long saga of the tobacco wars, already fraught with
misfortune, this new development represents a major setback. Just
when it seemed that the nation was finally coming to grips with the
single most preventable cause of death in America, the Supreme
Court has stymied further progress with a narrowly drawn
interpretation of the Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act (FDCA).
 &HT;    Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, writing the majority opinion,
seemed to acknowledge this reality when she noted that smoking
``poses perhaps the single most significant threat to public
health'' in the U.S. Nonetheless, she argued for a narrow
interpretation of the FDCA, despite the huge stakes involved.
 &HT;    This is unfortunate, because such an interpretation consigns
millions of Americans to the prospect of premature death and
disability. Given the ambiguity of the law, it seems an
unnecessarily dogmatic decree.
 &HT;    Writing the dissenting opinion for the court, Justice Stephen G.
Breyer stressed the importance of this very issue. He contended
that when assessing the agency's authority to regulate tobacco, it
is crucial to consider the basic purpose of the FDA: ``the overall
protection of public health.''
 &HT;    Precisely. When considering a product that kills more people
each year than AIDS, car accidents, alcohol, homicides, drugs,
suicides and fires COMBINED, it seems reasonable to take an
expansive view of FDA authority that is consistent with its
legislatively mandated role to protect the public welfare.
 &HT;    Yet the conservative majority of the court ignored this
reasoning, choosing instead to take a much more limited view of the
agency's domain. Such a limited view does little to advance the
cause of public health, which happens to be the statutory realm of
the FDA.
 &HT;    The convoluted reasoning doesn't end there. Curiously, the court
cited the unusual nature of the case in order to justify a more
restrictive view of FDA authority. After recognizing that an agency
can set its own agenda in cases of ``legislative ambiguity'' (in
which the intent of Congress is unclear), the court then argued
that this prerogative should not be used in extraordinary
situations like the tobacco case.
 &HT;    Extraordinary indeed. But the court wasn't referring to the
appalling health effects of smoking here -- it was referring
instead to tobacco's ``unique political history,'' which apparently
obliges the court to exercise great care before granting the FDA
broader authority over cigarettes.
 &HT;    If this sounds like a lot of energetic posturing to justify a
rather contorted, precarious position, perhaps it reflects the
court's discomfort with the ramifications of its decision.
 &HT;    After all, the central issue of this case involves the
appropriate role of government in managing a public health crisis
of enormous magnitude. Regrettably, as more than 400,000 Americans
are killed each year by smoking, the Supreme Court seems content to
focus on other issues like the unique political history of tobacco.
 &HT;    The point here isn't that Congress's intent regarding the FDA is
clear. It isn't, as we've seen over the last two years as
legislators have proven incapable of passing comprehensive tobacco
legislation. But something else is quite clear: hundreds of
thousands of people are dying unnecessarily as the tools to save
them remain underutilized. The question is, when will the
legislative and judicial branches of government allow the executive
branch to do its job?
 &HT;    Whether one takes a conservative or more expansive view of FDA
jurisdiction, one thing is certain: in the absence of aggressive
federal action to reduce smoking, millions more will die in the
coming years. Given the uncertainty regarding congressional
intentions -- and the Supreme Court's inability to reach a
consensus even among its own members -- it is tragic that the
justices have allowed a narrow interpretation of the law to do so
much harm to America's nascent anti-smoking campaign.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.2000 Stephen L. Cohen
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Stephen L. Cohen, M.D., is a medical journalist based in New
York.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
