u i BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-1STLD-     04-05 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARLIAMENT APPROVES YOSHIRO MORI AS JAPAN'S NEW PRIME MINISTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS lede to recast; 3rd graf to delete material now in lede; 
 adds new 4th graf with figures for parliament vote;   subs 8th
graf `There are strong..., and 10th graf `Politicians said
other...' to clarify.) 
 (See also JAPAN-MORI-PROFILE) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Capping an extraordinary morning of abruptly shifting
emotions, Japan's parliament Wednesday elected a new prime
minister, replacing Keizo Obuchi, who was left in a coma by a
stroke over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi's successor, Yoshiro Mori, was nominated, as expected, by
the ruling Liberal Democratic Party after a party meeting Wednesday
morning. His candidacy was quickly put to a vote before the two
houses of parliament, which overwhelmingly approved.
</P>
<P>
   Teary remembrances of Obuchi made by the leader of the caretaker
government the night before gave way to Mori's selection in an
almost lusty acclamation by the Liberal Democratic Party lawmakers,
and then to his confirmation by an overwhelming vote in the Diet.
</P>
<P>
   Mori needed 245 votes for a majority in the lower house, and he
received 335 of 488 votes cast. In the upper house he won 137 of
244 votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue to pursue Obuchi's economic revitalization
policies and make every effort to restore the economy to stable
growth,'' said Mori, a burly former rugby player and debating team
colleague of Obuchi's from their days together at Tokyo's
prestigious Waseda University. Both men are 62 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The speedy ratification put to rest concerns about a power
vacuum, which were voiced within the governing party after Obuchi's
hospitalization late Sunday and immediately triggered an electoral
scramble to decide who would be Japan's next popularly elected
leader.
</P>
<P>
   With Liberal Democratic Party leaders eager for prompt elections
that would in theory give them a sympathy vote in the wake of
Obuchi's catastrophic stroke, many legislators hastily left the
parliament after the ratification of Mori, hoping to book trains
and flights back to their districts to prepare for elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are strong feelings within LDP that we should quickly
dissolve parliament and hold elections as quickly as possible,
because the sympathy vote may be easy to get,'' said Hiroshi
Mitsuzuka, a former finance minister and close friend of Mori.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the deep superstitions that prevail in Japanese
politics, ruling party members were said to favor June 4 for the
upcoming vote, in part because the date is considered reasonably
auspicious according to Chinese astrological calendars.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians said other considerations in arranging a quick vote
included a summit meeting of leading economic powers, the Group of
Eight, scheduled for July in Okinawa. Also, the transition of power
from Obuchi to Mori, after a brief caretaker's turn at the helm by
Mikio Aoki, was regarded by many Japanese as an episode of
political razzle-dazzle unworthy of a major economic power and
putative democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Aoki claimed that his legitimacy as caretaker was based on what
he said was a conversation he had with Obuchi during his illness,
in which he said the prime minister had asked him to take over the
government temporarily. Aoki announced Obuchi's illness to the
nation 22 hours after the prime minister was hospitalized. What
ensued were further secretive rounds of maneuverings, which
produced Mori as the governing party's standard bearer.
</P>
<P>
   If Mori's route to Japan's top political office was
controversial, little about his style could be described that way.
The longtime Liberal Democratic Party stalwart is expected to
continue most of the policies of his predecessor and work hard to
avoid rocking the boat. The intended tack was made clear by Mori's
re-adoption of the entire Obuchi Cabinet, which had resigned
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In case the message was lost on anyone, Mori, who was previously
his party's secretary-general, used baseball imagery in an early
morning exchange Wednesday with journalists to explain his
intentions. ``I was a catcher for Obuchi,'' he said. ``I think it
is important to carry through what he wanted to accomplish and what
he was concerned with.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Mori's retention of the old Cabinet and plans to carry out
Obuchi's policies were also reminders for many that he has no
popular mandate and occupies a tenuous position as interim leader
at a time when the Liberal Democratic Party's governing coalition
is deeply unpopular and saddled with stubborn economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   The governing party's chief coalition partner, the New Komeito
Party, is a Buddhist-affiliated group that many voters disapprove
of as blurring the lines between church and state.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders, sensing that the coming elections may be
their best chance in years to unseat the conservative Liberal
Democrats, who have governed for all but two years since 1955, were
quick to drive home these points.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new Cabinet will demonstrate that the LDP is reaching a
dead end, and I don't think that Mr. Mori will be able to break
through the wall,'' Kazuo Shii, secretary-general of the Communist
Party, said. ``It is worth mentioning that his appointment is not
something that has been submitted to the approval of the people of
Japan. More correctly, it is an appointment that defies the will of
the people of Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as they expressed trepidation about a possible sympathy
vote on behalf of the Liberal Democratic Party, other opposition
leaders said they felt the Japanese electorate was deeply
disillusioned with the state of the country after 10 years of
recession and a spate of recent scandals involving abuse of
authority, and would be particularly receptive to a campaign of
ideas about government reform.
</P>
<P>
   The Obuchi administration enjoyed a number of successes in
pulling Japan from the depths of a near economic meltdown in the
late 1990s. But it has kept the economy going largely through huge
spending programs on public works projects and by protecting
industries that are not competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Although Japan cannot easily abandon its heavy spending for fear
of triggering a deep recession, the country is fast approaching
dangerous levels of public debt for programs that in many cases
will never prove productive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next election will be a battle between the LDP and its
coalition partners, which are wasting public funds by scattering
money about for public works, versus an opposition, which is very
serious about structural reform,'' said Naoto Kan, the policy chief
of the Democratic Party of Japan, the leading opposition group.
``In terms of message, I think things will be very clear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1732EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8010 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-DEMS-GOP-ELIAN-HNS &LR;      04-05 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-GOP-ELIAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TOP DEMOCRAT ACCUSES GOP OF RAISING MONEY FROM GONZALEZ CASE  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of the Democratic party on Wednesday
cited a fundraising appeal by Florida Republicans to accuse the GOP
of using the custody battle over 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez to raise
campaign donations.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph J. Andrew, the national chairman of the Democratic party,
made the allegation after releasing an intercepted GOP fund-raising
appeal that condemned the Clinton administration's handling of the
Gonzalez case.
</P>
<P>
   The February letter appealed for donations to serve as a
``powerful force against the Democrats and the liberals who act
cowardly before the intimidating tactics, the hysterical speeches
and the criminal lies of (Fidel) Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida GOP Chairman Al Cardenas, a Cuban-born U.S.-educated
lawyer, signed the fundraising appeal.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore and other Democrats are ``struggling to make sure we
have the best interests of the child'' at heart, ``we've got
Republicans here fundraising on it,'' Andrew declared.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew said the four-page GOP fundraising appeal was ``literally
an attempt to make direct political hay (and) raise cash over a
6-year-old boy's plight,'' adding that it is ``unconscionable''
that Republicans are ``taking a complicated issue and trying to
raise dollars off of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Portia Palmer, a spokeswoman for the Florida Republican party in
Tallahassee, Fla., conceded that the criticism was ``appropriate''
but emphasized that the fundraising letter was sent to ``a limited
mailing list'' in February and repudiated by the Florida GOP in
March.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Republican party has forwarded all proceeds from the
mailing to the Elian Gonzalez Legal Defense Fund, Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   The fund is helping to finance efforts by Gonzalez' Miami-based
relatives to enable the youngster to remain in the United States
rather than return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer declined to discuss the number of letters mailed or the
amount of money turned over to the Gonzalez fund.
</P>
<P>
   The statement issued by the Florida GOP on Wednesday said ``the
Democrats are late and wrong on the real issue at hand,'' adding
that the Clinton administration has been responsible for ``8 years
of capitulation toward the Castro dictatorship'' and for the legal
``limbo'' suffered by Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has been staying with anti-Castro relatives in Florida
since being rescued at sea on Thanksgiving Day after his mother and
10 other Cubans died when their boat capsized while trying to reach
the United States. The boy's parents had been divorced.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who lives in Cuba, won a
go-ahead from Castro on Wednesday to travel to the United States to
stay with his son until the custody battle is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department set a Thursday deadline for the boy's
Miami relatives to sign an agreement promising to return the boy to
his father if they lose their case in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew distributed the intercepted Republican fundraising appeal
after defending Gore's controversial public break with the Clinton
administration last Thursday to support an effort to keep Gonzalez
in the United States so that a Florida family court could
adjudicate the custody battle.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew insisted that Gore's announcement 18 weeks into the
controversy was a sign of political courage rather than evidence
that the vice president was bending to political pressure to curry
favor with the Cuban American community in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm actually very proud that he did it,'' Andrew said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has scheduled campaign stops in Florida on Thursday and
Friday, with stops in Palm Beach, Fort Lauderdale and Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew said Democrats believe that Gore has a good chance to
carry Florida and its 25 electoral votes in November despite the
fact that the state's governor, Jeb Bush, is a younger brother of
the presumptive GOP presidential nominee, Texas Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore hopes to repeat President Clinton's feat in 1996 when he
carried Florida by 6 percentage points over Republican Bob Dole to
become only the third Democrat in the 10 elections since 1960 to
carry the nation's fourth largest state.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton recovered from his 1992 defeat in Florida in part by
boosting his share of the state's Hispanic vote from 31 percent in
1992 to 42 percent in 1996. Florida's 800,000 Cuban-Americans make
up the largest share of Hispanics in Florida, who account for 12
percent of the voting-age population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida is clearly a state that's in play,'' Andrew told
reporters. ``We have no secret signal that we believe that Florida
is a state that we can win and we're going to make sure that we
have the resources and the time and the energy to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent opinion surveys found the state up for grabs. A
Mason-Dixon poll completed on March 8 showed Bush leading Gore in
the state, 45 percent to 37 percent. A Rasmussen Research survey
completed March 16 showed Gore leading Bush, 43 percent to 37
percent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart(at)hearstdc.com )
</P>
