<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8013 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-FAMILY-RADIO-ART-     04-05 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FAMILY-RADIO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING A WALKIE-TALKIE IN EVERY POCKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ga., N.C., Md., Col.)   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent as NYT9 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 By ROY FURCHGOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On their February ski vacation to Crested Butte in Colorado,
Madeline Bayard and Wendy Black woke one morning to whiteout
conditions and a tough decision: Should they waste valuable
vacation time waiting for the weather to improve or brave the
storm? Emboldened by a pair of $90 palm-size two-way radios that
would let them find each other if separated, or even call for help,
they decided to strap on their skis.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, later that day the two did become separated, and Bayard
was uneasy. ``It was like skiing in a pillowcase,'' she said. Cold
and unhappy, she turned to the radio, which she had bought back
home in Baltimore, and called for Black. ``When Wendy's voice came
back, it was like, `Yeah!''' Bayard recalled. They rendezvoused and
traded cold toes on the slopes for warm drinks in the lodge.
</P>
<P>
   Small but powerful two-way radios _ updated versions of the
walkie-talkie _ are growing in popularity among families on the go,
gadgeteers, hikers, cyclists, roller skaters and other sports
enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission had these very people in
mind when it created the Family Radio Service in 1996 and carved
out a section of the airwaves for it. The FRS handles two-way
radios that broadcast up to two miles; no license is required.
Radio manufacturers won approval to produce 14 FRS models in 1997,
41 in 1998, 72 in 1999 and 23 so far this year, a testament to the
demand for these devices.
</P>
<P>
   The radios have become popular partly because they are so easy
to use _ the push of a button is all that is needed to communicate
with friends or family members on the other side of a shopping
mall, at the base of a ski run or farther up the road or trail. Any
number of radios, even ones from different manufacturers, can be
used together.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these short-distance radios offer communication over 14
channels, with 38 squelch settings that help the user block out
other people's conversations. By selecting the same channel and the
same squelch setting, two or more people can have a conversation
and effectively block transmissions from other users who are within
range but are not on the same setting (although the conversation is
not private _ it can be overheard by others tuned in to that
frequency).
</P>
<P>
   The radios cost roughly $35 to $200 each, (street prices can be
much lower than list prices), with the least expensive models
featuring fewer than 14 channels and no squelch settings. The more
expensive radios come with many extra features, like
voice-activated transmissions for hands-free operation, a choice of
sounds to signify incoming calls (including vibration), a built-in
weather radio or a scramble mode that makes your conversation
unintelligible to nearby listeners using a different brand.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few months, however, the manufacturers will
introduce new models that really load on the extras. Motorola will
offer a model with a digital compass, thermometer, altimeter,
barometer and FM radio. Cobra will have a unit with a weather radio
that will turn on automatically for an alert. And Audiovox will
sell a radio with a Global Positioning System receiver to pinpoint
locations.
</P>
<P>
   The radios are also popular because they are generally less
expensive to buy and use than other communications devices, like
cell phones, and can work better at short range. That was the
experience of Gary Eheman, a senior market support representative
stationed in Atlanta for International Business Machines, when he
attended an industry convention in Anaheim, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Although Eheman had a wireless phone and his co-workers had
pagers, he was thwarted when he tried to use his cell phone to call
a colleague from a basement conference room. That's when he thought
about how useful family radios would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at my cell phone and I can't get a signal. Why?
I'm below ground,'' he said. He switched to a set of Uniden 1400
radios _ a friend had purchased the pair for about $80 at a
warehouse buying club _ and reached a colleague on the 10th floor.
And there were no per-call charges.
</P>
<P>
   Away from work, Eheman and his son use the radios to stay in
touch while hiking. The range of the radios is generally advertised
as 2 miles, although atmospheric conditions, location and the type
of terrain can alter that range significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Another fan of the FRS radios is Paul Folmsbee, a real estate
agent with Block &AMP; Associates in Raleigh, N.C., who uses the radios
to talk to clients traveling in a separate car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Car to car, you get three-quarters of a mile,'' he said. ``Out
in the clear, you get about a mile and a half. Under exceptional
conditions, at the beach to someone out on the water, you'll get
the 2 miles.''
</P>
<P>
   Folmsbee also uses the radios at the mall with his wife. ``If I
want to go to Radio Shack and she wants to go to the shoe store, we
have a way to meet back up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under optimal conditions, the radios can far exceed the expected
range. Hobbyists in a short-distance radio Usenet group claim to
have transmitted 38 miles, from a Tennessee mountaintop to the
valley below, and others have claimed a distance of 58 miles,
transmitting mountaintop to mountaintop.
</P>
<P>
   Since all models are limited by law to the same power output, a
half-watt, they differ primarily in the extra features they offer.
</P>
<P>
   A look at four 14-channel radios _ the Motorola T289 (a more
elaborate radio, the Motorola T6100, is not yet available), Kenwood
UBZ-LH14, Cobra FRS 310WX and Audiovox FR-314 _ show the range of
features available. In a test, all had good sound and range,
comfortably covering more than a mile in a downtown area.
</P>
<P>
   All the models offer the 38 squelch settings to block out
signals from other radios. That is becoming more important as the
airwaves become more crowded, especially in tourist locations. The
models can communicate with one another if they are set to the same
channel and same squelch setting.
</P>
<P>
   The family radios are like CB radios in that anyone who has one
can eavesdrop on a particular frequency. To make a conversation
more private, you need a scramble feature, which makes your signal
intelligible only to others with the same brand who have tuned
their radios to the same channel and turned on their descramblers.
That, of course, could still include listeners other than the ones
you intend to reach.
</P>
<P>
   Most family radios come with a keyboard lock, which turns off
all but the push-to-talk button and volume controls. That can keep
children from inadvertently changing channels, which could lead to
missed calls.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On the Motorola, holding down the display light button for two
seconds disables the keyboard. That's so simple that it's easy to
shut down the keyboard accidentally.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, other units required a visit to the manual to set
the lock. On the Kenwood radio, the instructions read, ``With
transceiver power off, press and hold the mode key, then press the
power switch.'' That is difficult to remember, but it also makes it
hard to disable the keyboard by accident.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the Motorola radio was the easiest to use without
consulting the manual. Ease of use and attractive cases have made
Motorola's models popular.
</P>
<P>
   A handy feature on the Cobra radio is the ``roger beep.'' When
the Send button is released, a beep tone is transmitted to the
other handset to let that person know when it is time to talk. That
is easier than saying, ``Over,'' or perhaps, ``Roger wilco,'' after
every transmission, which might be a thrill (or an embarrassment)
for the neophyte but in either case gets old very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The Cobra also has a more sophisticated call signal, which
alerts the other person _ or people _ that you want to talk. The
Cobra's signal is silent at the sending end, while the other radios
play a ringing tone at the sending end that is duplicated at the
receiver. The Audiovox radio offered a series of different tones,
including a song from the Popeye cartoon and ``shave and a haircut,
two bits.'' The Cobra can also be set to vibrate like a pager,
rather than ringing.
</P>
<P>
   The Kenwood radio is notable for its scanning feature, which can
be set to either find the busiest, or least busy, channel or a
clear channel. The Kenwood scanner can also search for signals from
a companion handset, although the Talk key on the other radio must
be depressed at the right moment. The process may require as much
coordination between users as does manually calling back and forth
until a clear channel is found.
</P>
<P>
   The Audiovox is the most compact of the four models, about a
half-inch smaller in width and height than the other radios but
just as powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of the careful limits on engineering that the
FCC has specified for these short-distance radios, there was no
clear difference in broadcast distance or clarity in the radios we
tested. Many features come down to personal preferences, like
whether to get models with rechargeable or single-use batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Rechargables are less expensive to use, and some would say more
environmentally friendly. The advantage of single-use batteries is
that you can buy more when you are at Disneyland and your power
runs low. The Cobra, Motorola and Audiovox can run on either power
source. The Kenwood uses only single-use batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Some models, including the Cobra and Kenwood, have fold-down
antennas, while some, including the Motorola and Audiovox, have
fixed antennas that are more rugged. The fold-away antennas make
the radios easier to pack, but the radios work best when their
delicate antennas are extended and vulnerable. The fixed antennas
are beefy enough to withstand everyday use.
</P>
<P>
   Walkie-talkie owners say they buy the units for security but
become hooked on them because they are fun. The Washington Area
Roller Skaters, which holds a group skating excursion that starts
near the White House several times a week, gives an FRS radio to
the lead skater, who picks the route, and the sweeper, who makes
sure that no one is hurt or left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Clayton, a hair salon owner from Baltimore, makes it a
point to be the sweeper whenever she goes. ``You can volunteer to
sweep, and I like to so I can play with the walkie-talkie,'' she
said. ``It looks official.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Family radios are not the only two-way wireless devices. Here
are some others: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOY WALKIE-TALKIES These toys, like those emblazoned with
Pokemon or Buzz Lightyear, have about the same broadcast power as a
garage door opener. The range may be 100 yards _ the front yard to
the back yard, provided the house isn't in between. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMMERCIAL WALKIE-TALKIES Often carried by construction workers,
these are usually General Mobile Radio Service devices. They have a
power output of one to five watts and a range of up to 5 miles for
portable units, more for base units. These devices can also be for
personal use. An $80 license is required. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CITIZENS' BAND RADIOS These are powerful, with a four-watt
transmitter of broadcast power, and no license is required. But
reception can vary greatly, depending on atmospheric conditions.
Under good conditions, CBs can broadcast several miles; under
exceptional conditions, the range can be 20 miles or more. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CELLULAR WALKIE-TALKIE SERVICE This is available through
wireless phone service providers like Nextel. The handset can be
used as a walkie-talkie, sending free calls to matching handsets.
No license is needed, but you need a phone-service contract. &QL; 
(af)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
