</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFANT-HEARING06-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GROUP URGES MANDATORY HEARING TESTS FOR ALL NEWBORNS
 &HT;    Eds: Corrects congressman in first graf following optional trim.
 &HT;    420&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Newborns should receive mandatory hearing tests
from hospitals before they are taken home, a national group said
Wednesday as it released its state-by-state report card on newborn
hearing screenings.
</P>
<P>
   More than 12,000 babies are born deaf or with serious hearing
loss annually, and it sometimes takes parents up to two years to
find out, according to Hear Us: The National Campaign for Hearing
Health (NCHH).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's 22 babies who go home every day without being able to
hear their parents say 'I love you,''' said Elizabeth A. Foster,
campaign director of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Tom and Laura Miller of Long Island, N.Y., are parents of two
hearing-impaired children. They told a forum hosted by NCHH that
they did not realize that their oldest daughter, Veronica, 5, was
deaf until she was 14 months old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine, with mandatory testing at birth, Veronica would not
have any speech delays today,'' said a sobbing Tom Miller. ``With a
simple inexpensive test given at birth, you are not going to
eliminate hearing loss, but you can identify it and address it.
</P>
<P>
   Universal Newborn Hearing Screenings (UNHS), a system that tests
hearing abilities shortly after birth, costs as little as $20.
</P>
<P>
   But less than 35 percent of all newborns in the United States
are tested for hearing because hospitals are not required to
administer the test, and parents don't know that they should get
their children tested at birth, Foster said.
</P>
<P>
   The group is launching a campaign, called May Babies, aimed at
increasing by 50 percent the number of newborns who are screened
for hearing problems.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing deficiencies can affect a child's cognitive, language
and academic development, said Dr. Eugene Sussman, a pediatrician
at Holy Cross in Maryland. But if detected early enough, he said,
steps can be taken to help the child.
</P>
<P>
   Only 24 states have adopted policies or mandates supporting
UNHS, according to the NCHH report card. Of those states, nine got
grades of excellent.
</P>
<P>
   Texas received a ``good'' rating, while Florida, Ohio and
Georgia were given grades of ``fair.'' Georgia and Texas have
enacted screening legislation, while bills are pending in Ohio and
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's legislation encourages, but does not mandate
screenings. Georgia screens 21 percent of babies born in the state
annually, while Florida screens 25.8 percent for hearing. Ohio
screens 17.3 percent of its newborns, and Texas screens 26.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Congress last November passed the Infant Hearing Screening Act,
sponsored by Rep. James Walsh, R-N.Y. The three-year law gives seed
money in the form of grants to states that want to set up their own
UNHS programs.
</P>
<P>
   States can apply for the grants through the federal Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention or the Health Resources Service
Administration. Both organizations were allocated $3.5 million
under the new law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's give our kids the chance to hear the rush of a stream,
to hear the genius of Mozart or Wynton Marsalis,'' said Walsh, who
for nine years had been unsuccessful in his attempts to get the
legislation to pass in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can have all the research and all the legislation we want,
but it won't make a difference if parents don't get involved and
demand that their babies get tested,'' said Dr. Karl White,
director of the National Center for Hearing Assessment and
Management at Utah State University.
</P>
<P>
   More information about hearing screening can be obtained at the
National Campaign for Hearing Health Web site at
www.hearinghealth.net or at National Center for Hearing Assessment
and Management's site at www.infanthearing.org.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
