<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8022 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-UNIVERSE-1STLD-$ADV09     04-05 1535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSE-1STLD-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FLASHES BRIGHTER THAN A MILLION GALAXIES MYSTIFY ASTRONOMERS
 &HT;    Eds: Corrects univerity in graf 4 to ``Santa Cruz.''
 &HT;    750&AMP;add. For release Sunday, April 9.
 &HT;    Eds: Second in the occasional ``Window on the Universe'' series.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For roughly 30 years, astronomers have known that
mysterious flashes of radiation are lighting up the distant
universe about 100 times a day, each with the energy of all the
stars of a million galaxies.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, more than 170 different explanations of what
is going on have been suggested. Nearly all of them have been
proved wrong, and Stan Woosley was the author of five of them.
</P>
<P>
   So, Woosley remains cautious about the growing popularity among
physicists of his sixth explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been wrong before,'' said the University of California,
Santa Cruz, astrophysicist, ``so I like to keep a certain amount of
skepticism, even about my own models.''
</P>
<P>
   In about three years, the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration plans to launch a ``low-budget'' $163 million
satellite called ``Swift'' to make the observations that could
finally determine whether Woosley's newest theory is correct.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is built around a scenario in which an extremely
large star abruptly collapses, then explodes in what astronomers
are calling a ``hypernova.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause of the bursts, astronomers agree they
represent the most violent explosions to occur since the ``Big
Bang,'' in which the universe is believed to have originated
billions of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Radiation from a gamma ray burst taking place 5,000 light years
(or about 30,000 trillion miles) from the Earth would burn away the
ozone layer and wipe out life on the planet, some scientists
believe. That's not a likely prospect, since the bursts are
believed to occur only once every 10 million years in our entire
galaxy, which is 100,000 light years across.
</P>
<P>
   If a burst occurred at a distance of about 50,000 light years,
it would shine as brightly as the noonday sun for a minute or two,
then disappear forever.
</P>
<P>
   This fleeting nature of gamma ray bursts has frustrated
scientists for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Some bursts last for a minute or two, others for a fraction of a
second. Like camera flashes you see from the corner of your eye,
then turn to find gone, the bursts fade rapidly from view and with
one notable exception, astronomers have never seen one.
</P>
<P>
   If it works as intended, the Swift satellite will detect a gamma
ray burst, then wheel about and focus its onboard telescopes on the
site while the event is still going on.
</P>
<P>
   Gamma ray bursts were first observed on July 2, 1967, said Neil
Gehrels, head of the gamma ray astrophysics branch of NASA's
Goddard Space Flight Center at Greenbelt, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force ``Vela'' satellites had been placed in orbit to
monitor Soviet compliance with the Nuclear Test Ban Treaty by
watching for the high-energy gamma rays given off by nuclear
explosions. Soon, it became apparent that the satellites were
detecting gamma ray events that did not originate on the Earth's
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Since gamma rays from the bursts are absorbed by the atmosphere,
these phenomena had never been detected before.
</P>
<P>
   About two years later, satisfied the phenomena had no military
significance, Air Force officials revealed their existence,
creating overnight a new branch of astronomy and astrophysics and
setting in motion the three-decade search for an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Woosley said he has ``loved things that go kaboom'' since
childhood, when he used a toy chemistry set and a small tank of
propane to blow up a backyard shed. His gamma ray bursts, however,
are confined to the innards of a computer, which he used to make
complicated calculations describing the explosion of an star 30
times or more the size of the sun.
</P>
<P>
   He figured the explosion would send ``jets'' of matter racing
through space at 99.995 percent of the speed of light.
</P>
<P>
   When these jets collide with wispy-thin clouds of gas that
surround the exploded star, the gamma ray burst is created, Woosley
thinks. Because they are moving at a speed that is at the very edge
of scientific imagination, the particles within the jet collide
with the gas clouds and with each other with such awful force that
a beam of gamma rays, visible light and X-rays is propelled into
space in the direction of the jet.
</P>
<P>
   Only when the Earth lies in the path of the beam would it be
seen. The fact that the bursts are seen about once a day implies
that another 99 or so are happening but point away from this
planet, Woosley says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our model can explain the bursts that last around 20
seconds,'' Woosley said, ``but not the burst that lasts only
three-tenths of a second. We think that some other model, like
merging neutron stars, might explain those.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The collision of two neutron stars would amount to about the
biggest atom smasher imaginable. Both stars would be converted to
raw energy in a fraction of a second.
</P>
<P>
   But Bohdan Paczynski, a Princeton University astrophysicist who
proposed the merging neutron star model, says he has become
skeptical about all of the explanations, including his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a long chain of if-if-if and hypotheses and so on,''
he said, ``but observational evidence is limited. I am very cynical
about the models. I used to do this myself and it is difficult to
be very positive or very negative about any specific model.''
</P>
<P>
   What's needed, Paczynski said, is more observation.
</P>
<P>
   So far, astronomers have seen only a dim ``afterglow'' of gamma
ray bursts, and they believe these represent the supernova
explosions the jets left behind. Instruments aboard NASA's Compton
Gamma Ray Observatory, launched in 1991, have been detecting the
bursts for the past decade and locating them within general regions
of sky roughly as large as 1,600 full moons.
</P>
<P>
   By the time, astronomical telescopes can search such an area,
the burst has long faded.
</P>
<P>
   One gamma ray burst has been seen directly, and that was
achieved with the help of the Internet and the 800-millimeter lens
of a Canon telephoto camera like those use by ``paparazzi''
celebrity photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Physicists at Goddard, the University of Michigan, and the Los
Alamos and Lawrence Livermore national laboratories used an an
Internet link to monitor Compton detections of gamma ray burst
events. Four of the Canon cameras automatically aim at the spot
where the Compton detected the bursts and start clicking away.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are far less powerful than astronomical telescopes,
the Canons cover a much larger area of sky, and on Jan. 23, 1999,
one of them photographed a burst of visible light inside the area
where the Compton had detected gamma rays.
</P>
<P>
   The light grew increasingly brighter for several minutes, then
faded. Astronomers are convinced it was the visible portion of the
event that created the gamma ray signal. But it was little more
than a small dot that became a large dot before fading away
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The event that caused the light appears to have happened 9
billion years ago, said Michigan physicist Carl Akerlof, director
of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a failure of one of its guidance systems, NASA has
decided to ``de-orbit'' the Compton in the next few weeks in an
effort to avoid having it fall onto a populated area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a sad moment for us,'' Akerlof said.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Swift satellite is in orbit, the observations will
continue.
</P>
<P>
   NASA astronomer Ann Parsons said gamma ray sensors on the
satellite will cover virtually the entire sky at all times. Small
blocks of lead will be scattered over the sensor panels in random
arrangements, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since lead absorbs gamma rays, the blocks will throw gamma
``shadows'' on the sensor panels, and an onboard computer will uses
these shadows to calculate more precisely the location of the
bursts.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite will then evaluate this information to decide
whether to swing around and aim its visible light and X-ray
telescopes at the spot, Parsons said. Such considerations as
whether the maneuver would expose the spacecraft's telescopes to
ruinous rays from the sun will go into the computer's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the 12 to 14 hours it now takes for close-up views of
the bursts, Swift will theoretically be able to start snapping
pictures within 20 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers can barely wait to get a look at those pictures.
</P>
<P>
   During a breakfast speech recently, Akerlof held up a bran
muffin to describe the enormous size of the event that caused the
flash recorded by his Canon cameras last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of matter that is converted to energy in a
one-megaton thermonuclear explosion is about the size of this
muffin,'' he said. ``But in a gamma ray burst, the quantity of
matter found in the sun appears to be converted to energy in about
10 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   It should make quite a celebrity photograph.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
