<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8025 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-PRESIDENT-REVIEW-S     04-05 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PRESIDENT-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTS GET SHORT SHRIFT IN PBS SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a big, fat PBS series about a topic so important that the
program has a companion book, ``The American President'' feels
rather sparse.
</P>
<P>
   The series jams profiles of all 41 presidents into 10 hours,
over five consecutive nights. Figure the math, and that's why the
program doesn't seem bloated. By TV measure, each president is half
a sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   That's all right for some. William Henry Harrison took office on
March 4, 1841, and died on April 4, 1841. What can they say, that
most of his furniture arrived? But it's a squeeze to stay on
schedule with an Abraham Lincoln or a Franklin Delano Roosevelt.
FDR loved his work, signed a lot of bills, got elected four times,
and wham, gone.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the profiles are like a theme week speed read on A&AMP;E's
``Biography'' series, only a bit more serious.
</P>
<P>
   Produced by the father-and-sons team of Philip B. Kunhardt Jr.,
Philip B. Kunhardt III and Peter W. Kunhardt, ``The American
President'' isn't flashy.
</P>
<P>
   It's not lushly photographed or scored. It ventures few grand
pronouncements. The narrator, Hugh Sidey of Time magazine fame, is
serviceable but not rich of voice. It doesn't lend a sense of
pageantry to the nation's highest political office.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there a profusion of on-camera historians. In fact,
there's one. He's Richard Neustadt of Harvard _ smiley,
bespectacled, bad teeth, good mind, pretty much down-to-earth.
</P>
<P>
   If you hang around, you might find yourself getting to like
Neustadt's modest observations about the presidents. The same is
true of the series itself. Don't expect brilliant illumination or
glitzy footwork, and ``The American President'' can grow on you.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, you won't learn what the Founding Fathers had in
mind for the presidency, but you do learn that ``Hail to the
Chief'' was first played for James Polk.
</P>
<P>
   The program's organization is problematic. Rather than starting
with George Washington and moving chronologically, it bunches the
presidents around one-hour themes.
</P>
<P>
   The first hour on Sunday, for example, looks at presidents who
reached office on the wave of family dynasties: John Quincy Adams,
son of John Adams; Benjamin Harrison, grandson of William Henry
Harrison; Franklin D. Roosevelt, cousin of Theodore Roosevelt; and
John F. Kennedy, son of the willful Joe Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   That's a curious and not altogether effective way to batch these
presidents. Sunday's second hour makes more sense. John Tyler,
Millard Fillmore, Andrew Johnson, Chester Arthur and Harry Truman
were some, but not all, of the ``accidental'' presidents _ vice
presidents under men who died in office.
</P>
<P>
   With these thematic batchings, some presidents seem hammered
into the wrong holes. Who wouldn't feel a little tug of remorse to
see that Abraham Lincoln turns up on Monday in a ``professional
politician'' category?
</P>
<P>
   (If you're wondering, Bill Clinton is the last president on the
last night, profiled with James Madison, James Polk and William
Howard Taft in a ``balance of power'' category. In Clinton's case,
it's about how 1990s partisanship strained the constitutional
balance of power.)
</P>
<P>
   The program provides voices for those presidents who didn't
leave audio recordings behind. Some of these are uneasy fits, too.
George Will's voice doesn't work with John Quincy Adams' visage. I
have heard Teddy Roosevelt's voice, and it didn't sound like
William F. Buckley. Others are ... interesting. Former Atlanta
Mayor Andrew Young voices Thomas Jefferson. Walter Cronkite is
George Washington. That one'll do.
</P>
<P>
   The presidents who speak for themselves include several
interviewed specifically for the series. Clinton and all the living
ex-presidents, except for Ronald Reagan, consented to on-camera
interviews. Clinton thanks the public for his ``second chance.''
Jimmy Carter credits his self-confidence and religious faith for
getting him through his disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the series makes clear is that unlike modern
presidential prospects, who practically drool to get elected,
plenty of presidents didn't want the job and were happy to leave
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel no regret that I was relieved of the thankless task of
running this government,'' Fillmore said after a presidency of
barely two years.
</P>
<P>
   And that from a man who never even had to figure out a
definitive position on Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
