<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, April 6, 2000, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Jet stream winds moving quickly above the northern tier of
states will bring rapid weather changes to that region in the next
few days.
</P>
<P>
   Mild air will surge across the Ohio Valley into the Middle
Atlantic States on strong winds from the Southwest. Patchy clouds
will accompany the arrival of the milder air but sunshine will be
ample. Wind gusts over 30 miles an hour will be common as vigorous
low pressure moves east near the Canadian border. Clouds and a
broken area of rain and snow showers will occur in the chilly air
near the track of the low pressure center.
</P>
<P>
   A strengthening disturbance will produce intermittent snow over
the northern Rockies. In the wake of the low, blustery northerly
winds will deliver colder air to the region. Later Thursday night
and Friday as the storm center moves swiftly east, thundershowers
will develop in the central Mississippi Valley. Some snow will
whiten the eastern Dakotas and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: FIRE SEASON
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, residents of northern Virginia were alerted to a
heightened risk of wildfires Thursday. In much of the East, the
greatest risk from forest and brush fires typically occurs in
spring. Brush, leaves and grass deadened from winter provide fuel
for the fires. Also at this time, winds are relatively strong and
humidities are relatively low resulting in high evaporation rates
and fast drying. As a result, even after a period of spring rain,
the risk of fires can return within days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (JT)
</P>
