<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-AID06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. HOUSE MEMBER ANGERED BY DELAY IN FLOOD AID
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A North Carolina lawmaker expressed frustration and
anger Wednesday that more than $300 million in hurricane relief for
the state is stalled in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just absolutely ridiculous,'' said Rep. Bob Etheridge,
D-N.C. ``People living in trailers don't want to be there for a
second winter. ... They've been through hell. They don't want to
have to go through it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and other GOP
leaders this week indefinitely postponed action on a $12.6 billion
supplemental spending package for the current fiscal year that
includes the disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans say the bill is bloated and that Congress
should deal with much of the spending, including flood relief, as
part of the normal appropriations process for fiscal 2001, which
begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no excuse for it,'' Etheridge said of the possible
delay. ``We are talking about American tax-paying citizens who've
lived by the rules and done the right things, and they don't
deserve to be treated this way.''
</P>
<P>
   The spending bill approved by the House, which more than doubled
President Clinton's request, includes $2.1 billion for peacekeeping
operations in Kosovo and $1.7 billion for drug intervention in
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The Colombia issue is particularly controversial, as critics
have expressed concerns about human rights violations and drug
trafficking by military and paramilitary groups fighting a civil
war there.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Walter Jones, R-N.C., said the problem with the spending
bill is not the money for drug interdiction or for U.S. troops in
Kosovo, but the millions in special projects that are not
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping that in the short term ... Senator Lott will go
ahead and move what is a true emergency,'' he said. ``Obviously,
the needs of North Carolina _ they are an emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones also said he was confident that North Carolina's two
senators would work with the Senate leadership to secure the money.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lanier, an aide to Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said that Helms
would try to get the flood relief in the first spending bill to
move through Congress, whether that is a supplemental bill for
fiscal 2000 or a regular appropriations measure for fiscal 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Last fiscal year's first appropriations bill was signed into law
Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, language could be inserted to make the money
available as soon as the bill passes, he said. ``We don't want
people to have to wait until October,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only a month or two longer but the truth is, that
matters,'' said Michael Briggs, a spokesman for Sen. John Edwards,
D-N.C. ``We need to get the money to the people who need it ... as
soon as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has sent nearly $2 billion in disaster
aid to North Carolina, but much of it was delayed for weeks last
fall in a budget fight between Congress and the White House. In
addition, the state legislature has provided $836 million.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency spending package, which was approved by the House
last week, includes $81 million for tobacco farmers, $68 million
for home buyouts, $43 million for road repairs, $41 million for
rental housing and assistance, $12 million for a new Armed Forces
Reserve Center in Greenville, and $1.5 million for a U.S. Army
Corps of Engineers study on raising the dike on the Tar River in
the historic town of Princeville, in Edgecombe County.
</P>
<P>
   Etheridge said that Republicans could suffer politically if they
don't move the desperately needed hurricane aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, it's in their camp and if they fail
to do it, I don't think there's any question about who held it
up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eunice Moscoso's e-mail address is eunicem(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
