<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-AID _ WASHINGTON _ A North Carolina congressman said
Wednesday it was ``ridiculous and outrageous'' that residents of
his state might be forced to wait six months or longer for flood
relief funds. More than $300 in aid is contained in an emergency
spending bill that Senate leaders have decided not to act on.
(Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-PORK _ WASHINGTON _ In flush economic times, the
congressional largesse has hit historic levels, says a critic of
``pork barrel'' spending. In its annual accounting, the ``Pig
Book'' of Citizens Against Government Waste says that pet projects
for home states will cost $17.7 billion this year, 22 percent
higher than the previous record of $14.5 billion set three years
ago. Among the ``award winners'' this year is Rep. Jack Kingston,
R-Ga., for obtaining $100,000 for Vidalia onion research. (Malone,
Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   INFANT-HEARING _ WASHINGTON _ The National Campaign for Hearing
Health hosts a forum to discuss ''the leading birth defect in the
nation: undetected hearing loss.'' NCHH will also release its
state-by-state ``report card'' identifying which states provide
comprehensive newborn screening programs. (Turay, Cox News
Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   BUSWRECK-FOLO _ Updating investigation into Tennessee-Georgia
train wreck that killed three kids and injured four other people,
including the bus driver. Driver Rhonda Cloer still has not spoken
to investigators. Her daughter remains in induced coma and Rhonda
remains with her. Updating conditions of Cloer and the other child.
(Bennett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10
</P>
