<HEADER>
A8034 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-BOOKS-LAURENTS-SFCHRO     04-05 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-LAURENTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 A BROADWAY ORIGINAL: Writer-director Arthur Laurents hasn't
lost  any of his feisty spirit  
 By STEVEN WINN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK &LR;   &LR; _ The name might not register as quickly as Stephen
Sondheim, Ethel Merman, Barbra Streisand or Alfred Hitchcock, all
of whom he has worked with in over a half century on Broadway and
in Hollywood. But there's probably not a man or woman alive who
epitomizes the ebullient, feisty and pretension-skewering spirit of
20th century show business like the playwright and director Arthur
Laurents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is almost nothing on stage, screen or the printed page
that isn't too long,'' Laurents asserts with typical swagger,
``largely because of the notion that length equals importance.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurents wrote the classic books for ``West Side Story'' and
``Gypsy'' and the films ``Anastasia,'' ``The Way We Were'' and
Hitchcock's ``Rope.'' He directed the landmark gay musical ``La
Cage aux Folles.'' He was blacklisted in the 1950s and battered for
the infamous 1991 Broadway flop ``Nick and Nora,'' which he wrote
and directed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at a very unbowed 82, he's published a bracingly frank
memoir, ``Original Story By'' (Knopf; $30), that pulls few punches.
</P>
<P>
   Greeting a visitor at his spacious Greenwich Village townhouse
one recent morning, Laurents looked as trim and almost as energetic
as a bantam weight prizefighter, a plum-colored ascot at his
throat. He was just back from a European ski vacation, followed by
a stint of London theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing worth seeing,'' he groused, his view made
uncontestable by the native Brooklyn burr in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions come easily and in unvarnished form for Laurents, both
on the page and in person. Unlike most showbiz autobiographies,
this one celebrates the joys of collaboration without blinking at
the flaws of his colleagues, friends and lovers. There was ``West
Side Story'' director Jerome Robbins' paranoia and composer Leonard
Bernstein's ego, ``Gypsy'' star Merman's obtuseness and his own
long struggle to embrace his homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Of today's musical theater, Laurents is equally blunt.
``Ragtime'' is ``god-awful. How many scenic styles can one show
have? I liked the first 10 minutes of `The Lion King.'''
</P>
<P>
   Laurents is dismayed by the current director-driven theater.
``They have this tendency to say, `How can I make it mine?' instead
of serving the intentions of the piece.'' And he bemoans the
dwindling of new American plays on Broadway (``There's no place for
them there anymore'') and the dearth of true theatrical producers.
</P>
<P>
   But Laurents is at heart an optimist, a doer. ``I think life's
terrific. There are plenty of people who would hit me for saying
it.'' His own creative plate is full _ with new plays, a musical he
is writing with his godson (and Richard Rodgers' grandson) Adam
Guettel and forth coming revivals of his McCarthyism play ``Jolson
Sings Again'' and others.
</P>
<P>
   His friend Stephen Sondheim's gloomy reflections in a recent
prominent interview nettled Laurents. ``It sounded whiny. He's had
too much success to complain. The theater (set ital)is(end ital) in
a bad place, but you don't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by engraved mementos of his hits and flops in a sunny
sitting room, Laurents can boil down success or failure to an
essence. ``West Side Story'' worked ``because it was done out of
innocence. We didn't think we were doing (set ital)art.''(end ital)
``Gypsy'' was written (with lyricist Sondheim and composer Jule
Styne) in three months, with no director or producer interference:
``It came from one viewpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurents blames himself for attempting a ``Nick and Nora''
musical: ``It can't be done without William Powell and Myrna Loy. I
saw the story as a metaphor for dancing, and then I cast two people
(Barry Bostwick and Joanna Gleason) who couldn't dance. That wasn't
smart.''
</P>
<P>
   With ``La Cage,'' Laurents was convinced a 1983 Broadway
audience would never accept the gay love story if it were too
sexual. ``The gay community thought we pussyfooted, but they forget
this was the first time a man sang a love song to another man, held
his hand and kissed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Only in one area of his memoir, Laurents said, did he exercise
self-censorship: ``I didn't mention the names of any married
gays.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Original Story By'' is a jittery, jump-cut portrait of a life
devoted to the theater and the movies, with the joys of physical
love right up on the list. ``I think sex is absolutely primal. It
has always been a big part of my life, and it is today, at 82,''
said Laurents, whose book details some heady exploits with men in
his Army days and beyond, not to mention a fling with Lena Horne.
He also had a long-term relationship with film idol Farley Granger,
who starred in ``Rope.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurents met his longtime companion, Tom Hatcher, in the 1950s,
and he attributes much of his serenity to their life together. In
conversation, by contrast, serenity never suits Laurents for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see Kevin Spacey (on `60 Minutes'),'' Laurents replied
impishly, when asked about his own exit from the closet. ``He went
on and said he wasn't gay. OK. Then he said he was 40. And you
don't believe anything he says.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
