<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-SARAJEVO-WATERPOLO-AR     04-05 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SARAJEVO-WATERPOLO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE RUINS OF SARAJEVO TO STARDOM AT PRINCETON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.) (ART ADV: Photos NYT32-33 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SOPHIA HOLLANDER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Goga Vukmirovic heard a strange noise. It was a Monday morning,
April 6, 1992, the day of a dreaded biology test that the Sarajevo
seventh-grader had spent the entire weekend studying for furiously.
</P>
<P>
   She heard voices from outside her room, which made her pause,
because her parents were normally at work by the time she crawled
out of bed.
</P>
<P>
   Trodding tentatively into the living room, she saw her parents
gathered on the couch with her older sister Maja, watching scenes
on CNN _ scenes they had seen for weeks in Croatia, other places.
Not in Sarajevo. She sat on the couch and saw the war blowing apart
in her city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your first instinct is hey, no school today!'' Ogjenka
Vukmirovic said ruefully, sitting in her dorm room at Princeton
University where she is a senior, captain of the nationally ranked
women's water polo team and known to everyone as Goga. ``But it
hits you pretty quick when the bombs start exploding that it may
not be such a good bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   Vukmirovic, now 21, never went back to school in Bosnia, never
went back to seventh-grade, or eighth-grade for that matter. After
fleeing from the war with her mother and sister, she enrolled as a
high school student in Venezuela. The next year she was at a
Connecticut boarding school to finish high school, where she was
introduced to the sport of water polo.
</P>
<P>
   Now she lives in a neat, white-walled room with typical college
decorations: post cards on the wall, shelves of academic books, a
poster of the rock group U2. But the books on the shelves are
mostly on the war in Bosnia, research for one of two senior theses
she is writing. She will point out the postcards that picture
places bombed and destroyed in the war, use her mouse to diagram
shelling trajectories on her screen saver of the mountains outside
of Sarajevo. Next to a box of computer disks sits a small clear
glass container, filled with bullets that she picked up from the
floor of her room in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that strange?'' she asked, smiling. ``It keeps you
motivated to write your thesis, Ill tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't seem as if Vukmirovic needs motivation. A founding
member of Princeton's varsity water polo team, which is 18-3 this
season, she was the 1999 Ivy League and Eastern Collegiate Athletic
Conference most valuable player, and a 1999 all-America goalie. She
is the only senior in the four-year-old program and was the most
valuable player in the ECAC championships which Princeton won last
weekend. The nationals are May 5-7 in Bloomington, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Women's water polo is an emerging collegiate sport. Thanks to
Vukmirovic's efforts, Princeton was ranked in the top 10 for the
first time in its history earlier this season and remains, after
traditional West Coast powers, a national contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's kind of a legendary kid here,'' said Bill Berghoff, her
high school coach at Choate Rosemary Hall in Wallingford, Conn.
``She'll come to visit a practice and she'll walk on the deck and
all these little high school girls will collect around her. She's
very embarrassed by it.'`
</P>
<P>
   At Choate, there is the ``Goga defense,'' where the goalie
glides out of the goal into the center of the pool to help defend,
the ``Goga save'' _ anything spectacular _ and the ``Goga cap,''
which she wore at Choate and is now ratty and falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   She does not talk with teammates about her experiences unless
somebody asks, but it is always there. In the mornings at Choate,
she would rush to check her e-mail messages, the only way she could
communicate with her parents. When an e-mail message wasn't there,
she wondered why, and would check compulsively until it came.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was actually my lifeline which helped me a lot in this
period of separation,'' Vukmirovic's mother, Svjetlana, said
recently in an e-mail message from Sarajevo, to which she returned
after her daughters went to the United States. ``The situation in
Sarajevo was so difficult in that time, that we were actually happy
not to have them with us in that hell.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a series of missions for Vukmirovic, some seemingly
impossible. Lead a normal life without being able to hear or see
your parents for years, learn water polo, a sport she had never
seen until she started to play it. In Venezuela, where she lived
with her mother's family for 18 months, she attended school where
everything that was taught was in English and all she knew were
basic phrases. The first book she was assigned was ``Great
Expectations'' by Charles Dickens.
</P>
<P>
   But there was something to make her feel at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right as we went to Venezuela, they had a coup,'' she said.
``You saw all these people who are shocked that there are airplanes
flying over their homes and we were like, `oh, been there, done
that.' It's a sink-or-swim situation.''
</P>
<P>
   So she swam and followed her older sister to the United States
when a Choate representative visited her school. ``The progress as
a water polo player through her senior year was because she made it
a priority to learn,'' Berghoff said. ``When she commits to
something, she's just a hard driver. She does what she intends to
do. And she does it well.''
</P>
<P>
   After spending three years at Choate, Vukmirovic was accepted
into Harvard, Princeton, Yale and MIT. She chose Princeton because
she was offered an opportunity to work in a lab her freshman year
even though Princeton offered only a club water polo team.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the backbone of our team because you can always count on
the big save,'' Coach Luis Nicolao said. ``She has a very good
perspective on life, her priorities and the way she carries
herself. She's beyond her years.''
</P>
<P>
   Vukmirovic said that ``when you're not given a choice, you deal
with things much better because you can't second-guess yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can roll up and die and be depressed and sit in your room
all day, or you can figure out a way to go and deal with it,'' she
said. ``A lot of my papers and a lot of the work that I've done
relates to Bosnia. My thesis right now kind of brings a closure to
scattered years of thinking about some of these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Vukmirovic hoped that it would do more than provide a
personal closing. She considered returning to Bosnia after
graduation to try to implement her ideas for a truth commission to
promote ethnic reconciliation. She has since abandoned that idea,
stunned at the lack of support among her people, hurt that some now
view her as an international, someone too removed from the problem
to understand its solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a typical Bosnian; I thought that I was,'` she said (her
father is Serbian, her mother Muslim). ``Even at Choate, I thought
my views on reconciliation were something that 99 percent of the
Bosnian population would agree with, but they're absolutely not.
I'm a huge minority view, which was completely discouraging and
disheartening.''
</P>
<P>
   So instead, Vukmirovic will live in New York, and work at the
private-equity group J.H. Whitney in Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no econ background,'' she said, grinning. ``But I'm
very excited. It will be a challenge to me to learn it, to fit in.
This is going to be a sink or swim.''
</P>
<P>
   Been there. Done that.
</P>
<P>
   (JT)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
