<P>
   These business stories for release Thursday, April 6, 2000, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-MAIN _ Market slumps a bit early. The Nasdaq off about 20
points in the early going, while the Dow is off about 70 points.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DOW-SIDE _ Where are the safe havens for nervous investors who
worry a lot in the kind of volatile markets we have today?
Blue-chips? Bonds? Gold? O rnone of the above. The best advice for
most investors is usually to sit tight, but some people find this
hard to do these days. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AOL-BROWSER _ America Online Inc., the world's largest Internet
service, upgraded its Netscape Internet browser and said Gateway
Inc. will offer specialized Internet appliances featuring the
program. America Online said the new version, Netscape 6, is based
on open-source software, meaning programmers outside the company
can use the code it's based on to modify the browser. Such
contributions helped Netscape develop the underlying browser
program, called Netscape Gecko. America Online bought Netscape
Communications Corp. for $9.8 billion in March 1999. (Katz, Atlanta
Journl-Constitution). 16.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-STOCK _ Coke shares fell sharply on both short-term and
long-term concerns about the company's prospects. The dramatic
decline came only a day after Chairman Doug Daft and other
executives traveled to Wall Street to explain their strategy to
some 250 beverage analysts and money managers. But the company did
not get the buy-in it was hoping for. ``We expect investors to
restrain enthusiasm for KO until actual evidence of volume and
earnings growth acceleration begins to materialize,'' wrote analyst
Marc Cohen of Goldman, Sachs. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-DISCRIMINATION _ A coalition of advocacy groups has offered
their support to organizers of a bus ``ride for justice'' against
Coca-Cola Co. to get the company to settle an employee racial
discrimination case quickly. The Coalition for the People's Agenda
_ which includes the NAACP in Georgia, Concerned Black Clergy, the
Georgia Association of Black Elected Officials, the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference, the Coalition of Black Women and
others, says it will also help raise funds to underwrite the costs
of the April 15 trip from Atlanta to the company's annual
shareholders meeting in Wilmington, Del., on April 19. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ACE-WEBKIOSKS _ Ace Hardware is testing an Internet kiosk
program at stores in Atlanta. The co-op will show the kiosks to the
AJC at the World Congress Center on Wednesday. They're being rolled
out to stores this week. Hope to include update on web plans from
other hardware retailers, including Home Depot. (Bond, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
