<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8040 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER06-COX     04-05 2121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Primary padding continues
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore and George W. Bush, with the nominations already locked
up, coasted to two victories in two more states: Pennsylvania and
Wisconsin. But they weren't the only candidates on the ballot.
Pennsylvania Republicans (unofficial): Bush, 73 percent; John
McCain, 23 percent; Steve Forbes, 3 percent; Gary Bauer, 1 percent.
Pennsylvania Democrats (unofficial): Gore 74 percent; Bill Bradley,
21 percent; Lyndon LaRouche, 5 percent. Wisconsin Republicans
(unofficial): Bush, 69 percent; McCain, 18 percent; Alan Keyes, 10
percent; Forbes, 1 percent. Wisconsin Democrats (unofficial): Gore,
89 percent; Bradley, 9 percent; LaRouche, 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   HOME ON THE RANGE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush was taking the day off the campaign trail
Wednesday and turning to the business of governing Texas. And for
the first time, Bush's campaign team distributed a schedule of his
activities in Austin, Texas, to campaign reporters. The new
openness comes on the heels of recent press reports suggesting that
Bush doesn't work hard and may lack the stamina and drive for a
long campaign. ABC News reported that the governor was slated to
meet with staff and to sit through a series of campaign policy
briefings.
</P>
<P>
   BUT THEY'RE NICE PEOPLE THERE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush claimed victory in Tuesday's Kansas primary with
thanks to all the voters who came out to support him. One problem:
The primary was canceled in February. ``Thank you Pennsylvania,
Wisconsin and Kansas,'' Bush said in a statement issued by his
campaign. Bush and Al Gore coasted to victories in the other two
states, but Kansas officials, citing a tight budget and lack of
relevance so late in the primary season, dropped their primary.
Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer blamed the press release on a
``goof.'' He said the writer had used a chart that hadn't been
updated.
</P>
<P>
   GIULIANI SUPPORT WANING
</P>
<P>
   Another poll is out showing a drop in support for Rudy Giuliani
_ in the wake of another fatal police shooting of an unarmed black
man. The Quinnipiac College poll (3 percentage point margin of
error) shows Giuliani's lead over Hillary Rodham Clinton in New
York's Senate race melted into a 46 percent to 43 percent edge for
Clinton. Polls released last week from Zogby International for the
New York Post and from Marist College's Institute for Public
Opinion had similar results. In the March 2 Quinnipiac poll,
Giuliani led Clinton 48 percent to 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   SICK FRIEND COMES FIRST
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore abruptly scuttled a campaign trip to North Carolina
Wednesday to visit a sick friend. He spoke Wednesday morning at an
AFL-CIO meeting in Washington and is still expected at an evening
fund-raiser in Maryland. But Gore was to have flown to Charlotte
Wednesday night for a visit today to a middle school. Spokeswoman
Laura Quinn said Gore wanted to keep the matter private. But she
said, ``This is not in any way related to any family member nor the
health of the vice president or Mrs. Gore; it has to do with the
health of a friend.'' Gore's schedule was to resume this evening in
Florida. The Charlotte school visit has been rescheduled for April
13.
</P>
<P>
   MAKING THEM HAPPY IN MASSACHUSETTS
</P>
<P>
   John McCain, who won all 37 of Massachusetts' Republican
delegates, has agreed with Gov. Paul Cellucci, a Republican, to
send seven supporters of George W. Bush to the national convention.
The Boston Globe reported that Cellucci and Lt. Gov. Jane Swift are
expected to be among them.
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN MAKES SOUTH DAKOTA BALLOT
</P>
<P>
   Partly because of petition signatures gathered by Pat Buchanan's
campaign, the Reform Party has earned a place on the South Dakota
ballot, the Buchanan camp announced Wednesday. The Reform Party of
South Dakota ballot slot, earned after 6,505 signatures were
submitted to the secretary of state, marks the first time Reform
has ever had its own ballot line in South Dakota. Buchanan workers
secured a place on the Utah ballot earlier this year. Ross Perot
ran in South Dakota as an independent in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   THAT FREE SOIL MUST BE SHIFTING
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore made three different statements on Elian Gonzalez, and
it was not entirely clear what he had meant to convey. In short,
Gore said that the 6-year-old's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
should get to take his son to Cuba if he makes the request ``on
free soil'' in the United States. A Wall Street Journal analysis
noted that ``Gore has taken different approaches on Elian Gonzalez
and the Microsoft antitrust case.''
</P>
<P>
   IT'S KLINK TO FACE SANTORUM
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania Democrats chose Ron Klink in a six-way battle to
challenge the re-election of freshman Republican Sen. Rick
Santorum. Klink received 41 percent; State Sen. Allyson Schwartz,
26 percent; and former state Labor Secretary Tom Foley, 25 percent.
Three other, lesser-known candidates split the rest. Santorum had
no Republican opposition.
</P>
<P>
   OLD RACIAL COMMENT QUICKLY RESURRECTED
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after state Rep. Terry Van Horne won the Democratic
nomination for a congressional seat in southwestern Pennsylvania,
Republicans began circulating news stories alleging he used a
racial slur six years ago. Soon after the results were announced,
the Republican National Congressional Committee sent reporters
copies of 1994 news stories that quoted Van Horne, who is white,
referring to a black lawmaker from Philadelphia. The remark, made
in a state Capitol hallway, was reported at the time in the
Pittsburgh Post-Gazette. Van Horne said he was repeating what he
had heard others say when he was overheard by a reporter. Van Horne
and Republican state Sen. Melissa Hart are running for the seat
being vacated by four-term Democrat Ron Klink, now running for the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   RE-ELECTION IN MILWAUKEE
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee Mayor John Norquist won a fourth four-year term,
defeating a downtown businessman, George Watts, who targeted
Norquist's record on crime, taxes and keeping jobs in the city. The
tally: 56 percent to 44 percent. Norquist ran upbeat ads showing
him jogging around Milwaukee streets and closing up drug houses
alongside police officers. Watts challenged Norquist's assertion
that crime in Milwaukee is going down, and called for the ouster of
the police chief.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTION GAMBLE PAYS OFF
</P>
<P>
   About 125 miles from Milwaukee, in the small town of Tomah, Ed
Thompson, the younger brother of Gov. Tommy Thompson, beat
incumbent Mayor Bud Johnson 1,179 to 909. ``I feel like I'm king of
the world,'' said Ed Thompson, 55, who has been a professional
poker player in Las Vegas, a prison cook, a snow plow driver, and a
boxer in ``Toughman'' contests. He said he decided to run for mayor
after his supper club, Mr. Ed's Tee Pee, was raided. Thompson
settled out of court and agreed not to operate video poker machines
for two years. The governor did not campaign in Tomah for his
brother.
</P>
<P>
   LOTT'S CHALLENGER SELECTED
</P>
<P>
   An ex-college administrator who ran an unsuccessful campaign for
lieutenant governor of Mississippi last year will take on Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott in November. Troy Brown defeated farmer
Rickey Cole in the Democratic runoff. Lott, of course, is about as
unbeatable as it gets. In the only other Mississippi primary
runoff, accountant Randy McDonnell won the GOP's nomination for the
House 5th District race and will face incumbent Gene Taylor, a
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   BIG SLAP IN LITTLE RHODY
</P>
<P>
   Party endorsements may not mean everything, but it was a slap to
second-term Democratic Rep. Robert Weygand when the Rhode Island
Democratic Party voted to give its endorsement for senator to
Weygand's opponent, Richard Licht, a former lieutenant governor.
Licht has been trailing Weygand in polls for the chance to take on
Republican Sen. Lincoln Chafee, who took over the seat last year
after the death of his father, John Chafee. Licht last held a state
office 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT MICROSOFT MAY NEED
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, who has high-level backing from within Microsoft
Corp., is trying to steer clear of the software giant's legal woes.
In a bland statement issued when a federal judge declared Microsoft
an illegal monopoly, Bush said little more than that he would
``fully enforce antitrust laws.'' Back in February, though, Bush
had a lot more to say on a swing through Washington state,
Microsoft's homeland. ``I think the great fear is that Microsoft
will be broken up,'' he said, adding that he ``worried'' about the
consequences. Washington think-tank experts with opposing views on
what's best for the country, according to Cox Newspapers' Ken
Herman, think a Bush win in November is what's best for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   MAKE THEM SHOW THEMSELVES
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lloyd Doggett (D-Texas) filed legislation aimed at forcing
nonprofits to disclose their donors. Several high-profile
Republicans have set up 527 organizations that rake in a lot of
money to aid their causes, but are exempt from having to disclose
the donors. Cox Newspapers' Jena Health reported that Doggett wants
groups such as Republicans for Clean Air, which ran ads attacking
John McCain days before the March 7 Super Tuesday primaries, to
have to disclose the names of the people who control these groups
and anyone who receives payments of more than $200. Under Doggett's
bill, failure to do so could cost the groups $100 a day and as much
as $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   STILL NECK-AND-NECK HORSE RACE
</P>
<P>
   Two new polls indicate that November is still a tossup. An ABC
News/Washington Post survey has George W. Bush leading Al Gore by
47 percent to 45 percent, while a CNN/USA Today/Gallup survey has
Gore leading Bush 45 percent to 44 percent. Both polls were
conducted March 30-April 2 and have a margin of error of plus or
minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   LAZIO WILL HAVE TO WARM THE BENCH
</P>
<P>
   New York GOP chief William Powers says he's found no support for
a possible Senate run by Rep. Rick Lazio as an alternative to Rudy
Giuliani. ``I've taken the pulse of the party and there is nothing
there for Rick Lazio,'' Powers said. But Lazio said that ``a
handful'' of local county chairmen ``have called and pledged their
support, so I know he's not speaking for all county chairmen.''
Several days ago, Lazio said the party might be ``blowing'' the
Senate race against Hillary Rodham Clinton by lining up behind
Giuliani, and that he, Lazio, was ready to run if the party wanted
him.
</P>
<P>
   FOR WYLY, ADVERTISING DIDN'T PAY
</P>
<P>
   That wealthy Texan who spent $2.5 million on ads backing George
W. Bush said he's getting out of political advertising. Sam Wyly
stirred the presidential campaign last month with the Republicans
for Clean Air ads. Broadcast in New York, Ohio and California, the
ads praised Bush's environmental record and attacked John McCain.
But in a speech in Seattle, Wyly said the ads were not effective in
publicizing his message about environmentally friendly power and
that he would not be making any more. The ads also apparently were
not effective in promoting Wyly's company, GreenMountain.com, which
sells renewable energy in states that have deregulated to allow
competition.
</P>
<P>
   DIVIDED LOYALTIES
</P>
<P>
   Florida Republicans are torn between Rep. Bill McCollum and
Education Commissioner Tom Gallagher, who are seeking the party's
U.S. Senate nomination. Gallagher is viewed ``as more moderate,''
while McCollum ``has been a champion of conservative causes,''
according to the Tampa Tribune. Former party Chairman Tom Slade
told the newspaper: ``The problem people are having with this race
is that it is the closest thing to a mathematical split I've ever
seen in how it's divided up Republican loyalists in Florida. ...
And they feel pretty passionate about it, so if you take sides,
you're going to tick off half the loyalists.''
</P>
<P>
   SO SHARP SOMEONE COULD GET CUT
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore says his campaign against George W. Bush presents voters
with ``as stark and clear and sharp a contrast as in any election
in American history.'' In a speech to party donors in Glen Cove,
N.Y., he criticized Bush's policies and said this period in time
could be described as a ``mountaintop moment.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time of continued economic growth, Gore said the country
must ask itself ``not only how do we keep this prosperity going,
but how do we make sure that nobody is left behind?''
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from Cox staff and wire reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
