<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON COMPUTERS AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spills Are Not a Problem For a Flexible Keyboard  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is generally considered a bad idea to clean your computer
keyboard by holding it under running water. But then, it is also a
bad idea to spill tabouleh salad between the keys, and thousands of
people do that every day.
</P>
<P>
   The Flexboard is a keyboard that you cannot only wash but also
hang out to dry. The flexible, rubber-covered keyboard resembles a
no-slip bathmat, and its sealed surface can withstand any number of
spills. You can clean it, disinfect it (with bleach, if you wish),
then simply roll it up and put it aside.
</P>
<P>
   The Flexboard has been available in Europe for a couple of years
_ about 50,000 units have been sold there _ and it is now being
distributed in the United States. The touch of the Flexboard is
closer to that of an electric typewriter than the average computer
keyboard, so typing on the Flexboard requires a little more elbow
grease.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were going to write a doctoral thesis, it's not the
keyboard I would necessarily use,'' said Ken Corsun, president of
Man &AMP; Machine (www.mmits.com), which is distributing the Flexboard
in the eastern United States.
</P>
<P>
   The basic model sells for $99; an industrial model, which can
withstand harsher chemicals, is priced at $229. Corsun said
potential customers would include restaurants, hospitals and places
with children, like schools and day care centers. ``Peanut butter
and jelly won't damage it,'' he said. ``And as far as I can tell,
they can't break it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Headlam &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Dreamcast Players, A Network of Their Own &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dreamcast devotees will have their own network this fall, and
Sega is offering some heady incentives, including cash and
Dreamcast consoles, to attract them.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Sega Enterprises announced the creation of Sega.com,
a company devoted to online interactive entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to developing new games, Sega.com will offer
SegaNet, a private network devoted to high-speed console gaming.
SegaNet is expected to give game fanatics plenty of the things they
crave, like online 3-D multiplayer games, industry news, instant
messaging, game downloads, tournaments and cheat codes.
</P>
<P>
   SegaNet will also function as an Internet service provider. The
network will also cater to the other interests of its target market
of young males, including tie-ins with movies, sports and music.
SegaNet is expected to cost $21.95 per month, which is comparable
to the monthly fees of other Internet providers, and users can sign
up for the service at www.sega.com.
</P>
<P>
   Although no incentives may be needed for some Dreamcast fans,
Sega.com is dangling an attractive rebate offer to those who sign
up for the SegaNet service, which is scheduled to start in early
September. New subscribers who own a Dreamcast machine will receive
a check for $200 from Sega and a keyboard. PC owners who sign up
will get a Dreamcast console and keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   The Dreamcast console, two million of which have been sold since
the fall, hooks into the user's television and has a built-in
modem. The company is making adapters that will support both
Ethernet and broadband connections.
</P>
<P>
   By creating its own network of people using the same hardware,
Sega.com hopes to quell the common complaints of online gamers,
mainly slow response time due to Internet traffic and hardware
incompatibility. That should allow users to bond, brag and blow one
another off the screen faster than ever. J.D. Biersdorfer &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Backflip Lets Web Users Store and Share Bookmarks &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new service from Backflip, based in San Francisco, offers Web
users who have obscure interests a chance to create Internet
directories that reflect their personal obsessions.
</P>
<P>
   Backflip is one of several companies that allow users to store
their Web browser bookmarks or favorites list on the company's Web
site (www.backflip.com) rather than on their _ or perhaps more to
the point, their employers' _ hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   With its recently introduced feature, called Show and Tell,
users can create folders of links on a specific topic and attach a
series of e-mail addresses. People on that list automatically
receive messages telling of any updates to the mini-directory.
Everyone invited to view the directory can contribute additional
links or post comments. ``Our users are building up a huge
collection of wisdom,'' said Tim Hickman, Backflip's chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Hickman said the free service would probably be of interest to
users like teachers, students and book clubs, but he said not all
the wisdom being gathered was of the ages. He said the service had
also been used to help plan weddings and to coordinate house
hunting between a couple and their real estate agent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ian Austen &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RECYCLING COMPUTERS Don't know what to do with the 1988
Macintosh Plus? You aren't alone. According to estimates from the
Clean Computer Campaign, a project of the Silicon Valley Toxics
Coalition, more than 12 million computers became obsolete last year
and only a fraction of those ended up in landfills. Three-quarters
are still sitting in basements and garages.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition also surveyed 21 major computer manufacturers to
determine their environmental policies for old products, including
policies on hazardous waste and on taking back used machines. At
the top of the environmental group's list were Apple and IBM, and
toward the bottom were Packard-Bell/NEC, Unisys (the only company
that filled out the coalition's questionnaire) and Hitachi. The
1999 environmental scorecard is at
www.svtc.org/cleancc/99reportcard.htm.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Pentax Digital Camera Has Built-In Computer  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Pentax VersaCam doesn't have a viewfinder and it doesn't run
on batteries. But it does have one feature not commonly found on
digital cameras: its very own personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   The VersaCam's built-in PC and its laptop-style slot for modems
or network cards allow it to take snapshots, convert them to the
common JPEG Internet file format and _ without any human
intervention or extra equipment _ post them on a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably doesn't fall into the digital camera
classification,'' said Jeffrey McAlister, the camera's program
manager at Pentax Technologies. ``It's more an Internet camera.''
</P>
<P>
   McAlister said the boxy camera, which must be plugged into an
electrical outlet, is designed to be used for tasks like security
surveillance. To frame the camera's view and focus its lens, users
must plug in a monitor. A cable connection to a PC is also required
to set the duration and frequency of the camera's photo sessions
and specify the Web site where its images are to be displayed.
</P>
<P>
   In its current form, the $899 VersaCam is palm size. McAlister
said the next model will probably have a viewfinder and be
battery-powered. If so, when combined with a wireless modem card,
it could create a new way for tourists to pester the folks back
home with their vacation photos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ian Austen &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Retracing an Ill-Fated Shackleton Expedition &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sir Ernest Shackleton's great renown as an explorer is not based
on what he discovered, but on what he survived. The captain of the
British ship Endurance set out in 1914 to become the first man to
cross the Antarctic continent. Four months after the Endurance was
caught and crushed in ice, Shackleton and five crewmen set out in a
22-foot boat, hoping to reach a whaling station on South Georgia
island, some 800 miles away. Remarkably, their attempt was
successful and the rest of Shackleton's crew was rescued 22 months
after their expedition began. PBS/Nova Online
(www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/shackleton) will follow three modern
mountaineers as they retrace Shackleton's steps across the glacier
peaks of South Georgia. Online dispatches will include audio from
the climbers themselves, digital maps and, weather permitting,
360-degree panoramas from the peaks.
</P>
<P>
   The site also features visits to other scenes of the Shackleton
voyage, illustrated by stunning still pictures and film captured by
Endurance photographer Frank Hurley. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Headlam &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A selection of events and sites on the Web. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Events &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
