<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8060 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-E-COMMERCE06-COX     04-05 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WORKER SHORTAGE THREATENS TECH BOOM, CLINTON WARNED
 &HT;    With E-COMMERCE-GATES. Moving in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While the longest economic expansion in U.S.
history remains healthy, a looming shortage of workers could
threaten the good times, President Clinton was warned Wednesday by
top economic thinkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This economy has gotten not just bigger, but also better,''
said Abby Joseph Cohen of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., one of Wall
Street's most influential analysts. But because this ``better''
economy requires more skilled workers, boosting education will be
``our greatest challenge in the coming years,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan agreed that today's
labor pool, the tightest in a generation, may not keep pace with
employers' needs. As result, the central bank has had no choice but
to nudge up interest rates to cool the economy and keep labor
supply and demand in balance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan warned that ``short of a repeal of the law of
supply and demand,'' if labor shortages develop they will ``almost
surely'' make wages rise faster than productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan and Cohen were among dozens of ``A list'' economists
and business leaders who joined Clinton in a day-long discussion on
how to keep the ``new economy'' growing.
</P>
<P>
   Even Microsoft Corp. Chairman Bill Gates couldn't resist the
invitation to the ornate East Room of the White House, despite his
battle with the Clinton administration. Just two days after the
company he co-founded was found guilty of anti-trust violations in
a case brought by the Justice Department, Gates sat next to the
president on a panel.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are living through ``an economic transformation as
profound as (the one) that led us into the Industrial Revolution,''
Clinton said in opening remarks.
</P>
<P>
   The president recalled that when he held his first economic
summit in Arkansas shortly after his 1992 election, ``unemployment
was high, interest rates were high, the deficit was exploding, the
debt had quadrupled, and even an apparent recovery was generating
no jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the U.S. economy has flourished amid an explosion of
new technologies that are boosting productivity and jobs. ``I
believe the computer and the Internet give us a chance to move more
people out of poverty more quickly than at any time in all of human
history,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, considered a leading optimist on Wall Street, agreed that
the ``new economy'' is generating opportunities for workers,
entrepreneurs and stock investors. ``For the past decade, we have
been enthusiastic about the outlook for U.S. prices,'' she said.
``And we remain so.''
</P>
<P>
   But amid the enthusiasm for a tech-driven economy, many speakers
said the nation's educational system must do a better job of
getting more people, regardless of economic background, into the
ranks of skilled workers.
</P>
<P>
   Another note of caution was sounded by International economist
C. Fred Bergsten, who said he was worried about ``the huge and
growing trade deficit.'' That imbalance, which hit a record high of
$267.6 billion last year, could trigger a panic in which foreign
investors flee U.S. markets and drive down the value of the dollar.
``A sharp decline in the dollar would push up interest rates and
push down the stock market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But while the economists weighed the possibilities for an end to
today's prosperity, they generally were upbeat. University of Texas
economics professor James K. Galbraith was perhaps the cheeriest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the nervousness of the markets, these are good
times,'' he said. ``They are very good times.'' With wise
leadership in Washington and cooperation from the Federal Reserve,
``we can continue to grow and prosper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
