<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8061 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-LIGHTNING-RODS-ART-2T     04-05 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHTNING-RODS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HIGH COST OF UNDERESTIMATING LIGHTNING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.M., Conn.) (ART ADV: Photos, NYT 29-30, have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LYNN ERMANN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Silvester, owner of Zeus Lightning Rod Inc. in Hopewell,
N.J., knows that proselytizing is hopeless: not until an electrical
storm gives homeowners firsthand experience _ when it blows their
chimneys apart, zaps their computer disk drives and fries their
air-conditioners _ do they think of buying a lightning rod. Until
then, they consider the chore as pressing as recaulking the
windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think about it after you've been hit,'' said Karen
Shapiro, who bought a lightning rod after her Georgian-style home
in Croton-on-Hudson was struck last summer. ``Something that
sounded like a cannon went off next to the house,'' she recalled,
and _ mid-e-mail _ her computer screen went black. Much of her and
her husband's other electronic equipment also went down, and the
laptop computer was destroyed. They bought a $3,000 lightning
protection system with lightning rods and surge suppressors for the
electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Matthew Martin of Sanbourne, N.Y., was finally moved
to act in July, when a bolt shot through his window and ignited the
sofa and rug in a fire that spread rapidly through the entire
house. ``Only the walls and the roof were left,'' said his fiancee,
Marisa Crane.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics confirm that lightning exacts a heavy toll on homes
across the country, particularly in the Northeast, which has the
most violent thunderstorms. The National Fire Protection
Association's most recent report, covering 1993 to 1997, said that
on average there are 6,150 lightning-related fires a year resulting
in 11 deaths and $129.7 million in residential property damage.
</P>
<P>
   Policyholders submitted 500,000 lightning-related claims to
State Farm Fire and Casualty Co. between 1995 and 1999. ``Among all
of our reported fire losses, lightning damage is the leading cause
and represents one of the most costly types of damage that State
Farm pays,'' said Phil Supple, a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Modernization and the advent of the wired home make lightning a
greater threat to property. ``One thing that has changed is the
proliferation of electronic equipment, which is sensitive to
lightning,'' said Richard Kithil, founder of the National Lightning
Safety Institute, a nonprofit organization in Louisville, Colo. In
1997, according to statistics cited by Kithil, lightning destroyed
101,000 laptop and desktop computers.
</P>
<P>
   Anything with microcircuitry, including digital television sets,
security systems and portable phones, is especially at risk.
Lightning, even when it hits many miles away, can travel through a
power line or phone line and deliver 20,000 to 30,000 amps, enough
to melt the delicate circuitry in a modem.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ed Frank, a licensed engineer with the home inspection
company InspectAmerica Engineering, in White Plains, said lightning
rods are rare in old and new houses alike. Similarly, Sylvester
said, ``only the high-end builders building custom houses recommend
them to customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony F. Abone, a real estate agent in Rome, N.Y., could not
remember the last time he saw one on a new house.
</P>
<P>
   One reason may be the cost: to outfit a 2,500-square-foot house
with a standard system, which includes several lightning rods
(often called air terminals), and a central surge suppressor at the
main fuse box, costs about $2,500, according to Underwriters
Laboratories, the safety certification organization.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Brinn of Folsom, N.J., said the cost kept her from
adding a lightning rod to her three-story Victorian home. ``You
don't want to put money out because it's not something you see;
it's like buying insurance,'' said Brinn, who installed a rod after
a co-worker's home was hit.
</P>
<P>
   Other homeowners could be put off by the perception that
lightning rods are crudely ineffective relics of another era. There
are also the rare naysayers. ( Kithil believes chances are slim
that a house will be hit dead-on and said surge suppressors are
more important.)
</P>
<P>
   But watchdog groups like the National Fire Protection
Association and Underwriters Laboratories believe that lightning
rods are essential; one proponent likens them to plumbing in terms
of lasting usefulness. Among the believers is Charles Moore, a
lightning expert and professor emeritus at Langmuir Laboratory for
Atmospheric Research at the New Mexico Institute of Mining and
Technology in Socorro, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Made of materials that conduct electricity easily, like copper
and aluminum, the rod acts as the path of least resistance. The
lightning charge passes to wire conductors alongside the house
(either inside or outside the walls), which are connected to ground
rods driven into the earth about 2 feet from the house.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs a lightning rod? Homes in large, empty fields are at
obvious risk. But so are houses in suburban areas that are not
surrounded by larger structures, which act as targets. (This
explains why buildings in cities may need only surge suppressors;
the Empire State Building, for example, acts as a lightning rod for
the buildings nearby.)
</P>
<P>
   One of the many myths about lightning is that flat-roofed houses
are safer from strikes than peak-roofed ones. Not true, said Moore.
The corners on any building are vulnerable, he explained, while the
edges of the roofs are the prime strike points, so the pitch of a
roof is inconsequential.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will trees protect homes from lightning. Trees do not
conduct electricity well, and if struck they can crack and fall
thunderously on the house. ``We felt the house shake,'' said Jill
Papenhausen of Haddonfield, N.J., whose house was struck a year
ago. ``A tree had gone through the picture window.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Koshofer, owner of Koshofer Lightning Protection Inc., in
Westchester, N.Y., recommends installing seven lightning rods on a
30-foot-by-80-foot home. ``The best way to protect your home if
you're surrounded by large trees is to put lightning rods in the
trees themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Hartnett, a project engineer with Underwriters
Laboratories, says lightning rods should be spaced no more than 20
feet apart.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to another myth, lightning rods, which typically
measure 10 to 12 inches, are not significantly taller than the roof
line and do not increase the chances of the house's being hit. They
only attract lightning that would otherwise be hitting the house.
</P>
<P>
   Surge suppressors for individual pieces of equipment are
recommended, Hartnett said, because lightning protection standards
are not designed ``to protect solid state or electronic equipment
within a structure, but to prevent fire or explosions within a
building.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that homeowners with electronic equipment may want to
add surge suppressors at points like the power strips or electrical
boxes that are installed to accommodate appliances and phone lines.
Surge suppressors are sold for under $10 (the UL stamp means the
suppressor complies with the most recent requirements) and are
recommended for sensitive equipment like the computer _ not the
toaster oven.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Suspicion over the effectiveness of the lightning rod is as old
as Ben Franklin's 1752 invention itself. It was sold door-to-door
to incredulous homeowners; there were no general standards in the
industry, and each salesman had a theory as to the best design and
installation. (The lightning rod salesman is lampooned in Herman
Melville's short story ``The Lightning-Rod Man.'') Today the only
real debate _ if you can call it that _ is over the relative merits
of different models. Franklin designed a pointy lightning rod, but
it was soon challenged by a blunt version introduced by the
British. Possibly for patriotic reasons, pointy has stayed the
American standard. Most shapes will do, Underwriters Laboratories
says.
</P>
<P>
   Installation is not typically a do-it-yourself job (the UL
installation requirements fill more than 45 pages). For example,
any metallic objects grounded near the house, including water
pipes, have to be accounted for to prevent lightning from being
directed toward the house and causing a fire.
</P>
<P>
   Underwriters Laboratories recommends that even if a home comes
with a lightning protection system, the new owner have it inspected
to ensure installation was done properly. Underwriters Laboratories
puts its stamp on systems and can verify whether it lists a local
installer; information from (847) 272-8800, extension 12578.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Proper lightning protection is a lasting investment, as Robert
McCracken and his wife, Sarah, can attest. In 1993, they returned
to their weekend home in Lyme, Conn., to find that lightning had
destroyed a hemlock tree 30 feet from the house before shooting
along the ground, hitting an irrigation pipe in the yard and
splitting it wide open. The bolt kept going, right into the house,
``frying everything there was to fry,'' McCracken said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple installed lightning rods and surge suppressors, and
they believe that in the seven years since, the home has survived
potentially nasty hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to say, it's working,'' McCracken said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
