<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FROGS-THEATER-REVIEW-     04-05 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FROGS-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FROGS, LIZARDS, ORBS AND SLINKYS': AMPHIBIOUS DISPLAY OF SILLINESS
AND STRIPES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review) 
(ART ADV: NYT Photo 25 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Giggles galore greet the gaggle of frogs that
populate the first of the nine captivating vignettes that are
sending the talented performers of the Imago Theater Mask Ensemble
hopping, slithering, jiggling, undulating, waddling, strutting and
rolling over the stage of the New Victory Theater these days.
</P>
<P>
   The impetus for all this varied movement, which also evokes
outright laughter, oohs and enthusiastic applause from children and
adults alike, is a gently humorous, charmingly creative show called
``Frogs, Lizards, Orbs and Slinkys,'' scheduled for five more
performances Friday through Sunday at the warm and welcoming
theater in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by music that ranges from the tinkling bells of Bali
to the scores of old westerns and never speaking a coherent word, a
supple, talented troupe of five from Portland, Ore., with a
well-developed taste for mischief is providing a novel diversion.
</P>
<P>
   Even the announcement of the intermission in this
one-hour-and-45-minute show created by Carol Triffle and Jerry
Mouawad is turned into clever entertainment, as three masked
performers in striped clown costumes with bulbous bellies or
bulbous behinds create a tottering tower of lettered cartons to
spell out their intent.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has ever enjoyed a Slinky toy is bound to respond to
the sight of three human-size versions curling across the stage,
looking at times likely to flop into the audience and then pulling
back, contracting like accordions and all the time appearing to
have very lifelike emotions, including a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   The long, long two-faced alligators with glowing eyes and the
enormous lizard that joins them are moody menaces, and a huge paper
bag that pulses with life, stands up, tips this way and that while
eventually emitting some strange yowls, turns out to have an inner
life.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the cleverest of the vignettes tells the tale of a
handlebar-mustached, bowlegged cowboy of the Old West who has a
screen for a face. And as the cowpoke's hand cranks the screen, the
story unspools through illustrations by the cartoonist George Smith
that track the cowboy's ordeal under a blazing desert sun to a
saloon and an encounter with a gunslinger.
</P>
<P>
   Besides all this, there are glow-in-the-dark strings that assume
all manner of beguiling shapes, an acrobatic larva, huge fabric
orbs that roll all over the place and a pack of penguins that play
a not-so-sporting but very funny game of musical chairs.
</P>
<P>
   With all its movement, ``Frogs, Lizards, Orbs and Slinkys''
turns out to be an exercise in audience relaxation and inventive
fun.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   FROGS, LIZARDS, ORBS AND SLINKYS
</P>
<P>
   Created by Carol Triffle and Jerry Mouawad; lighting and
production management by Jeff Forbes; original music by Katie
Griesar; cowboy illustrations by George Smith. Imago Theater
presented by the New 42nd Street Inc., by arrangement with Arthur
Shafman International Ltd. At the New Victory Theater, 209 West
42nd St., Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Graydon Kouri, Kimberly Dahle, Michael Vertlieb, Quinn
Casey and Ryan Custer.
</P>
<P>
   (JT) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
