<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, April 6 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-DIAMONDS (Undated) _ The value of diamonds, coupled with
the anonymity and portability of the stones _ millions of dollars
worth can be smuggled in a sock without triggering a metal detector
_ have made diamonds one of the most potent, and dangerous,
currencies of modern Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Eds.: This article was reported by Alan Cowell in Zambia and
Belgium, Ian Fisher in Congo, Blaine Harden in Angola and New York,
Norimitsu Onishi in Sierra Leone and Congo, and Rachel L. Swarns in
Botswana. It was written by Mr. Harden.
</P>
<P>
   Special Report: 5,200 words. The story will be divided into two
parts.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT1-4, and map.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The trial judge and the
litigants in the Microsoft antitrust trial agreed Wednesday to
conclude the case and impose a remedy on the software giant by
roughly the end of May, and the state attorneys general who have
pushed for the harshest remedies are coalescing around the view
that they will not ask the judge to break up the company, several
officials said. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BIOTECH-FOOD (Undated) _ Amid growing concerns over possible
risks posed by genetically modified crops, the National Academy of
Sciences took a new tack on biotech organisms, issuing a report
Wednesday calling for stronger regulation of the novel plants and
pointing to the potential for both food and environmental hazards.
While noting the potential for problems, the report stated that so
far there is no evidence that any genetically modified foods
currently on the market are unsafe to eat. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon and
Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LAPD-RECRUIT (New York) _ Faced with calls to increase the
diversity of its force and an expected exodus of officers, the New
York City Police Department embarked on an ambitious recruiting
drive over the past several years. The department learned Wednesday
that the drive had produced only 5,500 people interested in taking
the qualifying test this year, a 50 percent drop from the year
before. But, as New York struggles to lure its residents to its own
department, police recruiters from Los Angeles have come to the New
York Police Department's own hiring turf with promises of warmer
climes, higher starting salaries and openings at the academy as
soon as this summer. By C.J. Chivers.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT34.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-POLITICS (Washington) _ How a spending bill can act as
a political lever. (Editors: This story is exclusive and
competitive; details to come later. We expect to move this story at
9 p.m.) By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-DRUG (Paris) _ The 23 million Africans infected with the
AIDS virus should be given regular doses of a common and affordable
antibiotic, the World Health Organization and UNAids said
Wednesday, as a way to ward off fatal secondary infections. They
based their recommendation on encouraging preliminary studies, and
added that if the results are borne out, the impact could be
dramatic. Many people could add years to their lives and have
longer gaps between debilitating complications. But the antibiotic
is not a cure for the fatal disease. The drug, known as
trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole or as cotrimoxazole, is marketed as a
generic drug in the U.S. called Bactrim. It can cost as little as
$8 a year in Africa. Its use for prophylaxis there was endorsed for
the first time last week by AIDS experts who convened in Zimbabwe
to assess the new studies. The Clinton administration is spending
more than $100 million to fight AIDS in Africa and trying to raise
that to $325 million. It may spend millions of those dollars to
help distribute Bactrim in Africa, but has not yet calculated how
much to commit. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   HERMAN-CLEARED (Washington) _ The independent prosecutor who has
been investigating accusations of corruption involving Alexis
Herman, the Clinton administration's secretary of labor, said
Wednesday he has concluded that Herman did not break any laws and
should not be indicted. Herman, the fifth Cabinet officer in the
Clinton administration to come under the scrutiny of an independent
counsel, was accused by a former business partner of engaging in a
plan involving kickbacks and solicitation of illegal campaign
contributions to the Democratic Party. But Ralph Lancaster, who
conducted the the 23-month-long investigation, announced in a
one-sentence statement that he would not seek an indictment of
Herman. By David Johnston and Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT26.
</P>
