<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BUSCETTA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMMASO BUSCETTA, ITALIAN MOB LEADER AND WITNESS , DEAD AT 71 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Tommaso Buscetta, the first important Italian mob leader
to break the Mafia's oath of silence and who gave testimony that
helped convict hundreds of Mafia leaders in Italy and the United
States, died of cancer on Sunday, his Italian lawyer, Luigi
Liggotti said. He was 71 and living at an undisclosed location
under the American witness protection program.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's best known ``pentito'' _ the Italian word for a penitent
is now used to describe Mafia informers _ Buscetta was a ruthless
pioneer in the Sicilian Mafia's turn to drug trafficking. His
decision in 1984 to cooperate with Italian and later U.S.
prosecutors changed the course of one of the darker chapters of
modern Italian history.
</P>
<P>
   Buscetta's testimony about heroin smuggling in the ``pizza
connection'' case in the mid-1980s won him American citizenship, a
place in the U.S. witness protection program and the gratitude of
Italian and American law enforcement. Notoriety gave him a public
forum for disingenuous expiation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, I have seen our organization change from
within,'' Buscetta, speaking behind a screen, told U.S. senators at
a 1988 hearing on organized crime. ``I have seen money, drugs and
greed corrupt and destroy the Cosa Nostra code of honor and loyalty
to the families.''
</P>
<P>
   His career as a mobster-turned-state witness spanned the highs
and lows of Italy's long, bloody battle against organized crime.
The government's reliance on ``pentiti'' culminated with the 1993
arrest of Salvatore Riina, whom Buscetta identified as the head of
the Sicilian mafia. But it reached its nadir two years later. In
August 1995, Buscetta, back under Italian government protection to
testify against former prime minister Giulio Andreotti, was
photographed by a journalist on a Mediterranean cruise ship,
sunbathing and mamboing in the ship's ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   Andreotti was found innocent of colluding with Mafia chieftains
in two trials last year, partly because the testimony of Buscetta,
who mentioned Andreotti's reputed intimacy with mob leaders eight
years after he joined the witness protection program, was hearsay.
</P>
<P>
   Andreotti, seven times prime minister and one of Italy's most
powerful postwar politicians, noted Buscetta's passing with his
customary dryness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased the state helped him try all the cures,'' he
told reporters on Tuesday. ``It would have been very serious if his
illness had stopped him from attending my trials.''
</P>
<P>
   Buscetta, the son of a Sicilian glazier, began his criminal
career in the black market after World War II, moved to Argentina
in 1948, then back to Sicily to join the Mafia in 1957. He fled mob
turf wars and local law enforcement in 1962 and was on the lam for
10 years until he was arrested in Rio de Janeiro on international
drug trafficking charges and extradited to Sicily, where he served
eight years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   His release coincided with a fierce power struggle between his
clan and Riina's mob, a bloodbath that cost him many relatives,
including two sons. He again fled to Brazil, and was arrested there
in 1983. Learning that he was about to be extradited back to Italy,
Buscetta made an unsuccessful suicide attempt by swallowing
strychnine. In 1984, three days after his plane landed in Rome, he
told a top mafia prosecutor, Giovanni Falcone, words that quickly
became famous: ``I am a mafioso.'' He began talking and did not
stop for 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   Buscetta, a self-described ``man of honor'' in the Mafia
hierarchy, didn't just provide investigators with names and dates.
He painted an intimate portrait of the means and mores of the Cosa
Nostra, explaining the sometimes complex, often feudal rituals,
codes, and castes below the surface of organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Falcone and his fellow prosecutor Paolo
Borsellino, won the first ``maxi-trials'' in Sicily, putting
hundreds of mobsters behind bars. That victory unleashed a decade
of unbridled violence as the mafia brazenly challenged the state,
killing judges, prosecutors and local officials. Falcone and
Borsellino, two of Italy's most respected magistrates, were
assassinated within two months of each other in 1992. In 1996,
Riina was convicted of conspiring in the murder of Borsellino and
five bodyguards and the next year he was convicted of ordering the
assassination of Falcone, his wife and three bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   Buscetta, who had three wives in three different countries and
seven children, was so famous in Italy that he earned a certain
cachet. In 1994, the design house Dolce e Gabbana brought out a
men's spring collection inspired by the mobster, featuring black
pinstripe suits, shiny pointed shoes and black sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   When his death became known on Tuesday, Buscetta was mourned by
Italian prosecutors and government officials as a hero of the war
against organized crime _ jarring accolades for a man who once
described the ``liberating'' feeling that comes with pulling the
trigger and watching an opponent fall.
</P>
<P>
   On the meaner streets of Palermo, however, the word ``buscetta''
has become a slang insult in the same the way ``sbirro'' is a
pejorative term for a cop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a pentito,'' Buscetta once told Enzo Biagi, one of
Italy's best known journalists. ``I am a man who had to defend
himself and to do so, had to tell the truth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8071 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-FAKE-GARDENS-ART-NYT &LR;      04-05 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAKE-GARDENS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVANT GARDEN: JUST DON'T ADD WATER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photos 6,7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What is reality?
</P>
<P>
   For the $6.2 billion artificial, dried and preserved flower and
foliage industry, it is not a metaphysical question or a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Business is blooming: a 35 percent increase over the last five
years for the domestic wholesale ``permanent botanicals'' industry,
as it calls itself, according to a 1999 study commissioned by the
American Flower Importers Association, a trade association, and the
Dallas Market Center, the trade capital of permanent floral
products.
</P>
<P>
   And resistance is wilting. A mainstay of hotels, offices, malls
and atriums, they don't require watering or spraying. They don't
produce pests or provoke allergic reactions (and subsequent
lawsuits). They resist the effects of chemicals like pool chlorine.
And because they stay pretty and ``live'' forever, permanent
botanicals are making inroads into home decor.
</P>
<P>
   Now permanent floral products are finding themselves at home
where they might least be expected: outdoors in the garden. For a
family living in a ground-floor duplex apartment on the Upper East
Side in New York, the situation was too real: a charming back court
with a view of the Cottages, a row of 1930s stores topped by
apartments overlooking an interior garden, that became a dark,
bricked-in well last year when the neighboring site was developed
as a 76-story luxury condominium.
</P>
<P>
   Not willing to lose the amenity of their garden, the homeowners
(a real estate broker and her husband, a lawyer) contacted
Christian Duvernois, a New York landscape designer. Duvernois, who
created an artificial garden for Hermes' East 57th Street boutique
in 1996, suggested for the new garden a folly, based as it would
have been in the 18th century, on the amusements of fakery.
</P>
<P>
   Everything in the wooded, informal grove, bowered by white birch
and trellised and vined with ivory cameo-size roses, canopied by
white and purple wisteria and tendriled by tender shoots of ivy, is
synthetic: several hundred plastic and polyester pieces and $20,000
worth of state-of-the-art sylvan parts. Nymphs will need knee-pads.
A gardener comes once a month to wash it, and ``plump it,'' as
Duvernois said. Delicate items, like hydrangea flowers, can be
popped off their stems and washed in the sink, inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no choice,'' said the homeowner, who asked not to be
identified. ``It was a beautiful, open garden before, then it was a
blank wall, now it's more beautiful.'' She explained: ``I'm sure
someone who wanted to be a slave to a garden could put in real
things, but I knew I couldn't keep it going. We spent a ton of
money putting ivy up, and that completely died, and we put in
bamboo, and then it died, and evergreens, and they died. I have no
problem with its being fake.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit to the garden, Duvernois, the designer,
straightened a yew with a firm yank, bent an ivy shoot to point it
back toward the wall it was intended to train on, then sat down to
talk at a wrought-iron garden table. A watering can by the gated
door to the kitchen had been put there ``for effect,'' he said. Two
plastic owls were being installed, near the second story window
boxes to discourage pigeons, which were a problem at Hermes.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way, the trellis is plastic too,'' he said, gesturing
toward the 18-foot-high gazebo facade that towered above him and
was hand-twined with rose vines and wisteria twigs. Duvernois
created the architectural element, flanked by 15-foot white
birches, as a proscenium seen from the house, to break the
bluntness of the new cement-block wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we did the garden, a little overgrown, is exactly the
way they were making follies in the 18th century,'' he said,
explaining that the expectation for plastic plantings is that they
will be artificially prim. Duvernois' garden looks like a high
hairdo after a hard bounce.
</P>
<P>
   There were no problems in making it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very easy to deal with plastic plants, actually,'' he
said. ``If you need more, you just put one more in.'' He
demonstrated by jamming a hydrangea stem down through a leafy
tangle into its potting medium, a trash-bagged loose polystyrene
that Duvernois covers with real wood chips: a simulation trick.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can play with this garden,'' he said, beheading a rose
with a snap. ``It's really like a toy.'' The homeowners intend to
honor the seasons, more or less, by removing the flowers in the
fall and having them reappear in the spring, as plastic buds. The
garden is sheltered from harsh weather; wear and tear, and
replacement, is more typically a consequence of people touching the
plants to see if they are real.
</P>
<P>
   To realize the garden, Duvernois worked with Permanent Foliage,
a floral import and design company on West 26th Street (on the edge
of the flower district, though not by fiat), whose clients include
decorators like M Group, corporations like Sony and hospitality
groups like Marriott. They have shipped palms to Saudi Arabia,
orchids to Hawaii.The American Museum of Natural History in New
York bought materials from it in 1998 when they moved in their
annual live-butterfly exhibition, to help sell the butterflies on
their new home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The butterflies wouldn't go to the real trees,'' said Lawton
Toodle, a partner with Permanent Foliage. ``The butterflies liked
our stuff better.'' John Walker, a partner and Permanent Foliage's
principal designer, said, ``The quality of the materials themselves
is phenomenal now.'' Walker, under the direction of Duvernois,
worked with three assistants for three weeks to complete the Upper
East Side garden. Thanks to newer technologies like
photographic-transfers, improved materials like polyesters and
foams and closer attention to fresh-flower trends, artificial
foliage and flowers are more realistic than they were even five
years ago. Many large wholesalers and designers like Supersilk in
Salt Lake City, which won last year's Fame award (the Oscar of
artificial plants), have showrooms in High Point, N.C., capital of
the domestic home furnishings industry, whose spring trade market
opens Thursday. Furniture retailers like Haverty, with 100 stores,
sell artificial flower and foliage arrangements as decorating
accessories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The permanent botanicals industry is a fashion business,''
said Beatrice Chang, executive vice president of Supersilk. ``It
follows fashion in home decor.'' The last big hullabaloo, now
dying: sunflowers, courtesy of the interest in Arts and Crafts.
This year's excitement: the feng shui look. ``Lots of reeds and
grasses,'' Chang said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(JT) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
