<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AIDA-HEADLEY-ART-NYT &LR;      04-05 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDA-HEADLEY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE VERGE OF FAME, AND FEELING PLAIN LUCKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attn: Trinidad, Canada, Ill., Ind.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT16 is
being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Glasses propped on her close-cropped hair, a scarf
tossed around her regal neck, Heather Headley casually swivels on a
stool as she rehearses Elton John's ``Your Song'' in preparation
for a charity benefit in his honor. With the ease of a seasoned
rock singer, Headley holds the room rapt as she puts a fresh spin
on the familiar refrain, ``I hope you don't mind, I hope you don't
mind. ...''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, at the benefit for two AIDS charities at
Broadway's New Amsterdam Theater, she brings down the house. One
would think Headley had been doing this kind of thing forever. But
she is only 25. It wasn't so long ago that she was a schoolgirl
walking barefoot on the shores of her native Trinidad, singing in
her church choir and dreaming of becoming the next Whitney Houston.
It was only three years ago that she won her first major role, as a
member of the ensemble and an understudy in the Toronto tryout of
``Ragtime'' _ a production she left to play Nala in the Broadway
cast of ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 23, she opened to rave reviews in the title role of
Disney's Broadway show ``Aida.'' No more waiting in the wings for
the lead to get sick. No more lioness mask. Headley is now front
and center, singing to the rafters of the Palace Theater in the
Elton John version of Verdi's tragic romance about a Nubian
princess and her Egyptian captor.
</P>
<P>
   ``She not only has what is called It _ that ineffable, sensual
glow _ but also a voice of stunning emotional variety and
conviction,'' Ben Brantley wrote in The New York Times. The praise
for Headley, echoed by other critics, is particularly striking
given the generally poor, even harsh, reviews of ``Aida'' itself,
which has been characterized as style without substance. Headley
alone, some critics seem to be saying, is worth the price of
admission.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the life of the show proves to be, ``Aida'' is a major
moment for this young actress, proving that she can not only carry
a show but also lift it up. It has established her as a force to
watch. ``I felt from the beginning that when a New York audience
saw her, it would be like an audience in the '60s discovering
Barbra Streisand for the first time,'' said Robert Falls, the
director.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a powerful voice, Headley has an arresting poise
and intensity. When she appeared in the Encores concert production
of ``Do Re Mi'' last May, Brantley of The Times described her as
``a Modigliani-faced beauty,'' adding, ``She finds hypnotic
expressiveness in the simplest gestures, and you can't take your
eyes off her.''
</P>
<P>
   Falls repeatedly reminds Headley to ``keep it simple'' in
performances, in part it seems because she radiates so much feeling
without really trying that the slightest additional inflection or
gesture can be distracting.
</P>
<P>
   But as is often the case this early in a career, Headley seems
untouched by the fame that may be in store. She talked about her
sense of being lucky. Every night before a show begins, she walks
to the center of the curtain and prays, ``not calling all the gods,
just the main one,'' she said. By now, she said, the rest of the
cast and crew know to leave her alone at such moments.
</P>
<P>
   Headley said she needs a lot of solitude these days to
concentrate her energy and attention on this role. (She is also
working on her first solo album for Hollywood Records.) Friends
know not to call before 5 p.m. because Headley is resting her
voice. She does not go out after the show; she heads home to her
apartment in Washington Heights. ``My social life is kaput for
now,'' she said. ```Aida' is the boyfriend right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem staying at home,'' she continued. ``The way
I look at it, you're paying me to do something I do in the shower.
I'm honored and blessed that at 25 I have this role. Not in a proud
way, but in an awed, grateful way.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Pascal, who plays Radames, the conquering Egyptian captain,
said that this ascetic lifestyle was typical of Headley. ``She's a
good girl in the truest sense of the word,'' Pascal said. ``Heather
doesn't curse, Heather doesn't drink, Heather doesn't smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Headley grew up as the daughter of church pastors. A skinny
little girl with a big voice, she sang in church and, without any
formal voice training, tried to imitate Houston, Anita Baker and
CeCe Winans. ``I was just screaming,'' Headley said. ``the higher
the note, the louder you are, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   When she was 15, her parents moved the family _ she has one
younger brother _ from Trinidad to a new pulpit in Fort Wayne, Ind.
There, as a member of her school's show choir, Headley won several
awards for her solo performances, trophies that she said her mother
still refuses to put in the basement. In junior high school she
played Fanny Brice in ``Funny Girl.'' Deciding she wanted to go to
Northwestern University, Headley said she had to prepare four
arias, three of them in different languages. She listened to opera
recordings of stars like Kathleen Battle and tried to mold her
voice to sound like them.
</P>
<P>
   In her sophomore year Headley landed a leading role in a
production of ``Dreamgirls'' at the Marriott Lincolnshire Theater
in the suburbs just north of Chicago. Already working her way
through school as part of a scholarship, Headley began living a
double life, rising at dawn to do her schoolwork, attending class
until late afternoon, then heading to the theater and returning to
campus by midnight. The work paid off: she met her agent, Janet
Louer, who is now her manager.
</P>
<P>
   Next came an audition for ``Ragtime.'' She sang ``Out Here on My
Own'' from the movie ``Fame.'' Garth H. Drabinsky, then the
creative director of the production company Livent, along with the
lyricist, Lynn Ahrens, and the composer, Stephen Flaherty, came to
hear her sing. ``We saw her and said, `Who is this beautiful
creature?''' Ahrens recalled, ``and wooed her away from college.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining ``Ragtime'' in Toronto meant leaving Northwestern.
``Leaving school was a hard decision for me,'' Headley said. She
said she consulted each of her professors about the move. ``I was
crying as each one told me to go,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now Headley believes it was the right choice. Working in Toronto
with seasoned performers like Audra McDonald, Brian Stokes Mitchell
and Marin Mazzie taught her the basics of being part of a
professional production. ``It was the best training I could ever
have,'' she said. ``How to be part of an ensemble, how to do my
makeup, how to dress in 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was by myself in a new country, and I couldn't call Mommy
for any and everything,'' she continued. ``I just grew up.''
</P>
<P>
   Next came the role of Nala in ``The Lion King.'' Then Disney
chose her for ``Aida.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We auditioned lots of people,'' said Peter Schneider, the
chairman of Walt Disney Studios and a producer of ``Aida.'' ``And
when she sang it and when she acted it, you felt the chemistry in
the room. You felt the star power.''
</P>
<P>
   Schneider said that Headley had come a long way from the days
when a young girl made her first trip to New York to sing in ``The
Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   Headley said, on a visit to Trinidad in January, she was struck
by how much her life had changed. ``I walked places I had walked
barefoot or to piano lessons,'' she said. ``Back then, I didn't
know any of this was going to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
