<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8080 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-E-COMMERCE-GATES06-CO     04-05 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-GATES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, GATES ALL SMILES AT WHITE HOUSE VISIT
 &HT;    With E-COMMERCE. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton turned to Microsoft Chairman Bill
Gates on Wednesday and asked him how the nation could encourage
more ``young billionaires'' like him to take a stand.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton was not talking about the Gates who has dug in his
heels in a legal battle with the federal government. Instead, he
was talking about the Gates who co-founded a charity that has
quickly vaulted to the top of the world's philanthropy charts.
</P>
<P>
   The setting was the East Room of the White House, where Clinton
had convened a day-long conference on the challenges and
opportunities posed by the ``new economy'' of the information age.
</P>
<P>
   As both men listened to a speech by Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan, Clinton gave Gates several friendly pats on the
back.
</P>
<P>
   Then Gates, seated to the president's immediate right, joined an
afternoon panel on ``Closing the Global Divide'' along with other
luminaries such as World Bank President James Wolfensohn.
</P>
<P>
   In a question-and-answer session after the panel discussion,
Clinton cited philanthropists from an earlier era such as Andrew
Carnegie, J.P. Morgan, and John D. Rockefeller, who, he said, ``had
built monuments to our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have all these young people who have made a lot of
money,'' Clinton went on. Turning to the world's richest man, he
asked, ``what we can to encourage more philanthropy from this
group?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good question,'' Gates replied. I think about it a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   But he did not have any ready answers, other than allowing that
``as I learn more (about giving), I get more excited myself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Philanthropy, if it is done the right way, can have a
tremendous impact,'' said Gates, whose Bill and Melinda Gates
Foundation focuses on ways to help to improve peoples' lives
through health and learning. ``It's a full-time job. I need to
think about that some more.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no apparent exchange between the two men about
Monday's ruling by a federal judge in a case brought by Clinton's
Justice Department that Microsoft had violated antitrust laws,
harming consumers by stifling competition and innovation.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Clinton left Gates to chat amiably with another attendee,
Treasury Secretary Larry Summers.
</P>
<P>
   He told the cabinet officer that ``unlike United Nations, who
have to defend themselves whatever they do in the developing world,
whether it works or not, we are free to spend $50 million and admit
we made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   In his formal remarks to the panel, Gates said the ``technology
revolution has been one of the greatest job creation engines ever''
and will lead to ``breakthroughs that will allow computers to
listen, to learn, to be in a tablet form connected up to a wireless
network that you just carry around with you.''
</P>
<P>
   When the session ended, Gates and his small traveling party were
escorted to a private White House elevator, the first step on a
trip back to Seattle on a Microsoft jet.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
