<P>
   UNDATED _ Olives _ they're not just Thanksgiving finger puppets
anymore. While Heinz and Vlasic are reporting flat pickle sales,
olives are taking up more and more shelf space in supermarkets. And
it's not just those ``awful things from California,'' in the words
of uber-chef Stephan Pyles, but exotica from Tunisia and Provence
and Sicily. Oodles and oodles of olives. ``Olives are going through
a renaissance,'' says Marino Garbis, general manager of West Coast
Products, an olive-curing operation in Orland, Calif., in business
since 1937. Garbis sees consumers being more adventuresome in their
olive options. By BEVERLY BUNDY. Story has moved in ``d'' food and
dining category. (Accompanied by OLIVES-PRIMER.) &QL; 
