<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-OZONE-DEPLETE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECOVERY OF OZONE MAY BE DELAYED BY COLDER TEMPERATURES OVER ARCTIC
REGION 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM K. STEVENS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unusual cold and a sharp loss of ozone in the Arctic
stratosphere over the winter just past have heightened concern that
changes in global climate may delay recovery of the earth's
partially depleted ozone layer, scientists said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The stratospheric ozone layer, composed of a form of oxygen that
blocks some kinds of solar radiation, protects all forms of life
from the harmful effects of the sun's ultraviolet rays, which can
cause skin cancer, cataracts and damage to the immune system and
can harm natural ecosystems. If there were no ozone shield, plants
and animals could not exist on land.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, it was found that synthetic chemicals used in
refrigerants, plastic foams and aerosol propellants were destroying
the ozone layer. Production of the most destructive chemicals,
mainly chlorofluorocarbons, was halted or curtailed in the early
and mid-1990s by international agreement. Scientists say the
atmospheric concentrations of such chemicals have peaked and are
slowly decreasing.
</P>
<P>
   The ozone layer is expected to recover eventually, possibly by
the mid-21st century. But computer simulations of the atmosphere
have suggested that colder temperatures in the stratosphere, about
11 miles high, could increase the rate of ozone depletion in the
meantime, delaying recovery by a decade or two.
</P>
<P>
   Measurements taken by instruments carried aloft by aircraft and
balloons over the past winter have found that temperatures in the
crucial layer of the Arctic atmosphere were, indeed, among the
coldest on record, and that ozone losses of more than 60 percent
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   In three of the last five winters, stratospheric temperatures in
the Arctic were colder and more persistent, and covered a wider
area, than at any other time in the last 20 years, said Dr. Ross
Salawitch, an ozone researcher at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in
Pasadena, Calif. He was one of hundreds of U.S. and European
scientists from many institutions involved in the recent Arctic
survey.
</P>
<P>
   The survey's results were announced Wednesday by the Pasadena
laboratory and the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's
Goddard Space Flight Center in Greenbelt, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Most Arctic winters in the last decade brought unusually low
ozone coincident with an unusually cold stratosphere, according to
the World Meteorological Organization.
</P>
<P>
   When the Arctic region cools, ``that's bad news for the ozone,''
Salawitch said, adding that the new data has ``really solidified
our view'' that the ozone layer is sensitive not only to
ozone-destroying chemicals but also to temperature.
</P>
<P>
   He said the conditions observed this winter also ``heighten our
concern regarding possible couplings between climate change and
stratospheric ozone depletion.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozone depletion and global climate change are essentially
separate phenomena, but they can interact in some ways. For
example, emissions of heat-trapping industrial gases like carbon
dioxide, which warm the lower atmosphere, have the opposite effect
in the stratosphere: they cool it. Indeed, a general stratospheric
cooling has been observed in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Chlorofluorocarbons and other industrial chemicals cause large,
rapid ozone losses in the polar regions when the stratospheric
temperature reaches 105 to 110 degrees below zero Fahrenheit. The
critical threshold is reached only in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Over Antarctica, the coldest place on earth, severe ozone
depletion takes place every winter. In the Arctic, some winters are
too warm for a major depletion. But this year the temperature
stayed well below the threshold for long periods, sometimes
reaching 120 degrees below zero.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the long-term pattern could be changing toward a colder
Arctic stratosphere is an open question for researchers, Salawitch
said. One complicating factor, he added, is that the three plunges
to very cold temperatures in recent winters are much bigger than
the stratospheric cooling produced by emissions of gases like
carbon dioxide that warm the lower atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   It may be, Salawitch said, that some dynamic machinations within
the atmosphere are enhancing a stratospheric cooling by carbon
dioxide. Although computer models have suggested that such a
cooling might delay the recovery of the ozone layer by 10 to 20
years, scientists are far from pinning down the possible
relationship between climate change and ozone depletion, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While colder temperatures make the polar regions most
susceptible to ozone loss, midlatitude regions have experienced it
as well, although more gradually and to a much lesser extent.
</P>
<P>
   In a broad assessment of the ozone problem in 1998, the World
Meteorological Organization reported that the problem had eased in
the midlatitude regions, with the rate of depletion slowing.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that the peak of ozone depletion globally should
come within the next two decades, but that it would probably not be
discerned for some time after that.
</P>
<P>
   (rk)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
