<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8089 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-CHAMBER-WEBBE-(TR     04-05 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CHAMBER-WEBBE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SURFER DELIVERS THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  By MICHEL MARRIOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mark Chamber's introduction to digital technology
came when he was an inquisitive teen-ager growing up in a rural
area of Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   One day in 1985, a friend brought home a strange contraption
after visiting his father, a computer programmer who lived in
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was some kind of a computer, the first one I had ever
seen,'' Chambers recalled. The modest machine was made by the
British Broadcasting Corp. Similar to a Commodore 64, it had to be
connected to the family television set to work.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers, who was 13 at the time and had already impressed his
teachers with his talent for mathematics, raided a stash of
computer manuals belonging to his friend's father. In weeks,
Chambers was writing his first computer programs. Within a month he
had developed a simple game that the two boys could play on the PC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing software became my passion, and it still is,''
Chambers said. ``I started thinking of myself as a software
developer.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, at 27, Chambers has more than home-made video games to
his credit. He has created an Internet tool that is the culmination
of his self-taught mastery of software.
</P>
<P>
   Called Webbe, the software device appears on a computer screen
much like a virtual remote control. Webbe controls, integrates and
streamlines Internet functions like chat, e-mail, searches, news
alerts and buddy lists _ functions traditionally spread among
separate programs, browers and Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Webbe manages the functions from a single place on the screen.
Chambers says it makes easy and intuitive what was often difficult
and confusing. He plans to license Webbe's technology to e-commerce
sites, which will be able to use it to stay in contact with
customers and manage e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier versions of Webbe started attracting users last year. To
Chambers' surprise, a large percentage of Webbe's 100,000 users are
in Italy. Even though the program is in English, Chambers said, it
appears to be popular in Italy because there are many small
Internet service providers and Webbe, being Web-based, can work
with all of them.
</P>
<P>
   A corporate version of the software, used mainly for instant
messaging, also has been sold to offices of Merrill Lynch and
members of the U.S. Navy Seals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrific tool,'' said Tom Donovan, an administrative
manager at Merrill Lynch in New York. ``It is used from senior vice
presidents down to support staff.''
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration for Webbe, Chambers said, was simple. Like many
users, he found himself increasingly frustrated by the
ever-widening gap between the Internet's bright promise and its
often dull delivery. He was fed up with computer screens filled
with useless information, mind-numbing redundancies and virtual
dead ends in his searches for meaningful data.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just found it harder and harder to get the right information
at the right time,'' he said. Three years ago, he sat down in his
parents' home on Long Island, N.Y., and started writing lines of
code. In a few months, Chambers created Webbe, which not only
greatly simplified his Internet searches, he said, but helped him
to communicate more easily with friends and family online.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Chambers and his small company, Webbe Inc., of Long
Island, release Webbe 3.0, packed with new functions like on-line
gaming and drag-and-drop file transfer capabilities. (It is
available for free downloading at www.webbe.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Internet analysts are watching what some call the ``desktop
attention'' category that Webbe wants to occupy. Several years ago,
PointCast Network, one of the so-called push technologies, enjoyed
a surge of popularity and then suddenly fell out of favor.
</P>
<P>
   PointCast Inc. and Launchpad Technologies, major developers of
Internet and e-commerce tools, have combined to form Entrypoint
Inc. and recently produced EntryPoint 2.0, which does tasks similar
to Webbe's, although it lacks Webbe's instant-messaging features.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 2 million downloads of EntryPoint 2.0 since it
was released in the fall of 1999. But Chambers is undaunted. ``It
doesn't have robust communications,'' he said of EntryPoint.
</P>
<P>
   Being undaunted by challenge, even failure, has been a
consistent component of Chambers' personality, friends and
colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, after he completed high school in Jamaica, where he
took some computer courses in a class of 50 students with four
aging computers, his parents decided to move the family to the
United States and settled in Hempstead on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Suffering from culture shock, Chambers, a middle child, said he
decided not to go to college. (All of his six brothers and sisters
graduated from U.S. colleges and universities.) Instead, he
concentrated on developing software.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin Optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew about Gates and Jobs and I was just trying to outdo
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His parents helped him get a job running the computers for a
construction company in Brooklyn. On the job, he got an education
in what he called practical computing.
</P>
<P>
   (End Optional Trim)
</P>
<P>
   By late 1993, while still living at home, he began working to
create a touch-screen-based computer terminal called Movie Master
that could give video store customers instant access to
information, including short, on-screen video previews, on
videotapes available for rental. But the prototype failed to
interest the video rental industry.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin Optional Trim)
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just so disappointed,'' Chambers said. ``I had this
great product but couldn't get it to the people who needed to see
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He put Movie Master on the shelf and went to work on something
more modest, something he said he felt he could present to the
buying public without a lot of outside help.
</P>
<P>
   (End Optional Trim)
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 he introduced Power Quotes, a screen saver with
inspirational quotations, including the words of John F. Kennedy
and Martin Luther King Jr. The quotes would appear on the screen
along with music and images.
</P>
<P>
   The screen saver sold well, giving Chambers some breathing room
to start working on what would become Webbe, which was completed in
1998. The first person he shared it with was Rawle Howard, the
cousin of a friend.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin Optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Man, this is the greatest thing I've ever
seen,''' recalled Howard. ```How can I get one?''' He said he had
no idea that Chambers had created the software. Three or four weeks
later, Howard, now the vice president of operations for Webbe,
received the first copy of the program.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Howard said he should not have been surprised. He
described Chambers as driven and said that he constantly sits in
front of his computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I'll come by and say let's go exercising, let's go
lift weights,'' Howard said. ``And he'll say: `No. The only thing
I'm lifting today is a mouse.'''
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   In the next few months, Chambers said he hopes to lift the
profile of his fledgling company, and at the same time lift the
spirits of other living-room tinkerers who dare to do more than
just dream about success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreaming is only important,'' Chambers said, ``when you go and
act on it.''
</P>
<P>
   (mg)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
