<HEADER>
A8094 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MICROSOFT06-COX     04-05 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT PUNISHMENT HEARING SET FOR NEXT MONTH
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal judge who ruled Monday that Microsoft
Corp. has broken the nation's antitrust laws set May 24 to hear how
the company and the government think it should be punished.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting Wednesday with lawyers for both sides in the
landmark case, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson relented
from an earlier stand, allowing the Justice Department and the 19
states which joined forces two years ago to file their proposed
remedies separately if they could not agree on a common approach.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Jackson met with the attorneys, Microsoft Chairman Bill
Gates drove by the federal courthouse on the way to the U.S.
Capitol for separate meetings with Republican and Democratic
lawmakers. Gates spent much of the afternoon with President Clinton
attending a White House economic conference.
</P>
<P>
   Gates blames hard-liners among the attorneys general for the
failure of settlement talks in which he took a highly active part.
The collapse prompted Jackson to quickly issue his scathing
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson placed the historic case, with the full approval of the
litigants, on a fast legal track. The Justice Department and the
states have until April 28 to file their proposed remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is to reply by May 10, and the government is issue its
answer to Microsoft's views by May 17.
</P>
<P>
   That exchange will set the stage for the final courtroom drama
before the case is appealed, possibly directly to the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft could still seek a lengthier proceeding if the
government proposes ``something that was so radically different
than anything that somebody had talked about before,'' said David
Boies, the government's chief trial lawyer, according to a
transcript of the discussion in Jackson's chambers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My transcendent objective is to get this thing before an
appellate tribunal _ one or another _ as quickly as possible
because I don't want to disrupt the economy or waste any more of
yours or my time on a remedy if it's going to come back here,''
Jackson said at an earlier meeting on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1974 law, the high tribunal can decide to hear a direct
appeal from the trial court decision in major antitrust cases
brought by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
