u f BC-DISABILITY-WORKPLACE-     04-05 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABILITY-WORKPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING HER WORKSTATION IN LIFE
</HEADLINE>
  (My Job column) 
 
 By SUSAN BARTERS With ROBERT WADDELL   
Ms. Barters is a customer service representative at Unum Provident,
a disability and life insurance company in New York. 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I live with multiple sclerosis, so when I roll into
work, my fellow employees sometimes have to tell me to slow down or
yell for people nearby to watch their toes. They raised my
workstation here, so that I can roll right in. I was given a
21-inch computer, and my printer is at my desk.
</P>
<P>
   And everyone is jealous.
</P>
<P>
   There are constant jokes. They make fun of me in the office, but
no one has ever crossed the line. We all work hard, and joking is
one way of getting through the day. They tell me I've got to get a
horn on that wheelchair and call me a daredevil menace. The horn
that I do have right now is kind of wimpy. I need something that
goes aoogaw! I've got a big mouth, and that works better.
</P>
<P>
   The business that I'm in is disability insurance. I've never had
anything really negative happen to me. I don't show fear or that
I'm different in any way. I just happen to be sitting. It comes
across to my boss, my co-workers and clients that I don't take guff
from anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of our work at Unum Provident is that you're injured,
then you get back to work. I'm on the phone most of the time trying
to help people with billing or with changing their policies.
</P>
<P>
   Once this poor girl called. Her boyfriend had died, and she said
that his parents wanted to keep all of the money for themselves. I
tried to help her. It turned out her boyfriend had overdosed on
heroin, and she wanted money for her own drug problem. She kept
insisting that she was being swindled, but she wanted the money for
her own heroin addiction. I felt so sorry for her, but we don't pay
out if someone commits suicide.
</P>
<P>
   I probably talk to 100 people a day. I deal with brokers and
policyholders who have no idea of my disability. Sometimes people
get angry and start shouting at me and berating me. I always try to
remain composed, but once I just lost it. I shouted right back; the
conversation got pretty nasty. My manager heard part of it. She
didn't chew me out. She just told me that I had to maintain control
and not talk to my brokers that way. I got no special treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Once, before an open-enrollment meeting at a law firm, a woman
there said, ``You're not what I expected,'' and I said, ``You're
not what I expected either.'' Normally, you go to meetings, and
you're there to do your job, but with this woman, we seemed to
click. There was no guff. Even though I showed up in a wheelchair,
she saw past that. Unfortunately, the first thing that most people
see is the wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if anyone would appreciate this story, but it is
kind of heart-warming to me. Last week, one of the bigwigs was
coming to our office in Manhattan. I was a little nervous, but she
turned out to be so down-to-earth that I thought to myself: ``If
these are the types of people running this company, then I know
that I'm not going anywhere else.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (mg)
</P>
</TEXT>
