u s BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     04-05 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: RETOUCHES FOR GOLF'S MONA LISA 
</HEADLINE>
  (With GLF-MASTERS) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ If Cypress Point, out there with the surf and the
seals on the rocks of the Monterrey Peninsula in California, is
considered the Sistine Chapel of golf courses, Augusta National is
the Mona Lisa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a true piece of art,'' said Jose Maria
Olazabal, who won the Masters last year for the second time. ``When
you have a great painting or whatever, you don't try to change much
on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal seemed to be quietly questioning the subtle retouching
on nine holes, mostly the gentle rough that has narrowed the
fairway landing areas, for the 64th Masters that starts Thursday
with the same story line whenever Tiger Woods is playing: can
anybody here beat him?
</P>
<P>
   But a great golf course _ even, if not especially, Augusta
National _ is as much a work in progress as a work of art.
</P>
<P>
   With all the high-tech changes in equipment and agronomy over
the years, name a famous golf course that hasn't made changes and
you'll find it is as outdated as the hickory shaft. And the Augusta
National green jackets, on the advice of the golf architect Tom
Fazio, have retouched the Mona Lisa again.
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody appreciates the retouching, beginning with
Jack Nicklaus, the six-time Masters winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This golf course has always been played by the tree lines,''
said the Golden Bear, who has designed nearly 200 courses in 27
countries. ``I'm in favor of rough, but don't cut it in straight
lines that aren't along the tree lines. It looks like it's done by
someone who doesn't play golf or understand golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Harsh words for Fazio and the current green-jacket descendants
of Augusta National's original co-designers, the legendary Bobby
Jones and the worldwide architect Alister Mackenzie.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bobby Jones and Alister Mackenzie were great
designers,'' Mickelson said. ``I don't think it's the place of
anybody, if you can't break 90, to be changing the golf course from
those original designs.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson might be surprised to learn that those ``original
designs'' hardly exist now. After the first Masters in 1934, the
original front nine and back nine were reversed.
</P>
<P>
   If that switch had not been made, Gene Sarazen's legendary
double-eagle 2 in 1935 would have happened on the sixth hole
instead of the 15th hole, if it happened at all.
</P>
<P>
   In those early years, the greens were almost as hard as an
asphalt road. As Sam Snead remembers, ``When you walked across 'em,
you could hear your spikes.''
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, both the 11th and the 16th holes were
altered. On the 11th, now a par 4 of 455 yards, a pond was created
to the left of the green and a new tee was built in the pine trees
behind the 10th green.
</P>
<P>
   The 16th, originally a little par 3 of about 125 yards over a
meaningless ditch, was extended to what is now 170 yards over a
yawning pond to a slippery green.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, the bunkers were filled with different sand. In 1981,
the greens were converted to bent grass from Bermuda grass.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, after more than 60 years of no discernible rough, what
Augusta National likes to call ``the second cut'' was grown _ one
and three-eighths inch of rough that's smoother than the fairways,
if not the greens, at some golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   And for this year's Masters, hoping to put a premium on driving
for Woods and golf's other big bombers, the green jackets narrowed
the landing areas on six holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt,'' said William (Hootie) Johnson, the Masters
chairman, ``that we could no longer let them swing from the heels.
We had to require more accuracy off the tee. If you're hitting a
sand wedge or a pitching wedge or no more than a 9-iron to almost
any green, then we have to call on some premium on accuracy off the
tee.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Woods and the other big bombers must be more
careful with their tee shots on the ninth and 10th holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``On No. 9,'' Woods said, ``now you have to go right of that big
tree, which means you can't hit to the middle of the fairway. The
middle has moved over 15 or 20 yards. On No. 10, a ball that used
to hang up on the fairway is now in the rough. Now there's a longer
shot from the rough to a green that is now harder and faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the changes just represent a little retouching for
golf's Mona Lisa, still a work in progress. Low score will still
win.
</P>
<P>
   (JT)  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
