<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE STEPS UP ATTACKS ON BUSH'S EDUCATION AND TAX PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Al Gore stepped up his attacks on George W. Bush's
education and tax policies Wednesday before an enthusiastic labor
union crowd here.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president charged that the Texas governor's education
proposals would not lower class sizes or help rebuild schools that
are falling apart and that his planned tax cuts would create
spending deficits.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing a cheering audience at the Construction and Building
Trades Department of the AFL-CIO, Gore called Bush's tax plan a
``reckless scheme that (would) devastate public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line of his plan is a return to the Bush-Quayle
deficits,'' he said, referring to the administration of President
George Bush, the candidate's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``We face an opportunity to build on today's prosperity, use it
</P>
<P>
   to make sure no one is left behind, or to choose the other
</P>
<P>
   direction, which would mean a right-wing U-turn back to the
</P>
<P>
   Bush-Quayle deficits, the Bush-Quayle recession, the Bush-Quayle
</P>
<P>
   assault on working families,'' Gore declared.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating his earlier attacks, Gore criticized Gov. Bush's
record on education in Texas, saying the Lone Star State rates 45th
in the nation in SAT scores and 48th in the percentage of high
school students who finish college.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says he wants to do for the nation's schools what he's done
for the schools in Texas,'' Gore added sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks followed the release of a Washington Post-ABC News
poll Tuesday that showed 48 percent of Americans say Gore is the
candidate better able to improve public education while 39 percent
claim Bush is better.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign replied to Gore's speech with an attack on the
Clinton-Gore administration's record on education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore's rhetoric of bringing revolutionary change to our
nation's schools rings hollow,'' said Bush spokesman Scott
McClellan. ``Texas is leading the nation in closing the achievement
gap (between minority and non-Hispanic white students) while the
Clinton-Gore administration has done nothing in closing the
achievement gap.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Wednesday, Bush asked Gore why 68
percent of children in the nation's poorest schools cannot read and
why America lags behind other industrial nations in certain
international test scores.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan also accused Gore of distorting Bush's tax plan
figures and his record on education.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's education plan calls for $115 billion in federal spending
over 10 years in part to hire new teachers and help districts build
new schools and rebuild old ones.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has proposed holding poorly performing schools accountable
by shutting them down and later reopening them with new
administrators and with teachers who have received new training. He
would also reward successful teachers with higher salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan, which he amended last week to boost federal funds,
now calls for $13.4 billion in federal spending over five years.
About $3 billion would go to recruiting and training new teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would hold schools accountable for students' success on
standardized tests by permanently closing poorly performing schools
and making available money to low-income parents who could then
enroll their children in private schools. Gore opposes the
private-school voucher idea.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has often boasted about the accountability standards he
oversees as Texas governor that have raised standardized test
scores among minority students in the state. His critics have noted
that many of the standards were already in place or had been
proposed before Bush took office in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, citing their differences, said of Bush's education plan:
</P>
<P>
   ``He's wrong on rebuilding public schools, wrong on small class
sizes, wrong on universal pre-school, wrong on teacher quality and
accountability.'' Gore added that Bush also is ``wrong on a tax
giveaway for the few at the expense of education and health care
and a strong economy.''
</P>
<P>
   McClellan, however, argued that Bush's tax cut would save $2
trillion for Social Security and preserve the budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is proposing a $483 billion tax-cut package over five
years, and Gore supports the $250 billion net tax cut over 10 years
that President Clinton outlined in his State of the Union address
in January.
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920.)
</P>
</TEXT>
