s e BC-WILD-PARTY-THEATER-AR     04-05 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILD-PARTY-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HOST OF A PARTY MIRRORING AN ERA 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 9)
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo was sent as NYT38 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
Maura Spiegel, a professor of English and film at Columbia
University and Barnard College, is writing a book on postwar
political message movies. 
 By MAURA SPIEGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the summer of 1926, Joseph Moncure March,
something of a rebel at 26, sat down at a battered kitchen table in
his airless $20-a-month walkup in Manhattan to write a narrative in
verse about ``a lot of people getting drunk at a party,'' a subject
he had come to know very well.
</P>
<P>
   The result, ``The Wild Party,'' is, as almost everyone knows by
now, the source and title of two musicals this season: one, by
Andrew Lippa, ends its run this Sunday at the Manhattan Theater
Club at City Center; the other, co-produced by the Joseph Papp
Public Theater, is to open on Thursday at the Virginia Theater on
Broadway. With music and lyrics by Michael John LaChiusa and
directed by George C. Wolfe, it stars Mandy Patinkin, Toni Collette
and Eartha Kitt.
</P>
<P>
   No era is so fully identified with its parties (and no parties
seem to have been wilder) than the Jazz Age, a period that comes
down to us as one decadelong, tinseled, alcohol-saturated
celebration. March's poem offers a jolting peek at the hard-driving
pursuit of illicit pleasure, the intoxicated throwing off of
inhibitions and the thrill of getting down and dirty.
</P>
<P>
   Great parties can reveal a lot about an era, its moods, the
character of its gaiety, its resources for pleasures and for the
ability to suspend ordinary life, from Nero's notorious excesses to
the dizzying sexual undercurrents of 19th-century balls captured by
Flaubert in ``Madame Bovary.''
</P>
<P>
   As Truman Capote's 1966 Black and White Ball marks and comments
on its historical moment, the '70s are forever linked to the
cocaine-charged parties at Studio 54.
</P>
<P>
   March's ``Wild Party'' is a tale about the dangers _ and the
frisson _ of crossing boundaries and of a restless pursuit of the
forbidden. It tells the racy story of an all-night debauch in the
bohemian squalor of the Manhattan apartment of a vaudeville dancer,
Queenie, and her swaggering boyfriend, Burrs. When Black _ a man
who ``made you think of squash-rackets;/ And dinner-jackets./ And
had that air of poise without pose/That only a well-bred person
shows'' _ turns up to mix with the exotic lowlife, Queenie makes
her move on him, and the results are deadly.
</P>
<P>
   The plot owes something to the ballad form and to the words of
blues songs and African-American ``toasts,'' while the poem's tone
veers between stark tabloid luridness and street-talk patter: ``
`Listen to me, kid!' Kate admonished:/ `Keep away from that
blond-headed vamp:/ She was wise to herself/ When your ears were
damp!'''
</P>
<P>
   The writer of these words was a New Yorker, born in 1899 into an
established, powerful family. He described feeling unnerved when,
as an undergraduate attending Amherst College's compulsory daily
chapel, he was seated beneath a portrait of his grandfather, an
Anglo-Saxon scholar and philologist who had received honorary
degrees from Princeton, Columbia, Oxford and Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   March's uncle, Gen. Peyton Conway March, served as Army chief of
staff in World War I. His father, whom March described in a 1968
autobiographical essay as ``an imposing figure, 6 feet 6, 190
pounds, with black burly eyebrows,'' ran the legal department of
the Equity Life Insurance Co. These forebears, who took very solemn
approaches to their manly pursuits, would loom large in March's
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   In that same essay, titled ``A Certain Wildness,'' March
described himself in the mid-1920s: ``A tense, somber young man, 6
feet 2 inches tall, weighing 148 pounds, with high cheekbones, a
slanting forehead, blackish-brown hair, a jutting nose much too big
for the rest of my face, and dark shadows under my eyes, which gave
me a dissipated look.'' His hats were by Knox and he carried a
walking stick.
</P>
<P>
   March grew up on West 112th Street before being packed off to
prep school at Lawrenceville in New Jersey, where he was
alphabetically seated beside Reginald Marsh, who would later
illustrate the first edition of ``The Wild Party,'' and at whose
home March would meet his second wife, Susan Wise.
</P>
<P>
   At Lawrenceville, March began writing poetry, and at Amherst he
studied with Robert Frost, whom he described as ambling the campus
``with the uncertain gait of a man who was slightly tipsy, or
perhaps walking in his sleep ... his gray suit looking like he had
slept in it all summer.'' Frost's ``unpretty'' diction,
disparagement of free verse and unconventional rhyme patterns
became reference points for March in writing ``The Wild Party.''
</P>
<P>
   At college, March's uneasy truce with the establishment was made
even more difficult after he wrote two articles criticizing school
policy and spoofing the rhetorical style of a minister. In hot
water with the dean, he halfheartedly apologized, then packed his
bags and headed for New York, enlisting in the Army the next day.
He served a year in France as a private in the artillery, making no
use of his connections: ``My family regarded nepotism with
disfavor,'' he wrote later.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, he finished up at Amherst and made his way to New
York the same year as F. Scott Fitzgerald and just in time for the
Roaring Twenties.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling them years later, Fitzgerald said he had ``gone to New
York on a terrible party,'' and the epigraph to his 1922 novel,
``This Side of Paradise'' _ ``The victor belongs to the spoils'' _
could serve as one for the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The New York to which March returned, pumped up by the postwar
Wall Street boom, swarmed with a prosperous crowd bent on nocturnal
diversion. Prohibition pushed pleasure into the realm of the
illicit and seemed to provoke experiments in misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
   Speakeasies and nightclubs multiplied, as partying became big
business for bootleggers and club owners. Cafe society came into
routine contact with mobsters. For the well heeled, rubbing
shoulders with people ``out of one's set'' was itself a highly
charged act of defiance of respectability. And slumming _
selective, pleasure-oriented contact with a colorful low-life,
homosexuals and ``the race'' _ became a pastime of the rich. The
romantic possibilities of transgression seemed inexhaustible; all
lines demanded crossing: racial, class, gender and legal.
</P>
<P>
   While Upper East Side clubs like the Heigh-Ho excluded blacks
and Jews, and blacks could enter many Broadway clubs only as
entertainers or hired help, white patrons were making nightly
pilgrimages to Harlem, which had displaced the bohemian Greenwich
Village as the city's nocturnal nerve center.
</P>
<P>
   Harlem clubs like Jungle Alley, Small's Paradise, Connie's Inn,
Tillie's Chicken Shack and the Cotton Club presented such talent as
Fats Waller, Ethel Waters, Bessie Smith and Duke Ellington.
Audiences included many ``downtown'' musicians like Paul Whiteman,
Hoagy Carmichael, Bix Beiderbecke and Benny Goodman, and
celebrities like Tallulah Bankhead, Joan Crawford, Mae West, Jack
Dempsey, Gene Tunney and Lady Mountbatten.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a column devoted to nightclubs and carrying the signature
``Lipstick,'' The New Yorker instructed those heading uptown that
the area did not really heat up until 5 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the wealthy prowlers of the gaslit Victorian night world,
affluent women of the 1920s went along for the ride. H.L. Mencken's
American Mercury, reporting on gin in 1927, wrote that 10 years
before then, ``no virtuous white woman in all this Christian realm
ever tasted it.'' The article continued, ``But now it is the common
beverage of American youth, and the daughters of the white
``noblesse'' carry it to parties as they used to carry smelling
salts.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Broadway theater buzzed to the electricity of the risque.
Along with Eugene O'Neill's ``Desire Under the Elms'' and Cole
Porter and Gershwin musicals, there were shows like ``Naughty
Cinderella,'' ``The Unchastened Woman'' and ``Is Zat So?,'' about
the world of prizefighters. Prostitution was explored in ``Shanghai
Gesture,'' ``Lulu Belle'' and Mae West's ``Sex.'' And homosexuality
was openly treated in ``The Captive'' and ``The Virgin Man,'' which
Mayor Jimmy Walker attended on opening night.
</P>
<P>
   March's New York life was a fluid one and he moved easily
between worlds. He even served briefly in 1925 as the first
managing editor of The New Yorker, all the while feeling himself to
be a writer who was not writing. Meanwhile, he plunged into the
nightlife.
</P>
<P>
   In his autobiographical essay, March describes one Greenwich
Village soiree where the host quietly hanged himself in the
bathroom; at another, a friend filled a lull by jumping from a
fourth-story window to a neighboring roof: ``For a split second I
thought he wasn't going to make it,'' March wrote. ``He grinned at
us amiably, then crouched and sprang back to the window.''
</P>
<P>
   A five-year marriage to a woman he describes as a ``Vassar
intellectual'' ended in 1926, and he took up with a tall
good-looking blonde: ``We had nothing in common except boredom, and
spent most of our time ... drifting from party to party and
drinking compulsively.'' Soon out of money, he gave up his tasteful
apartment on Gay Street to begin work on ``The Wild Party,'' his
father staking him to $30 a week.
</P>
<P>
   The poem took March three months, an entire hot summer, to
write: ``On good days, I would be able to do as much as 10 lines;
on bad days, I was lucky to get four. Once in a while, the lines
would seem just right as I set them down, but that was rare.
Generally, I had to work the passage over and over until it was the
way I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   But in his ``improvised'' cadences he felt he had stumbled onto
a ``new beat,'' and he was elated. He later described the influence
of silent film on the poem: ``My school for storytelling was the
cinema. I had sat in theaters watching films like `The Last Laugh'
and `Variety' over and over again, admiring their tremendous pace
and economy, and the way the swift succession of images on the
screen kept the story moving without any let-down.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite enthusiasm from literary critics, including the
influential Louis Untermeyer, it took March two years to find a
publisher. Richard Simon of Simon &AMP; Schuster was scared off by a
letter from the head of the New York Society for Suppression of
Vice, threatening to jail him if he published the piece.
</P>
<P>
   Finally brought out in 1928 in a tiny edition of 750 copies by
Covici, the poem became an underground sensation, was banned in
Boston and went through a number of private printings in Germany
and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But March's next work, ``The Set-Up,'' the story in verse of a
black prizefighter, inspired by Jack Johnson, who is destroyed by
corruption and racial prejudice, brought him more conventional
success. It made the New York Times best-seller list and was later
adapted for the screen _ but with a white protagonist.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, March found his way to Hollywood, where he
wrote screenplays and met his third wife, Peggy Pryor, whom he
married in 1931. His first movie, ``Hell's Angels,'' featured Jean
Harlow, the Blonde Bombshell, as an upscale Queenie, a scantily
clad pre-Hayes-code vamp, and it made her a star. His roster of
films includes ``Madame Butterfly,'' with Cary Grant as Pinkerton;
``Journey's End,'' a war drama, and ``Three Faces West,'' a
melodrama starring John Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941 he returned east, worked on documentaries for the State
Department and wrote feature stories for The New York Times
Magazine, mostly about Hollywood. He ended his career writing
industrial films for General Motors and Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps March found and lost himself in the 1920s. His wayward
spirit discovered its most fertile ground then, and if he ever
returned to writing narrative verse, we have no trace of it yet. In
1968 he wrote: ``My own preference has always been for the
disreputable. I feel much more at home in a pool parlor or a
nightclub than I do in a church; walking on the sunny side of the
street makes me quite ill, and even entering the lobby of a place
like the University Club will give me a qualm of apprehension and
nausea.'' He died in Los Angeles in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   As for these two productions of ``The Wild Party'' _ have they
something to tell us about our own era? Where are the wild parties
of today? How wild do parties get in our smoke-free, nonalcoholic,
decaffeinated, nonsexually harassing, Prozac-medicated world?
Perhaps they are not to be found in the dark depths of night but in
buoyant afternoons on the stock exchange floor. (af)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
