 &QL; 
 &UR; LADIES' DAY &LR;
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; TIPS FOR LIVING A BETTER LIFE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Martha decants her detergents into pretty containers to
brighten up a utility room,'' says the catalog Marthabymail, which
hawks just such a $15 container. And furnishings designer
 &UR; Kathryn Clarke &LR;  told Country Home, ``I try to create items that are
like women: strong, attractive, comfortable, and reliable.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a Yoga Journal essay about the convergence of yoga and
tango notes, ``In tango, two strangers meet and, within seconds, if
the alchemy is right, explore the intimate wrestle of desire, the
tension between dominance and submission. And when at last they
surrender as one, their pelvises pressed together ... the struggle
is over. In that moment, the Zen of tango awakens. ... A sweaty
little tango parlor can become a sacred space where one can dance
through memories and karma.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ADVICE FOR THE GALS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lauren Hutton &LR; , 56, was in Washington this week meeting with
lawmakers (Sens.  &UR; Arlen &LR;   &UR; Specter &LR; , R-Pa. and  &UR; Tom Harkin &LR; , D-Iowa)
and lecturing about the benefits of hormone replacement therapy,
which she told the Washington Post ``saved my life.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the women who take estrogen, including  &UR; Diane Sawyer &LR; 
and ``all the smart New York professional women ... look much
younger than their age, and they don't look like they've shrunk or
dried up.'' Hutton is a paid spokeswoman for Wyeth-Ayerst
pharmaceuticals, which sells estrogen pills.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Svelte new mom  &UR; Cindy Crawford &LR;  shares advice for staying
slim with new moms who read McCall's magazine: When friends or
family members stop by to see the baby, have them take care of the
baby while you work out. ``That way, everyone's happy.'' And if the
baby's crying, maybe it's time to get a pedicure. ``New moms
sometimes forget that they can't take care of anyone else until
they've taken care of themselves,'' Crawford says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; VILLAINS AND WIMPS, TOO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Health magazine's Relationship column tackles nagging, which,
says  &UR; Beth Singer &LR; , ``may be one of a wife's chief duties.'' After
all, notes University of Chicago sociologist  &UR; Linda Waite &LR; , married
men with wives who sometimes nag them live longer and stay
healthier than singles.
</P>
<P>
   The column sticks to the old-fashioned stereotypes: All the
naggers are women, all the nagged are men. And if you think you're
a woman who never nags, don't let yourself off the hook so fast,
sister. You might start worrying about being a wimp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Patti Breitman &LR;  and  &UR; Connie Hatch &LR; 's new book, ``How to Say No
Without Feeling Guilty'' (Broadway; $23), tackles saying no in many
cases, among them: sexual situations, work assignments, social
obligations, and when money is requested.
</P>
<P>
   Recommendations to ``give up reading beauty and fashion
magazines'' and ``steer clear of `Free makeovers''' are clearly
directed toward women. Seems if they aren't nag, nag, nagging,
they're agreeing to too many things. It's a hard knock life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Billy Joel &LR; 's sale of his Hamptons estate to  &UR; Jerry Seinfeld &LR; 
for $40 million must be a bit annoying to Joel's ex-wife,
 &UR; Christie Brinkley &LR; , says New York magazine, because a few years ago
he gave her $3 million for her share of it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``All the real babes work in PR firms. You see a lot of dating &LR; 
 &UR; between industry guys and PR girls.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Sean Garrett,  &LR; PR director for Listen.com, in a Harper's
Bazaar story about gold-diggers in Silicon Valley, where the
millionaires, ``most of them young single men,'' are turned out at
the rate of 64 a day.
</P>
