A8117 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-IRAQ-IRAN-OIL-NYT &LR;      04-05 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-IRAN-OIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN SAYS IT SEIZED SHIP WITH SMUGGLED IRAQ OIL
</HEADLINE>
  By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Two weeks after the United States warned that
increased oil smuggling from Iraq could not be stopped without
Iran's help, the Iranian government said Wednesday that it had
seized a tanker illegally exporting Iraqi oil as it passed through
Iranian waters.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian national news agency said that revolutionary guards
boarded an Iraqi ship flying under a Honduran flag on Saturday. The
ship was reported to be carrying 2,500 tons of smuggled oil. The
Iranian agency said the ship and its captain and crew were in
Iranian custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the reports are true, we are pleased to see that Iran is
taking measures against this illegal traffic,'' a spokesman for the
State Department, James Rubin, said Wednesday. Rubin said the
United States had not confirmed the arrest, which follows more than
18 months during which Iran allowed what U.S. officials say is
significant growth in the illegal coastal trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, Iran has taken measures to halt smuggling along
its coast, and we hope this is an indication they intend to do so
vigorously again,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   On March 23, Vice Adm. Charles Moore, the U.S. coordinator of an
international fleet that patrols the Persian Gulf off Iraq and
intercepts illegal shipments, told the Security Council sanctions
committee on Iraq that oil smuggling had increased significantly
since the fall, with much of the trade beginning in Iranian coastal
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Moore told the committee that a diplomatic or political overture
to Iraq was needed and that the smuggled Iraqi oil _ most of it
gasoil, similar to diesel fuel _ went to a variety of countries
including Iran, as well as to Pakistan and India. Recently, two
Thais and a Singaporean were charged in a court in California with
trying to buy Iraqi oil, apparently for shipment to Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials told the sanctions panel that with high oil
prices Iraq could earn more than $1 billion in illegal sales this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Under Security Council sanctions imposed in 1990 after Iraq
invaded Kuwait, President Saddam Hussein's government is not only
prohibited from selling oil without U.N. supervision, but it is
also barred from refining oil, as it has to do to produce gasoil.
</P>
<P>
   Since December, Iraq has been allowed to sell as much crude oil
as it wants, with profits going to a U.N. escrow account to pay for
food, medicines and equipment for a range of public services. A
third of the money goes to compensate victims of the Kuwait
invasion.
</P>
<P>
   In another sanctions dispute, U.S. officials considered
Wednesday how to respond to an illegal flight into Baghdad by an
Italian plane that was taking anti-sanctions campaigners to Iraq.
All flights to Iraq have to seek approval from the sanctions
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot of the small Italian passenger plane left Jordan
Tuesday saying that he was going to Syria and then turned and flew
at a very low altitude into Iraq. On board were, in addition to the
pilot, an Italian businessman, identified by the Jordanians as
Nicola Grauso; a member of the European Parliament, Vittori Sgarbi;
and a French priest, the Rev. Jean-Marie Benjamin. When the plane
returned to Jordan Wednesday, it was intercepted, forced to land
and impounded.
</P>
<P>
   The businessmen were allowed to leave Amman by commercial
flights, but the pilot was detained. The priest, who had campaigned
against sanctions, remained in Baghdad, the Jordanians said.
</P>
<P>
   In Baghdad, the group said the flight had been deliberately
planned to break the air embargo. Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz
called the flight a ``noble and courageous initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   (rk)
</P>
</TEXT>
