<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8131 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-PHILLY-PRESERVATION-N     04-05 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-PRESERVATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE STREETS OF PHILADELPHIA WITH TONY GOLDMAN
</HEADLINE>
 By BARBARA FLANAGAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ If hype were an art form, Tony Goldman might have
won a Pulitzer by now. And if Pritzker prizes were awarded not for
boutique architecture, but for turning seedy buildings into
world-class destinations, then Goldman would surely be on the short
list.
</P>
<P>
   Most real estate mavens do not mess with losing propositions,
but this developer loves them. So far, Goldman, a trustee for the
National Trust for Historic Preservation, claims to have saved SoHo
in Manhattan (in the late '70s); South Beach in Florida (in the
mid-80s); and Wall Street (in the mid-90s). Now, he has plans to
recycle Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   What he sees is an infinitely walkable town with nothing to walk
to. Goldman has every intention of lifting the curse off
Philadelphia, a shrinking city of 1.5 million, semi-famous for
greasy food, high taxes, a surfeit of bricks, a dearth of style and
a lack of news.
</P>
<P>
   In five years, Goldman says, Philadelphia could be the Paris of
the Northeast, a town of affordable, comfy live and work quarters,
bustling with so much alfresco dining and strolling that people
would actually make Philadelphia the kind of destination that South
Beach has become. Without the beach, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, 56, who is based in Manhattan, likes to discover
once-flourishing neighborhoods, buy them up cheaply (his buying
spree in Philadelphia happened two years ago) and then nurture them
over a decade or two. While other developers tend to bulldoze
defunct, outmoded buildings, Goldman likes to turn them back into
intricate neighborhoods. (He did this in South Beach where, among
other things, he bought the Tiffany Hotel, built in 1939, and
eventually hired Todd Oldham, the fashion designer, to turn it into
a chic boutique hotel.) That's one reason he rejects the term
developer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Developers are knock 'em down, build 'em up guys,'' said
Goldman, the president of Goldman Properties, a company with 375
people in three cities: New York, Miami and Philadelphia. ``That's
not me.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that right now few Philadelphians want to take
leisurely strolls around their city. And the suburbanites who do
venture into the fancy restaurants downtown won't walk around;
instead, they pay $12 for curbside valet parking.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you remake the place?
</P>
<P>
   Goldman has acquired a motley zone of modest buildings in Center
City, an area with just enough grit _ porno movies, bars and vacant
buildings _ to deter most people from investing. Of the 30-some
properties Goldman has bought in Philadelphia, 13 are in the 13th
Street Passages neighborhood, as he calls the area around Walnut
and 13th Streets.
</P>
<P>
   His plan is to revamp the place over the next 18 months and
connect it to the nearby Avenue of the Arts section on Broad
Street, where the Regional Performing Arts Center, designed by
Rafael Vinoly, is rising among theaters and hotels. (The
Pennsylvania Convention Center, home to the Republican National
Convention this summer, is nearby.)
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, Goldman has spent millions on
Philadelphia. To stretch his money, he convinced the city to make
the 13th Street Passages into a tax increment financing district,
which helps developers borrow money for blighted areas.
</P>
<P>
   His plan is to clean the area up by ending leases for, he said,
``a porno video store, check cashing place, gold chain store and
palm reader.'' He has turned an old office tower into his flagship
Philadelphia Building, on Walnut Street, and filled it with office
tenants. Now, he said, he has deals for three restaurants and three
shops on his desk. One is his own SoHo Kitchen and Bar, which is
being moved from Manhattan to Philadelphia. (He is redeveloping
part of Greene Street in Manhattan, where the restaurant used to
be.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be edgy,'' he said of his proposals. ``I want
impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's vision often involves relentless boosterism.
Philadelphia is ``the most undervalued, underappreciated and
overlooked city,'' he has told most publications in his newly
discovered town. Dressed like a carpetbagger _ in Armani,
black-on-black or white-on-white with an I-play-hard tan set off by
hipster shades and white hair _ he harangues Philadelphia residents
about their low civic self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his more-talk-than-action approach to remaking
Philadelphia, he has fans throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Kaplan, the executive director of the Philadelphia City
Planning Commission, believes his project is solid. ``We just wish
he would hurry up and do it,'' she said. Kaplan, an ex-New Yorker,
thinks that Philadelphia, her adopted city, is the ``undiscovered
gem of the East Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the city is such a gem, why isn't the place full of
developers?
</P>
<P>
   ``Plenty of New York developers have come in and bought cheap _
then realized why it was cheap,'' Kaplan said. Philadelphia, a
smaller, slower city, has had an entrenched ability to withstand
gentrification.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to do the easy or obvious thing,'' she said.
``They're not willing to take a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Others also feel that it is time for Goldman's plans to be put
into action. Craig Berger, the director of projects at
Philadelphia's Foundation for Architecture, an organization that
promotes public dialogue in urban development, said, ``We're a
little tired of the hype.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he accepts that Goldman's talking about his
projects creates optimism, which fuels new deals.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman says that the infrastructure is already there. ``I love
the little streets,'' he said. ``Street beds 12 feet wide.
</P>
<P>
   What he is counting on is the same urge to live downtown that
has transformed other cities, from New York to Denver and beyond.
His tenants will be the entrepreneurs who buy living and work
spaces in old office buildings, and suburbanites who are ready to
abandon their big houses and cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just wait,'' he said. ``But don't believe what I say, believe
what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   (mg)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
