<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8139 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-EDIT-MICROSOFT-AZR &LR;      04-05 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MICROSOFT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SAVED' FROM BIG, BAD MICROSOFT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In 1997, with its battle against the Justice
Department already 3 years old, Microsoft Corp. maintained a
Washington, D.C., government affairs office with all of four
employees. As columnist James Glassman noted at the time, AT&AMP;T
employed 45 lobbyists. IBM had 26.
</P>
<P>
   If there ever was a curious innocence to the unwillingness of
Bill Gates to play the Washington extortion game, it has
evaporated, along with tens of billions of dollars' worth of
investment in America's technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   Is Microsoft guilty, as federal District Court Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson concluded Monday? It certainly is. Of criminal
naivete in the first degree. Microsoft, the greatest success story
of the New Economy, forgot Rule No. 1 of the Old Economy: Ignore
the regulatory power of the federal government at your peril.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of no one (except, it seems, the denizens of
Wall Street who utterly panicked at the news), Judge Jackson found
the Redmond, Wash., firm guilty of predatory anti-competitive
behavior. The world's largest software manufacturer, he said,
``placed an oppressive thumb on the scale of competitive fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's bill of particulars is equally unsurprising.
</P>
<P>
   He found that by means of restrictive contracts and bullying,
Microsoft monopolized the personal-computer operating system
business. Further, Jackson concluded that by tying its Internet
Explorer Web browser to its Windows operating system, Microsoft
unfairly blocked its competition in that incipient industry.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge fails to explain in any coherent way what damage
has been wrought upon consumers by Microsoft's manipulations _ a
point Attorney General Janet Reno has asserted on numerous
occasions rests at the core of the suit her prosecutors brought.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, the ultradynamic computer industry has changed so
radically since the government leaped in to protect us that it is
utterly retro to even refer these days to the ``computer''
industry.
</P>
<P>
   To a great extent, technology has bypassed this fight. The
future of computerization today is not in the operating systems of
bulky, do-it-all desktops, but in Palm Pilots, wireless telephones
and a staggering variety of small appliances, all connected through
the Internet by systems that have nothing to do with Microsoft.
Does this suggest a latter-day version of a ubiquitous telephone
monopoly? Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   Well before the decision, Microsoft already had mitigated its
most egregious behaviors. It no longer writes into contracts
``bundling'' requirements for its various systems, for example. And
it will change still more. By the time this fight reaches a Supreme
Court resolution, as expected, technology and time may well have
rendered all points moot.
</P>
<P>
   There's another, not-insignificant point worth noting:
</P>
<P>
   When Judge Jackson's decision came down Monday, many among us
learned the details first by accessing a news Web site via
Microsoft's archcompetitor, Netscape Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   As the feds battled to save the world from Microsoft, some of us
already had saved ourselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
