A8150 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-EURO-NYT &LR;      04-05 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-EURO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE SWINGS WITH WALL STREET; LONDON TAKES TIMEOUT DUE TO
TECHNICAL PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Stoxx in 11th graf is cq.) By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Unsettled by Wall Street's wild swings, European stocks
fell Wednesday, pulled down by some of the technology shares that
had been leading the market higher. But for British investors the
real news was that they could not trade for much of the day because
of an unexplained technical problem that crippled the London Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension of trading until late afternoon could hardly have
come at a worse time. Wednesday was the last day of the British
fiscal year for individuals, when investors usually scramble to
reduce tax exposure using a strategy known in the business as ``bed
and breakfast'' _ selling stocks today with an arrangement to buy
them back tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had all these private-client brokers coming in today to
arrange these deals, finding the stock exchange closed and going
ballistic,'' said one broker.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the breakdown coincided with reports that the London
exchange was in early merger talks with the Deutsche Boerse in
Frankfurt, and its negotiating position was clearly undermined by
such a technical debacle. Brokers showed no hesitation in venting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's diabolical,'' said David Donnelly, chief
investment officer at Gordon House Asset Management. ``If you think
that in today's technological world, the London Stock Exchange
can't open, it's incredible, farcical that there's no backup
facility to keep it running.''
</P>
<P>
   When trading did open at 3:45 p.m. _ the close was extended to 8
p.m. _ the London market followed the rest of Europe down.
</P>
<P>
   Europe's retreat affected just about every index, with new
economy stocks taking the brunt of the selling, which analysts
attributed to fears among investors that the risks of owning
technology and Internet stocks had risen because of the huge swings
on Tuesday on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trans-Atlantic correlation between the two markets is very
high,'' said Paul Horne, a European equity market economist with
Salomon Smith Barney in London. But, he said, the fall in European
technology stocks was part of a process that had been going on for
about a month, driven by expectations of higher interest rates in
the United States, Britain and the 11-nation euro-zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The markets are taking profits out of these overvalued and
under-earning shares,'' he said. ``There's a lot of hope, but not
much earning.''
</P>
<P>
   He forecast that volatility would continue on Thursday, as
investors bought their way back into old-sector stocks with the
potential to benefit from newer technologies.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Stoxx 50 Price Index of European companies fell
2.8 percent, its sharpest drop since Jan. 4. But the Euro.NM index
of computer-related shares fell 4.7 percent, extending declines
that have stripped 35 percent of its value since its record high
set on March 10.
</P>
<P>
   In Helsinki, dominated by new economy stocks, the General Index
slumped 7.7 percent, dragged down by a sharp fall in Nokia, the
mobile phone company, which partly recovered before the close.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, the CAC-40 index closed off 3 percent, and Frankfurt's
Xetra DAX fell 2.6 percent. Among individual stocks, the sharpest
losses were among technology and computer-related companies with
high valuations based on assumptions a booming future profits.
</P>
<P>
   Sonera, Finland's biggest telephone company, fell 8.6 percent;
Canal Plus, the Continent's largest pay-TV company, fell 11.4
percent; and Cap Gemini, Europe's the biggest computer-services
group, fell 9.6 percent. The gloom disrupted plans by some
companies for initial share sales. Newconomy, for instance, which
aims to provide support for Internet-related businesses, postponed
plans for a $96 million flotation. Analysts forecast that the
number of such offerings would be sharply scaled back.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the misery elsewhere, there was one beneficiary of the
day's upheavals in London. Tradepoint Financial Networks, which
operates an electronic rival to the London exchange, recorded seven
times the trades as usual. ``This is a great day for us,'' a
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
