<HEADER>
A8152 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-HOUSE-ABORTION-BOS &LR;      04-05 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-ABORTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE VOTES TO BAN `PARTIAL-BIRTH' ABORTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Facing a certain presidential veto and an uncertain
hearing by the Supreme Court, the House Wednesday overwhelmingly
passed a ban on ``partial-birth abortions,'' holding doctors
criminally liable for performing the late-term procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The 287-141 vote is large enough for the House to overturn a
threatened third veto by President Clinton, though the Senate fell
short of a veto-proof majority when it passed its version of the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the impassioned debate in Congress provides a glimpse of
the arguments that will echo in the courts and the congressional
and presidential campaigns in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court is to consider a Nebraska ban on the abortion
procedure April 25, and a decision is expected before the high
court adjourns in late June. With the high court narrowly divided
on abortion, the matter is also expected to enter the presidential
campaign, since the next president may appoint as many as three new
justices to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   In the House Wednesday, Democrats who favor abortion rights
railed against their Republican colleagues, charging that they were
trying to eradicate the landmark Roe v. Wade decision legalizing
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans repeated gruesome, graphic descriptions of the
procedure, challenging Democrats to explain to voters this fall how
they could support what critics called ``infanticide.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you cannot see the abject, inhuman cruelty'' of the
procedure, ``then I fear for you,'' said a somber-sounding House
Majority Leader Richard Armey, Republican of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats said the Republicans were using the distasteful
description of one abortion method to take the right away from all
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Proponents of this bill are not just chipping away at the
right to choose. They are taking a jackhammer to it,'' said
Representative Louise Slaughter, Democrat of New York.
</P>
<P>
   The all-Democrat Massachusetts congressional delegation voted
against the bill, except for Representatives J. Joseph Moakley and
Richard Neal, both of Massachusetts. Both men are antiabortion.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation seeks to prohibit what opponents call
``partial-birth abortion,'' a politically loaded term for a medical
procedure known as ``intact dilation and extraction.''
</P>
<P>
   The process involves dilating the cervix and manipulating the
fetus into a breech position, according to the American College of
Obstetricians and Gynecologists. The fetus is pulled through the
vagina, and the head is partially evacuated while still inside the
pregnant woman. The dead fetus is then extracted vaginally,
according to the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Since no one keeps figures on methods of abortion, it is not
possible to determine how many such procedures are done yearly, the
ACOG said. But since fewer than 6 percent of abortions are
performed after the 16th week of pregnancy, ``it's not very
common,'' said ACOG spokeswoman Ann Allen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really done for tragic circumstances,'' such as when
the pregnant female's life or health is at stake, or when the fetus
has a ``fatal anomoly,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion foes described the procedure Wednesday in far more
graphic terms, using photographs to attempt to sway their
colleagues to vote for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Partial-birth abortion isn't being done for the health of the
woman. It's being done for the convenience of the abortionist,''
said Representative Tom Coburn, Republican of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the measure said the bill went much further than
banning the procedure and could theoretically be used to ban nearly
all abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Partial-birth abortion is a political term, not a medical
term,'' said Pam Nourse, spokeswoman for the Planned Parenthood
League of Massachusetts, which is fighting a similar bill in the
Massachusetts Legislature. ``We asking people to look beyond the
rhetoric to what the bill really does,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Barney Frank, Democrat of Massachusetts, also
tried to insert language that would make an exception if the health
of the pregnant female was at stake, but that, too, was defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Frank accused the Republicans of cynically passing legislation
they knew would never become law so they could schedule a veto
override vote right before the November elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
