<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGELLAN-SLIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGELLAN FUND NO LONGER NO. 1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fidelity's Magellan fund was edged off its pedestal as
the world's biggest mutual fund during Tuesday's stock shock,
according to a firm that closely tracks the Boston fund group.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard Group's Index 500 fund grabbed the No. 1 spot by a
hair, according to calculations by Jim Lowell, editor of the
Fidelity Investor, an independent newsletter, and Daniel Wiener,
who follows Vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   At the close of trading Tuesday, Lowell said, Magellan had
$106.9 billion of assets, while Vanguard's Index 500 fund had
$107.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first day in its history that Magellan woke up
without the crown on its head,'' Lowell said.
</P>
<P>
   Magellan is the fund that made Peter Lynch famous in the 1980s.
The portfolio exploded under his watch, and his prowess at stock
picking became the standard for investing in growth companies.
</P>
<P>
   Magellan's vast girth came under attack when Jeff Vinik ran the
fund and underperformed the benchmark Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index.
Critics argued that investors were better off in Vanguard's index
fund, which mirrors the S&AMP;P 500, saying Magellan could no longer
beat the index.
</P>
<P>
   But Bob Stansky has silenced the critics during his tenure
running Magellan, beating the S&AMP;P 500 in 1998 and 1999. Even in the
recent battering of technology stocks, Magellan maintained a 2.9
percent gain since Jan. 1. Its top holdings include stocks that
have tumbled lately, such as Microsoft Corp. and Texas Instruments
Inc. Vanguard's index fund is up 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Neither fund company would confirm the latest asset numbers, but
both said the figures were slightly low.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell and Weiner said their estimates were based on careful
calculations. They used the funds' reported assets from March 31,
then accounted for investment performance in the first four days of
April, plus estimates of the average daily sums investors put into
the funds and remove from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tug of war,'' said Lowell, who's been watching the
horse race between Magellan and Vanguard's index fund for three
months. Wiener predicted Vanguard would overtake Fidelity's
flagship fund as early as January, but the lead is hardly a
commanding one _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   Said Lowell, ``Magellan will probably take it back _ maybe
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard nonetheless put out a quietly celebratory statement:
``The asset growth of the Vanguard 500 Index Fund is a clear
indication that investors have come to realize the fundamentally
compelling benefits of indexing,'' said John Brennan, the Valley
Forge, Pa.-based firm's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Index fans say returns in passive funds are better than in
active funds over time. Expenses are generally lower in index
funds, and capital gains taxes are smaller because the funds buy
and sell stocks less frequently than actively managed funds.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard funds mushroomed in size with the rise in popularity of
index funds in the second half of the 1990s. The S&AMP;P 500 beat most
active funds in those years, until last year. Magellan closed to
new investors in September 1997 but remains Fidelity's most popular
fund among retirement-account customers.
</P>
<P>
   Magellan's assets appear to have fallen more sharply than
Vanguard's in the first week of April, with the market's gyrations.
Fidelity said Magellan's assets totaled $109.1 billion on March 31.
Vanguard Index 500's were at $107.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity spokeswoman Ann Crowley said, ``We're not concerned
with having the largest fund. We're concerned about good
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard's Brennan, too, noted that investment performance
matters more than size.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also believe that it is irrelevant for investors to focus
on a single fund's assets,'' he said in his statement. ``We measure
our success by how well we are serving our shareholders _ both
individual and institutional.''
</P>
</TEXT>
