<HEADER>
A8156 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CAMBODIA-LAND-760-ART     04-05 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-LAND-760-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHNOM PENH JOURNAL PUSHED FROM THE LAND, AND THE TREES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT pHoto clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SETH MYDANS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ This is the way Doc Phum got his land: by
crawling on his belly through a minefield, poking at the ground
with a knife until he hit something hard, then throwing rocks at it
until it exploded.
</P>
<P>
   ```I know it wasn't my land,'' he said. ``It didn't belong to
anybody. But I demined it, and it was good farmland.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the way he lost it three years later: 200 armed men
arrived with bulldozers just before harvest time last year and tore
up the fields and thatched huts of Doc Phum and 100 other
subsistence farmers. A local general had decided to build a casino.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go ahead and file your complaints,'' said the general,
according to another villager, Reach Somaly. ``I don't care. The
guys at the top are my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   As Cambodia emerges fitfully from three decades of mass killings
and civil war, land disputes and land grabbing have spread across
the country. And a basic truth about Cambodian society is being
reaffirmed: Cambodia belongs to the powerful.
</P>
<P>
   With the collapse of the Khmer Rouge guerrilla insurgency and an
end to factional fighting within the government, tens of thousands
of landless farmers now find themselves in competition with
business interests and military officers for former battlegrounds
and minefields.
</P>
<P>
   A result is a new generation of dispossessed people in a country
where land ownership has been in dispute since the overthrow in
1979 of the brutal Khmer Rouge government, which had taken all the
land for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, mass killings and warfare have created huge waves of
refugees, and many of Cambodia's people _ more than 80 percent of
whom are farmers _ remain wanderers.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, only 14 percent of land is properly registered, and
many of those registrations are fraudulent. Even in the capital,
Phnom Penh, three-fourths of the land is not secured by a legal
title, according to the ministry of land management.
</P>
<P>
   The battles over land are being fought by people who have been
toughened by generations of brutality in Cambodia. So the methods
of eviction sometimes involve throwing a hand grenade into a crowd
or firing B-40 rockets at buildings or cutting off the heads of
stubborn villagers or, as in a case in March, burning down 60 homes
that had been built for widows, orphans and disabled veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Desperation and a dawning sense among some poor people that they
do have rights have led to a new phenomenon _ a changing but nearly
permanent colony of squatters in a park outside the Parliament
building here. They are evicted villagers who have come from
various provinces to petition for redress, spending their days with
paid scribes to send letters to every official and ministry they
can think of.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of their lack of sophistication, people when they are
angry go everywhere and send letters everywhere to every kind of
official,'' said George Cooper, a lawyer with a private group
called Legal Aid of Cambodia. ``It's sort of, in one way,
inefficient because they are firing shots all over the place. On
the other hand, it means officials of all kinds have been bombarded
_ really bombarded _ by complaints. Because these people are really
up against it; they don't have any land, and they don't have any
food.''
</P>
<P>
   Doc Phum and Reach Somaly are among more than 200 landless
people from four provinces who now live under the tamarind trees
outside the Parliament building, not far from a hospital where most
of the children they have brought with them are being treated for
chicken pox, which is epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   Among the people here are Meas Sophan, 45, and her three hungry
children, who pull off and chew the tender, sour leaves of the
tamarind trees that shelter them. They are part of a group of
villagers from the province of Kompong Thom who are protesting not
the loss of their land but the loss of the trees in which they
lived.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, Meas Sophan said, they were forced by flooding to
leave their rice fields. When they tried to return, the fields had
been occupied by other, more powerful people.
</P>
<P>
   So the villagers climbed big trees along a river, and had lived
there ever since _ cooking, sleeping and fishing in the branches
above the water. When the river rose, they climbed higher, she
said. When it receded, they descended.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy way to live,'' she said, ``especially when
you drop a pot or a glass or a knife into the water. There's
nothing you can do until the dry season, when you can go down and
look for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the government granted a fishing concession
to a private company, and the villagers were evicted from their
trees.
</P>
<P>
   Now all they have is this sidewalk in Phnom Penh, where they
subsist for the moment on donations from aid groups and sacks of
rice from King Norodom Sihanouk, the nearly powerless monarch, who
lives next door in his palace.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Va Sophal, 40, is a former Khmer Rouge foot soldier and a former
refugee who describes himself, with a surprisingly bold grin, as
``a powerless person, the poorest farmer you can find.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he fled the Khmer Rouge ranks in 1979, he said, he has
spent his years shifting from one refugee camp to another and from
one plot of farmland to another, barely managing to feed himself
from day to day.
</P>
<P>
   He came here with a group of evicted farmers from O'Smach, in
northwestern Cambodia, an area filled with land mines and malaria.
It had been a battleground for most of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the first time, he said, he is doing battle for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my own feelings, I believe I have as many rights as
anybody,'' he said. ``But when they use their power against me and
take my land away, I'm not so sure anymore. The only thing for us
is to unite and come here and sleep under the tamarind trees and
see whether anyone will do anything to help us.''  &QL; 
(JT)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
