u a BC-BUSWRECK-FOLO06-COX     04-05 0356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSWRECK-FOLO06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Decision pending on school bus-train wreck charges
 &HT;    By D.L. Bennett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tennessee authorities won't determine until at least
next week whether they will file criminal charges against a school
bus driver who rolled into the path of a freight train, causing a
collision that killed three children, according to the Tennessee
State Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still attempting to gather evidence and talk to
witnesses,'' said Dana Keeton, spokeswoman for the agency, which is
investigating the March 28 crash in which the bus driver's daughter
was among those critically injured. ``We want to make sure we do
everything right.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency has given National Transportation Safety Board
investigators the videotape from the camera inside the school bus.
Technicians at the NTSB, which investigates all major crashes, will
enhance the audio and video, Keeton said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators have said the tape, witnesses and physical
evidence show bus driver Rhonda Cloer, 34, failed to stop before
entering the crossing, which is near the Tennessee-Georgia line.
Tennessee law requires school bus drivers to stop 15 to 50 feet
from a crossing. Violation of the law is a misdemeanor punishable
by up to six months in jail and a fine of up to $500.
</P>
<P>
   Cloer, of Chatsworth, Ga., has not talked to investigators. Her
lawyer, Greg Melton of Dalton, Ga., said he has advised Cloer not
to talk until he reviews the bus' videotape.
</P>
<P>
   ``She very badly wants to talk about this,'' Melton said. ``I
hope that will be sooner rather than later. It is her absolute
right to remain silent. At a minimum, we've been asking for a piece
of evidence we have every right to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Kayli Cloer, 5, and Kevin Sherrill, 8, are in critical condition
at T.C. Thompson Children's Hospital in Chattanooga, Tenn. Rhonda
Cloer and two students were hospitalized briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Cloer has remained with her daughter at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how she's held up as well has she has,'' said
Melton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
