u a BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      04-05 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBTS ABOUT LEWIS DIAGNOSIS VOICED AT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ During tense, combative testimony, the former
supervisor of Gilbert H. Mudge Jr., the doctor who announced
publicly that Reggie Lewis had a benign fainting condition that
would not end his basketball career, said Wednesday that he had
doubts about Mudge's diagnosis and worried that, if Mudge were
wrong, Lewis could die.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying for the first time in the case, which ended in a hung
jury last year, Dr. Eugene Braunwald said he questioned Mudge's
diagnosis, which was at odds with the conclusion reached by a team
of preeminent cardiologists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I questioned his degree of certainty,'' said Braunwald, a
cardiologist at Brigham and Women's Hospital who chaired the
hospital's medical department when Lewis was under Mudge's care in
1993. ``I thought he might be right, but I wasn't as confident and
sure as he seemed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Mudge ``seemed to think this was open and shut. . . but I wasn't
all that certain,'' added Braunwald, testifying on the third day of
the retrial in the medical malpractice lawsuit stemming from the
Celtics star's July 1993 death.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew that if he was wrong, Mr. Lewis's life was in
jeopardy, didn't you?'' asked Neil Rossman, the lawyer representing
Lewis's widow, Donna Harris-Lewis, who sued Mudge for wrongful
death after her 27-year-old husband died of heart failure three
months after he came under Mudge's care.
</P>
<P>
   Braunwald paused for several seconds, then replied, ``That's
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Braunwald, who was not called to the stand during the first
trial, was clearly a reluctant witness. Called as a plaintiff's
witness by Rossman, Braunwald acknowledged that he had refused to
meet with Rossman or take his phone calls prior to his courtroom
appearance. And throughout Rossman's questioning, Braunwald was
frequently argumentative and uncooperative, prompting the judge to
intercede several times and ask him to answer the questions posed
to him.
</P>
<P>
   In one exchange that lasted at least 10 minutes and prompted
laughs from the jury, Rossman tried to get Braunwald to concede
that neurocardiogenic syncope _ the fainting condition Mudge said
Lewis had _ is not a medical condition that can cause death.
Braunwald insisted that if a person experienced neurocardiogenic
syncope while crossing a street and fainted in front of a truck, he
could indeed die.
</P>
<P>
   ``But doctor,'' Rossman finally asked, ``neurocardiogenic
syncope alone won't kill you, right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right,'' Braunwald said.
</P>
<P>
   But Braunwald also testified that while he asked Mudge if he
felt ``all that certain'' about his fainting diagnosis, which Mudge
announced at a May 1993 press conference, Mudge told him privately
that he was also considering a second diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   A central component of Mudge's defense is that despite his claim
at the press conference that Lewis suffered only from a fainting
disorder, he also believed Lewis might have a cardiac arrhythmia, a
potentially lethal heart condition. Indeed, at the first trial,
Mudge testified that he, the Lewises, hospital officials, and
Celtics representatives had a ``calculated plan'' to conceal the
second, more worrisome diagnosis from the public.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis has testified that Mudge never told her or her
husband that he could have a life-threatening disorder.
</P>
<P>
   During his questioning of Braunwald, Rossman established that
nowhere in Lewis's Brigham medical records was there any indication
that Mudge believed he suffered from an arrhythmia.
</P>
<P>
   Braunwald appeared more composed under questioning by Mudge's
attorney, William J. Dailey Jr., who asked him to elaborate on why
he had called Lewis's medical case ``challenging'' and
``difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Braunwald noted that multiple tests run on Lewis had yielded
conflicting data, forcing doctors to ``try to sort out a lot of
evidence, some of which was contrary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a clear set of signals that we received from the
patient,'' he added. ``That's what made the case very, very
complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Braunwald also noted that a person can suffer from
neurocardiogenic syncope and arrhythmia simultaneously, further
complicating efforts to diagnose Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Mudge had said during the press conference that
``medicine is an art, not a science,'' Dailey asked Braunwald if it
is ``true that medicine is not a precise science?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You bet,'' Braunwald replied.
</P>
<P>
   Dailey's questioning went to the core of a key issue the jury
will have to consider: in medical malpractice cases, juries are
told it is not enough to find that a doctor made a mistake. They
must find that the care deviated from ``acceptable standards of
practice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
