<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8160 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-PATAKI-LAZIO-HNS &LR;      04-05 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATAKI-LAZIO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAZIO, CRITICAL OF GIULIANI, RECONSIDERS SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., said Wednesday a thumbs
down from New York Gov. George Pataki would make it virtually
impossible for him to challenge New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for
the Republican senatorial nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki appeared to oblige him, telling reporters in Albany that
``it's not particularly helpful'' for Republicans like Lazio to do
anything other than support Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, 42, a fourth-term House member who last year bowed to
Pataki's entreaties to make way for Giuliani, said in an interview
Wednesday that the governor's disapproval would ``disincline me''
from challenging Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   But he continued to insist that the controversial mayor was
dragging the GOP down with him in an increasingly bitter contest
against the Democratic candidate, First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton. The winner in November will replace Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, a Democrat who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to be difficult or defiant or create heartburn
for the Republican leadership in New York,'' Lazio said. ``What I'm
trying to do is encourage the Republican leadership to make a sober
assessment as to where they are with the Senate race, and to think
of the world not in terms of the way they'd like it to be, but the
world the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said he wanted to discuss with the Republican governor
about getting into the race, but that Pataki had not returned a
phone call. Pataki's spokeswoman, Zenia Mucha, said late Wednesday
that Pataki had placed a call to Lazio, but she was unsure if they
had connected.
</P>
<P>
   Still, whether on the phone or to reporters, Pataki's message to
Lazio was loud and clear: Stay out. ``I don't think it's
particularly helpful for other Republicans to do anything other
than get behind the candidacy of Mayor Giuliani,'' Pataki said. ``I
urge (Lazio) and all others to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Byzantine political drama arose in the wake of Giuliani's
strident defense of the New York police in shootings of unarmed
minorities. Last month, after one such shooting death, Giuliani
released the sealed juvenile arrest record of the victim, Patrick
Dorismond, and insisted that he was not ``an altar boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Giuliani's poll numbers have plummeted. A Quinnipiac
College Polling Institute survey released Wednesday showed Giuliani
with 43 percent to Clinton's 46 percent. Early last month in the
same poll, Giuliani led Clinton 48 percent to 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a real problem,'' Lazio said. ``If you don't
acknowledge it's a problem, you're not dealing in reality. Some of
that (support) may well come back. But some of it might not.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani could have defended the police and shown sympathy for
concerns of the minority community as well as the victim's family,
he said. ``There is racial tension in New York, and if you want to
alleviate that, you've got to show some sensitivity to the way
people think.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has won an implicit nod from New York's Conservative
Party, whose candidates poll anywhere between 300,000 and 2 million
votes, and often make the difference between Republican electoral
success and failure.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, by contrast, has drawn the Conservatives' ire for not
backing efforts to outlaw late-term abortions and accepting the
endorsement of the state's Liberal Party.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lazio favors keeping abortion legal, he has voted in
the House to ban late-term abortions _ a measure ultimately vetoed
by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Lazio could be the right person,'' said Michael Long,
Conservative Party chairman. ``The ballgame is a wide-open
ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio insisted that although Election Day is seven months away
and he is way behind Giuliani in raising money, he stands the best
chance of beating Hillary Clinton. Republicans ``can either have
someone who can unify the party, who can draw soft Democrats and
independents, (and) who can bring the Conservative Party on board,
or they can go in another direction,'' he said. ``Before they go
down another path, I just would like them to think about what
they're buying into.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, for his part appeared unimpressed by Lazio's argument.
``I think he's just wrong,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
