<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8164 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-BOSNIA-RAPE-BOS &LR;      04-05 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-RAPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBUNAL HEARS VIVID TESTIMONY OF RAPES BY SERB SOLDIERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Note strong content thruout.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE _ She was a virtual slave, forced to do the housework
when she wasn't being raped, and so when she saw her captor, a Serb
soldier, come through the door wounded, his arm heavily bandaged,
for once she was thankful for the war and thought she would be left
alone for one, just one, night.
</P>
<P>
   But he raped her anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1992. She was 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about how an individual who had been wounded or
injured could do something like that,'' the woman, a Bosnian Muslim
and now 23, said Tuesday as she sat in the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   How anyone could do what is being alleged in Courtroom One at
the International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia is
almost beyond comprehension.
</P>
<P>
   But the charges, besides being sickening, stake out new ground
in international law. This is the first case in which rape and
sexual assault are the sole basis of a war crimes prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making history here, and it's about time,'' said
Patricia Sellers, the tribunal's legal adviser for sexual crimes.
``It's too late for all the women who were raped in war time. But
we are drawing a line here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sellers, 45, is a lawyer with a remarkably varied career that
has seen her work as a public defender in Philadelphia and a tax
attorney for the Price Waterhouse accounting firm. Now she has
orchestrated a precedent-setting case that aims to change the way
the civilized world regards rape in wartime.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first case in which prosecutors are arguing that
rape can be genocidal,'' said Sellers. ``We're trying to show the
war as sexual violence, that part of the attack on the civilian
population was sexual violence.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, 1992, the town of Foca, southeast of Sarajevo, was
overrun by Serb forces bent on ridding Bosnia of Muslims and
Croats. About half of its 40,000 residents were Muslim, the rest
Serb.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens, if not hundreds, of Muslim women were made sex slaves,
held in homes, apartments, hotels, and the local sports auditorium
and high school, to serve Serb soldiers, who returned from a day of
fighting to rape them. The men would line the women up and pick
them, as if for a pickup basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   A 12-year-old girl told investigators she was raped daily by
soldiers for months. A woman described how she lost her virginity
at 15 to a group of soldiers. One woman said she fainted when her
attackers bit her breasts bloody while raping her. Another said she
was gang raped by 15 soldiers for three hours. Still another said
she was raped by more than 20 soldiers after they had killed her
mother in front of her.
</P>
<P>
   One woman said a neigbhor raped her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was 20 years older, married,'' she testified. ``He laughed,
and I had the feeling he was doing it exactly because he knew me,
to cause me even more evil.''
</P>
<P>
   The women were forced at gunpoint to cook, clean, and do the
laundry when they weren't being raped. Soldiers sold them to others
for less than $100. Some women cried. Others tore their hair out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Muslims, we will show you!'' one soldier cried before
committing a rape.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Ryan, a lawyer with the Coalition for International
Justice, a private group that monitors the tribunal, said the case
is being watched closely around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a legal perspective, the significance here is that it is
the first time that a charge of enslavement has been made in which
sexual abuse was the focus,'' said Ryan, who next month will leave
The Hague for a stint at the John F. Kennedy School of Government
at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   ``To prove crimes against humanity, you have to prove that there
was an organized and systematic attack on a civilian population.
This is the first time that sexual assault has been used as the
basis of a systematic attack. . .''
</P>
<P>
   When she was the United States ambassador to Austria, Swanee
Hunt, director of the Women and Public Policy Program at the
Kennedy School, dispatched some of her staff to take statements
from rape victims in the Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statements I read made me sick to my stomach, and I have a
strong constitution,'' said Hunt, who has worked extensively in the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Armies have raped civilians throughout history, she said, but
rape was used differently in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The language that was used had a genocidal context,'' said
Hunt. ``Soldiers would say to Muslim women they raped, `Now you'll
have a Serb baby.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what is alleged in the indictment charging three
Serb soldiers, Radomir Kovac, 39, Dragoljub Kunarac, 39, and Zoran
Vukovic, 44, with crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   One woman who refused their advances was allegedly beaten and
dragged into a room at the Hotel Zelengora. After Kunarac and
Vukovic raped her, they said she would ``give birth to Serb
babies,'' she testified. Another woman said that after Kunarac and
two other soldiers raped her, Kunarac humiliated her by saying
``they would never know whose son this was.'' She said Kunarac took
her back to her apartment and robbed her of what little money and
jewelry she had hidden.
</P>
<P>
   It was Kunarac who allegedly raped the 15-year-old even after he
had been wounded in battle.
</P>
<P>
   Kovac is alleged to have sold a 12-year-old girl he was
routinely raping to another soldier for less than $100. Kovac
allegedly made the 12-year-old and other women disrobe and dance
naked for him on a table. Kovac allegedly sold two other women to
soldiers from Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Serb soldiers were heartless. Several women told
investigators of Serb soldiers who took pity on them and helped
them escape, often to Montenegro. After watching Kunarac allegedly
rape two women for six months, a Serb soldier who was disgusted by
his comrades took the women away to safety.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony that began two weeks ago is expected to go on for
another month, and there could be a verdict by the end of the year,
Sellers said. She said investigators are now in Kosovo, gathering
evidence for possibly similar charges there.
</P>
<P>
   War crimes investigators believe at least 20,000 women have been
raped in Balkan fighting over the last decade. Those telling their
stories at The Hague are the few and the brave.
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain poetic justice in the central role that women
are playing in this effort to hold men accountable for using rape
as an instrument of war. Sellers made the case happen. Two of the
three main prosecutors are women, as is the tribunal's chief
prosecutor. The presiding judge is Florence Mumba, a no-nonsense
jurist from Zambia.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the Bosnian Muslim women who, day-in day-out,
climb onto the witness stand and confront their demons, and their
alleged assailants.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old woman who said she was raped by Kunarac turned
to face him Tuesday afternoon. When asked by Peggy Kuo, the
prosecutor, to point out her attacker, the woman leveled her eyes,
and then her finger, at Kunarac.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Kuo asked her to say how often she had been raped.
</P>
<P>
   The woman paused, trying to recall all the times. Then she said,
more in resignation than anger, ``I don't think that is possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
