<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8176 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-STOCK06-COX     04-05 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-STOCK06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola shares fall 8% despite Daft's talk
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola shares fell $4.12 1/2, or 8 percent,
Wednesday on both short-term and long-term concerns about the
company's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic decline to $47.62 1/2 came only a day after
Chairman Doug Daft and other executives traveled to Wall Street to
explain their strategy to some 250 beverage analysts and money
managers.
</P>
<P>
   But the company got a sell-off instead of the buy-in it was
hoping for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect investors to restrain enthusiasm for KO (Coca-Cola's
stock ticket symbol) until actual evidence of volume and earnings
growth acceleration begins to materialize,'' analyst Marc Cohen of
Goldman, Sachs wrote Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Jennifer Solomon of Salomon Smith Barney on Wednesday
lowered her 12-month target to $60 a share, from $70, ``given the
disappointing first-quarter volume trends as well as the fact that
KO is now in a 'show me' situation,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The analysts were disappointed in Coca-Cola's announcement
Tuesday that its first-quarter volume, or case sales, will increase
about 3 percent worldwide, and only 1.5 percent excluding the
recent acquisition of Cadbury Schweppes brands in 161 nations
outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``KO's volume recovery is developing at a slower-than-expected
pace,'' Cohen wrote as he lowered his 2000 earnings estimate by 2
cents a share to $1.43.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to disappointing first-quarter case sales, analysts
also think the company is being overly ambitious with its long-term
growth targets.
</P>
<P>
   At this week's meeting, Daft said the company will be able to
produce long-term volume growth of 7 percent to 8 percent annually,
and earnings-per-share growth of about 15 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   But several analysts disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goals described by management ... continue to be
challenging in our view,'' Cohen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon agreed with Cohen. ``We think 12-14 percent EPS
(earnings per share) and 5-6 percent volume is more appropriate, ''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
