   &UR; THEATER &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HAYLEY-MILLS-THEATER (Undated) _ Given her theatrical pedigree,
Hayley Mills must be aware of more than a few show business maxims.
For example: try to avoid following a tough act, and, there is no
tougher act than a cute kid. But what happens when you're your own
toughest act to follow? In one way, Mills has already found out,
having worked on the London stage for the last 30 years. But in
this country she is still best known as that saucer-eyed little
girl in such popular Disney films as ``Pollyanna'' (for which she
won a special 1960 Academy Award), ``The Parent Trap'' (1961) and
``That Darn Cat'' (1965). If Mills has her way, her New York stage
debut will begin the third act of what has already been a long
career. The London-born actress, who turns 54 next week, opens
Monday at the Lucille Lortel Theater in ``Noel Coward's Suite in
Two Keys,'' an evening of two one-act plays directed by John
Tillinger. By Steven Drukman. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WILD-PARTY-THEATER (New York) _ In the summer of 1926, Joseph
Moncure March, something of a rebel at 26, sat down at a battered
kitchen table in his airless $20-a-month walkup on West 14th Street
in Manhattan to write a narrative in verse about ``a lot of people
getting drunk at a party,'' a subject he had come to know very
well. The result, ``The Wild Party,'' is, as almost everyone knows
by now, the source and title of two musicals this season: one, by
Andrew Lippa, ends its run this Sunday at the Manhattan Theater
Club at City Center; the other, co-produced by the Joseph Papp
Public Theater, is to open on Thursday at the Virginia Theater on
Broadway. With music and lyrics by Michael John LaChiusa and
directed by George C. Wolfe, it stars Mandy Patinkin, Toni Collette
and Eartha Kitt. By Maura Spiegel. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
