   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SULLIVAN-MUSIC (Undated) _ A look at Sir Arthur Sullivan's
music, expecially ``The Lost Chord,'' which was inspired by the new
music from France, with its murky chromatic harmony and langid
sensuality. By Anthony Tommasini. (Moved).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARLAND-WORLD-MUSIC-BOOK (Undated) _ The Garland World Music
Encyclopedia, a projected 10-volume series of telephone-book-size
reference works from Routledge started appearing in 1998. Six
volumes have been published; the two volumes just released, on
Europe and South Asia, are up to the level set by their
predecessors, on Africa, Southeast Asia, Australia and the Pacific
Islands and South America, Mexico, Central America and the
Caribbean. Don't spend too much time fussing here about the loaded
term ``world music.'' In this case it is not a naive stand-in for
``music that North Americans consider foreign''; it literally means
music made all over the world, including here. By Ben Ratliff.
(Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STIG-ANDERSEN-MUSIC (Houston) _ One last question for Stig
Andersen (the G is silent), the athletic tenor from Denmark.
Suppose singing had not worked out. What would he have done
instead? ``I am a ceramicist,'' he answers. ``I make pots. I like
to work against some resistance. I don't like clay that's too soft
or too weak. I have to have something to grab.'' This exchange took
place recently backstage at the Houston Grand Opera, where Andersen
was appearing in ``Tristan und Isolde.'' In jeans and a biker's
jacket, looking less tall but stouter in person than onstage, he
still seemed an exceptionally plausible physical match for Wagner's
Siegfried, the role that takes him to the Metropolitan Opera in
Manhattan for his house debut on Saturday afternoon. By Matthew
Gurewitsch. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHINESE-STOOLS-ART (New York) _ William Lipton remembers the
first time he saw Chinese stools. It was the late 1950s, and he was
5. A pair of barrel-shaped stools, in blue and white porcelain,
flanked the sofa in his grandmother's parlor in Dallas. Lipton has
no idea today what became of the stools, family heirlooms that were
trophies of a trip around the world made by a
great-great-grandfather in 1887. Then, on a first visit to China in
1979, when Lipton was a textile designer working for Jim Thompson
Ltd. in Bangkok, stools loomed large again. In Beijing he saw a
towering pile of weathered wood stools, with elegantly carved
aprons and legs, with hoof feet, scrolled feet and flat feet
protruding here and there from a stack that looked like a bizarre
offering to the gods of good taste. The memory of that scene stayed
with him. He became an antiques dealer in 1989, ultimately
specializing in Chinese furniture. Four years ago he began to
assemble as many examples of stools ``with personality'' as he
could find for a show on a form of furniture that is the most
humble and versatile of all in China but is rarely exhibited. He
selected 92 of them for ``The Wondrous and Amenable Chinese
Stool,'' an exhibition at his shop, William Lipton Ltd., in
Manhattan, through April 22. By Rita Reif. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OLSHER-RADIO-SHOW (New York) _ Most radio shows are as
predictable as sunrise. Dean Olsher 36, has decided to surprise
listeners by following his own fancy. Olsher, a former cultural
correspondent for National Public Radio, will be the host of ``The
Next Big Thing,'' a one-hour weekend program that will go on the
air this summer on WNYC. By Valerie Galdstone. (Moved). WITH
PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-MEN-COMEDIES (Undated) _ Men in a growing number of comedies
are depicted as rude, crude, sex-crazed, sexist, childish and
blindly egotistical. The curmudgeonly title character of ``Becker''
(Ted Danson), a middle-aged doctor, says things like: ``If you want
to know about women, you don't ask a woman. If you want to know
about meat, do you ask a cow?'' On ``Friends,'' Joey eats steak
with his fingers at Ross's wedding reception. Prime time gives us
grown men who can't stop giggling in church, bawdy male magazine
publishers married to women half their age and men who stick
Montblanc pens up their noses in order to meet women in the
emergency room. Anyone who watches television regularly could get
the impression that one of the two sexes on this planet is not only
dimwitted and uncouth but darned proud of it. By Anita Gates.
(Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
