<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-MORI-PROFILE-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S NEW PREMIER DESCRIBED AS ADEPT BUT INDECISIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With JAPAN-POLITICS) 
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In Nagatacho, Tokyo's political hub, Yoshiro Mori, who
was elected prime minister Wednesday, is often referred to as ``an
elephant with a flea's heart,'' a reference to his 220-pound frame
and what many of his critics say is his indecisiveness, especially
under fire.
</P>
<P>
   Mori, 62, has held several cabinet posts, including the trade
and education portfolios, and is considered an adept political
operator who has been in parliament for more than 30 years. Lately
he has played a pivotal role in keeping the Liberal Democratic
Party's coalition, one of the largest in decades, intact.
</P>
<P>
   He is also said to have especially warm relations with New
Komeito, a Buddhist-backed party whose strength is greater than the
Liberals, which recently splintered from the government coalition.
</P>
<P>
   What Mori does not have is experience in either the foreign or
finance ministries, two government powerhouses where several of his
predecessors have served.
</P>
<P>
   Those deficiencies, together with his reputation for blunt talk
that has got him in trouble in the past, have prompted some to
question whether he is little more than an interim leader until a
general election can be called.
</P>
<P>
   Mori's lack of broad experience may be an immediate handicap
given the fact that as the world's second-largest economic power,
Japan is in frequent contact with foreign officials and that it is
scheduled to be host at the annual summit meeting of the world's
leading economic powers in Okinawa in July. The meeting will
include Russia's new president, Vladimir Putin, whom Mori is now
expected to meet later this month, his first overseas trip as prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   But Mori's domestic policy views are not well known either. And
like many politicians of his generation, he has steadily climbed
the political ladder here by staying assiduously loyal to the
leadership of the dominant party, the Liberal Democrats, not by
staking out policy initiatives or specialties.
</P>
<P>
   When he has attracted attention it was usually for some misstep
like the time his blunt language or a flip remark got him into hot
water.
</P>
<P>
   In January, he apologized to AIDS patients after he likened them
to unwelcomed guests. ``When I visited a village, all farmers out
in the fields went home, as if AIDS had come in town,'' he was
reported to have said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, he angered many people in Okinawa by saying that
teachers there opposed the government's new policy of requiring the
national anthem at functions because they were ``controlled by
Communists'' and ``oppose everything the government does.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday night, Mori said that his
comments on Okinawans and AIDS patients were taken out of context.
</P>
<P>
   His career also has not been without scandal. In the late 1980s,
he was implicated in a major stocks-for-favor scandal known as
Recruit that illuminated the Liberal Democratic Party's history of
cronyism and corruption, and toppled Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita.
</P>
<P>
   Back then Mori admitted making more than $950,000 by selling
shares that he had acquired in a company before it went public. At
his first news conference Wednesday night as prime minister, Mori
seemed to brush aside the 11-year-old scandal and his role in it by
characterizing it as a ``regular business transaction,'' a remark
that struck some as a sweeping oversimplification and dangerously
cavalier.
</P>
<P>
   Before being named prime minister, Mori, a former college rugby
player, held the Liberal Democratic Party's No. 2 position as
secretary-general and was a close ally of his longtime friend
Obuchi, whom he met on the college debate team.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
