<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-MORI-PROFILE-2N     04-05 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-MORI-PROFILE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TOKYO: debate team.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``When continuity is most important, you need someone like Mori
who is colorless and can fit into any kind of mold,'' said Yukio
Okamoto, a political consultant. ``Because he is not biased in his
ideology and political beliefs, he can change according to the
situation. He was a safe bet because he epitomizes middle of the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   While members of Mori's party praised his selection as prime
minister, some opposition party legislators ridiculed it.
</P>
<P>
   Hiroshi Kawauchi, a lawmaker belonging to the Democratic Party,
which is not part of the Mori's coalition, said, ``I think he's
better suited to be a sumo wrestling stable master than prime
minister of a country.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference Mori clearly signaled that he would make
no major changes. He offered no new policy agenda but vowed to
continue Obuchi's economic plan. He also retained Obuchi's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will aim to achieve a government that would walk with the
people and is trusted by the people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he had no immediate plans to call elections,
despite the rumors Wednesday that the party was considering moving
them up to take advantage of public sympathy over Obuchi's massive
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Mori was born on July 14, 1937, to a family of middle-class rice
farmers in Neagari, a rural town in Ishikawa Prefecture on the
coast of the Sea of Japan. Politics ran in the family, and both
Mori's father and grandfather served as mayor of Neagari.
</P>
<P>
   Mori graduated from prestigious Waseda University where he
majored in commerce and pursued his boyhood passion for rugby. But
an illness forced him to give up the sport, and on a whim he joined
the debating club where he met Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
   After working briefly as a newspaper reporter in the early
1960s, Mori started his political career as secretary to a Lower
House member and was first elected to the Diet in 1969 at age 32.
He has been re-elected to that seat nine times. Mori was named to
his first cabinet post as education minister in 1983, followed by
an appointment as trade minister in 1992. When Obuchi became prime
minister in 1998, Mori assumed the party's second-ranking job. Mori
and his wife, Chieko, have a daughter and son.
</P>
<P>
   Junzo Nishino, who played rugby with Mori when the two were in
high school, dismissed criticism that his former teammate lacked
the leadership skills for the prime ministership.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very considerate and compassionate man,'' Nishino said.
``Whenever we wanted to exclude some boys from the game, Mori-san
would always say, `No, let's give him a chance to train harder and
improve his ability.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(JT)
</P>
</TEXT>
