<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER WORKS TO ARRANGE MIAMI VISIT BY CUBAN BOY'S FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ As talks between federal officials and lawyers
representing the Miami relatives of Elian Gonzalez were put on hold
until Thursday, the US lawyer representing the boy's father spent
the day in Cuba scrambling to arrange Juan Miguel Gonzalez's
immediate visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The father's lawyer, Gregory Craig, spent most of Wednesday in
Havana before flying back to Washington Wednesday night.
Accompanied by members of the US Council of Churches and
representatives from the Methodist Church, he reportedly met with
Juan Gonzalez and top members of the Cuban government in hopes of
persuading the father to travel to the US as soon as &UR;  &LR; possible to
reunite with his 6-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   But there appeared to be two main sticking points in the
discussions: when Gonzalez would travel to Washington, and who
would accompany him.
</P>
<P>
   The US Interests Section in Havana handed over six visas on
Tuesday for Gonzalez, his wife, another son, a young cousin,
Elian's kindergarten teacher and a pediatrician. But Gonzalez, 31,
and the Cuban government have requested visas for a 28-member
delegation, including several of Elian's classmates and Ricardo
Alarcon, president of Cuba's National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has said that he would be willing to come with a
smaller group, or even by himself, if he could take Elian back to
Cuba immediately. But he wants the larger group to be with him if
he has to stay in the US while Elian's case is decided by a federal
appeals court in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, no additional visas had been approved, a
Havana-based US official said, adding that there had been no formal
contact with Craig during his visit.
</P>
<P>
   Craig left Havana for Washington late in the afternoon without
issuing any statement about his talks. And there was no official
word Wednesday from the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the secrecy of Wednesday's negotiations, the drama
surrounding the young boy, who survived a shipwreck off the Florida
coast last November, continued to galvanize the residents of this
Caribbean country of 12 million people. Dozens of billboards around
Havana depict a larger-than-life painting of the boy with the
words, ``Return our Elian to us.''
</P>
<P>
   State-run Cuban television and the official newspaper, Granma,
argue that Elian has been ``kidnapped'' by anti-Castro Cuban
Americans in Miami, a group often referred to here as ``la mafia.''
</P>
<P>
   At the closing ceremony of a convention for Latin American
college students, held at the Karl Marx Theater, Cuban President
Fidel Castro joined in the ovations as a litany of student speakers
denounced the Cuban-American community protecting Elian and
demanded the boy's immediate return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are lying to everyone, to the public, to us and to
Elian,'' said one student from the eastern Cuban city of Santiago,
referring to Elian's Miami relatives. ``It's time to stop the lies
and let our Elian come home where he belongs.''
</P>
<P>
   A few miles away, at a triangle in front of the US diplomatic
mission in Havana along the Malecon, the city's famous shoreline
drive, where Cubans have regularly held protests for Elian's
return, government workers put finishing touches on the new Plaza
de la Dignidad, a football-field-length outdoor stage with
state-of-the-art spotlights and hundreds of new, black chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a coincidence that this was built here, in front of
the office where the Americans work,'' said Rodolfo Santos, 27,
lives just a few blocks from the new stage. ``It was built because
of Elian and it's a symbol of how serious we are about getting him
back.''
</P>
<P>
   But for others, the $2 million spent to build the stage could
have been used for something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not more food or better houses?'' asked one man who walked
along the stage and refused to give his name. ``That would be a
better example why we believe Elian would be better off here than
in Miami.''
</P>
</TEXT>
