<SLUG> BC-HERMAN-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR SECRETARY CLEARED IN FUND-RAISING PROBE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Labor Secretary Alexis Herman was cleared Wednesday
of any wrongdoing by an independent counsel who spent 23 months
investigating allegations that she was involved in illegal
fund-raising and influence-peddling while working at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by Independent Counsel Ralph Lancaster that
Herman faces no criminal charges also signals that his inquiry will
end. Charges were filed against only one person, a Singapore
businessman accused of illegally donating $200,000 to the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Herman is the third Clinton Cabinet member cleared of wrongdoing
after lengthy, multi-million dollar investigations by a variety of
independent counsels. One other _ former Housing Secretary Henry
Cisneros _ pleaded guilty to perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Lancaster investigated allegations that Herman solicited the
illegal campaign contributions through two friends and engaged in a
kickback scheme when she was a White House aide during President
Clinton's first term in office.
</P>
<P>
   The two friends, Vanessa and Caryliss Weaver, have been notified
by Lancaster's office that they would not be prosecuted, their
attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was pleased by Lancaster's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I said at the start of this inquiry nearly two years ago,
Secretary Herman did nothing wrong,'' the president said. ``She did
not deserve what she has had to endure over the past many months.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the Herman investigation, the president _ who was
impeached in a separate, 5{-year, $52 million inquiry that has yet
to end _ was interviewed under oath by Lancaster and two of his
deputies in September 1999.
</P>
<P>
   After Lancaster announced that he would seek no indictment
against her, Herman said she was ``gratified personally and for my
family that the independent counsel has terminated his
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Her attorney, W. Neil Eggleston, said he was pleased.
``Secretary Herman cooperated with (the independent counsel) in
every way possible, and we always believed that he would conclude
that she had engaged in no wrongdoing,'' Eggleston said.
</P>
<P>
   Lancaster's investigation of Herman centered on allegations by
Cameroon-born businessman Laurent Yene that he delivered an
envelope of cash to Herman's home. The money, Yene said, was
Herman's share, or 10 percent, of a consulting fee he earned from a
Singapore businessman, Abdul Rahman, while seeking a federal
license for a satellite telephone system.
</P>
<P>
   Yene said Herman earned her share by using her influence to aid
clients of a consulting business he partly owned with Vanessa
Weaver.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver had purchased the company from Herman in 1993 when Herman
took a job running the White House Office of Public Liaison. Yene
subsequently joined the consulting business as co-owner.
</P>
<P>
   Yene and Vanessa Weaver worked with Rahman to obtain a license
from the Federal Communication Commission, eventually awarded in
1997. Yene and Weaver ended their business relationship in the
mid-1990s, and Rahman hired another Weaver firm in Sept. 1996. A
month later, according to federal records, she and her sister
Caryliss gave $150,000 to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Yene accused Herman of soliciting the money from Rahman, who
could not legally make political contributions as a non-U.S.
citizen. Rahman was introduced to Herman by Vanessa Weaver on one
or two occasions and to Clinton during his 1996 re-election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 16, Rahman was indicted by a federal grand jury on
charges of making $200,000 in illegal contributions to the
Democratic National Committee and four state party organizations in
1996. As a foreigner, Rahman is barred from making donations to
political candidates or political parties. The indictment said
Rahman made 11 donations under the Weaver sisters's names.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecution of Rahman is considered unlikely unless he returns
to the United States and is arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation was begun in May 1998 when Attorney General
Janet Reno, against the advice of her staff, decided that financial
records ``might possibly'' support Yene's allegations and an
independent examination was needed. A five-month inquiry by the
Justice Department had found no evidence that Herman had committed
a crime.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lancaster, a lawyer from Portland, Maine, was the last special
prosecutor appointed under a now-defunct law that required
government-funded, independent investigations of credible
allegations of wrongdoing by top-ranking administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   Of the five investigations of Clinton's Cabinet members, only
one resulted in a conviction. Former Housing Secretary Henry
Cisneros pleaded guilty Sept. 7, 1999, to lying under oath to the
FBI about secret payments to his former mistress. Cisneros, who was
the target of a four-year, $12 million independent counsel probe,
was ordered to pay a $10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   An 18-month, $5.6 million investigation of Interior Secretary
Bruce Babbitt ended with no indictments. An effort to begin an
investigation into Commerce Secretary Ronald H. Brown ended when he
died in an airplane crash four years ago. Former Agriculture
Secretary Mike Espy was tried and acquitted on corruption charges
after a four-year, $22 million investigation.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
