<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIOCESE-ABORTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHDIOCESE TO WELCOME WOMEN WHO HAD ABORTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Archdiocese of Boston, known for its staunch
opposition to abortion rights, next month will launch its largest
effort yet to encourage women who have had abortions to return to
the church.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the outreach effort broader than anything previously
attempted here, but it is also the first that does not specifically
target Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will feature radio advertisements on five FM radio
stations popular among female listeners, and also may include a
newspaper advertising insert. The ads will urge women who have had
abortions to call an archdiocesan office that will refer them to
clerical or psychological counseling or other services.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, according to archdiocesan officials, is to offer
assistance to women from any religious background and to inform
Catholic women who have left the church that it wants them back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is that many of the people who would
benefit from help after an abortion are not in church, because they
think that the church doesn't welcome them, or that they don't
belong there,'' said Barbara Thorp, director of the pro-life
activities office for the archdiocese. ``They're afraid to go to
church because of shame, and the only way we can reach them is
through the secular means of advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church in the United States has had a 15-year
effort to reach out to women who have had abortions through a
program called Project Rachel, which has been publicized through
church bulletins and on occasion with small radio buys. But this
year the National Conference of Catholic Bishops is encouraging
dioceses to expand their efforts in the spirit of reconciliation,
which is one of the themes Pope John Paul II has declared for this
Jubilee Year in which the church is celebrating its 2,000th
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign was conceived by the bishops conference and has
aired in Maryland, Virginia, and Washington, D.C., where it was
combined with billboards and bus and subway placards. Officials say
the number of women calling for help skyrocketed, in Washington
from eight calls per week to 150.
</P>
<P>
   The radio ads do not mention the Catholic Church, and an
estimated 50 percent of the women who responded to the ads in the
Washington area were not Catholic, officials said. Those women were
referred clergy of their own faith or with lay counselors.
</P>
<P>
   ``To us this is part and parcel of a complete and consistent
pro-life voice that says everybody's life is uniquely valuable,''
said Helen Alvare, spokeswoman for the Secretariat for Pro-Life
Activities of the bishops conference. ``Just as the church reaches
out to anyone with uniquely difficult suffering, we reach out in
this case as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The 60-second radio ads, which carry the tagline, ``Something
insides dies after an abortion,'' are composed of lines uttered by
women who have had abortions. In one spot, women speak of feeling
pressured by boyfriends or parents to have an abortion; in others,
women speak of a lack of support for the grieving they feel.
</P>
<P>
   The ads urge women to call a number for Project Rachel, which is
named after a verse in Jeremiah describing a woman mourning the
death of her children.
</P>
<P>
   The ads are being viewed with some skepticism by officials at
the Planned Parenthood Federation of America, a family planning
organization that performs abortions. The officials said they are
concerned that the church is exaggerating the number of women who
suffer long-term emotional trauma from abortion and that church
counselors may criticize women for their choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe that an organization which teaches that
abortion is a mortal sin is appropriate for unbiased and healthy
counseling,'' said Virginia Martin, an executive vice president of
Planned Parenthood of Metropolitan Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Michelle Ringuette, spokeswoman for Planned
Parenthood League of Massachusetts, was less critical, saying, ``A
very small number of women experience extreme distress after the
procedure _ what we mostly see is relief.'' She added that ``if
women need this, they should be able to access it, and Project
Rachel is a valid place for people to contact if they have
emotional distress.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Boston nor Washington affiliates have received any
complaints from women who have been counseled through Project
Rachel, agency officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Two women who were counseled by Project Rachel, who agreed to
talk to the Globe at the request of the church program but asked
that their names not be published, spoke positively of their
experiences. Both women had attended retreats with other women who
had had abortions to talk about their experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an abortion about 17 years ago, and had pretty much
dismissed it, but whenever I went into a church I found myself
filling up with tears,'' said a 46-year-old businesswoman. ``I
needed to make peace. Project Rachel referred me to a priest, and
he so lovingly took me through the process of talking about all the
upsets I had about the church, without any recrimination or
judgment. I felt such peace coming home.''
</P>
<P>
   A 50-year-old woman who had been active in pro-life causes
before having an abortion said she had struggled for years to come
to grips with the emotional impact of the procedure before finally
calling for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call abortion the silent sin, because people go out and talk
about how they've had affairs or whatever, but this is not
something that you can talk about,'' she said. ``But when I finally
went in, I was made to feel so welcome that all my fears left me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church, which considers abortion to be the taking
of a human life, places abortion among the most serious category of
transgressions, called mortal sins. Abortion is termed
intrinsically evil by the church, and until they are formally
absolved by a priest, women who have had abortions are considered
to be outside of the communion of the church, which makes them
ineligible to receive the sacrament of the Eucharist.
</P>
<P>
   When Project Rachel began in Boston in 1986, it referred women
seeking absolution to one of a select group of priests who had been
specially trained to work with women who had had abortions. This
year, in honor of the Jubilee, Boston's Cardinal Bernard Law has
permitted any priest to perform such absolution, and every priest
has been given training materials on working with such women.
</P>
<P>
   To receive absolution, a woman must attend confession, admit
sorrow for sin, and receive mercy, which is acknowledged when the
priest recites a specific prayer of absolution.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials say they do not condemn the women who call
them, do not force them to talk to clergy, and do not urge them to
rejoin the church, but instead try to convince them that God
forgives them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never would be judgmental because they'd walk right out
the door,'' said the Rev. Jerome F. Gillespie, who has counseled
many women who have had abortions. ``They're still a very good
person who made a tremendous mistake and a misjudgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie said there is no conflict between the church's
antiabortion stance and its effort to reconcile with women who have
had abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, the church has to keep doing what she
believes in: to preach against abortion, which we believe is a
great evil and sin,'' he said. ``On the other hand, we believe that
there is a God who is very merciful and compassionate, and we
believe in forgiveness. No sin we commit is greater than God's
love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
