<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARBINGER06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harbinger to be sold for $2.1 billion
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Harbinger, one of Atlanta's early software companies,
will be acquired by San Diego-based Peregrine Systems in a stock
swap valued at $2.1 billion. The deal was announced after the
market closed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Harbinger looked at a number of ways to reach its target of
being a major player in the rapidly growing field of
business-to-business electronic commerce and decided the best path
was a merger with Peregrine Systems, said James M. Travers,
Harbinger's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies complement each other, he said, with Harbinger
providing the software for business-to-business commerce over the
Internet, and Peregrine Systems with software to manage computer
systems and communications, facilities and transportation assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this was the best long-term way of creating
shareholder value,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, which has been in the works for about 60 days,
Harbinger shareholders will get three-fourths of a share of
Peregrine Systems for each share of Harbinger they own. Based on
Wednesday's close for Peregrine Systems _ $58 _ the deal values
Harbinger shares at $43.50 each. That's 80 percent above
Harbinger's close of $24.12 1/2 and well above the 52-week high of
$39.87 1/2 hit in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   Travers said the companies expect to close the deal in the
second quarter. It is subject to regulatory and shareholder
approvals.
</P>
<P>
   Headquarters for the merged companies will remain in San Diego,
but Travers expects a ``significant management presence'' to remain
in Atlanta and little impact on employees.
</P>
<P>
   Harbinger, with headquarters in Atlanta, has about 1,100
employees worldwide, including 350 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Peregrine Systems has about 1,500 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
