 UNDATED: the rebels.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONGO: Creating a Wasteland
</P>
<P>
   There is no U.N. embargo on diamonds from Congo or Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Hunger for looted diamonds is a major reason why six outside
states have sent soldiers into Congo, formerly Zaire. Angola,
Namibia and Zimbabwe have dispatched troops to protect the
government of President Laurent Kabila, while Burundi, Rwanda and
Uganda have sent soldiers to assist rebels seeking to overthrow
him.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, they have succeeded in shattering much of the
economy of eastern Congo, and transforming Kisangani, the major
city of eastern Congo, into a gaudy and ghostly ruin.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The streets of Kisangani are nearly empty of cars. The textile
plant is closed and the once-thriving port on the Congo River is
quiet. Apart from spotty electricity from a hydroelectric dam,
there are hardly any public services left. Public salaries go
unpaid. Prices have soared.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The only businesses that seem alive are those buying diamonds
from diggers coming in from the dense forest that encircles
Kisangani. To catch their eye, storefronts have been dressed in
garish paint that shouts the names of diamond buyers like Mr. Cash,
Jihad the King of Diamonds and Jehovah Ire, run by one Papa Samuel,
``in connection with Jesus Christ.'' One store is painted with an
image of the Sylvester Stallone movie character Rambo, his machine
gun replaced with a shovel.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the diamond shops, it is possible to see hundreds of
thousands of dollars worth of stones. Shop owners say the diamonds
are often flown out of Congo to Rwanda or Uganda, as commanders
from those countries reward themselves for their revolutionary
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think is the reason for this war?'' asked a
diamond buyer named Papa Ben, who plies his trade in Kisangani.
``It's only about the riches of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Only about a third of Congo's annual diamond production is being
sold through the country's official market, according to diamond
experts in Antwerp, Belgium. They say the rest is being smuggled
away for sale in bordering countries.
</P>
<P>
   By far the biggest diamond prize in the Congo is more than 1,000
miles to the southwest of Kisangani, near the city of Mbuji Mayi.
Diamond experts say Kabila has allocated a substantial percentage
of that huge diamond complex to Zimbabwe, which has dispatched
11,000 troops to prop up Kabila's wobbly regime.
</P>
<P>
   So Zimbabwe has recently become a major diamond exporter,
although it has a negligible local industry.
</P>
<P>
   With their eyes on the prize at Mbuji Mayi, large numbers of
Congolese rebels and supporting troops from Rwanda began massing
about a year ago to the north and east of the city. If they take
the diamond mines there, many military analysts believe, Zimbabwe
would lose its will to fight and Kabila's regime would probably
fall.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA LEONE: Allying With Smugglers
</P>
<P>
   In Freetown, the capital of Sierra Leone, the surgeons were
frantic. Scores of men, women and children, their hands partially
chopped off by machetes, had flooded the main hospital. Amputating
as quickly as they could, doctors tossed severed hands into a
communal bucket.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolutionary United Front, a rebel outfit that barters
diamonds for weapons, was trying early last year to conquer
Freetown. Chopping off limbs was their trademark strategy, as it
greatly simplified conquest in the diamond fields of eastern Sierra
Leone. When word got out that rebels were moving in, tens of
thousands of terrified people would take off. The rebels chased
half the country's population of 4.5 million out of their homes in
the 1990s. Half a million people fled the country.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One day during last year's carnage in Freetown, a diamond trader
approached a reporter at the Cape Sierra Hotel. He stuck out his
tongue and from beneath it plucked out a stone, which he offered to
sell. When no sale took place, the trader popped the diamond back
in his mouth and moved on.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Most of Sierra Leone's diamonds were _ and still are _ smuggled
into neighboring Liberia for sale, according to several human
rights groups and diamond industry experts.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the Sierra Leone rebels, Foday Sankoh, has
established a lucrative partnership with his longtime Liberian
friend, Charles Taylor, the rebel-boss-turned-president. Both had
training in Libya, both their rebellions began in the late 1980s,
and their armies have helped each other fight.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh's access to the world's diamond bourses and to arms was
secured when Taylor was elected president of Liberia in 1997.
Sankoh and the Liberian government deny this trade.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of diplomats, international relief officials and
mining experts say there is persuasive evidence. Liberia was a
marginal exporter of diamonds until the mid-1990s. Since then it
has it exported some 31 million carats _ more than 200 years worth
of its own national capacity, according to trading records in
Antwerp.
</P>
<P>
   After Sankoh failed to take Freetown last year, he signed a
peace deal granting his rebels amnesty for war crimes. The deal,
which was brokered by the United Nations, also gave him a
government job _ chairman of the Strategic Minerals Commission,
which controls diamond mining.
</P>
<P>
   (PHOTO DESCRIPTIONS: NYT1 _ a jeweler looks at the final product
in a New York City. NYT2 _ a diamond miner shows some of the fruits
of his labor from a mine deep in the jungle. NYT3 _ a diamond
dealer's sign outside a shop in Kisangani, Congo. NYT4 _ miners use
picks and shovels to dig to the gravel layer where diamonds are
found.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
