<HEADER>
A8202 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCFOOT-LADN-(SLAN     04-05 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCFOOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
 
McCANN GETS QB CALL FOR UCLA _ FOR NOW 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Last spring, UCLA had five quarterbacks and no
starter. This spring, the Bruins, who began practice Tuesday, are
down to three quarterbacks . . . and, again, no starter.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, they have a temporary starter, sophomore Ryan McCann, and
they definitely have a third-stringer, junior Scott McEwan.
However, because of a shoulder injury to sophomore Cory Paus, who
cannot participate in contract drills this month, coach Bob Toledo
won't name an opening-day starter until training camp in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't be fair to Cory,'' Toledo said. ``He was the
starter for most of the games last year and then he got hurt. When
he comes back healthy and can compete in the fall, that's when
we'll make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Paus broke his left (nonthrowing) collarbone Nov. 13 against
Washington. On Jan. 18, he had surgery to tighten the capsule in
his left shoulder, a condition that's plagued him since high
school. The combination of the broken bone and the offseason
surgery prevented Paus from throwing for four months.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Paus is involved in all the meetings, film sessions and
passing drills this month, though he cannot participate in the
contact drills and scrimmages that are essential to quarterback
evaluation. He expects to be ready for training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't able to do anything when it comes to being a better
quarterback,'' Paus said after Tuesday's practice. ``But I feel
really good. I thought I'd be a lot more rusty. . . . I thought I'd
look like a high school quarterback. My accuracy was a little off,
but I didn't lose too much arm strength. I haven't thrown at a
moving target for four months.''
</P>
<P>
   McEwan will be the second-stringer during contact drills. Drew
Bennett, who started opening day last season, is a full-time
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   McCann, who completed 17 of 29 passes against USC in his only
start, did not play baseball this spring in order to focus on
football. One of the hardest workers on the team, he organized the
7-on-7 passing drills (receivers and running backs against
linebackers and defensive backs), and he spent two hours each day
studying film and the playbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see an opportunity and I'm trying to take advantage of it,''
said McCann, who is from Westlake. ``I can honestly say that now I
know what everybody does on every play. That's come from the 7-on-7
drills and studying the playbook. Now I have to apply it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Position changes: The most noteworthy changes involve three
starters on the offensive line. Tackle Brian Polak has moved to
guard, his natural position. Guard Mike Saffer has moved to tackle,
and tackle Blake Worley has moved to guard. Polak and Saffer are
expected to start.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Santi Hall has moved to outside linebacker, where
he'll compete with Tony White for the starting job. Defensive
tackle Steve Sanchez, a redshirt freshman, has moved to center,
where he'll relieve starter Troy Danoff. Reserve linebackers Ed
Stansbury and Chris Jackson have moved to fullback, where the
Bruins must replace Durell Price. Reserve cornerback Paul Nelson
has moved to receiver, his primary position in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was combination of a couple players asking for the changes
and us deciding on a couple guys,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury update: Several players aren't available this spring,
including Polak (offseason knee surgery), Danoff (knee surgery),
reserve cornerback Joe Hunter (knee surgery) and reserve offensive
tackle Josh Webb (shoulder surgery).
</P>
<P>
   __ Roster update: Junior wide receiver Freddie Mitchell won't
participate in spring practice because he's playing baseball _ and
hitting .286 through nine games.
</P>
</TEXT>
