u w BC-DRUG-PRICES-NYT     04-05 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-PRICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG PRICE ISSUE CATCHING FIRE IN SENATE
</HEADLINE>
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Republican senator said Wednesday that he was
drafting legislation to reduce price disparities that force
consumers to pay much more for prescription drugs in the United
States than in Canada or Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The senator, Slade Gorton of Washington state, who is running
for re-election, said that drug companies had become ``the new
health care villains,'' and that consumers were being ``ripped
off'' by their pricing practices.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton's comments, echoing concerns expressed repeatedly by
President Clinton and other Democrats in the last two years,
suggested that the two parties might be able to find common ground
on the issue this year. The comments alarmed drug companies, which
adamantly oppose government restrictions on their prices.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton's remarks _ and a vote in the Senate Wednesday on a
related question _ were the clearest signs to date that some
Republicans had begun to focus on drug prices as a potent political
issue. The Senate vote came on a Democratic proposal that would
have forced lawmakers to create new Medicare drug benefits before
they could cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 51-49 in favor of the proposal. But the proposal
failed because 60 votes were needed. Although Gorton voted no, six
other Republicans, including four facing the voters this year,
joined all 45 Democrats in supporting the measure.
</P>
<P>
   A drug company lobbyist said the industry's main trade
association, the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of
America, was ``in a panic'' because of Gorton's initiative. In an
interview, Gorton said the drug companies were so distressed ``they
have gone into orbit.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton has not yet introduced his bill, but drug companies are
frantically trying to dissuade other senators from signing up as
co-sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton said he met last week with the president of the drug
manufacturers organization, Alan F. Holmer, and with
representatives from most of the big drug companies to find out
``why Americans pay more than people in Canada or Mexico for the
same exact drug.''
</P>
<P>
   In setting drug prices, Gorton said, drug companies discriminate
against Americans and force them to pay most of the costs of
research to discover and develop drugs sold around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Unless drug companies come up with a solution of their own,
Gorton said, he will introduce legislation this month to prohibit
drug makers from charging higher wholesale prices in the United
States than in Canada or Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech on the Senate floor and in an interview Wednesday,
Gorton, a former attorney general of Washington, said he was not
telling drug companies what prices they had to charge. Rather, he
explained, ``I am simply saying that manufacturers can no longer
discriminate against American consumers by charging Canadian and
Mexican pharmacies lower prices than they charge Americans for the
same product.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton said that ``several Republican senators have committed to
supporting my idea,'' and that the majority leader, Trent Lott, has
``expressed interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton said his constituents often went to Canada to buy cheaper
drugs. ``I was astounded to learn that for the top 10 most commonly
prescribed drugs,'' he said, ``average prices are 64 percent lower
in Canada than in Washington state. That is outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Another border-state Congressman, Bernard Sanders of Vermont,
has made a similar point many times. But Sanders is a Democratic
socialist. Gorton is a loyal Republican who voted with a majority
of his party on 92 percent of last year's recorded votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a mainstream Republican to sponsor a raw price control
bill is troubling,'' Glaxo Wellcome said in ``talking points'' sent
to Senate offices.
</P>
<P>
   In a memorandum sent to one Senate office, Elizabeth Beavin, a
lobbyist for Glaxo Wellcome, said: ``No matter what Senator Gorton
is calling this proposal, it's plain and simple a price control
bill. The result would be disastrous for American consumers, our
industry and research everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton insisted that his bill would not impose price controls.
But he said it would put pressure on Canada and Mexico to let drug
companies charge higher prices, so consumers there would eventually
``pay their fair share of research and development costs.'' Then,
he said, residents of the United States would pay lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton said Americans felt ``ripped off'' under the current
system. The victims, he said, include ``40 million Americans who
are uninsured and those seniors without drug benefits who pay
higher prices at the drugstore cash register than just about anyone
else'' in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of their pricing policies,'' Gorton said, ``the drug
companies have become the new health care villains. In my state, I
hear constantly from constituents who rail against the drug
companies for charging them hundreds of dollars more than what they
would pay in Canada.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Holmer said Canadians were getting ``a free ride,'' receiving
the benefits of research done by drug companies based in the United
States without bearing an appropriate share of the costs. Holmer,
an international trade lawyer, said the United States should use
its leverage in trade negotiations to challenge this practice.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is considering a budget blueprint that could set
aside up to $40 billion for Medicare drug benefits over the next
five years. Democrats wanted to add language saying the Senate
could not take up tax-cutting legislation unless Congress had first
approved such drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Republicans who supported the Democratic proposal are
four senators who face the voters this fall: Spencer Abraham of
Michigan, Conrad Burns of Montana, Lincoln Chafee of Rhode Island
and Mike DeWine of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The other Republicans voting ``yes'' were Sens Peter Fitzgerald
of Illinois and Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   (rk)
</P>
</TEXT>
