<HEADLINE>
ABERCROMBIE BIG HIT IN MATADORS' CAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A leaner, quicker Cos Abercrombie is the hit of
the Cal State Northridge football team's spring camp. Especially
since he's making so many.
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie is making a strong transition from middle to outside
linebacker. He's lost eight pounds since last season _ ``a lot of
stomach weight,'' he said _ and he now carries 220 pounds on his
6-foot-1 frame.
</P>
<P>
   And despite having the flu, Abercrombie was one of the quickest
defenders in a team scrimmage on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think (Abercrombie)'s playing to (our) expectations,'' said
CSUN linebackers coach Terrance Johnson. ``He's dedicated the
offseason to getting in shape. He's dedicated himself in the weight
room.''
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie said he was not happy with the way he played last
year. He was fifth on the team in tackles, with 51, but as soon as
the season ended, he made lifestyle changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I didn't play to my full potential,'' said
Abercrombie, who will be a junior. ``My mind wasn't there. I
changed my whole attitude. I went on a diet. I stopped eating fast
food. . . . I played a lot of basketball over the winter, which
helped with my footwork.''
</P>
<P>
   The CSUN coaches hope Abercrombie's commitment is similar to
that of Brennen Swanson, a two-time All-Big Sky first-team
selection. Swanson, a pass-rushing linebacker, became the team's
defensive MVP as a junior.
</P>
<P>
   __ Immediate help: The football program signed 15 high school
recruits in 1999 but has only signed nine this year.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin said the decrease is a direct effect of the school's
decision to jump from the Big Sky Conference to the Big West _
which forces the Division I-AA football team to go independent in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Big Sky gets an automatic bid to the Division
I-AA playoffs, but independents are forced to compete for at-large
spots. Kearin said the Matadors needed good, experienced players
rather than relying on incoming freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to win now,'' Kearin said. ``We had huge holes to
fill on the offensive and defensive lines. We needed some good
players, right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Midsemester transfers Ramsey Venner (Fresno State), Jason
Nicastro (Chaffey College) and Andrew Holt (Idaho) are all in
spring camp. Venner and Nicastro are defensive linemen and Holt is
an offensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   __ New coach: Junior Thurman is the Matadors' new
defensive-backs coach, replacing Brent Huff. Thurman's most recent
experience was in the Canadian Football League as a guest coach
with the Calgary Stampeders.
</P>
<P>
   Thurman, 35, played at USC from 1984-86, and CSUN defensive
coordinator Foster Andersen was his position coach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 2044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
