<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETS RELATIVELY CALM AS DOW ENDS LOWER AND NASDAQ UP SLIGHTLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also STOCKS-MARKETPLACE, MARKET-TRADERS, MARKET-GREENSPAN) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices bounced around again Wednesday, but the
markets calmed considerably from Tuesday's steep, violent swings
and record volume, conditions that at times verged on the
disorderly.
</P>
<P>
   Major gauges ended mixed as activity subsided, with many
investors stepping back to assess damage and to await earnings
reports for the first quarter and the government's survey of the
job market in March, due Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had such turbulence that some investors are simply
exhausted,'' said Hugh Johnson, investment strategist at First
Albany Corp. Tuesday's relentless selling, mostly by institutions,
followed by bargain-hunting that erased most of the losses, gave
way to a to-and-fro market of lesser, but still substantial,
swings.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite, for example, pulled out of an early 3.4
percent decline and boasted a 3.3 percent gain by mid-afternoon,
only to slip back and finish with a modest advance of 20.33 points,
or 0.49 percent, at 4,169.22. It was just the second advance in the
last eight trading days.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which was ahead in early
trading, finished 130.92 points, or 1.17 percent, lower, at
11,033.92. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 7.36 points,
to 1,487.37.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many recent sessions, when stocks seemed to gyrate with
every political or expert whisper, the market largely ignored the
appearance, at a White House conference, of two of the chief
influences of recent years: Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve
chairman, and Abby Joseph Cohen, the strategist at Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said once again that monetary policy is not aimed at
lowering stock prices and Cohen said she remained bullish.
</P>
<P>
   But biotech companies benefited from President Clinton's
statement that they should be able to patent privately financed
gene discoveries. A joint declaration on that subject with British
Prime Minister Tony Blair, either misworded or misinterpreted, was
a big factor in starting Nasdaq's spring swoon, which has chopped
17.4 points off the Nasdaq index since its March 10 peak, a loss
that was almost 28 percent at its low point Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's action was a combination of bargain hunting,
covering of short positions and cashing in of profits, said Ken
Sheinberg, head of listed trading at S.G. Cowen, adding that
traders tended to avoid big exposure when news with such
market-moving potential as the monthly labor market report is
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices were steady as Greenspan's comments assured the
market that the Fed would maintain its policy of raising interest
rates to prevent inflation. The price of the Treasury's benchmark
30-year bond fell 5/32, to 106 22/32, while the yield, which moves
in the opposite direction from price, was 5.78 percent, up from
5.77 percent Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest drag on the Dow, 24 of whose 30 components declined,
was Coke, which stumbled 4}, to 47|, after saying that global case
sales will trail estimates. It was followed by Intel, Exxon Mobil,
American Express, Microsoft and United Technologies, all down
between two and three points.
</P>
<P>
   Sears, Roebuck, dropped from the Dow last year, was a standout
gainer, soaring 7 to 37{, the biggest rise in at least 20 years,
after announcing it expects to beat Wall Street's profit estimates
for the first quarter and full year.
</P>
<P>
   In technology, investors gravitated toward such long-established
companies as Motorola, up 12], to 148, and Texas Instruments, up
4\, to 150, partly at the expense of some recent Internet
favorites. Microsoft, in the wake of an adverse, but not
unexpected, antitrust decision on Monday, fell 2 3/16 to 86], down
from a peak of 113 on Dec. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Over-all, strategists said that while the market might move
sideways for awhile, it will likely rise again when earnings
reports prove even better than expected.
</P>
<P>
   When the current ``information void'' ends, said Thomas M.
Galvin, chief investment officer at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette,
``I think fundamentals will overwhelm nervous psychology.''
</P>
<P>
   After the close Yahoo reported strong earnings that beat
published Wall Street estimates but that fell a bit short of
so-called whisper predictions. The shares, which at 4 p.m. were
down 1 13/16 to 165 9/16, traded as low as 159 in after-hours
trading.
</P>
<P>
   In first public offerings, Metlife advanced 1\, to 15{ and was
the session's most actively traded issue with 65.6 million shares
changing hands. Shares of Krispy Kreme, the doughnut company,
jumped 16 to close at 37.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, stocks fell broadly in most major markets _ 3.4
percent in Hong Kong, 3 percent in Paris, 2.5 percent in Frankfurt,
0.7 percent in London and 0.6 percent in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
