<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE AGAIN PASSES BAN ON `PARTIAL-BIRTH' ABORTIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House approved a ban on so-called
``partial-birth'' abortions Wednesday for the third time in five
years, but the measure is certain to be vetoed by President Clinton
if it passes the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has vetoed similar measures twice before, and Congress
has failed to override his decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Republican supporters of the measure acknowledged that a like
fate may await the bill this year, but they pressed ahead in an
effort to fulfill a political promise to social conservatives in
the party to promote the passage of ``family-oriented''
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The ban on such abortions was approved by a House vote of 287 to
141, with 77 Democrats joining 209 Republicans for passage.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the measure complained that the ban would provide no
exception for the health of the mother, even though it does contain
a provision that would allow the procedure to be used only to save
the life of the mother.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said that language was not broad enough to
address other health concerns short of death and insisted that the
bill would infringe on the right of a woman, in consultation with
her doctor, to decide whether the procedure was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Although the issue has been debated in Congress seven times
since 1995, the arguments that unfolded on the floor were highly
emotional and politically-charged. Republican advocates of the ban
used graphic illustrations to make their point that the procedure,
performed during the second or third trimester of pregnancy,
constitutes a murderous and immoral act.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, described how the
procedure involves partially delivering the fetus and then piercing
its skull with an instrument to abort it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't see the abject cruelty of this procedure, then I
feel for you,'' Armey told his colleagues, calling it a ``cruel and
ugly'' way to end a baby's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Americans wouldn't want this process done to a dog,''
added House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, calling the procedure
``a stain'' on our nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   He called on Clinton ``to listen to the conscience of America
and sign this ban.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the measure, however, accused Republicans of trying
to turn it into an election year issue while ignoring state court
rulings that say banning the procedure would be unconstitutional
because it would infringe on a woman's right to choose abortion as
guaranteed under the Supreme Court's Roe vs. Wade decision.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., called the ban ``an attack on the
constitutional right to reproductive choice,'' adding that it would
``insert the government into one of the most personal and painful
decisions a woman will ever have to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Texas, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am strongly opposed to late term abortions,'' Edwards said.
But he added that such a decision ``should be made by a woman and
her doctor, not by politicians in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   He warned his colleagues that the bill would ``do harm to
decent, loving women'' unless its language was broadened to include
exemptions for health concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``A health exemption for women is not a loophole, it's a
constitutional right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Texas, also accused Republicans of putting
politics over policy at the expense of women's health issues. He
called on GOP lawmakers to consider a compromise bill that would
take into account the serious long-term health consequences to a
mother if she was forced to carry a questionable pregnancy to the
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in Congress are not medical specialists,'' Bentsen said.
``Most people agree that there are too many late term abortions.
But that's no reason not to make exceptions for the life and health
of the mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Bentsen noted that a number of states, including Texas, already
have laws addressing the procedure, but they make exceptions for
serious health concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders refused to allow a vote on any substitute
legislation, insisting that anything short of an exemption to save
the life of the mother would be condoning murder.
</P>
<P>
   The vote marked the seventh time the House has dealt with the
issue since Republicans took over control of Congress in 1995.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The vote came as the Supreme Court is preparing to hear
arguments later this month on the constitutionality of a ban on the
procedure enacted by the Nebraska legislature that provides no
exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   There is no connection between the Nebraska law and the federal
ban pushed by Republican leaders. But by including a narrowly
defined exemption to save the life of the mother, sponsors of the
federal ban hope to avoid a constitutional challenge if their bill
ever becomes law.
</P>
<P>
   The debates have always caused considerable anguish for
Democrats who are abortion rights supporters, but find it difficult
to oppose ending a procedure that many find repulsive.
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri, for example,
voted along with 77 other Democrats and 209 Republicans for passage
of the ban. Eight of the 17 Texas Democrats in the House voted in
favor of the ban, along with all 13 of the state's Republican
members.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
