<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8212 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-ABORTION-CONGRESS-ART     04-05 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-CONGRESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGING CLINTON, HOUSE BACKS BAN ON `PARTIAL BIRTH' ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT27 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Disregarding President Clinton's promise of yet
another veto, this one in an election year, the House on Wednesday
passed a bill that would ban an abortion procedure that its
opponents call ``partial birth.''
</P>
<P>
   In what has become a routine showdown over the procedure,
replete with photographs of cuddly babies and accusations of
infanticide, 287 House members voted for the ban and 141 opposed
it, exceeding the number needed to override a presidential veto by
2 votes. Abortion rights supporters have picked up 9 votes since
the last time the House took up the measure, in 1997, mostly from
new members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In order to override a presidential veto, both the House and
Senate must pass a bill with a two-thirds majority. However, when
the Senate approved the ban in October, it fell 2 votes short of
the number needed to block a veto.
</P>
<P>
   So Wednesday's vote was a kind of kick-off for a broader
abortion rights debate, both on the campaign trail and before the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court will hear arguments this month on the
constitutionality of a ban on ``partial birth'' abortions in
Nebraska, making it the first time in eight years the court has
taken up an abortion case. Such bans have been enacted in about 30
states, but in most cases have been struck down or curtailed by
lower courts.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's House vote drew a clear line between Gov. George W.
Bush, who supports a ban, and Vice President Al Gore, who opposes
one.
</P>
<P>
   Both presumed presidential nominees have tread into the
perennial debate over Roe vs. Wade, the 1973 decision that
legalized abortion. Bush supports the Republican platform opposing
abortion. And Gore, an abortion-rights backer, does not miss an
opportunity to remind voters that the next president will likely
name three Supreme Court justices, appointments that could lead to
the reversal of the Roe decision.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, several Republicans made it clear on the House
floor that the ban was one piece of a larger strategy to chip away
at the Roe decision. Public opinion surveys have shown that
abortion opponents have drawn support by focusing on this late-term
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never in the history of man has more lip service been paid to
the needs of children, never in the history of man have so many
children been sacrificed so mercilessly in such high number,'' said
Rep. Tom DeLay, the Texan who is the third-ranking Republican in
the House. ``Abortion is a stain we must begin to wash away. A ban
on partial birth is the first step.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats complained that Republicans did not want to pass a
bill that Clinton would not veto _ one that would include an
exception to protect the health of the mother _ because they wanted
to use the issue for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about politics, not about saving lives, not about
winning hearts,'' said Rep. James Greenwood, D-Pa. ``It's about
winning seats in the Congress. It's not about making law; it's
about making noise.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would outlaw a kind of abortion, in which, the
bill's supporters say, a fetus is partly extracted feet first. An
instrument is then inserted into the skull, and the brain is
removed before the fetus is taken out. The procedure is used in the
second and third trimester. Exceptions to the ban would be
permitted to protect the mother's life.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the legislation argue that this kind of abortion is
never medically necessary. Its opponents counter that, while they
dislike the procedure, Congress should not dictate to doctors how
they should do their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   A ban was first passed by the House in 1995 and then again in
1997. But each time, the Senate failed to secure the votes needed
to override a presidential veto, and each time, President Clinton
vetoed the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Wednesday that Clinton would veto the
legislation again, explaining that while the president opposes
late-term abortions, he would demand exceptions to a ban in cases
where the mother's health was in jeopardy, not just cases in which
a mother might die without an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats proposed an alternate bill that they said would have
addressed the president's concerns, but abortion opponents voted
not to consider it. Republicans argued, among other things, that
the wording would have allowed third-term abortions for mental
health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joseph Pitts, R-Pa., drew protests from Democrats when he
said that their suggestions on how to refine the bill would allow a
woman who was ``having a bad day'' to undergo the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would have you believe that there are women out there who
would cavalierly choose to have an abortion,'' said Rep. Rosa
DeLauro, D-Conn. ``How dare you demonize, how dare you trivialize
what women in this country do in giving birth to children?''
</P>
<P>
   The gruesomeness of the procedure has made it difficult for some
Democrats to vote against the bill, even those who support abortion
rights. For example, Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the minority
leader, has consistently voted for the ban.
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
