<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8213 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BELLSOUTH-SBC06-COX     04-05 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-SBC06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth, SBC shake hands on new wireless phone deal
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth Corp. and SBC Communications Inc. unveiled
plans Wednesday to combine their U.S. wireless units into a new
company that will become the nation's second-largest carrier.
</P>
<P>
   The bold move _ coming a week after BellSouth announced a
separate stock for its multibillion-dollar Latin American business
_ will create a wireless unit with revenues of $10.2 billion and
16.2 million phone subscribers in 32 states. Only Verizon, the
24-million-subscriber joint venture of Bell Atlantic, GTE and
Vodafone AirTouch, is bigger.
</P>
<P>
   F. Duane Ackerman, BellSouth chairman and chief executive, said
during a teleconference that the company expects approval from
regulators by year's end. ``This will let us do things much faster
than either company could do on its own.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some big-ticket action could come even before the deal
is consummated, starting perhaps with offers of flat-rate deals for
cellular phone use while traveling, said Edward E. Whitacre Jr.,
SBC chairman and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   And while the BellSouth-SBC venture is still shy of complete
coverage _ lacking, for example, metropolitan New York _ it covers
70 percent of the nation's population and can fill in the gaps by
purchasing licenses in coming auctions or buying smaller providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chances are we will do some of both of these,'' Whitacre said.
</P>
<P>
   National ``footprints,'' like those of competitors Verizon,
Sprint and Nextel, offer the hope of eliminating roaming charges
with one-rate plans. The companies also lower costs while providing
more consistent service _ and for customers, taking everything on
the road will be increasingly key as customers buy new features
such as Internet access, said telecom analyst Jeff Kagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, the U.S. marketplace is a patchwork quilt of
technologies and standards. Tomorrow, it will be a seamless
experience for the customer. SBC and BellSouth apparently read the
writing on the wall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While falling far short of the merger once contemplated by SBC
and BellSouth, the wireless combination is a dramatic effort to
make the companies national players. With the move, the two
leapfrog past nearly everyone else _ including AT&AMP;T with its 11
million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   They also preserve their option to make the arrangement more
than just an alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is saying this will happen, but many mergers start with
partnerships,'' said Rikki Lee, editor of Wireless Week.
</P>
<P>
   SBC _ the larger company _ will own 60 percent, and BellSouth 40
percent of the venture, but the companies will share control: Each
will have the same number of board members and top executives.
SBC's ownership share will be larger, but BellSouth added its
national wireless data unit to the package.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both companies believe that wireless data is a significant
part of the future growth of the company,'' Ackerman said.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth Wireless Data, based in New Jersey, is the company's
only nationwide offering. The unit offers interactive paging and
its network also carries messages from the popular Palm VII.
Moreover, America Online plans to deliver its wireless applications
via the BellSouth network.
</P>
<P>
   SBC and BellSouth have not settled on a name for the venture,
but say they will somehow preserve their own brand recognition in
selling the service. Among other questions left unanswered are a
headquarters location and a chief executive to run the unit.
</P>
<P>
   While the venture will meld the work forces of SBC and
BellSouth, the companies say they have no plans at this time to
shift employees.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has about 10,000 employees in its wireless unit.
</P>
<P>
   Executives and some managers might be concerned, since the
venture is likely to mean consolidation at the top. But field staff
may be fairly safe: Wireless is a rapidly growing industry, and if
nothing else, the deal will give sales people more ways to sell
service.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth and SBC overlap in their coverage only in New Orleans
and Indianapolis, where one or the other would sell that property.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies also share the same technology through most of
their networks. Where they differ, they are planning to use the
next generation of phones that will be able to shift back and forth
as a user travels from one area to another.
</P>
<P>
   The new wireless company is expected to eventually sell stock,
although BellSouth and SBC would presumably retain control. When
that public offering occurs, SBC and BellSouth hope to let
investors see and value wireless by itself, separate from the
traditional phone businesses that have lately been in disfavor.
</P>
<P>
   But just rumors of a deal, followed by the announcement, helped
boost both stocks. On a day that the Dow Jones industrial average
dropped 131 points, SBC rose 31.25 cents to close at $46.3125 per
share. BellSouth, which was trading below $40 weeks ago, climbed
37.5 cents to close at $49.25.
</P>
<P>
   Talks aimed at an alliance have been an open secret for weeks,
and analysts have praised the arrangement as a benefit for both
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Ferrugia, analyst for AG Edwards, said the deal's
long-term stock value hinges less on spotlighting wireless than on
the companies' competitive positions. ``A joint venture would
probably help them in terms of the stock,'' he said, ``but the
reason it would is it would change things operationally, giving the
companies a bigger footprint.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth estimates the venture will be worth upwards of $70
billion _ and that estimate could be conservative. ``Pure play''
wireless companies have often been valued by investors at more than
$9,000 a subscriber. Nextel, for instance, has fewer than 5 million
subscribers and a market value of $47 billion.
</P>
<P>
   By that measure, the BellSouth-SBC company could be worth more
than $100 billion.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has long been praised by analysts for its cautious,
frugal management _ a reputation that hasoffered little bump to the
stock in the epoch of the Internet boom. Some analysts have come to
see BellSouth as bait for a big acquisitor; the company has
probably been more aggressive in the past year than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, BellSouth bought 10 percent of Qwest
Communications. More recently, BellSouth took an interest in
Dutch-based KPN Telecom, confirmed plans to put its television
service on satellite throughout the Southeast and announced its
Latin American tracking stock.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the SBC deal, negotiated by the same BellSouth team
that hammered out the agreements with KPN Telecom and Qwest.
</P>
<P>
   At least some of the impetus for the high-stakes partnership
comes from the top. Ackerman and Whitacre are both longtime
veterans of the old AT&AMP;T system who get along well enough to have
gone bird hunting together.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot depends on the personalities of the people running these
companies,'' said Elliott Hamilton, vice president of the Strategis
Group. ``People forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
