<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACE-WEBKIOSKS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ace is the place for Internet visits on in-store kiosks
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ace Hardware is bringing Internet shopping to stores
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The country's second-largest hardware chain has installed kiosks
in two stores that link shoppers to its Internet partner,
OurHouse.com. Consumers using the computer terminals can look up
and purchase products, as well as order installation and household
repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're aiming to offer virtually anything that takes care of
the home,'' said Gary Briggs, founder and chief marketing officer
of OurHouse.com. Briggs is promoting the kiosks this week in
Atlanta at Ace's spring convention, which starts today at the
Georgia World Congress Center and runs through Monday.
</P>
<P>
   OurHouse.com hopes to sign up about 2,000 Ace dealers at the
show. About 1,200 of its 5,100 independent dealer stores already
have signed up, Briggs said.
</P>
<P>
   The kiosk program is Ace's latest move into online shopping.
Last fall the Oak Brook, Ill., dealer-owned cooperative bought a 20
percent stake in OurHouse.com, which exclusively promotes and
distributes Ace products.
</P>
<P>
   Ace and other home improvement retailers have moved quickly in
recent months to sell their goods via the Internet, where they can
get a head start on Home Depot and Lowe's Cos. Those two
``big-box'' retailers still are fine-tuning their Internet
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Last month TruServ Corp., the largest hardware store chain,
began selling 3,000 hand and power tools through Truevalue.com. By
midyear, TruServ plans to sell about 20,000 items on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Ace started selling products through the OurHouse.com Web site
in November. Ace now is promoting the kiosks to its dealers as a
way to make stronger links with the shoppers in the stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest advantage is that it expands our product offerings
and services,'' said Rodney Etheredge, general manager of six Ace
company-owned stores in Atlanta. ``Most of the Ace retailers do a
good business in special orders. Having the kiosks for online
ordering will be great.''
</P>
<P>
   The typical Ace store carries 13,000 to 15,000 products.
OurHouse.com currently offers 22,000 products and is adding about
3,000 items a month, said Briggs of OurHouse.com.
</P>
<P>
   The retail store gets an undisclosed percentage of any sale made
through a kiosk, he said. Also, OurHouse.com is putting store
coupons in the boxes it ships to consumers to drive traffic back
into the store.
</P>
<P>
   Ace will test the Web stations for a month before beginning a
nationwide rollout, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Home Depot plans to begin selling products online
in a city-by-city launch that will begin in the summer. North
Wilkesboro, N.C.-based Lowe's will begin a major online sales push
nationwide in the summer. It already sells some products through
manufacturer Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   This month Lowe's is setting up ``Web lounges'' in 30 stores to
test online appliance sales, said spokesman Brian Peace.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
