<HEADER>
A8220 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-LAPD-ART-860(2TAKE     04-05 1477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAPD-ART-860(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK POLICE RECRUITING HAS NEW PROBLEM: LOS ANGELES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT34 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For two years, New York City has been struggling to
attract applicants to take the Police Department's admissions test,
battling a downward trend that saw the number of applicants plummet
from 31,000 in 1996 to fewer than half that number last year.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday, despite last year's $10 million recruiting
campaign, police officials learned that the number had dropped
sharply again: only 6,000 people have expressed interest in the
latest exam, forcing the city to extend the application deadline
for a second time, to April 20.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials, union leaders and critics of the department
have described a list of factors that have hindered local
recruiting: the relatively low pay for rookies, the sizzling
private-sector economy, the strained relations with minority
residents and the shootings of unarmed men that have prompted
public outcry.
</P>
<P>
   Now add this: poaching. Even as the city struggles to lure its
residents to its own department, police recruiters from Los Angeles
have come to New York's own turf, offering promises of warmer
climes, higher starting salaries and openings at the academy as
soon as this summer. And they are having surprising success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably fielding 300 or 400 phone calls a day just from
people in New York City asking for information about the test,''
said Los Angeles Police Officer Jose A. Ferreira, who is recruiting
this week at John Jay College of Criminal Justice in Manhattan.
``With our salaries, and with living in L.A. being what it is _ the
beaches, the weather _ we're finding a lot of people who are
attracted to this work.''
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-town recruiting is not a new phenomenon, and no one
claims it has caused the steep drops in applicants to New York's
department. But the visit by the Los Angeles recruiters, their
first in nearly 20 years, is remarkable for its scale _ and for its
timing.
</P>
<P>
   Not only have they arrived at a time when fewer people are
applying to New York's Police Academy, but they are directly
competing for minority applicants. The Los Angeles department has
run advertisements on minority radio stations, inviting all New
Yorkers _ not just students at John Jay College _ to take the test.
It is part of a national recruitment effort by the department,
which seeks to add 1,000 officers to its ranks, Ferreira said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, 34 percent of the department's 40,000 officers are
black, Hispanic or Asian. The Los Angles Police Department, with
9,600 sworn officers, has a minority representation of 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the possibility that Los Angeles police
recruiting would be successful in New York underscores the serious
problem that NYPD has in recruiting minorities,'' said Norman
Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil Liberties Union.
``It illustrates what some of us in the civil rights community have
said, which is that you can get African-Americans, Latinos and
Asians interested in applying for your police department, if you
send out the message that you want them to apply.''
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said criticism of the
department's recruiting was ``made of whole cloth'' because the
department has a list of people who have passed the test in recent
years that is far larger than the 3,000 to 6,000 openings he
expects at the academy in the next two years. No one can say how
many people on the waiting list are still available to be hired.
And by extending the deadline Wednesday, it was clear the
department is still seeking fresh talent.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of declining applications, he said, had little to do
with the department's ability to fill its ranks. He said the drop
in applicants was a natural extension of the booming economy and
what he described as negative coverage of the department by the
news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, based on the media attention, and the way the
department has been portrayed in the media,'' he said, ``it is not
surprising to me that the people are not applying in the numbers
they applied in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir also said the Los Angeles was forced on the road to
recruit because it could not find enough applicants in its own
region. In New York, recruiters have not had to travel to fill the
department, he said, except for trips to military bases to recruit
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jerome H. Skolnick, a professor at New York University
School of Law who teaches a seminar in police practices, said the
recent decline is grounds for serious concern. ``I think this is
really a crisis now _ the small number of potential recruits,''
Skolnick said. ``There is the danger that you may have so few
applicants that you can not get the quality you desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Like police officials, Skolnick said the prosperous economy has
caused the decline. But he also said the cases of Abner Louima, who
was tortured in a Brooklyn police station, and Amadou Diallo, who
was killed by the police on the doorstep of his house, have raised
awareness of racial tension between the department and the city's
residents, discouraging some applicants from even considering the
test. ``Among blacks, it is likely that there is a stigma to saying
I am going to be a New York cop,'` he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Patrick Lynch, president of the Patrolmen's Benevolent
Association, said he agreed that the perception of the department
has suffered in recent years. But he said New York City's drop in
applicants, and Los Angeles' prediction of success on the New
York's turf, can be attributed to a simple factor: pay. Police
salaries in Los Angeles start at $41,000 each year; in New York,
salaries start at $34,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said the gap is particularly aggravating to the union
because New York's recruits are required to have completed 60
college credits or two years of military service for admission to
the academy. In Los Angeles, cadets are admitted to the academy
with only a high school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fairly obvious that the New York Police
Department is not paying a livable wage,'' Lynch said. ``Our rookie
officers are taking home $700 every two weeks. That's not enough to
put food on the table, much less pay the rent. We have young
officers living in the basements of their parent's homes, while I
think Los Angeles is an example of a department that is paying its
officers a livable wage, which allows people to follow their
passions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles police hope to take advantage of this gap
Thursday. At 8 a.m., in an auditorium at John Jay College, Ferreira
will reach into one of 19 sealed boxes, remove bundles of
standardized tests and distribute them to rows of potential
recruits. And by Saturday evening, when the last would-be rookie
has taken the test, Ferreira and his six colleagues expect to have
screened as many as 4,000 applicants, an accomplishment in three
days that rivals the New York Police Department's recruiting effort
so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   On the campus Wednesday, students who met with the Los Angeles
recruiting team had money on their minds. Ato Gordon, 22, a senior
from Canarsie, Brooklyn, met with the officers near the cafeteria.
He and his peers asked questions about police-community relations
and the Los Angeles crime rate, but they also asked about the cost
of renting an apartment. Gordon eyed the salary on the LAPD
literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could be in Beverly Hills right now driving around,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Skolnick also described another phenomenon. The New York
department is not alone in receiving harsh criticism, he noted,
even as crime has declined. The department in Los Angeles has been
roiled by its share of scandals during the past decade, including
the beating of Rodney King by officers and the controversial tenure
of former Chief Daryl Gates during the early 1990s, as well as the
recent decision by Chief Bernard Parks to disband an anti-gang unit
that had been at the heart of a corruption and brutality scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the students who were interviewed seemed to know any
substantive details about recent controversies in Los Angeles. And
many were in their preteen years when Rodney King was beaten, and
the riots erupted in 1992. Skolnick said perhaps when a department
recruits away from the area in which it serves, it enjoys less
biased view among the pool of applicants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some of the reason for the Los Angeles police coming
to New York is that they don't have the local stigma in New York,''
he said. ``Knowing this, maybe New York ought to go to Los Angeles
to recruit.''
</P>
<P>
   (rk)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
