<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8223 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-STIG-ANDERSEN-MUSIC-A     04-05 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STIG-ANDERSEN-MUSIC-ART-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HEROIC TENOR WHO AIMS FOR THE NUANCES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos 43-44 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
 Matthew Gurewitsch writes about the arts for The Wall Street
Journal and other publications.  
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ One last question for Stig Andersen (the G is silent),
the athletic tenor from Denmark. Suppose singing had not worked
out. What would he have done instead?
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a ceramicist,'' he answers. ``I make pots. I like to work
against some resistance. I don't like clay that's too soft or too
weak. I have to have something to grab.''
</P>
<P>
   Andersen, it turns out, used to own his own kiln, but he sold it
years ago along with all his tools. When does a tenor have time to
throw pots? Still, I wonder: Was his style rugged and sturdy?
Smooth and fragile?
</P>
<P>
   ``The big forms were quite rough, but within that I like very
delicate lines,'' he says. ``I like that contradiction.''
</P>
<P>
   I jot this down. ``Maybe it sounds as if it had something to do
with the way I sing,'' he concludes, reading my mind.
</P>
<P>
   This exchange took place recently backstage at the Houston Grand
Opera, where Andersen was appearing in ``Tristan und Isolde.''
Offstage, his bright eyes, broad cheekbones and shock of healthy
chestnut hair made a happier impression than in the role of
Tristan, that gloomy lover born to ``yearn and die.''
</P>
<P>
   In jeans and a biker's jacket, looking less tall but stouter in
person than onstage, he still seemed an exceptionally plausible
physical match for Wagner's Siegfried, the role that takes him to
the Metropolitan Opera for his house debut on Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The protagonist of the second half of Wagner's four-part epic,
``Der Ring des Nibelungen,'' Siegfried enters the action in the
opera that bears his name, proceeding to his tragic end in the
concluding opera, ``Gotterdammerung,'' which Andersen sings on
April 22, to complete the Met's first cycle of the season. He
returns early next month in the season's third and last ``Ring.''
(Wolfgang Neumann is Siegfried in the second cycle.)
</P>
<P>
   OK, Andersen does the work of a heldentenor, a fabled beast like
the unicorn, much in demand. But what is a heldentenor, exactly?
And is Andersen the Real Thing?
</P>
<P>
   ``Held'' meaning hero, we associate the term above all with the
heroic music dramas of Wagner. The prototype remains Lauritz
Melchior, another Dane, who towered over the 1930s and '40s, rising
to Wagner's challenges with matchless stamina, brilliance and
brawn.
</P>
<P>
   In the common taxonomy of vocal types, heroic (or ``dramatic'')
voices lie at the far end of a spectrum from the lyric variety. The
distinction is a mite crude.
</P>
<P>
   ``If by `dramatic' you mean singing loud all the way through, in
my opinion that's not dramatic but boring,'' Andersen said. ``If
`lyric' means that you're trying to express the words and emotions,
then yes, I'm lyric, and maybe I'm singing the wrong repertoire.
But I'm convinced Wagner never meant us to shout all the time. He
wants everything, from extra loudness to extra silence. In whatever
I sing, I try to find the right color for every moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston ``Tristan,'' with Renate Behle as Isolde, gave a
clear account of what Andersen has to offer. The poignant longing
in his early lines describing the view from ship to shore went
straight to the morbid heart of the romance. In the love duet, his
finespun legato gave the passage repeated in the last act as
Isolde's transfiguration a calm, eerie bliss that few sopranos
could equal. The hero's delirium as he lies dying _ veering from
exhaustion to elation, punctuated by eruptions of searing anguish _
unfolded with spontaneity, immediacy and a remarkable palette of
apt timbres, now ashen, now aglow.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rich and deep performance. True, the Houston Symphony
Orchestra in the pit, conducted by Christoph Eschenbach, gave no
quarter, momentarily swamping Andersen here and there. Without
raising the specter of Melchior, one could cite living tenors who
roar louder. Sometimes their cries get lost, too. Andersen's
instrument held firm and steady to the end, and his identification
with the character never faltered.
</P>
<P>
   For an engrossing non-Wagnerian sample of Andersen's vocal and
interpretive gifts, seek out the recent Grammy-nominated recording
of Franz Schmidt's oratorio ``The Book With Seven Seals,'' on EMI,
in which he invests the awesome text of St. John the Divine with
apocalyptic dread and wonder.
</P>
<P>
   David Gockley, the general director of the Houston Grand Opera,
had long hoped to stage ``Tristan,'' he said. Only his discovery of
Andersen, in a Copenhagen ``Tannhauser,'' persuaded him to go
forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has qualities seldom found in a heldentenor,'' Gockley
explained. ``The singing is lyrical, musical, always in control of
the pitch. The phrasing is sensitive. It's much more to my taste
than the Bayreuth bark. It's all part of a package. Onstage, he's a
credible human being. He thinks in terms of character, not just of
the singing voice.'' Volume is not everything.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Copenhagen barber and a nurse who later ran a home
for the elderly, Andersen grew up making music for fun. ``I'm old
enough to have had the luck to have a childhood without
television,'' he said with an impish grin, declining to give his
age.
</P>
<P>
   He studied in Copenhagen and Aarhus, and it was in Aarhus, in
1978, that he made his operatic debut, as the undetectable Don
Curzio in Mozart's ``Nozze di Figaro,'' soon graduating to the
melodious bel canto juveniles. With his engagement at the Royal
Opera in Copenhagen in 1980, he juggled roles like these against
such punishing grown-up fare as Canio, the sobbing clown of ``I
Pagliacci.'' Another purely lyric interlude ensued, lasting several
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   By now, Andersen has worked up roles extending from Mozart's
Tamino in ``The Magic Flute'' and Beethoven's Florestan in
``Fidelio'' to Verdi's Otello, Britten's outcast Peter Grimes and
the young Buddha in Per Norgard's ``Siddharta.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wagner's heroes hold a special place in his affections.
``I'm rare in that I sing them all at the same time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The note of pride is justified. Nowadays, the name-brand artists
most in demand prefer to take their Wagner a role or two at a time:
not necessarily an unwise policy. Unlike Handel, Mozart, the bel
canto composers and even Verdi on occasion, Wagner composed first
and cast later.
</P>
<P>
   His were the ``works of art of the future.'' He wrote, it has
been said, for artists yet unborn. More to the point, he conceived
each character as a total entity, the voice the mirror of a soul.
No two are alike.
</P>
<P>
   Siegfried, for instance, is nothing like Tristan. He enters the
``Ring'' as a child of the forest in his days of youthful glory. In
five of the most arduous hours in the tenor literature, he forges a
sword, slays a dragon and wins a sleeping beauty, who awakens in
highly vocal condition.
</P>
<P>
   The first act of ``Siegfried'' _ crushing in its orchestration,
relentless in its high, jubilant tessitura _ is a marathon in
itself. In Act III, the pressure mounts anew, with the competitive
love duet saved for last. In ``Gotterdammerung,'' treachery
(suffered and inflicted) is the order of the day, culminating in
Siegfried's murder. The hero's part begins much as it left off in
the previous opera but concludes in trancelike radiance, with tense
episodes along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen has trod this road before, in Aarhus (before the
cameras of Danish television), in the Finnish capital and at the
Royal Albert Hall in London as well as at the Teatro Colon in
Buenos Aires, with a Met scout in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   The two Siegfrieds are among Andersen's favorite Wagnerian
leads, but then, he has trouble whittling his list down to as few
as five. The others are Siegmund (Siegfried's father, in ``Die
Walkure''), Tristan and Tannhauser, the poet torn between celestial
and carnal love.
</P>
<P>
   Not Parsifal? ``When I do `Parsifal,' I'm in heaven, but I feel
restrained,'' Andersen said. ``Act II is wonderful to sing, but in
Act III, I'm not sure I'm in an opera. I feel like it's an
oratorio. The characters aren't really theatrical.''
</P>
<P>
   And Lohengrin, the white knight? ``The part is wonderful to
sing, but he's in armor all the time,'' Andersen replied. ``I like
it more when a character is slightly crazy. I like as many colors
as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Singing, as Andersen conceives of the job, is an
all-encompassing affair. For the last 12 years, he has honed his
technique on his own, without the benefit of a voice teacher. ``But
not without advice,'' he instantly added. ``I'm married to an opera
singer, and if there are problems, we discuss them. If ever I am in
doubt, there's someone to trust completely. Singing is so complex.
If you concentrate on one aspect, it's easy to forget another.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I concentrate on the placement of my voice, I might forget
the balance of my body. I sing with my knees bent, for a feeling of
complete balance. The hips must be brought forward, as if you were
riding a horse. With your feet, you must grab the ground the way a
monkey grabs a branch, like John Wayne, with his rolling walk.''
</P>
<P>
   He rose and demonstrated, with the same youthful pounce he
displays onstage: a great theatrical plus for characters far
younger, in general, than any artist ready to sing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to be able to move instantly in any direction, to
express the particulars of a character with the body as well as the
voice,'' he added. ``Technically, the body and the voice are one
and the same. I'm very bad at vocalizing. I almost never sing
arpeggios. To warm up, I do bits of my parts. My wife does this,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   She is Tina Kiberg, whose light, fresh soprano resounded in
church music and Mozart to exquisite effect in 1987 on the
soundtrack of Gabriel Axel's film ``Babette's Feast.'' Like her
husband, she has moved on to heavier repertory.
</P>
<P>
   The list of operas in which one of them has appeared without the
other is not long. When Kiberg sang the dancing Judean princess of
Strauss's ``Salome,'' Andersen even looked on as her lust-crazed
stepfather, King Herod. Soon the couple will be reunited in
Copenhagen as the star-crossed lovers of Tchaikovsky's ``Queen of
Spades.''
</P>
<P>
   One stage on which they have not yet performed as a team is that
of Wagner's Festspielhaus in Bayreuth, a theater no more overrun
with heldentenor talent than any other. Kiberg has been called to
the shrine repeatedly, singing Sieglinde in ``Die Walkure'' and
Elisabeth in ``Tannhauser.'' Andersen has gone along with their two
daughters and his two sons from a previous marriage, a company
spouse.
</P>
<P>
   Does he dream of singing in the house Wagner built?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anybody who sings Wagner who doesn't want to
try,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there is the world. (af)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
