u f BC-MARKET-TRADERS-NYT &LR;      04-05 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-TRADERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK MARKETS SEEN AS UNCONTROLLABLE DUE TO SIZE AND VOLATILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MARKET, STOCKS-MARKETPLACE and MARKET-GREENSPAN) 
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At high noon Tuesday, after a rocky morning, stocks
pitched into a 90-minute freefall. By the time the dive ended,
shares in some of the market's biggest and most important
companies, from Internet leaders like Yahoo to corporate titans
like General Electric, had fallen 5, 10 or even 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There was no news bulletin to explain the decline, no mad rumor
of presidential ill health or war in Asia, only a tidal wave of
selling. Then, just as quickly, the market turned, and many stocks
finished the day close to where they began or even up slightly.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened?
</P>
<P>
   What happened, said professional traders said as the dust
settled Wednesday, is that the U.S. stock markets have become
bigger, more volatile, and more uncontrollable than ever before.
Even the billions of dollars that Wall Street firms put up to
``make markets'' _ to buy and sell stocks from individual investors
and mutual funds _ is no longer enough money to significantly slow
the moves in companies like Microsoft and Intel, which are valued
at well over $400 billion each.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the commissions paid by individual investors to trade
shares have dropped, leading to more trading than ever before and
adding to the volatility on days like Tuesday. Billions of shares
worth hundreds of billions of dollars now routinely change hands
every day on both the Nasdaq stock market and the New York Stock
Exchange, the two primary U.S. markets. On Tuesday, investors
traded a total of more than 4 billion shares on the Nasdaq and the
Big Board, topping the previous record by almost 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market caps have never been this big, and the volumes have
never been this high or this concentrated.'' said Mike Molnar,
managing director of equity sales and trading for Salomon Smith
Barney. As a result, securities firms that try to stand against a
large market move by buying shares run the risk of quickly losing
tens of millions of dollars, Molnar said. The moves ``are dwarfing
the amount of capital that any one firm could reasonably be
expected to commit to any given name.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Ketchum, president of the National Association of
Securities Dealers, which owns the Nasdaq, offered a blunter
assessment. ``No market, whether it's the New York Stock Exchange
or us, requires its market makers to commit suicide'' by trying to
prop up a plunging market, Ketchum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that there have been significant changes
in the markets over the last few years,'' Ketchum said. ``The
amount of trading that comes in that dealers have to execute
against is much greater than it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom is that individual investors panic more
quickly than institutions. But Laszlo Birinyi, who runs a stock
market research firm in Westport, Conn., said that both large and
small investors were quick to look for the exits Tuesday. ``When
you look at the size of the trades, there were a lot of large
institutional trades,'' Birinyi said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the 18-year-old bull market may have entered a
perilous new phase. For if the Nasdaq composite index can fall by
13 percent, as it did Tuesday, on a day with little news, how much
might it drop on a day an earthquake shakes Silicon Valley?
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, investors have to understand that if everybody
wants to go out the door at the same time, you can't get there,''
Ketchum said. ``There is only so much liquidity in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Wall Street firms risk only a small portion of their
capital to keep markets orderly, a comparison of their capital
growth to that of the overall market shows just how outgunned they
have become. In 1987, firms had $25 billion in equity capital,
according to the Securities Industry Association, a trade group. At
the time, that equaled about 1 percent of the total value of U.S.
stocks, which was $2.54 trillion, according to data from Birinyi's
firm.
</P>
<P>
   By 1999, the equity capital of Wall Street firms had almost
tripled, to $71 billion. But the total value of U.S. stocks had
risen sevenfold, to a whopping $17.4 trillion. As a result, the
ratio of securities firms' capital to the total value of U.S.
stocks had shrunk to barely 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the role of market maker in Nasdaq stocks has
generally become less profitable for securities firms, because of
lower commissions and smaller ``spreads,'' or markups between the
prices paid by buyers and to sellers, on stocks. Those changes have
led some securities firms to retreat from market making in smaller
stocks in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Their place has been taken, at least in part, by ``electronic
communications networks'' which attempt to match buyers and sellers
directly. When there are lots of investors making bids for and
offers of stock, the new networks are generally considered a plus
for investors, because they cut trading costs. But if the markets
suddenly turn down, ECNs cannot slow their slide, because they do
not put up any of their own capital to help match buyers and
sellers.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Nasdaq stocks are swinging more wildly than ever
before. Big companies like Yahoo and JDS Uniphase, with market caps
of close to $100 billion, fell 15 percent or more in minutes on
Tuesday, while some smaller companies recorded 25 and 35 percent
declines before recovering.
</P>
<P>
   The volatility was not quite as severe on the New York Stock
Exchange, which funnels all trades in a particular stock through a
single market maker called a ``specialist,'' who has responsibility
for matching buyers and sellers. But the most heavily traded stocks
are on the Nasdaq, not the Big Board, making the New York's
argument that its system is superior hard to prove. Like the
Nasdaq's market makers, the Big Board's specialists do not have
enough capital to oppose major market moves, traders said. The
Nasdaq and the New York ``are closer together than they have ever
been before,'' said Ken Sheinberg, head of listed trading for SG
Cowen.
</P>
<P>
   The increased volatility is unlikely to abate soon, said Molnar
of Salomon Smith Barney. But over time, market makers and traders
will find new ways to profit from the wild swings in price, he
said. And those new strategies will almost certainly moderate the
swings, since they will probably involve buying on the dips. Until
then, investors can only hope the ride does not get too bouncy.
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
