<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8231 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLA-MEDICATION06-COX     04-05 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-MEDICATION06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Makers of brand-name drugs can make millions
 &HT;    By Mary Ellen Klas
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Thirteen-year-old Carolyn Ruben of Stuart
lives daily on the edge. Her rare heart condition makes her
dependent on a host of medications which, if not managed properly,
could kill her.
</P>
<P>
   Her situation is so delicate, her father traveled to Tallahassee
on Wednesday to plead with legislators not to pass a bill before
the Senate to allow six pharmaceutical drugs, including the blood
thinner his daughter depends on, to be replaced by a generic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not need one more factor that will complicate our
efforts to give Carolyn the care that she both needs and
deserves,'' said her father, Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   If her medication were changed from the name brand Coumadin to
the generic warfarin and that causes her blood to fluctuate, he
said, her doctors ``should not have to wonder whether her
medication has been switched.''
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacists are required to indicate on the label when a generic
drug is substituted, but patients may not always read the labels.
</P>
<P>
   There is more at stake here than Carolyn's condition. About a
dozen name-brand drug manufacturers have reaped millions of dollars
because they have been been protected for decades in Florida from
competition from cheaper generic equivilents.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal before the Senate, which has been one of the most
heavily lobbied bills of the session, allows a lower-priced generic
drug to be substituted for four name-brand drugs because the
federal Food and Drug Administration has determined them to be
``bioequivalent.''
</P>
<P>
   State law now prohibits 11 name brand drugs from being
substituted unless a doctor orders otherwise because of fears that
even a slight fluctuation in the composition of the drugs could
have a deterimental effect on patients.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the change, mostly makers of the generic drugs,
argue that officials in 46 other states, where generic
substitutions are allowed, have reported that the switch is safe.
</P>
<P>
   They claim that the medical profession in Florida has been
heavily saturated with scare stories about the variabilitiy of the
drugs at symposiums and educational seminars paid for by the large
drug manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   One drug maker, Barr Laboratories _ which makes warfarin _
recently obtained letters from the deans of the colleges of
pharmacy at the University of Florida and Florida A&AMP;M that say
warfarin can be safely substituted for Coumadin.
</P>
<P>
   Barr said it has not given money to the schools.
</P>
<P>
   Under an amendment proposed by Sen. Ron Klein (D-West Palm
Beach), four generic drugs could be substituted for Coumadin,
Dilantin, Quinaglute and Slo-Bid beginning July 1. After that,
Florida's boards of medicine and pharmacy would report to the
legislature whether any of those drugs, and the seven other generic
drugs not on Klein's list, should remain on the list of restricted
generics, known as the ``negative formulary'' list.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was scheduled for debate Tuesday but was later
postponed after some opponents said they were not prepared. Senate
leaders said they were confident the bill will pass, regardless of
the postponed debate.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the House has postponed all efforts to raise this
issue. House leaders oppose it and barring the governor's
intervention, it may be dead there.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben said he came to Tallahassee as a man concerned not only
for his daughter, but also for his wife, Patricia, who takes an
asthma drug on the protected list. ``Nobody paid me to be here,''
he said. ``I came to try to protect those who I love most from a
profit-motivated scam that could endanger the health and safety of
Carolyn, Patricia and thousands of Floridians who endure similar
hardships.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
