<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8233 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-POLITICS-NYT     04-05 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH PARTIES WOO A RENEGADE OHIO DEMOCRAT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Va, Texas)  By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leaders of both parties are wooing Rep. James
Traficant Jr., a blustery former sheriff who is, by his own
admission, about to be indicted and who over the years has been
scorned by his colleagues as often as he has been courted.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, with Republican support, Traficant, a Democrat, won
the first legislative round in his effort to get a $35 million
grant for Youngstown, Ohio, the main city in his district.
</P>
<P>
   Traficant often sides with Republicans, and he has said that if
he is re-elected, he might actually vote with Republicans to elect
their candidate as speaker. That vote would amount to switching
parties and that could be critical, given the uncertainty over
which party will be in the majority.
</P>
<P>
   The majority party, even if it has a majority of just one,
controls the legislative agenda, all the committees and most of the
staff positions. The balance between Republicans and Democrats is
so close that if Democrats gain a net of six seats from the
election in November, they would be in control.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the House Rules Committee, which is effectively an
arm of the current Republican leadership, agreed to allow a vote on
Thursday by the full House on Traficant's proposal to give
Youngstown $35 million for a new community center as part of a
broad, bipartisan housing bill. The House is expected to approve
the proposed amendment.
</P>
<P>
   It is unusual, though not unheard of, for the Republicans to
champion this kind of pork-barrel project in a Democratic district.
When they were asked how it came about this time, lawmakers, who
often treat Traficant as something of a misfit, answered with
winks, nods and smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif., who is chairman of the Rules
Committee, said: ``Traficant is someone we've looked to for
support, and he has often helped us when we've needed a vote. We
look kindly on someone like that.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Congressional Quarterly, Traficant sided with
Republicans 57 percent of the time in 1999 on votes when most
Republicans voted one way and most Democrats the other. Only two
other representatives broke party ranks more often: Virgil Goode
Jr. of Virginia, who left the Democratic Party this year and became
an independent, and Ralph Hall, D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Traficant was sheriff of Mahoning County before he was elected
to Congress in 1984. While he was sheriff, he was accused of
accepting money from a mobster after federal agents videotaped a
meeting between the two. In his trial, he testified that he was
conducting a sting operation when he took the money, and he was
acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   In his primary campaign this year, Traficant acknowledged that
he expected to be indicted again this year as part of a grand jury
investigation into corruption in Youngstown. He proclaimed his
innocence and won the primary anyway last month with more than 50
percent of the vote in a three-way race.
</P>
<P>
   He has said he suspected that the national Democratic Party
worked against him in the primary and has threatened to bolt the
party as a consequence.
</P>
<P>
   If he learns for sure that the Democratic leaders did try to
purge him, Traficant said in an interview last month on C-Span,
``it will be the biggest mistake they ever made.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there was a 50-50 chance he would vote for Republicans
to control the House next year.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., who is chairman of the housing
subcommittee of the Banking Committee, grinned broadly when he was
asked how the proposal for the grant to Youngstown had won so much
support. `` Mr. Traficant made a good case for it,'' he declared.
Lazio's subcommittee has jurisdiction over the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Nichols, the spokeswoman for Rep. Richard Gephardt of
Missouri, the Democratic leader, said she understood some Democrats
in the House were opposed to the grant but that the Democratic
leadership was behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John LaFalce of Buffalo, the top Democrat on the Banking
Committee, also broke into a grin when he was questioned. ``I don't
want to oppose it at this juncture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Traficant would not comment. ``I never discuss pending
legislation,'' he said when he was confronted outside the House
chamber this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   If the House approves the grant, it would be only the first step
in a long legislative process. Not only would the grant need to win
support in the Senate, but the money would also have to be included
in the appropriations legislation that determines what money is
actually spent.
</P>
<P>
   The only outspoken opponent of the Traficant grant is Rep.
Barney Frank of Massachusetts, a senior Democrat on the Banking
Committee. ``It's a zero-sum game,'' Frank said. ``The $35 million
comes out of someone else's pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   By Frank's account, Traficant's price more than doubled in the
last two weeks. Frank said he was first approached about supporting
a $15 million grant. He said he declined and thought that was the
end of it. But on Friday, he said, he was told the amendment would
now cost $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This seems to come from the Republican leadership,'' Frank
said, ``but I got the impression the Democratic leadership wanted
me to go along.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
