<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   PARAGUAY: ARGENTINA TO EXTRADITE TWO
</P>
<P>
   An Argentine court ordered the extradition of two Paraguayans
accused in the assassination of Vice President Luis Maria Argana of
Paraguay last year. The men, arrested in January, were named by a
man who confessed to being an accomplice in the killing, which led
to the overthrow of Paraguay's president and forced its armed
forces chief, who was accused of ordering the crime, into exile.
Lawyers said the two men would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: MAYOR WARNS PRESIDENT
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of Mexico City, Rosario Robles, warned President
Ernesto Zedillo not to interfere in the city's prosecution of Oscar
Espinosa, a former mayor and cabinet member and a close associate
of the president, on charges of embezzling $50 million. A deputy
interior minister responded, calling Espinosa's prosecution
politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: FRENCH SUPPORT FOR QUEBEC
</P>
<P>
   France will back Quebec in whatever political path it chooses,
independence or continued federation with Canada, French officials
told Quebec's premier, Lucien Bouchard, on a visit to Paris.
Referring to the 7.4 million inhabitants of the former French
colony, Catherine Colonna, spokeswoman for President Jacques Chirac
of France, said, ``It is up to Quebec to make up its choices.''
</P>
<P>
   HAITI: U.N. MISSION LACKS MONEY
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. secretary-general, Kofi Annan, warned the General
Assembly that there is not enough money to staff a civilian
policing, human rights and development mission in Haiti, the
successor to a Security Council-directed operation backed by
American troops. The United States has not fulfilled its pledges of
support for the mission, the first the council has turned over to
the assembly as an experiment in sharing the workload.
</P>
<P>
   THE MIDDLE EAST ISRAEL: SETTLERS RETAKE HILLTOP
</P>
<P>
   Jewish settlers have set up camp on one of the West Bank
hilltops where an illegal outpost, Maon, was dismantled last fall
as part of an agreement between Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
settler leaders. They are protesting a High Court ruling that
allowed neighboring Palestinian cave dwellers, who were evicted at
about the same time, to return to their caves. Both groups had been
told that the area was a firing zone for the army.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: DISCUSSION ON LAND REFORM
</P>
<P>
   President Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe has agreed to send a
delegation to London to discuss the possibility of British support
for the former British colony's land redistribution program. The
British and other international donors had withdrawn support for
land reform after Mugabe threatened to seize land without
compensation from white farmers, some 4,000 of whom own more than
half of Zimbabwe's fertile land.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA: PRESS CRACKDOWN
</P>
<P>
   Security agents searched the Lagos offices of ThisDay, a
prominent daily newspaper, and tried to arrest its editor in chief,
Nduka Obaigbena. The raid, the first of its kind under President
Olusegun Obasanjo, followed articles implicating at least one
senior aide to the president of past corruption. The newspaper said
the editor had been absent during the search.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: ACCUSATION IN ANWAR TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   Former Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim accused his former
mentor, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, of trying to ``run away,''
a day after Mahathir filed a long affidaivit arguing that he should
not be called to testify in Anwar's trial for sexual misconduct.
Anwar, who has said the accusations are politically motivated,
called the prime minister ``the mastermind behind the evil
conspiracy to ruin me.''
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM: HIGHWAY GROUNDBREAKING
</P>
<P>
   At a formal ceremony, Prime Minister Phan Van Khai broke ground
for a new highway that will follow part of the route of the wartime
Ho Chi Minh trail. Officials said volunteers would be mobilized to
contribute 60 million work days in constructing the first, 800-mile
phase of the project, with a target date of 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
