<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8235 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-MASTERS-CRENSHAW0     04-05 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-CRENSHAW06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Echoes of glory
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ His approach shot on No. 9 carried the hole and
instantly spun backward like a yo-yo on a string. The ball headed
toward that menacing slope in front of the green that serves as
golf's version of a boomerang.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of returning from whence it came, the ball took dead
aim toward the cup, lipping out at the last second and stopping
only a foot away for an easy birdie.
</P>
<P>
   The gallery cheered wildly, appreciative of the excellent shot
and oblivious to the fact that this was only a Wednesday practice
round, just a prelude to the real thing that begins in earnest
today.
</P>
<P>
   But they cheered just the same. As they always have for Ben
Crenshaw.
</P>
<P>
   The roars of the gallery aren't as frequent as they once were
for Austin, Texas', own, but the embrace with which golf fans hold
the two-time Masters winner remains as warm and firm and genuine as
ever.
</P>
<P>
   No man holds as dear the vivid memories of this prestigious
tournament as the slender, affable, 48-year-old Texan. No
professional athlete has ever been classier or more accommodating
with the press. And no one knows better than Crenshaw that twilight
has caught up with his career. He recognizes it as well with the
barest of lament, but then he's had more moments in the bright
Georgia sun than most and will soon play on the Senior Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight times, he has come to this tiny, scenic community
that clings to the state's eastern border, and on 18 of those
occasions, he has finished in the top 25. He's been in the top 10
an amazing 11 times and finished among the top three in six
Masters. It's never been a course that terrifically suited
Crenshaw's game. He has never been long off the tee or particularly
straight, but his ability to scramble, to imagine, to create on a
tract of land that demands it were virtually unmatched. And it
didn't hurt that he was one of the best putters the game has ever
known.
</P>
<P>
   But those are times gone by.
</P>
<P>
   He has missed the cut in his last two trips to Augusta and
hadn't played on the weekend here three of the last four years.
Sadly, that's been the state of his game overall for some time. He
lunges at the ball now instead of smoothly stroking it toward the
hole.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, he has missed the cut in 22 consecutive
tournaments and not survived one since the Buick Classic in June
1998 when he tied for 63rd and cashed a check for $11,393.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he's received more notoriety lately for his wife
Julie's sexy pose alongside her fully clothed husband in Sports
Illustrated's annual swimsuit issue than for anything he's done on
a golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to have a good tournament this week,'' Crenshaw said
softly, almost in a whisper under the sprawling, thick 150-year-old
oak tree set behind the storied Augusta National clubhouse. ``But I
haven't had a good tournament in so long.''
</P>
<P>
   The last good tournament he had a hand in wasn't even a
tournament, not in the conventional sense. Last September, Crenshaw
captained the U.S. team that stormed from behind on the final day
at the Country Club in Brookline, Mass., to win 8 1/2 points in the
biggest comeback in the event's history to dramatically recapture
the Ryder Cup. The two-year obsession with every last detail of
that competition from the matching player uniforms to the team
dinners physically and mentally drained Crenshaw and ultimately
consumed a man who's so sentimental he almost tears up over a
sunset. Underneath the photo in the family Christmas card he and
Julie mailed out were the words ``Our Cup runneth over ...''
</P>
<P>
   To this day, Crenshaw is besieged with positive response from
the Ryder Cup. ``It's nice,'' he said in his understated way.
</P>
<P>
   As he came off the course Wednesday, one woman approached him
and shouted into his ear, ``You made me proud to be an American.
Thank you, thank you, thank you.'' A small boy posed for a snapshot
with Ben. Others clamored for him, calling his name, yelling out
encouragement, just wanting to slap him on the back.
</P>
<P>
   The well wishes and tributes continue to overwhelm the highly
emotional Crenshaw, whose declaration on the eve of the Ryder Cup
comeback that he had a ``good feeling'' about the next day proved
him a prophet. Unfortunately, he cannot predict his next successful
round of golf as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go out and play well,'' said Crenshaw, who has
played in only four Tour events this year and has yet to break par
in any round. ``I feel capable at times, but a few holes derail me.
I'll play good at times, then I'll have a squirrelly hole, and it
stops me. I'm slowing down.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, his days are as consumed by devotion to his three
daughters and attention to the new Austin Golf Club he co-designed
with Bill Coor west of the city that may open this fall. Where once
he derived his greatest pleasure from one of his 19 Tour victories
that brought him $7 million in career earnings, now he measures
happiness in watching 12-year-old Katherine Vail play softball and
7-year-old Claire Susan go through a gym practice or dance routine
and bouncing 2-year-old Anna Riley on his knee. The simple
pleasures are always the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy just getting up with them,'' Ben said, ``and putting
them to bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Crenshaw would like to play better, like to be in a
contending position this week and have that Gentle Ben blade in his
hands, needing to sink a 20-footer on 18 to win. But he doesn't
need to. His life is fulfilled, his legacy assured. And if his last
golf championship on the PGA Tour is the improbable 1995 Masters
that he won just five days after burying his beloved golf
instructor, Harvey Penick, then he can think of no better way to go
out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
