<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTLNOTES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Opening-leg losses put Barcelona, Lazio in bind
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The four main contenders for the European Champions
League have some hefty work to do when they return home for the
second leg of quarterfinal play in two weeks' time. But Barcelona
and Lazio, considered two of the best clubs on the continent this
season, may soon be eliminated thanks to two disastrous opening-leg
results this week.
</P>
<P>
   Valencia, missing two key starters, smashed Lazio 5-2 on the
Spanish coast on Wednesday, getting a hat trick from Gerard. The
Italian club can advance in Rome on April 19 by a minimum 3-0
score, which won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Barcelona's task is not much easier, as Chelsea dominated in a
3-1 victory. The Spanish champions were the victims of a three-goal
blitz by the Londoners during an eight-minute stretch in the first
half, as Gianfranco Zola opened with a free-kick strike and Tore
Andre Flo scored twice on quick counterattacks. Luis Figo got the
away goal in the second half for Barca.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, defending champion Manchester United drew 0-0 at
Real Madrid as goalkeeper Mark Bosnich made a series of dramatic
saves. Bayern Munich needed an 80th-minute goal from Paulo Sergio
to pull even with Porto 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   In today's first leg of the UEFA Cup semifinals, two English
clubs are favored. Arsenal plays host to former French champion
Lens, while Leeds visits Istanbul club Galatasaray.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN: EL SALVADOR WINS
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay Mutiny striker Raul Diaz Arce scored on a header in
the 50th minute for the only goal of the game, and traveling El
Salvador defeated bitter rival Guatemala 1-0 Sunday in a World Cup
qualifying match. . . . A penalty kick by Julio Dely Valdes lifted
Panama to a 1-0 win over Honduras. . . . In South American
qualifying, a penalty kick from Newcastle's Nolberto Solano was all
Peru needed in a 2-0 upset of Paraguay in its opening qualifier. .
. . Two goals by Juan Sebastian Veron and single tallies from
Gabriel Batistuta and Claudio Lopez helped Argentina crush Chile
4-1. ENGLAND: VILLA REACHES FINAL
</P>
<P>
   A penalty kick by Dion Dublin and two clutch saves by David
James propelled Aston Villa to its first FA Cup final in 43 years.
The Birmingham club ousted Bolton 4-1 Sunday after a scoreless
draw. In the finals on May 20 at Wembley, Villa will play either
Chelsea or Newcastle, which meet Sunday in the other semifinal. . .
. The only suspense left in the Premier League is which two teams
will join Manchester United in next year's Champions League.
Liverpool moved to within a point of second-place Leeds by getting
two goals from Michael Owen and beating Coventry City 3-0. John
Harley's second-half goal lifted Chelsea to a 1-0 win over Leeds,
which has lost three in a row. Chelsea and Arsenal are also in
striking range.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: LEVERKUSEN LEADS
</P>
<P>
   Bayer Leverkusen's ambition of winning its first Bundlesiga
title moved a step closer to reality Saturday with a 2-1 win over
1860 Munich to take over the league's top spot. Second-half goals
by Ulf Kirsten and Markus Schroth pushed Bayer to 57 points, two
ahead of Bayern Munich, which drew Wolfsburg 1-1 and lost the lead
for the first time since Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: LAZIO MAKES IT A RACE
</P>
<P>
   Less than a minute after Juventus defender Ciro Ferrara was
red-carded for a hard tackle, Lazio's Diego Simeone responded with
a scoring header midway in the second half Sunday. Lazio won 1-0 on
the road to cut the Turin club's Serie A lead to three points.
SPAIN: ATLETICO `BANKRUPT'
</P>
<P>
   The on-the-field problems for Atletico Madrid _ second from the
bottom in the Primera and facing relegation for the first time in
67 years _ are bad enough. But an accountant charged with examining
the club's woeful books this week declared it ``technically
bankrupt.'' Atletico, winless in its past nine matches, is roughly
$75 million in debt. Club president Jesus Gil y Gil has been
suspended because of financial irregularities that have led to
government charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE: MARSEILLE IN DANGER
</P>
<P>
   The last time Olympique Marseille was relegated, in the
mid-1990s, it was the result of a match-fixing scandal. Now, the
French club with the most passionate following could be making the
drop without the smell of corruption. Its fate could be sealed
Saturday when it plays host to AS Monaco, which has a 13-point lead
in Le Championnat. Marseille, a preseason title favorite, is in
13th place, a point out of relegation. . . . Sporting Lisbon,
seeking its first Portuguese first-division title in 18 years,
stretched its lead over Porto to four points with a 1-0 win over
Belenenses.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
