<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CANOE-TRIALS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olympic course awes 8th-grader
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When 8-year-old Eric Hurd saw paddlers battling the
Ocoee River's roaring whitewater during the Olympic trials in 1995,
he said to his father, ``I wonder if I'll ever paddle on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, Hurd will be the youngest kayak competitor
among 125 hopefuls in the Olympic canoe/kayak slalom team trials
this weekend on the Ocoee.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodstock Middle School eighth-grader is one of six paddlers
in the trials who have received support from the U.S. Olympic
Committee's Community Development Program. The program distributes
money left over from the Atlanta Olympics to smaller sports such as
kayaking to help pay for equipment and coaching.
</P>
<P>
   Hurd said his return to the Ocoee ``is awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1995, I'd just started to paddle, and now I'm actually
racing in it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hurd, Eric's father, was an elite kayaker but left the
sport by 1980, so his son didn't grow up on the water. It was only
after Eric saw old 8-millimeter films of his father competing that
he got interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he got interested, I got interested again,'' said Mike
Hurd, 48.
</P>
<P>
   They started with an old broken kayak. Once Mike saw his son's
talent, they each got new kayaks.
</P>
<P>
   Eric soon moved to the Atlanta Center for Excellence and coach
Mike Larimer.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hurd said Eric's strong points are his ability to read the
water and his strength-to-weight ratio. He can move his 4 feet, 9
inches and 100 pounds through the water better than most older,
stronger paddlers. Coaching did the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``With as much talent as Eric has, Mike (Larimer) is responsible
for his climb,'' Mike Hurd said.
</P>
<P>
   Eric earned a spot in the trials with a fourth-place finish at a
national qualifying meet on the Nantahala River in North Carolina.
Larimer is hoping for a top-20 finish this weekend, Mike Hurd said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Eric wins, he can't go to Sydney. ``I'm too young,'' he
said. ``You have to be 18.''
</P>
<P>
   CANOE/KAYAK TRIALS
</P>
<P>
   When: Today-Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Olympic slalom course, Ocoee River, Ducktown, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule: Today (practice) 9 a.m.-5 p.m., Friday 9:40 a.m.-3
p.m., Saturday 9:40 a.m.-3 p.m., Sunday 9:40 a.m.-2:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: Available at the site. Adults $5, 18-and-under $2.50,
11-and-under free. Parking $3.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Copper Basin Economic Development Association,
423-496-2275 or Atlanta Center for Excellence, 770-937-5073.
</P>
<P>
   Online: www.acecanoekayak.org or www.usacanoekayak.org or
www.ocoeewhitewater.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
