<HEADER>
A8240 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-STOCKS-MARKETPLACE-AR     04-05 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASS OF `99 LEADS REVIVAL ON NASDAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MARKET, MARKET-TRADERS, MARKET-GREENSPAN) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The new-economy stocks may be battered, but they
aren't dead.
</P>
<P>
   The high-technology companies led the market down in the rout
that ended about 1:15 p.m. on Tuesday, but many of those same
stocks turned around and led the market back up in the next day and
a half.
</P>
<P>
   No group of stocks better represented the stars of Nasdaq's rise
_ a gain that saw the Nasdaq composite index double from last
summer to its peak early this month _ than 1999's best performing
initial public offerings. A total of 23 new stocks ended the year
trading at least 10 times their original offering price _ a
performance almost unheard of until the last couple of years, when
public enthusiasm soared.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the 1999 class of very hot deals were Internet
related, and nearly all of them have no profits. They trade on
hopes and expectations to the extent they reflect fundamentals at
all, and they have been highly popular with momentum investors who
pay more attention to price movements than to financial statements.
</P>
<P>
   The group has performed horribly since the Nasdaq market peaked
on March 10. Since then, the Nasdaq composite is down 17.4 percent,
while the best performing of last year's new stars, Brocade
Communications, is down 18.9 percent. On average, the group has
lost 48 percent of its value in just 18 trading sessions. Anyone
who got in near the top has good reason to moan.
</P>
<P>
   But the figures were far worse before the revival. Measured from
Tuesday's lows, these stocks were up 33.9 percent by the close of
trading Wednesday, more than twice the 14.3 percent recovery of the
overall Nasdaq market.
</P>
<P>
   After selling ended Tuesday, there was a lot of talk that
traditional valuation measures would once more come to the fore,
and that the amazingly optimistic valuations that had characterized
the market in recent months would fade away.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that will still happen. But the revival of those stocks
_ including some that had fallen out of favor in early 2000, before
the Nasdaq market began to fall _ shows that the investors who bid
up their prices with enthusiasm are still in the market, and many
see the latest market slide as merely being the most recent in a
series of buying opportunities dating back to the 1987 crash. In
each of those declines the eventual profits went to those who
bought, not to those who panicked and sold. That may change one of
these days, but many do not believe it has happened yet.
</P>
<P>
   The recent fall has been far more rapid than most declines since
1987. It stems in part from the sharp rise in margin borrowing by
speculators. The lows reached on Wednesday morning, when the Nasdaq
composite briefly traded down 3 percent from Tuesday's close,
probably reflected forced selling of positions by brokerage firms
whose customers had not come up with the cash needed to prevent
liquidation of some or all of their positions.
</P>
<P>
   But after that selling was done, prices in the Nasdaq market
broadly recovered, and buying was again concentrated in many of the
previous favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 23 hot new issues of 1999, all are still trading at
prices well above the initial offering prices. But most of them
have declined so far in 2000, by an average of 22.2 percent even as
the Nasdaq composite has risen 2.5 percent. Still, seven of the 23
are ahead in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It may be no coincidence that the worst performer of the hot 23
in the last day and a half is also the only one that has virtually
no happy public shareholders. Akamai Technologies, whose software
speeds the delivery of Internet pages, went public at $26 a share
in October and ended the first day of trading above $145. The low
trade that day was $110, which happens to be the price at which the
stock closed at on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It is still up 323 percent from its offering price, but there is
not a shareholder who bought in the public markets who has a
profit, save for any who bought near the lows Tuesday or yesterday.
Unlike many similar stocks, it has not served momentum investors
well.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai is also one of the stocks whose lockup period for
investors who owned shares before it went public is about to
expire. On Monday, the Securities and Exchange Commission received
13 filings from those investors stating that they planned to make
such sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
