<HEADER>
A8241 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-FRANKS06-CO     04-05 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-FRANKS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Franks catching scouts' attention
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Miami tight end Daniel Franks was a toddler, he
earned the nickname ``Bubba'' because that's what he called his
bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Now, NFL scouts are the ones drooling for ``Bubba,'' a man-child
from Big Spring, Texas, who runs and catches like a receiver but
blocks like an offensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, 6 feet 5 and 265 pounds, will be the first tight end
chosen in the draft. Before a somewhat disappointing workout last
month in Miami, it was thought he would become the highest-drafted
tight end since Southern California's Charle Young was picked sixth
by the Eagles in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Franks) is one of the top tight ends to come out of college
football in the last 10 years,'' said Gil Brandt, the Cowboys'
director of player personnel. ``When you start talking about the
next greatest tight end, this is the kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks left college after a junior season in which he had 45
catches for 565 yards and five touchdowns. In his final two seasons
with the Hurricanes, he often went in motion and worked out of the
slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say I'm probably a tight end,'' Franks said. ``I am a
big receiver, but I can also block. Most people don't see that part
of a tight end. They just see me running down the field making
one-handed catches and stuff like that. But I try to take pride in
my blocking.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks, a two-time All-Big East selection, also was a Division I
basketball prospect, but he didn't know it. Franks said his high
school football coach hid the recruiting letters from him because
he knew that his star player's future was on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Franks said he realized it last season, when his former
roommate, Indianapolis Colts running back Edgerrin James, suggested
that it was time for Franks to play in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edgerrin whispered in my ear that it would be my decision,''
Franks said. ``He felt it was probably time for me to come out, but
that was something I had to figure out myself.''
</P>
<P>
   After Franks had somewhat slow sprint times in the workout last
month, NFL scouts are wondering whether he is worthy of a top-10
pick. The Broncos, who have the 10th choice, didn't re-sign Pro
Bowl tight end Shannon Sharpe in the offseason. The Bears, who pick
eighth, use the position heavily in coordinator Gary Crowton's
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like Bubba Franks,'' Bears coach Dick Jauron said.
``The tight-end position should explode in our offense. The numbers
should go way up, especially if the wide receivers come through the
way we expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
