<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-CHEATING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
30 NORTHEASTERN FRESHMEN SUSPECTED OF CHEATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At least 30 Northeastern University freshmen, many of
them honor students, face cheating charges after discovering a
glitch in an Internet-based homework service program used by
college campuses nationwide that is supposed to prevent cheating,
university officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The students used WebAssign.net, which promises professors and
students a variety of other benefits, including immediate feedback,
reduced grading errors, more practice with difficult problems, and
the elimination of monotonous grading.
</P>
<P>
   But freshmen in an introductory physics class turned in
identical homework assignments even though the program is supposed
to give each student a different set of problems, said Nathan
Israeloff, an associate professor of the class.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is different than other cheating cases on the Internet,
in that the answers weren't available on the Web,'' said Israeloff.
``What they did is copy from other students. It's similar to
photocopying the answers or downloading directly off the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   In figuring out how to dupe WebAssign.net, a site used by more
than 200 high schools and colleges and about 40,000 people per day,
the Northeastern freshmen have forced the North Carolina State
University-based company to redesign its program, according to
WebAssign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key thing is that it's no longer possible to do what the
students did,'' said Brian Pittman, WebAssign's senior programmer,
adding that the problem has occurred at one other university. ``The
whole thing has been closed up, and I have given all those students
zeros on the assignment.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Israeloff and Pittman said, the students discovered
that entering the Web site numerous times on the same computer
would generate identical questions even if the students used
different passwords and user IDs.
</P>
<P>
   WebAssign was designed to avoid such a scenario. When students
in the same class log on, they are supposed to receive individually
tailored homework assignments. In addition to making it easier for
professors to grade the assignments, it is also supposed to prevent
students from sharing questions and answers.
</P>
<P>
   But apparently once freshmen in ``Physics for Scientists and
Engineers'' learned their way around the system, the word spread
and others decided to ditch learning how to solve gravity and
oscillation equations for a few clicks of a computer mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Several students have turned themselves in, Israeloff said, and
others may be innocent if they can prove their actions were a
mistake or another student stole their answers.
</P>
<P>
   At least one freshman was willing to admit his dishonesty:
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't understand how to do the assignment,'' said a
computer engineering major who asked not to be named. ``I asked a
guy for help and he said he didn't have the time, but he said he
would let me use his answers. I regret not just being caught. I
came out of the class not knowing how to use the program, and it's
something I'm going to have to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   The penalties, university officials say, range from probation if
it is a first offense to expulsion if it is a second offense.
</P>
<P>
   Using the Internet and computers to cheat is an increasing
phenomenon plaguing professors around the country. At Northeastern,
during the past winter term, five students were put on disciplinary
probation for copying each other's computer code, school officials
said. Last month, 78 students at Dartmouth College were exonerated
after their computer science professor accused them of filching
answers to a homework assignment off a class Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern officials downplayed any notion that the school has
a unique cheating problem, saying that it has an average of about
12 such cheating cases a year out of a population of 12,000
students.
</P>
<P>
   And as clear as what the freshmen in the introductory physics
class are accused of is wrong, Richard Scranton, Northeastern's
associate dean of engineering, said the more important thing is
that students learn from their mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to remember that freshmen are students in
transition from high school to college, coming from a
parent-supervised life to one where they make their own
decisions,'' he said. ``Students have to learn how to do that. They
have to learn that there are consequences to bad decisions. They
have to understand ethical responsibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
