<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-SCENE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI-AREA LATINOS DIVIDED ON ELIAN ISSUE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI _ While the American public is fed televised images of
Cuban-Americans storming barricades and shouting anti-American
epithets aimed at U.S. leaders, Latinos have differing perspectives
on how the Cuban exile community has responded to the plight of
6-year-old shipwreck survivor Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban-Americans who share the protesters' anti-Castro sentiment
believe the community as a whole is being unfairly portrayed. Other
Latinos, however, believe the exile community has gone too far and
has used the boy as a conduit to vent its long-standing hatred for
Cuban President Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the press wants to show us in a bad light,'' said Dell
Godvina, 38, who was born in Cuba, grew up in Little Havana and now
lives in Kendall, south of Miami. ``They show scenes of people
rushing the gates, and that's what people want to see. They don't
want to see professional Cubans sitting behind a desk. What they
want to see is Miami burning, they would love to see us burn, but I
don't think they're going to see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Andres Ulloa, a 23-year-old native of Ecuador, who believes
``sangre es sangre'' (blood is blood) and that Elian belongs with
his father, said any claim on behalf of the boy's best interest has
been tainted by the daily spectacle outside his Little Havana home.
</P>
<P>
   There, hundreds of exile demonstrators spew verbal attacks
against Castro, U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno and President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban-American demonstrators, he said, ``grab on to anything
to try to make a big deal out of Castro. That's their way of
fighting back, sort of like wanting Castro to leave, but I really
don't think they're going to get anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of public opinion, Americans are getting their fill
of a Miami not often seen _ a city seemingly dominated by its
Cuban-American community whose political clout compels
Cuban-American officeholders to boldly challenge the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Sullivan, spokeswoman for the Greater Miami Convention
and Visitors Bureau, said the issue has not affected the city's
tourism industry, which just ended its high season, running from
December to March. She also said the controversy has been isolated
to a small section of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 2,000 square miles, and we're business as usual,'' she
said. ``The average American person is educated enough to realize
that this kind of controversy happens everywhere in America and
that the actions of one segment of the community do not reflect the
whole of the community.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the storm surrounding the Elian case dominates the
daily letters-to-the-editor section of The Miami Herald, with most
critical of the Cuban exile community.
</P>
<P>
   John Hopkins of North Augusta, S.C., wrote recently: ``I once
considered Miami a good prospect for vacationing. No more. I never
could feel comfortable in a city that puts itself above the laws of
the country, humanity and God. Elian belongs with his father, not
with a great-uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   C.L. Conrad of Homestead, Fla., wrote, ``The Department of
Justice and the Immigration and Naturalization Service have been
swayed too long by threats of disruption from community members if
Elian is returned to Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   The threat of violent demonstrations is prevalent enough that
Miami City Manager Donald Warshaw toured the scene outside Elian's
home Wednesday to ensure calm prevailed and to downplay the
possibility of violent demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, demonstrators took their protests to Reno's
Kendall home, where they held signs showing the attorney general
with devil's horns.
</P>
<P>
   Tomas Von Hertz, a 19-year-old native of Argentina, believes the
issue has been given ``more attention than was really needed and
now has been blown up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something simple, actually, and it's been turned into a
political matter,'' he said. ``It's a simple thing, really. The boy
belongs in Cuba. He should be back in Cuba, not only in Cuba, but
back with his father. It's good that they say what they feel is
wrong, but they shouldn't have the power to keep the boy here when
he belongs in Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Cobo, 23, also was disturbed by the attention focused on
Elian, especially in light of how other immigrant children are
regarded when they arrive in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't fair,'' Cobo said. ``If it was another kid who is not
like Elian, like a Haitian, for example, it would not get the same
attention. If he were to be from Haiti or Ecuador or wherever,
nobody would pay attention to that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
