<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8245 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-FLORIDA-2TAKES(9     04-05 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-FLORIDA-2TAKES(950)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE HOPES TO UNNERVE BUSH IN FLORIDA
</HEADLINE>
 By RICHARD L. BERKE  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It seems these days as if Vice President Al Gore is
running for president of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The night he clinched the Democratic presidential nomination,
Gore neglected five other states where there were primaries and
popped up in Tallahassee, the capital of Florida, for his victory
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   His advisers have been eagerly floating the name of Sen. Bob
Graham of Florida as a possible running mate _ even as Gore has
insisted that he has no short list yet.
</P>
<P>
   And in the most brazen gesture, Gore bucked his own
administration last week by declaring that 6-year-old Elian
Gonzalez should be granted permanent residence status in the United
States, a statement that drew furious responses from many loyal
Gore backers who called it a craven bid to win Cuban-American
votes.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, these and other early moves _ including Gore's
return later this week to West Palm Beach, Fort Lauderdale and
Tampa for more events _ seem to telegraph to Floridians that, yes,
he intends to compete energetically in a state that the Republicans
are counting on winning.
</P>
<P>
   In the minds of Gore's strategists, the maneuvers are aimed less
at the Florida electorate than at a far smaller audience in Austin,
Texas: Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the conventional wisdom that Bush needs to win
Florida more than Gore does, the vice president's campaign has
opened an all-out drive to appear competitive in Florida. The last
Republican to win the White House without winning Florida was
Calvin Coolidge in 1924. And Gore's aides are confident they can
win with victories in California and New York, even if they lose
Texas and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The calculation is that Gore can rattle his foe and force him to
pump resources and campaign time into a state that only months ago
Bush's advisers had assumed he could win easily, at least in part
because Bush's brother Jeb happens to be the governor here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can force Republicans to spend three or four dollars
for every one or two dollars you're spending, it's obviously to our
benefit,'' said a leading Gore strategist.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview on Wednesday, Jeb Bush said his brother
was not about to be unnerved. Gore's behavior, he said, reminds him
of the campaign of Michael Dukakis, the Democratic presidential
nominee in 1988, who lost to Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the Dukakis campaign made a big deal about Florida,
they had four highly seasoned paid people,'' the Florida governor
recalled. ``By September we were saying good-bye to the Dukakis
campaign. They had packed their bags and left.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Bush acknowledged that the state is more
competitive now than it was in 1988 and that his brother cannot be
too complacent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irrespective of these antics,'' he said, ``George needs to
take Florida very seriously because we are a swing state in many
ways. President Clinton carried the state in '96 _ it is an
indication that we can't take it for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   After months in which Bush was ahead in Florida with a
double-digit lead, polls now show that Gore has closed the gap. The
most recent poll, by Mason-Dixon Polling &AMP; Research, had Bush with
a lead of 8 percentage points. Gore's advisers say that winning
Florida is certainly possible, though by no means certain. Still, a
common belief among Gore advisers is that their efforts in Florida
come at little cost, particularly if they make Bush fight hard for
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a tong war going on in Florida, that's a good
thing,'' said the Gore strategist. ``We don't necessarily need
it.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Gore's prospects in this state, the strategist said:
``You have to be smart about playing it. You don't want to be lured
by the sirens of a big win if it's not there. But there is a
potential for victory there, and it has to be explored and
exploited.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Butterworth, the Florida attorney general and the
chairman of the Gore campaign in the state, said the Bush campaign
would be unwise to neglect Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has no choice but to spend a lot of money here,''
Butterworth said. ``If he doesn't he's going to lose the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also are adroit at playing that game. For instance,
Bush has been traveling to California and insisting that he is
competing vigorously in that state. As with the vice president's
campaign in Florida, some Bush advisers concede that Gore has an
edge in California and that the Bush campaign could eventually
decide not to mount an all-out effort for victory in the state.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida, which has the fourth-largest trove of electoral
votes with 25, is especially alluring for Gore because, while it
leans Republican, Democrats are viewed as having a better chance
here than Republicans have in California.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bush's support among Cuban-Americans, Hispanics _ of
which Cubans are the largest subset _ make up only about 12 percent
of the state's electorate. And Democrats hope that black voters,
distressed by Gov. Jeb Bush's elimination of affirmative action in
university admissions and state government contracts, will turn out
more heavily in November. Black voters reliably vote Democratic.
But Republicans cite surveys showing that Democrats do not have as
strong a grip on the votes of the elderly as they once did.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore organization's effort to torment Bush is not without
costs. Even many of Gore's advisers have said privately that they
were confounded by the vice president's decision to break with the
president over the case of Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The advisers said Gore was determined not to alienate the
state's powerful Cuban-American community, whose leaders believe
that Elian should not be sent back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's advisers argue _ and many Gore aides do not dispute _
that the Cuban-American community in Florida is predisposed to back
Bush. And in reaching out to those voters, Gore may have alienated
liberals and immigrant groups around the country who complain that
he is showing favoritism toward Cuban-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where it plays well other than in perhaps
demonstrating his independence,'' said Bob Poe, chairman of the
Florida Democratic Party. ``The Cuban community is not the base''
of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Gov. Jeb Bush said he could not see how Gore's
move would help Democrats. ``To disagree with the administration's
policy and do nothing about it doesn't ring with sincerity,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Miami, some Democrats who are not immigrants from Cuba
said they were offended by Gore's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I'm from Nicaragua and I want my 10-year-old son to get
residency here,'' said Lucia Madrid, 47, a housekeeper who has
lived in Miami for 17 years. ``Gore's going to do that for me? I
don't think so. He's just trying to get votes and is not thinking
of what he's doing. In general, I thought he was an OK candidate
until this. This is as cheap as he can get. And I'm certainly not
voting for him now.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats seemed less exercised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he let down his own party to defend the Elian
Gonzalez cause doesn't bother me at all because it's only normal _
he's trying to win votes,'' said Elena Henriquez, 67, a retired
teacher from Nicaragua who arrived in Miami 11 years ago. ``He's
just saying Elian Gonzalez should become a resident. But he's not
actually doing anything about it. I think it's just a tactic.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Democratic and Republican strategists offered decidedly mixed
assessments of whether Gore's remarks about Elian would help him or
hurt him. But they seemed to agree that the political effect would
depend on how the matter is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on how it ends,'' Butterworth said. ``If the
INS goes in and brings out Elian with plastic handcuffs, and the
kid screaming, `I want to stay in America!' that will hurt anyone
who is associated with the administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan A. MacManus, a political scientist at the University of
South Florida in Tampa, said this state's rapidly changing
demographics made it impossible to predict what might happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think it's Bush's to lose,'' she said. ``But any
misstep and you might just lose one group of voters that you need
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides and Republican officials said they were confident
that they would win Florida, but they expect a spirited contest.
Some Bush supporters even said they welcomed the Gore campaign's
drive to appear competitive here, saying it would only heighten
expectations for the vice president and spur Republicans here to
work harder for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush's brother did not seem exercised about Gore's courtship
of Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he whispers sweet nothings in other people's ears,''
Gov. Jeb Bush said. ``That's standard operating procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   (mg)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
