<HEADER>
A8248 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-MASTERS-ADVANCE06     04-05 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-ADVANCE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good drives are a must to enjoy trip
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Expect horrible early traffic today for the first
round of the 64th Masters. Get as close to Washington Road as
possible, find a parking lot and head to the course.
</P>
<P>
   In case you haven't heard, there never has been a more pressing
need to arrive early on a Thursday. You might miss the whole
tournament. Tiger Woods starts at 10:38 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   To listen to the man's competitors, if he shoots a few strokes
under par, they might as well just start thinking about Pebble
Beach and the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   If it's a 68 or something lower, get the green jacket pressed _
a 44 Long, because Tiger's been working out so much since 1997 _
and get the TV lights ready in the Butler Cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Is that the probable story of this Masters? The oddsmakers say
there's nearly a 2-1 chance that Woods, who made Augusta National
his own private playground three years ago, will do it again. The
Masters committee, meanwhile, has grown rough and pinched the
fairways. ``I think the biggest adjustment is going to be the
fairways,'' Woods said. ``You can't go out there and take driving
for granted like you used to around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Such mower-driven changes affect veteran players, who have
collected unique local knowledge of Augusta National. But they
should be nothing major for the golfers at the top of the world
rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like you come in here and say, `Wow, I've got to know
how this putt breaks or learn how this green reacts,' '' Greg
Norman said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Augusta National allowed even off-line drives to
remain in the fairway. Unless they were positioned in the proper
section of the short grass, however, it was all but impossible to
guide an approach to the proper quadrant of the greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I've played well here in the past, I've always felt that
you had to drive the ball on the correct sides of the fairways,''
Woods said. ``The fairways were huge, but if you hit the ball down
the wrong side of the fairway, you have no flag. You had to play
the correct angles. Now, some of that's been moved over a little
bit. You have different angles. It's going to be quite a
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Six-time champion Jack Nicklaus, who pointed out that the tree
lines always have been the guide to playing the course, was stunned
that the rough was cut in straight lines along the fairway. Now a
ball that in recent years was heading for fairway could end up in
the land of the flier lies.
</P>
<P>
   In a practice round this week, Norman and Nicklaus were being
shown the driving line on the 11th tee box by 19-year-old amateur
Aaron Baddeley, who had played several times the week before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry,'' Nicklaus said to the gallery, smiling, ``I haven't
played this course before.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
