u w BC-HERMAN-CLEARED-1STLD-     04-05 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERMAN-CLEARED-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-410&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR SECRETARY DID NOT BREAK LAWS, INVESTIGATION CONCLUDES
</HEADLINE>
 (CHANGES ``charges'' to ``accusations'' in 4th graf; SUBS beginning
with graf 6 with more information, background; ADDS 400 words) 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT26 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The independent prosecutor who has been
investigating accusations of corruption involving Alexis Herman,
the secretary of labor, said Wednesday that he has concluded that
Herman did not break any laws and should not be indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Herman, the fifth Cabinet officer in the Clinton administration
to come under the scrutiny of an independent counsel, was accused
by a former business partner of engaging in a plan involving
kickbacks and solicitation of illegal campaign contributions to the
Democratic Party. But the independent counsel, Ralph Lancaster, who
conducted the 23-month investigation, announced in a one-sentence
statement Wednesday that he would not seek an indictment of Herman.
</P>
<P>
   Herman said she was ``gratified personally and for my family''
that the investigation was over. Her lawyer, Neil Eggleston, said
Herman had cooperated ``in every way possible'' with Lancaster.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations against Herman were made by Laurent Yene, a
Cameroonian businessman living in the United States who said
Herman, while head of the White House office of public liaison,
improperly agreed to accept payments in return for generating
business for a consulting firm owned jointly by Yene and a close
friend of Herman's, Vanessa Weaver.
</P>
<P>
   Yene also accused Herman of directing Weaver to pressure the
firm's clients to illegally contribute money to the Democratic
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The donations would have been illegal because some of the
clients were foreign citizens, who are prohibited by law from
donating to candidates in federal elections.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Barcella, a lawyer for Weaver and her sister, Caryliss,
said Wednesday that he had been notified that Lancaster had also
decided there were no grounds to prosecute his clients.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's decision is not only a welcome relief for Herman,
but it could help Vice President Al Gore, because any indictment of
her could have proved an embarrassment for his presidential
campaign. Some of the accusations against her involving
fund-raising were connected to the system of raising money for the
Democratic Party by holding White House coffees, an issue with
which Gore was closely connected.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton issued a statement Wednesday repeating his
insistence that Herman had done nothing wrong and saying he was
``proud to call her my friend.'' He said Herman ``did not deserve
what she had to endure over the past many months.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The four other Cabinet officers who were investigated were
Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, who was cleared last October by
an independent counsel of charges that he lied about his role in an
Interior Department decision to deny an application by three Indian
tribes to operate a casino in Hudson, Wis.; former Housing
Secretary Henry Cisneros, who pleaded guilty to one misdemeanor
count of lying to the FBI about payments to a former mistress;
former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy, who was acquitted of
corruption accusations, and Ronald Brown, who was commerce
secretary until his death in a plane crash in Croatia in April
1996. The corruption investigation of Brown ended with his death.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 16, Lancaster obtained an indictment against Abdul
Rahman, a Singapore businessman, accusing him of lying about the
source of $200,000 in political contributions to Democratic Party
groups. Rahman was charged with a felony count of making a false
statement and eight misdemeanor counts of improperly making
political contributions as a foreign citizen. He is the only person
indicted during Lancaster's inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Barcella, the lawyer for the Weaver sisters, said his clients
were relieved at the outcome. ``It's been an ordeal,'' he said,
adding that the investigation showed many flaws in the independent
counsel law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame that it took a couple of years and $4 million or
$5 million of public money,'' he said. ``This is why the
independent counsel law is well buried.''
</P>
<P>
   The law providing for the appointments of independent counsels
expired last June after having produced over the years bipartisan
disgust and weariness. Republicans first complained that the
Iran-Contra investigation, which spanned the Reagan and Bush
administrations, was an effort to use the criminal law to challenge
political actions.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats found themselves saying much the same thing about the
Whitewater investigation of President Clinton, which spread into
many areas and resulted in last year's impeachment battle.
</P>
<P>
   The track record of the independent counsels used to investigate
Cabinet officers during the Clinton administration is ammunition
for both supporters and opponents of the law.
</P>
<P>
   The law was designed in part to make it more credible when a
senior administration official is investigated and cleared by an
outside lawyer rather than the Justice Department. That was the
case with Babbitt when the decision to clear him was widely
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   But to critics of the law, the investigations of Cisneros and
Espy showed its flaws. Cisneros pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor
after a four-year investigation that cost $10 million and saw him
originally charged with 18 felony counts. Espy was acquitted of all
charges.
</P>
<P>
   When Reno sought the appointment of an independent counsel in
Herman's case, she emphasized that she had no choice but to do so
under the law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
