<HEADLINE>
DAVIS CUP: DOSEDEL HAS STAR QUALITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The United States hasn't cornered the
Hollywood market for this weekend's Davis Cup quarterfinal.
</P>
<P>
   And the winner for best actor at the Czech Film Festival . . .
Slava Dosedel?
</P>
<P>
   It seems fitting that Dosedel is part of the Czech Republic team
that will play the U.S. starting Friday at the Forum, near the
heart of film industry. He'll soon be spending time with the movie
camera focused on him.
</P>
<P>
   He said Wednesday he would rather surpass Ivan Lendl as his
country's most famous tennis player than try to make it as an
actor. Still, because of his uncanny resemblance to a Czech doctor
who cured high fever in the 1800s with cold-water therapy, as well
as his living the same healthy, vegetarian lifestyle as said
doctor, Dosedel in October starred in ``Life Water.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the same opinion of life like me,'' Dosedel said. ``He
was trying to treat people with nature's type of life, eating
right, drinking right, not partying.''
</P>
<P>
   Dosedel learned his lines while on tour, then flew to the Czech
Republic to film. The movie debuted in the doctor's hometown of
Jesenik.
</P>
<P>
   However, being a movie star there isn't the same as here, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People recognize me as a tennis player,'' he said. ``I'm on
the tour 10 years. They don't bother me. When I'm home (in Prerov),
I'm in a small town and everybody knows me. They don't bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dosedel, on tour since 1989, is ranked No. 48 in the world. His
best finish this season is a quarterfinal loss at Sydney,
Australia. The next week, at the Australian Open, he lost in the
fourth round to Pete Sampras, who he could face in Sunday's reverse
singles.
</P>
<P>
   __ Czech them out: The other Czech team members, Jiri Novak,
David Rikl and Martin Damm, who each have at least two years of
Davis Cup experience, haven't been particularly successful. They've
combined for a 14-17 record.
</P>
<P>
   Novak has had the most Davis success. He's 5-1 in singles
matches and 4-0 when teamed with Rikl. In the first-round against
Great Britain in February, Novak accounted for all three of his
team's points.
</P>
<P>
   Novak is ranked 39th in singles, and he and Rikl are the world's
fifth-ranked doubles team. This season, they reached the Australian
Open quarterfinals, won an event in Dubai and have reached the
semifinals in Auckland, New Zealand, and Rotterdam, The
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Damm, a late addition to the team (he replaces Daniel Vacek), is
ranked tied for 65th, but he reached the Ericsson Open doubles
final last week at Key Biscayne, Fla. Captain Jan Kukal chose the
hotter player.
</P>
<P>
   However, Damm probably won't play. Kukal is leaning toward
playing Novak and Dosedel in singles and Novak and Rikl in doubles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
