<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judge Sets Deadline in May for Microsoft Penalty Plan
</P>
<P>
   The next phase of the Microsoft antitrust case should be wrapped
up by late May under a schedule set by Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson, who is presiding over the case. The timetable calls for
the Justice Department to propose remedies by April 28 and for
Microsoft to make its proposal on May 10. State attorneys general,
meanwhile, appeared to be giving up any attempt to force the
breakup of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   `Yield Burning' Case Settled
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen Wall Street investment banks, led by
Citigroup's Salomon Smith Barney unit, have agreed to pay more than
$120 million to end federal investigations into whether they
overcharged state and local governments nationwide for Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Life Issues Shares
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. issued nearly 500 million
shares to more than 9 million policyholders, making the company's
shares the most widely held in America. Shares the company sold in
its initial public stock offering closed at $15.375, up from their
initial price of $14.25. Robert Benmosche, the company's chief
executive, said the company was in the position to raise more
capital and make acquisitions if it wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Arms Charges Filed in Satellite Case
</P>
<P>
   The State Department charged Lockheed Martin with 30 violations
of arms export laws in connection with its help in evaluating
problems in Chinese-made satellite technology in 1994. The claims
expose the aerospace company to a possible penalty of $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Peregrine to Buy Software Concern
</P>
<P>
   Peregrine Systems agreed to acquire an electronic-commerce
software provider, Harbinger Corp., for $2.1 billion to expand its
selection of software used for corporate procurement.
</P>
<P>
   Technology Stock Selloff Hits Asia
</P>
<P>
   Stock markets in Asia were battered as investors sold
technology, Internet and telecommunications shares. The Hang Seng
index of stocks traded in Hong Kong was the biggest loser, falling
3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   European stocks fell, pulled down by technology shares that had
been leading the market higher. But British investors could not
trade for much of the day because of an unexplained technical
problem that crippled the London Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo Posts Profit of $78 Million
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo said it earned $78 million in the first quarter, up from
$1.8 million a year earlier, helped by growth in its overseas
operations. The company reported a sharp increase in the number
users visiting the Yahoo Web site. Yahoo's shares fell $1.8125, to
$165.5625. The company released its results after the close of the
market, and in after-hours trading, its stock fell as low as
$159.75 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Fact Over Supply-Side Fiction
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan campaigned for president promising to shrink the
federal government, and once he reached the White House he pushed a
huge tax cut through Congress. But his mission ultimately failed.
In fiscal 2000, the share of the gross domestic product collected
by the government as taxes will amount to more than 20 percent, up
from an average of 18.7 percent during the last five
pre-Reagan-administration years.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights and Corporate Risk
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International has issued a report that describes the
risk that multinational corporations face when they operate without
regard for human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Quiz Show Generates Knockoffs
</P>
<P>
   The media are capitalizing on the popularity of the television
game show, ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' with an increasing
number of spoofs, knockoffs and ripoffs in advertising.
</P>
</TEXT>
