<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAVERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANIMAL BACKERS SAY TEXAS TOWN TOO EAGER TO KILL BEAVERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARVEY RICE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAGECOACH, Texas _ No one disputes that beavers have felled
trees on private property and their burrows threaten a levee in
this East Texas town of about 450.
</P>
<P>
   But what seemed a straightforward decision to use traps that
would drown the mischievous rodents has turned into a showdown with
those who oppose killing them.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Stagecoach Farms Civic Club asked the Texas
Wildlife Management Service in February to trap the beavers after
discovering they had toppled a crepe myrtle planted in memory of a
former constable.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the club, which owns the city's two beaver-infested
lakes, were miffed later when they discovered that Cathy McNew, a
veterinarian's assistant, had phoned the service and canceled the
trapping request.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all are a little mad because we've already made our
democratic vote and this lady decided she doesn't want to let us be
a democracy,'' Municipal Judge Roger Daigger said.
</P>
<P>
   McNew, backed by the national group People for the Ethical
Treatment of Animals, favors methods that encourage the beavers to
move on, such as wrapping tree bases with chicken wire or painting
them with a latex-and-sand solution.
</P>
<P>
   The trapping request was renewed, but that didn't stop McNew.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked to numerous residents in the area and most are
aghast that they were going to be killing the animals,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The club held a March 31 meeting at which she presented
alternatives to lethal trapping, but it became raucous and the
members again voted to trap the beavers. They agreed, however, to
give McNew a chance to convince residents to put wire around trees
or trap beavers alive.
</P>
<P>
   She persisted, saying most of the community didn't know that
trapping would kill the beavers.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is to be decided at a club meeting Sunday. McNew
agreed to abide by the decision.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Daigger said there are thousands of trees near Apache Lake and
Hardin Lake, making it impractical to consider McNew's methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't protect every single tree,'' he said Wednesday. ``We
need the state to (set traps) because her method has never been
successful and by the time she gets rid of those beavers we won't
have any trees left.``
</P>
<P>
   Roger Dolle, a management biologist with the Texas Wildlife
Damage Management Service, examined damage to the levee, which is
topped by an important road and is threatened by collapse because
of beaver burrowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trees are not the main thing,'' he said. ``The beavers are
burrowing underneath the (levee) and no wire or paint is going to
stop them from doing that.``
</P>
<P>
   But Ali Hegler, a licensed wildlife rehabilitator who is to
speak at Sunday's meeting, said she believes wire mesh could keep
the beavers away.
</P>
<P>
   PETA spokeswoman Stephanie Boyles, who has written to the club
listing nonlethal control methods, said beavers venture only a
short distance from water, so only a limited number of trees would
need protection with wire or paint. She also said beavers eat trees
only in the winter when other vegetation is unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Boyles said the method has been used successfully in the
Northeast, where beavers have long been a problem. She also said
many communities have recruited Boy Scouts and Girl Scouts to put
wire around trees.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
