<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8260 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-LEEPETTY-OBIT06-C     04-05 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LEEPETTY-OBIT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lee Petty, 86, NASCAR pioneer, patriarch of racing family
 &HT;    By Rick Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lee Petty didn't start driving race cars until he was
33, but he became one of stock car racing's greatest drivers. His
two sons went on to make the family name one of the most
recognizable in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Petty, who had three generations of his family follow him
into NASCAR's Winston Cup Series, died Wednesday at Moses Cone
Hospital in Greensboro, N.C. He was 86. He had surgery for a
stomach aneurysm several weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Petty's son Richard is NASCAR's winningest driver, with
seven Winston Cup championships and 200 victories. His grandson
Kyle has eight wins, and his great-grandson Adam ran his first
Winston Cup race Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Petty owned a garage in his hometown of Level Cross, N.C.,
and worked on hot rods before he tried driving race cars.
</P>
<P>
   In an injury-shortened 15-year career, he won three Winston Cup
championships and 54 races, including the first Daytona 500 in
1959. In that race, he and Johnny Beauchamp swapped the lead 11
times in the final laps, then finished in a dead heat. Three days
later, photos showed Mr. Petty's No. 42 had won by inches.
</P>
<P>
   He was as successful on dirt tracks as on the paved
superspeedways, and he didn't shy away from the on-track knocking
and banging common in NASCAR's early days.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gazaway of Newnan, a retired vice president and competition
director of NASCAR, said Mr. Petty also won because he took care of
his equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was smart in that he didn't try to run out front all the
time, like Joe Weatherly and some of the others did,'' Mr. Gazaway
said. ``A lot of times he'd run a six-cylinder Plymouth against the
bigger V-8 engines. They'd blow up, and there he'd be leading the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Smith, who raced against Lee and Richard Petty, said Lee
Petty was one of racing's innovators. ``He tried different things
and found parts that wouldn't break,'' Mr. Smith said. ``And he
knew how to get help from manufacturers like Oldsmobile and
Chrysler.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Winston Cup champion Rex White said he first met Lee
Petty when Mr. Petty showed up at a race with his entire family
riding in the car he drove in the race. He said Mr. Petty always
treated racing like a business and was willing to work hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd do anything to win a race because he liked those
dollars,'' Mr. White said. ``He was a lot like David Pearson in
that he didn't worry about qualifying, he just wanted to be fast at
the end of the race. He always came prepared to take money home.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Petty drove in NASCAR's inaugural race at a dirt track in
Charlotte in 1949 and retired in 1964. His career essentially ended
on the last lap of a 125-mile qualifying race at Daytona Beach,
Fla., in 1961. He and Mr. Beauchamp, whom he battled to win the
inaugural Daytona 500, locked bumpers, and both cars hurtled over
the guardrail and out of the speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Petty suffered multiple injuries and ran only six more
events before retiring.
</P>
<P>
   But the company he started, Petty Enterprises, kept thriving,
winning seven more championships and a total of 271 races.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Petty stayed out of the public eye but made many of the
major decisions for his race teams. His sons played the key roles,
with Richard the primary driver and Maurice the engine builder.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Kyle and Adam Petty drive for Petty Enterprises, along
with John Andretti.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Smith said Lee Petty made his sons work hard for everything
they got.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was tough on those kids,'' Mr. Smith said. ``He wanted
things done his way.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1959 at Lakewood Speedway in Atlanta, it appeared that
Richard Petty, then 21, had gotten his first victory in Winston Cup
(then called Grand National). But his father, who had finished
second, demanded a recheck of scoring cards. Richard was stripped
of the win; it was awarded to Lee.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he challenged his son's first victory, Mr. Petty
replied: ''I don't reckon I regret it. When he wins, he can have
it, but he ain't going to have it given to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Gazaway said those hard lessons are the reason Petty
Enterprises has remained strong as NASCAR has grown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He drove those boys hard to be successful,'' Mr. Gazaway said.
``They started out in an old chicken house with a dirt floor and
built a dynasty.''
</P>
<P>
   A private graveside service for family members will be held
later this week. The family asked that instead of flowers,
donations be sent to Level Cross United Methodist Church Building
Fund, 10142 U.S. 220 North, Randleman, NC 27317.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
