<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8263 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-EXP-MARKET-GREENSPAN-     04-05 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXP-MARKET-GREENSPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN SAYS FED IS NOT AIMING TO FORCE DOWN STOCK PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This article is part of TIMES EXPRESS. It is a condensed
version of a story that will appear in tomorrow's New York Times.) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A day after Wall Street endured one of its most
unnerving rides, Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman,
offered soothing words to investors Wednesday, saying as explicitly
as he ever has that the central bank's interest rate increases are
not intended to drive down stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   But as he has now for months, Greenspan continued to identify
the wealth being generated by rising stock prices as the primary
cause of imbalances in the economy that could potentially lead to
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan seemed intent on drawing a distinction between raising
or lowering interest rates based on movements in the stock market _
a strategy he said would be ineffective and perhaps inappropriate
for the Fed to attempt _ and acknowledging that Wall Street's
effects on the rest of the economy are so powerful that they have
to be taken into account in monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction was subtle if not meaningless to some analysts
and investors. In their view, Greenspan wants to have it both ways,
putting pressure on the markets without taking heat for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time he denies that he's targeting asset prices, he
highlights the fact that equity prices are central to monetary
policy at the moment,'' said Rory Robertson, an economist at
Macquarie Bank in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a White House conference on the technology and the
economy, Greenspan was much clearer that he is sticking for now to
his strategy of raising rates in small steps until he is sure that
the economy is on an even keel. In Greenspan's view, growth in
demand is exceeding the corresponding increase in supply because it
stems not from an increase in the nation's capacity to produce but
from the wealth created by rising prices for stocks, homes and
other assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rise in stock prices, as well as in the capital gains on
homes, has created a marked increase in purchasing power without
providing an equivalent and immediate expansion in the supply of
goods and services,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Economists, analysts and investors have taken Greenspan to mean
that the most direct way to bring supply and demand back into
balance is to choke off the wealth effect. But Wednesday, Greenspan
moved closer to the more traditional central bank position that the
remedy is as simple and as complex as slowing the entire economy,
halting the gradual drop in unemployment and arresting the growth
in the trade deficit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8264 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-MASTERS-TEE06-COX     04-05 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-TEE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First-hole jitters
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ It is not a get-it-in-play, easy-on-the-Zantac
starting hole.
</P>
<P>
   Not with a sleeping sand monster on the right side and a lip as
high as a curb on Washington Road.
</P>
<P>
   Not with a power-fade tee shot required to carry a giant fairway
bunker about 270 yards away.
</P>
<P>
   Not with a sloping green that hasn't allowed a straight putt
since Tom Watson threw out his last pair of plaid bell-bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   Not with that famous scoreboard at the bottom of the hill, with
its international flags fluttering in the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Not with all those little green chairs surrounding the tee box
and their inhabitants so clearly spoiled by past performances from
Nicklaus, Palmer, Player, Snead and Nelson. The hole is 410 yards.
Uphill, turning right. Sometimes into the wind. With trees on the
left, where a fairway quickly disappears for a ball drawn too
sharply.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get jumpy when you get up there,'' Sea Island's Davis Love
III said, ``but the more you play, the easier it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nervous? I think `anxious' is maybe a better word,'' Steve
Elkington said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unavoidable to get a little nervous on that tee box,''
Jeff Sluman said. ``You want to hit a good shot, get your legs
under you, get the round started in a positive way.''
</P>
<P>
   John Daly said, ``I get butterflies on every hole out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly has blown it left, into the 9th fairway. He has hit a ball
so far right on No. 1 that it's been closer to the media center
than the fairway. He is about the only player who would even think
of launching his approach over the trees, from that right side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, but that's the greatest way to go into that hole, out of
the straw,'' Daly said, ``because you're hitting back into the
slope. You can hit it into that bank and spin it a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a tee box with more distractions than anywhere else on the
course. People pack the area from early in the morning. With the
big oak tree at the clubhouse a gathering place for conversation
and interviews, No. 1, known as Tea Olive, is a place where
commotion sometimes must be blocked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an awful lot of people around there,'' said Bernhard
Langer, who had a four-shot lead after 54 holes in 1993 and
promptly bogeyed No.1 to begin his Sunday. ``It's a busy place.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price will never forget the first hole at Augusta. On a
near flawless day in 1986, when he tied the Masters record with a
9-under-par 63, he bogeyed No. 1. It's a tee shot that demands a
lot of accuracy, contrasting to much of the course, known for its
room to roam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tougher hole for the average-length hitters,'' he said.
``Not for the long hitters. They still blow it over that bunker.
But if you've got any kind of a draw on a ball that starts down the
middle of the fairway, invariably, you're going to end up in that
left rough, or second cut. Then, basically, on your second shot,
you're just aiming for the front right-hand portion of the green.
It's difficult. It's probably one of the more specific strategy
holes on the golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   If the flagstick is in the left half of the green in the back,
players have to guard against going left and long, which means an
almost automatic bogey. Unless the pin is back right, the approach
has to be short and right of the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Among the players the assumption is that the Masters committee,
having exhausted all other ways to lengthen the hole without anyone
really noticing, has taken extreme measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be a pretty easy tee shot, but now they've
lengthened the tee by about 30 yards,'' Steve Elkington said.
``Davis Love asked them if they put in a new tee and they said,
`No.' And Davis said, `Well, you've either moved the tee or moved
the clubhouse, one or the other.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's only a tough tee shot for those who don't own the 285-yard
power-fade, which is probably 80 percent of the field. The carry
over the huge fairway bunker on the right used to be about 260
yards. Now the caddie books put it more like 275.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be you teed off down there by the pro shop
almost,'' Elkington said. ``Now you're about 10 steps off the
putting green.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the first tee at the Masters with all the pressure
building, said Jeff Sluman, sometimes it's hard to get yourself to
hit a left-to-right shot. The more natural tendency is to swing
harder than you want to and more likely draw the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about how you need to hit the ball right to left
at Augusta, but the fact is, there's every bit as many left to
right shots as there are right to left,'' left-hander Phil
Mickelson said. ``At No. 1, boy, if you hit a draw as a
right-handed player, you're going to go right into those trees.
You've got to cut it if you're going to take it over that bunker.''
Ernie Els said the trouble off the tee and the approach shot are
only the beginning. ``To be honest, that green is one of the most
difficult greens on the golf course. You're really just trying to
make four and get out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
