<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8266 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GERMAN-BANKS-(TRIMS)-     04-05 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMAN-BANKS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN BANKS CANCEL MERGER PLANS
</HEADLINE>
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
  FRANKFURT _ Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank of Germany canceled a
planned $29 billion merger on Wednesday, only a month after they
had announced the deal. Their action set the stage for new takeover
bids in Germany's once-impenetrable banking industry.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The demise of what would have been the biggest bank combination
in Europe came after a bitter disagreement over the fate of
Dresdner's investment banking business, Dresdner Kleinwort Benson,
which Deutsche Bank wanted to sell or disband and Dresdner wanted
to keep.
</P>
<P>
   By failing to complete the merger, the two banks remain exposed
to long-term structural weaknesses at a time when rival banks in
Europe are shoring up their own power in a wave of deal-making.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years banks have merged or announced plans to
merge in Switzerland, France, Britain, Spain and other countries.
Germany has been an exception, even though its banking market is
one of the most crowded and least profitable in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Dresdner, Germany's third-largest bank, would
almost certainly become a takeover target, possibly pursued by a
big U.S. company like Chase Manhattan or Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   Many said Dresdner was too small to manage on its own, and they
warned that its investment banking business had been gravely
damaged by the recent feuding.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse also is a setback for Deutsche Bank, Europe's
largest bank. Its chairman, Rolf-Ernst Breuer, has dismayed
investors with contradictory statements about his plans and
apparent disagreements with his executives.
</P>
<P>
   But the most immediate loser may be Allianz AG, the German
insurance conglomerate that owns big stakes in both banks. Allianz
engineered much of the deal, and its executives are said to be
furious. Even before the dust had settled, people close to Allianz
said the company would be open to new deals involving foreign and
German banks.
</P>
<P>
   As a part of the merger, Allianz would have taken control of the
retail branches of the two banks and acquired Deutsche Bank's
mutual fund business. The idea was to let the banks escape the
business of running local branch networks, which barely broke even,
and focus on lucrative fields like investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   Allianz shares plunged 14 percent on Wednesday, to 380 euros,
their biggest decline in 10 years. (One euro equals about 96 cents)
By contrast, Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank stock jumped amid
relief from investors who had soured on the plan. Deutsche Bank,
which had declined 21 percent since the takeover was disclosed on
March 9, rose 4 percent, to 80.01 euros, or $76.80.
</P>
<P>
   Dresdner shares, which has also taken a drubbing, jumped 4.3
percent, to 49 euros, or $47.04
</P>
<P>
   Executives of both banks acknowledged on Wednesday that the deal
fell apart over the fate of Dresdner Kleinwort Benson. Though
Breuer said last month that Kleinwort Benson was ``a jewel,'' and
would neither be sold nor shut down, he reversed himself a few days
later and began pushing for an outright sale.
</P>
<P>
   That plan ran into opposition from Bernhard Walter, chairman of
Dresdner Bank. Deutsche Bank then agreed ``to integrate'' Dresdner
Kleinwort Benson, but, according to Dresdner executives, insisted
on eliminating the jobs of most employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In both word and spirit, Deutsche Bank rejected a balanced
integration of Dresdner Kleinwort Benson,'' Dresdner Bank said in
an unusually pointed statement on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a contractual agreement, but we had more than that _ we
had an understanding,'' one Dresdner executive said. ``If they
wanted to shut down Dresdner Kleinwort Benson, then they should
have taken us over. But if they did that, they would have had to
pay a control premium.''
</P>
<P>
   Breuer, in another reversal, replied that the deal had never
been planned as a ``merger of equals.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the deal been completed, some specialists said, it would
have transformed the German financial market and eased some of the
overcrowding that has dragged down banking profits.
</P>
<P>
   As envisioned, the two banks would have consolidated their
corporate and investment banking activities, but spun off their
vast and barely profitable retail banking businesses.
</P>
<P>
   This new retail bank would have been controlled by Allianz,
which planned to use the branch network as a channel for selling
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   For the banks, the idea was to concentrate on lucrative
businesses like investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said that the two companies had a lot of
overlapping activity in the investment banking area and that they
had little choice but to impose severe staff reductions.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   The biggest dispute seems to have been in global bond and equity
trading. Deutsche Bank has built a huge presence in bond trading,
largely under the leadership of Edson Mitchell, an American
recruited from Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives say Mitchell did not want to cede much if
any territory to counterparts at Dresdner, and fear of an exodus of
valued eecutives prompted Deutsche Bank to toughen its position.
</P>
<P>
   Josef Ackermann, the Deutsche board member in charge of all
investment banking, led the charge in favor of simply selling
Dresdner Kleinwort Benson, then later proposed eliminating most of
its trading operations.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, after a euphoric reaction when the deal was
announced, have been pounding the shares of both banks, in part
because of uncertainty over cost reductions.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty was provoking a rush for the exits among
executives at Dresdner Kleinwort Benson. Salomon Smith Barney
recruited its seven-member team of analysts covering the utilities
industry. And a top Dresdner executive said on Wednesday that
scores of others were planning to defect.
</P>
<P>
   ``This became a matter of hours,'' the executive said. ``If we
hadn't made a decision immediately, we would have lost so many
people.''
</P>
<P>
   John Leonard, a banking analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, said
the damage had been severe but might have been inevitable. ``The
only thing that could have rescued it would have been a neat, clean
sale of Dresdner Kleinwort Benson,'' Leonard said.
</P>
<P>
   An analyst who spoke on condition of anonymity said Dresdner
Kleinwort Benson's problems might be irreparable. Given that
Dresdner came so close to selling the company, he said, it will
have a very hard time recruiting or retaining deal makers and
traders.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   Within Germany, there are not too many options for expansion.
The most obvious path would be a merger of Dresdner and the
Munich-based Hypovereinsbank AG, in which Allianz also holds a big
stake.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, Dresdner could also start talks with Commerzbank, the
fourth largest. But Commerzbank has thus far rebuffed all
overtures.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign banks could decide that this is the time too make their
own moves. Dresdner already has a longstanding relationship with
Banque Nationale de Paris, which acquired the rival Paribas last
year.
</P>
<P>
   But other foreign banks have been seeking acquisitions for some
time: HSBC reached agreement last weekend to acquire Credit
Commercial de France in a deal worth $10.6 billion. ABN Amro of the
Netherlands has been acquiring smaller banks across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   American financial institutions like Citigroup and Chase
Manhattan may also be interested. According to European press
reports, Chase Manhattan expressed interest in Dresdner Kleinwort
Benson before Dresdner shut the door on a sale. (mg)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
