<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8269 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-GENERAL-SEX-CHARGE-NY     04-05 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENERAL-SEX-CHARGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY GENERAL UNDER INVESTIGATION HAD WON KEY APPOINTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The general accused of sexual harassment in 1996 by
the Army's highest-ranking woman was appointed last August to be
the service's deputy inspector general, an officer responsible for
investigating accusations of wrongdoing, including sexual
misconduct, Pentagon officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The movement of the officer, Maj. Gen. Larry G. Smith, into that
job has been frozen while the Army's inspector general investigates
the accusation by Lt. Gen. Claudia J. Kennedy that Smith made an
unwanted sexual advance in her office at the Pentagon, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, the Army's first woman to earn three stars, complained
informally to her superiors at the time the incident is alleged to
have occurred, but filed a formal complaint with the inspector
general only after the Army announced last Aug. 27 that Smith would
be appointed deputy, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, whose identity had not previously been disclosed in
connection with the investigation, did not respond to a request
through the Army to comment on the accusation against him.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether any of the Army's top leaders knew about
the informal complaint _ which, the officials said, Kennedy had
assumed would hurt Smith's chances for advancement _ when they
chose him for the new assignment. Army Secretary Louis Caldera and
the chief of staff, Gen. Eric K. Shinseki, both declined through
spokesmen to comment on the investigation or the appointment.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior Army official said that since Kennedy had
originally handled her complaint informally, her grievance had very
likely not ended up in Smith's records as a red flag that would
have derailed consideration of a new assignment or promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since this case was handled informally, it would not have been
made a part of the officer's permanent record,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation of Kennedy's accusation has roiled the Army
and left its leaders in a difficult position. They can either
dismiss her account as unfounded or confirm it and mete out
punishment to another senior officer. That choice follows a number
of sex scandals that the Army has endured in recent years, from the
rape and assault cases at the Aberdeen Proving Ground in Maryland
in 1996 to the recent demotions of two major generals found to have
had affairs with the wives of subordinate officers.
</P>
<P>
   One of those punished officers, Maj. Gen. David R.E. Hale, had
also been appointed deputy inspector general, in 1997. Hale served
in that post four months before he was allowed by the Army to
retire quietly, having been made the target of a complaint brought
by the wife of a colonel who had worked for him. The Army
eventually calling him out of retirement, charged him with 17
counts of misconduct and, after he had pleaded guilty to eight of
them, demoted him one rank.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's case has taken on particular significance, in part
because the accused officer is also a general but also because of
her prominence as one of only three women currently in the armed
services who have reached three-star rank. Her steady and highly
publicized rise has often been cited as a model of women's
expanding role in the military.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry became publicly known last week, although the
identity of the general being investigated was not then known. Army
officials have repeatedly declined to discuss the matter, saying
they intend to protect the privacy of those involved and the
integrity of the inquiry. This week the Army's chief of public
affairs, Maj. Gen. John G. Meyer Jr., sent an electronic message to
all the service's generals telling them not to discuss the case
with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Since the investigation became public last week, Kennedy has
declined to comment and, associates say, has not discussed the
accusation even among friends.
</P>
<P>
   But four senior officials familiar with the case identified
Smith as the accused officer.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's inspector general, Lt. Gen. Michael W. Ackerman, has
been allowed to conduct the investigation, since Smith had not yet
begun serving as his deputy when the complaint was filed.
</P>
<P>
   But the office of the Pentagon's inspector general is overseeing
the Army's investigation, because of the senior ranks of those
involved. A senior Defense Department official said the Army,
having conducted its inquiry, might turn over any decision on
punishment to the Pentagon's inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   Smith joined the Army in 1966 and steadily rose through its
cavalry and armored ranks, serving three tours in Vietnam as a
cavalry officer. He has a bachelor's degree in history and
political science from Western Kentucky University and a master's
degree in industrial management from the University of Alabama that
he received after his last tour in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   He became a major general on Nov. 1, 1996, around the time
Kennedy has said he made an inappropriate advance in her office. At
the time, he was serving as the manager of the Saudi Arabian
National Guard Modernization Program, which has provided training
and equipment to elite Saudi forces since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Kennedy held the same rank as Smith, wearing two stars
in her position as the Army's assistant deputy chief of staff for
intelligence. She was promoted to lieutenant general the next year.
</P>
<P>
   When he was appointed deputy inspector general, Smith was
serving as commander of the U.S. Army Security Assistance Command,
a part of the Army's Materiel Command that works with the State
Department managing sales of Army equipment to foreign countries.
Since last November, the service has had him in an interim position
as special assistant to the director of the Army staff, while he
awaits the outcome of the inspector general's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The details of Kennedy's accusation remain unclear, although
officials have described the encounter in her office as a fleeting
one that evidently did not recur.
</P>
<P>
   One person familiar with the accusation said that by Kennedy's
account, Smith made an unwanted overture that involved brief
physical contact.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Kennedy chose not to file a formal complaint. ``All
sides wanted to handle this informally,'' one senior Army official
said. ``That's what you'd like to do to avoid ruining someone's
career.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army chief of staff at the time, Gen. Dennis J. Reimer, said
last week that he never knew of Kennedy's complaint against another
officer. The vice chief of staff then, Gen. Robert H. Griffith,
said Wednesday that he, too, had been unaware of any incident. He
added that if Kennedy had brought the encounter to his attention
then, he would have pursued an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system takes allegations very, very seriously,'' Griffith
said.
</P>
<P>
   Changing her mind, Kennedy filed a formal complaint last year
because Smith's new position could involve investigating complaints
like hers against him, according to an Army official familiar with
her accusation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
