<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, APRIL 6
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-DEFENSE-NYT (moved on Monday, April 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, April 3,
about Defense Secretary William S. Cohen's criticism of Israel's
decision to sell advanced airborne radar systems to China misstated
the arrival day of the Chinese president, Jiang Zemin, for an
official visit in Israel. It is next Wednesday, not today.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CALIF-AFFIRM-NYT (moved on Tuesday, April 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, April 4,
about the number of black, Hispanic and American Indian students
accepted at the University of California, three years after the end
of affirmative action there, referred imprecisely to the figures
cited. They were for admission, not enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT (moved on Tuesday, April 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, April 4,
misstated Gov. George W. Bush's schedule. He was not in Sacramento
and Martinez, Calif.; he will be there today.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BESTFOODS-AD-COLUMN-NYT (moved on Sunday, April 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, April 2,
about the marketing plans of the maker of Skippy peanut butter and
Hellmann's salad dressing, misstated the name of the company. It is
Bestfoods, not Bestfoods International.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-BRUTTEN-NYT (moved on Monday, April 3)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Milton Brutten, sent by the New York Times News
Service on Monday, April 3, omitted a survivor. He is a brother,
Gene Brutten of Winter Springs, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The obituary also misstated the year that Dr. Brutten founded
the Vanguard School in Paoli, Pa., for children with learning
disabilities. It was 1959, not 1960.
</P>
</TEXT>
