<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8271 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-GATES-CLINTON-ART-NYT     04-05 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATES-CLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATES MAKES THE ROUNDS IN WASHINGTON
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
By MARC LACEY and ERIC SCHMITT  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Gates had business before all three branches
of government on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, Gates _ the founder of the Microsoft Corp. and
still considered the world's richest man despite the battering his
company's stock has taken lately _ met with lawmakers on both sides
of the Capitol, where he expressed confidence that his company
would overturn a federal judge's ruling this week that Microsoft
had violated the nation's antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, at a White House conference on the new
economy, he sat side by side with President Clinton, whose
administration had taken him to court. He stuck to the president's
agenda _ how to spread technology to the poor _ and studiously
avoided any mention of the court case.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're invited to a forum on global warming, you don't talk
about saving the Social Security trust fund,'' explained Ginny
Terzano, a Microsoft spokeswoman. ``It would have been
inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates also had some business at Washington's federal courthouse,
but it wasn't on his itinerary. Microsoft's lawyers appeared before
U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who ruled against
Microsoft on Monday. Jackson set a May 24 hearing on sanctions
against the company.
</P>
<P>
   Gates' visit to Washington showed the many sides of the man.
</P>
<P>
   In court documents filed by the Justice Department, he is
portrayed as a ruthless monopolist who built his own wealth at the
expense of the marketplace. Clinton, however, invited him to the
White House to highlight his philanthropic efforts through the Bill
and Melinda Gates Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, meanwhile, were aware of his growing political clout.
Microsoft topped the list of computer industry contributors to
political campaigns last year, according to the Center for
Responsive Politics, with $1.2 million going almost equally to
Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has long preferred to focus its attention on
Washington state, where the company is based, rather than on
Washington, D.C. But the company has clearly come to realize the
necessity of operating on both coasts.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's version of ``Gates goes to Washington'' began about
9:15 a.m. In four back-to-back meetings with adoring House and
Senate Democrats and Republicans, Gates was treated neither as a
victim nor a villain, but as a national treasure whose fate in the
courts has yet to play out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was treated like an icon of the New Economy,'' said Rep.
Norman Dicks, D-Wash., who set up Gates' meeting with about 50
House Democrats. ``People are willing to wait and see how the
lawsuit plays out. The sentiment was that members would like this
to settle.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates has plenty of detractors, especially in the Silicon Valley
districts that are home to Microsoft's chief competitors. But the
naysayers were nowhere to be found on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very upset and disappointed by the court decision,''
said Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., who arranged Gates' meeting with
about 60 House Republicans. ``He was encouraged by our members to
hang in there and never, never give up. He said he believes he'll
win on appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging discussion with about a dozen Senate
Democrats, Gates covered subjects from education to health care to
the global economy, and the roles industry and Congress play.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop was an hour with House Republicans, where Gates, after
brief introductory remarks that did not touch on the court
decision, forecast a technological future in which even
technology-shy lawmakers would carry their daily schedules in a
tablet device, and the Internet would be a staple of work and
personal lives.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, before House Democrats who are trying to burnish
their image with the high-tech community, Gates fielded questions
about the so-called digital divide between those enjoying the
wealth and advantages that flow from access to computers and the
Internet versus those who may be left behind in the race to improve
their lives. He also put in a plug for high-tech industries' need
for more H-1B visas for software specialists and other technical
workers, a measure that's now pending in both the House and the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   When one Democrat groused that the booming economy had bypassed
his district, leaving some highly qualified engineers unemployed,
Gates insisted the legislator send him their resumes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of tapping into Gates' software expertise, White House
officials invited him to the conference because of his
philanthropic efforts. He participated in a panel discussion on how
best to bring health, education and technology to poor people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work he's doing around the world, we have admiration
for,'' said a senior White House official. ``As far as the company
and its practices, we had a problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates was able to make a similar distinction. His aides say he
considers the Justice Department to be the entity pushing the
lawsuit, not the White House. He also keeps in mind, they said,
that the federal government is one of Microsoft's largest clients.
</P>
<P>
   But there was clearly a bit of angst on both sides before Gates
arrived at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   After the court ruling this week, John Podesta, the White House
chief of staff, checked with Joel Klein, the assistant attorney
general in charge of the antitrust division, to determine whether
Gates' participation in the White House was appropriate. No
objection was lodged.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gates also called the White House after the ruling to
determine whether Gates' invitation, which was issued a month ago,
was still valid. It was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't appear to be awkward in any way,'' Trevor Neilson, a
spokesman for the Gates Foundation, said of the White House visit.
</P>
<P>
   And despite Gates' warnings about what effect government
meddling would have on his company, he sounded positive about the
future, sanctions or no sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the beginning of what the computer can do to change
our lives,'' he said at the White House. ``The best is yet to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   (mg)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
