<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8272 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-GATECH-HEWITT06-C     04-05 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GATECH-HEWITT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hewitt: `It's the right situation'
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The task of turning around the Georgia Tech basketball
program falls to a young coach most Yellow Jackets fans probably
had not heard of before Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hewitt of Siena College was expected to be approved
Wednesday night by the board of the school's athletic association.
If so, he was to be introduced formally today as the 12th coach in
Georgia Tech history.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, 36, led Siena to a 66-27 record in three seasons at the
school in Loudonville, N.Y. The Saints were in the NCAA Tournament
in 1999 and the NIT this season.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt was offered the job Wednesday morning by athletics
director Dave Braine. Terms of the contract were not disclosed, but
it is thought to be a four- or five-year deal worth about $500,000
annually, including money from radio and TV shows, camps and shoe
deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited,'' Braine said. ``Paul fits the criteria we were
looking for when we set out to hire a coach. He has an excellent
record. He is a good teacher who is able to develop players. And he
is a very good recruiter who is not turned off by the academic
standards we have at Tech.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt succeeds Bobby Cremins, who announced Feb. 18 that he
would not return after 19 seasons. Cremins compiled a 354-237
record, including 13-17 this season. Tech missed the NCAA
Tournament six of the past seven seasons, and interest and
attendance lagged.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, who last year turned down an offer from Pittsburgh and
interviewed for the Notre Dame job, was scheduled to be introduced
at a news conference at 11 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't because it's a matter of time for leaving Siena.
It's because this is the right situation,'' Hewitt said from New
York Wednesday before heading to Atlanta. ``There are one or two
schools I would go to, this happens to be one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Braine headed a search committee that reported to the full
board. He had discussions with several coaches, including
Appalachian State's Buzz Peterson, Oliver Purnell of Dayton,
Tulsa's Bill Self and Mike Brey of Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Braine insisted that Hewitt was not a consolation pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the first choice,'' Braine said. ``He is the only one
who has been offered the job, and in no way is Paul some fourth or
fifth choice. Finding a coach who fit our search criteria was of
the utmost importance.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Tech fans expressed dissatisfaction via Internet chat rooms
with the selection of a coach from a mid-major program without a
high profile, and some board members were lobbied to nix the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Braine said he was not aware of such sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that is the case, I haven't heard about it,'' Braine said.
``When Dean Smith was hired at North Carolina, nobody knew who he
was. Three or four years ago, most fans didn't know who Billy
Donovan or Tom Izzo was.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have hired one of the very best and brightest coaches in
the country who came highly recommended.''
</P>
<P>
   Others agree, including George Raveling, who hired Hewitt as a
graduate assistant in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the Final Four ... when the conversation got around to
young coaches,'' Raveling said. ``We all shared the thought that
the two brightest young coaches around were Paul and Tommy Amaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is certainly in the small cluster of young coaches who can
become a Mike Krzyzewski, a Lute Olson, a John Chaney or John
Thompson. Paul goes about things in subtle ways but gets things
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt's immediate concern will be recruiting, with the spring
signing period that begins Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, Cremins signed three players, Brendan Plavich, a
high-scoring guard from Dalton High; Halston Lane, a forward from
Oak Ridge, Tenn.; and Marvin Lewis of Baltimore, one of the top
shooting guards in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   With 7-footer Jason Collier leaving and 6-11 Alvin Jones
considering the NBA draft, adding a center and a power forward is
important.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt also must solidify his staff.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Cantwell, Cremins' longtime aide, wants to seek a
head-coaching job, and Mark Price's plans are uncertain. Willie
Reese, who has held the program together since the season ended,
would like to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
