<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8273 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-HEWITT-PROFILE06-     04-05 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HEWITT-PROFILE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hewitt resume: X's, O's, superb people skills
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Any criticism of the hiring of Paul Hewitt, chosen
Wednesday as Georgia Tech basketball coach, is not new to the man.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, when Hewitt was hired at Siena College, some
people predicted that he was in over his head.
</P>
<P>
   An Albany, N.Y., newspaper columnist wrote: ``Hewitt has been
the top assistant at Villanova. For all of one year. At 33, his
experience at running a program consists of a 1985-88 stint as the
head junior-varsity coach at Westbury High School on Long
Island.... Siena deserves better. Groveling in front of assistants
from big-time programs is not the way to get Siena back on its
feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Hewitt _ who beat out Ron Jirsa, then a Georgia assistant,
to gain the Saints job _ revived a program that had won only 23
games the previous three years at the 2,300-student Jesuit school.
</P>
<P>
   Associates say Hewitt is positioned to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a great job for me,'' Villanova coach Steve Lappas said
Wednesday, ``and he did wonders at Siena. With all Georgia Tech has
to offer _ a good school, in a great city and outstanding
conference _ there's no reason to believe Paul won't be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul is a very good communicator. He will relate well to the
kids, with professors and the community. It's a great hire.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Southern Cal coach George Raveling, who works for Nike,
is effusive in complimenting Hewitt, who served one season as his
graduate assistant at Southern Cal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul's quiet and reserved but very, very bright,'' Raveling
said. ``He is an excellent coach who is a players' coach but is
able to get close to them without having to sacrifice his authority
or leadership philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just has great people skills. The high school coaches in
the state, and the Atlanta community, will embrace him. You have to
work hard not to like Paul Hewitt.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, who attended high school on Long Island, always has made
education a priority. He earned an undergraduate degree in
journalism and economics from St. John Fisher College, a highly
rated private school in Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   He has emphasized education at Siena, and the class he signed
for next season averaged nearly 1,100 on the SAT.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt also is a good promoter. He used a fast-paced offensive
attack and relentless defensive pressure to help boost Siena's
attendance to a record 7,000 per game.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's Hewitt the person that people rave about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (athletics director) Dave (Braine), you will never have
any problems with Paul,'' Raveling said. ``He will never lie to
you, and he will never resort to cheating. He's a fine young man.''
</P>
<P>
   THE PAUL HEWITT FILE
</P>
<P>
   Born: May 4, 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Playing experience: Westbury High, Long Island, N.Y.; four-year
letterman at guard for St. John Fisher College, Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching experience: C.W. Post, assistant (1988-89); Southern
Cal, graduate assistant (1989-90); Fordham, assistant coach
(1990-92); Villanova, assistant head coach (1992-97); Siena
College, head coach (1997-2000).
</P>
<P>
   Career highlights: Helped sign Top 20-rated recruiting classes
at Villanova; turned around Siena program that was 23-59 in three
seasons before he arrived; went 17-12 the first season and reached
the MAAC Tournament final; was 25-6 in '99 and won the MAAC
Tournament to make the NCAA field; was 24-9 last season and beat
UMass in the NIT before losing to Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Wife Dawnette; daughters Olivia, Danielle and Kayla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
