<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-KHAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KHANNOUCHI: NO CITIZENSHIP, NO MARATHON TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world record-holder Khalid Khannouchi said Wednesday that he
would not participate in the U.S. Olympic marathon trials on May 7
unless he receives citizenship in the next few days. According to
his Houston-based lawyer, Harry Gee, Khannouchi would not get his
citizenship that quickly because the marathoner had not been
persistent enough to complete the already expedited process.
</P>
<P>
   The Moroccan native said that he would consider trying to make
the American team at 5,000 or 10,000 meters if he received his
citizenship before the Olympic track-and-field trials, which are
scheduled July 14-23 in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Track and Field Federation said it would allow
Khannouchi to participate in the marathon trials in Pittsburgh if
it received an official notice from the Immigration and
Naturalization Service saying that he would be sworn in as a
citizen before the Summer Olympics in September in Sydney,
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   However, Khannouchi said he was sensitive to criticism from some
American runners, who do not believe he should compete in the
trials if he was not yet a U.S. citizen. Another complicating
factor is the London Marathon, which Khannouchi is scheduled to run
on April 16 for a six-figure payday.
</P>
<P>
   His contract stipulates that he can withdraw from London up to a
week before the race if he received his American citizenship,
Khannouchi said. That cutoff date would be Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   If he runs London, he said he would not run the American trials
three weeks later, despite previous speculation by friends who said
that he would consider it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't logical to do two marathons in three weeks,''
Khannouchi said in a telephone interview from Madrid, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Sandra Khannouchi, said on March 29 the couple had
filed papers with the INS office in Houston seeking to expedite
Khalid Khannouchi's citizenship under a provision that speeds up
the naturalization process if a spouse has an overseas job with an
American company. This provision, most often used by the military,
was used to secure American citizenship for the French soccer
player David Regis in time for the 1998 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   For several weeks, Sandra Khannouchi said, she has been working
in Madrid as a recruiter and promoter for Elite Racing Inc., an
American firm that puts on events such as the Rock-'n'-Roll
Marathon in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Gee said there was an 80 percent chance that Khannouchi would
have received his citizenship under the spousal-job provision by
the May 3 entry date for the U.S. marathon trials if the runner had
set a higher priority for naturalization.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Gee said, Khannouchi was scheduled to be
fingerprinted in Houston Wednesday, and the fingerprints were to be
submitted to the INS in a meeting Thursday. However, Khannouchi is
out of the country. ``We could get it done if he'd get over here,''
Gee said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, who is working on the case without pay, said he was
unaware that Khannouchi was scheduled to run the London Marathon,
and that he would skip the American trials if he did, until
informed Wednesday by a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't been smart,'' Gee said of Khannouchi. ``He
definitely should have shared what his goals and objectives might
be. We thought eligibility for the Olympics was his top priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the London payday, Gee said, ``It sounds like he
took a bird in hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he could run the marathon trials without being a
citizen, Khannouchi said he would not. He said that he had been
stung by criticism from other American marathoners, including Keith
Brantly, a 1996 Olympian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never go to the trials if I am not an American
citizen,'' Khannouchi said. ``It doesn't feel right. I don't want
them to see me as a foreigner. It will damage my reputation. There
will be too much controversy. I am not doing it to make money. I am
doing it to promote the sport and to give something back to the
country that supported me.''
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi, who lives in Ossining, N.Y., and who set the world
record of 2 hours 5 minutes 42 seconds at the 1999 Chicago
Marathon, came to the United States in 1993 to participate in the
World University Games. Unhappy with his support from the Moroccan
track federation, he moved to Brooklyn, married Sandra Natal, a
naturalized American, and applied for American citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   His case was frozen when the INS agent who interviewed him was
accused of taking bribes and left the agency. Because he did not
become a permanent U.S. resident until 1998, Khannouchi would not
be eligible for citizenship on the basis of marrying an American
until 2001. That is why he is using the special spousal-job
provision.
</P>
<P>
   He would be the favorite in the Olympic marathon, but he would
face stiff competition for a medal at 5,000 and 10,000 meters,
where his best times, 13:24 and 27:45, respectively, have been run
on the road.
</P>
<P>
   He would also need permission from Morocco to compete in the
Sydney Olympics, but Moroccan track officials have said they would
not interfere. (JT)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
