r f BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      04-05 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ONE SHOULD GET COMPLACENT ABOUT JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The company said a couple of months ago that
it no longer could compete with other publications unless it
reduced the expenses of the business news desk. It will cut costs
by ``outsourcing'' the desk, turning operations over to outside
contractors.
</P>
<P>
   We business writers and editors, many of us with 15, 20, even 25
years of experience, were told we would be laid off. Reporters were
told they could reapply with an organization that had been
contracted to manage reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The company said editors could buy, at a nominal monthly cost,
their computers, telephones and other tools of the trade, but
they'd have to work as free-lancers after applying to an
independent contractor hired to manage them.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario, of course, is a metaphor. We still have our jobs _
for now. Other workers do not. Hundreds of workers in Kansas City
and Springfield have been hit with that kind of change.
</P>
<P>
   The current wrangle between Associated Wholesale Grocers and the
Teamsters union is worth heeding, no matter how you view contract
disputes between organized labor and owners. Even if you feel
immune in a nonunion, ``merit-based,'' white-collar world, the
scenario should shake any job-related complacency you may have.
</P>
<P>
   Outsourcing. Re-engineering. Reorganizing. Downsizing.
Rightsizing. Layoffs. Whatever the label, workers lose jobs all the
time, and not necessarily through performance faults of their own.
Owners across industries make staffing changes they think they need
to make to compete and increase profits. The changes often
eliminate or greatly alter jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's possible to pin this kind of job loss on
intractable union leadership that fails to negotiate in the best
interests of its membership. Sometimes it's the fault of bad-faith
bargaining by owners. Sometimes it's about mutual failure to change
us vs. them cultures of entitlement into cultures of shared
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   It's always about economic reality. Those who control the assets
can, as they always have, allocate them as they please. That's why
collective bargaining grew to protect workers. That's also partly
why the power of unions has waned.
</P>
<P>
   But don't pass off the conflict between Associated and the
Teamsters as a clash of workplace dinosaurs who would rather claw
each other to death than communicate. The next job loss you hear
about might not be because of a declared impasse in union
negotiations. It might be any owner's choice to increase
``competitive efficiencies'' as he or she sees fit.
</P>
<P>
   A Teamster on the picket line said he felt betrayed and bitter.
Anyone who has ignored or felt insulated from this inexorable sweep
of change would feel the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Pay attention to the hallmarks of Generations X and Y: loyalty
to no employer and focus on self-directed careers. Younger workers
understand inexorable change, the demand for adaptability and
self-responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   They know there is no job security, no entitlement in exchange
for service, no corporate or union cocoon, no tenure or benefit
plan that provides fail-safe job protection. Dinosaurs they are
not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0410 </DOCNO>
