<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAREHOUSEONE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAREHOUSE ONE REWARDS OWNER AS IT GATHERS AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Mary Lou Jacoby's philosophy is simple: If
you're handed lemons, it's time to make lemonade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love a challenge,'' said Jacoby, president and chief
executive of Warehouse One. Her company sells, recycles, trades and
reconditions warehouse, retail and office equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Where many people would have seen mountains of junk, unskilled
workers and a dilapidated building, Jacoby saw potential.
</P>
<P>
   She started on a shoestring budget in 1986 when she bought a
building at 33rd Street and Forest Avenue filled with surplus
factory seconds and used merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Jacoby got the opportunity to haul away in one
weekend everything left over as Macy's closed its downtown store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know I knew so many people with pickup trucks,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Warehouse One has about 60 employees at its
400,000-square-foot warehouse near Interstates 435 and 70.
</P>
<P>
   Sales have climbed about 30 percent each year, to $6.6 million
in 1999. About 21 percent of that business is in Kansas City, 23
percent is within 150 miles and the remainder is national.
</P>
<P>
   Working Woman magazine recently named Warehouse One a regional
winner in its second annual Working Woman Entrepreneurial
Excellence Awards.
</P>
<P>
   A pink sign hangs at the entrance of the company's headquarters,
a building that is gradually being renovated. The pink is
intentional.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed something to differentiate ourselves from the rest
of the companies in our business,'' said Jacoby, who was wearing a
trademark pink blazer one day last week. ``It seemed logical that
one of the differences was that I am female. Rather than a
negative, I thought it was a positive. The pink represents the fact
that we are unique and very human. We're very concerned about the
customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby offers two employees a ride as she drives her pink golf
cart through the huge warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   The millions of items include mountains of light fixtures,
conveyor belts and shelving, as well as rooms of new and
reconditioned office furniture.
</P>
<P>
   The primary source of this stock is Fortune 500 companies that
are downsizing, moving or upgrading their warehousing operations,
offices or retail locations. Supplies also come from growing and
expanding small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the unique items she has discovered over the
years, such as the Santa Claus that had been at the downtown Macy's
department store.
</P>
<P>
   Many of her clients are small and midsize businesses seeking
quality items at discounted prices. Customers include Fortune 500
companies that are Warehouse One suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortune 500 companies are learning the economics of buying
reconditioned or used equipment,'' Jacoby said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Keefer, warehouse manager at the Westlake Ace Hardware
distribution center in Lenexa, Kan., said his company selected
Warehouse One because of ``the price and the products they had.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the stuff we bought was brand new,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby said many of her clients were repeat customers who trade
in equipment when they are ready to grow.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is e-commerce. Already, the Internet is making
sales much easier because clients can view products and place an
order within minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While Jacoby is proud of the company's growth, she is also proud
of the effect the business has had on its employees, the
neighborhood and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the company was honored by the Missouri Waste Control
Coalition for its commitment to waste conservation, recycling and
disposal.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Warehouse One recycled 9 million tons of surplus,
overstock, industry seconds and outdated equipment. It expects that
number to increase to more than 13 million tons in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Initiative for Competitive Inner City also selected
Warehouse One as one of its ``Inner City Top 100'' in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always accepted our inner-city location as an advantage,''
Jacoby said. ``The part of the city we're in has a population that
has a good work ethic; people want to work.''
</P>
<P>
   More than half the employees come from the immediate
neighborhood, and many do not have a high school degree. But more
than 60 percent have been with the company at least five years.
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby attributes the longevity to the family atmosphere. It's a
place where on Fridays the youngest member of the staff, Jacoby's
grandson Sterling Boone, takes lunch orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good fit for the type of business we are,'' Jacoby
said. ``We recycle stuff, we recycle people, we recycle property.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
