<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8283 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-APPEAL-NYT &LR;      04-05 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-APPEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEDERAL JUDGE MAKES USE OF AN OBSCURE RULE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Stung after a major reversal by his superiors on
the appeals court on a central issue in the Microsoft antitrust
case nearly two years ago, Federal District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson has responded in kind this week.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Jackson took the unusual path of rebuking the appeals
court, casting aside its reasoning as ``not formally binding'' and
rebuking them for failing to follow the Supreme Court precedents
``in at least three respects.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court had found that Jackson was wrong on the law
when he ordered Microsoft to immediately unbundle its Windows
operating system and its Internet Explorer Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, the tactical thinking behind Jackson's unusual
criticism became clear. Reminding lawyers at a status meeting in
his chambers of an obscure appeals rule, he indicated he would help
government lawyers to bypass the United States Court of Appeals
entirely and take any appeals by Microsoft directly to the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the Antitrust Expediting Act, the rule gives a federal
district judge the power to certify any final judgment in a civil
lawsuit brought under the Sherman Antitrust Act to be ripe for
immediate review by the Supreme Court if the appeal ``is of general
public importance to the administration of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The rule is now rarely invoked. But it could shave a year or
more off of the appeals that Microsoft has already vowed to pursue,
a significant amount of time in a rapidly changing industry. Both
Jackson and the government's lawyers have said they want the case
resolved before the issues become moot.
</P>
<P>
   The expediting act, thus, enables the government to circumvent
an appeals court that has already handed a significant defeat to
the government by overturning a Microsoft decision by Jackson and,
with the same reasoning, could do it again. It would permit the
case to be put on the Supreme Court docket as early as next term,
which begins in October.
</P>
<P>
   But for all of its promise in moving the two-year-old case along
to a speedier conclusion, it is far from certain whether any
Microsoft appeals will ultimately be expedited. While many lawyers
expect that the Justice Department will ultimately seek to put the
appeals on a fast track, officials in both the antitrust division
and solicitor general's office said Wednesday that no decision had
been made about whether to accept Jackson's invitation, and that
none would be announced before the completion of the remedies phase
of the case this summer.
</P>
<P>
   And even if the government seeks an expedited appeal, the
Supreme Court cannot hear the case unless four justices vote to put
it on the calendar. Experts in appellate procedure said it would be
a marked departure for the court to take the Microsoft case
directly if it presented a long laundry list of appeals issues.
</P>
<P>
   But they said that it was impossible to know whether the
justices would be willing to review Jackson's work rather than send
it back to the appeals court first to narrow some of the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly possible the justices would take the case, but
it would be a challenge for them to deal with such a voluminous
record,'' said Mark Levy, a former official at the Justice
Department involved in appellate litigation and now in private
practice.
</P>
<P>
   In his decision on Monday, the judge concluded that the company
violated Section 1 of the Sherman Antitrust Act by bundling its
Windows operating system software with its Internet Explorer
browser. Two years ago, a federal appeals panel found that the
bundling did not appear to violate Section 1 and reversed an
injunction by Jackson that had ordered the company to separate the
two software packages.
</P>
<P>
   The judge replied in his opinion that the appeals court's
decision was ``inconsistent with the pertinent Supreme Court
precedents'' and ``not formally binding.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the century, all final judgments in civil antitrust
suits brought under the Sherman Antitrust Act would automatically
go directly from the district court to the Supreme Court. But
Congress changed the law in 1978, making expedited appeals
discretionary.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the rule has been used sparingly. It was used twice
by the government in the AT&AMP;T antitrust case heard by Federal
District Judge Harold H. Greene. In both cases, the Supreme Court
accepted the appeals and then summarily upheld Greene without
hearing any arguments on the merits. &QL; 
(af)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
