<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PA-HOUSE-RACES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENN.   PRIMARIES PUT FOCUS ON CONGRESSIONAL RACES
</HEADLINE>
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With polls showing Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George
W. Bush running neck-and-neck for Pennsylvania's 23 electoral
votes, the state was already one to watch in November. Now the
results from congressional primaries on Tuesday make it even more
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   More congressional races appear to be in doubt in Pennsylvania
than in most states, so the state could play a significant role in
determining which party will control the House and the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate contest bids to be among the nation's hardest fought.
So do races in three congressional districts _ the 4th, 10th and
13th.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate primary, Rep. Ron Klink, a 48-year-old moderate
Democrat from the Pittsburgh area, was nominated to take on the
Republican incumbent, Rick Santorum, 41, a conservative who is
facing his first re-election battle and had no opposition in the
primary. Klink, first elected to the House in 1992, defeated six
other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have had Santorum in their cross hairs ever since he
squeaked into office five years ago with a winning margin of just 2
percentage points. They say he is too conservative for Pennsylvania
and not collegial enough to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   Santorum has said that he was willing to stand on his record
because ``it's a good record _ I know it's a good record.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the three Pennsylvania House races that will be closely
watched this fall, the one in the 4th District to choose a
successor to Klink shapes up as the hottest.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican nominee, state Sen. Melissa Hart, faced no
primary opposition and goes into the fall contest with her treasury
intact.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democratic primary winner, state Rep. Terry Van Horne,
is not the candidate many state and national party leaders had
hoped to nominate. Their choice had been Matthew Mangino, a
district attorney from Western Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The upset was embarrassing enough by itself for the party
leaders. But on top of that came more trouble _ a Republican
accusation on Wednesday, based on a 6-year-old newspaper clipping,
that Van Horne had once used a racial slur to describe a black
state legislator.
</P>
<P>
   According to the clipping, Van Horne subsequently ``tearfully
apologized.'' Nevertheless, Rep. Thomas Davis III, R-Va., the head
of the National Republican Congressional Committee, saw a political
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats woke up this morning with an unelectable
candidate with a frightening past,'' Davis said in a statement.
``I'd be surprised if most voters would want to have anything to do
with Van Horne.''
</P>
<P>
   The race in Pennsylvania's 10th Congressional District, in the
northeast corner, is a rerun of one of the closest races in the
nation in 1998. The winner of that contest, Rep. Don Sherwood, a
Republican, defeated his Democratic opponent, Pat Casey, a son of
former Gov. Robert Casey, by 515 votes. On Tuesday, Pat Casey won
the Democratic nomination a second time _ and with it a second shot
at Sherwood.
</P>
<P>
   In the 13th Congressional District, outside Philadelphia,
Republicans nominated state Sen. Stewart J. Greenleaf to face the
Democratic incumbent, Joseph Hoeffel. Hoeffel was narrowly elected
in 1998, and national Republican leaders believe Greenleaf has a
good chance defeat him this fall.
</P>
<P>
   (mg)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
