radios are going high tech, with additional features you'd never
expect. From left: The Motorola T6100 weighs 6 ounces, uses
rechargable NiMH, or three AA batteries, features a compass,
altimeter, barometer and thermometer and will cost $160, when
available; the Kenwood UBZ-LH14 weighs 6.3 ounces, uses three AA
batteries, features a scrambler for privacy and four call tones and
costs about $90; the Cobra FRS-310WX weighs 6 ounces, uses four AAA
batteries, features a scrambler, weather radio and ``roger beep,''
and costs about $95; the Audiovox FR-314 weighs 5.5 ounces, uses
rechargable NiMH, or three AA batteries, features seven call tones
and voice activation and costs about $85. (Tony Cenicola/The New
York Times)
