<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8291 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-BEDS-TWOTAKES-KAN &LR;      04-05 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEDS-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONATIONS FROM MATTRESS MAKER FOLLOW SENATOR'S ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ Just three months after state Sen. Bill
Kenney pushed through legislation sought by the bedding industry,
Missouri's largest bed-springs maker began cutting checks totaling
$100,000 to Kenney's campaign for lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   The money from Leggett &AMP; Platt Inc. _ four $25,000 checks
written in August and September _ represent 43 percent of all
contributions Kenney took in last year, campaign finance records
show. The first check was received Aug. 28, the day the new law
took effect.
</P>
<P>
   Both Kenney and a spokesman for Carthage-based Leggett &AMP; Platt
denied any connection between the contributions and the
legislation, which requires large warning labels on refurbished
mattresses.
</P>
<P>
   But critics said the sequence of events was troubling. Sen. Joe
Maxwell, who is seeking the Democratic nomination for lieutenant
governor, said a contribution of $100,000 from a single supporter
created undue influence no matter how Kenney explained his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no evidence that there was a quid pro quo,'' Maxwell
said. ``But it raises questions about improprieties and whether a
deal was cut in regards to that legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of how the bedding bill became law provides a long
look at the legislative process, the influence of lobbyists and the
effect of limitless campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Kenney, a Lee's Summit Republican, said he maneuvered the
bedding provision into law to protect consumers from unscrupulous
mattress sellers, especially those who prey on low-income residents
of inner cities.
</P>
<P>
   Without the warning labels, he said, mattresses with
contaminated, bug-infested linings often are sold as new. And
buyers can suffer severe health consequences from bacteria and
fungi embedded in the mattress, Kenney said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kenney said he owned ``a few thousand shares'' of
Leggett &AMP; Platt stock, he said he never considered how the
legislation might help the company, which sells nearly $2 billion
of new-mattress and other furniture components every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone wants to sell shoddy, used, urinated, bed-stained
mattresses and cover them with fabric (and sell them as new), I'm
saying, `You can't do that,' '' Kenney said. ``I don't want the
consumer buying something that they think is something else.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department of Health staff, however, recommended the
governor veto the bill, contending that it sought to fix a
nonexistent problem and created a regulatory nightmare for the
state. Pam Walker, director of the department's Division of
Environmental Health, said she viewed the bill as part of a turf
war between bedspring makers and recyclers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coil makers are the ones who benefit financially from this
(new law) because it's the coils that get recycled,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   John Cuaderes, Leggett &AMP; Platt's chief lobbyist, said the
company supported Kenney's legislation as a way to protect
consumers. But the company did not actively lobby for the measure,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leggett &AMP; Platt, he said, made a six-figure contribution to
Kenney because of his conservative, pro-business philosophy. The
company contributed $100,000 to U.S. Rep. Jim Talent's Republican
campaign for governor for the same reason, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Kenney is a person we believe in,'' Cuaderes said. ``His
philosophy is aligned with southwest Missouri. He shares the same
beliefs we do, period. If we gave contributions because we wanted
to pass legislation, we wouldn't be giving to Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, which started in 1883 as a maker of spiral steel
bedspring coils, still sells bedsprings, bed frames and foam
padding to mattress manufacturers. That division reported 1999
sales of $1.95 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Kenney said the company had supported him since he first ran for
the Senate in 1994. Campaign finance records show Leggett &AMP; Platt
executives contributed at least $4,920 to Kenney's unsuccessful run
for lieutenant governor in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   For this year's campaign, Kenney said he asked company
executives last summer for $100,000 _ and they delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Kenney said he MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
