<SLUG> BC-BEDS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONATIONS FROM MATTRESS MAKER FOLLOW SENATOR'S ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ ....they delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Kenney said he got involved in mattress legislation in 1998
after he saw Cuaderes in the hallway at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``John told me that (Rep.) Chuck Gross has this good bill, it
will really help consumers,'' Kenney said.
</P>
<P>
   Gross, a St. Charles Republican, had sponsored a similar bill in
1997. That bill required a refurbished mattress to contain a label
warning that it was a ``used article and sterilized.''
</P>
<P>
   Gross said he was inspired to file the bill by an episode of
``Dateline NBC'' that showed mattress refurbishers in New York that
bought mattresses that had been left on the street and in
landfills. The mattresses were re-covered, then sold as new.
</P>
<P>
   Rancid smells soon began coming from the mattresses. Tests on
reconditioned mattresses bought in New York, Maryland and
California found none had been properly sterilized, the show said.
</P>
<P>
   Gross' bill went nowhere. In 1998, Gross filed a similar
measure, and Kenney filed a Senate version. Neither reached the
Senate or House floor.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Gross hooked up with the International Sleep Products
Association, a Virginia group that represents companies that make
new mattresses or their components. Leggett &AMP; Platt is a member.
</P>
<P>
   The association recommended changes to make the bill match model
legislation the group was pushing in several states. Kenney filed a
similar bill in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   This time the label was to say, ``This bedding contains
previously used materials which have been cleaned and sanitized in
a reasonable manner to kill germs and insects and to prevent
infection.''
</P>
<P>
   Association Vice President Andrea Herman said the wording was
not intended to discourage sales of refurbished beds. The wording,
she said, gives consumers ``a sense of confidence that the mattress
has been cleaned and sanitized.''
</P>
<P>
   Herman estimated that 10,000 to 15,000 refurbished mattresses a
year were sold in Missouri without labels showing the mattress had
been rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, Missouri's environmental health director, said she
viewed the labeling as overkill. The state, she said, had not
received a complaint about renovated mattresses in decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't view this as a public health threat,'' Walker said.
``We would rather see old mattresses recycled than end up in a
landfill.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell said the labeling bill was a marketing tool for mattress
makers aimed at reducing sales of refurbished mattresses to motels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, no one wants to check into a hotel, lift up the
sheets and tell their wife, `Honey, this thing had to be
disinfected and the bugs killed.' If you're a hotel owner, you're
not going to buy that mattress,'' Maxwell said.
</P>
<P>
   When the bill reached the Senate, however, Sen. Jerry Howard
stripped out the bedding provisions. Howard, a Dexter Democrat who
is chairman of the Senate Aging, Families and Mental Health
Committee, said the mattress issues violated the law against a bill
involving unrelated matters.
</P>
<P>
   The bill came to the Senate floor May 13, the next to last day
of the session. Kenney rose and offered an amendment to add back
the bedding provisions. Howard argued that bedding regulation was
not germane to nursing homes. A debate ensued.
</P>
<P>
   In the waning days of a legislative session, extended debate can
be a bill's death knell.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the wee hours, any time spent on a bill is critical,''
Howard said. ``Everyone is anxious their bill won't be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   In the back of the Senate chamber, Howard huddled with other
senators. He said he was told that Kenney's allies in the Senate
would continue to debate the matter unless Howard allowed the
bedding provision to go on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Howard relented, and the bill was approved unanimously.
</P>
<P>
   In a June 3 memo, the Department of Health's Walker recommended
that the governor veto the bill. It had conflicting definitions of
bedding, the memo said. And it violated privacy rights by requiring
a refurbished mattress label to list the name and address of the
previous owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information required on these labels does not directly or
indirectly reflect, or have any impact on, the safety or
healthfulness of the bedding,'' the memo said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Mel Carnahan, however, did not want to lose the nursing
home reforms, and he signed the bill on July 13.
</P>
<P>
   Kenney said he knew that taking large checks from Leggett &AMP;
Platt would open him up to criticism. But he said it was no
different than state Treasurer Bob Holden taking contributions from
bankers or Joe Maxwell, a lawyer, taking money from trial
attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigns depend on money, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have said (to Leggett &AMP; Platt), `Why don't you call
the presidents of all your subsidiaries and see if they'll give me
the money?' I took the chance by taking large checks because I knew
I had never done anything wrong,'' Kenney said. ``My record's
clean.''
</P>
</TEXT>
