u s BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT &LR;      04-05 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A THEATER OF TRADITION DEMANDING POISE TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Of the top 60 players in the current world golf
ranking, only four have won the Masters _ Tiger Woods, Mark
O'Meara, Fred Couples and Jose Maria Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   If you have won at Augusta National Golf Club, you belong to an
exclusive group. It is a tournament steeped in tradition, in an
atmosphere that demands poise, and is played on a course that
demands excellence. The world's best golfers have been
concentrating on this week for months, hoping to be at their best
for the 64th Masters, which begins Thursday morning. Ninety-five
players will vie for one precious green jacket, with enough
potential drama to make millions pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   Will Woods continue his recent dominance, and win his third
major tournament, at the age of 24? Will David Duval, Colin
Montgomerie or Phil Mickelson win that elusive first major? Can
Greg Norman, the sentimental favorite, finally find a happy ending
in his 20th Masters? Or will someone unexpected enjoy the thrill of
walking up the 18th fairway and into history?
</P>
<P>
   As the tournament unfolds, there will be pivotal shots and
swings in momentum. But here are some points to ponder as one of
the special events in sports gets under way.
</P>
<P>
   LONG-BALL HITTERS DON'T ALWAYS WIN _ Players talk about length
being an advantage at Augusta, but in the last 10 years, only two
power players have won: Woods (1997) and Fred Couples (1992).
Olazabal, who won both last year and in 1994, would admit that
driving is the weakest part of his game. And none of the other
winners in the 1990s _ O'Meara (1998), Nick Faldo (1990, 1996), Ben
Crenshaw (1995), Bernhard Langer (1993) and Ian Woosnam (1991) _
would win a long-driving contest among their peers .
</P>
<P>
   While length is an advantage, you can't win at Augusta without
superb distance control on approach shots, a solid short game and
excellent putting. A huge drive followed by a poor second shot will
put you in a defensive position, making Augusta's lightning-fast
greens even more treacherous. But those who consistently put their
approach shots on the proper part of the green, then capitalize by
making putts, will have a strong chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Masters has always been a thinking man's tournament, and it
continues to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to play extremely aggressive here and start firing
at flags, you'll have three-putts,'' Norman said. ``All of a sudden
your mind changes and it's hard to regroup. This is one of those
classic golf courses where you have to shoot for a target on the
green, and sometimes that target may be no more than 10 square
feet. But you have to hit that spot to putt with confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY SUCCESS IS NOT SUNDAY GLORY _ No first-round leader has
won the Masters since Crenshaw in 1984. Many players have shot one
low round at Augusta. Far fewer have put together four days good
enough to win. The tournament is mentally taxing, and the
conditions can change dramatically with the weather. Windy days at
the Masters can blow contenders off the leader board. So having the
lead Thursday is no reason to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   THE FOREIGN-PLAYER FACTOR _ Eight of the last 12 Masters have
been won by non-Americans. There are 35 non-Americans in this
year's field, including two who have played well recently at
Augusta National. Darren Clarke of Northern Ireland finished fourth
in 1998, and Lee Westwood of England finished sixth last year.
</P>
<P>
   WHO IS LIKELY TO WIN? _ Surprisingly, some prominent players
have struggled at the Masters. Montgomerie, Ernie Els, Hal Sutton
and Vijay Singh have never finished in the top five. And no player
has won in his first Masters appearance since Fuzzy Zoeller in
1979, a bad omen for Masters' rookies like the defending British
Open champion, Paul Lawrie, and Mike Weir, who is ranked No. 40 in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Those with recent strong finishes at Augusta include Duval, who
tied for second in 1998; Jim Furyk, who finished fourth in 1998;
Davis Love III, who finished second last year; and Mickelson, who
finished second in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the attention will be directed toward Woods, who
enters the tournament with three victories this year, and 10 in his
last 17 starts on the PGA Tour. Jack Nicklaus, who has won the
Masters a record six times, said that Woods' recent streak ranks
among the most impressive he has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that during the last six or eight months, Tiger is
playing better than I ever played, but I don't think a career is
made over six months,'' said Nicklaus, who won 18 major
professional championships. ``If he keeps going the way he's been
going, he's going to break all my records. A lot will depend on his
health and his desire to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he has the ability to make himself do something when he
needs to. That's the mark of champion. You're not going to keep
Tiger from playing well. He's too good a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Woods' record-setting 12-stroke victory in 1997 at the
Masters, however, he tied for eighth place in 1998 and tied for
18th last year. There are no guarantees at Augusta, and there have
been many unexpected winners. So while Woods enters as the
favorite, many players liked their chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want it badly,'' Norman said. ``It doesn't matter how
you're playing when you come here. When you get here, you want
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
