<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTERS MIGHT WITNESS PASSING OF TORCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Fittingly, Jack Nicklaus, Arnold Palmer and Gary
Player are paired together today in the first round of the Masters
tournament that they lifted like a priceless antique and carried
lovingly into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus, Palmer and Player won eight of the nine Masters
contested between 1958-1966. Among them, they have 13 green jackets
and 34 Grand Slam titles. They ushered in golf's Golden Age.
</P>
<P>
   And now, this first year of a new decade affords the threesome
the perfect opportunity to step aside and let the next terrific
triad play through.
</P>
<P>
   If CBS were on top of its game, it would orchestrate the passing
of the torch from Nicklaus, Palmer and Player to Tiger Woods,
Sergio Garcia and Aaron Baddeley. For the opening montage of its
telecast it would gather them all on Augusta National Golf Course's
putting green, soften the camera's focus, start the film rolling
and cue the violins.
</P>
<P>
   The era drawing to a close in golf and the one alighting are as
different as TV and DVD, Levittown and Islesworth, private lives
and private jets.
</P>
<P>
   As tough as it was for Palmer to make his first million and for
Nicklaus to win a following and for Player to stave off jet lag,
the stresses and strains facing Woods, Garcia and Baddeley will be
in many ways worse. The next set of torchbearers will carry the
burden of success but also of savage scrutiny. Since Nicklaus won
his last major here in 1986, the world has shrunk and the celebrity
culture has swelled so much it can swallow its young.
</P>
<P>
   The clamoring for information on today's public figures in this
24/7 news age knows no bounds. Goodness knows, a 20-year-old Palmer
never had to sit in front of a hundred reporters from all over the
world as Sergio Garcia did here Wednesday and answer the question,
``Is that a long-term relationship?''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that to the average 20-year-old, anything with a
shelf life longer than potato salad qualifies as enduring. Forget
that the question was about the working arrangement between Garcia
and his caddie, for crying out loud.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta National's slick, sloping greens must look tame to
Generation Next compared to the challenge of navigating adolescence
knowing perfect strangers are watching, pens poised to record every
step and stumble.
</P>
<P>
   It's an awkward time in a boy's life no matter how purely he can
strike a golf ball. Garcia might have come within two strokes of
beating Woods at the PGA Championship last August, but two months
earlier he had to withdraw from a tournament in Memphis after
suffering a severe acne attack.
</P>
<P>
   The number of pimples on his face was infinitesimal next to the
number of people who knew they were there. Talk about adding insult
to indignity.
</P>
<P>
   At the tender age of 24, Woods already is a seared veteran of
mass scrutiny. He has taken heat for telling a tasteless joke or
two, for being moody, for being self-involved. For, in short,
acting his age.
</P>
<P>
   During the PGA Championship last year, Woods was criticized for
looking too grim on the course by the same people who pop antacid
pills as their story deadlines draw near. After five years on the
PGA Tour, Woods is hip to the hypocrisy. He moves within a circle
of close friends who are less an entourage than a cocoon. They
protect him from all the rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier (being in the spotlight) now because I have
a better understanding of myself and what goes on around me,''
Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just grown up a little bit through trial and error and
experiences, just like everybody else my age.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody wants to work as hard on his public persona as he
does his golf game. Fred Couples shirks the spotlight and Davis
Love III and David Duval circle it warily. Sometimes it's hard to
blame them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen players who don't want it,'' golfing great Greg
Norman said of the responsibilities that go hand-in-hand with
superstardom. ``They don't want those extra outside pressures. You
don't know what they are until you get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Baddeley, a 19-year-old amateur, officially arrived last
November when he beat Norman and Colin Montgomerie to win the
Australian Open. Woods, who has entertained Baddeley at his home in
the gated Orlando community of Isleworth, says the Australian has
more game than he did at the same age.
</P>
<P>
   Baddeley's parents have reservations about their son turning
professional. They don't want his career to go the way of Justin
Rose's, the English teen who tied for fourth at the 1998 British
Open, turned pro and hasn't been seen on the leaderboard since.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, their son doesn't share their concern. In fact, being
around other pros this week has made the prospect of joining them
``in a way nearly irresistible,'' Baddeley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have so much fun out here,'' Baddeley said. ``The pros
get treated so well. I'm definitely looking forward to being out
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The easy-going Baddeley sees only the free food spreads and the
courtesy cars and the manicured grounds now. All the rest, he'll
have to deal with later.
</P>
<P>
   Or not. The choice, really, will be his.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
