<HEADLINE>
GORE ABRUPTLY CANCELS A NORTH CAROLINA TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore Wednesday abruptly canceled
a campaign trip to North Carolina on Thursday, citing the illness
of a friend. But aides would not disclose the friend's identity and
provided no further details.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was to spend the day at the Marie G. Davis middle school in
Charlotte, N.C., in what would have been the second in a series of
``school days'' the vice president plans to attend. The event was
rescheduled for April 13.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's staff first said the event was canceled for ``personal
reasons.'' Questions about whether Gore or his wife was ill,
though, Gore's communications director, Laura Quinn, issued a
statement saying: ``This is not in any way related to any family
member, nor the health of the Vice President or Gore. It has to do
with the health of a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Several top advisers to Gore said they had no more information.
</P>
<P>
   Gore did speak Wednesday morning to about 2,000 members of the
Construction and Building Trades Department of the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, he vowed to keep Social Security intact and
suggested that Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, his Republican rival,
wanted to privatize the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to pursue a privatization formula that would take a
good bit of the money that is now put into the fund and divert it
toward a private personal savings account,'' Gore said of Bush's
plan. ``He's talking about privatizing it? No way!''
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for Bush, said that Gore was
distorting Bush's plan to allow payees invest part of their payroll
taxes in personal savings accounts. ``That's not really privatizing
it,'' Fleischer said. ``He likes to use attack words.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also referred to his support for ``free and fair trade.''
But he did not mention the coming legislative battle over permanent
normal trade relations for China, which he supports. The AFL-CIO,
which endorsed Gore for president, opposes the pact and plans a
major demonstration against it here next week. (af)
</P>
</TEXT>
