<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARY STEVENS FINDING SUCCESS AS TRAINER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ This week more than most, with a Santa Anita
Derby to be run, it's hard for Gary Stevens to believe he'll never
ride a Stevens won seven of the past 12 Santa Anita Derbies as a
jockey before abruptly retiring in December because of chronic pain
in his arthritic right knee.
</P>
<P>
   If he wins the $1 million race on Saturday, he'll do it in the
normally anonymous role of an assistant trainer, helping to prepare
2-year-old champion Anees for California's premier Kentucky Derby
springboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still having a hard time dealing with it,'' Stevens said
of the end of his Hall of Fame riding career. ``The hard part is
accepting that it's over. I'm 37 years old and what the hell am I
going to do with myself?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great,'' he said, walking through the Santa Anita barn
where he assists Alex Hassinger, trainer of horses owned by Saudi
Prince Ahmed Salman's Thoroughbred Corp. ``But it's not like
riding.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Stevens said, the knee feels so good he envisions a
comeback. But then he'll exercise horses for a couple of days and
need a week of rest for the swelling to go down. Or the weather
will change and a stabbing pain will appear from out of the clouds.
Or a doctor will deliver a second, third or fourth opinion as
gloomy as the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw an orthopedic specialist in New York,'' Stevens said.
``He basically counseled me for 45 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   So, at least until a medical miracle occurs, Stevens leaves
behind a 20-year career in which he rode three Kentucky Derby
winners and seven Breeders' Cup winners.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at 5 o'clock each morning, the son of Pacific Northwest
trainer Ron Stevens devotes himself to learning new aspects of the
craft of horsemanship. From the ground up. His future could hold a
career as a trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wanted to, he'd be a great trainer,'' Hassinger said.
``He has a keen perception of the personalities of these horses . .
. . Everybody thinks of Gary as a Hall of Fame rider, but he's an
extremely experienced horseman. He goes over Anees every day and
probably knows as much as anybody about this horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens' Thoroughbred Corp. riding contract has been reworked.
He's an assistant trainer ``and consultant'' now. For Hassinger,
there must be some advantage in getting advice from the man who
rode Anees to his Breeders' Cup Juvenile victory at Gulfstream Park
last November and has dominated the Santa Anita Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have certain ideas about what it takes for a horse to get to
the grand finale, which is the Kentucky Derby (May 6),'' Stevens
said. ``Fortunately for us, we were set back (by Anees' foot
bruise) at the first of the year, but we were about to get the work
in that we needed and get in the race we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Anees, third behind Fusaichi Pegasus and The Deputy in the March
19 San Felipe Stakes, his only start since the Breeders' Cup,
reminds Stevens most of Thunder Gulch, the colt he rode to victory
in the 1995 Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an improving colt who never came into his own until the
Kentucky Derby,'' Stevens said. ``This colt . . . . he's improving
with every single race. You see steps forward every day he
trains.''
</P>
<P>
   Corey Nakatani is scheduled to ride Anees in the Santa Anita
Derby. Also expected to be entered this morning for the 1-mile race
for 3-year-olds unbeaten San Rafael Stakes winner are War Chant
(Jerry Bailey), San Felipe runnerup The Deputy (Chris McCarron),
leading filly Surfside (Pat Day), Captain Steve (Robby Albarado)
and Cocky (Alex Solis).
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who won the race the past two years with Indian Charlie
and General Challenge, will watch from somewhere other than
horseback for the first time since 1984. Being a trainer in
training doesn't sound like his dream job, but it has one benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only thing that's keeping my mind off not riding,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
