<HEADLINE>
FIRMS PITCH WARES AT INTERNET EXPO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They came in search of customers, strategic
partners, even employees.
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies schlepped their computers, Web cams and
plenty of promotional goodies Wednesday to Spring Internet World
2000, an event organizers say is the largest gathering of Internet
professionals to date.
</P>
<P>
   About 50,000 people registered to attend the show, which will
run through Friday at the Los Angeles Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the wandering masses of Internet professionals and
elaborate booths featuring rock-climbing walls, celebrity
spokespeople and talking robots, Greater San Fernando Valley area
companies ranging from Westlake Village-based Internet service
provider NetZero Inc. to start-ups such as Woodland Hills-based
FocusFocusInc. pitched their products.
</P>
<P>
   For FocusFocus Inc., the trade show represents a chance to
introduce its product, free Web teleconferencing software.
</P>
<P>
   The product is designed to allow smooth operation with a 56K
modem, and it installs quickly on a user's Web site. The product
will allow users to talk to and see each other over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The company had its booth inside the Microsoft Partners
Pavilion, a cluster of companies that have partnerships with
Microsoft Corp. Although FocusFocus could have set up its own
booth, the company partnered with Microsoft to take advantage of a
shared high-speed Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   Jillian Pinsker, co-chief executive officer of FocusFocus, said
the Microsoft booth increased her company's visibility by placing
it at the front of a large exhibit hall rather than in the middle
of a smaller one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This way, we know we're going to get a lot of people,''
Pinsker said.
</P>
<P>
   FocusFocus' goal at the show is attracting investors. The
private company is funded by its parent company, Skyline Tools, but
is entering a second round of financing, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mainly, we're looking for venture partners and strategic
partners,'' Pinsker said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Woolery, senior director of strategic business for
Chatsworth-based DataDirect Networks, used the show to introduce a
new product, SAN DataDirector.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of the network of equipment that manages the flow of
data on the Internet. The SAN DataDirector processes requests and
distributes information more quickly than the current technology,
Woolery said.
</P>
<P>
   The product is designed for companies that access software from
remote locations, called application service providers; Internet
service providers and others who must manage vast stores of data
and distribute them over networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're interested in reaching the folks who build the Internet.
We also want to reach out to a new pool of employees,'' Woolery
said. ``You have the whole gamut here, and we're trying to reach
all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolery said DataDirect hopes to begin shipping the SAN Data
Director in late May or early June. The company, formed in 1998
with the merger of two private companies, plans an initial public
offering early next year.
</P>
<P>
   DataDirect Networks has 140 employees, and hopes to bring that
number to 250 in the next six to nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Van Nuys-based Centerlinq's booth attracted a steady stream of
visitors Wednesday. The company, a division of
GenesisIntermedia.com, places kiosks in malls across the country
offering special deals, coupons and Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Account executive Russell Mayes and his partner, Mark Howard,
came to the show in search of advertising customers and companies
interested in partnering with Centerlinq.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to reach the dot-com people,'' Mayes said. ``We come
in with a new way to advertise dot-com companies.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
