<SLUG> BC-NC-TOBACCO-COMPANIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH CAROLINA ACTS TO PROTECT TOBACCO COMPANIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Va., Ky., Ga.)  (No byline)   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The North Carolina Legislature took just four hours at a special
session Wednesday to pass a law to protect the state's tobacco
companies from potentially industry-crippling penalties in a
class-action smoking lawsuit in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The law, signed by Gov. Jim Hunt, places a $25 million cap on
the amount North Carolina-based companies must post as bond in any
state in appealing a punitive damage verdict.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina is home to three defendants in the lawsuit, the
R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., the Liggett Group and the Lorillard
Tobacco Co. Brown &AMP; Williamson and Philip Morris U.S.A. are also
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   A Miami jury is deciding whether to award compensatory damages
of $13.2 million to three plaintiffs in the class-action suit
involving 500,000 Florida smokers who are ill. Punitive damages in
the case, if awarded, are expected to reach tens of billions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   According to Florida law, a defendant who appeals must post a
bond equal to 115 percent of an award once a judge enters that
verdict. Such a bond could financially ruin tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina law is similar to laws passed recently in
Virginia, Kentucky and Georgia. A federal judge Wednesday struck
down an order barring parties in the Florida suit from talking to
the news media. Judge Adalberto Jordan of U.S. District Court
called the order unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The order, which was imposed in 1998 by Judge Robert Kaye of
Florida Circuit Court, had been challenged by The Wall Street
Journal, The New York Times, USA Today, The Miami Herald, The Tampa
Tribune and the Richmond, Va., Times-Dispatch.
</P>
</TEXT>
