<SLUG> BC-FBC-SCFOOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY ARRIVAL PAYING OFF FOR ROGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If USC's football season started today, the
starting right tackle would be . . . . Jacob Rogers?
</P>
<P>
   In the most surprising development in the opening half of spring
practice, Rogers, a redshirt freshman from Oxnard High who arrived
as a tight end, has moved atop the depth chart _ for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy who has moved above all the others is Jacob Rogers,''
USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``He has a nose up on everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-6 Rogers has gained 50 pounds since arriving at USC
and now weighs 285.
</P>
<P>
   There was a possibility that starting guard Zach Wilson would be
moved to tackle, but Hackett said Wilson will continue to play
right guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing for us is to start Trevor Roberts at left guard
and Zach at right guard,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that helped Rogers, according to Hackett, is that he
graduated early from Oxnard and enrolled at USC in January, 1999,
which allowed him to attend last year's spring drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a heck of a way to do it,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   One side effect of Rogers being the top right tackle is that it
provides a huge opportunity for freshman Joe McGuire to try and win
the spot when he arrives in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe is in the catbird seat in terms of having an
opportunity,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   __ McCaffrey out: Senior offensive tackle Brent McCaffrey
suffered a high ankle sprain in Friday's scrimmage and will miss
the rest of the spring. It's also doubtful that freshman tight end
Chad Cook will return after twisting his knee.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Shamsud-Din Abdul-Shaheed underwent shoulder
surgery Tuesday and will be out the rest of the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole complexion has changed,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   With McCaffrey out, junior Faasea Mailo will be the left tackle.
Redshirt freshman lineman Norm Katnik has moved to tight end on a
temporary basis to replace Cook.
</P>
<P>
   __ Academic problems: Linebacker John Cousins, tight end Antoine
Harris, wide receiver Kareem Kelly and defensive end Omar Nazel are
all sitting out practices this week to concentrate on academics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably have more exact things to say in a couple
days,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   There's a possibility some of the players will not return for
any more spring practices, and might have to attend summer classes
to retain their eligibility. Hackett has kept players out of spring
practices the previous two years to concentrate on academics.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly also might be out of track; he is one of the Trojans' top
sprinters.
</P>
<P>
   __ Scholarship for Nickels? Hackett never has awarded a
scholarship to a walk-on in the spring, but wide receiver Matt
Nickels is close to earning one based on his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt Nickels is making a move,'' Hackett said. ``He's right on
line (for a scholarship).''
</P>
<P>
   Nickels was a high school teammate of Palmer at Santa Margarita
and should be USC's fifth wide receiver behind Kelly, Marcell
Allmond, Steve Stevenson and Keary Colbert.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tight battle: The position that is the intensely contested,
according to Hackett, is tailback, where sophomore Sultan
McCullough and junior Malaefou MacKenzie are vying for the No. 1
spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably the most heated competition on the entire
team,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   The situation could be even more muddled in the fall, when
Banning High tailback Chris Howard arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, junior Kori Dickerson has taken a lead over freshman
Chris Prosser and Cousins at strongside linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   __ Scrimmage Saturday: USC will hold a scrimmage Saturday at 1
p.m. at the Coliseum. Admission is $25 for adults and $20 for
children under 12. Included is a luncheon package. Children under 5
are free.
</P>
</TEXT>
