<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY OF WOMEN; GORE GETS BRADLEY AIDE; VICTORY CLAIMED, NOT WON;
LOTT CHALLENGER SELECTED; GOVERNOR'S BROTHER IS MAYOR
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Includes shorted WOMEN-VOTERS, budgeted earlier) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SURVEY OF WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   A survey for a Democratic women's group, Emily's List, shows
that Vice President Al Gore has made big gains among women in the
last three months and now leads Gov. George W. Bush among women by
46 percent to 40 percent. But the candidates are intensely
competitive among several subgroups of women, including white
suburbanites, married mothers and mainline Protestants. Education
is solidly at the top of women's agenda, according to the poll,
which was conducted March 21-24 and has a margin of error of plus
or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   GORE GETS BRADLEY AIDE
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of his continuing efforts to unite the Democratic
Party, Vice President Al Gore plans to announce on Monday the
endorsements of a group of Bill Bradley's Florida supporters. The
group will be lead by Stephen Pajcic, a Jacksonville lawyer who
raised money for Bradley. Pajcic said he also expects to help raise
money for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   VICTORY CLAIMED, NOT WON
</P>
<P>
   Although the competition has vanished, the Bush campaign
continues to trumpet its victories in Republican primaries. It went
a boast too far on Tuesday. ``Thank you Pennsylvania, Wisconsin and
Kansas,'' read a statement from Gov. George W. Bush that was
electronically mailed to reporters. The problem was that Kansas had
canceled its contest. The campaign seems to have an itchy e-mail
finger: other recent mailings teased Vice President Al Gore for a
mistake that was actually made by a news service that distributed
the information and misidentified Education Secretary Richard Riley
as Bill Riley.
</P>
<P>
   LOTT CHALLENGER SELECTED
</P>
<P>
   In a Mississippi Democratic runoff election Tuesday, Troy Brown
defeated Rickey Cole by a wide margin. Brown, 36, an
African-American who ran unsuccessfully for lieutenant governor
last fall, is now set to face the Senate majority leader, Trent
Lott, in November.
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNOR'S BROTHER IS MAYOR
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Ed Thompson, the brother of Gov. Tommy Thompson of
Wisconsin, was elected mayor of Tomah, a Wisconsin town of about
8,000. Thompson, a former poker player in Las Vegas, entered the
race after his supper club was suspected of illegal operation of
video poker games and raided. The case was settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Sacramento and Martinez, Calif. AL GORE: West
Palm Beach, Fla. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 2242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
