<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8304 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-RUTAN-AIRCRAFT-LADN     04-05 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUTAN-AIRCRAFT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUTAN UNVEILS NEW BREED OF AIRCRAFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM SKEEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOJAVE _ A twin-engine aircraft described as giant leap in
general aviation design rolled out Wednesday at famed designer Burt
Rutan's Scaled Composites Co.
</P>
<P>
   Featuring twin tail booms and propellers at both the front and
back of the fuselage, Adam M-309 flew over about 100 invited guests
at the Mojave Airport, then landed so they could take a closer look
at the craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really taking a modern approach to aircraft,'' said
John Knudsen, president of Colorado-based Adam Aircraft Industries.
``Most airplanes that are out there are based on 40-year-old
designs.''
</P>
<P>
   The product of a collaboration between Rick Adam, founder of
Adam Aircraft, and Scaled Composites, the M-309 is expected to be
manufactured in Denver. First deliveries are expected in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   No price has been set for the airplane, but Adam Aircraft
officials said it will be competitive with other twin-engine
general aviation aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Differing from most other general aviation aircraft, the
airplane is built out of carbon fiber composites and features a
glass cockpit in which traditional analog gauges are replaced with
digital, finger-touch displays.
</P>
<P>
   The six-seat aircraft is just under 32 feet long and has a wing
span of 42 feet. The aircraft is expected to have a top speed of
about 290 mph and a range of over 1,500 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has very, very long range - the range is about twice what
it is for airplanes in its class,'' Rutan said.
</P>
<P>
   While Wednesday's event was the aircraft's official rollout, the
aircraft actually made its first flight March 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not very often you fly a new airplane and the pilot comes
back and says, `There was no squawks, let's go again,''' Rutan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Adam M-309 is also expected to be a step up in terms of safety
compared to other twin-engine aircraft. The positioning of the
engines means that if a pilot were to lose one engine, the aircraft
would maintain its lateral stability.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft will have a low stall speed of about 84 mph,
allowing a pilot to regain control of the aircraft at low speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Adam M-309 is the latest project from Rutan, whose previous work
has ranged from a keel for an America's Cup yacht to fabricating an
experimental aircraft the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration is using to test the design of a space station
``lifeboat.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutan is perhaps best known as the designer of the Voyager
aircraft that his brother, Dick, and Jeana Yeager flown around the
world nonstop on one tank of gas in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
