<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8305 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0406-COX     04-05 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0406-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELIAN'S FATHER COMING TO U.S., SETS UP SHOWDOWN WITH MIAMI
FAMILY
 &HT;    Moving in both International and Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In a major development that sets the stage for a
dramatic showdown in Miami, the father of 6-year-old Cuban rafter
Elian Gonzalez is expected to fly to Washington, D.C. early
Thursday in a bid to regain custody of his son.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez, his second wife and their infant son will
arrive at Washington Dulles International Airport outside the
nation's capitol around 7 a.m. EST, said Gregory Craig, an
influential Washington attorney representing Elian's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for this reunion to go forward,'' Craig told
reporters shortly after he returned to Washington from Havana late
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate reaction from Elian's Miami relatives,
who have cared for the boy since he was rescued at sea on
Thanksgiving Day. The family said months ago they would welcome
Elian's father should he come to the United States, but in the past
week they have thrown up numerous roadblocks to the reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Federal immigration officials maintain that they have the
authority to remove the boy from the Miami family, and have said
they would put Elian in his father's custody should Gonzalez come
to this country.
</P>
<P>
   But the wild card remains Miami's volatile Cuban exile
community, which has turned Elian into a symbol of their struggle
against Cuban President Fidel Castro. A small, but determined group
of protestors has maintained a near-constant vigil outside the
Miami relatives' Little Havana home, vowing to form a human chain
to block any effort to send Elian back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the pending arrival of Elian's father to the United
States was just spreading through Miami late Wednesday, but it
seemed certain the crowd of protestors would swell as the reunion
grew imminent.
</P>
<P>
   But details of the reunion remained unclear. U.S. Immigration
and Naturalization Service officials have been negotiating for the
past week with attorneys for the Miami relatives, but have been
unable to reach an agreement over the timing and location of the
event.
</P>
<P>
   The family has been demanding that an independent team of
psychologists should first examine Elian and determine whether
turning him over to his father is best for the child. They also
want a promise that Elian will remain in the United States until a
federal court battle over the matter is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The family has also said that while they would welcome Elian's
father into their home, they would not assist in taking the boy
elsewhere to meet his father.
</P>
<P>
   Citing unnamed sources, Miami television station WSVN-Channel 7
reported late Wednesday that it may be a week before the reunion
takes place. The family would be served notice and given time to
prepare the boy for the change of custody, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The station also reported that Elian was not at the home of his
great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzales, Wednesday night, but was at an
undisclosed location with his cousin, Marisleysis Gonzalez, who has
been his primary care-giver the past four months.
</P>
<P>
   Marisleysis Gonzalez was released from a Coral Gables hospital
Wednesday after spending the night there following her collapse
from emotional exhaustion early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the rapidly-unfolding events seemed to point toward a climax
of the long-running saga which has placed the little boy with the
angelic face at the center of an international tug-of-war. Elian
was one of the few survivors of an ill-fated trip from Cuba that
left his mother and 10 other people dead after their boat capsized.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials immediately placed the boy with his Miami
relatives, but maintained custody over him.
</P>
<P>
   In January, they ruled he should be returned to his father. The
Miami relatives filed a federal lawsuit to block the decision, but
in March a Miami federal judge ruled against them.
</P>
<P>
   The family appealed to the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in
Atlanta, which is scheduled to hear the case May 11.
</P>
<P>
   Craig indicated that Elian's father would remain in the United
States until the court appeal is resolved. It is believed that he
will live in the home of a Cuban diplomat near Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear late Wednesday whether an entourage of more than
20 other people would be allowed to join him. Castro wants a team
of psychologists, as well as some of Elian's schoolmates, to help
him begin readjusting to life with his Cuban family.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have not yet finished processing travel visa
applications for the entourage.
</P>
<P>
   The key stumbling block still remained the actual transfer of
the boy to his father. Without the Miami family's cooperation,
federal officials are faced with going to the Little Havana home
and taking the boy, an event likely to touch off angry protests and
possibly violence in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno, who has ultimate authority in
the case, has insisted she would do everything possible to avoid
sparking any disturbances. But she has also said the boy will be
placed in the custody of his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Attorney General has been clear that if we can't bring
about this reunion in a cooperative way, she will enforce the
law,'' Bo Cooper, general counsel of the INS, told reporters
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
