<HEADER>
A8314 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MILLIONAIRE-AD-COLUMN     04-05 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLIONAIRE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WANTS TO PARODY `MILLIONAIRE'? THERE IS NO FINAL ANSWER. 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALLISON FASS  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A contestant on the Comedy Central game show ``Win Ben Stein's
Money'' was recently asked this question: ``For $1, what is your
first name?''
</P>
<P>
   As Ben Stein, dressed as Regis Philbin, stood by, the
contestant, named Joe, was offered these choices: a) Santa b)
Moesha c) Jesus and d) Joe.
</P>
<P>
   That parody is just one example of how the media are
capitalizing on the popularity of ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' the ABC game show that has been topping the Nielsen
ratings week after week with Philbin as the host.
</P>
<P>
   Though giveaway shows have always been around _ ``Win Ben
Stein's Money'' itself has run for three seasons _ the madness
surrounding ``Millionaire'' is inspiring an increasing number of
spoofs, knockoffs and ripoffs in advertising as well as
programming.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigns for marketers as disparate as exercise clubs, discount
retailers and banks have played off the ``Millionaire'' theme,
complete with make-believe lifelines and variations on the Philbin
catch phrase, ``Is that your final answer?'' The series even
inspired a skit that was part of a presentation last week at the
annual Television Advertising Forum sponsored by the Association of
National Advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Crunch Fitness, which operates gyms in Los Angeles, Miami, New
York and other cities, plans to start running a $15 million
campaign this week centered on ``Millionaire.'' The ads, created by
DiMassimo Brand Advertising in New York, suggest that being fit
enough to beat up a millionaire is better than being a millionaire,
or even marrying one.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will offer a contest for consumers at least 18
years old: the chance to win six weeks of free kickboxing lessons
and then box with a millionaire.
   ``There's so much mania around money right now in this
country,'' said Mark DiMassimo, president and creative director at
DiMassimo, ``we want to make fun of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The hoopla surrounding ``Millionaire'' is not confined to the
United States. In Canada, where the CTV network carries the show in
a simulcast of ABC, Zellers, a discount retailer owned by the
Hudson's Bay Co., is running a television campaign to promote a
contest aimed at mothers. Its theme: ``Wouldn't a million dollars
make your life so much easier?'' Three commercials depict a mother
who uses the $1 million prize to hire an executive assistant, who
performs undesirable tasks like lecturing her children.
</P>
<P>
   Zellers had been considering a million-dollar promotion to start
in the fall, said Janet Kestin, creative director at the agency
that created the campaign, Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Toronto, part of the
Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide unit of the WPP Group. But everyone
involved agreed that, as she put it, ``millionaire fever is now.''
</P>
<P>
   WingspanBank.com in Wilmington, Del., an online bank owned by
First U.S.A. Bank N.A., recently completed a 28-market, two-month
radio campaign with a millionaire theme. The radio spots by eSource
Marketing in Westport, Conn. _ the interactive unit of the Source
Marketing division of Maxxcom _ were centered on a game asking
trivia questions about famous millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   Marketers are eager to tap into popular phenomena like
``Millionaire,'' said Howard Steinberg, president at Source
Marketing, because they ``are fighting for that little edge that
pulls a consumer's attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Money was no object _ and was not the object at all, in fact _
when David Marans, senior partner and director for media research
at J. Walter Thompson U.S.A., part of WPP, parodied ``Millionaire''
at the TV ad forum, which was held last Thursday at the Plaza Hotel
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a presentation on problems with using ratings to
measure audiences, Marans mimicked Philbin's sartorial style by
wearing a dark blue tie on a dark blue shirt. As his contestant, he
``drafted'' a client, Kaki Hinton, senior director for advertising
services at the Warner-Lambert Co., to pretend to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   All the dollar amounts for correct answers referred to amounts
of money spent by advertisers to run commercials on network and
local television. The humorous format, Marans said, allowed him to
get his ideas on audience measurement across in a more ``palatable
form.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, one question he asked Hinton was to identify the
``21st-century, state of the art, reliable method'' by which
ratings in local markets were collected. Her choices were:
(a)infrared devices (b) solar powered sensors (c) unobtrusive
passive devices and (d) paper and pencil. The answer was ``d''; in
fact, all the answers were ``d,'' a clue that Marans shared with
Hinton and the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're spoofing something so part of pop culture, so
overexposed,'' Marans said, ``you better make it good.'' (af)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8315 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-GIULIANI-PRESS-NYT     04-05 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-PRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVALS FOR SENATE EMPLOY OPPOSITE MEDIA STRATEGIES  
 BY ELISABETH BUMILLER  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the beginning of the year, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has
given interviews, by his count, to at least eight national
television programs across the country, all part of a plan, his
advisers say, that has helped him get national attention and raise
millions of dollars for his Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Giuliani has mostly avoided the headaches of
one-on-one interviews with local newspapers because, the mayor said
this week, they tend to write such nettlesome things as ```When he
said that, he twitched' or `When he did this, he was angry.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton, by contrast, has turned down almost all
interview requests from national programs and instead focused on
television affiliates and large and medium newspapers across the
state, all part of a plan, her advisers say, to underscore that she
is a local political candidate and not just the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Local, local, local,'' emphasized Howard Wolfson, Clinton's
press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Like so much else about New York's most intense Senate
candidates, their media strategies are mirror opposites of each
other. Both also reveal some of the character of their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, strategy dictates that she never do anything, such
as give an interview to Barbara Walters, to remind voters that she
comes from anywhere but New York. For Giuliani, it is a chance to
raise his national profile and enjoy the attention of media
luminaries like Larry King, Cokie Roberts and Tim Russert, even if
Russert, as Giuliani's advisers admit, pinned him to the wall in a
recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor isn't afraid of tough questions, nor does he duck on
the issues,'' said Bruce Teitelbaum, Giuliani's campaign manager.
``But he prefers to answer those questions by speaking directly to
people.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Giuliani has become something of a radio
talk-show host, and sometimes seems to be on the airwaves as often
as a local traffic report.
</P>
<P>
   He already has three regular radio programs, dating from before
the campaign: ``Live From City Hall With Rudy Giuliani,'' a
45-minute call-in show on Friday mornings on WABC; ``Ask the
Mayor,'' another call-in show on the first Thursday of every month
on WCBS; and a weekly Sunday morning address to New Yorkers on
``current topics of interest'' on WINS.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, the mayor has stepped up his interviews with radio
stations across the state. By his count, he has been interviewed by
no less than 23 radio stations since the year began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked the idea of direct communication with the
people who are going to get to decide whether to vote for me,'' he
said on Tuesday on a bus trip to Long Island with Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz. ``That's why I do so many radio shows.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Giuliani has done far fewer interviews with local
television stations and no long interviews about his Senate
campaign with New York City television reporters, with whom he
often spars at his daily press briefings at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The mayor added that he likes it when newspapers and magazines
print only questions and answers from an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's great, when they print the entire Q-and-A,'' Giuliani
said. ``Then somebody can say, `Oh, yeah, he's a jerk,' or `He's
very smart,' as opposed to somebody else interpreting it.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani's advisers also say that his approach, particularly
with national television, has helped him raise $19 million for his
race _ $7 million more than Clinton _ and has bolstered the
response from his national direct mail campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say you're a $25 donor and you live in Kansas,'' said Roger
Stone, a Republican political consultant. ``You see Rudy on TV, you
get a solicitation in the mail and you send in your check.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone added that he thought the mayor's strategy of avoiding
long local interviews about his Senate ambitions was wise, for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a school of thought that you limit media access to
your candidate and you control the flow of news,'' Stone said.
``That's exactly what he's doing. It's a viable strategy, and it's
certainly working for the time being.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, on the other hand, has talked to nearly every
large and medium newspaper and television affiliate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the first lady, and she needed to establish
relationships for the first time with local media people throughout
the state,'' said Ken Sunshine, a public relations consultant who
is informally advising her campaign and who was chief of staff to
Mayor David Dinkins. ``There's no history positively or negatively
between her and the local media here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8316 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-WHITMAN-GRANT-NYT &LR;      04-05 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-WHITMAN-GRANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUPS QUESTION $1.6 MILLION GRANT TO COMPANY TIED TO WHITMAN'S
HUSBAND
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Gov. Christie Whitman's husband, John Whitman,
was a major shareholder and director of an Internet company that
was approved for a $1.6 million grant from the state last November,
according to records from the New Jersey Department of Commerce and
Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
   John Whitman, a venture capitalist, was a director of the e-mail
company Mail.com last fall when the company applied for and won a
state tax incentive grant to move its offices from Manhattan to
Jersey City, N.J., creating at least 175 jobs in New Jersey,
according to the company. Through Whitman's family investments and
those of his venture capital firms , he owned about 10 percent of
the company at the time of the grant application, state officials
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although state officials said neither Whitman nor her husband
were involved in the application or approval of the grant,
government watchdog groups said John Whitman's role in a company
that received state money raised questions of a conflict of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there's no evidence of any legal wrongdoing, this
certainly gives the impression of a possible impropriety to members
of the public,'' said Pamela Garfield of Common Cause. ``We need to
be looking at ways to strengthen the laws governing spousal
business interests so that members of the public don't have to
worry about whether people are given special treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's spokesman, Pete McDonough, insisted that Mail.com
received no preferential treatment and that John Whitman had not
been aware that the company was seeking a state grant until after
the application had been submitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would applaud John Whitman for bringing 500 high-paying,
high-tech jobs to New Jersey,'' McDonough said, giving an upper
estimate of jobs added. ``The company took advantage of the
benefits New Jersey has to offer any high-tech company and it would
be to our detriment if they didn't, because those jobs would still
be in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman joined the board of Mail.com in July 1998 and left
shortly after the company was approved for the grant. By partaking
in a series of stock issues and IPOs, Whitman, his investment firm
and the charitable trusts he controls have bought more than two
million shares in the company. Its stock closed at 12.93 Wednesday,
making Whitman's shares worth at least $26 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mail.com officials said their decision to seek a grant from New
Jersey's Business Employment Incentive Program was made without the
board's knowledge and was suggested by an outside consulting firm
that was hired to compare tax incentive packages of various
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Holly Lehr, a company spokeswoman, said Whitman was not involved
in preparing the application. Whitman was not listed on the
application because only those who own at least 15 percent of the
company are required to be listed.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we know, he wasn't even aware of it,'' Lehr said.
</P>
<P>
   John Whitman did not return calls seeking comment. But McDonough
said that once Whitman learned that the company had applied for the
tax incentive, he called Gualberto Medina, the State Commissioner
of Commerce and Economic Development, to ask whether he should
disclose his involvement with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Medina's spokeswoman, Lisa Kruse, said that he told Whitman
there was no need to disclose his role in the company because he
owned less than 15 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8426 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-MASTERS-HNS &LR;      04-05 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
AUGUSTA, Ga. _ If it was a sure thing that Tiger Woods was going to
slip on his second green jacket Sunday evening, the other 94
participants in the 2000 Masters would be shaking with fear instead
of excitement when they step up to the first tee today.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the man for whom a TigerWoodsisGod.com Web site is
circulating through cyberspace was a dead-solid lock to conquer
Augusta National Golf Club, the next 55 players behind him in the
world golf rankings wouldn't bother spending the next few days
strolling around the prettiest acreage in golf.
</P>
<P>
   There are no gimmies in sports. Bookmakers in England have
installed Woods as the 9-4 favorite, meaning it's still more likely
somebody else will win. So, operating under the assumption that
Woods can be beaten, the next question becomes who has the best
chance of pulling off the upset.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who insist they won't bow down to Woods, even if
he's playing a course that seems handmade for him. Some people
don't believe this is his tournament to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, people think any event he plays in is Tiger's event
to win,'' said David Duval. ``I personally think this is my event
to win or lose this week. I've been working hard trying to make
sure everything falls into place this week. And I believe I will be
successful in that.''
</P>
<P>
   With Duval, and a few select others, you tend to believe them
when they say that.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that this Masters is as wide-open as ever. If it's
not Mark O'Meara or Jose Maria Olazabal surprising the field, it
could be Bernhard Langer or Craig Parry. If not Duval, then Colin
Montgomerie.
</P>
<P>
   Or it could be Woods. But the point is that 72 holes at Augusta
National make it as much a crapshoot as any tournament.
</P>
<P>
   And while Woods has finished first or second in 10 of his last
11 starts, it also should be noted that he has lost four of his
last five tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   In that span, he has three seconds and a tie for 18th.
</P>
<P>
   The many splendid chasers have had their moments more often than
Woods of late.
</P>
<P>
   ``When players say Tiger is playing at 80 percent and we've got
to be playing at 110 percent to beat him, man, I'd love people to
say that about me,'' said Greg Norman. ``Davis Love made the
comment that he gets intimidated by Tiger Woods. Think about that.
I like Davis, and he's a good friend of mine. But when you read an
article like that, you go, `Whoa, they're already beaten.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't think you're good enough to beat Tiger Woods,
don't even play out here.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, there are certain players who have the style of play
that fits at Augusta National.
</P>
<P>
   ``This course favors the long, high-ball hitter _ Tiger Woods,
Jack Nicklaus and Arnold Palmer in his day,'' Norman said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods couldn't agree more, saying that recent changes in the
course over the past two years play right into his hands rather
than having the intended effect of Tiger-proofing the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's helping anybody who can hit the ball long and high,''
Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   And doesn't that include himself? ``Last time I checked,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Before the tournament even starts, there are some marquee
players you probably can mark off the list of contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Sutton? Hasn't survived a Masters cut since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Jesper Parnevik? Has broken par only once in 10 Masters rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Singh? Six appearances, never better than 17th.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Maggert? Only one top-20 in seven appearances at Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Janzen? Has never missed a cut here but hasn't finished
higher than 12th, either.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are those who seem a logical fit for a green
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Duval? Top six in each of the past two years. Could be ready for
a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els? Always hovering, never winning in the Masters. He's
due, considering he hasn't had a top-10 in a major since '97.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Furyk? Four of his last seven rounds at Augusta are 70 or
lower.
</P>
<P>
   Langer? Has made 16 consecutive cuts here, won twice and tied
for 11th in '99.
</P>
<P>
   Love? Top seven in four of the past five Masters. Par or better
each round in '99.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson? Came back from missing the cut at The Players to
win in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Montgomerie? Eighth and 10th in the past two years but
never a serious threat.
</P>
<P>
   You can go on and on, including the past two winners (O'Meara
and Olazabal) among the possibilities. But the bottom line remains
that Woods is the only name that crops up when talk turns to the
Grand Slam, which remains a mythical feat until somebody does it.
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood of Woods winning the Masters, the U.S. Open, the
British Open and the PGA Championship remains remote, to say the
least, although he likes to think it can be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you win the right tournaments, you'll do all right,'' he
said. ``I won eight times last year on tour. You just have to win
the right ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price, another player who has had lukewarm results in his
Masters career, is among those who believe the Grand Slam is not
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tall order, even for Tiger,'' Price said. ``But if
anyone could do it, certainly he could.''
</P>
<P>
   But the first step often is the hardest. You can't win all four
unless you win the first one.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 2311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
