<HEADER>
A8443 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-MEXICO-IMMIGRATION-LA     04-05 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-IMMIGRATION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRATION, NAFTA TOPICS IN MEXICO RACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOMINIC BERBEO 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The North American Free Trade Agreement should be
revised to ease immigration laws and protect Mexican workers
crossing the border into the United States, foreign policy advisers
for the top three Mexican presidential candidates said Wednesday in
a Los Angeles debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands of Mexican laborers are going to come north every
year seeking jobs, and we're not going to change that overnight, so
we should be realistic and not address the issue by building bigger
walls,'' said Carlos Salazar, a top aide to Vicente Fox of the
National Action Party (PAN).
</P>
<P>
   The topic has become a hot-button issue between Fox and his two
opponents, front-runner Francisco Labastida of the ruling
Institutional Revolution Party (PRI), and far-left candidate
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas of the Democratic Revolution Party (PRD), who
will face off in the July 2 Mexican elections.
</P>
<P>
   It could also become a hot topic in the U.S. presidential
elections in November because organized labor supports granting
amnesty to the 6 million illegal Latino immigrants the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Services estimates work in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Workers and small businesses are losing under the current
NAFTA rules,'' Salazar said at the debate organized by the
U.S.-Mexico Chamber of Commerce and Town Hall Los Angeles, a
private speakers forum.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Congressman Carlos Heredia, representing Cardenas in the
debate, suggested forming a commission with representatives from
Canada, the United States and Mexico to review the 1994 NAFTA deal
and add concessions on immigration and environmental protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tri-national forum looking at long-term immigration
solutions is the only realistic way to deal with this problem,
which has truly become a crisis for all sides,'' Heredia said.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Trevino, a Labastida adviser, also suggested creating an
ombudsman position in Mexico to act as an intermediary between the
U.S. and Mexican presidents strictly on the issue of immigration, a
plan all three parties have agreed on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a situation where two-thirds of the Mexican
population is living in poverty,'' Trevino said. ``We all know this
means that immigration into the United States is not going to be
solved overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates also discussed setting up a system for
Mexican-Americans to send money to relatives in Mexico without
paying stiff bank or agency fees, and boosting California-Mexico
trade.
</P>
<P>
   James Clark, director of the U.S.-Mexico Chamber of Commerce,
said Mexico is the No. 1 importer in the world of goods produced in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still see room for improvement in trade to Mexico,'' Clark
said. ``The next Mexican president is going to have to have a
viable plan for creating more jobs in Mexico and boosting trade
from California, including agriculture and technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a Harvard graduate and former governor of Mexico's
Guanajuato state, poses the most serious threat to Labastida and
the PRI, which has controlled the presidency since the 1929 Mexican
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8444 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-DENTIST-NYT     04-05 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-DENTIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENTIST ACCUSED OF USING FORCE ON CHILDREN 
 
</HEADLINE>
  By MARIA NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New Jersey Board of Dentistry has temporarily suspended the
license of a pediatric dentist accused of using so much force to
restrain his young patients that he broke their bones or otherwise
bruised their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The dentist, Kevin Ward, who practiced in Union City, Vernon and
Maywood, will not be allowed to practice on any child or adult
until a hearing on Monday, said Mark S. Herr, the director of the
Division of Consumer Affairs, which oversees the board.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension came after the state's attorney general, John J.
Farmer, filed a complaint with the Division of Consumer Affairs,
charging that Ward's conduct was ``grossly and repeatedly
negligent'' and ``poses a clear and imminent danger to his
patients.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last seven years, according to the complaint, Ward used
so much force to restrain five children that he broke the leg of a
5-year-old boy, the wrist of a 4-year-old and the thumb of a
10-year-old girl. The complaint said Ward also frequently pulled
the arms of infant patients behind the dental chair and held them
there with his legs, covered their mouths and noses, pushed down
with his fist on patients' chests to restrain them and began dental
treatment without letting anesthesia take full effect.
</P>
<P>
   The board notified Ward of the complaint on Wednesday morning,
and called him to a hearing in the afternoon, Herr said. After
hearing from Ward and his lawyer, Vincent Loughlin, the board moved
to bar him from practicing until Monday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ward nor his lawyer responded to requests for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general made his complaints after the police and
county prosecutors refused to file criminal charges against Ward,
concluding each time that there was not enough evidence to prove
wrongful intent.
</P>
<P>
   Herr said although there was no criminal prosecution, the
attorney general, who oversees the licensing board, could seek
other action.
</P>
<P>
   ``While something may not violate a criminal statute, it may
violate a civil statute,'' Herr said. What is alleged in the
attorney general's complaint, he said, ``violates state civil
statutes governing dentists' conduct, more particularly the
statutes that regulate the performance of dentists.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be safe to say it's not the generally
accepted practice to break the limbs of your patients,'' Herr said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the board suspended Ward's license for a year in the
case of a 4-year-old boy who had been given an overdose of
anesthesia in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly this prior disciplinary matter failed to deter Dr.
Ward's continued misconduct,'' the attorney general's complaint
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ward works at the Children's Dental Center in Union City. He
recently lost two part-time jobs in Vernon and Maywood when reports
of the injuries to other young patients surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest case, he is said to have broken the leg of Mario
Rivero, 5, of North Bergen, N.J., whose mother said she had been
prevented from accompanying her son into the treatment room. Other
parents who filed complaints said they also had been kept from
being with their children.
</P>
<P>
   In all of the cases, according to the complaint, ``Dr. Ward
failed to obtain informed consent from the parents to use physical
restraint prior to commencing dental treatment and failed to obtain
the parents' assistance and/or consent when a problem arose.'' (mg)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000405.0442 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8446 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-MEXICO-IMMIGRATION-LA     04-05 0542
