<HEADER>
A8450 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-660(2TA     04-05 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-660(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON CALLS SCHOOL CUTS A GIULIANI `ADMISSION OF FAILURE' 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKVILLE CENTRE, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton said Wednesday
that plans to sharply cut back summer school in New York City
represented a ``terrible admission of failure'' on the part of
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. She attacked Giuliani's push for teacher
merit pay, the issue that led to the breakdown in talks over the
school program, calling it a crude and ineffective way to improve
public education.
</P>
<P>
   With her remarks, Clinton took the side of one of her most
influential supporters, the United Federation of Teachers, in its
increasingly acrid battle with Giuliani over merit pay. The mayor
has argued for individual teacher stipends based on student test
scores as an incentive for teachers to work this summer and as his
opening move for negotiations with the union, whose contract
expires in November.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between Giuliani and the union over the incentives
led the interim schools chancellor, Harold O. Levy, to announce
Monday that he was scaling back the number of summer school slots
by nearly 70,000, limiting the program to 250,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Wednesday that she could support merit pay awarded
to entire schools rather than individual teachers, a position close
to that of the union and Levy. And she said she supported ``pay for
performance,'' a position that, again, resembles the union's, and
would provide extra pay to teachers who take on additional
responsibilities like serving as mentors to other teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said merit pay to individual teachers would discourage
teachers from helping troubled students and would create a
distorted competition among teachers. ``I don't think that's a very
good way to inspire teachers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want our best teachers to work with the kids who are
hardest to teach,'' she added. ``And if teachers are going to be
told that the people who look better on a test, or who please an
administrator more, are the ones who are going to get them rewarded
in their salary or compensation, why would anyone take on the kids
who are harder to teach?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's statement offered a strong contrast with Giuliani's
position on an issue that has received increasing attention in New
York's public school system. Giuliani was raising personal campaign
funds in Tennessee on Wednesday, and his campaign aides issued a
statement attacking Clinton and asserting that her position was
evidence that she was too close to the teachers' union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since Mrs. Clinton shared a stage with the teachers'
union to announce her candidacy, she has been much more concerned
about perks, pay and privilege for union leaders than about
reading, writing and arithmetic for our children,'' said Kim
Serafin, a campaign spokeswoman, in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Clinton should be embarrassed for placing job protection
before our children's education,'' Serafin said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's statements marked the latest evidence of her
increasingly aggressive stance against Giuliani and her campaign's
intention to try to turn what her aides see as mayoral difficulties
into a Senate race issue.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not suggest that the question of how to staff summer
schools in New York City, or even merit pay, was likely to appear
on the Senate floor any time soon. Nonetheless, her aides have
counseled her to seize on the issue as a way to emphasize two of
her main differences with her opponent: her assertion that he has a
weak record in administering the city schools, and her claim that
he is too belligerent to serve in a collegial body like the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me start by saying how disappointed I am by the mayor's
failure of leadership on the issue of summer schools for the
children of this city,'' Clinton said. ``For me, the idea that we
couldn't get people together under the mayor's leadership to do
what was necessary to provide summer school for every child in the
school district who needed it is a terrible admission of failure on
his part.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The merit pay dispute was one of a number of differences that
emerged between Clinton and Giuliani in a day of exchanges,
conducted at news conferences, across state lines and through
e-mail. Clinton, who began her day appearing at a public school
anti-smoking rally, said she would support expanding a New York
City anti-smoking bill to include, among other things, bars and
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hesitated at first when asked about enlarging the
existing anti-smoking bill. Mark Green, the city's public advocate,
stepped forward to explain the legislation _ which, in fact, has
not been formally introduced in the City Council _ as Clinton
nodded in approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would vote for it, if I were on the City Council,'' she
said, adding: ``You know, I took some grief for saying that no one
would be permitted to smoke in the White House. I'm sure I'll take
some grief for saying I would vote for this.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Giuliani later said the mayor, who signed the
original legislation, did not consider it necessary to expand
strictures on public smoking, saying the mayor believed the
original legislation struck a proper balance between the rights of
smokers and nonsmokers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, speaking at a news conference after the anti-smoking
rally, also said she was against a proposed constitutional
amendment that would ban flag-burning, asserting that it ran afoul
of the free speech provisions of the First Amendment. Serafin said
Giuliani strongly supported the constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's main focus, though, was on tobacco. She appeared with
Green at an anti-smoking rally at the Salk School of Science on
East 19th Street, where she attacked the tobacco industry and
endorsed legislation that would authorize the Food and Drug
Administration to treat it as a drug.
</P>
<P>
   Such legislation would overturn a recent Supreme Court ruling
that the agency did not have that authority and would permit the
drug agency to proceed with efforts to restrict tobacco advertising
aimed at youth.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``What the tobacco companies have done is to target children,''
Clinton said at the school. ``And they've done it deliberately.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you think that the tobacco companies are still
advertising? Well, because it is legal for them to do that, and
they need to keep getting more customers. They keep having to try
to convince more and more people _ particularly young people _ to
start smoking, because it is addictive.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Clinton-Giuliani campaign continued to churn along at a
rapid pace, Giuliani prepared to announce Thursday that his
campaign fund raising enabled him to start a statewide television
advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It will be unusually early to start a statewide commercial push.
It comes at a time when a series of public polls have shown
Giuliani losing ground to Clinton, and Giuliani's allies suggested
that the advertising was intended, at least in part, to halt those
losses.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, the two sides stepped up, if slightly, their talks
about holding debates, even as aides said privately that it was
highly unlikely that the candidates would actually meet in debate
before the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce J. Teitelbaum, the mayor's campaign manager, sent a letter
to Clinton's campaign manager, Bill de Blasio, politely suggesting
that the two candidates begin conversations on the ground rules for
debates.
</P>
<P>
   De Blasio replied with a sharp response suggesting there would
be no such discussions anytime soon. de Blasio noted that on Feb.
22, Clinton challenged Giuliani to a series of debates across the
state, an offer Teitelbaum had, at the time, dismissed out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry it has taken you so long to respond, but I guess
Giuliani's falling poll numbers necessitated a change in your
strategy,'' de Blasio said.
</P>
</TEXT>
