<HEADLINE>
A BILL TO HALT INSURER TAX FLIGHT TO BERMUDA 
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass., Calif.)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Legislation to prevent property and casualty insurance companies
from avoiding corporate income taxes by moving their corporate
headquarters to Bermuda was introduced Wednesday by three members
of the House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn., , joined with two Democrats,
Richard Neal of Massachusetts and Robert Matsui of California, in
sponsoring the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is outrageous that our own tax system encourages tax dodges
like this,'' Johnson said. She called the Bermuda tax avoidance
device ``a double slap in the face of the American taxpayer,
adding, ``First we lose tax revenue, and then we provide American
companies with an unfair advantage over U.S. companies and American
workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Property and casualty insurers make money from investing
premiums from the time they are collected until they pay claims.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, The New York Times reported that half a dozen U.S.
insurers had moved their corporate headquarters to Bermuda, which
imposes very light taxes, and had left the unprofitable portion of
their business subject to taxation in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Four major U.S. insurers _ Chubb, Hartford, Kemper and Liberty
Mutual _ sought legislation to block the Bermuda tax-avoidance
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   (rk)
</P>
</TEXT>
