u a BC-NY-SCHOOL-EMBEZZLE-75     04-05 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-EMBEZZLE-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAD OF PRIVATE SCHOOL CHARGED WITH EMBEZZLING COUNTY MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROOSEVELT, N.Y. _ For two decades, Ms. Shelley's Upward Prep
School has been a rare source of educational good news _ boasting
high test scores and an emphasis on discipline _ in a Long Island
town whose public schools are now under state control.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, bad news has mixed with the good. The small
private school, which once had classes from preschool to grade 12,
has become even smaller, now serving preschool through grade 4. In
January 1999, its founder and executive director, Shelley Williams,
held a forum to quell false rumors that she had been arrested and
jailed.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday morning, Williams surrendered to law enforcement
officials to face charges that she had stolen more than $329,000
from day care funds provided by Nassau County.
</P>
<P>
   County officials said her indictment threatened the continuing
survival of the school, which has sought to serve the working poor
in this predominantly black community. Her arrest also came as
another blow to the fight for better education for the children of
Roosevelt, whose failing public schools were placed under the
control of the state Board of Regents five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children are the ones who will suffer, and the children of
Roosevelt already have enough problems,'' said Frederick E. Parola,
the county comptroller, whose 1998 audit of the school touched off
the investigation, according to the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 51, a strict disciplinarian who founded her school in
1979 as an alternative to public schools, was charged Wednesday
with four counts of grand larceny, according to a statement by the
Nassau County district attorney, Denis Dillon. Her lawyer, John
Carman, said she had taken an extended leave of absence from her
$175,000-a-year job at the school to focus on her legal defense.
</P>
<P>
   Williams surrendered to law enforcement officials Wednesday
morning at the district attorney's office in Mineola, and was
arraigned Wednesday afternoon in 1st District Court in Hempstead.
If convicted of the charges against her, Dillon said, she could be
sentenced to up to 15 years in prison. Judge George Peck of Nassau
County District Court ordered that she be released on an interim
bond of $5,000, pending the posting of a $40,000 collateral-backed
bond on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Carman, Williams' lawyer, said after the arraignment that
Williams would plead not guilty. ``Any money she took she was
entitled to as compensation for the enormous amount of time she
worked at the day care center,'' he said. ``And all the monies she
spent were in the best interest of the center. The school was her
life. She would do nothing to harm the school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, it was a matter of poor bookkeeping and
accounting methods,'' Carman said. ``She has committed no crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Dillon said the embezzlement was discovered during an audit of
the school's finances by the county comptroller's office in the
summer of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' school, a nonprofit organization, contracts with
Nassau County to provide day care services for poor children
through the Nassau County Department of Social Services, Dillon
said. The school, which receives about $2 million annually from the
county, received more than $7 million from 1995 to 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
   During that four-year period, he said, investigators discovered
that Williams had diverted more than $92,000 from school finances
to pay for improvements to her home in an affluent neighborhood of
Old Westbury, including stained glass windows, an automated gate at
the entrance of her property, landscaping and a greenhouse
enclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is also charged with diverting nearly $237,000 from
school funds to her personal bank account. Dillon said that
Williams did this by fraudulently placing family members, including
her now-estranged husband, her adopted daughter and her
now-deceased grandmother, in no-show positions on the school
payroll. She would then feign salary payments to these individuals,
but would divert the money to her personal bank account, Dillon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the tuition costs for children in low-income families are
paid by government subsidies provided by Nassau County taxpayers,
periodic audits are required by the county comptroller's office.
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller, Parola, said it would be up to the County
Legislature to decide whether Nassau should continue to finance the
program at the school.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Parola said that Williams had cooperated fully with his office
and had complied with many of his auditors' requests for
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has been very cooperative, and our analysis is that she
runs a good program,'' Parola said. The audit report found that the
school had committed ``a serious case of misreporting'' the
expenditure of funds resulting in county overpayments totaling
$1.03 million. He said that Williams had returned nearly $420,000.
</P>
<P>
   Reactions to William's arrest were mixed Wednesday from parents
who send their children to the school.
</P>
<P>
   Joelle Day of Baldwin, who is a teacher in Hempstead, was
picking up her 14-month-old son, Brandon. She said she had
previously sent her daughter, Cristina, to the school, where the
girl learned to read at age 4. ``Academically they are doing what
they have to do,'' she said, adding that Williams' finances ``are
not my concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn Laysaun, a New York City corrections officer from
Westbury, said he had already decided to pull his 4-year-old son
from the school after Williams recently announced a tuition
increase to $780 a month from $470. ``I knew something right away
was wrong,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
