<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8461 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r n BC-PORK-REPORT-LADN     04-05 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORK-REPORT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORK SPENDING CRITICIZED, DEFENDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``a'' national news file.) 
By BILL HILLBURG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Depending on how you slice it, Southern California
Congress members Julian Dixon, Lucille Roybal-Allard and Jerry
Lewis are either wallowing in pork barrel spending or very adept at
bringing home some needed bacon.
</P>
<P>
   The three House members were slammed Wednesday in the ``2000
Congressional Pig Book Summary'' by Citizens Against Government
Waste, a watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   The book highlighted $17.7 billion in outlays from the 1999-2000
federal budget that were frivolous wastes, said CAGW President
Thomas A. Schatz.
</P>
<P>
   California ranked first among the states in terms of total pork
spending with $676 million but only 29th in per-capita pork -
$20.39 for each Californian compared to the $25.92 national
average.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Democrats Dixon and Roybal-Allard, and Redlands
Republican Lewis all defended their alleged pork as worthwhile
local investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fail to understand their definition of pork,'' said
Roybal-Allard. ``My definition is something that is not needed. But
my projects filled tremendous needs in my district and other areas
of Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lewis: ``I'm reminded of the saying that `pork barrel' is
that which is at least 100 miles away from your home. To critics,
pork barrel spending is any kind of spending you disagree with.''
</P>
<P>
   CAGW, which has been tracking federal spending since 1991, said
the 1999-2000 total set an all-time record and was up 47 percent
over 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon endured the toughest grilling from CAGW, which gave him
the ``Jurassic Pork Award'' for securing $1 million for the Natural
History Museum of Los Angeles County's planned dinosaur egg
exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon and Allard-Roybal were criticized for jointly securing
$18.2 million for the California Bureau of Narcotic Enforcement's
battle against methamphetamine production and trafficking; $2
million for Los Angeles' Better Educated Students for Tomorrow
program, a tutoring and recreation effort; $1 million for LAPD's
family violence response teams; and $500,000 for the L.A. Bridges
anti-gang program.
</P>
<P>
   Roybal-Allard was singled out by CAGW for securing $400,000 in
Housing and Urban Development Department money for such projects as
a $200,000 youth and senior center in Maywood and a $10,000
decorative street gate for Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was criticized for a long list of local programs,
including $4 million for a proton beam accelerator at Loma Linda
University Medical Center, which is used by the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration; $3 million to refurbish the
historic San Bernardino train depot; $800,000 for the Redlands
Trolley project; $500,000 for a Discovery Center attraction in Big
Bear; $425,000 each for recreation programs in Highland and
Yucaipa; and $250,000 for Fogelson Pool in Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   CAGW's designated top pig was Sen. Ted Stephens, R-Alaska, who
was credited with raking in $394 million in pork - $636 for each
Alaskan.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
