<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-FATHER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIAN'S FATHER FLYING TO U.S. FOR REUNION WITH SON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Juan Gonzalez will arrive in Washington this
morning to begin the process of being reunited with his son Elian,
who survived a daring boat trip from Cuba and became the subject of
a major custody dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Gregory Craig, the father's American attorney, said
Wednesday night he expects Justice Department officials to
``immediately begin'' the process of reuniting father and son after
Gonzalez's arrival at Dulles International Airport in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Department spokesman Myron Marlin said the reunion
process might take time. Federal immigration officials are
continuing to talk with lawyers for Elian's Miami relatives, who
have been caring for the boy, in hopes of negotiating a ``prompt
and orderly way'' for Gonzalez to join the boy, Marlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, addressing reporters at his Washington office, saying,
``It is time for this reunion to go forward. ... He is prepared to
stay here until he has achieved that objective.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez is to arrive by private plane at the airport in
suburban Washington at 6 a.m. CST with his second wife and infant
son, Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   The pending reunion would mark the latest chapter in a stirring
tale of survival and a family battle over the custody and care of a
6-year-old boy who may have seen his mother drown.
</P>
<P>
   Elian has been living with Miami relatives since his
Thanksgiving Day rescue off the coast of Florida, following an
ill-fated shipboard escape from Cuba in which his mother and 10
others drowned after the boat broke down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even as Elian lost the love and companionship of his mother
when she died last November, Juan Miguel has lost the love and
companionship of his 6-year-old son for four long months,'' Craig
said. ``The first tragedy cannot be reversed. The second tragedy
can and will be ended.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal immigration officials have said Elian belongs back in
Cuba with his father. But the Miami relatives have strongly
objected, saying Elian's return to the communist dictatorship of
Cuban President Fidel Castro would not be in the boy's best
interest.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. immigration officials have been meeting with the
relatives lawyers in hopes of reaching an agreement under which the
family would surrender Elian to federal authorities or the boy's
father. Negotiations were to resume today.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno has said her first hope is to get a
peaceful and prompt agreement but that she is prepared to send U.S.
marshals, if necessary, to retrieve the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's large population of Cuban expatriates, sympathetic to
the relative's desire to keep the boy in the United States, has
taken to the city's streets to denounce the Clinton administration
for calling for the boy's return to Cuba.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But religious organizations, saying the boy belongs with his
father, retained Craig, a widely respected Washington attorney, to
represent Gonzalez and help coordinate his trip from Cuba to the
United States to be reunited with Elian.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as late Tuesday it appeared the lawyer, who
successfully defended President Clinton during his Senate
impeachment trial last year, would not be able to pull off the
reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Craig flew to Cuba on a private jet Tuesday night to meet with
Gonzalez, who had earlier in the day surprised U.S. supporters when
he said he would not come to the United States unless certain
conditions were met.
</P>
<P>
   Either federal officials give him custody of Elian when he
arrives in the United States and allow him to return to Cuba with
the boy immediately or allow him to bring more than 20
``indispensable'' fellow Cubans with him to the United States,
Gonzalez said on Cuba's state-run television.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department, which has granted permission for Gonzalez
and five others to come to the United States, said it has no plans
to let any more people escort Gonzalez when he comes to this
country. Besides Gonzalez, the State Department granted visas to
Elian's step-mother, infant half-brother, favorite cousin, teacher
and pediatrician.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, after meeting with his lawyer, dropped his demand for
an entourage. Craig, returning to Washington after his day in Cuba,
called his meeting with Elian's father ``a success.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
