<SLUG> BC-PAT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORM PARTY CANDIDATE PAT BUCHANAN VISITS KANSAS CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Pat Buchanan who ran for president as a
Republican in 1996 sounds a lot like the Pat Buchanan running for
president this year on the Reform Party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   In a visit to Kansas City on Wednesday night, the candidate was
his old rhetorical self, preaching the same anti-abortion,
anti-China trade and anti-immigration gospel that propelled him to
national prominence in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In those years, he bedeviled then-President Bush in the 1992 GOP
primaries, and then Bob Dole four years later. This time around
he's the early favorite to win the nomination of the Ross
Perot-founded Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't change my views and ideas,'' Buchanan said. ``But I do
believe now that the Republican and Democratic establishment are so
similar, so powerful, that if we're going to change this country,
we have to change it from the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   The former aide to Presidents Nixon and Reagan said he was
confident that he could defeat a group of largely unknown rivals
for the Reform Party nod this summer. His confidence may be
bolstered by his belief that Perot will not run again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd clearly be formidable, but we have no indication that
he's going to'' run, Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to about 50 persons at the Kansas City Airport
Marriott, he emphasized the importance of being included in this
fall's presidential debates. A debate commission has said that to
be included, a candidate must draw 15 percent support in a set of
five polls before the first debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can win if we don't get into the debates,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign has filed a complaint with the Federal Election
Commission over the debate issue. If that proves fruitless,
Buchanan said, he will go to court.
</P>
<P>
   He may be a Reform Party member now, but Buchanan plans to steal
a page from Republican John McCain's playbook this fall by
traveling the country in a bus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
