u a BC-NJ-NEWARK-STADIUM-NYT     04-05 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-NEWARK-STADIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCORD IS REACHED IN NEWARK FOR DOWNTOWN SPORTS ARENA
</HEADLINE>
  By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Paving the way for one of the largest development
projects here in decades, the YankeeNets and a major landowner have
struck a deal for a $295 million downtown sports arena that
officials hope will spark the rejuvenation of one of the state's
poorest cities.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, reached on Tuesday, removes the most serious
obstacle to the project, settling a dispute over whether the arena
_ a new home for the New Jersey Nets and the Devils _ will be built
in the heart of downtown Newark, or 600 feet away, next to the
city's public transportation hub, Pennsylvania Station.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the YankeeNets, which owns the Nets and Devils,
succeeded in moving the arena closer to the station, easing its
concerns that sports fans arriving by train would be loath to walk
through the center of a city that has long been associated with
urban blight.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new plan, those attending basketball or hockey games
will be able to proceed directly from Pennsylvania Station to the
arena through an elevated passageway, eliminating the need to walk
on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Many urban planners have criticized that plan, saying it would
keep visitors bottled up near the station rather than getting them
into the historic center of Newark.
</P>
<P>
   The new plan, however, eliminates a soccer stadium for the New
York-New Jersey MetroStars that had been proposed in earlier plans.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Sharpe James hailed the settlement Wednesday and predicted
that the 18,500-seat arena would be finished within four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This undertaking will create thousands of new jobs for city
residents, new opportunities for local families and tax ratables
for Newark,'' he said. ``It's a win-win situation for all
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   The completion of the arena would be an astonishing feat for a
city that not long ago was being written off. After decades of
calling itself ``America's Renaissance City'' with few solid signs
of rebirth, Newark is finally enjoying the fruits of the nation's
economic boom. A performing arts center opened here three years ago
to nearly unanimous praise, aging office buildings are being
renovated for dot-com upstarts, and city officials have plans for a
downtown arts and entertainment district.
</P>
<P>
   Although the redevelopment plan, including the condemnation of
about 100 homes and 50 businesses, still requires approval by the
City Council and the Planning Board, Newark officials agreed that
Tuesday's deal had defused a threat by the YankeeNets to build an
arena somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   A group of residents initially sued the city to stop the
condemnation process, but continuing negotiations between the
residents and the YankeeNets have won over even the most stubborn
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   (nk)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
