u a BC-NY-COMMUTER-TAX-NYT     04-05 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COMMUTER-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST A COMMUTER TAX BREAK, NOT A PAPERWORK HEADACHE
</HEADLINE>
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ From New York's highest court, the message was
simple: New York City's commuter tax is no more. But for 340,000
commuters from other states, getting refunds will not be simple,
and will involve a maze of paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   As the deadline for filing income tax returns approaches, it is
not clear whether those commuters, most of them from New Jersey,
will be able to claim their refunds as part of their returns. If
not, or if they have already filed their returns, more paperwork
awaits them, as well as a longer wait to get their money back.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Court of Appeals ruled on Tuesday that state
lawmakers were within their rights last year when they repealed New
York City's tax on the incomes of in-state residents who work in
the city but live outside it. The state, which collects income
taxes for the city, stopped collecting the money from in-state
commuters on July 1, when the law went into effect.
</P>
<P>
   But the law left the tax in place for out-of-state commuters,
and the state continued to collect the levy, 0.45 percent of
taxable income, usually through automatic payroll deduction. The
Court of Appeals said that such discrimination against residents of
other states was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The state reckons that commuters from other states now qualify
for $70 million in refunds on tax collected in the second half of
last year _ more than $206 each, on average.
</P>
<P>
   But the New York Department of Taxation and Finance says it
cannot begin helping people get their money back until the Court of
Appeals order is ``entered,'' meaning that it is signed by the
court clerk, returned to the trial court that first heard the case
in Manhattan, and added to the case file. The process usually takes
several days.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves barely a week until tax day, which falls on April 17
because April 15 is a Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are geared up with pamphlets that we will be sending out to
all of the out-of-state taxpayers and to tax preparers,'' said Marc
Carey, spokesman for the state Department of Taxation and Finance.
``But legally, our hands are tied and we can't send that out until
that order is entered.''
</P>
<P>
   Those pamphlets explain how to fill out New York State tax
returns so that the commuter tax paid in the second half of 1999 is
subtracted from the total tax bill. (All taxpayers who work in New
York State must pay New York state and local income taxes, even if
the taxpayer lives in another state, and that will continue. What
has ended is a New York City tax that applied only to noncity
residents.)
</P>
<P>
   If commuters do not receive the pamphlets in time to meet the
filing deadline, they have two choices. They may file 1999 returns
without making the adjustment, and then file amended returns later
to claim the refund. Or they may file for extensions, along with
estimated tax payments, giving them until August to file their
returns.
</P>
<P>
   For people who have already filed their 1999 returns, the only
way to claim the refund is to file an amended return.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the problem of taxes on this year's income,
because$45 million has already been deducted from paychecks through
the first three months of 2000. Rather than wait until year 2000
tax returns are filed next year, the tax department will send each
commuter an application to get the amount paid so far this year
sent back, in the form of a refund check.
</P>
<P>
   (mg)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 2334EDT &QL; 
