<HEADLINE>
NEW-LOOK RANGERS, SAME OLD PITCHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ With or without Juan Gonzalez, it's still the
American League. Any talk of pitching duels coming soon to The
Ballpark in Arlington has been premature so far.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are still in their outslug-the-opposition mode, only
yesterday they couldn't quite finish the job. The Chicago White
Sox, after blowing a 7-1 lead, scored five runs in the top of the
ninth inning to defeat the Rangers, 12-8.
</P>
<P>
   There were 28 hits, 11 walks, four errors and 346 pitches in the
31/2-hour game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good day to be a vendor, the last two days,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said. ``You can make a lot of money in 31/2
hours. They have to be sold out in the concession stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Three games into the season, Oates is almost worn out in his
bullpen. He tried to get an extra inning out of Jeff Zimmerman
yesterday, and it didn't work. Instead, the White Sox roughed up
Zimmerman and Francisco Cordero to get their five runs in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had just tied the score 7-7 in the bottom of the
eighth. But Chris Singleton, leading off the ninth, jumped on a
first-pitch fastball from Zimmerman and smashed it into the
right-field seats for a home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could have held them there, we definitely would have
won,'' first baseman David Segui said. ``Some days you do; some
days you don't. But I don't think there was a time at any point of
the game where we didn't think we had a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not, but it got pretty bleak from there. Carlos Lee
walked and later scored on Ray Durham's two-out single. After
Zimmerman walked Jose Valentin, Oates tried Cordero, but Frank
Thomas hit a two-run double, and Paul Konerko delivered a
run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost a little bit of my aggressiveness,'' Zimmerman said.
``I started to nibble at the corners rather than going after
hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman had pitched well until the ninth. Entering the seventh
with one out and runners at second and third, he kept the White Sox
from scoring by striking out Josh Paul and Ray Durham. Valentin led
off the eighth with a double, but Zimmerman got Thomas and Magglio
Ordonez on fly balls and struck out Konerko.
</P>
<P>
   Oates had closer John Wetteland warmed up going into the ninth
but, with his bullpen thin from Tuesday's 12-8 battle, he was
hoping to get one more inning out of Zimmerman. Oates said if the
game were still tied in the 10th, Wetteland would have pitched.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my last bullet,'' Oates said. ``Zimmerman was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Zimmerman: ``I felt great. I wanted to go out there for the
ninth.''
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen became thin because starter Darren Oliver struggled
early, allowing four runs in the first two innings. Two of the four
runs got on base by drawing walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really no excuse for walks out there,'' Oliver said.
``If you put guys on base, you want to make them earn it.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox added three more runs off Oliver in the fifth
before Oates brought in long reliever Matt Perisho.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez's two-run single and Rafael Palmeiro's three-run
homer in the fifth made it a 7-6 game. The Rangers then tied it in
the eighth on singles by Segui and Frank Catalanotto, and Durham's
throwing error.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Curtis' leadoff homer in the ninth backed up Segui's belief
the Rangers could have won it if they had held the White Sox in the
ninth. But this is the American League. You can never stop
slugging. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
