<HEADER>
A8474 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PRIVACY-WEBSEALS-SFCH     04-05 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-WEBSEALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 APPROVAL SEALS DON'T GUARANTEE PROTECTED DATA  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Almost everyone who uses the Internet fills out
forms, even if they don't buy anything. Name, address, e-mail
address, age, even income level _ most people part with all this
information and more without thinking twice. But federal regulators
and consumer groups are worried about what Web pages do with all
that information.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies sell or trade the details to other companies or
use it to send unsolicited sales e-mail. Others combine it with
information about an individual's Web-surfing habits and use it to
build lengthy files about the person and their spending habits.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Internet companies are trying to reassure both
users and regulators about the use of the information by forming
groups, such as Truste of Cupertino and the Better Business
Bureau's BBBOnline, whose privacy seals adorn thousands of Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   But having a seal from one of these groups doesn't mean much,
say privacy advocates. Truste, BBBOnline and the new
Personalization Consortium, which said yesterday that it would
offer its own privacy seal of approval, don't tell their member
sites not to collect information about users. Each simply requires
the sites to list their policies, which could include selling names
and e-mail addresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Truste) only requires that Web sites disclose their
practices, no matter how invasive or objectionable they are,'' said
Jason Catlett, founder of privacy consulting and advocacy firm
Junkbusters in Greenbrook, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Truste members don't even have to agree not to link actual
names, addresses and phone numbers to anonymous Web users _ a
practice so controversial that it caused public outrage when Web-ad
giant DoubleClick considered it earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The outrage caught the attention of the government, which was
already moving toward regulating Internet privacy. The Federal
Trade Commission is investigating the privacy practices of
DoubleClick, and several bills dictating Internet users' privacy
rights have been drafted in Congress. Members of the U.S. House of
Representatives have proposed forming a 17-member commission to
consider Internet privacy issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's already too late (for Internet companies to set
privacy rules),'' said Christopher Kelly, an associate researcher
with Forrester Research. ``It's been about three years now that the
government has been looking into this, and it's been about three
years that the industry's been dragging its feet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Personalization Consortium is composed of 26 companies _
including DoubleClick _ that are involved in collecting data about
Net users.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick _ the ad agency that puts banner ads atop most Web
sites _ gathers information such as where Web users shop and browse
in order to show those users ads that are targeted to individual
tastes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, someone who has bought dog toys at Pets.com in the
past might start seeing ads for Dog Chow pop up as they surf, while
someone who spends time at ESPN.com might start seeing ads for
soccer shoes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Other members of the Personalization Consortium, such as
eCustomers.com, provide technology to Web sites that want to
provide personalized content to users.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 90 days, the consortium's founding members will
draft guidelines that all members will have to adopt. But the
group's co-chairman, Larry Poneman of PricewaterhouseCoopers, did
not say that the new group's standards would be any tougher than
those of Truste and BBBOnline.
</P>
<P>
   To become a member of Truste, all a Web site operator has to do
is post a privacy policy telling users two things:
</P>
<P>
   1) What data is being collected and what is going to be done
with it.
</P>
<P>
   2) How users can ``opt out,'' or prevent personally identifiable
information about them from being used or shared by a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   BBBOnline has similar standards.
</P>
<P>
   Truste members also aren't required to mention the practices of
their advertising partners, such as DoubleClick, which do much of
the information collecting on the Internet. Although the Web site
you're using might have promised not to sell your name and address,
clicking on an ad puts you in the hands of an advertising company,
which might not be as scrupulous about your privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Truste has formed a committee to create guidelines for what Web
sites must disclose about their advertising partners.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy advocates complain that none of the groups enforce their
standards. Seal-of-approval programs aren't monitors that patrol
the Web relentlessly, searching for violations. They make their
membership decisions mostly based on questionnaires filled out by
the Web sites themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Once a Web site gets the seal, the programs depend largely on
customer complaints to point out violations.
</P>
<P>
   Neither BBBOnline, Truste or even Secure Assure, a less
well-known and slightly stricter program, have ever revoked a seal
from a member because of privacy violations. BBBOnline had to kick
out one Web site, but that was because the site failed to pay its
membership fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do as much as we can ourselves, but obviously that's very
difficult for any of these privacy seal programs,'' said Phil
Lockwood, CEO of Secure Assure, which employs four people to
oversee member compliance. ``We rely heavily on consumer input,''
Lockwood said. Truste in particular has come under intense
criticism because sites that have been caught violating users'
privacy continue to bear the Truste seal. In one case last
November, Truste member RealNetworks was found to be monitoring the
music listening choices of users of its RealJukebox software. But
Truste did not revoke RealNetworks' membership, saying that its
agreement covers only Web sites, not software downloaded from
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Truste is also working toward a standard that would include such
cases, said Bob Lewin, Truste's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Consortium's Poneman, who created PricewaterhouseCoopers'
privacy practice, said the group's seal will be more meaningful
than Truste and BBBOnline because members will be periodically
audited by an outside company to prove that they are complying with
their own privacy policies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Staff at Truste and BBBOnline do look at applicants' Web
sites, and occasionally even test sites' compliance by posing as
consumers. But Truste has 20 staff members to keep an eye on its
2,000 members. BBBOnline has three full-time staffers watching its
238 members.
</P>
<P>
   Truste said it calls in an independent audit on members only if
a user complains, while BBBOnline has Underwriters Laboratories
Inc. perform random audits to see if member sites are living up to
its standards.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at ckirby(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-05-00 2337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
