<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ZIMBABWE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RESISTING CHANGE IN ZIMBABWE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Thursday, April 6: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After two decades of blighted hope and slow decay in Zimbabwe, a
fledgling democracy movement seems to have captured popular support
and is threatening to topple the established order. But change will
be neither easy nor, it now appears, free of violence. President
Robert Mugabe, struggling for political survival, is playing a
cynical and dangerous game, promoting violent intimidation and
race-baiting in the face of an extraordinary political alliance
between blacks and whites in what was once Ian Smith's Rhodesia.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend 200 thugs wielding clubs and machetes attacked
several thousand peaceful anti-government demonstrators in Harare,
the capital. Deployed by Mugabe's ruling ZANU-PF party, they hurled
stones and beat protesters, mostly whites, in an overwhelmingly
black crowd. In recent weeks black squatters have occupied more
than 800 white-owned farms. The country's High Court ordered the
police to evict them. But Mugabe has refused, warning of ``very,
very severe'' violence if farmers ``provoke'' the squatters.
</P>
<P>
   Land distribution is a legitimate issue in Zimbabwe, a legacy of
British colonial rule. The country's whites, less than 1 percent of
the population, own more than half of the most fertile land. But
the way to remedy this is not with threats of violence and illegal
squatting. More than a million acres acquired from whites for
redistribution to landless peasants have instead been given to just
400 people, many of them cronies of Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe is bracing for its most competitive parliamentary
election since 1980. Zimbabweans recently defeated a constitutional
referendum that would have strengthened Mugabe's powers. The vote
illuminated widespread disaffection with corruption, fuel
shortages, high inflation and unemployment, as well as with a
military intervention in Congo that is sapping the treasury while
enriching generals and cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling Movement for Democratic Change represents an
unusual collaboration between blacks and whites who have the
financial wherewithal to promote it. Mugabe has often resorted to
intimidation to secure his power. But a recent poll showed that
four out of five Zimbabweans no longer blamed whites for the
country's problems. Instead, 70 percent blamed the government.
Mugabe needs to cease this ugly business and spare his country
further bloodshed. (af)
</P>
</TEXT>
