<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR OATES, BAD PITCHING ISN'T A LAUGHING MATTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers manager Johnny Oates is the last guy
you'd expect to be doing standup comedy, but there he was
yesterday, making like Jerry Seinfeld.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that we've scored 29 \Ractually 30\S runs,''
Oates cracked, suppressing a half-hearted smile. ``The bad news is,
we've given up 24.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch. That's no laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's tedious 12-8 loss to the White Sox at The Ballpark
in Arlington on the heels of Tuesday night's come-from-behind 12-8
victory left fans with an uneasy and familiar feeling of deja vu.
</P>
<P>
   The concern after the Rangers lost Juan Gonzalez, Todd Zeile and
Tom Goodwin in the off-season was whether they could still score
enough runs with diminished firepower.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching was not supposed to be the problem after general
manager Doug Melvin signed free-agent left-handers Kenny Rogers and
Darren Oliver and traded for Justin Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Oates elected to break camp with 12 hurlers and a
seven-man bullpen. Three games into the season we're left to wonder
if even that will be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually it will be,'' Oates said, sounding as if he might
be trying to convince himself as well. ``If not, we're all in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Hear, hear.
</P>
<P>
   Oates' bullpen was hurting even before yesterday's debacle by
starter Darren Oliver and a cast of thousands. Oates said before
the game that Tim Crabtree and Mike Munoz would not pitch and that
he hoped to avoid using either Mike Venafro or Francisco Cordero.
The latter two would both be pressed into action anyway, much to
Oates' chagrin.
</P>
<P>
   He had hoped to get by with long man Matt Perisho, followed by
Jeff Zimmerman and, for one inning if needed, closer John
Wetteland. But that was before an erratic 102-pitch, 42/3-inning
performance by Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back-to-back days like this, especially early, makes it a
little bit tougher,'' Oates said. ``You really are cautious not to
extend anybody too much, and everybody has to carry their load.''
</P>
<P>
   Some aren't doing that.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran starters and a talented bullpen were expected to be two
of the team's strong points. But the 'pen has question marks, too.
Wetteland and Venafro were injured for much of the spring.
Zimmerman was trying to find himself again after struggling down
the stretch last season.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, poor outings by starters Rick Helling on Tuesday and
Oliver yesterday left Oates wondering where to turn next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are magnified right now because it's just three days
into the season,'' Oates said. ``We know we're going to have days
like today. We know we're going to have days like yesterday when we
don't pitch well and we still win. And we're going to have a few
days like Opening Day, when we do everything right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we're going to average nine] runs all year. I
know we're going to pitch better than we are right now.''
</P>
<P>
   That, Oates admitted, will be good news to everyone but the
concessionaires.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good day to be vendors the last two days,'' he said,
doing Seinfeld again. ``You can make some money in 31/2 hours. They
have to be sold out in the concession stands.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the bullpen dilemma is simple enough: Better
starting pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we were counting on,'' Oates said. ``It's early
but it doesn't matter whether it's April, July or September, you
can't keep going like this. You've got to get it straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't come to the ballpark every day worrying about how I'm
going to finish the game if we get into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was a place to nitpick Oates' strategy yesterday,
considering his paper-thin bullpen, it came in the ninth when he
allowed Zimmerman, who had looked sharp for two innings, to go back
to the mound after the Rangers had tied the score at 7-all in the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Oates could have called on Wetteland for his one inning, hoping
that his closer could hold the White Sox off and that the Rangers
would win it in the bottom of the inning. But Oates didn't feel he
had that luxury.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RWetteland\S was the last bullet I had,'' he said, ``and Zim
said he felt fine.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't feel so good after Chris Singleton hit his first pitch
into Home Run Porch, the first salvo in what would be a five-run
inning that forced Oates to use both Cordero and Venafro after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put a first-pitch fastball right on a tee, and
\RSingleton\S whacked it,'' Oates said. ``After that, he got
tired.''
</P>
<P>
   By that time, you could say that about all of us.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
