<HEADER>
A8484 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-AOL-GATEWAY-SFCHRON &LR;      04-05 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-GATEWAY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GATEWAY, AOL SHOW WEB UNITS  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c.2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In what could be the biggest challenge yet to
Microsoft's domination of the home computing market, America Online
and PC maker Gateway unveiled a trio of sub-$500 Internet-access
devices yesterday based on the Linux operating system instead of
Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled to ship within the next year, the three devices will
deliver ``nearly all'' the features that have attracted some 23
million Windows and Mac users to AOL, including e-mail, proprietary
content, Web access, chat and instant messaging, according to a
joint announcement at the Internet World trade show in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The lineup will include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A ``countertop'' appliance intended for the kitchen or family
room. Designed to be mounted on any flat surface, it will have a
flat-panel touchscreen and come with a wireless keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   _ A larger desktop appliance, including keyboard, mouse and
conventional screen, designed to serve as a simpler, less expensive
alternative to an extra PC in households where multiple family
members want to get online simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   _ A wireless Web pad, weighing less than three pounds, that can
be used anywhere within the home. Like a cordless phone, it will
connect to a compact base station that in turn is connected to a
phone jack.
</P>
<P>
   While the first two are expected to ship by the end of the year,
the wireless pad won't be available until early next year, the
companies said.
</P>
<P>
   The hardware, which will carry a Gateway label but will be
marketed by both companies, is intended to supplement, not replace,
desktop computers in the home, according to AOL spokeswoman Anne
Bentley. Because the devices won't have any built-in storage
capability, users won't be able to install additional software or
save files; they won't even be able to print documents.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the new products will put AOL and Gateway in a
strong position within the emerging ``information appliance''
category, but hedged their bets about how soon that market will
take off. ``These aren't going to be earthshaking products anytime
in the near future,'' said Kevin Hause, director of consumer
research at International Data Corp., ``but they do have the
potential to establish leadership in an area that will be important
eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Reynolds, vice president of Dataquest, was more cautious
about the devices' near-term prospects. ``It's kind of neat to poke
around with one of these things while lying in bed or watching
TV,'' he said, speaking of the wireless Web pad, ``but we've yet to
see really compelling applications for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, ``it's good that they're trying _ if anyone has
a chance of making a strike, these are the companies who do.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL and Gateway will, however, face plenty of competition in the
appliance category. Several smaller companies, including Austin,
Texas-based Netpliance, already offer such devices.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Microsoft showed off prototypes of similar products
called ``Web companions,'' based on its Windows CE operating system
and designed for its Microsoft Network Internet service; companies
showing samples including Acer and Compaq. In January, Intel
announced plans to join the fray, and IBM followed in February.
</P>
<P>
   The new browser that will be built into the AOL-Gateway
appliances will also be available for conventional computers, under
the name Netscape 6. Free ``preview'' versions for Windows, Mac and
Linux were posted yesterday at www.netscape.com.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's own software for Windows and Macs currently includes a
customized version of Microsoft's Internet Explorer. But yesterday,
Steve Case, CEO of the giant service, said he wants to make Gecko
its default browser as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement under which AOL licenses Internet Explorer runs
out at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at hnorr(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
