<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAC-Q&AMP;A-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MAC Q&AMP;A COLUMN: MAC MODEMS CAN PERFORM BETTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By HENRY NORR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; C. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: &LR;   &LR; I recently purchased a blueberry iMac with Mac OS 9. My
problem is that I can never get above 26 to 28 kilobits  &LR; cq  &LR; per
second on the ``56K'' internal modem. Previously, when I used a
Performa 6115 with a 56K external modem (US Robotics Sportster), I
always got between 48K and 52K, so I figure it can't be the
telephone lines ... or could it? What can I do to get the modem up
to speed?
</P>
<P>
   A: If it's any consolation, you're not alone. Many buyers of
recent iMacs report similar problems, as do some users with iBooks,
PowerBooks and even Power Mac G4s.
</P>
<P>
   Two indispensable Mac Web sites, MacInTouch and MacFixIt
(www.macintouch.com/modemproblems.htmlimac and
www.macfixit.com/ultimate/Forum7 /HTML/000662.html), have collected
scores of reports on the subject. It's also been discussed
regularly on Apple's Tech Exchange support bulletin board
(discuss.info.apple.com/boards /imac.nsf/by+Topic?Openview).
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, all this discussion hasn't produced any easy
answers. Apple's responses so far, in the Tech Exchange forum and
in tech notes at til.info.apple.com /techinfo.nsf/artnum/n24482 and
til.info.apple.com/techinfo.nsf /artnum/n43079, cite myriad factors
that can affect the speed of dial-up connections, but they don't
confront the heart of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   As in your case, most users posting the complaints say they've
seen much better performance over the same phone lines, usually to
the same Internet service provider, with older Macs _ even earlier
iMacs _ and PCs.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the problem is clearly with Apple's recent
modems, even though the company has so far refused to accept
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   At least according to some Apple technicians, the root cause is
that the modem chips Apple's been using recently implement V.90,
the international standard for 56-Kbps modem connections, in a way
that's not fully compatible with chips from other manufacturers in
V.90 modems used by many Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   What then to do? Some technical users have improved things by
tweaking the scripts that control modem settings. Other folks
report good luck with alternative scripts that have been posted at
several Web sites, particularly those developed by Ross Barkman
(www.taniwha.cwc.net/).
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, none of this should be necessary, especially
considering that Apple markets its machines as the ``fastest,
easiest way to the Internet.'' To my mind, the company owes it to
you and other customers to acknowledge the problem and fix it _
ideally with a software fix, but if necessary with a free hardware
upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Look for Discounts
</P>
<P>
   Q: Last month, you complained that Apple charges $99 for System
7.6. Why didn't you point out that you can get it for much less
than that at several discount dealers, including Sun Remarketing?
</P>
<P>
   A: Good point. Sun Remarketing of Logan, Utah, has been selling
old Apple hardware and software since Apple II days, and it has
System 7.6/7.6.1 on CD-ROM for $39. Call (800) 821-3221 or surf
over to www.sunrem.com, scroll down to the ``Software'' heading on
the left side of the page, click on the ``System'' link, then
scroll again until you get to System 7.6 _ or almost any other
version of the Mac OS you might be interested in. (In case you're
wondering, Sun Remarketing has no connection to Sun Microsystems,
the server and workstation manufacturer.)
</P>
<P>
   Other readers noted, correctly, that local Apple dealers often
have copies of old system-software releases and might sell one at a
reasonable price.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  USB, FireWire
</P>
<P>
   Q: A couple of months ago, you compared IDE and SCSI hard
drives. But what about USB and FireWire, the new interfaces Apple
is pushing? I'm starting to see a lot of drives for both of those
technologies. How do they compare with IDE and SCSI?
</P>
<P>
   A: Both USB and FireWire have one huge advantage over either IDE
and SCSI: They offer true plug-and-play convenience. You usually
have to install some software first, but once you've done that, you
can plug in an external USB or FireWire drive anytime, without
having to power down your system and without worrying about
``master'' and ``slave'' jumper settings (IDE) or ID numbers and
termination settings (SCSI).
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that common virtue, USB and FireWire have very different
attributes. The problem with using USB for connecting drives is
that it wasn't designed for that purpose; it was created as an
interface for devices such as keyboards, printers and floppy
drives, which transfer data slowly anyway.
</P>
<P>
   With the current form of USB (Version 1.1), throughput is
limited to 12 megabits, or 1.5 megabytes, of data per second, and
that's only in theory; the reality, for any Mac USB device I've
seen, is well under 1 megabyte per second.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine for floppy drives, and perhaps tolerable for Zip
drives and very slow CD-ROM drives and burners. But any hard drive
or any recent CD-ROM device can deliver data much faster than USB
can handle. Yes, such devices can be adapted to work with USB, but
at the expense of most of the speed they're capable of.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, I'd recommend USB storage devices, except
floppy drives, only to users who have no choice: specifically, to
owners of all 1998 and 1999 iMacs plus the current $999 blueberry
version.
</P>
<P>
   Because those models don't have SCSI or FireWire, and there's no
room for a second IDE drive, USB is the only way to add an extra
storage (unless, of course, you have a network with a file server).
</P>
<P>
   If you have a new iMac DV or a Power Mac G4, you have the option
of using FireWire (a.k.a. IEEE 1394) as a way to hook up external
drives. On the face of it, FireWire offers the best of both worlds:
the same kind of plug-and-play convenience you get with USB, plus
throughput of up to 400 megabits, or 50 megabytes, per second.
That's more than any single drive today can deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the reality is a little different. There are
actually no true, ``native'' FireWire storage devices on the market
today.
</P>
<P>
   The products marketed as FireWire or 1394 drives by VST
Technologies, LaCie, APS Tech and a growing list of others are
really IDE drives combined with ``bridge chips'' _ special
circuitry that translates between the IDE and 1394 formats. That's
true even of the 1394 products recently announced by Western
Digital, which (unlike the other FireWire drive vendors) actually
manufactures its own hard disks.
</P>
<P>
   This bridge-chip scheme has two notable consequences. First, it
adds to the cost. Right now APS, for example, sells a 20-gigabyte,
7,200-rpm external FireWire drive for $399.95.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, a 7,200-rpm, UltraATA/66 IDE drive with twice that
capacity _ Maxtor's amazing new DiamondMax Plus 40 _ is available
at many outlets for less than $300. (I recently picked one up on
sale at CompUSA for just $249!) Granted, the IDE drive is internal,
while the FireWire one is external, which means there's also a case
and power supply to pay for, but the point remains.
</P>
<P>
   The second effect of the bridge chip is to limit throughput _
currently to about 15 megabytes per second, according to my tests
with several drives lent by VST and to what I hear from industry
contacts. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  That's more than enough speed for products like CD, CD-R and
CD-RW drives, and it's more than any hard drive could deliver until
just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it's well short of what the latest hard
drives, in both IDE and SCSI flavors, are capable of. My new Maxtor
IDE drive, for example, delivers about 25 megabytes per second _ on
the same G4 where the FireWire drives top out at 15 megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean FireWire drives don't have an important role
to play. Their small size and plug-and-play capabilities, combined
with good if not great performance, make them a very convenient way
to move large files from one machine to another (assuming both have
FireWire, of course).
</P>
<P>
   And for iMac DV owners, FireWire is terrific not only for
connecting to digital camcorders, but also for archiving old movie
projects to CD or a secondary hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   But unless portability and pluggability are your key concerns,
IDE still delivers maximum value, in terms of price, capacity and
performance, while SCSI still reigns supreme in absolute
performance.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on storage interfaces, check out the white
paper at www.adaptec.com /technology/whitepapers/macscsiwp.html.
Adaptec, a major provider of SCSI products, obviously has a bias in
that direction, but the paper makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   You can also find lots of benchmark data in the storage sections
of two Web sites devoted to Mac performance comparisons,
AccelerateYourMac (www.accelerateyourmac.com/scsi.html) and
BareFeats (www.barefeats.com/speedtests.htmldisk).
</P>
<P>
   TIP OF THE WEEK: Got an iBook or one of the new PowerBooks with
FireWire? If so, hurry over to
www.apple.com/hardware/articles/sleepext.html and follow the
directions about downloading and installing a new item from Apple
called the Sleep Memory Extension _ it fixes a bug that can wipe
out all the data on your hard drive when it wakes from sleep.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at hnorr(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
