r f BC-GAP-SALES-SFCHRON &LR;      04-05 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAP-SALES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GAP RESHUFFLES MANAGEMENT AS SALES DROP
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CAROL EMERT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. &LR;   &UR; 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Is Gap Inc. losing it?
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco clothing retailer said yesterday that its
same-store sales plunged 11 percent in March and that a key
executive, Chief Operating Officer John Wilson, resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who joined the company in 1996, was credited with
instituting a program of ``operational excellence'' that helped Gap
attain record sales and profit growth in 1998. However, the company
has suffered significant setbacks in 1999 and early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question in my opinion that (Wilson's) departure
represents a significant loss to the company,'' said Richard Baum,
director of equity research with Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Company spokesman Alan Marks said Wilson's departure and the
other management changes announced yesterday ``are not related to
the business results.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's exit follows last month's announcement that Banana
Republic head Jeanne Jackson had resigned to run Wal-Mart.com.
</P>
<P>
   Gap shares fell 15 percent to close at $43.38 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Baum had forecast a 1 percent to 3 percent drop in March
same-store sales, or sales at stores open at least a year, many
multiples lower than the 11 percent posted.
</P>
<P>
   Gap blamed the large decline, in part, on the fact that Easter
fell later in April this year than in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The calendar shift hit Gap's Old Navy business and its domestic
and international Gap chains particularly hard because of their
large children's businesses, said Heidi Kunz, Gap's chief financial
officer, in a conference call.
</P>
<P>
   Banana Republic was the only chain showing positive same-store
sales. Sales at newly opened stores boosted total company sales 8
percent for the month to $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Kunz attributed much of the drop in same-store sales to a
strategy of discounting less merchandise. Since more goods were
sold at full price, March gross margins were ``the highest they've
been in at least 10 years,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Details on profits will be released with the company's
first-quarter results.
</P>
<P>
   Gap will not fill Wilson's COO slot but has restructured
existing management to fill those duties.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Pilot, an 11-year Gap veteran who had been running the
international division, was appointed president of the Gap brand.
Chief executive Mickey Drexler has been running the Gap chain since
the resignation of Robert Fisher in October. Drexler will continue
to oversee the chain's marketing and product development.
</P>
<P>
   Kunz will take on additional strategic planning duties. Anne
Gust added the title chief administrative officer to her executive
vice president position. And Chuck Crovitz, also an executive vice
president, was given the additional title of chief supply-chain
officer.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carol Emert at cemert(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
