<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8495 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-FASHION-HELP-NYT     04-05 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FASHION-HELP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SUITS LOOSEN UP IN AN UNEASY WAY
</HEADLINE>
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Walking into the Four Seasons restaurant in Manhattan
for lunch, Jim Finn, a senior vice president at Chase Manhattan
Bank, suddenly learned what it means to be in the vanguard of a
trend: He was the only man there without a tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to go boldly and confidently into the room,'' Finn said.
``I wondered if everyone was whispering, `Is that a guy with a
dot-com and a hundred-million-dollar portfolio?'''
</P>
<P>
   No, Finn is a point man in the newest assault on the business
suit that is sweeping New York's investment banks, consulting firms
and law firms, toppling a century of dress codes and pushing some
traditional tailors into uncharted waters.
</P>
<P>
   Originally a concession to summer's scorching heat, Casual
Friday has given way to Casual Every Day. Conventions are crumbling
as old-economy companies find themselves competing for scarce labor
against new-media enterprises run by people who take their fashion
cues from Silicon Valley, not Saville Row.
</P>
<P>
   From J.P. Morgan to Morgan Stanley to Chase Manhattan Bank and
the law firm of Cadwalader, Wickersham &AMP; Taft, members of the
professional and business elite in New York are being encouraged to
trade in their pinstripes for Polo wear and their wingtips for
Weejuns. Some employers are sponsoring fashion shows, seminars and
even shopping excursions.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps with good reason. Business casual, as the new standard
is called, does not come easy to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Employers have made it clear that jeans, sweatshirts and
T-shirts that are permitted on Saturdays and Sundays will not pass
muster Monday through Friday. At the Manhattan law firm of
Winthrop, Stimson, Putnam &AMP; Roberts, the chairman, John F.
Pritchard, said the dress policy could be summed up in a simple
rule: ``If you have to ask if the clothing is appropriate, chances
are, it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems that while many professionals have closets stocked with
pleated chinos, Shetland sweaters and blazers that conform to the
new standards, others do not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys only have two kinds of clothes _ suits and slob
clothes,'' said Ann Shipley, a partner at the law firm Battle
Fowler. ``I've seen guys come in here on casual Fridays, and they
look awful. They look like they've just cleaned out the garage.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, retailers that were once perceived as a source
solely of leisure wear are only too eager to guide customers
through the sartorial transition, which, by most accounts, has
placed more of a burden on men than women. Ever since they
abandoned the power suits of the 1980s, women have been accorded
more leeway in how they dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have a lot of questions,'' said Trudy F. Sullivan, the
president of J. Crew, which offered discounts to employees of
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter when that investment firm went casual
last month. ``They want to make sure that what they're going to buy
is going to be appropriate. We're happy to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Seizing on the trend, Brooks Brothers is setting up mannequins
in office conference rooms to illustrate different casual looks. On
Tuesday, the Polo Ralph Lauren on Madison Avenue staged a fashion
show, with lawyers as models, for Cadwalader, Wickersham &AMP; Taft,
which is thought to be the first large Wall Street law firm to go
all casual all the time.
</P>
<P>
   The fashion show demonstrated ``ways to distinguish yourself in
casual wear,'' said Scott Omelianuk, the executive editor of
Esquire magazine, a sponsor of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomingdale's is inviting its sales clerks to seminars with
major designers so they can instruct customers on dressing casually
and looking good at the same time. ``A lot of men don't know how to
do that,'' said Kal Ruttenstein, the store's fashion director.
</P>
<P>
   As with most fashion trends, however, there is no unanimity.
</P>
<P>
   Many professionals say that dispensing with suits has made them
more comfortable and hence more productive. In a March 13
memorandum announcing the new dress policy, William B. Harrison
Jr., the chairman of Chase, New York's largest private employer,
said, ``A more casual work environment mirrors the more flexible,
informal organization that we need to become.''
</P>
<P>
   But others say they have no intention of changing. ``I'm not
going to dress casual,'' said Richard Beattie, the chairman of the
law firm Simpson Thatcher &AMP; Bartlett. ``And I don't expect I'll see
Bill Harrison dressed in chinos at a meeting, either.'' Like other
law firms, Simpson Thatcher has been slower to adopt the trend; it
will allow casual dress this summer for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Beattie shops at Paul Stuart, the Madison Avenue store that is
not making concessions to the current trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies are shooting themselves in the foot by letting
down their standards,'' said Clifford Grodd, the store's president
and chief executive. ``There's no way we're going to do it _ not
while I'm calling the shots. Everyone recognizes that we stand for
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby merchants that also cater to the carriage trade are
similarly resistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in the big firms that we take care of,'' said John
O'D. Kennedy, the executive vice president of J. Press, ``they're
not dressing down.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressing down requires the type of planning that men are not
often called upon to make. Under the rules at most companies and
firms, old-economy clothes are still mandatory for meetings with
old-economy clients. When Mitchell Sonkin, a partner at Cadwalader,
was summoned at short notice to a meeting in Philadelphia, he was
relieved that he had a suit in his office to change into. ``I felt
like Clark Kent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its virtues, business casual has complicated the lives
of men who once thought they were immune to fashion gaffes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find the suit easier,'' concedes Chase's Finn, who is in his
late 30s and buys many of his suits in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Take heart, Finn. The tie may be gone forever, but another
change may be in the wind _ a kind of dressing up with softer
lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suit,'' Omelianuk of Esquire explained, ``is actually
starting to make a comeback.''
</P>
<P>
   (mg)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
