<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ZIMMERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
`BAD' ZIMMERMAN EMERGES AGAIN FOR RANGERS (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ For 12/3 innings yesterday, the Jeff
Zimmerman of the first half of last season, the virtually
unhittable Zimmerman, the Zimmerman the Rangers need this year, was
on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   But in the next inning, the Jeff Zimmerman of the mediocre
second half, the Zimmerman of the forgettable spring, the Zimmerman
the Rangers hoped had vanished was back.
</P>
<P>
   After quelling a rally in the seventh and pitching a scoreless
eighth, Zimmerman gave up four runs in the ninth as the Rangers
lost to the Chicago White Sox, 12-8, at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on top of the world for that inning and two-thirds,''
said Zimmerman, credited with the loss. ``One pitch later, and I
was six feet under.''
</P>
<P>
   The one pitch was the first one he threw in the ninth. The
Rangers had scored a run in the eighth to tie the score, but Chris
Singleton swatted a fastball over the fence to break the deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   After the homer, Zimmerman walked Carlos Lee, gave up a two-out,
run-scoring single by Ray Durham and walked Jose Valentin. He was
replaced by Francisco Cordero, who allowed both inherited runners
to score on a double by Frank Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The bad things happened in his third inning of work, so fatigue
might have been a factor. But Zimmerman, who pitched 22/3 innings
four times last season, said he wasn't tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt great,'' Zimmerman said. ``I had good stuff out there.
I just made one bad pitch, and then I lost my aggressive approach.
After that, I started to nibble at the corners. Four runs later, we
lost the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers didn't lose many ballgames when Zimmerman pitched in
the first half last season, when the rookie reliever was a
combination of Cy Young, Walter Johnson, Sandy Koufax, Bob Gibson
and Nolan Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   He was all but unhittable before the All-Star break, going 8-0
with a 0.86 earned-run average. He gave up a mere 18 hits in 521/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   After the All-Star break, though, he was decidedly mortal. He
was 1-3 with a 4.58 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The second-half Zimmerman showed up in spring training. He
surrendered six homers in exhibition games, the most by a Rangers
reliever.
</P>
<P>
   He did end the spring on a positive note, not allowing a run in
his last six innings, but he allowed three inherited runners to
score on Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   The ``old'' Zimmerman entered the game with one out and runners
at second and third in the seventh inning, and struck out Greg
Norton and Durham. He followed that with the scoreless eighth.
</P>
<P>
   That, not the horrendous ninth, is what Zimmerman wants to
remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got some positives out of it,'' he said. ``But I've still
got some things to work on.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
