u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-ROCKIES06-     04-05 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ROCKIES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Galarraga's homer Big Cat-alyst for Braves
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three at-bats into his 2000 season, Andres Galarraga
had convinced Braves fans he was OK. By the three-game mark, he'd
turned his attention to curing the Braves' ills.
</P>
<P>
   His three-run homer, the second long ball of the young season,
erased a miserable night from Kevin Millwood in his debut as the
Braves third starter and eased worries over Brian Jordan's news
that he'd be out a while with a strained rib cage muscle.
</P>
<P>
   It made winners out of the Braves, 9-6 over the Rockies, and 2-1
in the series.
</P>
<P>
   It also set up Kerry Ligtenberg for a chance to prove some
things. Returning from a year out following ``Tommy John'' surgery,
Ligtenberg collected his first save since Sept. 22, 1998, with a
scoreless ninth inning and capped a stellar night from the Braves
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Chen pitched two scoreless innings to get the win,
followed by two scoreless innings from Mike Remlinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm relieved I got the first one out of the way,'' Ligtenberg
said. ``Spring training is one thing, when games don't mean
anything, but to do it with the game on the line, it was a
situation I had to go out and prove to myself I'm back.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 6-4 with one out in the sixth, Galarraga took the plate
having been hit by a pitch for the third time in three games. He
launched a 413-foot shot off Manny Aybar into the left field seats
for his second homer in 12 plate appearances since he began his
return from lymphoma. That and a couple insurance runs on a Neifi
Perez error on an Andruw Jones grounder in the eighth completed the
Braves comeback from 6-2 down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really mad inside and I was really glad to hit a home
run,'' Galarraga said.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for some early-season solace for the loss of John
Smoltz, the Braves sent Millwood on his first trip to the mound as
the Braves third starter. It looked a lot like his last trip to the
Turner Field mound in October, when the Yankees roped him for five
runs in a two-inning night.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood left after four innings bearing six runs, matching the
most he gave up all last year in his Cy Young-contending second
full season in the majors. It was his shortest regular season
outing since his third start of last year, the final one before a
mechanical adjustment turned his season around.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood paid the price for a rare misplay by Andruw Jones in
center field. Having already surrendered a two-run homer to Todd
Helton in the first inning, he watched Tom Goodwin's fly ball coast
past Jones, who had misjudged it and tried to catch it over his
shoulder. It ticked off his glove and was ruled an inside-the-park
home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had it,'' Jones said. ``When I looked up again, it
kept going. It just carried. ... I had it easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
